<HEADLINE>
WINDS GUSTS HIT 104 MPH IN NORTHERN ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It tipped over trucks, caused one death in a multiple-car pileup
and blew off roofs in northern Arizona. It kicked up dust so thick
in the Valley that it looked like snow.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's gale was one of the worst northern Arizona has ever
experienced, with gusts as high as 104 mph. Much of central and
eastern Arizona were under high-wind warnings all day Wednesday,
and parts of Interstate 40 remained closed early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They talk about bad storms in the Northwest part of the
country, but this has been right up there in line with those,''
said Darren McCollum, meteorologist for the National Weather
Service in Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   At least one person died in a seven- to 10-car pileup near
Winslow that involved about 20 people. Police and the Arizona
Department of Public Safety received more reports of more
wind-related accidents than they could immediately handle.
</P>
<P>
   DPS Capt. Bill McCance said it was the most severe storm he had
ever seen. Officers on the scene of the fatal pileup wore ski
goggles to see through the dust. Details of the crash still were
sketchy late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   I-40 remained closed eastbound from Flagstaff and westbound
between Holbrook and Winslow. Rigs began stacking up at truck stops
about 11:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Because rainfall has been below normal throughout the state,
Wednesday's winds scoured up widespread dust storms.
</P>
<P>
   The Mormon church in Winslow fed chili and sandwiches to about
60 people who were stranded by the storm, including a busload of
second and third-graders from Vernon Elementary School in Vernon,
in Apache County. The children were on a class outing to Meteor
Crater when they were caught in the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Church teenagers came directly from school to entertain the kids
with basketball and games of Red Rover in a successful effort to
calm the frightened children.
</P>
<P>
   The group wound up sleeping overnight at the Winslow home of one
of the teacher's relatives.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the children were crying because Meteor Crater was
closed by the winds, according to Kelley Covert, a teacher's aide
at Vernon Elementary. Then, as the wind rocked the bus and they saw
a truck and trailer flip over, the kids became frightened and
started crying for their mothers, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was zero visibility in front of us,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If they hadn't stopped at a gasoline station to allow the
children to go to the bathroom, she believes they would have been
involved in the big pileup.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors of the pileup also spent several hours at the church
before spending the night at a Winslow motel.
</P>
<P>
   A weather station in St. Johns, northeast of Show Low, recorded
a gust of 104 mph. Most of the damage, however, was being reported
around Winslow and Holbrook. Gusts up to 93 mph raked Winslow, and
they reached 95 mph in Show Low.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three storms with gusts of 70 to 80 miles per hour
normally occur in Arizona in early spring, McCollum said, but this
was extreme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually you will get 70 or 80 mph at the worst,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Joseph City, between Winslow and Holbrook, there were reports
of roofs blown off houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have truckers everywhere,'' said Lucille Taha, assistant
manager of the Holbrook Truck Stop General Store, off Arizona 77,
near Holbrook. They were stranded there from 11:30 a.m. until about
8 p.m. Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are worried about missing their delivery deadlines in
Phoenix and California,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her boss was in his new truck and called to say that he had just
been involved in a traffic accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Stay off the roads because you can't see
anything,' '' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to weather forecasters, winds will calm overnight in
northern Arizona, followed by freezing temperatures and snow
possible about 5,000 feet today and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have a winter storm for the next three days _
anything can happen,'' McCollum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have to get on Interstate 40, I would avoid it.''
</P>
<P>
   Flagstaff high temperatures will be in the 30s and 40s instead
of the normal 50s and 60s.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, winds were 20 to 30 mph, just enough to cause some
discomfort for hikers and outdoor workers. No major accidents due
to the wind were reported, though some of Arizona's landmarks were
lost in the haze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Camelback looked like it was in a snowstorm,'' one caller told
The Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Lower than normal temperatures are expected Thursday and Friday
in the Valley, with highs the 60s. That may set a record low for
the date, according to Jim Perfrement, meteorologist for the
National Weather Service in Phoenix. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
