<SLUG> BC-TERM-LIMITS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAS SALMON FORGOTTEN HIS TERM PLEDGE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's hard to imagine a more ardent supporter of
congressional term limits than Rep. Matt Salmon, who was elected to
his third, presumably his final, term in November.
</P>
<P>
   As a freshman in 1995, one of the Arizona Republican's first
congressional acts was to submit, with a certain flourish, a ``Six
Year Resignation Letter'' to the House clerk announcing that he
wanted his name removed from the membership rolls after his third
term expired in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   All of which raises a large question: What was Salmon doing
holding a fund-raiser at a fancy Washington restaurant last month?
</P>
<P>
   The breakfast event cost $500 for political action committees
and $250 for individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon didn't publicize the fund-raiser but, this being a
gossipy town, word leaked out to ``The Arizona Republic'' and to
various political operatives who wondered whether Salmon _ as some
other term-limits advocates have _ might be having a change of
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``That raises my eyebrows,'' said Larry Makinson, executive
director of the Center for Responsive Politics, when told Wednesday
of Salmon's breakfast at the tony La Colline restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a reporter in Arizona, I'd be asking them, `What are
you doing holding a fund-raiser?' He's got to have a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Salmon's top aide said the congressman was
merely responding to the wishes of a small group of friends who
still harbor hope he may run again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a few folks that like Matt that want to be
helpful to his campaign, hoping that they can somehow convince him,
even though we told them up front before they gave a penny that
he's (not a candidate),'' said Mike Paranzino, Salmon's chief of
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Paranzino said the event took in about $3,000, which he called a
small sum by Washington standards. Salmon's wife, Nancy, attended
the breakfast with her husband. The contact for the event was
listed as Brandon Winfrey, whom Salmon has retained in the past to
raise money for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His (Salmon's) full expectation is that he's not running
again,'' Paranzino said. ``We're hearing that people are trying to
get petitions signed to try to convince him. I hear that other
members are trying to get him to run, because they seem to be
worried about (Republicans holding onto) that seat.''
</P>
<P>
   When he heard ``The Republic'' was writing a story, Paranzino
called back a reporter Wednesday night to insist that Salmon was
not equivocating about his term-limits pledge.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee already is
eyeing the seat as one it could take back in 2000 if Salmon doesn't
run. The GOP has only a six-seat majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress in its Easter recess, Salmon was traveling
overseas and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Salmon's House colleagues are having second thoughts
about their term-limits pledges. Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., ran in
1992 on a rallying cry of ``Eight Is Enough,'' but now is
considering a fifth two-year term. Reps. George Nethercutt,
R-Wash., and Martin Meehan, D-Mass., may abandon their three-term
pledges and run again next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is looking elsewhere around the oountry, whether it's
to Washington or Florida or Massachusetts, and they're seeing
members who have made similar statements who are probably going to
run again,'' Paranzino said.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Salmon doesn't run, he could use the money to pay
overhead campaign expenses, or squirrel it away for a campaign in
the future, Paranzino said. Salmon is weighing a run for governor
in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission gives candidates broad leeway on
using campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prohibition is against using funds for private, personal
use,'' FEC spokesman Ian Stirton said. ``But there are several
things you can do with excess campaign funds, and one of them is to
run for state office. You can also donate the money to charity, or
set up foundations, or set up a political action committee and
donate to other candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Makinson said, in a perfect world, contributors would be able to
know in advance where their money is going.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way of controlling the candidate,'' he said. ``They
really have an enormous number of options once they've collected
that money, and candidates tend to be using those options more
today than they ever have before.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Salmon's future is wide open, Paranzino said it's not
certain where excess funds could end up.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 41 years old, and federal campaign funds could be used
down the road and transferred to a Senate race someday if there's
an open seat,'' he said. ``And I don't even think it (the $3,000)
will last that long. Between the rent and the overhead and paying
someone to keep the campaign books . . . '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
