<HEADLINE>
TO HIS BROTHER, SLAIN OFFICER MORE THAN JUST ANOTHER COP
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
They grew up in a middle class neighborhood in West Valley City,
Utah, south of Salt Lake. Darin was the oldest, then Marc, then
sister April.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the kind of town that held on to the 1950s well into the
1970s and 80s. Maybe it still does. Kids played kick-the-can in the
streets and could stretch a roll of toilet paper across the road _
just to watch a car bust through _ knowing the driver wasn't going
to get mad.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how it is when you're the oldest,'' Darin Atkin son
says. ``I've got this little brother trailing along behind me,
driving me nuts. But, you know, it was a wonderful place to live.
We spent over 20 years in that neighborhood. Our mom is still
there. It's not like it is . . . in a big city.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Darin had been to the Maryvale precinct of the Phoe nix
Police Department to clean out Marc's locker and to pick up his
truck. Now he was thinking about what me might say at his brother's
funeral service.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't ever think anything is going to happen,'' he
says. ``You put it out of your mind and don't think about it. Af
ter all, you hear all the time about cops who go their whole ca
reers and never have to pull their guns.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Friday, when Officer Marc Atkinson was gunned down in an
ambush in an industrial park west of the freeway, all of the
headlines and all of the TV newscasters and all of the people
who've stopped by at the improvised memorial at 30th Ave nue and
Catalina have referred to him exactly that way _ as Officer Marc
Atkinson.
</P>
<P>
   That's how they'll refer to him to day when they show pictures
of the long line of police cruisers and mo torcycles leading the
funeral proces sion.
</P>
<P>
   The attention has been a comfort to Atkinson's family. Darin
says over and again how grateful they are for the kind words and
the support.
</P>
<P>
   But they don't see him like we do.
</P>
<P>
   We mourn the loss of a good cop.
</P>
<P>
   They mourn the loss of a good husband, a good father, a good
son.
</P>
<P>
   A good brother.
</P>
<P>
   Darin runs an insurance and in vestment firm in St. George,
Utah, just across the Arizona border. He was at work when he got
the call about Marc. He was the one who had to tell their mother,
whose hus band passed away only five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know how things will work out,'' Darin says. ``Marc
wanted to be a rock and roll star for a while. He loved music.''
</P>
<P>
   For years Marc took piano les sons. In high school he became a
drummer for the marching band, then, with some friends, formed his
own group. He moved to Phoenix because some of the guys from the
band had moved here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a restaurant manager back then,'' Darin says, ``and
they rented space in a warehouse and practiced music.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc's wife, Karen, has a broth er-in-law who's a police
officer. It was through him that Marc got in terested in the job.
Eventually, he took many family members on ride-alongs, hoping to
ease their anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved people,'' Darin says. ``I hope there is no one out
there who thinks Marc was one of those cops who went out of his way
to do things to people who were different than him. He wasn't. By
the same token, our family doesn't harbor any ill will toward any
community or ethnic group or anything else be cause of what
happened to Marc. We don't think that way. Marc didn't and we
don't. Not now. Not ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson wanted to become a motorcycle officer. He wanted to see
his son, Jeremy, grow. He wanted to grow old with his wife. He had
hopes and dreams, like ev eryone else in his line of work.
</P>
<P>
   Most times, we don't recognize that in police officers, or
choose not to. It's as if the shields they wear in public block our
view of the men and women behind them. Except in death.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a good cop like Marc At kinson can be seen for what he re
ally was. A good husband. A good father. A good son. A good
brother.
</P>
<P>
   A good man. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
