u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OFFICER-SHOT01-COX     04-01 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICER-SHOT01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gunfire near church leaves officer dead
 &HT;    By Gita M. Smith and Joshua B. Good
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An Atlanta police officer was fatally wounded in a
shootout on Peachtree Street that ended with the man suspected of
firing at him fleeing down the aisle of St. Luke's Episcopal Church
during a solemn worship service Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Inside St. Luke's, worshippers heard ``popping sounds'' but
continued Holy Week services even while the wounded assailant ran
down the main aisle, pursued by the church's security guard.
</P>
<P>
   Only after the man had been captured inside the church would
parishioners learn that a policeman had died in the struggle
outside.
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the slain policeman was being withheld at press
time, but his death was confirmed by Sgt. Lou Moore of the Atlanta
Homicide unit.
</P>
<P>
   According to police Lt. William Charles, the slain officer was
in his 20s and has worked on the force for at least three years.
The officer was assigned to the inner city Zone 5 district, which
covers the neighborhood around Crawford Long Hospital and the
church.
</P>
<P>
   A second officer was shot but spared from serious injury when a
bullet lodged in the police radio hanging on his clothing.
</P>
<P>
   The melee began about 7 p.m. when two patrol officers stopped a
man pushing a pickup truck down the center of Pine Street in front
of Crawford Long Hospital, said Charles.
</P>
<P>
   An argument developed between the officers and the man, then
escalated. After two more officers joined the scene, the man was
wrestled to the ground. As officers rolled him over to handcuff
him, he pulled a gun and shot several times, Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   The police returned fire, and at least one bullet struck the man
in the leg.
</P>
<P>
   The man jumped into a police car and tried to drive away.
Hindered by his wound, he wrecked about a block away at the corner
of Peachtree Street and Pine Street, Charles said.
</P>
<P>
   A St. Luke's parishioner said the man then ran into the church
parking lot and tried to carjack a young woman.
</P>
<P>
   Her screams alerted the church security guard, who chased the
man into the church and down the aisle, said the Rev. Dr. John
Westerhoff, who was leading the candlelight service.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 worshippers witnessed the disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   The security guard chased the man into the sacristy, a small
room with no other exit and which holds the Holy Communion
sacraments, and locked the door.
</P>
<P>
   Police almost immediately entered the side doors of the church
and subdued the man in the sacristy, Westerhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Holy Week and the church was dark except for candles,
so all we could really see was a shadowy figure running down the
aisle,'' said parishioner Barry Bynum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The choir was singing a canticle and didn't miss a beat, even
when we could hear the thumping and banging noises in the sacristy
as he was being captured,'' Bynum said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what it says about St. Luke's, that the service proceeded
to its conclusion amid the violence and noise, Westerhoff replied,
``Well, we're an inner-city church.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Luke's was founded in 1864 by refugees fleeing the Civil
War. The parish is known for its work with the homeless, including
a soup kitchen that feeds at least 400 on weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not such a surprise that people who are in trouble would
come in our door,'' Westerhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, prayers were offered in the church for the
policeman slain near their doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   _ Staff writers Doug Payne and Laura Woody contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
