<HEADLINE>
VALENZUELA PLEADS INNOCENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA -- Ex-jockey Patrick Valenzuela, who once rode Sunday
Silence to victories in the Kentucky Derby and Preakness Stakes,
pleaded innocent Wednesday to charges he robbed a cabbie of $150 at
gunpoint.
</P>
<P>
   He is charged with one count of robbery and one count of using a
handgun in the commission of a felony. If convicted, the former
jockey could be sentenced to 16 years in state prison. Valenzuela
is currently free on $40,000 bail.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Janice Claire Croft ordered Valenzuela back to court on
April 28 for a pre-trial hearing. The judge scheduled a tentative
trial date of May 28 in the case, court officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested on Feb. 26 on suspicion of committing the robbery two
days earlier, Valenzuela, an El Monte resident, has maintained his
innocence. His attorney, Donald Calabria, said that at the time of
the robbery Valenzuela was watching the Grammy Awards ceremony on
television with a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his 16-year career as a professional jockey,
Valenzuela was constantly in trouble. In 1989 he tested positive
for cocaine and was suspended for 60 days. The following year he
refused to take a drug test and had to enter a rehab program as a
condition of reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Valenzuela has had several petty brushes with law over the past
three years. In 1996 he was arrested and charged with vandalism and
being under the influence of cocaine. Both cases were dismissed. In
1997, he was arrested on suspicion of spousal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Recently Valenzuela had talked of making a return to racing.
Those plans are now on hold as he awaits trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
