<HEADLINE>
LAWYER SENTENCED TO PRISON CRIMES COMMITTED IN DEFENSE OF DRUG
CLIENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A former lawyer who had been accused of joining the
criminal activities of his clients was sentenced to just over seven
years in prison Wednesday by a federal judge who refused requests
for leniency.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Pat V. Stiso, 38, had pleaded guilty last year to
obstruction of justice and conspiracy to distribute heroin. He also
had agreed as part of the plea to resign from the bar and to
forfeit $600,000 in proceeds from illegal drug dealing.
</P>
<P>
   The case against Stiso had spurred debate in the legal community
about how far lawyers may go in defending their clients. Wednesday,
choking back tears, Stiso told a judge that he was embarrassed and
ashamed of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I failed to honor my own moral and ethical obligations,''
Stiso told Judge Denny Chin &UR;  &LR; in Manhattan, ``and the ramifications
have been overwhelming: disbarment, financial ruin and complete and
total devastation of an entire family unit.''
</P>
<P>
   The government had accused Stiso of crossing the line and
becoming, in effect, ``house counsel'' to a profitable heroin
organization that operated in the Bronx and that prosecutors said
was led by Francisco Maisonet. A number of other defendants,
including Maisonet, face trial later this year on federal
racketeering charges.
</P>
<P>
   In pleading guilty, Stiso had admitted receiving thousands of
dollars that he knew to be the proceeds of narcotics trafficking,
and concealing the money in his office in the Bronx. He also
pleaded guilty to a charge that he identified to Maisonet an
informer who might testify against him or other members of the
gang, in direct violation of a court order.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the plea last August, Mary Jo White, the U.S.
attorney in Manhattan, said, ``Lawyers who forsake their
professional oath should face punishment under the law as cynical
criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   The sentence of 87 months was the maximum allowable under
sentencing guidelines. Chin said that he had been moved by the
letters he had received on Stiso's behalf, including those from
former colleagues who wrote that it had been Stiso's ``passion for
his clients, his desire to do the best that he could for his client
that caused the blurring of the line between proper conduct as a
defense attorney and breaking the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chin said the letter writers had missed ``the side of him
that allowed him to accept grocery bags of money, tens of thousands
of dollars in cash in grocery bags, money that was earned from the
sale of heroin.''
</P>
<P>
   Chin added: ``Defense lawyers have to do their jobs, there is no
question. But this is not a case about the blurring of a line. This
case doesn't even come close.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 0020EST &QL; 
