</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CENSUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IMPEDIMENTS TO AN ACCURATE CENSUS  
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Thursday, April 1:
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans are up to their usual mischief on the census.
Fearing a loss of House seats, they have proposed legislation that
would disrupt efforts by the Census Bureau to produce accurate,
adjusted population counts in time for the states to draw state and
national legislative boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled in January that federal census law does
not allow the bureau to use scientific sampling techniques to
supplement the traditional head count in apportioning congressional
seats among the states. But the court allowed sampling for other
purposes, like drawing the boundaries of congressional and state
legislative districts and distributing federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   That ruling was a disappointment to Republicans who fear that
using adjusted figures in redistricting will result in more
districts with large urban and minority populations, who tend to be
undercounted by traditional methods and who tend to vote
Democratic. So their current tactic is to try to push through
legislation that would undermine the ability of the Census Bureau
to produce those figures with the help of sampling.
</P>
<P>
   One of the worst of their proposals is H.R. 472, which would
allow local governments to review the census numbers for accuracy.
That change sounds deceptively worthy but would actually be
disruptive. In 1990, that post-census review was so cumbersome that
only about a quarter of the nation's 39,000 local governments even
participated. The procedure added only 125,000 people to the
overall population count, and has since been replaced by a process
by which local governments review Census Bureau address lists
before the counting begins. This works well. But the House bill
would reinstate the old review, which would probably delay
completion of the count by many weeks, making it difficult to
produce the adjusted figures in time for states to use as they
begin redistricting in 2001. Kenneth Prewitt, director of the
Census Bureau, has called the Republican efforts ``just short of
disastrous.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggle over the census also bodes ill for the federal
judiciary and the Commerce, Justice and State departments could
lose their funding and be shut down on June 15 unless Congress and
the White House resolve their census fight. The threat has prompted
Chief Justice William Rehnquist to ask Congress to protect the
judiciary from this bitter battle.
</P>
<P>
   A vote in the House is expected to fall largely along party
lines, inviting a presidential veto. New York Republicans in
Congress have no business supporting efforts to tamper with the
census in ways that would harm the state's urban areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 0036EST &QL; 
