A1937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-HEART-BILL-NYT &LR;      04-01 0278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-HEART-BILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RETURN OF THE `HEART BILL'  
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial Thursday, April 1:
</P>
<P>
   The New York State Legislature has passed and sent to the
governor a bill decreeing that any state corrections officer who
comes down with a heart problem is suffering from a job-created
disability and thus entitled to a tax-free pension worth
three-quarters of his or her pay. The only real surprise is the
timing. This is the sort of special-interest giveaway that usually
gets passed under cover of the chaotic last-day race to
adjournment.
</P>
<P>
   Inveighing against the ``heart bill,'' or asking Gov. George
Pataki to veto it, seems almost futile. The Legislature overrode
the local collective bargaining process last year to confer the
same benefit on New York City corrections officers, and Pataki
signed it into law, even though Mayor Rudolph Giuliani claimed it
would cost the city at least $3.5 million a year in added pension
costs. In the past, lawmakers have handed the same sweet deal to
city police officers and firefighters. It is at least some solace
that this time the legislators passed a heart bill their own budget
has to pay for.
</P>
<P>
   Public employees who are genuinely injured on the job should be
compensated properly. But there is no reason to assume that any
corrections officer who comes down with a problem as common as
heart trouble was stricken because of his or her work. The
Legislature's impetus for passing the bill seems to have less to do
with medical evidence than with a dramatic increase in campaign
contributions from the state correction workers' union.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 0037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
