<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0019 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1952 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-01 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEUHEISEL'S BIGGEST TASK: DITCHING DITCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Identify the speaker:
</P>
<P>
   ``You got some 'splaynin' to do.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it isn't Ricky Ricardo. It's Ricky Neuheisel.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, in fact. Much like his namesake's wife in the ``I
Love Lucy'' show, Neuheisel has been caught doing the preposterous.
He knows that the University of Washington, Husky recruits and much
of college football have hands on hips, foot tapping, glaring at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question the publicity surrounding the ... mistake, has
left us with some explaining to do in the homes of recruits,''
Neuheisel acknowledged. ``But once we tell our side, I think you'll
see a positive impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``With respect to (dismayed UW fans), we just have to play. This
team will play with enthusiasm, and will be fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like these people don't want to be fans of the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, maybe so. Still, I can't recall anyone in Seattle's
modern big-time sports history who took such an important job with
so many people hoping he fails.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of spring football practice, Neuheisel met with a
handful of reporters over lunch to begin the climb out of the
ditch.
</P>
<P>
   Before he's even seen his players on a practice field, Neuheisel
finds himself in the crosshairs of coaches, administrators and fans
at two major rivals _ Oregon and Colorado _ under scrutiny by the
Pac-10, officially reprimanded by his new boss and resented by many
fans who liked his predecessor, who remains in the neighborhood,
stewing.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel's $1 million annual stipend has caused consternation
throughout campus and around college football for unreasonably
inflating salary scales. And he's made himself the butt of jokes
after he was identified by the FBI as a partier, albeit an innocent
one, at the Los Angeles home of a convicted mobster.
</P>
<P>
   I haven't even gotten to the part about inheriting a 6-6 team
whose defense was nearly the worst in the UW's last 30 years, a
team that will receive meager relief from a mediocre recruiting
class.
</P>
<P>
   Did I mention Washington plays Oregon and Colorado on
consecutive Saturdays?
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel has more than 'splaynin' to do. He has to coach as if
he's the second coming of Rockne and Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told my father I took the Washington job, after he
congratulated me, he said, `You go another step up the ladder, the
more your rear end is exposed,''' Neuheisel said. ``That has become
evident over the last five years.''
</P>
<P>
   The bull's-eye on his backside might never go away, at least
until he is no longer perceived to be too young, too glib and now
too rich for his station in life. But the criticism has yet to
produce a perceptible flinch in his game face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been given a great opportunity,'' Neuheisel said. ``When
you're in the spotlight and you do well, you can derive a lot of
benefits, with people jumping on the bandwagon.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the bandwagon unstuck, Neuheisel scored what might prove
to be his most crucial recruit. It isn't freshman-to-be running
back Paul Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   When Neuheisel appointed Keith Gilbertson assistant head coach,
he bought himself some quick local credibility. Think of it as
marrying into the Husky family _ if Gilby says Neuheisel's OK,
Uncle Torvald just might take the arch out of his eyebrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had an assistant head coach before,'' Neuheisel
said. ``I used to think of it as just a title. But I see this as a
bridge to history and to the behind-the-scenes activity associated
with the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson is the guy who knows everybody, from prep coaches to
Tyee Clubbers. He has the map to most of the local land mines. In
his third tour of coaching duty at Washington _ the last one
produced a team that shared the national championship _ and after
three years as a Seahawk assistant, he's the guy who will get
Neuheisel a table, a recruit, a tee time, maybe even a break.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a country club,'' Neuheisel said of the culture
surrounding the Husky program. ``It's the social hub for the movers
and shakers in this city.''
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel said at Colorado there were three or four influential
Buffalo backers of whom he said, ``you have to know.'' The circle
is larger at Washington, and even more important.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Husky program is still dialing for private dollars to
complete the facilities renovations for athletics, the head
football coach remains the primary shakedown artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, Keith knows the politics,'' Neusheisel said. ``That's
important to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In his final news conference as Husky coach, Jim Lambright said
his one regret was that he ``wasn't more political.'' He couldn't
have been more accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel has made more than his share of mistakes already, but
he won't be repeating Lambright's error. Some may find the
political aspect distasteful, but to dismiss it would be as foolish
as speed-reading the NCAA rulebook _ another mistake Neuheisel
isn't likely to make again.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbertson can't bulletproof Neuheisel, but he can help reduce
the amount of time he spends having to explain himself.
</P>
<P>
   The man needs every moment to get the bandwagon out of the
ditch.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
