<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-PANTHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEWART PRACTICES DAMAGE CONTROL AS ISLES BEAT PANTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ Bill Stewart has seen plenty of ugliness during
his three months as coach of the Islanders, but the ugliest
situation of his brief tenure is one he brought on himself.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning Stewart held a 10-minute meeting with his
players to clarify remarks he made after the Islanders' emotional
3-1 loss to the Rangers on Monday. The young coach's words, which,
he said, were taken out of context, not only hurt the feelings of
the players in the Islanders' locker room, but they were also taken
personally by the team's general manager and owners.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart has since backtracked, saying that he was emotional
after the bitter loss to the Rangers and that his comments referred
to the training camp mode that the team has been in since it was
dismantled before the National Hockey League trading deadline. The
remarks were not meant as a put down, Stewart said. But that was
how they were taken.
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday night, after the Islanders beat the Florida
Panthers, 5-3, Stewart said: ``Everybody makes mistakes. I'm man
enough to admit it. I think it was a situation where things I said
were misunderstood a bit. I'm a rookie coach in this league, and
I'm going to learn from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Milbury, the Islanders' general manager, was so upset with
Stewart that he faxed him two articles from New York newspapers at
the team hotel in Fort Lauderdale, Fla., on Tuesday morning.
Milbury circled a line that quoted Stewart as saying: ``Have you
looked at our lineup? Enough said.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Stewart received a phone call from Milbury, and the two
had a heated conversation as Stewart paced the hotel lobby on his
cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Mike Milbury was mad,'' Stewart said, ``and I apologized
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 48 hours since Stewart told reporters, ``Certainly if we
had the resources to go out and acquire some National Hockey League
talent, it would be a different story,'' outside the Islanders'
locker room at Madison Square Garden, the coach has been trying to
limit the damage. He may feel that his NHL future and reputation
have been tarnished.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, for the second straight day, Milbury was not
commenting. Islanders officials said that did not bode well for
Stewart, who is 8-16-6 with the Islanders since taking over as
coach on Jan. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps sensing Milbury's displeasure, Stewart, who had wavered
on the issue of whether he wanted to return to the Islanders next
season, said publicly for the first time on Tuesday that he wanted
to come back, that he would like the challenge of rebuilding the
Islanders (20-45-9), who have been eliminated from the playoffs for
the fifth straight year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that prior to the trading deadline we were headed in
the right direction,'' Stewart said. ``We lost a lot of one-goal
games, but we weren't embarrassing ourselves. There was some
chemistry building. We'd all like to have Robert Reichel, but there
were some economics involved, and I understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart described Wednesday's team meeting as very constructive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expressed to the guys the situation that occurred after the
New York game,'' Stewart said after this morning's pre-game
practice. ``I was emotional after that game. Right to the man, we
expressed our feelings and thoughts. It was positive. Sometimes
things get taken out of context. That's how we're leaving it. Let's
move on, let's move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Linden, the Islanders' captain, agreed, saying that it
was no longer an issue. Linden said: ``I never actually saw the
comments, but I heard a little bit about it. He's frustrated. He
was successful for the three years before he came here. It's a
difficult situation to be in. There's a lot of young people in our
lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Panthers, the Islanders trailed 2-1 after the first
period, then got two goals in a span of 42 seconds in the second
period to take a 3-2 lead. The first came from Mark Lawrence and
the second from Mike Watt.
</P>
<P>
   Mariusz Czerkawski clinched the victory with two goals in the
third period, one into an empty net.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Flaherty made 33 saves for the Isles, who snapped a four
game losing streak. Mark Parrish scored twice and Radek Dvorak
scored once for the Panthers. Sean Burke made 14 stops for Florida.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second straight game that the Islanders helped the
Rangers' slim playoff hopes. The Rangers and the Panthers remain
tied with 72 points in their pursuit of the Boston Bruins (77
points) for the final playoff berth in the East. The Islanders lost
to the Rangers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   And Wednesday's loss was costly for the Panthers. Mike Wilson,
the Panthers newly acquired defenseman, was knocked unconscious
during the second period after a frightening collision with the
Islanders' Steve Webb near center ice. Wilson was motionless on the
ice for several minutes before he was helped to the locker room and
taken to the hospital where he was kept overnight with a
concussion.
</P>
<P>
   Oleg Kvasha, the Panthers' rookie wing, sustained a separated
shoulder in the third period. Those injuries come two days after
the star forward Pavel Bure had season-ending knee surgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
