<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-DUCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS SET SIGHTS ON BIGGER GOALS
</HEADLINE>
  By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils finished the month the same
way they started it. Their lopsided 7-1 victory over the Mighty
Ducks of Anaheim Wednesday night at Continental Arena was their
seventh victory of the month, clinched a playoff spot and put the
Devils a step closer to the Atlantic Division title.
</P>
<P>
   After ties in their previous two games after slow starts, the
Devils came out with spark and enthusiasm, scoring three goals in a
span of six minutes before the game was 10 minutes old.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were so coordinated from defense to attack that they
caused disarray in the Mighty Ducks, who came into New Jersey with
a two-game winning streak and two of the league's top snipers in
Teemu Selanne and Paul Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   The victory came on a night of flawless hockey, from the
goaltending of Martin Brodeur to the last forward on the Devils'
fourth line.
</P>
<P>
   The triumph made the Devils a strong candidate to become the
first team to capture a third consecutive divisional title since
the Philadelphia Flyers did it 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gone through this scenario before, chasing titles and
losing in the playoffs,'' said Bobby Holik, who ended a scoring
slump with his first goal in 14 games Wednesday night. ``You can't
get distracted with minor goals like division titles. Nobody is
talking about the division title. It's all about playing well, like
we did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils were so effective that five of their players scored
goals to end long slumps.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Holik ending a slump, Kevin Dean scored his first
goal of the season, Dave Andreychuk scored his first in three
months, Vadim Sharifijanov scored his first in two months and Randy
McKay found the target for the first time in 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   With only two losses in March, the Devils, 40-22-11 over all and
9-2-4 in their last 15 games, seem as if they are peaking at the
right time. They have nine games remaining before the National
Hockey League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving in the right direction,'' Dean said. ``We're
starting to get production from guys, and we're getting ready for
the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils clinched a playoff spot as a result of Florida's loss
to the Islanders, putting Coach Robbie Ftorek's mind at ease. As
recently as a week ago, Ftorek refused to address any talk about
his team's possible matchup in the first round of the playoffs by
proclaiming, ``We're not in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears the Devils' first-round opponent will be the Buffalo
Sabres and Dominik Hasek, who played the Devils to a 1-1 tie here
eight days ago and will meet them again in Buffalo with three games
left in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Sharifijanov started the scoring with his eighth goal of the
season, 3 minutes 6 seconds into the game. Then McKay extended the
lead with his 17th goal 1:32 later. Holik gave the Devils a
three-goal lead 9:03 into the game, before Kariya narrowed the gap
30 seconds later with his 34th goal for Anaheim (33-29-11).
</P>
<P>
   Andreychuk's 12th goal of the season and first since Dec. 28
allowed the Devils to regain their three-goal lead with 2:37 left.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage was extended to five by the end of the second
period on Sharifijanov's second goal of the night and Sergei
Brylin's fifth before Dean scored the only goal in the last period.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils played with effectiveness even though they were
missing Lyle Odelein (bruised right knee), Jason Arnott (bruised
hip), Denis Pederson (sore back) and Jay Pandolfo (bruised
shoulder).
</P>
<P>
   They also played without Bob Carpenter for the final two periods
because of back spasms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
