</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-SCHOOL SHURMUR RAISES DEFENSE TO HIGHER DEGREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ They call him Fritz. Have for almost 65 years.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Leonard Frank Shurmur how it is that he goes by Fritz, and
only Fritz, and the Seahawks' new defensive coordinator can't help
but break into a hearty laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I understand it, my grandfather had a red-haired cocker
spaniel named Fritz,'' Shurmur offers. ``As I was crawling around
on the floor, every time he'd call the dog, I went. So that's how I
got the name. I'm named after a dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur laughs again and shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever calls me Leonard,'' he says. ``I've always been
Fritz.''
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur, and the game of football, have come a long way since
those days of rug-ratting with his grandfather's pooch in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Now 66, Shurmur is entering his 45th year of coaching football
and 24th in the National Football League. He came to Seattle from
Green Bay in January when former Packers head coach Mike Holmgren
took the job of Seahawks general manager and coach. Shurmur built
his reputation as one of the best and most innovative coaches in
the league during stints with the Detroit Lions, New England
Patriots, Los Angeles Rams, Phoenix Cardinals and the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Under that thinning patch of smoke-white hair is the mastermind
that devised so many of the defenses that have altered the course
of the game. Behind those wire-rim glasses are eyes than can
analyze and dissect every nuance of an opposing offense, and also
stop a 250-pound linebacker in his tracks with one fixed gaze.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   ``Fritz is a trip, man,'' says Eugene Robinson, a Pro Bowl free
safety with the Packers and Seahawks before jumping to Atlanta last
year. ``First, he'd come out in those little, messed-up gray sweats
that he wears. So he looked like Burgess Meredith in `Rocky.' Then,
he'd lay into us with that gravely voice and spit was flying
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd just come back at him with, `One more round, Rock,' and
we'd start doing the `Rocky' theme song and dancing around like we
were boxing. That's what's cool about Fritz; you can joke with him
as if he's one of the players.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because Shurmur has not forgotten one of the first things
he learned about the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never remove the word game from football, and game means
fun,'' he says. ``I have never ever had someone do a better job
with a frown on his face than with a smile on his face. So we laugh
and we joke around a little bit. But when it's time to go, we go.''
</P>
<P>
   And Shurmur, to twist another movie analogy, has taken a ``Star
Trek'' approach to his coaching. That is, taking his defenses where
no defenses have gone before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fritz has been extremely innovative,'' says Hudson Hauck, who
was on the same Los Angeles Rams' staff with Shurmur in the 1980s
and now coaches the offensive line for the Dallas Cowboys. ``A
couple of times when we were coaching with the Rams together, we'd
break the huddle in practice and just stop because he was running a
defense we or no one else had ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them was the ``Eagle'' defense that used only two down
linemen and five linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had five really good linebackers, and we didn't have many
defensive linemen,'' Shurmur says with a shrug. ``So it seemed
almost a sin to have really good players sitting on the bench while
you're playing with guys who aren't as good. So that `Eagle'
defense was born.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first or the last unexpected delivery by this
doctor of defense.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in his career, while coaching at the University of
Wyoming, Shurmur unleashed the blitz on college football. Later,
while with the Cardinals, he devised the ``Big Nickel'' that uses
four linemen, two linebackers and five defensive backs, and has
become as much part of football as the shotgun formation. Once,
while entering a game against the Philadelphia Eagles and
scrambling quarterback Randall Cunningham, Shurmur was down to one
healthy lineman so he deployed his Packers defense in a 1-5-5 that
robbed Cunningham of his lanes to run or pass.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of other examples. Mention Shurmur's names to
other coaches and the word innovative usually follows.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the No. 1 thing about Fritz, he's not afraid to change
things to help the team win,'' says Joe Bugel,who hired Shurmur to
coach the Cardinals' defense in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of that,'' Shurmur responds, ``comes about as a result of
survival as much as anything.''
</P>
<P>
   More of it comes about because Shurmur dreads doing something a
certain way just because that's the way it has always been done or
not trying something just because it never has been done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two statements stick at me, and what they do is refute
any responsibility to be creative,'' Shurmur says. ``That says,
`Hey, I find a comfort zone, I find guys who will fit into my
scheme and if they can't fit into my scheme I can't use them.' That
seems to be a little bit stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur is not stupid. He has helped turn playing defensive
football into a science and is the author of four books on the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fritz is a very intelligent football coach,'' Houck says.
``Not only is he real sharp and cerebral, he's also old school.
What he teaches is physical, get-down-to-basics, play-hard
football. That allows him to take some defensive sets and be
creative with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur has yet to determine exactly what he will do with a
Seahawks defense that led the NFL by scoring 10 TDs and the AFC by
collecting 53 sacks last season, but also allowed an average of
355.6 yards per game to rank 27th in the league. It's too early.
</P>
<P>
   At this week's quarterbacks camp he has been stressing
fundamentals, effort and precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea is to implement a scheme wide enough and broad
enough so we can identify the skills our guys have and find the
best spots for them,'' he said. ``It's kind of a long process.''
</P>
<P>
   The first phase was reviewing last year's games on video tape.
This week's camp is the second phase. The next phase will be seeing
the players perform in full pads, which won't happen until training
camp opens at the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Shurmur will continue to teach and scheme.
</P>
<P>
   _ _ _
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur goes back so far that what is now considered old school
was then the only school. He began his coaching career in 1954 as a
graduate assistant at his alma mater, Albion College, a small
liberal arts college in Michigan that did not have spring football.
So Shurmur spent his springs compiling the knowledge that remains
the base for everything he does. He made trips to the Michigan
State, where he became a sponge for anything offered by Spartans
head coach Duffy Dougherty and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd take the last $5 of grocery money and put enough gas in
the car to get from Albion to East Lansing, and then I'd sleep on
somebody's floor once I got there,'' Shurmur says. ``I had an
interest to see if I could progress in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur did take the next step, moving to Wyoming in 1962 and
eventually becoming head coach in 1971. He continued his learning
process. While at Wyoming, he would make trips to the St. Louis
Cardinals' training camps to study under defensive assistant
coaches Chuck Drulis and Jim Champion.
</P>
<P>
   But Shurmur really blossomed into his role as a beautiful
schemer during a nine-year stint with the Rams (1982-90), in part
because they were forced to play the San Francisco 49ers twice a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any question that was the best decade of
football anybody ever played in the National Football League. If
you didn't play well against the 49ers, they could just kill you,''
says John Robinson, the Rams head coach at that time and now coach
at UNLV.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers compiled a 96-30-1 regular-season record and won three
Super Bowls between 1983-90, when Shurmur was the Rams' defensive
coordinator. Six of those losses were to the Rams, and three times
Shurmur's defense held the 49ers to fewer than 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fritz always managed to come up with stuff that hurt them,''
Robinson says.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson talks about Shurmur being ``grounded in football and
grounded in life.'' He first saw it in the way Shurmur handling
being elevated to defensive coordinator in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fritz doesn't have an ego that gets in the way of success,''
Robinson says. ``Some of the guys who get into these coordinator
positions, their level of genius obscures all else _ including
winning and losing and the best overall interest of the team. Those
kinds of things don't get in the way with Fritz.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson continued to see it in the way Shurmur handled not
getting a head-coaching position in the NFL when less-qualified
assistant coaches did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fritz is and basically always has been a happy man. Happy with
his family. Happy with his life,'' Robinson says. ``It was always a
treat to go to work with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur's football philosophy has three tenets: play hard and
fast; play well together; and play efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   They roll from his mouth like a mantra, and the Seahawk players
will be hearing them in their sleep before the end of the first
minicamp.
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur inherits a defense that features four Pro Bowl players _
linebacker Chad Brown, defensive end Michael Sinclair, cornerback
Shawn Springs and defensive tackle Cortez Kennedy _ and made up for
a lack of consistency with big plays.
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur won't stand for such contradictory efforts. Before he
will allow his new players to spin off into what looks like some
scheme from another football galaxy, they must be grounded in the
basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the moving around we did, we simplify what we
do,'' says LeRoy Butler, the Packers Pro Bowl strong safety. ``If
you get too fancy, that's when you have a lot of breakdowns.''
</P>
<P>
   And breakdowns are the quickest way to see the dark side of
Shurmur, especially defensive penalties that prolong offensive
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a pretty volatile guy. Always have been,'' Shurmur says.
``So I tell the guys, `Just don't hold me responsible for anything
I say between 1 and 4 o'clock on Sunday, and I won't hold it
against you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Shurmur recalls getting more than one disbelieving glance from
defensive end Reggie White during his sideline snits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reggie used to kind of look at me and shake his head,''
Shurmur says. ``I'd tell him, `Reg, that's why the Good Lord put
you on this earth _ to take care of my soul.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Some expected Shurmur to retire after last season, what with
Holmgren moving to Seattle. Shurmur admits he thought Green Bay
would be his final coaching stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose someday something will tell me it's time to go, or
someone will tell me,'' Shurmur says. ``But I still come to work
each day with the same excitement I did 45 years ago. My wife says
there's something wrong with me.''
</P>
<P>
   The new fans of Shurmur's old-school ways can only hope that
excitement is contagious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
