<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1961 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      04-01 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOKIE MCCOY KEEPS IT REAL WITH POWERFUL START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ An immediate urge is to refer to him as ``The Real
McCoy.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Jelani McCoy has burst onto the court after being
virtually obscure to fans for most of this season, displaying what
the Sonics knew from the time they drafted him.
</P>
<P>
   Around the basket, McCoy is the real deal.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to describe his eye-popping penchant for rejecting
shots is to say that the blocks are the real intimidating kind. He
often plays with an expression that is real mean. His overall
skills are raw. But McCoy makes it obvious that he is real
comfortable on the court.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy's recent play has impressed to the point that a borrowed
nickname isn't justice for the 6-foot-10 forward/center. He has
blossomed into one of the team's most aggressive forces down low.
There is nothing ambiguous about that distinction.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has shown a lot better focus than he was advertised to
have,'' said Sonics coach Paul Westphal, who plans to use McCoy
often Thursday night against the young, athletic Denver Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been enthusiastic and working hard. He's really been
showing that he can play whenever he had a chance. That, coupled
with Vin (Baker's) injury and us needing help inside, it was a
natural thing to see what he can do.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been real impressive. He's really making a case for
increased playing time because of his shot-blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   McCoy's past three games have been most impressive since he was
activated Friday. He's averaged eight points, five rebounds and 2.3
blocks during the first three games of the Sonics' current
five-game, six-night road trip.
</P>
<P>
   That production has come in 19 minutes a game. The impact of
having McCoy, and fellow rookie forward Vladimir Stepania, has been
more noticeable than the statistics suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Both players are changing the flow of games with their exuberant
play. Stepania's slick ball fakes in the paint, solid outside shot
and willingness to scrap for rebounds give the team a different
dimension from the post.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy takes pleasure in being the brute on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   He attempts to throw down a vicious dunk just about every time
he receives the ball within arms-length of the rim. The Sonics
haven't seen that attitude since All-Star forward Shawn Kemp was
traded to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kemp, McCoy is strong enough to fight for rebounds. McCoy's
blocks, though, are the consistent and forceful part of his game.
</P>
<P>
   McCoy held his own in his toughest test during Tuesday's loss to
the San Antonio Spurs. He battled the Spurs' Twin Towers _ David
Robinson and Tim Duncan _ and left Duncan with a bold impression.
</P>
<P>
   On one play, McCoy leaped and blocked Duncan's shot attempt from
the foul line, then converted a dunk on the other end. McCoy
finished with four blocks in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't try to block everything, then you get caught in a
jumping-jack situation, going for everybody's head fakes,'' McCoy
said. ``But I try to get the ones that I know I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you make a big play around the basket, it sets up
your area. It sets up your paint. It changes a lot of shots. People
go in the paint second-guessing and looking around to make sure
they can get their shot off. By getting one or two blocks you might
change five or six shots in the course of a game.''
</P>
<P>
   McCoy is anything but intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   He got that out of his system after playing three seasons at
UCLA, in the NCAA tournament and against NBA players for several
summers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm used to mixing it up with pros,'' said McCoy, who left
UCLA as a junior with the school's record in career shooting
percentage (69 percent) and blocked shots (188). ``I'm not going to
be intimidated by anybody. I'm going to play my game, which is to
go out there to hustle and play hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always go out there and be aggressive. I'm not going to
let a guy have an easy layup. I'll put him on the line and make him
earn it.''
</P>
<P>
   McCoy makes his share of mistakes. He played only 16 minutes
against the Spurs because of foul trouble; Westphal wanted to use
him more. McCoy still struggles with NBA defenses. He doesn't
always know the tendencies of his opponent or when to rotate off
screens.
</P>
<P>
   Stepania has the same problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they're hustling so much and they're so active that even
when they make a mistake, the seem to recover,'' guard Hersey
Hawkins said. ``They've been getting in some kind of position to
make something good happen just by hustling around out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly enough, McCoy wasn't pegged to see much playing
time this season.
</P>
<P>
   His training camp performances weren't noteworthy. McCoy was
also considered sort of a problem child after being suspended from
the UCLA basketball team for violating team and university rules.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Sonics drafted in the second round (33rd overall),
the patented line on McCoy from team insiders was ``he's good
enough to play in this league for 10 years, or he could go the
other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict is still out, but McCoy is off to a regal start.
</P>
<P>
   ``My thing was staying mentally prepared so when I got an
opportunity, I could just play and not go out there and be happy to
be on the court,'' said McCoy, who spent 19 of the first 25 games
on the injured list. ``You get down (being on the bench). You
always want to earn your check. It's just a matter of keeping your
head and having patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely exciting (to play). But at the same time I'm
not going to go out there like a little kid. I have to act like an
adult and handle my business, which is what this game is all
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
