<HEADLINE>
STARS WIN UGLY, LOSE MODANO TO INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It wasn't pretty, but it sure was humorous.
</P>
<P>
   In what might have been their ugliest game of the season, the
Stars survived a 6-4 victory against the Tampa Bay Lightning last
night.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the Stars lost Mike Modano to a first-period
groin strain that likely will keep him out seven to 14 days. Stars
coach Ken Hitchcock said Modano, who was reaching for a loose puck
at the time of the injury, likely will miss three to five games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, that was one awful hockey game,'' Hitchcock said. ``What
you saw was a great game of \Ryouth pickup hockey\S. We ended up
winning, so we get the ice cream cones.''
</P>
<P>
   Fans couldn't tell by the performance, but the Stars improved
their NHL-best record to 47-15-12, good for 106 points.
</P>
<P>
   With eight games remaining in the regular season, that's already
the second-best record in Stars franchise history _ the team had
109 points last season _ and is 66 points better than the
Lightning, who fall to a league-worst 17-50-6.
</P>
<P>
   With Modano out of the lineup, the Stars should be able to take
a better look at their young players. Two Stars players _ Jon Sim
and Brad Lukowich _ scored their first NHL goals last night, and
young forwards Grant Marshall and Jamie Langenbrunner stepped up
their play in the absence of Modano and Guy Carbonneau, who
suffered a sprained ankle and is listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as we had some poor players, we also had some good
players,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars dominated the first period and leaped to a 3-1 lead on
strong plays by Langenbrunner, Marshall and Jere Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull carried the puck in on a breakaway and took Lightning
goalie Corey Schwab out of the play midway through the first
period. Lehtinen then swooped in to scoop in the rebound and it was
1-0 at the 10:37 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning's Stephane Richer then rambled in to push a goal
past Roman Turek and tie the game just over a minute later.
Langenbrunner answered with a wrister from the off wing at the
15:50 mark and Marshall gave the Stars a seemingly insurmountable
lead when he made it 3-1 at the 17:37 mark of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   Why insurmountable? Turek (15-2-3) had yielded three goals in
only four previous games this season and had not yielded four
before last night.
</P>
<P>
   But the scrappy Lightning wouldn't go away and the
not-so-scrappy Stars defense wouldn't settle down. Darcy Tucker
scored twice for the Lightning in the second period off great plays
from Michael Nylander to tie the score at 3-3 heading into the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, who are 12-2-5 when tied after two periods, quickly
took the lead once again on Sim's goal, a wrister from the slot set
up by Marshall. But Richer scored his second of the game at the
7:14 mark to tie the score once more.
</P>
<P>
   Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor coughed up the puck on the power
play and then let Richer walk around him for the game-tying goal in
what appeared to be a complete Stars' breakdown.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lightning defense proved even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nieuwendyk whipped in a snap shot from 35 feet to get the
game-winner at the 11:10 mark of the third period. It was
Nieuwendyk's 24th goal in 62 games this season and his eighth game
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Lukowich then added his first NHL goal when Marshall made a
smooth feed off a transition play with 1:11 remaining to seal the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could bundle this up as a ride and sell it to Disney
World,'' Hitchcock concluded. ``If there was ever justice for two
practices back to back, it's now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock said the Stars will practice hard for the next two
days before traveling to St. Louis for a game against the Blues on
Saturday.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
