<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UW-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEUHEISEL READY TO FOCUS ON FOOTBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The 23rd football coach in University of Washington
history fields a team for the first time Thursday, and Rick
Neuheisel hopes any April Fool's Day shenanigans are well behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by recruiting violations in the first month after he was
hired by the UW and sharply criticized by Colorado boosters,
players and writers for leaving the Buffaloes, Neuheisel begins
spring practice eager to get on with the more predictable business
of coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Inheriting a 6-6 team that returns 48 lettermen after losing 20
to graduation, including three starting offensive linemen,
Neuheisel's first order is to find ``a core group of guys who are
committed'' not only to him but to turning the Huskies' fortunes
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't squander any day,'' he said Wednesday. ``This is not
a team that has the luxury of just showing up.''
</P>
<P>
   At 38 the third-youngest coach in Division I, Neuheisel promises
a fresh start for the UW program and its players while treading
lightly on Husky football traditions. How does he want his team to
respond?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to play fast and furious and look like we're
having a blast,'' said Neuheisel, who replaces the fired Jim
Lambright.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the coach is approaching spring practice with an open
mind, saying he chose not to spend hours poring over video on
players so that he can evaluate them on the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to come into this with any preconceived
notions,'' Neuheisel said.
</P>
<P>
   That even extends to Brock Huard's replacement at quarterback, a
position that Marques Tuiasosopo would appear to have locked up.
Neuheisel said Tuiasosopo reminds him of Kansas State's Michael
Bishop or the Pittsburgh Steelers' Kordell Stewart, a quarterback
Neuheisel coached at Colorado in his one year as an assistant
before succeeding Bill McCartney as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   With Tuiasosopo's ability, ``the option will be a threat for
us,'' Neuheisel said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the players returning for the spring, there are five starters
on offense and eight on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fringe guys have to realize that if they're going to be on the
team, they have to come into the center,'' he said, promising not
to ``weed out'' any players until they've had a chance to prove
what they can do.
</P>
<P>
   Going into spring practice, only two players have left the team
for reasons other than graduation: sophomore tight end Kevin Cooper
transferred after the Oahu Bowl and freshman defensive back Darnell
Parhms was declared academically ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to define his coaching philosophy, Neuheisel said he plans
to be the overall administrative head of the program in its initial
stages, rather than one of the main teachers and coordinators on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that you have someone overseeing the
whole system,'' he said. ``My role needs to be evaluating and
making adjustments as we go.''
</P>
<P>
   He has former UW and Seahawk assistant Keith Gilbertson to serve
as assistant head coach and former Troy Aikman tutor Steve Axman to
coach the quarterbacks, a responsibility Neuheisel assumed until
his last year at Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   He also has Randy Hart, a Lambright assistant, returning to
coach the defensive line, a group that Neuheisel believes will
continue to be a source of strength with the return of Mac Tuiaea
and Jabari Issa. Defensively, the Huskies might try a new
three-down front line in passing situations, but Neuheisel doesn't
see a major change in focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Hart has done a great job and there's a reason we led
the nation in pressuring the quarterback,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, some of the questions might not be answered by the
end of spring practices, which culminate April 24 with the 1 p.m.
annual spring game. Neuheisel hopes to revive the inconsistent
Husky running game, but isn't yet sure how his inexperienced
offensive line will respond or if incoming freshman Paul Arnold
will be a factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that we don't want to run,'' Neuheisel said. ``But
you have to have the ability to run the ball effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though he's a former quarterback and quarterbacks coach,
that doesn't mean Neuheisel lives and dies with a passing offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I want to throw the ball. But I'm not of the mind that
you have to throw to get offense,'' he said. ``... I'm not locked
into any particular system. I'm locked into making defenses
behave.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies open the regular season with a nationally televised
ESPN Thursday night game on Sept. 9 at Brigham Young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's given me a great opportunity because the spotlight will
be on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   HUSKY NOTES: Spring practices are open to the public, beginning
Thursday at 3:35 p.m., the time for all weekday practices. The
first scrimmage is April 9 at 4 p.m., with the second scrimmage at
10 a.m. April 17. The first practice in full pads is Saturday at
9:25 a.m. ... Three players will not participate in spring
practices: Senior inside linebacker Lester Towns still is
recovering from foot surgery in January; senior tailback Maurice
Shaw is recovering from back surgery; and junior wide receiver
Ja'Warren Hooker is running track this spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
