<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY HURT IN EXHIBITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE ELSINORE -- With the news of shortstop Gary DiSarcina
having to miss the first three to four months of the season still
fresh in their minds, the Angels took another blow Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Chuck Finley, pitching against Oakland in the team's
final spring game in Tempe, Ariz., suffered a bruised left tricep
after getting nailed with a line drive off the bat of the
Athletics' Jason Giambi.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who threw out Giambi on the play, subsequently was
removed from the game after facing only three batters and throwing
20 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' probable Opening Day starter is listed as day-to-day
after being relieved by Scott Schoeneweis. Finley left Tempe Diablo
Stadium without speaking to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the last day of camp, what else can go wrong? Angels
manager Terry Collins said. ``Luckily, he's fine.
</P>
<P>
   Finley allowed a leadoff double to Tony Phillips and a walk to
Ryan Christenson before suffering the injury.
</P>
<P>
   Word of Finley's injury didn't reach many on the Angels squad
here for the team's other exhibition game Wednesday night against
the organization's top minor league prospects at the Lake Elsinore
Diamond, home of the Angels Single-A affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   But outfielder Jim Edmonds certainly is one player tired of
talking about the team's injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys just need to step up and stop making excuses, said
Edmonds, who sat out Wednesday's game, but not because of any
serious injury. ``Enough has been said about it and I think it's
time to move on.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Besides DiSarcina's situation taking a turn for the worse
Tuesday, the Angels also traded veteran third baseman Dave Hollins
to Toronto and released relief pitcher Rich DeLucia.
</P>
<P>
   Shigetoshi Hasegawa, one of DeLucia's bullpen comrades last
season, said he was a bit surprised by the club's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised because he did kind of the same job as me,
said Hasegawa, the Angels busiest reliever a year ago. ``But we
have a lot of good pitchers like (Mark) Petkovsek, (Mike) Magnante,
Toby (Borland), (Mike) Fyhrie. Those guys are all good.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa said he doesn't think his role will change this season
and expects to continue putting in plenty of work as a middle
reliever or set-up man for closer Troy Percival.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I can be a long reliever, short reliever, it doesn't
matter, Hasegawa said. ``I can do everything.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) In Wednesday night's exhibition, Angel regulars who
started were left fielder Darrin Erstad, first baseman Mo Vaughn,
designated hitter Todd Greene and center fielder Garret Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn played only the first inning and grounded out to second
in his only at-bat. Greene was scheduled to play several innings,
but those plans had to be altered.
</P>
<P>
   In his first plate appearance, Greene was struck in the chest on
a pitch by former Bonita High standout Matt Wise. Greene stayed in
the game and actually ended up scoring a run later in the inning,
but did not return. The extent of his injury was not known.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels major league club defeated a team of its minor league
all stars, 4-2 as Petkovsek pitched one-hit ball over the first
three innings and struck out four before being replaced by
Hasegawa, who pitched the next two, allowing a run on two hits.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Coach Rod Carew, who served as acting manager Wednesday,
said Collins is still toiling with the decision of who will be the
everyday shortstop until DiSarcina returns sometime after the
all-star break.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the Angels acquired two candidates through
trades, Andy Sheets from San Diego and Tomas Perez from Toronto.
Sheets appears to be the front runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't made up his mind yet, Carew said of Collins. ``We're
just going to have to play (Sheets) as much as possible and see
where he is. (Coach) Larry (Bowa) is going to work with him the
next few days.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) The Angels next game comes Friday night at Edison Field
against the Dodgers in what will be the only meeting in the
traditional Freeway Series.
</P>
<P>
   Before the spring, the Dodgers asked out of the final two games
so they could play host to the New York Yankees on those days.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds didn't seem too fazed by the snub.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care anything about the Dodgers right now, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (BOX) Former Angel Carney Lansford served as the minor league
team's manager Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lansford, who played for the Angels from 1978-80, will manage
the organization's Triple-A team in Edmonton this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
