<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-PISTONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS SPUTTER, FAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Paul Gaston watched the Celtics lose a game at the
FleetCenter Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night. He was probably as agitated as the
16,915 people who observed with him. But at least he didn't boo.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that opens up an interesting debate: Should Gaston
have been howling with the others during the Celtics' 87-72 loss to
the Pistons? If he had, no one would have said that his
dissatisfaction had anything to do with his position as chairman of
the board. No, it wasn't the type of game that irritated
millionaires who own basketball teams. It was a game that offended
basketball fans, regardless of their economic status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter, we'll take the end result,'' Grant Hill
said when the drab game was over.
</P>
<P>
   That was easy for Hill to say. He plays for the Pistons, a group
that has won 19 games this season. The Celtics? They have lost 19
games. They have lost four consecutive games at home. In three of
those games, they have walked off the court accompanied by two
sounds: music booming from big speakers and boos booming from
people with big lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night they scored 15 points in the first quarter and
33 for the entire first half. And they had to struggle for that 33,
needing a Paul Pierce runner with five-10ths of a second remaining
to get them there. Red Auerbach watched all of this from a seat
near Gaston's. He certainly didn't need to dig through his ``Red on
Roundball'' archives to see what the problem was in this one. It
seemed to be obvious, although the Celtics would provide a
different explanation later. The Celtics couldn't shoot. They
missed several layups and mid-range jumpers. They had scored 34
points in the first quarter during their win in Charlotte one night
earlier, but there were no signs of that game.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce (20 points) and Ron Mercer (16) were the only starters
who made at least half their shots. Antoine Walker was 5 of 15 from
the field, but did have 10 rebounds and 18 points. The team's
captain also was harrassed most of the night by injured Pistons
swingman Jerry Stackhouse. When Walker put up a shot, Stackhouse
would yell from the bench, ``Shoot it _ that's what we want you to
do.'' Walker also seemed to have trouble with the defense of Jerome
Williams, although he said afterward, ``To be honest with you, I
don't even think about him.''
</P>
<P>
   So after hearing about the Celtics' 15-point first quarter,
their 10-point halftime deficit, their 41 percent shooting, and
their three quarters of scoring in the teens, you are convinced
that offense was the problem, correct?
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. Offense was a problem, but not the problem. It was
not The Problem because the Pistons weren't shooting so well
themselves. When that happens, defense becomes the story. The
Celtics didn't do a good job on defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight we did not put a great effort forward,'' Pierce said.
``We were outhustled. They beat us to all the loose balls. We were
not able to get the little things done tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Take their defense of Hill. Everyone knows that the
6-foot-8-inch forward must be double-teamed. The Celtics did that
and limited Hill to one first-half field goal. What they did not do
was rotate on defense once Hill made his move. What that means,
simply, is that Hill's teammates moved when he moved. So everybody
was moving except the Celtics. And when they decided to move, they
moved too late.
</P>
<P>
   That became obvious in the fourth quarter, when the game was
still winnable, despite Boston's poor offense. It was 70-62 with
just over six minutes left. Jud Buechler had the ball. He was wide
open for a 3-pointer. He made it. Less than a minute later, he
stole the ball from Walker and got open for a 3. He made it. In
between those hoops, Pierce made a short jumper. But offense was
not the problem when the Celtics were defending like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This basketball team has to have a common denominator,''
Celtics coach Rick Pitino said. ``It has to be defense. You can't
deflate because your shot may not go in or your layup doesn't go
in. You have to keep your spirits high at the defensive end.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino said he was disappointed with the team's performance.
Kenny Anderson mentioned that the Celtics were outrun the entire
night. Pistons coach Alvin Gentry beamed about Lindsey Hunter,
whose 17 points and six assists inspired the coach to say, ``He's
playing so good it's unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics are not stunned. They have seen some strange things
happen to them this season. So strange that on a night when they
score a meager 72 points, they complain about their defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
