<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1998 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-SILVER-LADN     04-01 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-SILVER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY SUCCESS STORIES AT SILVERWOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRESTLINE, Calif. _ If you believe the doomsayers, the
largemouth bass are all but gone at Silverwood Lake, the Western
San Bernardino Mountains reservoir that has seen major turmoil in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no fish in it. It's one of the worst fisheries in
the state,'' said Pat Marley, an attorney from neighboring
Cedarpines Park who has taken the state to court to make amends for
bass lost in a controversial draining of lake.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``The quality in regard to the size of the fish has definitely
gotten better,'' said Jeff Lee, a Murrieta angling guide and
tournament director for the WON BASS Inland Empire region. ``I
wouldn't put Silverwood on the (tournament) schedule if I wasn't
absolutely convinced it was a good, exciting fishery.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who manage the lake's game fish, hearing such extremes
has become commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all a matter of perspective and your ability as an
angler,'' said Mike Giusti, a Department of Fish and Game biologist
and one of six members of a court-appointed committee expected to
make recommendations this month on how to return the lake's fishery
to its pre-drawdown condition.
</P>
<P>
   Court battles, misinformation _ one big, confusing mess. ``It's
a soap opera,'' said Silverwood's project manager Charles Keene of
the Department of Water Resources' Southern District in Glendale,
who is embroiled in the legal wranglings requiring the DWR to
return the lake's fishery to full health.
</P>
<P>
   From the scientific end, what is known is that the fishery is
not recovering at the rate anticipated once the DWR's 18-month
drawdown for earthquake retrofitting to the reservoir's outtake
tower was completed in March 1997. That's a big concern to
biologists and anglers alike; fortunately, the San Bernardino
County Superior Court is sorting it out and will require the DWR to
make amends.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is positive, according to Giusti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silverwood has a silver lining, and that is that right now you
can go up there and catch quality bass,'' the biologist noted.
``You are not going to catch a lot, but there are fish in the 2- to
5-pound range available, and there is always a potential to catch
big fish, to 8 pounds plus.''
</P>
<P>
   And fishing is really what it's all about, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   I recently pulled into Silverwood Lake State Recreation Area _
about 11 miles of seriously winding Highway 138 blacktop east of
Cajon Junction off the 15 freeway _ on an unseasonably warm Monday
not knowing what to expect. Some folks think the lake was drained
to a salt flat, killing everything in site, and that it's still
drawn down.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, the lake is every bit back up to its nearly 1,000
surface acres at an elevation of 3,352 feet; DFG surveys show that
more than 65 percent of the largemouth population was lost to the
drawdown, plunging from an estimated 13,500 bass to about 4,200.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's survey put the count at about 5,500 bass, well below
50 percent recovery and suggesting there is no way the DWR's goal
of reaching 100 percent by March 2002 would be met without help.
</P>
<P>
   At the reservoir's boat ramp I met angling guide Manny Freire of
Spring Valley Lake in Victorville. He was to show me the ins and
outs of early spring bass fishing at Silverwood.
</P>
<P>
   A tournament angler himself, Freire is convinced the fishing is
every bit as good as it was before the drawdown. He hasn't had to
change his technique, favoring a rubber-skirted jig with a brined
pork-rind trailer on a 4/0 hook _ a classic jig 'n' pig setup. And
now he's got more elbowroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's one of the best-kept bass secrets there is,''
said Freire, who uses 12-pound line with ]-ounce jigs and 15-pound
line on {-ounce jigs. ``After the drawdown, people weren't coming
up here because, they said, `They killed off all the bass.' But I
don't see any fish on the banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Using my efforts as a gauge, you'd have to side with the
pessimists, for I caught nothing on the day. During this picky bite
punctuated by afternoon winds topping out at about 30 mph, even
Freire managed just a couple of small bass.
</P>
<P>
   But he points to a 13-pound whopper caught two weeks earlier and
the results of a WON BASS tournament held the day before as
evidence many quality bass swim in the lake. Six bass weighing more
than 6 pounds were brought to the scales by the 37 two-angler teams
during the event; the big fish was an 8.38-pounder. There were six
five-fish limits registered, the winners boasting a total weight of
22\ pounds, or 4.45 pounds per bass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our minds were blown after this last tournament,'' Lee said.
``It just never stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Giusti, who served as weighmaster for the contest, was
encouraged to see there were a lot of big fish. ``But I'm
discouraged to see fewer small fish,'' he said. ``I would rather
have guys say, `I had to catch 50 10-inch fish to get a limit of
five keeper fish.' But there weren't any small fish. You need to
see fish from 2 inches to 12 inches. In most populations, your
largest number of fish are going to be small, below the legal size
limit (12 inches).''
</P>
<P>
   That means the bass are either having unsuccessful spawns or the
young are being preyed upon by the lake's non-game residents _
goldfish, Sacramento blackfish, hitch and carp, which make up more
than 80 percent of the population. Giusti estimates that before the
drawdown the lake enjoyed a 50-50 split of game fish to non-game
species.
</P>
<P>
   Among the recommendations offered in court by Marley and his
petitioners _ including the Southern California Bass Council and
the 53 bass clubs and related organizations it represents _ is to
commercially harvest non-game fish, stock largemouths and install
better artificial habitat for the bass.
</P>
<P>
   The court-appointed committee will take the suggestions and come
up with a resolution by mid-April, Giusti said. The next court date
to confer on the DWR mitigation process is June 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role will be implementing whatever the court says we have
to do,'' said Keene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DWR will cover the cost. It's our responsibility to do
that, and we will meet our responsibilities. That is part of our
mitigation. The intent of the DWR is to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Step back from the legalese for a moment, listen to Freire's
assessment of 27-year-old Silverwood Lake and you'd think it's a
plumber's paradise. It's like a toilet bowl, being constantly
flushed by the California Aqueduct. Sometimes you need everything,
including the kitchen sink, to fool some of these wily
bucketmouths. And there's a nearshore section of the impoundment
called the washing machine, which attracts big bass chasing
windswept baitfish.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just hope all the controversy, innuendo and mitigation
comes out in the washing machine. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
