<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 01:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2002 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEAR-FRAUGHT-FRAU-WAR     04-01 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEAR-FRAUGHT-FRAU-WAR-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN ANTI-WAR MOTHERS WANT TO MEET WITH MILOSEVIC  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This TIMELY 925-word ``separate buy'' article is from The
Independent newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By IMRE KARACS  
 c.1999 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ ``The Albanians are helpless,'' says Ilona Rothe.
``It's a crime what's happening to them. I don't know how I would
feel if I weren't personally involved.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Rothe is involved, because her son is one of 3,000
German soldiers awaiting orders in Macedonia. So she is against the
war in the Balkans, against NATO air strikes, and bitterly opposed
to German participation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rothe is the founder of ``Mothers Against the War,'' a
movement only a week old but already enjoying national fame.
</P>
<P>
   It began with a heartrending proclamation in the form of a
reader's letter addressed to a Berlin newspaper, accompanied with
her telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, she has received more than 1,000 calls, appeared on
television talk shows, and there is now talk of sending her to sort
it all out with Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have touched a nerve in Germany,'' she says. ``I hear the
women crying on the telephone for their beloved, their sons or
their husbands. They tell me about their suffering, and sometimes
about the medical treatment they are receiving for their anguish.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the Balkans, no country in Europe has felt the trauma of
war as acutely as Germany. A nation of pacifists for two
generations, Germans now find themselves striding into the quagmire
of Yugoslavia, with soldiers and their relatives at home mentally
unprepared for shedding blood.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rothe's 24-year-old son _ she will not give his first name
because ``I've already caused him enough trouble'' _ signed up for
the Bundeswehr four years ago, expecting little travel and even
less action.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three weeks, they have all been waiting in
Macedonia for an order that up to recently would have been
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``They lie awake at night, get up at half-past five in the
morning, and the first thing they do is listen to the news,'' Ms.
Rothe says. ``All sorts of questions are swirling in their heads:
`What happened last night? What if they fired a rocket at us? We
would be the perfect target.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rothe's son bears a weapon but he is a maintenance man for
the tank crews. He will not ride inside the tanks, if they ever set
off for Kosovo, and his gun is for self-defense only.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he and his comrades have done nothing more violent than
polishing the barrels, but the Luftwaffe is busy dropping bombs
Yugoslavia every day, and the possibility of using ground troops is
no longer excluded with as much vehemence as it was only a few days
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rothe, who in peacetime ran a removals firm in the east
German town of Erfurt, is trying to prevent that by giving peace a
chance. ``I heard an interview with a Serbian mother, in which she
said: `I want my son, I don't care about Milosevic.' That's how I
feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Her group proposes that ``all weapons fall silent immediately,''
and representatives from all sides uncompromised by past actions
gather around the negotiating table. Also in attendance should be
human-rights experts and an international womens' group.
</P>
<P>
   No, she does not think she is being naive. Naive were the
Western politicians ``who had eaten and drunk with Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They know what kind of a guy he is,'' she says. ``They have
given him one line: `This way or we bomb you.' And what have they
achieved? Did they not force the Serbs to close ranks? Are we not
risking a Third World War here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``We sit in front of the television in the evenings, and see
these wonderful computer simulations,'' she continues. ``And they
report that things are getting worse for the Serbs. And that one
atrocity is worse than the other atrocity. Somehow I just don't
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no easy answers. But German public opinion, despite
the traditional misgivings, is slowly coming around to the
``something must be done'' view.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest polls, 28 percent reject the use of
ground troops, but 47 percent think the Bundeswehr should not stay
out if NATO soldiers were to cross into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But faced by the pictures of fleeing Albanians, support for air
strikes has increased, with 62 percent of Germans now in favor.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the east, where a few days ago less than half of those
polled approved of the bombing, there is now a narrow majority in
favor. Three-quarters of west Germans approve.
</P>
<P>
   While German newspapers remain at best skeptical, and
politicians on the left campaign for a cease-fire, one group of
Germans have undergone a spectacular metamorphosis.
</P>
<P>
   The Greens are pacifists no longer. According to the latest
polls, 72 percent of Green supporters say the air strikes are
justified.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yugoslav government wanted to destroy NATO's resolve by
engineering a humanitarian catastrophe, the gambit has clearly
failed in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The images of civilians in flight from organized brutality are
painfully familiar here, triggering knee-jerk reactions that
Germans thought they had purged long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say, when I look at Milosevic, he reminds me of
Hitler,'' Ms. Rothe says. If her son were not in the firing line,
maybe even she could be persuaded to support bombing the Serbian
leader to smithereens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Couldn't somebody poison him?'' she asks, only half in jest. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 925-word article, it must be purchased from the
New York Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
