 (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For THURSDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Thursday, April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO  &LR; _ (Moved in ``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ The top civilian and military leaders
of NATO settled on a strategy of bombing alone against Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic despite several military assessments
and intelligence warnings, and even a clue from a Yugoslav general,
that bombs without ground forces could not stop Serb forces from
launching a purge in Kosovo. By Craig R. Whitney and Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ It is telling that only four days
into a long-planned bombardment campaign against the forces of
Slobodan Milosevic, President Clinton needed to buck up the senior
officials who advised him to pursue the military option. By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SOLANA (Brussels) _ A man-in-the-news profile of the head
of NATO: Javier Solana Madariaga, who as secretary general of NATO
is running the biggest air war the alliance has ever fought in 50
years of existence, opposed Spain's entry into the organization as
a young Socialist opposition politician in the early 1980s. By
Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VUKOVAR (Vukovar, Croatia) _ This ruined city beside the
Danube River is as good a place as any to meditate on the years of
misery and score-settling that lie ahead when the Serb campaign in
Kosovo comes to an end. By Blaine Harden.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STEALTH (Undated) _ In the wake of the recent downing of
the stealth fighter over Yugoslavia, a look at how stealth
technology works _ and doesn't work. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ASSESS (Budapest, Hungary) _ The crisis in Kosovo
presents precisely the kind of problem that the Western
democracies, for all their wealth and military might, find it most
difficult to cope with. And it is likely to be repeated elsewhere.
By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-TEMPLE-THEFT (Banteay Chhmar, Cambodia) _ One of the
boldest and most destructive temple robberies ever carried out in
Cambodia might have gone undiscovered for months or even years if
Claude Jacques had not wandered into an antique shop in Thailand
last December. By Seth Mydans. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAELI-POLITICS (Shfayim, Israel) _ Battling for every vote
they can obtain in a tight race, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and his opponents took their campaigns this week to Arab villages
and towns, paying holiday visits during the four-day Muslim Feast
of the Sacrifice. Arabs make up 12 percent of the electorate, and
their votes could be crucial in determining the outcome of the
balloting on May 17. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-OBUCI (Tokyo) _ When Keizo Obuchi was seeking the prime
minister's job last summer, he was dismissed as having ``all the
pizazz of a cold pizza.'' By Nicholas D. Kristof.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   HEMP-FARMERS (Bismarck, N.D.) _ Battered by sinking commodity
prices and rising costs, wheat farmers are looking across the
Canadian border at a crop they say could help save them _ if only
it were legal. That crop is hemp, banned in the United States as
part of the war on drugs. As farmers from Hawaii to North Dakota to
Vermont lobby state legislatures to study hemp's potential and make
it legal, they are opposed by federal officials unwilling to relax
drug laws even symbolically, whether by endorsing marijuana's
medical use, or by approving a once-common crop, hemp. By
Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   WVA-RESORT-CASINO (White Sulphur Springs, W.Va.) _ The paradox
of a luxury resort in a working-class county has always been
apparent here in southeastern West Virginia. But now it is fueling
a political fight, pitting the values of rural Christian
fundamentalists against a lifestyle of golf, aroma therapy and
finger bowls with breakfast. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   BLUE-MOON (Undated) _ It was supposed to be a banner year for
blue moons, with one in January and another that rose Wednesday
night, as March drew to a close. But now the astronomy magazine Sky
and Telescope has discovered that the modern definition of a blue
moon _ as the second full moon in a month _ is based upon an error
made more than five decades ago. And the perpetrator was none other
than Sky and Telescope itself. By Henry Fountain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-REPORT (Washington) _ The White House says that 92 percent
of the federal government's essential computer systems are ready
for the year 2000, but predicts that Americans will have difficulty
reaching some foreign countries by telephone or airplane next year,
because their computers will not be fixed in time. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ With its deep divisions over federal
authority versus state sovereignty on full view, the Supreme Court
may be on the verge of tilting even further in the direction of the
states than it had gone in a series of recent 5-4 decisions. By
Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-TUBES (Undated) _ With considerable hubris, Konka Group
Co. is seeking to make the leap from a well-known brand in China to
global consumer-electronics maker by grabbing a share of the U.S.
market for television sets. By Sharon R. King.
</P>
<P>
   BP-ARCO (Undated) _ With the acquisition of Amoco, Sir John
Browne, chief executive of BP Amoco, cut tens of thousands of jobs
and left an organization where there is almost no layer of middle
management and constant pressure to do better. Now he is poised to
do the same with ARCO. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   UNDERWRITING-QTR (New York) _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. underwrote
more securities than any other Wall Street firm in the first
quarter of 1999, while Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. was the leader in
mergers and acquisitions, according to rankings announced
Wednesday. By Joseph Kahn. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IBM-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Saying it hoped to ward off government
regulation and increase consumer confidence in electronic commerce,
IBM said Wednesday that it would pull its advertisements from Web
sites that lack clear privacy policies. By Jeri Clausing.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CIRCUITS &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CIR-MEMORY (Undated) _ The changing shape of memory, with a look
at Sony's memory stick and other very small devices for storing
very large amounts of memory. By Michel Marriott.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and timeline graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CIR-GOVERNMENT-EMAIL (Undated) _ Behind closed E-mail. A look at
