<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 03:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2103 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLAVE-LABOR-SFCHRON &LR;      04-01 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVE-LABOR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIF. GOV. GRAY DAVIS JOINS SUIT OVER NAZI SLAVERY  &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California Gov. Gray Davis has joined a private
lawsuit seeking what could be millions of dollars in damages from
Ford, General Motors and five German companies for allegedly
profiting from Nazi slave labor during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Besides alleging forced labor, the suit also claims that the
companies seized or took over the assets of German Jews during the
war.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is involved in the suit as a private citizen, not as
governor, said Hilary McLean, a spokeswoman in the governor's
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something he feels very strongly about,'' she said. ``He
wants to lend moral support.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed Wednesday in San Francisco Superior Court,
alleges that those actions are unfair competition under California
law. It calls on the court to order the companies to provide
restitution for the victims and divest themselves of those assets
and any profits those assets may have generated in California over
more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ford and General Motors were named because of the wartime
actions of their subsidiaries in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies that use slave labor should not be allowed to keep
the profits of the atrocities they committed in pursuit of business
profits,'' said Morris Ratner, a partner at Lieff, Cabraser,
Heimann and Bernstein, one of the law firms that filed the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Also named as plaintiffs in the suit are the Simon Wiesenthal
Center, a Holocaust studies organization in Los Angeles, and a
handful of Holocaust survivors living in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am joining this important lawsuit to maximize the just
compensation due to victims of the Nazi war machine,'' Davis said
in a statement. ``Common decency demands that those who were made
slaves ... should be compensated for the labor stolen from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Although a number of suits seeking compensation from German
companies for their wartime actions have been filed both in the
United States and abroad, Davis' name on the San Francisco action
is designed to raise the profile of the suit, McLean said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the lead attorneys in the suit is William Lerach, a San
Diego lawyer who was one of Davis' biggest donors in last year's
governor's race. Lerach personally gave $120,000 to the Davis
campaign, while his law firm donated $80,000 more. In additional,
Lerach raised hundreds of thousands more from California personal
injury lawyers, both for Davis and for other Democratic campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Davis became involved in the legal action at the request of the
Wiesenthal center, which he has worked with for more than 20 years,
McLean said.
</P>
<P>
   Suits under the state's wide-ranging unfair competition law have
been criticized for allowing lawyers to collect large fees without
necessarily compensating the alleged victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I applaud the attorneys who have taken up this just
cause on behalf of victims of the Nazis, I urge them to minimize
their fees and other costs relating to this litigation,'' Davis
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
