<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Castro wins again, by being Castro
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, April 4, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It wasn't a good week for Cuban dissidents or exiles. It
was a week when Fidel Castro again basked in a world spotlight,
sandwiched between the commissioner of Major League Baseball and
the owner of the Baltimore Orioles. It was a week when American
entertainers such as Jimmy Buffett came to Havana to jam with Cuban
artists; it was a week when a Vermont senator, while in Havana,
called for an end to the travel ban to the communist island.
</P>
<P>
   I found Sen. Patrick Leahy's proposal almost amusing, as anyone
who wants to go to Cuba already goes to Cuba, including Sen.
Patrick Leahy.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious that segments of the American population and
political structure are seeking warmer ties with Cuba, and that's
because Fidel Castro, like the snake-oil salesman he is, has
charmed them. He charms everyone, even the pope.
</P>
<P>
   (Anyone read anything lately about the pope calling Fidel to get
him to abandon the sentence of a firing squad for a Salvadoran
terrorist who set bombs in Havana hotels? It seems the pope calls
the U.S. weekly trying to head off executions.)
</P>
<P>
   The baseball commissioner, Bud Selig, said the game was all
about continuing U.S. efforts to broaden cultural exchanges with
the communist island, and I'd like to know when that became a
policy. I thought our position on Cuba was to isolate, to enforce
Helms-Burton -- which is not being enforced -- and to run Fidel out
of power.
</P>
<P>
   I never have believed the embargo was functioning anyway,
despite all those photos of antique automobiles in the streets of
Havana. It's the United States that has been isolated by its
embargo. Everyone trades with Cuba. Foreign investors build hotels,
receive land from the Marxist government that was taken from Cuban
and American investors in 1959 and 1960, create plush resorts.
</P>
<P>
   There is a ton of money coming into Cuba despite our obsolete
embargo, yet you don't see the people thriving, you don't see 1998
Toyotas instead of 1957 Chevrolets, you don't see restored
buildings -- only shambles of what once was.
</P>
<P>
   For all those decades of the embargo, Castro has used it to
unify his people; told them they were downtrodden because of the
Americans. So where has all that money gone that is borne in on a
wave of tourism, of construction, of investment?
</P>
<P>
   Castro keeps telling his people to tighten their belts because
of the U.S. embargo, but his seems to be getting looser and looser.
</P>
<P>
   Do not talk with him about the ongoing trial of four dissidents
who dared to say what they thought. That is not allowed in Cuba.
But listen to him brag that again this year a religious procession
has been allowed to pass through the streets of Havana to
commemorate Good Friday. In the U.S. and most everywhere else in
the world, that is a right, not a special permission.
</P>
<P>
   The American baseball commissioner and the owner of the
Baltimore Orioles may have thought the game last weekend was about
sports, but it wasn't. It was pure politics -- or Fidel wouldn't
have been there. He knew the American TV cameras were on him, that
dozens of American reporters were there to quote his every
utterance, observe his banter with the Orioles players.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the world, we take harsh action against dictators
who keep their boots on the throats of their people. We do it with
bombs, missiles, troops, embargoes that hold.
</P>
<P>
   Castro is a different story. His inexplicably attained world
prestige seems to grow with the tenure of his dictatorship. He is
an ardent revolutionary.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Americans and Cuban exiles talk in terms of how
things will change once Fidel dies -- like the exiles from Miami
will parade into Havana and make everything whole again.
</P>
<P>
   There is an impression among those gullibles that Castro is the
only Marxist holding things together in Havana. Think harder.
Castro could drop dead tomorrow; there will be thousands of
hard-line communists remaining to carry on his work.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
