<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: A good judge of judges
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ State District Judge Gerald Goodwin, who holds
forth as court jester most mornings at Firehouse Charlie's Cafe
downtown, was telling about the years he studied under Houston's
Judge Jimmy Duncan, now retired.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that back then, in the early 1970s, Judge Duncan of
the county court at law was annually named worst judge by vote of
the Houston Bar Association. ``That was only because they were all
scared of him,'' Gerald said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Gerald seemed attracted to one another. So it was that he
named Gerald ``Pine Knot,'' a semi-term of endearment reflecting
Gerald's upbringing in deep dark East Texas.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, as a newly minted attorney fresh out of law
school, Gerald took off for Houston, a U-Haul in tow, to start his
career as an assistant D.A. in the big city.
</P>
<P>
   He counts it as time well invested, thanks to the tutelage of
Judge Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   They got crossed up right off, Gerald says. The judge referred
to Gerald's performance in his court as stupid, and Gerald said as
much in open court concerning the judge's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that he made my life hell for months,'' Gerald said.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Duncan was a past master of such devilment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember how many times the judge would be calling the
docket ... `Jenny Jones, charged with DWI, are you represented by
counsel?' ... `No sir,' the young woman would answer, her voice
trembling. `My lawyer said if my case was in your court, I was on
my own.'''
</P>
<P>
   But try as the judge might, he couldn't run off Gerald. That's
when he took to calling him Pine Knot. Pine knots, in case you've
never tried to saw through one, are hard and tough.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt Gerald may have reminded him of himself at an earlier
age.
</P>
<P>
   ``He carried a .45 stuck in his belt there on the bench,''
Gerald said. ``He'd go to r'ar back in his chair, you'd hear this
heavy thud of something hitting the floor, and you'd know Judge
Duncan's pistol had come loose again.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge had a particular way of handling objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't say, `Your honor, I object to his leading the
witness,''' Gerald said. ``He'd growl at you, `Son, you don't have
to tell me he's leading the witness. I know what you're objecting
to. Or do you think I'm stupid?'''
</P>
<P>
   So all a lawyer could say was, ``Your honor, I object.'' Which
made a problem if you were the one doing the questioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd ask a question,'' Gerald said, ``the defense lawyer would
say, `I object,' and the judge would say, `Sustained.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'd try to change up the question and ask it again. The
other lawyer would object again, and the judge sustained it again.
This time he pointed to me and added, `You do that one more time
and you're going to jail for contempt.'
</P>
<P>
   ``My next question would be something like, `Mr. Jones, what do
you remember about the weather that day?'''
</P>
<P>
   A lady once called Gerald after serving on a jury in a case he
was prosecuting before Judge Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you spend most every day like that?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, yes ma'am, that's my job,'' Gerald said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You poor, poor man,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald stayed in Houston six years. That's how long, he says, it
took him to save the money to rent the same U-Haul to move back
home to Lufkin.
</P>
<P>
   Before it was over, Judge Duncan had come to appreciate him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be walking into his courtroom, and there'd be a bunch of
other lawyers gathered around the door and in the aisle,'' Gerald
said. ``The judge would bellow from the bench, `Stand back, boys!
Make way for a real lawyer!'''
</P>
<P>
   Good story. Good breakfast. Good judges.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin, TX,
75915.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
