</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Looks like war
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're at war in the Balkans _ you, me, our country. America. I
mention this because, while everyone knows it is so, no one seems
actually to have noticed, much less to care. There is an eerie
detachment, as if our war were _ what? _ say, a balloon, floating
out there somewhere but tethered to us only by a thin string, no
burden but after a while not much of an entertainment either. Just
sort of _ around.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the thing is all over the TV network news. It leads every
program. Newspapers spill it over full pages. There are ritual
briefings at NATO headquarters, the Pentagon, the State Department.
Screens fill with serious visages speaking somberly.
</P>
<P>
   But the war enters common conversation, if at all, only in
shallow dips at the margins. It seems to be on almost no one's
mind. ``How about Kosovo?'' is more a conversation killer than
starter, at first usually evoking only confusion and then
indifferent recognition.
</P>
<P>
   We are shooting up Serbia and, to a lesser degree, other parts
of what is left of Yugoslavia. Pouring explosives on the bomb
sites, and the political tinder, in a very modern version of
dumping boiling oil from the battlements _ that is to say, at least
for now, at relatively safe remove from most rejoinders and distant
from the horrors where the oil strips off skin and washes away
lives.
</P>
<P>
   There can be no doubt who the malefactors are in this matter.
Serbia and its awful Slobodan Milosevic first provoked a guerrilla
resistance _ itself a nasty business _ by ending the traditional
autonomy of Albanian-majority Kosovo and then used that resistance
as an excuse for another of their eager ``ethnic cleansings.''
</P>
<P>
   However this matter ends, it will have been the special
contribution of the Serbs, just as the century was running out, to
have added a new horror to the thick catalog of human torments this
century will pass on to the next. Is genocide a wee bit much for
you? The Serbs offer, as a slightly lesser alternative, ethnic
cleansing, in which citizens are murdered wholesale and whole towns
are cindered by way of forcing the larger number of survivors to
flee to other countries, all in a calculated application of tragedy
as an instrument of policy.
</P>
<P>
   It is by no means clear that NATO's bombing isn't exacerbating
the very problem it is meant to blunt, or that more of it will be
any more effective, or that it won't set off the region's
firecracker mini-states. We'll see. Military and policy planners
ask for time. All right.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there's this weird disconnect. The war plays as if it
were a video game. Some thousands of miles away, and thousands of
feet below us, or so it seems, there is another puff of silent
explosion. These are hits, not kills. We bomb, not people, but
targets. Refugees are churned up, but our attention drifts. Video
games are not much as spectator sports. There's no engagement when
you don't have the joy stick.
</P>
<P>
   But our virtual war is another people's bloody hell. Even in a
good cause, we owe ground zero the courtesy of caring.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
