A2387 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN02-COX     04-01 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suitcases end up scattered there and yonder
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Tony Bennett left his heart in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   I left my luggage in Orlando, Fla. And Atlanta. And points in
between.
</P>
<P>
   I've been on the road most of the past two weeks, attending
company meetings twice in Florida. Tough duty, I know. It's hard to
come back with a Florida tan and say with a straight face what a
long half-month it's been out of town.
</P>
<P>
   But God is a practical joker, and getting there and back, then
there and back again, was no picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling by air to Orlando during spring break should qualify
one for the loony bin. The plane was completely full, populated
primarily with young parents and their impatient children headed
for Disney World. I was not going to Disney World. By the time the
plane landed, the children wailed incessantly, and I was ready to
slug Mickey and mug Goofy.
</P>
<P>
   I have a pet peeve. Actually, I have several, being increasingly
curmudgeonly as time passes me by, but this one is relevant to our
conversation. My airline peeve is people who insist on trying to
carry all their luggage on board and stuff it in the overhead bins
rather than check it. The flight to Orlando was scheduled to last
two hours. One hour was spent loading people and unloading people.
At least 50 minutes of that hour was spent standing in the narrow
aisles as passengers attempted to stick suitcases the size of sides
of beef into the overhead compartments, just so they wouldn't have
to head down to baggage claim when the plane landed.
</P>
<P>
   This irritates me. It irritates the airlines too, which have
tried to crack down with little success. I am a good toad, checking
everything except my briefcase even if technically I could fit it
into the overhead bins. I feel morally superior and have been known
to exchange snide comments with other rule-obeyers as we watch some
poor lug try to wrestle his life's belongings out without beaning a
blue-haired lady sitting below.
</P>
<P>
   As Roberto Duran said when Sugar Ray Leonard whupped him in a
classic prize fight some years back, ``No mas.'' No more. If my
luggage is in the bin above me, one of two things are going to
happen. The luggage will depart the plane at the same time I do, or
the plane will crash, and it won't really matter.
</P>
<P>
   The first episode really wasn't the airline's fault. My golf
clubs got lost somewhere between the course and the hotel, and I
had to reluctantly leave without them. No big deal. The hotel
assured me they would find and ship them, and besides, they have
insurance. A week later, the clubs showed up on the big brown
truck.
</P>
<P>
   I returned home for two days and then flew to Palm Beach for
another meeting. Again, the cattle car was full, the flight
attendants harried, and the plane late. On the trip home, I had to
fly to Atlanta and switch planes to get to Shreveport, with a
one-and-a-half-hour layover in Georgia. Plenty of time.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderboomers hit Atlanta, and we sat on the runway in Palm
Beach for an hour. My window of opportunity was lessening. When we
hit Atlanta, aka the Airport From Hell, we spent another half hour
taxiing to the terminal. I had two minutes to spare before my next
flight. I made the flight, jubilant that I wasn't stuck in Atlanta
for the night, since this was the last flight to Shreveport.
</P>
<P>
   My luggage wasn't so lucky. And that's where stupidity came into
play. I had tossed my car keys in my small bag before I left
Shreveport four days earlier, intending to get them out before I
got back on the plane. I returned to Shreveport at 9 p.m. with no
luggage and no car keys, since I had checked the bag.
</P>
<P>
   The baggage clerk said there was an outside chance my luggage
would make it on a flight from Jackson, Miss., so I hung around the
airport until after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   No luck. I could tell he thought I was an idiot for putting my
keys in my luggage. I couldn't argue the point. The airline sprung
for a hotel room down the street and gave me a toiletry kit and a
voucher for a free breakfast. I spent the night in Shreveport,
resisting the temptation to go to a casino and play blackjack all
night long. Mainly, I was worried they wouldn't let me in, since by
then I had been in the same clothes for nearly 24 hours and smelled
a tad ripe.
</P>
<P>
   I was back in the airport at nine the next morning, awaiting the
red-eye from Atlanta. Funk artist Rick James got off the plane,
resplendent in a green silk outfit, accompanied by a lot of large
people wearing sunglasses and black clothes. He got into a waiting
limo while I sat in the corner fearful that my stinky clothes would
brand me as a vagrant. The cops kept eyeing me, and I just smiled
and tried to keep my eyes focused.
</P>
<P>
   My luggage showed up on the same flight with Rick James, along
with my car keys. I drove home with the window down, vowing to find
a set of collapsible golf clubs and a tiny suitcase before the next
trip.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
