<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Balkans and a time warp
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas - If you were a newspaper reader in 1914, you'd be
reading a lot about events in a far away city named Sarajevo. You'd
be reading about the war consuming Europe because a Serbian patriot
assassinated the archduke of Austria.
</P>
<P>
   If you were a newspaper reader in Texas in 1914, you'd be
reading about how a lopsided distribution of wealth coupled with
cancerous government corruption sparked a civil war in Mexico. That
civil war, in turn, caused a wave of immigration that was as
massive as it was unprecedented from that country to this.
</P>
<P>
   We live the consequences of those events today.
</P>
<P>
   I've been reading the newspapers for the past couple of weeks
wondering whether I'm in some kind of time warp. As a history
major, I concentrated on the Mexican revolution of 1910 and U.S.
history from the 1920s. The latter involved the events that led to
World War I. You really can't understand the developments in the
'20s and beyond without having a working knowledge of what was then
known as the Great War and its impact on the United States.
</P>
<P>
   That's why events in the Balkans strike me as proof of Harry
Truman's definition of news: It's history we haven't read yet. I
can appreciate the quandary in which the president, the joint
chiefs and the NATO alliance find themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, I'm blessed with access to all kinds of experts
(recognized and not) who are generous with the benefit of their
knowledge and insight into what could or should happen in the
Balkans. I was in the room when a guy who wears a lot of stars on
his collar briefed a relatively small group of Austinites on the
military situation in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Reasonable people believe that letting the situation in the
Balkans go unchecked threatens the stability of Europe. People who
are just as reasonable believe we are playing with the matches that
could start World War III.
</P>
<P>
   Only the most cockeyed optimists believe we can achieve ``our
goals'' _ whatever they are _ with air strikes alone. Whatever
technological advances we've made since World War I, it still takes
ground forces to win wars. Today's infantry soldier may carry some
very high-tech gear, but he's still a trooper with a rifle who has
to fight to get from Point A to Point B.
</P>
<P>
   I get paid to ponder, so I started pondering about the prospect
of a long, drawn-out war in the Balkans. How much will could the
American people muster once the body bags started coming home? How
long before the arguments would begin over the impact of a retreat
from our resolve? Even if we somehow stop the genocide through
force (``Stop those massacres, or we'll kill you''), we would have
to maintain a ``presence'' in the Balkans as we've had to do most
places where U.S. troops have seen battle.
</P>
<P>
   One notable exception, of course, was Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Very roughly speaking, the U.S. share of the Vietnam War lasted
from 1964 through 1974, with the six-year period between 1966 and
1972 exacting the heaviest casualties.
</P>
<P>
   So, a boy who was 12 when American involvement started had a
pretty good chance of getting involved in it one way or another
before the war finally ended with that ignominious withdrawal from
the embassy roof in Saigon. You've seen those pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I direct your attention to another young man. He is my
12-year-old son, Teodoro C. Garcia, or Teo to those who know him.
He is a very determined, very serious young man with a plan. His
plan is to earn a place in the U.S. Naval Academy in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring his perspective was just as valid _ maybe even more so
_ than many of the experts I talk to, I asked him what he thought
of the air strike launch.
</P>
<P>
   He gave me a rundown of the players, the stakes and even a
little about the terrain. We talked about the possibility of an
extended involvement and his chances of participating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it depends on my career path,'' he replied in earnest.
``If I go into aviation, I'll be flying air strikes against them.
If I go into the SEALs, I'll be doing black ops. If I go into
submarines, I'll be firing missiles at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Young Mr. Garcia, the future ensign, did not display a shred of
a notion of doubt about his future. Like any other young person, he
didn't give the risk so much as a nod.
</P>
<P>
   Risk is not something he thinks about. That's something I think
about.
</P>
<P>
   Teo may change his mind about the military, but he's pretty sold
on it and has been for two or three years now. He would be the
third generation of our family to serve, and I will be proud of
him. If he changes his mind about the Navy, that's OK with me, too.
</P>
<P>
   As this Balkans business progresses, I will be looking at it
with an eye toward 1914 and my young man's future. I will be
looking at the wire stories from both an intellectual and emotional
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a son or daughter involved in this conflict, God
bless them.
</P>
<P>
   And may God bless you.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Garcia is editorial page editor of the Austin
American-Statesman. You may contact him at agarcia(at)statesman.com
or 445-3667.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
