A2391 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MATRIX02-COX     04-01 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MATRIX02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eye-popping `Matrix' takes high-tech joy ride powered by nonstop
action
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Get ready to plug in. A dynamite science fiction flick
opened Wednesday, and it's not George Lucas' ``Star Wars'' prequel.
</P>
<P>
   With ``The Matrix,'' writer-directors Andy and Larry Wachowski,
the brothers who updated film noir with 1996's teasingly sexy
``Bound,'' bring their sharp storytelling and visual showmanship to
a new genre. Balancing intelligence with knockout special effects
and action, it's a movie that earns its explosions, high kicks and
cascades of spent bullets.
</P>
<P>
   Keanu Reeves plays Thomas ``Neo'' Anderson, a computer
programmer living in what appears to be a medium-size American city
of the late 1990s. But his life has lately become a tangle of
reality and dreams. His computer seems to be talking to him. A
black-leather babe named Trinity (Carrie-Anne Moss) slinks by
whispering news of a legendary hacker named Morpheus (Laurence
Fishburne). Then there's a clutch of men in black, led by Agent
Smith (Hugo Weaving), who take Neo into custody and jam a literal
electronic bug up his navel.
</P>
<P>
   By the time ``Matrix'' slows down to explain what's going on,
we're hooked. Awakened to a reality far different (and darker) from
the life he thought he was living, Neo finds he's been chosen by
Morpheus and a band of rebels to free mankind from a gruesome
enslavement.
</P>
<P>
   The movie presents a frightening variation of our plugged-in
world of Internet access and video games: What if what we believed
to be real life was actually a complex virtual-reality program
designed by computers? The movie borrows the dystopian future from
``The Terminator,'' Goth fashions from ``The Crow,'' a prophesied
messiah straight out of ``Dune,'' the live-or-Memorex conundrums of
``Total Recall'' and the jittery paranoia of last year's cultish
mind-blower ``Dark City.'' But these secondhand parts are fused
into an adventure that should please both comic-book fanatics and
mainstream moviegoers _ at least those with attention spans
resilient enough to follow the twisty plot.
</P>
<P>
   The Wachowskis take a risk midway through by slowing down and
taking time to explain the rules of the game. (Congratulations to
Warner Bros. for not trying to trim the film and wreck its logic.)
The movie treads through Joseph Campbell and Jungian territory,
creating a mythic plot line that leads Neo from naivete to a
mystical discovery of his own heroism.
</P>
<P>
   Though they may be cliche by the time Lucas' ``The Phantom
Menace'' does debut, the special effects are fresh and bracing _
whether we watch someone run up a wall to avoid bullets, or stop in
midair to deliver a karate kick. The movie's digitally manipulated
fight scenes play like a high-tech version of the surreal action
ballets you find in Hong Kong movies; gravity is a minor obstacle.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the action and FX, ``The Matrix'' offers smart, off-kilter
details. One example: a character known as the Oracle, a psychic
prophetess played by Gloria Foster as a matter-of-fact matron
living in a faded high-rise apartment.
</P>
<P>
   For all its sexy, nihilistic glamour, the movie doesn't take
itself too seriously. The Wachowskis throw in a wry, Old West
homage in the climactic showdown and get laughs from a character's
ability to mentally download complex computer programs in a matter
of seconds. The flick also has some unintentional giggles due to
Reeves. He's solid, but when he strikes a kung fu position, you
expect him to shout ``Dude!'' It's like being told the messiah is
the guy who delivers your pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Fishburne's mentor figure gives the movie the dramatic
heft it needs. Australian actor Weaving as the chief baddy turns in
a drily arch performance, delivering his lines in the plummy tones
of a Sunday news commentator. The movie's real find is leather-clad
Moss, powerful and sexy in equal measure (the movie kicks off with
her making mincemeat of some cops).
</P>
<P>
   A smartly calibrated mix of thrills and thoughtfulness, ``The
Matrix'' sends you out of the theater looking forward to the
sequel. When was the last time you felt that way about a movie?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
