<HEADER>
A2392 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-THINGS02-COX     04-01 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-THINGS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    10, well 9, things I like about you
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Ten things I sort of like about ``10 Things I
Hate About You'':
</P>
<P>
   1. The shiny teen comedy is loosely based on Shakespeare's ``The
Taming of the Shrew,'' and that can't be all bad. (Plot: Guy wants
to take out girl, but girl isn't allowed to date unless her older
sister chooses to date. Guy is paid to take out older sister so
young girl can go out. Problem is, older sister is a shrew and her
male peers repulse her. She finally gives in. All's well that ends
well.) Like ``Clueless,'' a contemporary spin on Jane Austen's
``Emma,'' the movie trafficks in high school social satire. But the
superior ``Clueless'' was pointed and hilarious and had Paul Rudd.
``10 Things'' is only half as inventive.
</P>
<P>
   2. The likable and talented young actors are relative unknowns,
not part of the pre-fab, WB and Fox TV brat pack. None of them are
very cute, and that's good. A plain but intriguing Julia Stiles
plays the Bard's shrewish Kate, here named Kat Stratford. A leonine
Heath Ledger, who looks like Val Kilmer doing Jim Morrison, fills
the Petruchio part. In Shakespeare's play, Petruchio is ``a
gentleman of Verona.'' Here he is named Patrick Verona, and so we
have another thread in the movie's tenuous Shakespeare connection.
There are others: the gorgeous Seattle high school where the movie
is set is called Padua High. Padua, Italy, is the setting of
``Shrew.'' Find the Shakespeare allusions, win a prize.
</P>
<P>
   3. Neat-o title; love its pucker of postmodern vinegar. Alas,
the movie isn't very sassy and this postfeminist Kat is hardly a
shrew. She's just desperately aloof, a trifle snarky and in dire
need of lipstick. She wears grungy clothes, doesn't date and reads
Simone de Beauvoir and ``The Bell Jar.'' And, no, we are informed,
she doesn't listen to k.d. lang.
</P>
<P>
   4. Young actor David Krumholtz is hilarious. He brings wit and a
big heart to campus goober Michael Eckman, fulfilling the promise
he showed as the lumpy older brother in ``The Slums of Beverly
Hills.''
</P>
<P>
   5. A lively alt-rock soundtrack that doesn't chafe. Songs are by
Barenaked Ladies, Salt 'N' Pepper and George Clinton, and there's a
passable Cheap Trick cover. (On another note, the music in teen
films is beginning to take the place of editing as a scene-changing
device. Ever so slightly, teen films are turning a visual medium
into a sonic one.)
</P>
<P>
   6. Smoking is portrayed as the putrid habit it is and drinkers
are shown doing dumb drinking things, like puking.
</P>
<P>
   7. Kat's line: ``Remove head from sphincter, and then drive.''
</P>
<P>
   8. Gratuitous frog dissection.
</P>
<P>
   9. It's only 94 minutes long.
</P>
<P>
   10. I can't think up a 10th. That's why the movie is getting two
stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``10 Things I Hate About You''
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Julia Stiles, Heath Ledger, Larisa Oleynik
</P>
<P>
   Director: Gil Junger
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriters: Karen McCullah Lutz, Kirsten Smith
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: PG-13 for mild language, teen-age buffoonery
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 1 hour, 34 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
