<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLEM02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New energy for an old Jewish tale
 &HT;    EDs: This is a AUS free-lancer; not for use by NYT clients
 &HT;    By Jeanne Claire van Ryzin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Take an age-old Jewish legend, refashion it to
take place during the Nazi occupation of Prague, then stage it as
late-20th-century hard-core theater _ that's the formula for
``Golem,'' Austin playwright and director Josh Frank's latest
production.
</P>
<P>
   And giving an old Jewish story new energy is precisely what
Frank hopes will be the appeal of his play. ``Young Jewish people
are so often detached artistically from Judaism because there isn't
a lot of `alternative' Jewish art,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golem'' is based on the legend of a humanlike creature formed
of clay. The best-known version of the golem story takes place in
Prague in the late 1500s during a time when the king threatens the
existence of the city's Jewish community and a rabbi creates a
golem for protection. Yet because it is made by man, the golem
possesses no soul and ultimately becomes a dangerous creature.
</P>
<P>
   Frank also places his play in Prague; yet this time it's 1942
during the Nazi occupation when Jews were forced to live in the
Jewish Quarter before being sent to concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to write a modern adaptation of the golem story, and
I also wanted to talk about a situation and a time that people in
my generation are wary of talking about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Frank's play, Zfeck the Rabbi decides to make a golem to seek
revenge on the Nazis. Yet Zfeck doesn't realize that a golem cannot
be created for the purpose of evil. Having no soul, any sin the
golem commits is a sin of the creator.
</P>
<P>
   Frank designed his play to be staged in the alley behind the
Dougherty Arts Center where two intersecting drives meet amid a
cluster of outbuildings and back entrances _ a visually arresting
space. The site is enveloped by the sound of passing trains during
the play, an effect Frank sought to intensify the threatening
Holocaust mood. Frank also enlisted musician Jake Zuckerman, of the
klezmer band Rubinchiks Orkestyr, to compose an original score.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to create a spectacle,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank, 23, moved to Austin a little more than a year ago and
started his Theaterless Theater Corps, advertising auditions for
his original script ``Night of the Werewolf.'' That play took off
when it debuted in June, drawing enthusiastic crowds with an encore
performance staged a few months later. Since then, Frank co-founded
the M.O.M. (Mind Over Money) Fest, a 10-evening theater showcase
that ran last November, and presented his play ``The Last
Immigrant.'' When he started work on ``Golem'' late last year,
Frank immersed himself in first-person accounts of the Jewish
Quarter in Nazi-occupied Prague. During a research visit to the
Holocaust Museum in Washington, Frank poured over more materials on
wartime experiences. This May, Frank plans his first trip to
Prague, where he hopes to explore opportunities to produce
``Golem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a playwright, I really want to touch my generation of Jews
and non-Jews,'' Frank said. ``This story has to be told and
retold.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
