<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-STEPHANOPOLOUS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Curious about George: Stephanopoulos a draw
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He scribbled flawless Greek in one woman's book with
nary a complaint nor need for a spelling prompt. Someone else got
four separate autographs and a grin for her disposable camera.
</P>
<P>
   Ask President Bill Clinton's former right-hand man to drink
carryout coffee from a rain-soddened cardboard cup? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's caffeine,'' George Stephanopoulos said gratefully in an
interview Wednesday night, just before starting to sign copies of
his memoir, ``All Too Human,'' at the Ansley Mall Chapter 11
bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   But mention _ as many critics have _ that the book might be
considered a betrayal and he will politely, but firmly, disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been clear ever since O.J., that there always has to be a
story that TV and cable latches onto for a week,'' said
Stephanopoulos, 39, who's been accused of violating White House
confidences in a book that only intermittently addresses the Monica
Lewinsky situation. ``There's also a lot of sublimated emotion from
the last year. People did want it to go away. But that's not the
same as not having deep feelings about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes these days for Stephanopoulos, who's changed
everything from jobs to zip codes _ he's an ABC news analyst and
teaches at Columbia University in New York _ but still can't seem
to make anyone forget who he used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's trying very hard, mind you. ``All Too Human''
(Little, Brown, $27.95), the lively account of his five years with
Clinton, is No. 1 on best-seller lists, in part because
Stephanopoulos pushes it with the same enthusiasm he once pushed
candidate Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign came to Atlanta on Wednesday. First, there was a
reading sponsored by Georgia Tech's bookstore, where about 250
people _ many of them students _ got a chance to fire a few
questions at the former high-ranking White House official.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody asked about saving Social Security, or even Kosovo. But
they did ask about Dick Morris, the one-time Clinton adviser who
resigned following a sex scandal, and about Joan, the girlfriend
who gave Stephanopoulos his walking papers not very long into the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like Dick Morris,'' Stephanopoulos said. ``I do like
Joan.''
</P>
<P>
   Then it was on to Chapter 11, where hundreds of people waited
outside in the rain to obtain his abbreviated autograph on their
books.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly abbreviated.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means `Many Good Years','' said Eva Georgeson, pointing
at his message and beaming at him like a proud mother. ``I like
him. Not because he's Greek. But that helped!''
</P>
<P>
   They liked him at Tech, too _ within limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows who Pearl Jam is,'' said Rich Shertenlieb, a Marietta
junior. Then Shertenlieb put things in proper perspective. ``Of
course, when Jerry Springer came, there were probably three times
as many people here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
