<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   GOODFRIDAY-GARDENS _ Thousands across the country today will
flock to garden centers to scarf up tender little plants, roll up
their sleeves to till cold packed soil and rip open colorful seed
packs to pour out the promise of hope _ all because it's Good
Friday, the traditional spring planting day. Yet serious gardeners
have been at it all year in one form or another, with some 72
million contributing to a $76 billion industry. In the South's mild
climate, it's serious business. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GARDENERS _ What is it with these people who can't keep their
nails clean _ who would rather plunge their bare hands into
40-pound bags of composted cow manure than plug in the Dirt Devil
or do a load of wash. People who don head lamps at 3 in the morning
in search of slimy slugs that in minutes will turn a perfect hosta
leaf into a block of Swiss cheese. People like Margie Archer who
swears every March she won't work with such vengeance to cultivate
a glorious garden, and already she's going at it gangbusters.
``Nowhere on earth do I feel more comfortable with no makeup on,
hair matted to my head, dirty old torn clothes, beat up shoes than
in a garden,'' the Duluth resident said. ``No one ever told me that
the sweat, aches and tears of battling mosquitoes, worms, bugs,
snakes and even spiders could be so much fun!'' Yet for Archer and
most of the other 2,630 readers who responded to the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's spring survey of gardening habits, the hobby
is about far more than just growing the brightest jonquil or
juiciest tomato. It's about a passion, an addiction _ even a
lifestyle. Hundreds wrote of the therapeutic benefits reaped from
outdoors. Their gardens are outdoor gyms for those who despise
exercise, brightly-lit bars for drowning their work-day stress,
psychologist's lounge chairs for coming to grips with a spouse's
death. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   COMICBOOKS _ One of biggest comic conventions of the year is in
Orlando. Who goes? Why do people line up to get autographs from
artists? Any Florida comic artists? By (Houck, Palm Beach Post).
45. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MONTREAL _ MONTREAL _ They wore bulky sweaters and clunky
boots, some clutching strollers with babies swaddled like mini
Eskimos, as they quietly lingered in front of Monet's lush
landscapes at the Montreal Museum of Fine Arts. The Montrealers
could be excused for stealing extra moments to savor the ``Monet at
Giverny'' exhibit, for outside on this late March afternoon it
didn't look anything like the French artist's famed garden. Still,
even at winter's ugly en worst, Montreal had plenty to recommend it
_ and to make an Atlantan more than a tad envious. Culture and
multiculturalism. A safe subway system that gets everywhere you
want to go. Beggars with shockingly good manners (``Sir, if I may
ask you seriously for some monetary assistance,'' one pitched me on
the Metro). Neighborhoods that invite a healthy walk. Historic
architecture that demands a gaze. Cool restaurants, bars and coffee
joints. Open-24-hours haunts (Monsieur Falafel's neon lights are
glowing when you need that 3 a.m. Middle Eastern fix). Endless
shops and boutiques to test the favorable exchange rate. Youthful
spirit. New York sophistication without the attitude. Hometown
pride. (Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-IFYOUGO _MONTREAL _ If You Go sidebar. (Pousner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MONTREALRUFUS _ MONTREAL _ Montreal singer-songwriter
Rufus Wainwright, whose debut album last year made a lot of critic
Top 10 lists, tips us to the hippest haunts in his hometown.
(Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MONTREALKIDS _ MONTREAL _ Thirty-eight 8th grade French
students from Northwood Middle School in Taylors, S.C., a
Greenville suburb, got a crash course in French-Canadian culture
during a recent three-night visit to Montreal and Quebec City. Four
of them told us of their favorite Montreal things.(Pousner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CANADA-FESTIVALS _ Summer in Canada is brimming with
festivals. From Yukon to Newfoundland, the provinces host a
smorgasbord of events during the warmer months. We provide a
sampler. (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CANADA-GOING _ Travel notes column (Canada specific this
week) (Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-CANADA-TRAIN_ Shorts on train and bus deals in Canada.
(Thrasher, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-GETAWAY _ NEW BERN, N.C. _ A preview of the home and
garden tour and tulip festival April 9-10 in New Bern, N.C..
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern Happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   STYLE-FALLTRENDS _ When the time comes for trend-conscious women
to reassemble their cold-weather wardrobes, many may find the task
as daunting as planning a wedding. The top designers of New York
and Europe seemed to agree on the fundamental trends for the
season. But the trends they agreed on were so plentiful that
filtering through them all still won't be easy. The surest way to
greet the next fall/winter season in style is to first decide which
essentials you need to complement your lifestyle, body type and
existing wardrobe. There are so many trendy colors, cuts and
materials coming that there has to be at least one that'll suit you
just fine. (Walton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   COXNET ENTERTAINMENT 0402 _ The great television 'toon-in is
gaining momentum like an Acme safe dropped from the top of a
building. The networks are going animated like never before,
loading their prime-time schedules with cartoons. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FUTURAMA _ Matt Groening, the middle-aged but still dizzyingly
adolescent creator of ``The Simpsons,'' has finally brought forth
his second TV series, ``Futurama,''a mere nine years after his
first. The show is definitely a Groening creation. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   RINGEL GILLESPIE ON VIDEO _ The 71st Academy Awards are history,
but maybe you'd like to know a little more about the winners and
their work. Here are a few rental suggestions. (Ringel-Gillespie,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN -- A 2-column graphic ``Countdown to
`Star Wars''' outlining the number of days remaining until ``The
Phantom Menace'' opens. (Staff, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   VIDEO REVIEWS -- The animated ``Rugrats'' hit the big screen
with a big issue: making way for a new baby. That's what Tommy
Pickles has to do in ``The Rugrats Movie.'' (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) With 2 column color studio photograph from
the film ``Everest.''
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEWS -- Consistent in its brilliantly haywire
inconsistency, the new album from British pop act Blur is both a
goofy head trip and a giddily accessible delight. (Staff, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES NEWS/REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MATRIX _ Movie review: ``The Matrix'' with Keanu Reeves;
weirdo everybody-dressed-in-black sci-fi thriller where the world
is but an alternate reality. It's an out-of-nowhere surprise _ a
smart-but-flashy flick that will make a lot of people forget that
they're just marking time till the debut of the ``Star Wars''
prequel. Grade: A-. (StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 23.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-HATE _ Movie review: ``10 Things I Hate About You'' _
What starts out as a terrible teen version of ``The Taming of the
Shrew'' unexpectedly starts to percolate with wit and charm, thanks
largely to its Kate-and-Petruchio stand-ins, Kat (Julia Stiles) and
Patrick (Heath Ledger). Grade: B. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 17. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-FLESH _ Movie review ``School of Flesh'' with Isabelle
Huppert. (A smart, cool-hot drama of sexual obsession.) Grade B+.
(StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-TOWNERS _ Movie review ``The Out-of-Towners.'' Remake
with Steve Martin, Goldie Hawn and John Cleese, who's actually
good. (A mostly lame comedy that's out to lunch). Grade: C+.
(Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ ``A Walk on the Moon'' with Diane Lane.
(It's as fake as the tie-dyed extras in its Woodstock re-creation).
Grade: C; ``Tango,'' Argentina Oscar nominee. (It's a dance-film
answer to Fellini's ``8 1/2''). Grade: B+; plus mini-reviews from
Wednesday openings ``The Matrix'' (A knockout sci-fi flick.) Grade:
A- ; and ``10 Things I Hate About You'' (A charming teen update of
``The Taming of the Shrew'' _ if you can get past the rocky opening
minutes.) Grade: B. (StMurray, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-THINGS _ Movie review: ``10 Things I Hate About You,''
the latest in a series of teen comedies, opening today. This one is
based on Shakespeare's ``Taming of the Shrew.'' (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman). 10-12. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GOLEM _ Review/interview with the playwright of Golem, an
adaptation of a traditional Jewish legend by Austin playwright Josh
Frank. (VanRyzin, Austin American-Statesman). 13-15. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SKUBE _ Each year, medical students at Emory University
pay solemn respects to those who have given their bodies to
science. Posthumous volunteers, theirs are the cadavers that
anatomy students live with _ so to speak _ in most intimate ways.
The students call their commemoration a Service of Reflection and
Gratitude, and about 10 years ago they asked John Stone,
cardiologist by training, poet by nature, to write a few lines for
the occasion. ``It's hard to write a commissioned poem,'' Stone was
saying the other day. ``You can't be sure it's going to be worth a
damn.'' (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-GOLD _ Reviews of John Feinstein's ``The Majors'' and
David Owen's ``The Making of the Masters.'' (Sheeley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 29.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil'' finally
will come out in paperback . . . Lisa Scottoline, dubbed the
``female John Grisham'' by People magazine and one of Diet Coke's
featured authors, posted a rough draft of the first chapter of her
new book on the Internet and invited suggestions from readers . . .
Chattanooga literary festival with Lee Smith, Clyde Edgerton and
Shelby Foote will honor Eudora Welty. (O'Briant, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-MILNER _ Jay Milner's review of the sequel to ``Get
Shorty,'' ``Be Cool,'' by Elmore Leonard. (Milner, Cox News
Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-STEPHANOPOLOUS _ George Stephanopolous visits Atlanta to
promote his book. Big crowds are expected at his two scheduled
stops. A reporter has an interview with him and will trail him all
day. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
