<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, April 2,
1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   GOODFRIDAY-GARDENS _ Thousands across the country today will
flock to garden centers to scarf up tender little plants, roll up
their sleeves to till cold packed soil and rip open colorful seed
packs to pour out the promise of hope _ all because it's Good
Friday, the traditional spring planting day. Yet serious gardeners
have been at it all year in one form or another, with some 72
million contributing to a $76 billion industry. In the South's mild
climate, it's serious business. (Flanders, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   GARDENERS _ What is it with these people who can't keep their
nails clean _ who would rather plunge their bare hands into
40-pound bags of composted cow manure than plug in the Dirt Devil
or do a load of wash. People who don head lamps at 3 in the morning
in search of slimy slugs that in minutes will turn a perfect hosta
leaf into a block of Swiss cheese. People like Margie Archer who
swears every March she won't work with such vengeance to cultivate
a glorious garden, and already she's going at it gangbusters.
``Nowhere on earth do I feel more comfortable with no makeup on,
hair matted to my head, dirty old torn clothes, beat up shoes than
in a garden,'' the Duluth resident said. ``No one ever told me that
the sweat, aches and tears of battling mosquitoes, worms, bugs,
snakes and even spiders could be so much fun!'' Yet for Archer and
most of the other 2,630 readers who responded to the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's spring survey of gardening habits, the hobby
is about far more than just growing the brightest jonquil or
juiciest tomato. It's about a passion, an addiction _ even a
lifestyle. Hundreds wrote of the therapeutic benefits reaped from
outdoors. Their gardens are outdoor gyms for those who despise
exercise, brightly-lit bars for drowning their work-day stress,
psychologist's lounge chairs for coming to grips with a spouse's
death. (Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 50. WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   COMICBOOKS _ One of biggest comic conventions of the year is in
Orlando. Who goes? Why do people line up to get autographs from
artists? Any Florida comic artists? By (Houck, Palm Beach Post).
45. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MONTREAL _ MONTREAL _ They wore bulky sweaters and clunky
boots, some clutching strollers with babies swaddled like mini
Eskimos, as they quietly lingered in front of Monet's lush
landscapes at the Montreal Museum of Fine Arts. The Montrealers
could be excused for stealing extra moments to savor the ``Monet at
Giverny'' exhibit, for outside on this late March afternoon it
didn't look anything like the French artist's famed garden. Still,
even at winter's ugly en worst, Montreal had plenty to recommend it
_ and to make an Atlantan more than a tad envious. Culture and
multiculturalism. A safe subway system that gets everywhere you
want to go. Beggars with shockingly good manners (``Sir, if I may
ask you seriously for some monetary assistance,'' one pitched me on
the Metro). Neighborhoods that invite a healthy walk. Historic
architecture that demands a gaze. Cool restaurants, bars and coffee
joints. Open-24-hours haunts (Monsieur Falafel's neon lights are
glowing when you need that 3 a.m. Middle Eastern fix). Endless
shops and boutiques to test the favorable exchange rate. Youthful
spirit. New York sophistication without the attitude. Hometown
pride. (Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-IFYOUGO _MONTREAL _ If You Go sidebar. (Pousner, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
