<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, April 1, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RESCUE-TRAINING (San Antonio) _ The Air Force personnel
who stand by to rescue downed pilots in Yugoslavia and other hot
spots are a small but elite team, enduring grueling training to
prepare themselves for risky work. These ``parajumpers'' begin
their training at Lackland Air Force Base. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
(Photos available on Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   URANIUM-BULLETS (San Francisco) _ As the war against Yugoslavia
escalates, NATO is expected to dispatch U.S. Air Force attack jets
to blast Serbian tanks with depleted uranium _ a radioactive
ammunition prized as a ``tank killer'' and deplored as a long-term
threat to human health. By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKOUT-BLAME (San Francisco) _ A state investigation into the
massive blackout last December has criticized PG&AMP;E, claiming that
more than 140 human errors occurred from the moment the outage was
kickstarted to when power was fully restored more than seven hours
later. By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU and ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   GREEN-ELECTED (Oakland, Calif.) _ The election of Green Party
candidate Audie Bock to the California state Assembly shocked the
political establishment because it confirmed how badly voters want
change in Oakland, even at the risk of turning away their own
Democratic Party. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SEX (San Francisco) _ An estimated 4.5 million daily
Internet users may end up having more sex with a mouse than a
person, claims a controversial new study published in a leading
psychology journal. By ERIC DRUDIS.
</P>
<P>
   CASHMERE-FASHION (San Francisco) _ Cashmere undershirts,
borrowed directly from the summertime doorsteps of Little Italy,
are definitely ``in'' for spring and summer. Which is perfect for
San Francisco's frosty Julys when the fog pounces on uninformed
tourists and the locals just add another layer (a summertime
cashmere twin set is a tank T with a cardigan). By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   CASHMERE-CARE (San Francisco) _ Believe it or not, cashmere is a
low-maintenance material. You can take care of it yourself for few
pennies and you will wear it more often because you can wash it.
Hand-washing only makes cashmere better and better, softer and
softer. By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-TEXAS (San Antonio) _ Two Texas authors have
produced enticing tales with romantic twists. ``Lessons of the
Game'' by Diane Gonzales Bertrand deals with a student teacher who
falls in love with an old acquaintance, while teens and adults will
understand and ponder the no-easy-answers plot of Cindy Bonner's
fourth novel, ``Right From Wrong.'' By JUDYTH RIGLER.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EASTER-EGGS (Albany, N.Y.) _ What do you do with all those
Easter eggs when you've had your fill of deviled eggs and egg
salad? Go beyond mayonnaise and mustard and add in other
ingredients that complement eggs such as curry powder, cheddar,
mushrooms and beet juice. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   EGGS-COLOR (Albany, N.Y.) _ Q: Why are some eggs brown and some
white? Other than the color, is there a difference between the two?
A: Brown and white eggs have the same nutritional value and
quality, says ``Cookwise'' author Shirley O. Corriher. The color
difference, however, is all in the ears. The hen's ears, that is.
By LISA STEVENS.
</P>
<P>
   SOUL-FOOD (San Antonio) _ Billy Williams and his Glory Foods are
giving traditional African-American cuisine a modern touch: good to
eat and good for you. The Columbus, Ohio-based company prides
itself on taste, convenience and produce fresh from black farming
cooperatives. By HECTOR SALDANA.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WAIKIKI (Waikiki, Hawaii) _ My generation has generally made a
point of skipping Waikiki, shuddering at the highrise hotels and
crowded beaches as we hurry to board our connecting flights to Maui
or Kauai. Curious to see what we've been missing all these years, I
recently visited Waikiki. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   With WAIKIKI-IF-GO.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TROUT-SEASON (Albany, N.Y.) _ April 1, opening day of the
state's trout season. This either means nothing to you, or
everything. There's no middle ground of feeling or appreciation for
what opening day really signifies to those afflicted or blest,
depending. By FRED LeBRUN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Usually we think of arts
organizations as beggars holding out tin cups for funding. Alma
Robinson, executive director of California Lawyers for the Arts
(CLA), a group that provides legal services for artists, has a
different view of the arts in San Francisco. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
