<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 11:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2431 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV04-C     04-01 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: THE MEDIA'S HURRY-UP WAR
 &HT;    For release Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Ever wonder what newscasts might have been like
following the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor if they had followed
the approach we're seeing and hearing about today's conflict in the
Balkans? Here's one notion:
</P>
<P>
   ``This ... is Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already been 72 hours since Japanese warplanes left the
pride of the U.S. Pacific Fleet ablaze in Honolulu. Now CBS has
learned that twin-engine Japanese Mitsubishi G3M bombers, operating
off the Malayan coast, have sunk the new British battleships
Repulse and Prince of Wales, each one longer than two football
fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``For an analysis of what this all means, we turn to CBS'
military commentator, retired U.S. Army General John J. Pershing,
who commanded the American Expeditionary Force in Europe during
World War I. Your thoughts, general?
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, this action was a fluke. We know that land-based
torpedo planes cannot operate effectively against capital ships on
a sustained basis. At the same time, we must face the fact that the
British will pull all their forces out of Asia to prepare for the
coming German assault on their home islands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks, general. And now for a look at the dark mood in the
Oval Office as World War II enters its third full day we turn to
CBS' chief White House correspondent, Eric Sevareid. Eric?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Ed, it's been quite a wrenching period for the Roosevelt
administration. Our CBS microphones have picked up the dispirited
voices of the president's most senior advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, surveying the dismal scene, the president
wheeled his chair into the Oval Office and, propped up on his heavy
steel leg braces by the secretaries of the Army and the Navy,
delivered a pep talk to his inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``FDR said, 'Guys, let's not lose sight of why Tokyo and Berlin
have done this to us. Let's not forget what prompted the savage
Japanese attack and who is responsible. While we don't have plan as
yet for winning this war, I'm sure that, in a few more weeks, we'll
have the victory the American people expect. But we must have the
patience to stay the course, even it means carrying the fight into
April of 1942.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks, Eric, for that exclusive report. But a new CBS poll
this evening reflects grave doubts by the American people over
waging a prolonged war. What can you tell us, Charles Collingwood?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed, I can tell you that there's a lot of second-guessing going
on. And that's prompted an increasingly sullen attitude by White
House officials. They are complaining that Roosevelt is being held
by commentators and political opponents to an impossible standard
that's continually shifting.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they hadn't cut off Japanese access to oil in the Dutch
East Indies, FDR aides say, the administration would have been
defying public opinion both here and in other Allied nations. While
that might have avoided the current military debacle, it would have
also allowed the militarists in Tokyo to create a humanitarian
tragedy in China. Back to you, Ed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All right, Charles. I'll be back with a wrapup of the day's
other news after these commercial messages.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is glass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
