NYT-04-01-99 1139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2445 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-BOTANICAL-$ADV     04-01 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BOTANICAL-$ADV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO CITY'S BOTANICAL GARDEN CULTIVATES PLANTS THAT COULD
YIELD CURES
 &HT;    PHOTOS AVAILABLE IN INTERNATIONAL FOLDER IN COX SERVER
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., April 3 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY Workers at this city's Botanical Garden get a
special bonus every day.
</P>
<P>
   They pluck the leaves of a nondescript native plant and brew a
stimulating tea that combats anemia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you strong!'' said gardener Jesus Rebollo, flexing
his muscles like Popeye.
</P>
<P>
   Rebollo's faith in plants is echoed by countless Mexicans who
use medicinal herbs that are sold fresh, dried or crushed in almost
every market.
</P>
<P>
   At the Botanical Garden, researchers from Mexico's National
Autonomous University, or UNAM, are dedicated to spreading the
Mexican tradition of using native edible plants as medicines and
nutritional supplements.
</P>
<P>
   At times in Mexican history, the use of native plants has been
threatened because their consumption was seen as backwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goes back to the Spanish,'' said Robert Bye, an American
botanist who came to Mexico nearly 20 years ago from the University
of Colorado and now is director of the garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cortes and his men talked about suffering for months because
they had to eat weeds' while they conquered Mexico,'' Bye said.
</P>
<P>
   One of garden's main activities today is the evaluation of
native medicinal plants -- not just to use as teas or poultices,
but for commercially produced drugs to treat illnesses as
life-threatening as AIDS and tuberculosis, as well as other
infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
   Bye and other botanists at the UNAM are participating in an
international plant-gathering and drug-discovery project started by
the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity. The project
was made possible by a treaty signed at the Earth Summit in Rio de
Janeiro in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers work with traditional herbal healers in rural and
Indian communities to gather and conserve valuable plants. Then
they team up with chemists at the UNAM and abroad to refine plant
extracts and evaluate their potential.
</P>
<P>
   The garden, on the UNAM campus, is working with the G.W.L.
Hansen's Disease Center of the U.S. Department of Health and Human
Services in Louisiana and commercial laboratories in the United
States, including that of American Home Products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bioprospecting'' in developing nations is controversial, with
native communities complaining they should receive profits from
medicines that are developed from their knowledge and plants
foraged on their land.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. treaty calls for native groups to share in those
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Bye's project requires researchers to receive permission from
the government and local communities to gather plants, and to help
the communities with infrastructure projects and conservation
efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The UNAM will set up a trust to divide royalties from products
that are produced in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico, like many other countries, is still developing laws to
determine who owns the fruits of plant research.
</P>
<P>
   It is at the center of bioprospecting because it is one most
biologically diverse countries in the world, with climates that
range from that of an alpine forest to desert to the tropics.
</P>
<P>
   But because Mexico also has one of the world's highest
deforestation rates, the search for new medicinal plants is a race
against destruction.
</P>
<P>
   There are many more plant species yet to be discovered in
Mexico, said Tom Wendt, a University of Texas at Austin botanist
who has studied Mexican forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico has an advantage because it has great plant diversity
and extremely old cultures, all of which have been studying
medicinal plants for thousands of years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bye and his wife, botanist Edelmira Linares, work regularly with
traditional healers who have learned about plants from their
forefathers.
</P>
<P>
   As they walk through the Botanical Garden, the couple point out
herbs that many low-income Mexicans grow at home because they can't
afford modern pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   Muitle, pronounced MWEET-lay, is brewed into a tea that fights
anemia.
</P>
<P>
   ``People drink it instead of coffee in the morning,'' Linares
said. ``That's what the workers here do.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaves of the Mexican laurel serve as a condiment or as a
tea to ease digestive problems. The herb estafiate calms stomach
cramps, as well as labor pains.
</P>
<P>
   And the Mexican arnica plant, which has tiny yellow blooms, is
brewed into a tea for ulcers or made into a poultice to soothe
bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Bye said botanists at the garden also debunk rumors that run
rampant in Mexico about so-called magic herbal cures.
</P>
<P>
   A popular substance called ``miracle tea,'' for example,
appeared to reduce stomach pains but could cause liver cancer if
drunk in large quantities.
</P>
<P>
   The Botanical Garden is open to the public. Besides a section
devoted to medicinal herbs, there also is a large collection of
desert plants and two greenhouses, one crawling with tropical vines
and plants.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the other greenhouse, researchers are studying native
plants that use less water and are more resistant to air pollution
than house plants commonly found in Mexico City today.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
