<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2449 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     04-01 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY BOOMER CONSUMERS WANT TO BE ENTERTAINED, CONSULTANT ADVISES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Show business can be big business _ even for companies that make
a living outside of the Hollywood spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   That's the message delivered by an entertainment industry
consultant in a new book called ``The Entertainment Economy: How
Mega-Media Forces are Transforming our Lives'' (Times Books, $25,
336 pages).
</P>
<P>
   Author Michael Wolf, who has dispensed advice to such media
giants as NBC and MTV, asserts that increasingly varied industries
will need to become skilled at incorporating entertainment elements
into their product offerings if they want to capture the attention
of today's most sought-after consumers _ the baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   As boomers age _ and their kids get ready to leave the nest over
the next few years _ they will have more disposable income than
ever before to shower on themselves and on the manufacturers and
retailers that know how to show them a good time, Wolf says.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not to say that people are not going to continue to
buy cars, couches, dishwashers and homes in record numbers,'' he
writes. ``The point is that these are more or less purchases that
the boomer generation has already made. Real growth is going to
come not so much in the purchase of real physical goods, or at
least durable goods, as it will in the purchase of services that
make life feel fuller and more enjoyable.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, watch out for an explosion in
entertainment-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Consider that entertainment-related spending already accounts
for 8.4 percent of overall spending in the American economy, while
savings wallow at a level of 2.1 percent of our nation's total
consumer budget. Any significant increase in entertainment spending
will translate into large structural shifts in what types of goods
and services are most highly valued in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As social, political, and technological change has opened up
new opportunities, entertainment has found itself at the forefront
of economic growth and cultural evolution,'' Wolf writes.
</P>
<P>
   As the founder and senior vice president of the media and
entertainment practice at the Booz-Allen &AMP; Hamilton consulting
firm, Wolf can draw on volumes of case studies and entertainment
industry stories that help make the book lively and fun to read.
</P>
<P>
   But he ultimately falls short of the mark for business readers
looking for insight into changing their business. He starts strong
in the first third of the book, writing expansively about the broad
impact that the entertainment industry is going to have on business
in general.
</P>
<P>
   But like a movie that seemingly loses its direction midway, Wolf
unfortunately returns to his comfort zone in later chapters,
writing internal industry accounts of why The Walt Disney Co. and
(his own client) MTV are effective stewards of their brand images.
It makes for good reading; it's just not very applicable to what
you do in your everyday job _ unless you just happen to run a movie
studio.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf does serve up an interesting analysis of the impact the
Internet will have on the entertainment industry, asserting that
traditional industries moving online will need to incorporate
entertainment into their Web sites to stand out with consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, take the forecast with a grain of salt. Even Wolf
acknowledges that the world of the Web is mostly unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   What Wolf can say with more certainty is that the integration of
entertainment components into other industries will change the
product and business cycles in those industries. Like a hit movie
or song that fades after a couple of weeks, businesses that drive
differentiation from entertaining a consumer will be subject to
fickle turns in consumer tastes.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of the Planet Hollywood restaurant chain, which
continues to spiral after early success based on its entertainment
eatery theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we are going to see new restaurant chains like
McDonald's with a 30-year viability as a category leader,'' Wolf
writes. ``Businesses will grow more quickly. They will die more
quickly, too.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   ``Goldman Sachs: The Culture of Success''
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Endlich
</P>
<P>
   Knopf, $27.50
</P>
<P>
   Investment banker Goldman Sachs is profiled here by one of its
own. Author Lisa Endlich was a vice president and foreign exchange
trader for them. With a hundred-year history, there are many
interesting and colorful stories to tell of this private company
that just last year turned partially public. Endlich takes readers
through that history and shows how a family-owned firm came to
dominate its competitors on the international playing field.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Car Buyer's and Leaser's Negotiating Bible''
</P>
<P>
   By W. James Bragg
</P>
<P>
   Random House, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   Half of the new-car sales today are minivans and other light
trucks. The U.S. market is shrinking, though, as its population
matures. Those and other trends, including the once-undisclosed
pricing information now found on the Internet, have made car buying
and leasing an even more complex decision. This book, now in its
second edition, seeks to unravel car-buying business tactics and
give you tips on how to make an informed decision.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Four Elements of Successful Management
</P>
<P>
   By Don R. Marshall
</P>
<P>
   Amacom, $24.95
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned consultant Don Marshall shows how to become a
successful manager by focusing on how to select, evaluate, direct
and reward employees. If you as a manager are constantly asking
yourself, ``What's wrong with these people?,'' then Marshall
suggests you instead ask ``What's wrong with the way I'm managing
these people who are working for me?'' Marshall provides a good
framework for managers to evaluate and improve their skills.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
