<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUL-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY MAKES TRADITIONAL RECIPES GOOD FOR HEART AND SOUL 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Williams photo available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HECTOR SALDANA  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Is canned and frozen food good for the soul? Billy
Williams, the chief executive of Glory Foods, is sure of it.
</P>
<P>
   Williams heads a Columbus, Ohio-based food manufacturing company
specializing in African-American cuisine. That's the fancy name;
many folks in the South still call it soul food.
</P>
<P>
   But that's really too antiquated a term, said the man who
pioneered the food line.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never did approach it that way from the beginning because
of the negative connotation of soul food. The negative image is in
the majority community. They simply want to think that it's all hog
fat and salt. That's just built in to their heads,'' said Williams,
who aims to change minds across the country.
</P>
<P>
   His healthful, ready-to-go, easy-to-fix soul food line includes
black-eyed and pinto beans, field peas, collard and mustard greens,
kale, sweet potatoes, okra and cornbread mix.
</P>
<P>
   The convenience value alone makes Glory Foods' concept appealing
(anyone who has ever prepared time-consuming greens, knows soul
food isn't always fun to cook), but Williams said his brand of
convenience foods was almost as good as mama's.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, such authentic, hunger-inducing aromas wafting from
the stove, oven or microwave could fool many a soul-food gourmet.
</P>
<P>
   And some might argue Glory Foods is better than homemade since
it's healthier than the old-style recipes. The product is lower in
fat and salt content than traditionally prepared dishes and
contains no preservatives.
</P>
<P>
   Williams started Glory Foods in 1989 with four partners and
$20,000, armed with favorite Southern recipes and inspired by a
market study they commissioned that discovered African-Americans
consume 600 million servings of greens annually, almost none of it
from cans or in heat-and-eat form.
</P>
<P>
   Glory Foods stepped in to fill the void in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with the idea that the African-American market was
not being served, and that has been our focus. We want to be good
at marketing to African-Americans first,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   But a cross-marketing approach was needed almost from the start.
Soul food had gone mainstream, much to Williams' surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're from Ohio, so we really didn't know Southern whites ate
this product like they do, so that was a plus market. We didn't
know Hispanics ate peas and beans like they do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing nothing different than, say, when Mexican foods
were marketed to wider markets, and other groups liked the flavor
and the taste,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glory Foods prides itself on being authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very much an ethnic, authentic food company. The real
spices are in there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glory Foods is now distributed in 32 states with annual sales of
$14 million. Collard greens are the company's biggest seller
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal favorites are the beans, the black-eyed peas and
the butter beans,'' said Williams, 54, who employs 20 people at his
Ohio plant and jokes that he's a hands-on sort of boss who lives
and breathes a 70-hour-a-week work schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a community-based operation. Our strength is that we
understand our community,'' said Williams, whose company is
involved with black farming cooperatives, effectively taking
quality control from the field to the store shelf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we strengthen our community, then we strengthen ourselves.
At the same time, it's the right thing to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Glory Foods took its first steps into the frozen food market
last year. Those products will be in stores in mid-April. Williams
also foresees an institutional line of products in the near future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
