<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TEXAS AUTHORS SPIN ROMANTIC TALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDYTH RIGLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Two tales with Texas ties and a romantic bent
would make for lively springtime reading for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   First up is Diane Gonzales Bertrand's young-adult novel,
``Lessons of the Game'' (Pinata Books/Arte Publico Press, $9.95).
</P>
<P>
   Bertrand, who teaches at St. Mary's University in San Antonio
and has written two other young adult novels and a bilingual
picture book, stresses strong role models in her fiction for young
women.
</P>
<P>
   Geared to readers 11 and older, ``Lessons of the Game'' opens
with a realistic fight scene between two girls in the hallway of
Leon Creek High School. Student teacher Kaylene Morales has the
presence of mind to throw cold water, literally, on the skirmish.
</P>
<P>
   But the mop water from the janitor's bucket also hits Alex
Garrison, coach and instructor at the school. Kaylene knows Alex
from a previous life _ 10 years ago, to be exact _ when she was
just a kid and he was her older brother's best friend. Of course,
she always had a crush on him; and of course, he never noticed her.
</P>
<P>
   But now he has.
</P>
<P>
   Alex is a dedicated coach whose personal life takes second
billing, and Kaylene must struggle with her feelings about that as
their relationship blossoms, then dies on the vine. Bertrand uses
plenty of details from firsthand experience teaching in high school
to bring credibility to the romantic tale.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers and adults will understand and ponder the
no-easy-answers plot of Yorktown novelist Cindy Bonner's fourth
novel, ``Right From Wrong'' (Algonquin Books of Chapel Hill,
$21.95).
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``Lily'' and other Texas-set tales, Bonner places
this one in McDade before, during and after World War I. Florida
Faye ``Sunny'' DeLony and her cousin, Gil Dailey, have always been
pals; but the summer that she's 12 and he's 14, things change.
</P>
<P>
   Her family senses what's happening and tries to separate them,
and Gil tries to avoid her when he realizes that he should resist
temptation, but their love for each other is a like a runaway
train.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gil goes off to war and Sunny seeks comfort in the
company of men who are bad for her, their passion endures despite
family strife and heartbreak.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments of sheer joy juxtaposed against those of
tragedy and lost dreams.
</P>
<P>
   As she has in her other novels, Bonner carefully weaves in
historical details and includes the mood of the time, an almost
Puritanical hatred for those who cross the lines of love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right From Wrong'' is a tale with a moral, but it also has
some juicy love scenes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
