<SLUG> BC-EASTER-EGGS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT TO DO WITH ALL LEFTOVER EASTER EGGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do you do with all those Easter eggs when you've had your
fill of deviled eggs and egg salad? Go beyond mayonnaise and
mustard and add in other ingredients that complement eggs such as
curry powder, cheddar, mushrooms and beet juice.
</P>
<P>
   Beet juice? Yes, beet juice. It's the secret ingredient in those
gallon jars of purple pickled eggs you used to see on truck stop
diner counters. And pickled eggs, sliced up with some red onion and
pickled beets are a classic Polish dish, according to ``Betty
Crocker's New International Cookbook'' (Prentice Hall, 1989).
</P>
<P>
   To make them, combine 3 cups water from cooking beets with 1 cup
red-wine vinegar, 8 black peppercorns, 4 whole allspice, 4 whole
cloves and 1 bay leaf. Bring the mixture to a boil and pour over 6
peeled, hard-cooked eggs. Refrigerate for 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Curried eggs from the ``Virginia Hospitality'' cookbook (Junior
League of Hampton Roads, 1975) is another fine use of 8 hard-cooked
eggs. Begin by making them as you would deviled eggs, mashing the
yolks with 1/3 cup mayonnaise but add 1/4 teaspoon salt, 1/2
teaspoon paprika, 1/2 teaspoon curry powder and 1/2 teaspoon dry
mustard to the mix. Spoon the yolk mixture back into the whites and
place in a 7-by-11-inch baking dish.
</P>
<P>
   Melt 2 tablespoons butter in a medium saucepan and add 2
tablespoons flour, 1 can of condensed cream of mushroom soup and 1
soup can of milk. Cook and stir until bubbly then add 1/2 cup
shredded cheddar cheese and stir until cheese is melted. Pour over
eggs, dust top with bread crumbs and bake at 350 degrees for 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A variation on curried eggs is deviled eggs and shrimp
casserole. Simply add 1 pound of cooked, peeled shrimp to the
casserole before pouring on the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, if you want to do something with your leftover Easter
ham as well, try creamed eggs and ham. Sure beats creamed chipped
beef.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CREAMED EGGS AND HAM
</P>
<P>
   (Makes 4 servings)
</P>
<P>
   From ``Holiday Eggs,'' by Georgeanne Brennan (Smithmark,
$14.98).
</P>
<P>
   Bechamel sauce: 2 tablespoons butter, 2 tablespoons all-purpose
flour, 1/4 teaspoon ground nutmeg, 1 teaspoon pepper, 1/8 teaspoon
cayenne pepper, 3/4 teaspoon salt, 3/4 cup milk.
</P>
<P>
   Main dish: 1 tablespoon butter, 8 ounces mushrooms, cut into
thick slices; 1/4 teaspoon salt, 1 pound smoked ham, diced 2
tablespoons minced parsley, 5 hard-cooked eggs, cut crosswise into
thick slices, 6 slices toast, 1 teaspoon paprika.
</P>
<P>
   Sauce: In a heavy saucepan, melt the butter over medium heat.
When the butter foams, remove the pan from heat and whisk in the
flour, nutmeg, pepper, cayenne and salt until a thick paste forms.
Return the pan to medium heat and gradually whisk in the milk in a
steady stream. Cook for 2 to 3 minutes, stirring constantly. Reduce
heat to low and simmer, stirring occasionally, until the sauce
thickens, 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Main dish: In a small skillet, melt the 1 tablespoon butter over
medium heat. When it foams, add the mushrooms and sprinkle with the
salt. Saute until lightly golden. Drain the mushrooms and stir them
into the sauce, along with the ham and parsley. Reserving 4
attractive slices for garnishes, gently stir in the eggs. Cook for
about 2 minutes, or just enough to thoroughly heat the ham and
eggs. Place 1 slice of toast on each of 4 plates. Divide the
creamed eggs evenly among the plates, spooning them over the toast.
Cut the remaining 2 slices of toast diagonally into 4 triangles
each. Place 2 triangles on each plate and garnish with the
remaining sliced eggs and paprika.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1242EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 12:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2470 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIV-TYLER-LADN     04-01 1304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIV-TYLER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIV TYLER   UNAFFECTED BY HER OWN CELEBITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Liv Tyler is a study in contrasts. She arrives for
an interview wearing a full-length, off-white velvet coat over
black capri pants and midriff-baring top. Her feet are slipped into
rhinestone-lined flip-flops. She's ready for both a cold front or a
heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   The outfit is indicative of the 21-year-old actress'
still-forming persona. Or, perhaps, of her versatility. So far,
Tyler has effortlessly made the transition from model and rock
video princess to respected movie star, and from no-budget indies
(``Heavy'') to money-churning mega-productions (``Armageddon'').
</P>
<P>
   She's even literally gone from cold to hot in her last pair of
movies, the Mississippi-set ``Cookie's Fortune,'' which opens
today, and an adaptation of Pushkin's classic Russian verse novel
``Eugene Onegin,'' which was shot first but is being saved for a
fall release.
</P>
<P>
   The most appealing contrast of all, though, is how Tyler seems
to have come through a lifetime of both reflected and earned
celebrity more or less unaffected. She's accessible and
unpretentious _ ``Pop a squat'' is how she offers a reporter a seat
_ and equal parts bemused by and willfully ignorant of the media
stirs she's caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, every day there's gonna be somebody new,'' she says in a
breathy, girlish voice that _ again, contradicting the expected
effect _ has a thoughtful ring to it. ``Especially with media now,
anybody new is just splashed on the front covers of magazines.
They're in the wind for that moment, and that's always going to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't feel particularly a part of all that. Maybe when
`Stealing Beauty' (her first star vehicle, directed by Bernardo
Bertolucci and released in 1996) came out, that happened a little
bit. I don't really remember because it wasn't any of my doing. But
the point is, really, to not let that affect you.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler was a pretty big story, not just because of her classic
dark Calabrian beauty, but because her tale was a little more
compelling than that of most starlets. She'd been born to model
Bebe Buell, who had dated a number of rock 'n' roll personalities,
and Todd Rundgren, a pioneer in the art and electronic rock music
fields.
</P>
<P>
   Or so Liv thought for the first decade of her life. Rundgren
raised her like a daughter, but then she discovered that her
biological father was really Aerosmith singer Steven Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than indulging recriminations, Liv reached out to Tyler,
who was overjoyed to acknowledge and accept her (she maintains warm
relations with Rundgren, too). Of course, the rock world being what
it is, one of the ways the elder Tyler expressed his fatherly
affection was by giving his daughter her first show-biz break _ as
a tube-topped nymphet (along with a budding Alicia Silverstone) in
Aerosmith's ultra-popular music video ``Crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler already had a thriving modeling career at that point;
supermodel Paulina Porizkova, a family friend, took the pictures
that landed the adolescent girl an agent. She made an impressive
acting debut opposite Richard Dreyfuss in the 1994 feature ``Silent
Fall,'' and was soon drawing the attention of an impressive array
of filmmakers ranging from Italian auteur Bertolucci to
``Armageddon's'' Michael Bay to Tom Hanks (``That Thing You Do!'').
</P>
<P>
   To, now, the legendary ``actors director'' Robert Altman, the
Hollywood iconoclast responsible for such indelible works as
``MASH,'' ``McCabe and Mrs. Miller,'' ``Nashville'' and ``The
Player.'' In ``Cookie's Fortune,'' Tyler plays the independent but
easygoing grand-niece of a Mississippi matriarch (Patricia Neal)
whose suicide throws her small, close-knit town into as much of a
frenzy as the laid-back hamlet can whip up.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler worked with an impressive ensemble that included Glenn
Close, Julianne Moore, Charles S. Dutton and Chris O'Donnell in the
out-of-the-way Delta burg of Holly Springs. Despite the
high-powered cast, the working situation was as relaxed as it could
be.
</P>
<P>
   Tyler loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just so liberating for me and such a free experience,''
she says. ``I learned so much from the whole process. I'd been in
England making `Eugene Onegin' in all these wigs and corsets, and
five days later I was in Mississippi with no hair and with this
amazing cast. Everybody was so welcoming and warm; Bob creates this
amazing environment, and we all just sort of morphed into our
characters. I was so excited to work every day _ not an ounce of
fear in me at all. It was just serious pretend.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-star Dutton describes working with Tyler in rapturous tones.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a young actress who hits upon so many things
accidentally, and you see it coming even before she does,'' the
Yale Drama School alum says with a big smile. ``You just know she's
going to be brilliant at this because there's no premeditation
about it. It makes you remember those days, in college and all that
stuff. Instinctively, she's got it going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler agrees that her strength lies in her instincts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because of all of the influences I had as a child, I
always had a sense of myself,'' she explains. ``I've always been
very comfortable being me and never was made to feel ashamed for
being that way. So, in that, I'm confident in the decisions that I
make.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I'm open to everything and everyone. But to be
around all of these creative people and seeing it work for them,
and for them to be following their own way and their own passion,
was definitely very inspiring to me. That's the only way I know,
and it would feel so bad in my soul to go any way that wasn't my
own. I wouldn't know how to do that, so therefore I just try to
keep that feeling inside and do things that I'm proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until she'd made a few movies that Tyler realized her
creative needs were best satisfied by acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the middle of `Heavy' when I really went, `This is
great, I love this! Finally, I've found something I can get all
this energy out doing.'''
</P>
<P>
   The awful, though hardly surprising truth is, though, that Tyler
loves music even more than acting. Although she has a nice singing
voice _ she helpfully broke into a few stanzas of an old Sam Cooke
soul song during the interview _ Tyler is frustrated that she's
never had the time to learn an instrument.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to sing, but I don't want to pursue it
professionally,'' she explains. ``Certainly not right now; I'm very
happy doing what I do. But I'm happy singing all day long and
listening to music. It's definitely something that's inside of me
somewhere, but I wouldn't know where to go with it other than as a
hobby.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler is making a lot of beautiful music at home these days.
Since the recent breakup of her three-year relationship with the
actor Joaquin Phoenix, she has been seeing Royston Langdon, who
plays bass for the band Spacehog.
</P>
<P>
   In a lot of ways, however, Tyler's heart still belongs to daddy.
Indeed, nothing was a bigger thrill than making joint first
appearances on the Academy Awards show with Steven last month, when
Liv introduced Aerosmith's performance of ``Armageddon's''
nominated song, ``I Don't Want to Miss a Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love him so much,'' she says of Steven. ``It's been so
amazing to get to know him as an adult, and we have such a
beautiful friendship. It's incredible to be going through all of
this right now, becoming successful together. It's such a
coincidence, but being at the Oscars together in the same year for
the same film was not only beautiful, but I think there was some
kind of reason for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're learning from each other in a lot of ways. I just think
that's really great.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
