<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOL-FASHION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STYLE WITH A SMILE: FASHION SATIRE LETS BOLD WOMEN HAVE A LITTLE
FUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by SLANG partners --)  
(NOTE USE OF ITALICS IN LAST GRAF) 
 
 
 
  
By BARBARA DE WITT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's playtime, girls.
</P>
<P>
   While the fashion police weren't looking, designers went on a
joy ride.
</P>
<P>
   Taking creative detours and speeding down memory lane, designers
such as Anna Sui, Gucci, Dolce &AMP; Gabbana, and Prada have brought
back rock-glam, hippie chicks and funky femmes. And along the way
they've resurrected two major fashion icons _ Cher and Elsa
Schiaparelli for a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us know all about Cher. Back in the '60s and '70s, the
taller half of ``Sonny and Cher'' recording fame dressed up in
feathers and fringe, as well as those fool-the-eye ensembles by Bob
Mackie that featured nude linings and lots of sequins. It was
fantasy dressing to the max, limited only by budget constraints and
school dress codes ... and one's sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   But Schiaparelli had women wearing lamb chops and shoes on their
hats long before Cher was creating youthquakes in fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schiaparelli was a designer during that surrealistic art
movement of the late '30s, and she created spoofs on serious
fashion that became known as fashion satire,'' says Maggie Murray,
the gallery director of the Fashion Institute of Design and
Merchandising in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   According to Murray, Schiaparelli was influenced by the work of
Spanish artist Salvador Dali, and her designs appealed to women who
had self-confidence and didn't mind showing a sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Schiaparelli may have led the fashion movement, but others
followed.
</P>
<P>
   Dale Carolyn Gluckman, curator of costumes for Los Angeles
County Museum of Art, says, ``It was Adrian (yes, just Adrian) in
the late '40s and early '50s who first made clothing from fabric
featuring photographic images of surreal items, like a loaf of
bread. Although many people might have thought it silly, it
definitely wasn't silly in principle. These types of fashions were
simply tweaking our perceptions of how things are supposed to
look.''
</P>
<P>
   More recent examples of fashion satire, cites Murray, are
Christian Dior's dresses worn backward (And you thought Celine
Dion's suit was a fresh idea?) in the late '40s, and Yves Saint
Laurent's famous X-ray dress of the mid-'60s that featured a
silhouette of a woman's nude body on the front of a dress.
</P>
<P>
   Popping up every 10 or 20 years, Murray says fashion satires are
just one of the cycles in fashion. And it's about time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been through a long stretch of severely serious clothes
and Plain Jane looks ... and simple and tasteful gets boring if you
do it long enough. However, I don't think Happy Face purses will
stay long. They simply open the door to a more creative era,'' she
observes.
</P>
<P>
   Saks Fifth Avenue fashion director Kelly Bevan Spirer calls
fashion's new direction the cookie cutter rebellion, commenting,
``How many pairs of black loafers and khaki pants can you have?''
</P>
<P>
   She believes that designers and the public are hungry for items
that are special, whether it's the Bohemian look of feathers and
beads, a dress with a message on the front, or a purse with photo
imagery. And, like Murray, Bevan Spirer believes the current trends
are simply a taste of things to come in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   On that note, trendies may have trouble locating the latest
looks. Although Gucci's torn and feather-trimmed jeans are in
numerous fashion magazines, a recent search through several
department stores showed none on the racks. Gucci's feather-trimmed
mules, however, were spotted at both Neiman Marcus and Saks Fifth
Avenue. Perhaps it's because retailers know there are very few who
are not only brave enough to wear the clothes _ but also brave
enough to fork over several hundred dollars per item.
</P>
<P>
   For those on a budget, torn jeans, poncho tops, Happy Face
buttons and plastic purses can be bought on the cheap at thrift
stores and fast-fashion outposts such as Claire's Accessories and
Rampage. Other sources for making your own fashion satire are craft
stores, where you can buy marabou by the yard and realistic silk
butterflies, as well as funky fashion locales such as the Silver
Lake district or Venice Beach boardwalk.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of where you shop, use a little restraint, say
fashion experts.
</P>
<P>
   Bevan Spirer says it's an item-driven season _ one humorous item
is all you need to jump-start your wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Gluckman says to pay attention to quality, especially when
looking at clothes with photo images or appliques. ``Be sure to try
the clothes on and take note where the objects fall on the body.
Then judge for yourself whether it's humorous or insulting,'' she
advises.
</P>
<P>
   TV stylist Jane Mannfolk stresses the importance of playing down
your clothes with monochromatic color statements or simple lines to
showcase a pair of feathered sandals or a novelty purse, and warns,
``If you overdo it, you'll ruin the effect, and people will laugh
(START ITALICS)at(END ITALICS) you instead of (START
ITALICS)with(END ITALICS) you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
