<SLUG> BC-EGGS-COLOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE COLOR OF AN EGG IS ALL IN THE FEATHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISA STEVENS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question: Why are some eggs brown and some white? Other than the
color, is there a difference between the two?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Brown and white eggs have the same nutritional value and
quality, says ``Cookwise'' author Shirley O. Corriher. The color
difference, however, is all in the ears. The hen's ears, that is.
The type of chicken actually determines the egg's color. Want to
know what color egg the hen is going to lay? Corriher says, push
back the feathers on the sides of the hen's head. White ears mean
she'll lay white eggs; reddish brown ears mean brown eggs. Looking
for something in a lovely pale shade of green or blue? Check out
the ears of Araucana hens.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know the fall crocus is the source of saffron for cooking.
But are spring crocus stamens harvested and used in the same way?
</P>
<P>
   A: The saffron crocus looks like its ordinary spring-blooming
relatives, but it always blooms in the fall, says Laurence Sombke,
author of ``Beautiful Easy Herbs.'' The others are poisonous.
Inside each flower of the saffron crocus are three thin red
stigmata, or threads. These are what are harvested.
</P>
<P>
   ``The New Food Lover's Companion'' by Sharon Tyler Herbst tells
us saffron is the world's most expensive spice. Each saffron crocus
produces only three threads, which must be carefully hand-picked
and then dried. It takes more than 14,000 of them for each ounce of
saffron. That explains the spice's price. The spice is sold in
threads and in powder form. The powered saffron loses its flavor
more quickly than the threads. The threads should be crushed before
using. Saffron, which can be stored for up to six months, should be
placed in an airtight container in a cool, dark place.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
