<SLUG> BC-CASHMERE-CARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASHMERE DOES BETTER WHEN WASHED BY HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Cashmere is a low-maintenance material.
</P>
<P>
   You can take care of it yourself for few pennies and you will
wear it more often because you can wash it. Hand-washing only makes
cashmere better and better, softer and softer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You figure, it's been on a goat in the Himalayas,'' says
Stephanie Todd, manager of N. Peal, a cashmere boutique in San
Francisco, ``it can take just about anything.'' Except
dry-cleaning, which really doesn't add to the life or luster of a
cashmere sweater.
</P>
<P>
   Simple rules for cashmere care:
</P>
<P>
   Before washing, turn sweater inside out.
</P>
<P>
   Hand wash in any clear, lightweight liquid. Baby shampoo is
actually the best because cashmere is a hair. Make sure you get all
the soap out by rinsing it in cold water. (You can even throw it in
the washing machine on a delicate cycle.)
</P>
<P>
   If you're hand-washing, blot out the extra water by wrapping the
sweater in a towel and pressing gently.
</P>
<P>
   Hand-block the sweater back to its original shape on a towel on
a flat surface _ but make sure you dry it away from direct
sunlight. White cashmere will oxidize and yellow.
</P>
<P>
   When it's dry, you can press a cashmere with a steam iron on
medium heat. Be sure to use steam because the cashmere yarn will
singe.
</P>
<P>
   Store your cashmeres in plastic bags in the bottom half of your
closet or in a lower drawer (heat rises, and so do moths).
</P>
<P>
   Never hang a cashmere sweater.
</P>
<P>
   If you're good to your cashmere, it'll be good to you _ for
years and years and years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1304EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 13:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2485 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN     04-01 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PINK PANTHER' BROUGHT OUT THE BEST IN SELLERS, EDWARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You may have forgotten, but before he became
Oscar's lovable Furby, Roberto Benigni tried to fill the shoes of
the British comic actor Peter Sellers in Blake Edwards' ``Son of
the Pink Panther'' (1993). But playing the illegitimate offspring
of Inspector Clouseau (Sellers) left even the usually irrepressible
Benigni flat-footed.
</P>
<P>
   The film's failure can be put down to it simply being a bad
idea. As hard as he tried, Benigni was too often over the top, with
the gags being more goofy slapstick than rising out of Clouseau's
particular bumbling dim-wittedness.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and Sellers were the two men most responsible for the
success of ``The Pink Panther'' series, but the pair reportedly had
an uneasy relationship at best, and a rivalry developed over who
should get the most credit for the films' popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' continuation of the series with ``Son'' was seen by
some as an attempt _ a failed one _ to show that he was the comic
genius behind the films. The film illustrates that the two of them
probably needed each other more than they thought.
</P>
<P>
   There were seven ``Panther'' films altogether, including ``Son''
and ``The Trail of the Pink Panther,'' which was essentially a
hodgepodge of outtakes strung together as a film. It was released
in 1983, three years after Sellers' death from a heart attack at
the age of 54. Now four of the best of the series _ ``The Pink
Panther'' (1963), ``A Shot in Dark'' (1965) ``The Pink Panther
Strikes Again'' (1976) and the last real collaboration of Sellers
and Edwards, ``The Revenge of the Pink Panther'' (1978) _ are out
on DVD (MGM Home Entertainment; $24.95 each).
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 years later (30 in some cases), the ``Panther''
movies hold up _ hilariously. Of course, neither Sellers or Edwards
probably realized what they had on their hands when they started
making ``The Pink Panther,'' which was a comedy-caper movie
starring David Niven, Robert Wagner, Cappucine and Claudia
Cardinale. The inept Clouseau character was meant to supply most of
the comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Niven played a sophisticated jewel thief (Sir Charles Lytton),
who the poor inspector is on the trail of but never close to
catching. The Pink Panther? Well, that's actually a priceless gem
that Lytton is out to steal. But the real stealing in this picture
was done by Sellers, who stole the show with his impeccable comic
despite having less screen time than other cast members.
</P>
<P>
   In the next film, ``A Shot in the Dark,'' Inspector Clouseau and
Sellers' comic genius were brought to the forefront. Edwards, who
produced and directed the film, also co-wrote the screenplay with a
comedy writer who would later come up with some head-spinning
ideas, William Peter Blatty, author of ``The Exorcist.'' The film
is filled with one sight gag after another (Clouseau at a nudist
camp is priceless). It also introduced the character of Chief
Inspector Charles Dreyfus (Herbert Lom), the inspector's nervous
superior. Dreyfus would find himself frustrated by Clouseau in
subsequent films.
</P>
<P>
   When Sellers returned to play Clouseau more than 10 years later,
his numerous disguises were often the highlights of his films. This
was a trademark of the actor, who played three roles in Stanley
Kubrick's ``Dr. Strangelove,'' including the title role and the
president of the United States. In ``Revenge'' alone he plays the
vertically challenge Toulouse-Lautrec, a rickshaw driver and a
Swedish herring fisherman.
</P>
<P>
   But Sellers often wasted his talents on turkeys like ``The
Blockhouse'' (1974), where he played six roles, or ``The Great
McGonagall'' (1974), where he played Queen Victoria. Remember
either film? No, probably better for your brain cells. Bad choices
were often the case in Sellers' later career.
</P>
<P>
   He had made his mark in the '50s on the legendary BBC radio
series ``The Goon Show,'' and then starred in a number of terrific
comedies such as ``I'm All Right Jack'' and ``The Mouse That
Roared.'' Besides ``Strangelove,'' in the '60s and early '70s he
was known for those swinging comedies like ``What's New Pussycat?''
``After the Fox,'' ``Casino Royale'' and ``I Love you Alice B.
Toklas.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the success of ``Pink Panther'' series, most of
Sellers' '70s films are forgettable with one notable exception _
the satirical ``Being There'' (1979), for which he received a best
actor Oscar nomination. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2492 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CRIMES-BOS &LR;      04-01 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CRIMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST SAYS CRIMES TRIBUNAL MORE PREPARED THIS TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKOPJE, Macedonia _ Captain Wayne Hennessy-Barrett wishes
otherwise, but he can't forget the time four years ago when he and
other British soldiers were digging for bodies in a suspected mass
grave in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   He pulled up a shovelful of earth and found the remains of a
4-year-old boy, one of a group of civilians killed by Bosnian Serb
troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those times when your body goes hot and cold at
the same moment,'' the Dublin-born soldier recalled. ``And I
remember thinking, I want to help get the people who did this. We
didn't get as many as we'd have liked in Bosnia, but things will be
different this time around.''
</P>
<P>
   That may not be one soldier's idle boast. The conflict in Kosovo
is expected to lead to more war-crimes prosecutions than took place
over the Bosnian turmoil, not necessarily because there will be
more such crimes but because the mechanisms to detect and build
such cases are more sophisticated now.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats and analysts say the International Criminal
Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia, located in The Hague, is much
better organized and more professional than it was during the
Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   When the tribunal was formed in 1993, it had an annual budget of
$276,000 and a skeleton staff. By 1995, when the Bosnian war ended,
its budget was $25 million. Today, under the leadership of an
American judge, Gabrielle Kirk McDonald, it has a budget of $94
million and a staff of 625 from 57 countries.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, say diplomats and analysts, the tribunal gets
strong backing from the Western powers, including the United
States, Britain, and France.
</P>
<P>
   George Robertson, Britain's defense secretary, has warned
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic that after NATO finishes its
military mission against Serb forces, it intends to prosecute some
Serb political and military leaders for war crimes. ``We are
meticulously collecting evidence,'' Robertson said. ``These people
will face justice at The Hague.''
</P>
<P>
   And if Milosevic thinks he can cut a deal in which he will pull
back his forces in Kosovo in exchange for an amnesty on war crimes,
he's likely to be sorely disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from The Hague, Christian Chartier, the
tribunal's chief spokesman, said there will be no amnesties for any
war crimes carried out against ethnic Albanian civilians in Kosovo.
``We have come a long way in five years,'' said Chartier. ``We have
established our credibility, and diplomats and politicians have
realized that there will be no lasting peace without justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Western powers's backing of the tribunal marks a shift from
1995, when many diplomats suggested that the threat of prosecution
was hindering a settlement to the Bosnian war. ``It's night and day
since Bosnia,'' said Christopher Bennett, a Balkans analyst and
former director of the International Crisis Group in Sarajevo, who
has long lobbied for the tribunal to be at the forefront of
international efforts to stabilize the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said that the Bush administration had labeled Milosevic
a war criminal as far back as 1992, but that the Clinton
administration saw Milosevic as someone it had to do business with
to keep the Balkans warfare from spreading. Now, however,
Milosevic's defiance of the West has led the Americans to conclude
that Milosevic is central to the problem. ``This is a trial of
strength. And the West _ and especially the Americans _ are not
going to back down,'' said Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   In this conflict, NATO is using sophisticated satellite imaging
to gather evidence of forced marches, and the burning and looting
of villages. ``NATO has good intelligence, and they say they're
going to hand it over to the tribunal,'' said Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   The British government also once viewed the tribunal as an
impediment to diplomatic settlements, but that changed when Tony
Blair was elected prime minister in 1997 with a massive
parliamentary majority. The British government last year paid for
the construction of the tribunal's third and newest courtroom.
``That huge majority gives Blair the ability to take risks, and to
stand on principle, which John Major's government could not,'' said
Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, he says, the Americans under US Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright now regard the tribunal as a potent weapon in
the campaign to depose Milosevic and stabilize the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal, whose jurisdiction allows it to prosecute crimes
committed in the former Yugoslavia since 1991, has indicted 83
people so far. Six were convicted, one was acquitted, and charges
were dropped against 18. Some of the most notorious alleged war
criminals, including former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic
and his military chief Ratko Mladic, remain fugitives, and critics
say the UN peacekeeping forces in Bosnia have not done enough to
capture them.
</P>
<P>
   Western authorities say that the conflict in Kosovo will lead to
more prosecutions, and that the conviction rate will rise.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees fleeing Kosovo have told of summary executions of
civilians by Serb forces, as they empty and burn villages inhabited
by ethnic Albanians, who make up 90 percent of the population.
While none of these stories has been independently corroborated,
few international observers doubt that war crimes have been
committed as Serb forces conduct a ``scorched earth'' policy in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal's chief prosecutor, Louise Arbour of Canada, has
said she believes war crimes have been committed. Serb authorities
refused to allow Arbour to enter Kosovo in January after 45 ethnic
Albanian civilians were allegedly killed by Serb forces in the
village of Racak.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Arbour disclosed a secret 1997 indictment issued by
the tribunal against a Serb paramilitary leader, Zeljko Raznatovic,
for alleged crimes during the Bosnian conflict, urging that he be
brought to justice quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, such indictments are kept secret until after an
arrest. But Arbour said that publicizing it would ``put on notice
those who might be inclined to retain his services or to obey his
orders that they, too, will be tainted by their association with an
indicted war criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said Milosevic could face indictment ``if evidence is
forthcoming that he personally ordered, instigated, or in any other
way participated in offenses within the jurisdiction of the
tribunal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Blythe, a spokesman for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, said members of his group's human rights
staff have begun taking statements from refugees who claim to have
witnessed massacres. Tribunal investigators will do the same, and
seek corroborating physical evidence. But to do that, the bombing
will first have to end, and the Serbs will have to allow
investigators into Kosovo. Neither prospect appears imminent.
</P>
<P>
   NATO soldiers who hope eventually to enter Kosovo to implement a
peace plan say they are prepared to assist in detecting war crimes.
Some of them, like Hennessy-Barrett, the British soldier still
haunted by the image of a little boy's body, have experience that
will prove valuable, both in finding evidence, and in arresting
indicted war criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time,'' said Hennessy-Barrett, ``we'll get more of them.
That I can promise.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Colleen Brush contributed from The Hague to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
