<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2493 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERBIA-MILOSEVIC-BOS &LR;      04-01 1390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERBIA-MILOSEVIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER MOTIVATES SERB LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELIZABETH NEUFFER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charming yet bullying. Confrontational yet evasive. Beloved
Serbian leader whose policies have destroyed his own country. These
are the contradictions posed by Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Since coming to power a decade ago, Milosevic has drawn on these
complexities to confound Western efforts to bring him to heel. Even
as NATO bombs him, Milosevic spurs his troops onward brutally to
oust ethnic Albanians from Kosovo, to the West's horror and
embarrassment. Now NATO leaders face the dilemma of indicting him
for genocide or negotiating with him, aware of his actions.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder his foreign minister once described the 57-year-old
Milosevic to US envoy Richard Holbrooke this way: ``The master will
pull all the strings.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo ushered Milosevic from obscurity into the political
limelight, and Milosevic has made his toughest stand on the Serbian
province. Milosevic will continue to defy the NATO bombing campaign
while driving as many ethnic Albanians out of Kosovo as he can. He
is likely to hold on to the north and center of Kosovo, rich with
mineral deposits and home to many significant Serbian religious
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Balkan analysts say he will halt the killing only when he senses
he is losing grip on his government, or in full martyrdom, when he
decides it is more convenient to give up in Kosovo and blame the
West for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is a megalomaniac, modern-day Balkan despot,'' said
Jack Scanlon, the US ambassador in Belgrade from 1985 to 1989.
``All he cares about is political power.''
</P>
<P>
   During a visit to the Serb province of Kosovo in 1987, Milosevic
first realized the popular appeal of Serb nationalism and tasted
the success of his own demagoguery. Crowds chanted ``Slobo!
Slobo!'' as Milosevic pledged to Kosovo's Serbs: ``No one will dare
beat you again.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Milosevic returned to Kosovo, riding a wave of
cult-like popularity in a campaign that would make him Serbia's
first democratically elected president. Addressing a rally of 1
million Serbs on Kosovo Polje, the famous battlefield where the
Serbs lost to the Turks in 1389, Milosevic exhorted the crowds to
revel in their Serbdom, which has been suppressed under communist
leader Josip Broz Tito.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were brave and dignified and one of the few who went into
battle undefeated,'' he told the cheering Serb crowds. Then, in a
hint of what was to come, Milosevic said: ``Six centuries later we
are again in battles and quarrels. They are not armed battles,
though such things should not be excluded yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Elected as president of Serbia in 1989, Milosevic went on to
strip Kosovo of its autonomy and its Albanians of their basic
rights, planting the seeds of today's crisis.
</P>
<P>
   It is the power that invoking Kosovo gives Milosevic _ not
Kosovo itself _ that he cares about. Like many Serbs, he cares
little for the reality of the shabby province, a place where
industrial complexes scar the landscape and trash litters even that
most sacred battlefield.
</P>
<P>
   It is the symbolism of Kosovo that matters, and by now it has
taken on the aura of Custer's last stand. Negotiators who have
raised Kosovo with him say it is where Milosevic always draws the
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was singularly opposed to any talk of autonomy there,''
said one State Department diplomat who has met with Milosevic. ``He
went off on a long harangue about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic's tragic childhood may provide some clues to his
political ruthlessness. He was born into poverty in the dusty,
unremarkable town of Pozarevac southwest of Belgrade, where he grew
up in a household marked by loss. His father, a Serbian Orthodox
priest, abandoned the family and later killed himself. Milosevic's
mother also committed suicide a decade later, as did his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   In Pozarevac Milosevic met the one person who would shape him
most: his wife, Mirjana Markovic, who has become a significant
player in Belgrade politics after launching her own communist
party. The couple have two children, a daughter who helps shape her
father's image in her job on state-run television and a
free-wheeling tycoon son who is now building a Disney-style theme
park in Pozarevac called ``Bambiland.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has kept his family's humble white house with a red
tile roof and visits it on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   As a young man, Milosevic studied law at Belgrade University and
went on to work as a banker, even spending time in New York. His
genius lies in neither field, however, but in his ability to grasp
issues that resonate with his fellow Serbs and to maintain an iron
grip on the country's media. Even those who oppose him admire his
skillful use of propaganda in the country he has reduced to a
veritable police state.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Dr. Goebbels produced was nothing compared to what you
can see on Serbian television,'' commented Milos Vasic, of the
independent weekly Vreme, in a 1994 interview.
</P>
<P>
   With his beady eyes, jutting chin, and distinctive bristling
hair, Milosevic himself rarely appears in public, knowing a
leader's allure and power lie in his lack of accessibility.
Instead, he relies on his propaganda machine in Belgrade to spin
out the vision of Serbs as noble warriors yet historic victims
misunderstood by the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our heroic people have demonstrated that we cannot be subdued
by forces of arms,'' said Milosevic in a typically defiant
statement issued Tuesday after his meeting with Russian Prime
Minister Yevgeny Primakov. ``Yugoslavia will never accept giving up
its freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   It is this message of Serb glory, manipulated by Milosevic, that
has allowed him to stay in power even as he has torn Yugoslavia to
pieces. A decade ago, Yugoslavia had six republics, a high standard
of living and was considered the most Western and progressive of
all the countries in the communist world. Today, four of the
republics have seceded and the country has been battered by two
wars. Its citizens live in poverty, their currency all but
meaningless and their economy a shambles.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic became president of the rump Yugoslavia, which
consists of Serbia and Montenegro, in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   With each war, Milosevic would exhort the Serbs to greater glory
and then turn his back on the forces he had unleashed when they
threatened to undermine his own position. Milosevic encouraged
Serbs in a section of Croatia, known as the Krajina, to revolt and
claim the area as their own. But when Croatian troops, aided by US
military advisers, drove the Serbs out of the Krajina in 1995,
Milosevic was nowhere to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Milosevic imported war to Bosnia, aiding Bosnian Serbs
in 1992 as they joined his call for a ``greater Serbia.'' Yugoslav
army forces aided Bosnian Serb soldiers in ethnically cleansing
huge swaths of northwest Bosnia. Milosevic made no secret of his
frequent consultations with Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic
and his top general, Ratko Mladic.
</P>
<P>
   But when the tide of history began to turn against the Bosnian
Serbs, Milosevic abandoned them, too. In 1994, Belgrade announced
an embargo against Bosnian Serb leaders. Serb media began to depict
Karadzic as a war profiteer. Milosevic condemned the Bosnian Serbs
when they refused to adopt the Contact Group peace plan.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he would emerge as one of the chief peacemakers
in Dayton, when a peace plan was hammered out that would end the
war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has no beliefs,'' said Peter Galbraith, the former US
Ambassador to Croatia, who was present at Dayton. ``He cares only
about himself.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO members now realize that Milosevic has done a far better
job of manipulating the West than they have him. Instead of
propping up Milosevic as the chief power broker, they say, the
allies should try to reach out to others in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Neighboring Montenegro, with its feisty leader, Milo Djukanovic,
is one alternative; Milosevic, who purged his Cabinet last fall of
some of his closest allies, also created a pool of malcontents for
the West to tap.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the future of Milosevic and the Balkans will be just
as it has been in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has taken our measure,'' said Galbraith, ``I predict he
will do whatever it takes to ensure he remains on top.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
