<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT THE US MUST DO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Failed nation-states fall into three rough categories. First and
foremost are mega-states like Russia and China. They're too big
(and nuclear) to be allowed to fail, even though they have failed
or are in the process of doing so.
</P>
<P>
   It is US policy to provide the maximum possible assistance to
these nation-states as they convert from command economies to
market economies. The goal is to integrate them gradually into the
consortium of developed nations and thus diminish, step-by-step,
their incentives for military adventurism.
</P>
<P>
   The second category is comprised of failed nation-states that
are insane.
</P>
<P>
   These include North Korea and Iraq, to mention just two. The
signal characteristic of this group is that they are fully capable
of insane acts, like deploying nuclear weapons for no apparent
reason or engaging in chemical and biological warfare against real
or imagined enemies. It is US policy to contain these countries, by
force when necessary, so that their ability to wreak wider havoc is
minimized.
</P>
<P>
   The third category is comprised of failed nation-states that
don't matter, at least for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   These include countries like Rwanda and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Their governments have failed, their economies have collapsed,
their people suffer terribly, but there are otherwise no serious
consequences. It is unstated US policy to ignore these countries
for as long as possible unless and until they become such a
nuisance that something has to be done.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia has, for most of the 1990s, shuttled back and forth
between the ``insane'' category and the ``doesn't matter''
category. Yugoslavia contributes nothing to the global economy. It
isn't territorially significant. It ``matters'' only to the degree
that it threatens to engage the Balkans in wider conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It matters now. Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's
genocidal campaign against Kosovo has vaulted his country into the
uppermost ranks of failed-and-insane nation-states. The inability
of US and NATO air-power to contain Milosevic's havoc now requires
a much greater US commitment to expelling Serbian forces from
Kosovo and an expanded diplomatic campaign to deal with the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   To put it bluntly, the United States must now declare the
equivalent of war on the Milosevic regime and use all acceptable
means to destroy his military and para-military forces.
</P>
<P>
   Those means include the deployment of US troops in large
numbers. Indeed, the crisis in Yugoslavia calls for full
implementation of the Powell Doctrine, which states that the US
commit overwhelming force in overwhelming numbers to crush military
forces that are hostile to US interests.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences of not doing so are simply unacceptable. The
problem with failed-and-insane nation-states is that there are,
potentially, a lot of them. Because of telecommunications, each
knows what the other is getting away with at any given moment. If
it becomes apparent that genocide is tolerable, then other
failed-and-insane nation-states will conclude, correctly, that
anything goes so long as it doesn't move too far afield.
</P>
<P>
   And they will act accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the United States is currently involved in two
``police'' actions against failed-and-insane nation-states. There's
the ongoing air-war in Iraq and there's the 9-day-old air-war over
Yugoslavia. It is possible that the United States soon may have to
engage in a third police action, against North Korea, which is
teetering on the brink of chaos.
</P>
<P>
   And there may well be more ``police actions'' needed if the
United States does not use overwhelming force somewhere. At some
point, our ability to execute such actions is overwhelmed by their
number.
</P>
<P>
   Military planners would not have chosen Yugoslavia as the ideal
place to deploy overwhelming force, but at this point the United
States has little choice.
</P>
<P>
   Either we commit ourselves to the destruction of Milosovec's
forces or we lay waste to the credibility of our threat to every
failed-and-insane nation-state.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in Yugoslavia could not come at a worse time for the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's credibility has been destroyed by his
ceaseless mendacity. The military officers who report to him have
the gravest doubts about his willingness to stay any course. He has
surrounded himself with what most experts agree is the weakest
national security advisory team of the post-World War II era. And
little has been done to prepare Americans for what may well become
a protracted military engagement.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, we're stuck with these people for the next 22
months. Their decisions will either make the world a safer or more
dangerous place.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing the president should do is retract his promise
to never commit ground troops to the conflict. The second thing he
should do is intensify the air war by a factor of five. The third
thing he should do is initiate commmando raids into Kosovo to
intercept Serbian death squads and kill them. And the fourth thing
he should do is reduce Belgrade's infrastructure to rubble.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing Milosovec will respond to is overwhelming force.
The sooner the United States applies such force, the sooner the
insanity will abate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
