<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASHMERE-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNERS GET INSPIRATION FROM THE STREET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``The street'' is more and more the source.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion designers get a lesson in what people are really
wearing, and they translate accordingly: Tommy Hilfiger sells his
preppie khakis (albeit three sizes too big) to hip-hop kids. Anna
Sui borrows the look for her spring runway in a pair of acid green
holographic-treated cotton Home Boy jeans. Hooded sweatshirts are
the uniform of the street _ and now nearly every designer, from
Michael Kors to Bill Blass, has adapted it in cashmere, cotton,
silk or wool.
</P>
<P>
   Women's designers are claiming street looks and tweaking them to
cross the gender line _ note the appropriation of military cargo
pants by no less a ``classics'' designer than Ralph Lauren. For
spring, there isn't a major American designer who hasn't done
cargos _ from the most expensive (Ralph Lauren's Easter egg silks
in pink, blue, green and yellow ran $1,150) to the most practical
(Banana Republic's khaki/chino collection).
</P>
<P>
   And to go with them: the ubiquitous cashmere undershirt.
</P>
<P>
   Cashmere T's are definitely in for spring and summer. Cashmere
has been refined and thinned down for the summer season.
</P>
<P>
   Usually one-ply, summer T's fit closely, just like underwear,
and require racer-back or no-seam bra styles, or for the very
intrepid, no bra at all.
</P>
<P>
   T-shirt dressing isn't just relegated to cargos and chinos; with
Banana Republic's short shorts, a great new pair of Levis or Gap
jeans, or trim white trousers, they're a go-anywhere item.
</P>
<P>
   The casual pleasure of slipping into something very, very
comfortable for nighttime finds the cashmere T quite at home with
silks, satins, tuxedos and pricey, European couture, too: Like
Michael Kors' hand-sewn rock crystal skirt for Celine and Giorgio
Armani's slinky pull of embroidered fuchsia with the thigh-high
slit. (Keri Russell wore the orange version to the Golden Globes
with a strapless hankie top).
</P>
<P>
   Allison Speer, West Coast public relations chief for Giorgio
Armani, declares cashmere T's to be ``chic.'' (When Speer showed up
for the fashion shoot, she was wearing a black cashmere undershirt
T with a cardigan over, from Banana Republic.) ``I'm addicted to
cashmere,'' she giggled. ``I sleep in a cashmere Ralph Lauren Aran
Isle blanket each night; I'm traveling to Italy this weekend and
I'll wrap myself in a cashmere shawl. It's such a comfortable way
to dress. So modern, so '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   At Banana Republic, you can buy a cashmere T for under $100; at
Saks, a private-label undershirt goes for $225, about $20 under
Emporio Armani's fluffy, cloud-like one-ply T's in shades of gray,
cream and lavender (which is quite a bargain considering that all
of Emporio's cashmeres are milled at Italy's Loro Piana, which
makes some of the finest cashmere in the world).
</P>
<P>
   ``I love this sweater and these pants,'' squealed Planet
Hollywood's energetic Lori Puccinelli. ``I'm definitely getting
this. It's soooo comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   And then someone informed Puccinelli that her cargo pants topped
$1,100, to which she immediately rejoined, ``and I won't be getting
them any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cecilia de Quesada, modeling Banana Republic was not a great
stretch. ``I live in Banana,'' said the slender and stunning
daughter of Urannia Ristow. ``I love the shorts. They're a good
length, not too long, not too short. And the tanks are neat; I like
layering them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always loved that look _ of casual cashmere with a
knock-out skirt,'' said Kimberly Bakker who dresses up almost every
night. ``I loooove this; I feel much more comfortable
underdressing.''
</P>
<P>
   The point? Fashion's rules are bending since the young
fashionables spend so much time not dressed up. They're in the gym;
they're digging in the back yard; they've dressed down on Fridays
and aren't about to dress up on Friday night unless they can take
some of that casual comfort with them.
</P>
<P>
   Call it luxurious comfort clothing; it's what people want to
wear. In taking it off the street, these designers are on the right
track.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1327EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
