<HEADER>
A2511 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-01 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIRD'S-EYE VIEW OF DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I saw death at work, right before my eyes.
</P>
<P>
   I was standing by my kitchen window, half dreaming, watching the
birds at my feeder, when suddenly there was a swoop of feathers and
all but one of the birds took flight. Despite the snow falling
outside, I'd been reflecting on their easy life _ the protective
shelter of the rhododendron, the warm fluff of their feathers, a
feeding station full of seeds and suet _ but now something fierce
and frightening was taking place.
</P>
<P>
   I could make out a hawk the size of a pigeon on the ground under
the feeder. I identified it immediately by its curved beak and long
talons though I'd never seen one up close before. It looked as if
the hawk was trying to fly, despite the small black bundle in its
claws dragging it down. It took several leaps into the air before
falling back, but in moments the creature in its grasp ceased its
struggling, and I understood this was the hawk's pattern for
killing. Had it strangled the bird? Broken its neck? I couldn't
tell.
</P>
<P>
   With all those black feathers, the victim had to be a starling,
but with both wings tightly pinned to its sides, it seemed to have
shrunk. Its body was so compressed, it looked like a narrow black
umbrella with a yellow beak handle. I wondered briefly whether I
ought to do something, but by the time I'd made sense of the event,
it was too late to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   I settled in to watch the proceedings. The hawk began plucking
feathers with its beak, tossing them into the snow. When it had
cleared an area near the stomach, it broke through into organs that
must have still been warm. I watched it swallow strings of
intestine, as if it were slurping up pasta in marinara sauce. It
tossed the craw aside. When it had emptied the central cavity, it
denuded the wings and chewed on some substance it discovered there.
Between every bite, it flicked its head left and then right, slowly
circling the body as it ate in order to extend its angle of vision.
It seemed hyper-aware of its vulnerability on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   By now there was a small circle of pale red snow under the body,
as if someone had tinted the background with a splash of
watercolor. There was little left of the starling but the head, two
feet, and one long feather at each wingtip. The outside membrane
attaching these parts to one another had been scooped as clean as a
lobster shell, except for a gleaming red tube running from front to
middle, which, when I examined it later, turned out to be the neck.
Finished at last, the hawk took a step back and hopped to a nearby
fence. It strutted back and forth several times before flying into
the upper branches of a nearby maple. In minutes, it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Marblehead, the most densely populated town in Massachusetts,
has little space for wildlife. I suppose that's why this hawk left
its natural habitat and suddenly dropped from the sky into my yard
at 3 o'clock on a Monday afternoon. The whole thing can't have
taken more than a half-hour, but a week later, I still feel the
lingering effects of horror.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's the idea of birds eating birds that takes getting
used to. I'm comfortable with the idea of owls eating mice, but it
was a shock to see one winged creature feed upon another. Part of
the surprise was seeing a hawk prey upon birds I've come to think
of as nearly tame because they're used to my feeding them. These
were suburban birds, for goodness' sake. I hadn't known the world
they inhabited was red in beak and claw. Yet perhaps the scene made
such a powerful impression for still another reason. As soon as the
hawk was gone, I went looking for a book to soothe my jangled
nerves. When I selected Carlos Castaneda's book ``Journey to
Ixtlan,'' it fell open to the page where Castaneda is recalling a
time he'd awakened from a nap to find a falcon he'd been pursuing
perched in a tree above his head. He tells Don Juan that although
he'd planned to kill it, he was strangely reluctant to shoot it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death is our eternal companion,'' Don Juan tells him. ``It is
always to our left, at arm's length. It was watching you when you
were watching the white falcon.'' I read that last sentence twice.
Is that why I felt so chilled by the sudden appearance outside my
window of a bird of prey? Is that the reason I felt unnerved by how
swiftly and surely it went about its deadly business? Is that why I
felt such pity for an ordinary starling, selected at random to end
its unremarkable life?
</P>
<P>
   A week has passed. The birds are slowly returning. I hope
they're keeping one eye cocked to the sky. As for me, every time I
leave the house, I carefully search our maple for the telltale
outline of a hawk.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
