<HEADLINE>
CHEMICAL IN GREEN TEA MAY INHIBIT TUMORS  
 FOLLOW-UPS FOR CANCER FALL SHORT, DOCTORS SAY  
 AID CUTS HIT MOTHERS WITH ILL CHILD AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
 
Chemical in green tea may inhibit tumors 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Green tea contains a chemical that chokes off the new blood
vessel supply that cancerous tumors need to grow, a research team
in Sweden reports. The report, based on mouse and test-tube
experiments, may be the first solid evidence for a blood vessel
growth blocker in a natural plant substance, one US researcher
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This observation sounds fascinating and is probably very
important,'' said Dr. Peter Polverini of the University of
Michigan. ``It's the first of many likely to emerge in the next few
years as people look for these compounds in plants.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by Boston's Dr. Judah Folkman, scientists around the world
are investigating drugs that block or promote blood vessel growth,
both of which have tantalizing potential to treat cancer, heart
disease, and diabetes. But no one knows whether such drugs will be
effective and safe.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, scientists have accumulated data
suggesting that consumption of green tea is associated with lower
rates of some cancers in large human populations (in China) and in
laboratory animals.
</P>
<P>
   The new report, which appears in this week's Nature, brings the
two lines of research together. Yihai Cao and Renhai Cao of the
Karolinska Institute in Stockholm found that a component of green
tea called EGCG (epigallocatechin-3-gallate) inhibited the growth
of new blood vessels in the test tube.
</P>
<P>
   Lab mice raised on a weak solution of green tea had sharply
reduced new blood vessel growth in their corneas, compared to mice
that drank only water, after scientists injected the eyes of both
groups with a substance that stimulates vessel growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once this hits the street, there probably won't be any green
tea on the shelf,'' Polverini said, althought he won't be adding it
to his diet just yet. ``This field has had many bumps in the road,
and we have to understand the mechanisms,'' the Michigan scientist
cautioned. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Follow-ups for cancer fall short, doctors say &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 130,000 Americans will undergo surgery for colon and
rectal cancer this year, but for 31,000 the disease will return
within five years. So doctors must be on the lookout for
recurrences in this high-risk group. However, most of the follow-up
tests doctors now perform for colorectal cancer are worthless, a
leading group of cancer doctors says in a statement released this
week.
</P>
<P>
   An expert panel of the American Society of Clinical Oncology
reviewed all the studies they could find on 10 different follow-up
tests and concluded that only two are useful: a regular physical
exam, and a colonoscopy every three to five years, in which doctors
insert a fiber-optic device to examine the length of the large
intestine.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the panel estimated, about 75 percent of doctors who
do follow-up care for colorectal cancer perform colonoscopies every
six to 12 months after surgery, but there's no evidence such
frequency does any good. A blood test for CEA (carcinoembryonic
antigen) can sometimes pick up a recurrence, but 30 percent of
these cancers do not produce CEA and the test misses some that do.
</P>
<P>
   The panel recommended against relying on liver function tests,
tests for blood in the stool, computed tomography scans, blood
counts, and chest X-rays to screen for colorectal cancer
recurrence. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Aid cuts hit mothers with ill child at home &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's a mom to do when work interferes with caring for a sick
child? It's a dilemma for millions, but a study published this week
in the American Journal of Public Health shows the problem is
especially severe for millions of women and children who have lost
public assistance since federal welfare reform in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Those reforms ``assumed that parents leaving welfare for work
would face conditions similar to those faced by parents already in
the work force,'' said Dr. S. Jody Heymann of the Harvard School of
Public Health and Alison Earle of Harvard's Kennedy School of
Government.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they found, welfare-to-work moms are more likely to be
caring for at least one child with a chronic health condition. But
36 percent lacked any sick-leave time, compared to 20 percent among
employed women who never were on welfare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
