<HEADLINE>
COURT JUSTICES BASED DECISION ON CONSTITUTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes Justices text table)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ They are five white men, the cream of their
profession, and the choice of a string of conservative governors.
They have led Army platoons, tussled in politics, or earned
reputations as spellbinding storytellers.
</P>
<P>
   They work in a building on a bluff on the Merrimack River. They
choose their cases by pulling slips of paper from a handsome silver
pitcher. And 15 months ago they issued a decision that landed with
seismic force in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The state's method of paying for its schools was illegal, the
court ruled. And, in an order that has yet to be fulfilled by
Thursday's deadline, it told state policymakers to find a new way
to fund education.
</P>
<P>
   In a state known for its conservatism, the court demanded
radical change, reshaping the political terrain of the Granite
State.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision touched off fiery talk of placing term
limits on the court's justices and efforts to diminish the court's
oversight of educational funding.
</P>
<P>
   More than two dozen Republican lawmakers, led by 27-year-old
freshman David Corbin of Stratham, are still arguing that the
Claremont decision, named for one of the poor towns in the original
lawsuit, was an unconstitutional power grab by the Supreme Court.
They want the Legislature to throw it out.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, court observers said, the far-reaching
school-finance decision seemed jarringly incongruous coming from a
court shaped by GOP governors from Meldrim Thomson Jr. to Stephen
E. Merrill. But some law professors and veteran attorneys said
careful students of the court should not have been startled by its
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shouldn't have been a surprise to anybody,'' said Fred
Upton, 80, a Concord lawyer who has practiced law in the state for
a half century. ``I know some people have claimed the decision was
social engineering. But they did their duty despite the political
winds of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the court found that the right to public education is a
fundamental right akin to the right to free speech or assembly, and
that New Hampshire is one state and not a collection of towns and
school districts, the old district-by-district system to pay for
schools was doomed. In essence, the court's dramatic decision was
wrought by the simple language of the state Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a word that describes this court, it's
independent,'' said James Duggan, interim dean of the Franklin
Pierce Law School. ``They take their responsibility as equal branch
of the government very seriously. It's a practical court that is
very conscious of the impact their decisions have on the trial
court, on police, and on citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's highest court is led by Chief Justice David A.
Brock, a 62-year-old former Dartmouth College hockey goalie, who
was Richard Nixon's choice for US attorney in New Hampshire in
1969. Brock, a native of Stoneham, Mass., the father of six, and a
former Army intelligence officer, is well-known in legal circles
for a 1985 ruling that roadblocks to stem drunken driving amount to
unreasonable searches and seizures.
</P>
<P>
   But he also authored the 4-1 schools funding decision, and has
publicly defended it in the face of a conservative outcry.
</P>
<P>
   The decision's lone dissenter, Justice Sherman D. Horton Jr.,
was the former law partner of Governor Hugh Gregg _ an avuncular
yarn-spinner who replaced David Souter on the court when Souter
joined the US Circuit Court of Appeals in Boston before his
appointment to the US Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   When Horton was appointed in 1990, he was the first high court
nominee in 44 years never to have served as a justice in a lower
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very strongly that real social policy ought to be set
by the Legislature,'' Horton said when he was nominated.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what some critics of the school finance decision
said the Supreme Court did when it threw out the existing local
property tax system of paying for public classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a surprise to me because I did not see our court in New
Hampshire as being one that typically ventured into areas that have
been traditionally reserved for resolution by the political
branches of government,'' said Manchester lawyer Eugene Van Loan
III.
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Hesse, a constitutional law professor at Franklin
Pierce Law School who was part of the plaintiffs' legal team in the
schools funding case, insisted that the court has been restrained
and mainstream, a body that has been reluctant to make radical
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no way they could have arrived at any other
conclusion but that the (local property) tax is not proportional
and reasonable,'' Hesse said. ``These are five guys who are up
there, trying to do the best job that they can. They're not
infallible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FOUR WHO ENDED NEW HAMPSHIRE'S STATUS QUO, AND ONE WHO DISSENTED
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The court decision that has had the state in turmoil for 15
months came down to just five people. One justice, William F.
Batchelder, retired from the high court in 1995 but was named a
special justice in the case to replace Justice W. Stephen Thayer
III, who had recused himself because his wife had chaired the state
board of education. The vote, in December 1997, was 4 to 1, with
Justice Sherman D. Horton Jr. dissenting.
</P>
<P>
   William F. Batchelder,
</P>
<P>
   retired
</P>
<P>
   Age: 72
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Plymouth
</P>
<P>
   Education: University of New Hampshire, Boston University Law
School
</P>
<P>
   Appointed: 1981 by Governor Hugh Gallen
</P>
<P>
   Party affiliation: Independent
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   David A. Brock,
</P>
<P>
   chief justice
</P>
<P>
   Age: 62
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Hopkinton
</P>
<P>
   Education: Dartmouth College, University of Michigan Law School
</P>
<P>
   Appointed: 1978 by Governor Meldrim Thomson Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Party affiliation: Republican
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John T. Broderick Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Age: 51
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Manchester
</P>
<P>
   Education: Holy Cross, University of Virginia Law School
</P>
<P>
   Appointed: 1995 by Governor Stephen E. Merrill
</P>
<P>
   Party affiliation: Democrat
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
