<SLUG> BC-WAR-POLITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BOTH PARTIES, SHOE WAS ON THE OTHER FOOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ To some who watch the way Washington wages war, the
Capitol Hill vote on NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia seemed upside
down. Legions of liberal Democrats, including Senator Edward M.
Kennedy, backed the military intervention, while many of the usual
Republican hawks opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   Many senators voted the other way in 1991, when Congress
authorized the use of force in the Gulf War. This has led to
widespread suggestions that the parties are simply following the
wishes of whichever leader is in the White House, rather than
acting on principle.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry, who voted in 1991 against the Gulf War,
on the grounds that diplomacy should be given more time to work,
disagreed with Republicans who had made a similar argument on the
Kosovo vote. Kerry backs the NATO air assault, and has chided
Republicans who opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate vote was 58-41 in favor of backing the NATO air
campaign, with 38 of 55 Republicans opposing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics has taken over foreign policy in a way that in the
past we managed to avoid,'' Kerry said. Those who supported
intervention ``in Grenada, Panama, Somalia, and Desert Storm are
suddenly opposed to the very same kind of intervention on greater
foundation. It is called politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Politics plays a major role, but members of Congress and foreign
policy experts say another trend is at work as well, perhaps
indicating a shift in the way two parties view war. Simply put, the
end of the Cold War has changed the way many politicians look at
military action.
</P>
<P>
   For many Republicans, especially those who supported the Gulf
War, the vote on Kosovo has reopened one of the oldest debates for
the party: whether the United States should be internationalist and
should police world affairs, or whether it should be isolationist.
</P>
<P>
   For many Democrats, including some of the most liberal
legislators, the vote last week was cast not just on the question
of foreign policy, but also on humanitarian policy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Senator Paul David Wellstone, the Minnesota
Democrat and one of the most liberal members of Congress, peppered
a news release defending his support of air attacks with references
to his concern about the unfolding ``humanitarian disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   William Hyland, a former national security official in the Nixon
and Reagan administrations and former editor of Foreign Policy
magazine, said the Kosovo vote indicates a fundamental shift for
the two political parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not so much who has the power in the White House, as the
end of the Cold War,'' Hyland said. ``The end of the Cold War has
changed the whole strategic calculation. It is now legitimate to be
for intervention, to say we should go into Bosnia, into Kosovo, to
defend values. In the Cold War that would have immediately have
resulted in someone who said, `Yeah, you want a nuclear war?' So we
didn't intervene in Hungary or Czechoslovakia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the Cold War is over, the risks of intervention are
suddenly quite different. That allows liberals or Democrats to say,
`OK, we have to stand up for things, if necessary use military
power.' And Republicans are lapsing kind of back to, `We might be
able to defeat these guys, but we're not the world's policeman,' ''
Hyland said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats who voted against the Gulf War, and for the
Kosovo intervention, said last week that the two situations are
different, and that no trends are at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gulf War resolution was rushed through Congress at a time
when many of us felt that ongoing diplomatic initiatives had not
yet been exhausted,'' Kennedy said. ``Kosovo is entirely different.
It was clear beyond any doubt that the only language President
Milosevic understands is force.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate minority leader, Tom Daschle, who also initially
opposed the Gulf War, said: ``I think in this case we have
exhausted every single diplomatic option available.'' He also
asserted that NATO had requested US participation.
</P>
<P>
   A few Democrats, meanwhile, say the party initially was too
quick to say that Clinton could act without congressional
authority. Representative Barney Frank of Newton, while supporting
the air attacks, said he was disappointed that most Democrats
initially were willing to let Clinton act without explicit
congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under Reagan and Bush, Democrats generally argued the
president needs congressional authorization to put our troops in
potential combat, and Republicans said it was a matter of
presidential prerogative,'' Frank said. ``A very large percent have
switched.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 11, the House voted mostly along party lines to back
the deployment of 4,000 US troops as part of a NATO effort in
Kosovo. After the air raids were launched last week, the House
voted Wednesday 424-1, with Democrat Barbara Lee of California the
lone dissenter, to express support for the troops.
</P>
<P>
   There is also the question of whether Democrats have dropped
concerns about whether the War Powers Act should be invoked. It
requires the president to notify Congress within 90 days that he
has placed US troops ``into hostilities or into situations where
imminent involvement in hostilities is clearly indicated by the
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The act also requires the president to withdraw those troops
unless Congress declares war or specifically authorizes the use of
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Before Friday, when Clinton notified Congress of the Kosovo
action, Kerry said the act had not become an issue because the
Kosovo action, technically, is not a war.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not yet war,'' Kerry said in an interview. ``We
haven't declared war. If this went on for a period of time, it
would then be under the War Powers Act.
</P>
<P>
   In the debate of last week, the question of whether senators
were switching their view on intervention became central. Senator
Ted Stevens, an Alaska Republican, questioned why Senator Joseph R.
Biden Jr., the Delaware Democrat, was supporting the Kosovo
intervention when he had opposed the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gulf War debate, Biden argued that President Bush was
unconstitutionally trying to wage war without congressional
approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the difference between that situation'' in the Persian
Gulf ``and this threat the senator is describing in Serbia and in
Kosovo now?'' Stevens asked Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a big difference,'' Biden replied. ``The difference
is it is in the center of Europe, number one. Number two, if Europe
in fact becomes destabilized, we are deeply involved in matters far
beyond what is existing now.''
</P>
<P>
   Biden then tried a novel argument, saying Republicans had been
right in the Gulf War debate and so should support Clinton on
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turns out it made sense to move in the Gulf, and I argue it
makes sense for us to take this action now in the Balkans,'' Biden
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
