<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIANS-REUNION-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIAN REFUGEES CONNECT WITH LONG-LOST RELATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 (Eds.: Charlee Chhay is cq; a and i coding))   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Charlee Chhay was only 17 years old when he lost his
parents in Cambodia's killing fields a quarter century ago. He was
an orphan, but he was also the oldest of three brothers. And the
choice he faced was terrifying: He could either hide his family in
the war-torn countryside or try to ferry his brothers to the
relative safety of a refugee camp over the Thai border.
</P>
<P>
   He chose flight.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying no food or water, Chhay strapped Vuthy, who was 12, on
the back of his bicycle for the two-day ride to the Thai border.
Once Vuthy found protection with a friend in the camp, Chhay
slipped back through the mountains, dodging bullets and landmines
meant for the Khmer Rouge and the Vietnamese Communists to retrieve
his younger brother, Kiravuth, 7.
</P>
<P>
   Even within the refugee camp, the boys endured near-starvation
and the ache of feeling they were alone in the world. Their loss
was cushioned _ but not erased _ once the trio made it to the
safety of a Plymouth, Mass., foster home in 1981 with the help of a
church group.
</P>
<P>
   While the brothers found a new life, they lost contact with
their extended family, many of whom were among the 1 million to 2
million Cambodians killed in the fighting between 1975 and 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, however, Chhay and his brothers, who now live in
Lynn, will be reunited _ on a video hookup _ with an aunt, uncle
and cousins they thought were lost to the past. The story of their
reunion is testimony to an aunt's persistence in a quest to find
her brother's children and the doggedness of the International Red
Cross on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Sopheap Chhay Sok, who had left Cambodia with
her children in 1982 after she learned her husband was living in
France, asked the Red Cross in Paris to help locate the nephews she
had last seen in Phnom Penh in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The scant information Sok supplied made its way last summer to
the desk of Regina Szwadzka, an international social services
coordinator at the American Red Cross of Massachusetts Bay. Armed
with immigration papers from the Red Cross in Bangkok and pictures
of the boys taken in the refugee camp, Szwadzka started asking
questions. She visited members of the Lutheran church agency in
Newton that had sponsored the brothers; she also placed ads in
local Cambodian newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Tracing relatives dislocated by war _ from the Holocaust to the
Rwandan genocide _ has become a key role of the International Red
Cross. In August, the organization will celebrate the 50th
anniversary of the Geneva Convention, which granted the relief
agency the authority to look for refugees scattered over the globe.
The searches can last from several months to several years.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, where the Cambodian population is estimated at
50,000, the Red Cross traces about 50 cases of Cambodian refugees a
year, second only to the caseload in Stockton, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Chhay case was complicated because neither family is living
in their native country. To Szwadzka, progress felt glacial. ``We
would make calls, leave messages and wait; it was very
frustrating,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But even after Chhay learned the Red Cross was looking for him,
he did not respond. That pattern, Szwadzka said, is a familiar one
among Cambodian refugees. After being traumatized by genocide and
uprooted repeatedly since the mid-1970s, many Cambodians are afraid
to accept or reply to an official message _ even one from the Red
Cross _ for fear that it could somehow harm a relative in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the reactions are visceral. For Chhay, the nightmares
of being chased by Pol Pot's henchmen came rushing back after he
heard the Red Cross was trying to find him.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Szwadzka persisted. ``I knew if he could only meet
me, it would be OK,'' she said. Szwadzka could only reach Chhay
through friends, because he insisted on keeping his telephone
number and address secret. So she sent him a letter through
intermediaries, promising to keep his whereabouts secret from
anyone she could not be sure was a relative.
</P>
<P>
   To Szwadzka's relief, Chhay phoned her after he received her
Feb. 19 letter. Chhay, she said, was incredulous that his relatives
were alive and living in France.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after showing him documents that listed his relatives'
address in France and details Sok had supplied, she convinced him
that some members of his family had indeed survived. Within 24
hours, he was on the phone with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot,'' said Chhay, whose eyes brimmed with tears as
he recalled the terror of running from the soldiers. ``I didn't
think I had any more family. We came here just the three of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Chhay, who is now a technician for a Wakefield laser company
where Vuthy is an assembler, was the only one of the brothers who
remembered his relatives; he was especially fond of Sok, who used
to serve him bowls of sweet sticky rice and juicy Asian pears.
Through the years, Chhay said he had never tried to track down any
family members, in part because he recalled only nicknames.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Chhay has learned that 60 relatives perished in
the conflict in his homeland. But he also has found out that
several other family members survived, including a few who are
still living in Cambodia. Sok and her husband, who had been a
Cambodian air force instructor who did not return to the country
when war broke out, and other cousins are safe in France.
</P>
<P>
   After Chhay accepted the idea that he had family, albeit an
ocean away, it was a relief. ``It was like he (Chhay) took some
very heavy bags from his shoulders,'' Szwadzka said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past four weeks, Chhay and his brothers have had long
conversations with their relatives in France, trying to recapture
some of the lost 25 years. But Chhay said he really won't believe
his aunt is alive until he sees her.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many years I've been thinking of this aunt, who looks like
my grandmother,'' Chhay said. ``I saw her in my dreams, but in my
head I'm not sure she's still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the money on either side of the Atlantic to pay for
travel, the families may have to settle for the teleconference,
which is being sponsored by Sullivan and Cogliano, a computer
networking company in Waltham. The firm responded to an appeal by
the Red Cross to defray the cost of a reunion.
</P>
<P>
   The preparations for the video reunion have taken place during
the ``ethnic cleansing'' and NATO bombing in Kosovo, when refugee
issues are resonating everywhere. ``I can feel how the refugees
feel right now,'' Chhay said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with the news that some members of his family survived,
he is comforted. ``I don't feel like I'm alone anymore.'' Chhay
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
