<HEADER>
A2529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHEF-EDUCATION-BOS     04-01 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHEF-EDUCATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROGRAM HAS YOUTH BOILING OVER WITH IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Corey Wallerson, 20, stands in front of a half-dozen
steaming, sizzling pans, casually stirring the kohlrabi sauce,
searing the scallops, and simmering the cippolini onions.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, he was headed nowhere, when he happened into
Reesa Levy's home-economics class at John Dewey High School in
Brooklyn. Now, he's a cook, in charge of the fish station at JUdson
Grill, a top-flight restaurant in midtown Manhattan, with ambitions
of opening his own place one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that program weren't around,'' Wallerson said of his school
days, ``I'd probably be in the streets right now. I wouldn't have
had any direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallerson is one of several thousand young people _ most of them
from the rougher neighborhoods of New York, Chicago, Philadelphia,
Washington, D.C., and Los Angeles _ now manning grills, knives,
broilers, steamers, mixers, and basters in some of the nation's
finest eating establishments.
</P>
<P>
   They got there with the help of Richard Grausman, a 61-year-old
former chef from the Cordon Bleu, who found himself in a funk one
day a little more than 10 years ago and decided to do something
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Grausman's revelation came in Boston, at a cooking conference in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone from Campbell Soup gave a speech predicting the future
of American cooking,'' Grausman recalled, sitting in his office, a
converted studio apartment on Manhattan's Upper West Side. ``He
said the future was the microwave and the fact that no one will be
sitting down at the table for a family meal. Well, this was very
depressing for a culinary educator.''
</P>
<P>
   Grausman had just written a cookbook called ``At Home with the
French Classics,'' and on his publicity tour, at various department
stores, he found that by ages 25 to 45, most people had made up
their minds what they liked or disliked in food.
</P>
<P>
   These two discoveries about the state of food in America _ a
static present and a hopeless future _ set in motion a new train of
thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized,'' Grausman said, ``that, if there was anything
that I could do to change that forecast I heard in Boston, the
answer was to get into the schools.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1990, he toured a dozen home-economics classes in
the New York public school system and was shocked by what he saw _
bare cupboards, no supplies, lackluster support. ``Home Ec had been
turned into a dumping ground for kids who didn't succeed
academically,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So Grausman started calling food companies and cookware
manufacturers, convincing them that it was in their own long-term
interest to cultivate the tastes and talents of this next
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Reesa Levy at John Dewey was one of the teachers Grausman
visited. ``Richard asked me, `What do you need?' '' she recalled.
``I said, `I have nothing.' So he gave me a catalog. I made out 18
pages of orders. My husband says, `Whaddayou, nuts? You're not
going to get anything.'
</P>
<P>
   ``A few weeks later,'' Levy said, ``I get a delivery. It's 20
boxes of food, equipment, supplies. Everything changed in those two
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   She waved her arm across the classroom. A couple dozen
apron-clad sophomores, working in several small groups, were making
chicken-curry crepes, delicately chopping meat, dicing scallions,
stirring white sauce. The shelves were filled with everything a
chef would need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without Richard,'' Levy said, ``I doubt there'd be any Home Ec
teaching in the city. So many schools were shutting down their
programs. Now, they're opening up kitchens like crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Grausman's program _ known as C-CAP, for Careers through
Culinary Arts Program _ has spread to 200 teachers in 190 urban
public high schools, 32 of them in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Every spring, he sponsors a cooking contest, where some of the
nation's top chefs serve as judges. Each teacher picks the two top
students to compete. All the finalists _ usually between 100 to 140
students _ receive scholarships to cooking colleges, several of the
prizes paying full tuition of up to $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   C-CAP has raised $5.3 million in scholarship money during the
past decade _ $1 million of it in the past year. More than 10,000
pupils have joined the program, and 525 have received scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Wallerson won a full-tuition scholarship to the Culinary
Institute of America in June 1996. Kirk Johnson, another C-CAP
beneficiary, won a scholarship that year at the French Culinary
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who grew up in Jamaica before moving to Brooklyn at age
12, had always helped his mother cook. ``But then in C-CAP,'' he
recalled, ``I read these French recipes and thought, `Wow! I'd like
to do stuff like that.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even now, the front lines of Manhattan's upscale restaurants are
rarely staffed by people having this sort of background _ poor,
black, barely out of their teens.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Telepan, executive chef at JUdson Grill, said Grausman's
program ``gives kids opportunities _ it evens the score a little.''
</P>
<P>
   One morning at Park West High School, near the Hudson River in
midtown Manhattan, Alex Askew, head of the Black Culinary Alliance,
a restaurant-consulting firm in Harlem, spoke to 500 students in a
big auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many of you want to be chefs?'' Askew asked, and about 300
raised a hand. ``This is a very successful career,'' he went on.
``If you're good, you can go anywhere in the world and get a job.''
</P>
<P>
   When one student asked him how much money he makes, Askew paused
and replied, ``More than $50,000,'' eliciting gasps. An assistant
chef, with a few years' experience, in a good New York restaurant,
can easily make that much; a head chef, much more.
</P>
<P>
   Latisha Anderson and Christopher Rivas, two students at Park
West, work after school as interns at Windows on the World, atop
the World Trade Center _ Anderson cooking cold dishes, Rivas hot
dishes. They make long commutes, from Bedford-Stuyvesant and
Prospect Heights, to attend class here. Both plan to enter the
C-CAP cooking contest next month, and both know what they want to
do with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing this program does, besides provide these kids with a
good career option, is it brings them to school,'' said Wayne
Berning, director of the culinary program at Park West High School.
``It gives them a hook. So then we get a chance to teach them
English and math and history and science. A lot of these kids
wouldn't show up without this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
