<HEADER>
A2531 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-CITIZENS-ART-BO     04-01 1476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-CITIZENS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZENS: QUIRKY BANK IN A BIG POND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- For years, it has flourished as an oddity.
</P>
<P>
   Flanked on one side by New England's two big banks and on the
other by community institutions, Citizens Financial Group Inc. is a
small, foreign-owned bank in a world increasingly divided between
publicly traded giants and pint-sized players.
</P>
<P>
   Its chief executive, Lawrence K. Fish, is surely one of the
hidebound banking industry's only leaders to have spent time in an
ashram in India. Even the company's annual report is offbeat,
listing how many lollipops and dog biscuits branches passed out to
customers last year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its quirkiness, Citizens may hold some important keys to
the future of banking in New England, already in the throes of
change as Fleet Financial Group Inc. and BankBoston Corp., the
region's top players, prepare to merge into the nation's
eighth-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   That combination is producing the largest branch and deposits
divestiture in US history. Citizens, once a sleepy mutual savings
outfit but now New England's third-largest bank, is viewed as a top
contender for a good chunk of those assets.
</P>
<P>
   But as Citizens ponders new growth, industry observers are
wondering how the company can maintain its devoted focus on
customer service, a feature more typical of smaller banks. And they
are quietly debating whether Citizens' sole owner, The Royal Bank
of Scotland, isn't preparing to bankroll acquisitions for its
favorite child as a prelude to selling off the company _ a move
that could usher a new competitor into New England.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding its awe-shucks homilies about being a big
community bank, Citizens ``is trying to be a bigger factor in New
England banking,'' said James Moynihan, a senior vice president at
Advest Inc., a stock brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   ``As their franchise grows, it becomes very attractive to a
bidder outside the region,'' Moynihan added. ``And the bigger
Citizens is, the bigger the premium it can fetch for Royal Bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, said Fish, the 54-year-old son of Chicago social
workers. ``If the divestitures present opportunities for us, we'll
look at them seriously,'' Fish said in interview earlier this week.
``With us, it's not about absolute size. But you can potentially be
a better bank for your customers with more branches and more
conveniences.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Citizens has a rich uncle, able and willing to help
its ward grow. The Royal, as it is known, quadrupled Citizens' size
this decade to $18.2 billion in assets and 280 branches by
bankrolling local acquisitions. (In contrast, a merged
Fleet-BankBoston will have $178 billion in assets.)
</P>
<P>
   While lacking the hundreds of millions of dollars in cash needed
to buy the 270 or so branches and $13.6 billion in deposits that
Fleet Boston Corp. will sell later this year, Scotland's largest
publicly traded company could easily raise the money on capital
markets, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Royal would be very keen indeed to acquire some of
those branches for Citizens,'' said Robin Down, a UK banks analyst
at ABN-Amro Holding in London. ``These opportunities don't come up
very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Citizens and its owner are acting coyly about the
soon-to-be divested branches, which Fleet and BankBoston must sell
to satisfy antitrust regulators. When asked earlier this week
whether Citizens would buy any of the outlets, a Royal spokesman
said, ``We don't know what's on the table yet. Citizens will be
watching that very carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview several weeks before Fleet announced it was
acquiring BankBoston, Royal Bank chief executive Sir George
Mathewson said he couldn't see Citizens getting much bigger than
$25 billion in assets _ a still-hefty increase of nearly $7
billion, or 40 percent. He brushed aside questions of whether
Citizens would be sold, saying the Royal currently had no such
plans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Far bigger than a savings and loan but dwarfed by Fleet and
BankBoston, Providence-headquartered Citizens sits smack in the
middle of an increasingly barren space in American banking. Mergers
and consolidations are creating a bipolar world populated by giant
banks with hundreds of billions in assets and by Lilliputian
outposts, some with less than $50 million in deposits. Banks of
Citizens' size are an endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   But with no publicly traded stock, Citizens faces fewer of the
do-or-die pressures its listed competitors confront each quarter.
While many banking analysts say it is conventional wisdom that the
Royal will eventually sell Citizens for a sweet profit, Fish
ignores such talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never operated in the shadow that we're going to be
taken over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fish _ the former head of the failed Bank of New England and an
ex-Bank of Boston executive who once worked for the US government
in Brazil _ said Citizens had in the past considered issuing stock
and going public. But it has no plans now to do so, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In its odd niche, 183-year-old Citizens has won plaudits by
combining the hand-holding typical of community banks with some of
the broader services typical of larger banks. The company, which
operates in Massachusetts and other New England states as Citizens
Bank, is New England's largest automobile lender. It provides
service in 42 languages, including Tagalog and Croatian, and even
sends out Good Humor ice cream trucks to branches in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the formula has kept the Royal pleased indeed. Citizens,
with record net income last year of $244.2 million, a third more
than in 1997, accounted for a hefty one-fifth of its owner's pretax
profits in 1998. In a landscape full of UK banks buying American
banks but failing to make a profitable go of it, the Royal's
Citizens investment is a rare success.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with 1.2 million customers, most of them middle income,
Citizens is tethered to a business with increasingly slower growth
opportunities. While it has double-digit market share for deposits
in New Hampshire and Rhode Island, it has less than 4 percent of
the larger Massachusetts market.
</P>
<P>
   Against that backdrop, the bank has quietly branched out into
asset-based lending and leasing through offices in Pittsburgh,
Atlanta, and New York _ sophisticated operations more typical of
Fleet. And it is trying to sell itself to customers as a one-stop
financial services house with mutual funds and insurance. This
month, Citizens will even add on-line banking _ a feature shunned
by community banks, which prefer the human touch.
</P>
<P>
   To some observers, the moves appear to be pulling Citizens away
from its community bank-style approach. Even at its present size,
the company is laboring to iron out inconsistencies in branch
service. Getting bigger would probably mean less of the personal
touch Citizens prides itself on (including what Fish calls ``phone
hugs'' _ morale-boosting calls to staffers). But buying more
branches may be necessary and desirable. While Citizens says it has
moved into a phase of ``organic,'' or internal, growth after buying
15 local banks since 1992, some see its ability to increase profits
without more branches as limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing earnings at Citizens is hampered by a lack of
opportunity to cut costs,'' said Matthew Charlton, a banking
analyst at Schroder Securities in London. ``Such an opportunity
would mostly come from acquiring branches.''
</P>
<P>
   Fish has sore memories of 1996, when Citizens got locked out of
the area's most recent big divestiture as Bank of Boston acquired
BayBanks Inc. and sold most of the divested branches to UST Corp.,
a smaller bank that competes with Citizens. This time he may push
hard to pick up assets.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Citizens will come out on top is unclear. From small
regional players like Portland, Maine-based People's Heritage
Financial Group Inc. to giant BankAmerica Corp., the nation's
second largest bank, a brace of competitors is rumored to be
jockeying for the assets. Regulators will not decide for several
months whether a sale to local, national, or a combination of banks
will best preserve competition. But many politicians, including the
members of the state's congressional delegation and Governor Paul
Cellucci, have urged officials to give smaller, local banks an edge
in the bidding.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, by bulking up on the remains of Fleet-BankBoston,
the quirky company that calls itself ``Not Your Typical Bank''
could become your typical takeover candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately,'' ABN-Amro's Down said, ``we expect the Royal to
opportunistically grow Citizens while it can, and then sell it
off.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
