<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY MANAGERS STIR MEMORIES OF A DYING BREED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe there's hope for the mutual fund cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   Fund managers free to buy whatever kinds of stocks they please
in the hunt for big returns are a dying breed, boxed in by the
style restrictions of a clientele investing for retirement and
demanding consistency. Managing within categories like small value
stocks or large growth stocks is a mandate in fund companies across
America.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Investments, once famous for its stable of unfettered
fund managers, changed with the times a few years ago. Columns like
ours declared the death of the cowboy culture.
</P>
<P>
   Now, fast forward and take a look at the hottest general stock
funds in Fidelity's lineup in these first months of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Fifty, invigorated by a new manager in January, has
shot the lights out with a year-to-date return of 27.1 percent
earlier this week. Close behind, New Millenium had advanced by 24.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Together they were the two best funds managing at least $10
million anywhere in their general category of capital appreciation
so far in 1999, according to fund tracker Lipper Inc. They are the
hottest funds in town at the moment (excluding some invested in
specific sectors or regions) and each ranks among the top 1 percent
of all general stock funds through last week.
</P>
<P>
   What's their mandate? Fidelity Fifty is supposed to be a
collection of 50 or 60 good ideas, just like its name suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity describes the New Millenium objective as finding
``future beneficiaries of social and economic change.'' Good luck
nailing that one down.
</P>
<P>
   Neither one of the funds seems likely to accumulate big holdings
of government bonds or peso-denominated debt. It would be a stretch
to call them cowbodys, but both are remarkably free to buy
investments of almost any kind.
</P>
<P>
   John Muresianu took over Fidelity Fifty on Jan. 4 and clearly
turned the portfolio upside down. But it's impossible to say
exactly what he bought because the most recent public information
on Fifty's top holdings dates back to Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The clear consensus opinion among Fidelity watchers and others:
Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fidelity Fifty became an Internet play shortly after he took
over,'' said Eric Kobren, publisher of Fidelity Insight, an
independent newsletter. ``We noticed in January that it was very
highly correlated to Internet stocks and obviously remains so.''
</P>
<P>
   Muresianu, a Harvard PhD who once worked as an assistant
professor of history at Knox College in Galesburg, Ill., was
putting up big numbers in relative obscurity before he took over
Fidelity Fifty. He had managed Fidelity's utility fund for five
years before moving to take over Fidelity American Trust Portfolio,
an offshore stock fund that earned 85.4 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   That portfolio jammed 42.6 percent of assets into its 10 biggest
holdings as of Jan. 1, according to Fidelity reports. At the very
top: Amazon.com Inc. and America Online Inc., each accounting for
9.1 percent of the portfolio, followed by Yahoo Inc, which amounted
to 6.3 percent of assets.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same kind of strategy manager Neal Miller is likely
following at his New Millenium fund, though not with as much
concentration.
</P>
<P>
   The fund counted CMGI Inc., the Internet investing firm based in
Andover, Yahoo and retailer Best Buy Co. Inc. as its three largest
positions at the end of last year. Technology investments accounted
for 40 percent of assets at the end of January.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Fifty, New Millenium owned 249 stocks in its year-end
portfolio. The roster was dominated by smaller and medium-sized
stocks, but also included giants like Intel Corp. and Microsoft
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Muresianu and Miller are hardly the only Internet investors at
Fidelity, one of the largest institutional investors when it comes
to Web stocks. Fidelity was the top institutional owner of variety
of Net stocks including America Online, At Home Corp., E(star)Trade
Group Inc., CMGI and Lycos Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But they are by far the most aggressive of Fidelity's Internet
buyers. That raises lots of serious questions, like how they will
get out of many of their big Internet positions when the bubble
bursts and what they will do next.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, for now. This has been a spectacular time to relish
the freedom of the old fund cowboys, with a minimum of questions
asked about style and diversification.
</P>
<P>
   Surely customers have noticed. New Millenium, which manages $2.1
billion, has been closed to most new investors. But the much
smaller Fifty counted $411.8 million in assets under management by
the close of business Wednesday, more than double its $178.9
million at the end of last year and much more than even the $239
million of a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   It probably makes sense that most mutual funds are held to some
kind of style discipline month after month. But it would be nice to
keep a few of the cowboys around.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
