<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD REASONS FOR INTERVENTION IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Long caravans of tired, terrified, desperate Kosovars fleeing
the savage onslaughts of Serbian soldiers and police provide
heart-wrenching testimony of a human catastrophe of enormous
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   It is evident that the Serbs are executing a genocidal plan in
Kosovo reminiscent of the Khmer Rouge infamy in Cambodia. Still,
there are those who question the need for and the humanitarian
motivation of the U.S.-led North Atlantic Treaty Organization
airstrikes against the rampaging Serbian military machine.
</P>
<P>
   They pose the rhetorical question: Why Kosovo and not a number
of other places in the world where people are being slaughtered,
cast out of their homes and sent on the refugee roads?
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't we intervene in Rwanda? Far more people were killed
there. Why not Sierra Leone, Congo, Uganda? Why not Sri Lanka or
even Afghanistan?
</P>
<P>
   The question is disingenuous because for the most part those who
are asking it are doing so for partisan political purposes, and
they know the answer.
</P>
<P>
   They know that the United States does not possess the capability
to intervene everywhere on the globe where atrocities are being
committed. Perhaps they are suggesting that if we can't do it
everywhere, we shouldn't do it anywhere unless there is a direct,
indisputable threat to our national interests.
</P>
<P>
   Another inference that can be drawn from the rhetorical question
is that this country has no well-defined criteria for selecting
places to intervene. That's just not true. Perhaps those criteria
have not been spelled out in two-syllable words for the slow. But
two of them are readily discernible.
</P>
<P>
   The first appears to be that the United States now chooses only
to insert itself militarily into situations where it can use its
technological superiority to good effect.
</P>
<P>
   Second, this country tries to avoid unilateral interventions,
choosing instead to act wherever possible with other nations
seeking the same humanitarian and geopolitical objectives.
</P>
<P>
   The debacle in Somalia taught us a bitter lesson about the
perils of good-intentioned introduction of American ground forces
into politically chaotic morasses with indiscernible battle lines.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the triumphant Desert Storm campaign underscored
the importance of acting in concert with others to stop aggression.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. military intervention in any of the current conflicts in
Africa would risk a repetition of the Somalia nightmare. Air power
would be virtually useless there, and U.S. ground troops in some
instances would be viewed as neo-colonialist intruders.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerian troops, for example, who have been sent into Sierra
Leone to try to restore peace have been subjected to the same kind
of horrors that have been visited upon unarmed civilians by the
rebel forces. Many have been killed or mutilated, and they want
out.
</P>
<P>
   It is an example of a situation where America's edge in
high-tech weaponry would not enable it to prevail without the use
of ground forces and taking substantial numbers of casualties. And
it is doubtful that the American public would be willing to pay
that price.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia, however, is a different story. Granted, the Serbs
have formidable military forces. But those forces are vulnerable to
air and sea power. The conventional wisdom that bombing alone will
not force a regime like that of Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic to capitulate may be anachronistic.
</P>
<P>
   Our weaponry today is much more precise and effective than it
was during the Vietnam War. A sustained effort could yield the
desired results, if the isolationists who are asking the rhetorical
questions don't weaken the nation's will to persevere.
</P>
<P>
   However, if ground forces ultimately must be used to halt the
carnage, at least the United States will not be going it alone.
</P>
<P>
   The case for staying the course in the Kosovo conflict is
overwhelming. There is a growing human tragedy there. If unchecked,
the aggression could threaten European security and stability.
Besides that, it is a place suited to the kind of warfare that we
and our NATO allies wage best.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can e-mail him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or call him at (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
