<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUG FOUNDATION LEAK WITH HYDRAULIC CEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I get a few water leaks in my poured concrete foundation
where the form bolts were installed. They are not big leaks, but
are a nuisance. How can I plug them?
</P>
<P>
   S.J., Andover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Here is one place that a plug of hydraulic cement should work
on the inside. Chip out a hole at the location of the bolt (it is
really a wire and not very thick). Make the hole wider at its deep
end, forming a reverse cone. Fill it with hydraulic cement, which
expands as it sets to fit tightly in the hole. The cone shape will
hold the cement in place, and if any water tries to come through,
it will make the plug even tighter. If the form wire is showing in
the hole, cut it off as close to the bottom of the hole as
possible. Left in place, such a wire could act as a duct for more
water to come in. If the wire is copper, it will corrode the
concrete, making it prone to leaks. That's another reason to cut it
off.
</P>
<P>
   If this does not work, do the same thing on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I removed the vinyl paper from a wall made of some kind of
pressed board. Can I wash it to get all the paste off before I
paint the wall? There is also some mildew on the wall. How can I
remove that?
</P>
<P>
   TRUDY GATELY, Wrentham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. That pressed board could be a hardboard, which can be washed
with water, especially if it is tempered. But whatever it is, it
can be washed. Even plasterboard can be washed with water; you have
to anyway to get off the glue. To remove the mildew (technically,
it's mold), make a mix of 1 part bleach and 3 parts water and just
paint it on. If it is mold, it will disappear. If it does not
disappear, it is dirt, which can be painted over. Be sure to rinse
off the bleach solution; it is incompatible with paint.
</P>
<P>
   If you find the water is softening the pressed board or ruining
the paper of any plasterboard, stop. Let it dry and sand the wall
with fine sandpaper to try to remove the rest of the glue or at
least smooth it out; latex paint should cover the glue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 14-year-old house has Texture 1-11 on the outside walls.
It is in good shape and not delaminating, but I don't like it, and
I don't like aluminum or vinyl, either. Can I install shingles over
it?
</P>
<P>
   TIM WILLIAMS, Thornton, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. You certainly can, but there are a couple of things to be
alert to. T 1-11 was probably used as sheathing and siding, which
means there is ony one layer of wood on the wall. So far so good.
In some construction, window frames are set directly on the
sheathing, and are sticking out 3/4 inch from the sheathing. If
that is so, you can shingle right over the sheathing, and the
shingles will butt up nicely against the frame, more correctly
called casing.
</P>
<P>
   In other construction, if vinyl-clad windows were used, the
vinyl nailing flange of the window was nailed directly to the studs
surrounding the rough opening of each window. Then the T 1-11 was
nailed to the studs, covering the nailing flange. In this case,
too, you can shingle right over the sheathing, butting them up
closely to the vinyl casing of the windows.
</P>
<P>
   There's one other possibility. Sometimes the windows, if they
have wood casings, are installed first, against the rough opening,
then the sheathing butts up against the casing, making the casing
flush with the T 1-11. It's not a good construction technique, but
you can handle it in one of two ways. To bring the casing out from
the sheathing, nail a new set of casing onto the old. That will
also allow the shingles to butt against the casing, which they must
do. If you don't do this, the shingles will end in midair _ not a
good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Apply Tyvek or other house wrap-type covering on the sheathing
before shingling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I own a wood ladder that I have to keep outdoors. Can I put
linseed oil on it to keep it in good shape?
</P>
<P>
   DAN DANIELS, West Roxbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes, but it would be better if you stored the ladder away
from the weather. Could you put a tarp over it? Even that would
keep it dry. The oil is a good idea because a ladder should never
be painted. Paint, while protecting the ladder, will hide any
defects or damage that might show up. Use boiled linseed oil;
slather it liberally on all surfaces, wait 15 minutes, then wipe it
all off with a dry cloth. If you don't, it will stay sticky
forever. Dispose of oily cloths carefully by burning them. Do not
store them or wash them; there is too much of a hazard of
spontaneous combustion.
</P>
<P>
   And while we're at it, the handyman had a lucky accident years
ago with his wood ladder, which he left outdoors, untreated. One
spring day, he got the ladder out, set it properly against the
wall, and stepped on the first rung. Twang! The rung broke off at
both ends. The drop was only 8 or 10 inches, but it was enough to
make the handyman cut that ladder up for firewood right on the
spot. As he was cutting, the handyman could only think, what if it
had been the top rung?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
