<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2539 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-VUKOVAR-2NDTAK     04-01 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-VUKOVAR-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 VUKOVAR, Croatia: for leadership.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He said, too, that the Croatian government has found it
politically impossible to devote much money to rebuilding the
damaged houses of Serbs. Nearly all of that money, indeed much of
the reconstruction in Vukovar, has benefited Croats, not Serbs. The
European Union and individual European nations have tried to alter
that formula and, in return, are accused by Croatian leaders of
being pro-Serb.
</P>
<P>
   Despite considerable investment by the Croatian government,
Vukovar and its surrounding villages have not become especially
attractive to Croats. Of the 80,000 who fled the area, Western
diplomats estimate, only about 15,000 or so have returned. Those
who do return are mostly older people without children.
</P>
<P>
   Stana Dakonca, 30, a married physical therapist with two young
children, is an exception. A Croat, she came back to Vukovar last
year after nearly seven years of living as a refugee in a hotel on
the Adriatic. She returned, she said, because the government
promised her and her husband jobs and promised to help rebuild her
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel betrayed after coming back to this place,'' Mrs.
Dakonca said. ``The state promised many things. But I cannot find a
job. My husband works for an electrical company that has not paid
his salary for six months. The state said it would help with fixing
the house, but it hasn't given us any money yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As for reintegrating with her Serbian neighbors, Mrs. Dakonca
called that a dream of the West. ``Croats and Serbs have virtually
no contact, as far as I can see,'' she said. ``We avoid each other,
especially now that NATO is attacking Serbia. No normal life will
ever return here, never.''
</P>
<P>
   Monitoring officials and representatives of the European
countries that are spending millions to rebuild Vukovar say such
pessimism will fade if the economy improves before all the Serbs
move out.
</P>
<P>
   But, ominously, these officials are much more pessimistic about
post-war prospects for a multiethnic future in Kosovo, where ethnic
Albanians outnumbered Serbs nine-to-one before the exodus of
refugees began last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a mixed society before the war and that is not the
case in Kosovo,'' Ratsiborinsky said. ``Serbs will not be able to
stay in Kosovo after the war. It will be much worse than here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
