<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; tad-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPOT-BJT02-COX     04-01 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, April 2, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA, KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ Developments in the NATO strikes
against Yugoslavia. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON _ NORFOLK, Va. _ President Clinton speaks to
members of this community, which is heavily dependent on the
military. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CNN _ ATLANTA _ Behind the scenes at CNN for coverage of
Kosovo. We concentrate on the International Desk, sort of the air
traffic controllers of CNN coverage, a multi-national,
multi-lingual bunch who work in the trenches. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   VIDALIA-ILLEGALWORKERS _ The spring harvest of south Georgia's
famed sweet Vidalia onions -- scheduled to begin in about two weeks
-- may dodge the bitter conflicts that erupted in the fields last
year when government agents swooped down to round up workers they
suspected of being illegal aliens. Hundreds, perhaps thousands, of
workers fled and part of the $90 million crop died in the dirt.
Now, growers are taking steps to hire only legal workers this year,
experts say. (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   GALOTTO-RECORD _ Tonight's giant jackpot, the largest ever in
Georgia, will join the growing trove of state lottery lore. Among
the fascinating tales: the woman who sent a copy of her winning
ticket to her ex-hubby; the man who waited six months to collect
because he had spent his money too quickly the first time he won;
the woman who won $8.5 million, but still bought her wardrobe at
Dollar General because ``I just don't see spending any more money
than you have to''; and the worst odds in the history of the Big
Game _ tonight's. (Steiden, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS CoxNet layouts are for sale over
the web, through the New York Times News Service's PageExpress
service, at www.nytsyn/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   If a budget line or story is marked with photos or graphics,
those are available from the New York Times News Service at
212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO REACH US
</P>
<P>
   Questions should be directed to CoxNet, the Cox News Service, in
Atlanta at 404-526-5456. We are staffed 8 a.m. to 10 p.m.
Monday-Friday, and 1-10 p.m. on weekends and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The news manager is Paul Foutch, 404-526-5429,
pfoutch(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The day news editor is Tom Oder, 404-526-5887,
toder(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The night news editor is Todd C. Duncan, 404-582-7282,
tduncan(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338, artd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
