<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TOWNERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OUT-OF-TOWNERS' SHOULD HAVE STAYED HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time Steve Martin and Goldie Hawn teamed up it was for
the smart, genuinely witty and highly original 1992 screwball
comedy, ``Housesitter.'' Unfortunately, despite mostly positive
reviews, the film was a legendary flop at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   So this time, thinking they've learned from their mistake of
overestimating the moviegoing public, they've given us a farce
that's the polar opposite of that first outing. This follow-up
teaming is broad, crass and so colossally stupid it's often
numbing.
</P>
<P>
   It's a remake of the 1970 Neil Simon comedy-of-frustration,
``The Out-of-Towners,'' in which Jack Lemmon and Sandy Dennis play
a stubborn Midwestern businessman and his whining wife who are
brought to their knees by a malevolent New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the couple are a recently fired ad man (Martin) and his
dense wife (Hawn) who leave Ohio for a job interview in the Big
Apple and are at war less with the city (it's no longer hip to hate
New York, Martin's character says early on) than with themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Still, everything goes wrong. The New York airport is fogged in,
their bags are lost when they arrive in Boston, they miss the train
to New York, the only rental car they can find is cranky, and the
wife gives the husband the wrong directions.
</P>
<P>
   Wait a minute. Haven't we already seen this Martin movie before?
</P>
<P>
   Sort of. But ``Trains, Planes and Automobiles'' _ as well as the
original ``Out-of-Towners'' _ were comedies of frustration that
worked because the characters were arrogant and it was fun to see
them terrorized by the malfunctions of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   This pair are nice folks, desperate for a job. What fun is it to
see them chased by a mastiff, abused by a hotel manager (John
Cleese), mugged and kidnapped by various stick-up men, and brought
to the edge of prostitution to get some food and a shower? It's not
funny, it's painful.
</P>
<P>
   The original was certainly no masterpiece, but it at least had a
clever Simon script and humor grounded in New York realities. This
un-Simonized remake is so clumsy, slapstick-laden and agonizingly
witless it plays like fingernails on a blackboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Out-of-Towners. Directed by Sam Weisman. Screenplay by Marc
Lawrence, based on a screenplay by Neil Simon. Cast: Steve Martin,
Goldie Hawn, John Cleese. Paramount. 91 minutes. Rated PG-13 for
sex jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1413EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2576 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-WALK-MOON-SPI &LR;      04-01 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WALK-MOON-SPI </SLUG>
  
 `WALK ON THE MOON' RECALLS '60s WITH SENSITIVITY  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The thing that makes first-time director Tony Goldwyn's ``A Walk
On the Moon'' unique is that it's the first high-profile movie in
ages that dares to view the great consciousness revolution of the
'60s in a somewhat positive light.
</P>
<P>
   It's far from totally successful, and it fails in its effort to
be an absorbing family-relationship drama. Its characters never
seem interesting enough to warrant too much investment of sympathy,
and the script moves relentlessly toward a highly contrived ending.
</P>
<P>
   But it's well-acted by its three stars, and its whole '60s
subtext is believable and seductive. By not trying too hard (and by
using '60s music that hasn't been overexposed to death in the
movies of later decades), it skillfully catches the mood and feel
of the Woodstock Summer of '69.
</P>
<P>
   It's about a lower-middle class New York Jewish family summering
at a tacky Catskills resort: Pearl (Diane Lane), the mid-thirtyish
mother and housewife; Marty (Liev Schreiber), her uncommunicative
TV repairman husband; and Alison (Anna Paquin), their 14-year-old
daughter, on the verge of rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the movie, the '60s hits each of them hard.
Pearl, who more or less missed her adolescence, falls for a
handsome hippie (Viggo Mortensen); Marty feels unfulfilled by his
life and betrayed by his wife; and Alison wants to go to the big
Woodstock Music and Arts Fair just up the highway.
</P>
<P>
   But the film is not really about the destruction of this family
unit so much as it's about how the '60s aura of unlimited
possibility _ as represented by both Woodstock and the titular Moon
landing _ allows these characters to re-examine their lives and
relationships, abandon the false assumptions of the '50s, and start
over.
</P>
<P>
   The (partially autobiographical) script by Pamala Gray is quite
good at chronicling the internal stresses on the family unit _
Pearl's sense of having missed her girlhood because of a teenage
pregnancy, Marty's agony at having missed out on a career as a
scientist, and Alison's resentment of her mother's belated sexual
awakening.
</P>
<P>
   The script is also good at dramatizing how these stresses
explode in the summer of Woodstock, and at suggesting how each of
these characters might come out of the experience a better person.
But the script has its share of false beats, its dramatic arc
depends on one gigantic coincidence, and its tag-on-happy ending
seems glaringly dishonest.
</P>
<P>
   The film also has it's share of false and annoying supporting
performances, especially Mortensen's one-note hippie lover, who
seems to have stepped out of a bad romance novel; and Tovah
Feldshuh's busy-body mother-in-law, who rides the script's least
engaging subplot and would have served the movie better on the
cutting-room floor.
</P>
<P>
   But the three lead performances are quite solid. Lane proves
once again that she may be the best of Hollywood's thirtysomething
actresses; Schreiber makes his character's pain and bitterness so
palpable that it's often painful to watch; and Oscar-winner Paquin
(``The Piano'') personifies the agony and ecstasy of adolescence.
</P>
<P>
   And though its third act is weak and unconvincing, ``A Walk On
the Moon'' also manages, in its sum total, to make a very
persuasive case that no one really ``missed'' the '60s, that
everybody who lived through that revolutionary era incorporated
something of its sensibility into their lives, even if they never
realized it.
</P>
<P>
   A Walk On the Moon. Directed by Tony Goldwyn. Produced by Tony
Goldwyn, Dustin Hoffman and Murray Schisgal. Written by Pamela
Gray. Cast: Diane Lane, Viggo Mortensen, Liev Schreiber, Anna
Paquin. Miramax. 107 minutes. Rated R for sexual situations.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
