<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BWITCHED-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL POWER: IRISH BAND WORKS MAGIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   tell. But America _ particularly, young America _ may be about
to fall under the spell of BWitched.
</P>
<P>
   In England, the winsome group's first four singles all debuted
at No. 1 on the national charts _ something no other group, not
even the Spice Girls, for heaven's sake, accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   Stateside, things seem to be moving along with promising speed.
The foursome's first offering, ``C'est La Vie,'' is breezing up the
top 20. A giddy, twerpy mix of female harmonies and cheerfully
mind-numbing hooks, the song drills its way into your brain like a
shouted nursery rhyme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think pop is coming back in America,'' says Sinead
O'Carroll. At 20, the blonde is the oldest member of the all-female
BWitched, which opens for 98 Degrees on Monday night at the
Celebrity Theatre. ``I think we're part of that generation. It's
like they like our music, they like the way we dress. We give a
very positive and happy feel to our music.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dublin group's gimmick, if you could call it that, is its
sheer Irishness. The songs on the group's self-titled debut are as
fizzy as a fresh can of Sprite, but they are spiced with definite
Celtic touches. The ballad ``To You I Belong'' _ written for the
girls' mums _ gains emotional heft with the help of a lonely tin
whistle and some evocative fiddle work.
</P>
<P>
   ``You basically have to do something to have your difference,''
O'Carroll says, dashing between appointments in Los Angeles.
``That's why the Irish influence was something we could do. We do
have our own sound. When people asked who influenced our sound,
it's really no one, because we try not to sound like anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, O'Carroll, Lindsay Armaou and twins Edele and Keavy
Lynch don't really sound like other pop acts _ not even Scary,
Baby, Sporty and Posh, to whom they're constantly linked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the comparison we always get,'' O'Carroll says in her
chipper brogue. ``We don't mind at all. They've been so successful
and they've done so well. We kind of mirror that because of the
success we've had in England. But once people see us and hear us,
they know we're completely different.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, they're definitely younger, both in terms of age
and lyrical content. These girls impatiently wait by the mailbox
for the mailman and breathlessly coo about riding a roller coaster
of love. The Backstreet Boys sound like a streetwise Snoop Dogg by
comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of Irish hip-hop pop,'' O'Carroll cheerfully says _
actually, she says everything cheerfully. ``It's a bit of
everything. That's why we wanted to write it all ourselves. The
music that we like is happy. It makes you want to get up and have a
dance, to be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the group seems on the verge of cracking it so big
in America while other British Isles phenoms such as Boyzone, Peter
Andre and Louise have failed to click is something that keeps
O'Carroll and her bandmates wide-eyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being big in America is something we never really thought
about,'' she insists. ``It was one of those things that just
happened. The record company reps saw us and liked us. And they
(begin ital) really (end ital) liked us. We just took it from
there. We're blown away by the fact that we're coming to America as
quick as we have. It's fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Equally fantastic, at least to American ears, is the charming
lilt of a young Irish brogue. Maureen O'Hara in her prime couldn't
have sounded any sweeter than O'Carroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so funny,'' she says, giggling. ``Here, they tend to
really like our accents. But the English people find our voices
really boring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, in LA, everyone is like, `Oh my gosh, you're really like
pale-skinned,'' she continues, doing a not-bad approximation of an
American accent. ``Everyone in LA is so leathery, so I think it's
nice for them to see us.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, c'est la vie. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
