<HEADER>
A2618 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-98DEGREES-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      04-01 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-98DEGREES-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HEAT OF THE MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - One thing about the current crop of boy bands. They
don't want to be known as boy bands.
</P>
<P>
   Take Nick Lachey, one-fourth of the platinum-selling 98 Degrees.
So what if the group consists of a gang of photogenic young guys?
Who cares if the band's official Web site includes such newsy
tidbits as astrological signs (Nick's a Scorpio) and favorite
drinks (he's a Yoo-Hoo man _ yeah, sure). This is a real band, darn
it!
</P>
<P>
   ``There's some negative stereotypes with that term,'' Lachey
says, carefully avoiding the dreaded BB phrase. ``We don't feel
that any of those apply to this group. Once people actually hear
our music, they walk away knowing we're talented.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, sure, there's no denying that. In fact, as far as these
things go, 98 Degrees is on pretty solid ground. The group sounds
more like a secular,hairy-chested variation of Take 6 than a
fifth-generation New Kids. That's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   The harmonies of Justin Jeffre, Jeff Timmons, Drew Lachey and
his big bro' Nick are pretty snazzy. And the group's best songs,
such as ``True to Your Heart,'' a thumping retro jam featured on
the ``Mulan'' soundtrack, are hard to resist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the image of the group, the age of the group, our
look, that causes people to sometimes put us in with other
groups,'' Lachey says, minutes after finishing an autograph session
for 1,200 fans in Winnipeg, Canada. ``We see ourselves as a pop
band.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio group was formed a few years back by Timmons (fave
colors are orange and blue) and Nick. The foursome did the
talent-show circuit before getting backstage at a Boyz II Men
concert, where they caught the attention of Montell Jordan's
manager. He signed them to a deal and hooked them up with Motown.
Two albums later, the group doesn't seem to have peaked.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, ``98 Degrees and Rising,'' the band's second disc,
recently passed a million copies in sales. The group is headlining
on its first genuine concert tour, unless one counts a
play-the-malls-to-backing-tracks thing it did last year.
</P>
<P>
   That mall tour seems like one of those marketing decisions that
is a little hard to fathom. Heavy exposure in teen-dream mags and
on the Disney Channel seems to nail the lid on the ``Tiger Beat''
coffin, something Nick and the guys don't exactly seem comfortable
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We control our marketing to a certain degree,'' Nick says,
choosing his words carefully. ``The record label really has the
responsibility. They kind of fit us where they can. . . . In that
respect, they make a lot of decisions we necessarily wouldn't agree
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of wind up in a lot of teen magazines with those
quote-unquote boy bands. That's kind of an inevitable thing. Our
music will set us apart from that whole movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, they do follow the classic teen-idol rules. There are the
autograph sessions. The group's opening act in Phoenix is BWitched,
Ireland's bubbly bubblegum import. And Lachey is as polite as can
be, even doling out nice-but-evasive sound bites _ ``It's like
having (three) brothers'' is how he describes his bandmates.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the short life span of being a teen idol is simply
something he doesn't want to dwell on. The group recently got to
perform as part of MTV's spring break programming and earned a
positive response from the cool college crowd. Maybe there is life
after high school for these guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all college-age girls, and they were really
enthusiastic about the group,'' he says. ``That's what we want _ to
get women and even men in their 30s, 40s and maybe even 50s
listening to us. To make good music and to appeal to a variety of
people _ that's the goal.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
