<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KING-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIZEN KING _ OR COURT JESTER? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Milwaukee group Citizen King is big on the radio
right now with ``Better Days (And the Bottom Drops Out),'' a clever
blend of melodic rock, hip-hop and some alt-flavored sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Sims, who handles bass and vocals for the five-member band,
says the song has a deep meaning beneath the summery chorus.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen when things are bad and we had to get over it,''
says Sims, sounding a bit groggy in his Portland, Ore., hotel room.
``We've had to pay our dues and stuff. You know that line in the
song, `My toes are busted?' Kristian Riley, our guitar player, got
a couple of his toes chopped off by a lawn mower. He's got a couple
of fakeys now.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, other than ripping Riley's shoes off during a concert
performance, it's going to be hard to prove the toe story. It's
that way with a lot of what Sims says. He's in a vaguely silly mood
today, three weeks to the day after the release of the band's
major-label debut, ``Mobile Estates. ''
</P>
<P>
   ``The first night of the tour was in Milwaukee,'' he recounts.
``It was awesome. People threw all kinds of stuff onstage. They
were getting rowdy, flicking their lighters. Girls threw panties up
onstage. Well, not really.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a positive buzz around the band. Early word on the
Beck-style disc was ecstatic. Part of that is due to co-producer
Eric Valentine, best-known for his work with such radio-friendly
types as Third Eye Blind and Smash Mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of producers we wanted to work with,'' Tims
says. ``We threw a bunch of names in a hat, and Eric's was the one
that came out. He does have a Midas touch, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Formed in 1993, the group now is finally tasting national
success with its first cross-country tour and a deal with Warner
Bros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there's way more champagne than we know what to do
with,'' Tims says. ``And there's always circus peanuts at our
shows. We put that in our rider (contract). A steady supply of
circus peanuts, socks, Raisin Bran, Skittles, a couple of pornos
and Miller brew.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course it would be Miller _ that's what made Milwaukee
famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all that people know about Milwaukee,'' Tims muses.
``Beer. And `Laverne &AMP; Shirley.' There's also a clown museum, so
it's kind of known for its unicycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's tack wrestling. People get into the ring, except
the mat is covered with tacks. Tack wrestling is a big deal in
Milwaukee.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Citizen King. Hometown girls love them so much they throw
their panties at them.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not really. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
