<HEADER>
A2623 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRUNCH-FOOD-AZR &LR;      04-01 2450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRUNCH-FOOD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GLORIFIED BREAKFAST' IS ALWAYS A HIT  
 (ADV: RECIPES AT END, WITH BRUNCHSIDE-FOOD)  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Brunch is not just easy. Brunch is fun, relaxing
(begin ital) and (end ital) easy. The secret to brunch is that
breakfast is the favorite meal of so many people. Brunch has no set
definition, but it's basically glorified breakfast, served sometime
before dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Hosting a brunch is much less intimidating than hosting a dinner
party. For one thing, some elements are standard. Coffee. You can
make coffee. Champagne is always appropriate, if you want to go the
alcohol route, and it's super simple to combine a little champagne
and OJ for mimosas.
</P>
<P>
   The options are numerous and attractive. You don't have to make
a big ``main dish.'' Think eggs and baked goods, sweet as well as
savory. Build a menu around a couple of items that you want to
prepare, and then plan to fill in with the rest from a bakery or
delicatessen.
</P>
<P>
   For example, you might want to make the Dutch Baby recipe, an
eggy soufflelike oven pancake. You mix up the batter, pour it in a
heated pan and it puffs up high in the hot oven. Sprinkle on
powdered sugar just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   You could serve crispy thick-slice bacon, cold poached fish,
grilled skewered shrimp, maybe? Or keep it vegetarian.
</P>
<P>
   Add steamed vegetables, maybe something seasonal, such as
Lemon-Glazed Asparagus. For dessert, purchase a fruit tart,
assemble strawberry shortcake or bake our rich and delicious
Raspberry Cream Cheese Coffeecake.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit can serve multiple purposes for brunch. It can be a salad;
a dessert; a sauce; a filling for crepes; a topping or crown for
cheesecake, waffles or the Dutch Baby. Plan on fruit in some form,
even if it's a centerpiece. You can even do that
sour-cream-and-brown sugar thing with strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   Or, make Lora Brody's White Wine Sangria: 3 cups sliced fresh
peaches, apricots, nectarines or sweet plums in a tall pitcher with
4 cups Riesling or other semisweet white wine and a half-cup of
brandy. Serve cold; spoon some fruit in the glass before you pour
in sangria.
</P>
<P>
   Several of our recipes would be appropriate for an Easter
brunch. You can glaze a ham with the Pepper Jelly, which you can
make either sweet or hot. Or melt the jelly to glaze a leg of lamb.
Serve a little Pepper Jelly with the lamb, too, instead of the
expected mint.
</P>
<P>
   The Cheese Blintzes recipe is not too sweet, with a wonderful
light filling of farmers cheese, topped with sour cream, berries
and lemon zest. Crepes are easy to make after a little bit of
practice, and they can be made and refrigerated ahead. Or freeze
some _ they're as handy as omelets for using up whatever bits of
filling you have on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Brunch Enchiladas are a little heartier and a good way to make
use of any leftover ham, turkey or chicken. Like many brunch
casseroles, you can make this one the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Brunches are easiest to serve buffet style. Set up coffee,
juices, other drinks and desserts in an area away from the buffet
table. Buffet service starts with plates, then cold dishes, hot
dishes and ends with carved meats.
</P>
<P>
   Like fruit, flowers are another must. What grows in your yard in
abundance?
</P>
<P>
   One more thing: When you invite people to brunch, you might want
to specify when it ends as well as when it begins. Champagne in the
middle of the day makes some people want to nap. Do you want them
sleeping away the afternoon on your sofa? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lemon-Glazed Asparagus &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``The World of Jewish Entertaining,'' by Gil Marks)
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 pounds asparagus
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon grated fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cook the asparagus in boiling salted water until tender-crisp,
about 5 minutes. Do not overcook. Drain and pat dry.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the broth, lemon juice, zest, ginger and pepper in a
small saucepan. Bring to a boil and cook until mixture reduces to
about 3 tablespoons. Strain. Brush over the asparagus. Serve warm
or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. Approximate values per serving: 23 calories,
.3 g fat, 0 cholesterol, 4 g carbohydrates, 1.6 g fiber, 2 g
protein, 99 mg sodium, 10 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dutch Baby &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``The Best of Waffles &AMP; Pancakes,'' by Jane Stacey)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter
</P>
<P>
   1 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Confectioners' sugar, for dusting
</P>
<P>
   Sliced fresh nectarines and blackberries, for topping
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 375 degrees. Put the butter in a 9-inch pie
pan and place it in the oven to melt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a large bowl, combine the flour, granulated sugar,
milk, eggs and salt. Using an electric mixer set at medium-high,
beat the mixture for 1 1/2 to 2 minutes, or until smooth. Remove
the pan from the oven and carefully swirl to evenly coat the bottom
with the butter. Pour the batter into the pan and bake for about 30
minutes, or until the edges have risen and are crisp and golden
brown and the center is set but still soft.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the pan from the oven and dust with confectioners' sugar.
Cut the pancake into wedges, top with nectarines and blackberries,
and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 to 8 servings. Approximate values per serving: 131
calories, 5 g fat, 62 mg cholesterol, 18 g carbohydrates, 0 fiber,
5 g protein, 130 mg sodium, 31 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Basic Crepes &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``The Best of Waffles &AMP; Pancakes,'' by Jane Stacey)
</P>
<P>
   cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   In a food processor fitted with the metal blade, combine all of
the ingredients and process for 10 to 15 seconds, or until smooth.
Scrape the sides of the bowl and process for 5 to 10 seconds more.
Transfer the batter to a medium-size bowl, cover with plastic wrap,
and chill for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a 6-inch crepe pan or small skillet over medium-high heat
until hot, or until a few drops of water sizzle on the surface.
Lightly grease the pan. Pour about 3 tablespoons batter into the
pan, tilting to coat the bottom evenly. Cook for about 1 minute, or
until the edges look lacy and begin to pull away from the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Before turning the crepe, lift the edges to check that the
underside is lightly browned. Turn the crepe and cook for 15 to 30
seconds, or until the underside is lightly browned. Transfer the
crepe to a sheet of waxed paper. Repeat with the remaining batter,
greasing the pan as necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Crepes can be made ahead. Stack completely cooled crepes,
wrap with foil, and refrigerate up to 5 days or freeze up to 2
months. Thaw at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 14 servings. Approximate values per serving: 68 calories,
3 g fat, 45 mg cholesterol, 8 g carbohydrates, 0 fiber, 3 g
protein, 111 mg sodium, 41 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Cheese Blintzes &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``The Best of Waffles &AMP; Pancakes,'' by Jane Stacey)
</P>
<P>
   1 recipe for Basic Crepes (see above)
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   Fresh berries, sour cream and lemon zest, for topping
</P>
<P>
   Cheese filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds farmers cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon pure vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Prepare crepes according to recipe. Set aside. Preheat the oven
to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the cheese filling: In a large bowl, combine all of the
filling ingredients (cheese, eggs, sugar, lemon zest, vanilla,
cinnamon), stirring until smooth and well-blended.
</P>
<P>
   Place 1 crepe on a work surface. Spoon 3 tablespoons of the
filling down the center. Fold the long edges of the crepe over the
filling. Turn the crepe seam side down and tuck under the shorter
open ends. Repeat filling and folding the remaining crepes.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet over medium heat, melt 2 tablespoons butter.
Cook the blintzes in batches, seam side down, for about 2 minutes,
or until the undersides are lightly browned. Transfer the blintzes
to a baking sheet and keep warm in the oven. Repeat cooking the
remaining blintzes, adding more butter as needed.
</P>
<P>
   When all the blintzes are cooked, transfer them to warmed
serving plates and top each serving with berries, sour cream and
lemon zest.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 14 servings. Approximate values per serving (not counting
toppings): 275 calories, 19 g fat, 119 mg cholesterol, 9 g
carbohydrates, 0 fiber, 19 g protein, 531 mg sodium, 60 percent
calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Raspberry Cream Cheese Coffeecake &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``Rise &AMP; Dine,'' by Marcy Claman)
</P>
<P>
   Coffeecake:
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cream cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup raspberry jam
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced almonds
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. In a large bowl, combine flour and
sugar; cut in the butter using a pastry blender until mixture
resembles coarse crumbs. Reserve 1 cup of crumbs for topping.
</P>
<P>
   To remaining crumb mixture, add baking powder, baking soda,
salt, sour cream, egg and almond extract. Blend well. Spread batter
over bottom and 2 inches up sides of a greased and floured 9-inch
springform pan. Batter should be \-inch thick on sides.
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine cream cheese, sugar and egg and blend
well. Pour over batter in pan. Spoon jam evenly over the cheese
filling. In a small bowl, combine 1 cup of reserved crumbs and
almonds and sprinkle over top.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 55 to 60 minutes or until cream cheese is set and crust
is a deep golden brown. Cool 15 minutes, remove sides and cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Best served at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings. Approximate values per serving: 574 calories,
30 g fat, 122 mg cholesterol, 69 g carbohydrates, 0.6 g fiber, 9 g
protein, 448 mg sodium, 47 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Vermont Cheddar Pie &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From `Rise &AMP; Dine'' by Marcy Claman) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups diced parboiled potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onions
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt-free lemon-herb seasoning
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chopped steamed spinach
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup crumbled feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly grated Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 cup grated white Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup low-fat milk
</P>
<P>
   Parsley flakes
</P>
<P>
   Paprika
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease a glass pie plate. Combine
potatoes and 1/4 cup onions, and press into pie plate as a crust.
Sprinkle with seasoning and garlic powder. Carefully put a layer of
spinach and crumbled feta cheese into the crust, then top with
Romano, then cheddar cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Combine eggs and milk, and pour carefully over cheeses. To
garnish the pie, make a small circle of 1/4 cup onions in center of
pie, sprinkle parsley flakes in a larger circle around the onions,
and sprinkle paprika in a larger circle around parsley flake
circle. Bake for one hour.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings. Approximate values per serving: 163 calories,
11 g fat, 91 mg cholesterol, 7 g carbohydrates, 0.6 g fiber, 10 g
protein, 324 mg sodium, 58 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Brunch Enchiladas &QL; 
(From ``Rise &AMP; Dine,'' by Marcy Claman)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups fully cooked ground ham
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sliced green onions
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped green bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups shredded Cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   8 flour tortillas (7-inch diameter)
</P>
<P>
   4 beaten eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 cups light cream or milk
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon garlic powder
</P>
<P>
   Few drops hot pepper sauce (such as Tabasco)
</P>
<P>
   Avocado slices
</P>
<P>
   Fresh salsa
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream
</P>
<P>
   In a bowl, combine ground ham, onion and green pepper. Place 1/3
cup of this mixture and 3 tablespoons cheese at one end of
tortilla. Roll up. Repeat with rest. Arrange tortillas seam side
down in a greased 12- by 7 1/2 - by 2-inch oven-proof casserole.
Combine eggs, cream, flour, salt (if using), garlic powder and hot
sauce. Pour over tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   Cover and refrigerate several hours or overnight. Remove from
refrigerator three-fourths of an hour before baking. Preheat oven
to 350 degrees and bake for 45 to 60 minutes or until set. Sprinkle
with remaining cheese. Bake additional 3 minutes until cheese
melts, then let stand 10 minutes. Garnish with final three
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Tip: For a wonderful mix of textures and temperatures, serve
this entree with spicy Mexican corn muffins and chilled shrimp
gazpacho.
</P>
<P>
   Variations: Try whole-wheat flour tortillas and use fully cooked
ground turkey or chicken in place of ham. &QL; 
Makes 8 servings. Approximate values per serving without avocado,
salsa and sour cream garnish: 476 calories, 32 g fat, 187 mg
cholesterol, 25 g carbohydrates, 1.3 g fiber, 23 g protein, 900 mg
sodium, 60 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Pepper Jelly &QL; 
 &QL; 
(From ``Fannie Flagg's Original Whistle Stop Cafe Cookbook``) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 large or 4 to 6 small bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   5 to 8 hot peppers (optional) or use additional bell peppers
</P>
<P>
   6 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/3 cups vinegar (5 percent acidity)
</P>
<P>
   2 packages (3 ounces each) liquid pectin
</P>
<P>
   2 drops green or red food coloring, according to the color of
peppers used (optional)
</P>
<P>
   You will need: six half-pint jelly jars for this recipe.
Sterilize them in boiling water just before making this, or run
them through the dishwasher. They should be hot when you pour in
the jelly.
</P>
<P>
   Rinse peppers, remove seeds and ribs, and cut into chunks.
Process each type of pepper in a food processor until coarsely
ground. Do not overprocess. Measure one cup ground bell pepper and
1/3 cup ground hot pepper. If not using hot peppers, measure 1 1/3
cup bell pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the ground peppers, sugar and vinegar in a large
saucepan; bring to a boil. Boil 6 minutes, stirring frequently.
Stir in pectin; boil 3 minutes, stirring frequently. Remove from
heat; skim off foam. Add food coloring if using.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly pour hot jelly into hot sterilized jars, leaving
1/4-inch head space. Wipe jar rims clean. Cover with metal lids and
screw on bands.
</P>
<P>
   Store in refrigerator, or process in boiling water bath for five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 3 cups. Approximate values per 1 tablespoon serving: 113
calories, 0 fat, 0 cholesterol, 29 g carbohydrates, .2 mg fiber, 0
protein, 8 mg sodium, 1 percent calories from fat. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
