<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEN-ELECTED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN PARTY VICTORY SHOCKS DEMOCRATS IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ The election of Green Party candidate Audie
Bock to the California Assembly shocked the political establishment
because it showed how badly voters want change in Oakland, even at
the risk of eroding the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows that there is a strong measure of dissatisfaction
with the status quo,'' said Oakland Mayor Jerry Brown, the former
Democratic governor and now the independent leader of a new guard.
``I think it's more about people being fed up with what has been,
and they want something better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic candidate in Tuesday's run-off election, former
Oakland mayor and state assemblyman Elihu Harris, was so confident
of victory that he had hired legislative staff members. He was
being talked about as the next Assembly speaker.
</P>
<P>
   The longtime Democrat was been rebuffed by Oakland, Alameda and
Piedmont voters in one of the biggest election surprises in years.
</P>
<P>
   Bock became the liberal Green Party's first elected state
official in the nation. She is a film distributor, community
college instructor and was a translator for the renowned Japanese
film director Akira Kurosawa before his death.
</P>
<P>
   Although the race was close _ Bock won about 50 percent to 49
percent for Harris _ the victory was considerable given that the
district is 65 percent Democratic and 1.2 percent Green.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican Party Chairman John McGraw issued a statement
Wednesday saying Bock's narrow victory in a lightly attended
election ``is a frightening prospect for Democrats, considering
(Harris) had previously held this seat for 12 years and 65 percent
of the district's voters are registered Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first public statement since the election, Harris blamed
his loss on low voter turnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 20 years in politics this is the first time that I've
suffered an election loss,'' Harris said. ``But obviously, if you
accept the will of the voters when you win, you must also accept it
when you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   A confluence of events helped sink Harris, even as Democrats are
celebrating victories elsewhere in California. The most prominent
problem may have been the Jerry Brown factor _ a call for change in
Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, 51, ran Oakland during the politically and fiscally
disastrous return of the Raiders football team, and during a time
when Oakland struggled to maintain itself. While Santa Clara County
and San Francisco boomed, Oakland stayed behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a reaction to Elihu,'' said Ed Blakely, former Oakland
mayoral candidate. ``I don't think this is about Democrats in
Oakland ... I think Ms. Bock should travel lightly. From what I've
heard, she's impressive. But she still has to win over the people
of Oakland. She got her voters out; Elihu didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakland activist Ces Butner said, ``I still think there is a
public outcry for change. That's one of the reasons why Jerry did
so well back in June ... Elihu represented the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris appeared to coast through his campaign, assuming he would
win the way Democrats have won here year after year. He refused to
debate Bock.
</P>
<P>
   Bock, 53, got only 8.6 percent of the vote in the Feb. 2
primary. But that was enough to get her into the runoff race
because there was no Republican running and Harris failed to get
more than 50 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   He remained stagnant, and it was difficult to find even Harris
campaign signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to a lot of people here,'' said state Sen. Don
Perata, D-Oakland, speaking from Alameda. ``They said they never
saw him. He didn't campaign here. It's almost like he was taking it
for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Bock will replace Perata, who was elected to the Senate last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Where Harris was virtually invisible, the Bock campaign seized
on the momentum of the primary.
</P>
<P>
   After the primary, a group of 50 to 80 Bock volunteers decided
there would be low voter turnout, and that they possibly could win
by not making mistakes and capitalizing on Harris' apathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure that they (voted for Bock) to make a statement, sort
of like they did in voting for Jerry Brown,'' said Ellen Gilmore,
of Piedmont, who voted for Harris. ``I think people want to shake
things up, and I think people voted for Bock for that reason.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a traditional Democratic ploy, the state party went to
largely minority areas before the primary and distributed 3,800
chicken-dinner coupons, at $5 each, in exchange for ballot stubs.
That was enough for Harris to get 48.7 percent of the vote, but not
enough to avoid a runoff with Bock, and face heated criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``That chicken-dinner thing was a big mistake,'' said Bob Marsh,
treasurer for Bock's campaign. ``I heard about it from a lot of
voters when I was out in the neighborhoods. The Democrats did a
voter campaign (flyer) trying to put fear in African-American
voters that Harris would lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Alameda County Registrar of Voters Bradley Clark blasted the
stunt, saying ``paying a person to cast a vote reduces our
electoral system to Third World standards ... This is the closest
thing to legal vote-buying I have experienced in my 17-year career
in election administration.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hurt by the chicken fiasco because it became a symbol
of the politics of the past,'' Perata said. ``To have the
Democratic Party just sort of machine-mower voters, particularly in
East Oakland, and to bribe them with chicken, it's one of the
things I think liberals were offended by.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
