<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Canada calendar, from coast to coast
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Summer in Canada is brimming with festivals. From the Yukon to
Newfoundland, the provinces host a smorgasbord of events during the
warmer months. The following is a sampler of some of the best
known.
</P>
<P>
   THE YUKON
</P>
<P>
   www.touryukon.com
</P>
<P>
   867-667-5340
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 17-20: Yukon International Storytelling Festival,
Whitehorse. Spinners of tales from around the world swap stories at
Rotary Park. 867-633-7550.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Aug. 13-16: Discovery Days Festival, Dawson City. A
commemoration of the 1896 discovery of gold with a parade, raft and
canoe races, dances and more. 867-993-5575.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHWEST TERRITORIES
</P>
<P>
   www.nwttravel.nt.ca
</P>
<P>
   1-800-661-0788
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 18: Midnight Madness, Inuvik. The summer solstice brings
everyone outdoors to walk, talk, bicycle, dine and party under the
midnight sun. 867-777-4851.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 18: Raven Mad Daze, Yellowknife. A crazy night on the
longest day of the year, with street entertainment, kids' events
and more. 867-873-3912.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 5-11: Festival of the Midnight Sun, Yellowknife.
Everything from folk art and watercolor painting to improvisational
theater is featured. 867-920-7118.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 16-25: Great Northern Arts Festival, Inuvik. More than 60
of the greatest aboriginal and nonaboriginal artists from across
the north gather to create works of art as visitors watch.
867-777-3536.
</P>
<P>
   NUNAVUT
</P>
<P>
   www.nunatour.nt.ca
</P>
<P>
   1-800-491-7910
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 1-5: Midnight Sun Marathon, between Nanisivik and Arctic
Bay. The world's northernmost marathon attracts runners from
Canada, the United States, Europe and Australia for 10-, 32-, 42-
and 100-kilometer races. 867-436-7502.
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH COLUMBIA
</P>
<P>
   www.travel.bc.ca
</P>
<P>
   1-800-663-6000
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  April 29-May 2, Okanagan Spring Wine &AMP; Food Festival, Okanagan
Valley. Tastings, vineyard picnics, orchard tours by horse drawn
carriages and more. 250-861-6654.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  May 31-June 6: Vancouver International Children's Festival,
Vancouver. Theater, circus acts, dancing and music performances for
age 3 and up. 604-687-7697.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 24-25: Prince George Air Show. Military jets, vintage
aircraft, aerobatics and a ground display. 250-564-9820.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 24, 28, 31 and Aug. 4: Benson &AMP; Hedges Symphony of Fire.
Musical fireworks create magic over Vancouver's English Bay.
604-738-4304.
</P>
<P>
   ALBERTA
</P>
<P>
   www.travelalberta.org
</P>
<P>
   1-800-661-8888
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 9-18: Calgary Exhibition and Stampede. The highlight is a
rodeo billed as the biggest in North America. 403-261-0101.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 22-31: Edmonton Klondike Days. Gold panning, pancake
breakfasts and more celebrate Edmonton's gold-rush heritage.
403-479-3500.
</P>
<P>
   SASKATCHEWAN
</P>
<P>
   www.sasktourism.com
</P>
<P>
   1-800-667-7191
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  June 30-July 3: Frontier Days Regional Fair and Rodeo, Swift
Current. Heritage village, exhibits, rodeo and more. 306-773-2944.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  July 1-Aug. 17: Royal Canadian Mounted Police Sunset Retreat
Ceremonies, Regina. Colorful and stirring drill displays by RCMP
Training Academy cadets. 306-780-5900.
</P>
<P>
   MANITOBA
</P>
