<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-GOING04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Riding, cycling and hiking: Canadian adventures await
 &HT;    Es: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ride the ranges _ the mountain ranges, that is. The Trail Riders
of the Canadian Rockies, based in Calgary, Alberta, is a nonprofit
riding club that offers back-country experiences to a limited
number of adventurers in Banff National Park each summer. There are
nine six-day rides going out each Sunday beginning July 4, ending
with the ninth ride returning Sept. 3. Three hearty meals are
served daily in camp and on the trail, and there's a campfire
sing-along each evening. The trip also includes horse and saddle
along with tepee or tent accommodation. The cost is about $650,
including 7 percent tax, which is rebated to non-Canadian riders.
Information: 403-264-8656 or www.canuck.com/(tilde)trcr
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pedaling Canada:
</P>
<P>
   The Vermont-based VBT Bicycling Vacations offers six Canadian
tours, including a new one in Quebec City that encompasses the
countryside and an island shoreline. Lodgings are at intimate and
luxurious inns, and the tour includes 13 meals, including four
dinners. The six-day journey is $1,245 per person, which includes
bicycle rental and maintenance, support vehicle and detailed daily
route directions and maps. The seven-day Canadian Rockies tour is
$1,395, and includes six nights in mountain lodges; admission to
Banff, Yoho and Kootenay national parks; and 15 meals, including
five dinners. Other Canadian tours include Prince Edward Island,
Nova Scotia, Downeast and Across the Bay (a tour through Maine and
Nova Scotia) and Eastern Townships of New France (an adventure
through Vermont and Quebec). Information: 1-800-245-
</P>
<P>
   3868 or on the Web at vbt.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The great escape: Talk about getting away from it all:
Canadian Mountain Holidays offers heli-hiking vacations at remote
lodges accessed by helicopter in British Columbia. After arriving
at the lodge, guests are flown each day to a different alpine
region for a day of hiking. When hikers return, it's time to kick
back: hors d'oeuvres await in the living room by a crackling fire,
the bar is open, a massage therapist is available, as are a
whirlpool and sauna. Dinner, which may include salmon or lamb and
freshly baked bread, is served family-style. Three-, four- and
six-night trips are available June through early September from
four lodges: Adamant, Bobbie Burns, Bugaboo and the newly opened
Valemont. Prices start at about $828 including ground transfers
from Banff, all helicopter flights, meals, accommodations, guide
service, special equipment and taxes. Information: 1-800-661-0252
or on the Web at cmhhike.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For golf lovers: ``The Big Fore Package'' is a sampler of the
four mountain courses of Tremblant and Gray Rocks at
Mont-Tremblant, Quebec. Located in the Laurentian Mountains, the
resort area is a 90-minute drive northwest of Montreal. Golf at Le
Geant, Le Diable, La Belle and La Bete and stay at Gray Rocks or
Tremblant Resort for four nights. At Tremblant, prices start at
$335 per person, double occupancy, for four nights lodging and four
rounds, based on Sunday arrival May 14-June 5. Call 1-877-873-6252,
Operator 44. At Gray Rocks, rates begin at $275 per person,
quadruple occupancy, for four nights in a two-bedroom condo and
four rounds of golf (Monday-Thursday only) in Value Season. Call
1-800-567-6767.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the rocks: If your fascination with ``Titanic'' has not
waned, you might want to visit ``Iceberg Alley'' off Newfoundland.
During the five-day ``Titanic Iceberg Tour'' offered by Maxxim
Vacations, you'll find yourself in the middle of a school of
breaching whales or gliding by the largest puffin colony in North
America. And you'll drift up close to icebergs that at five stories
high dwarf the tiny excursion boats. Prime time to witness this
procession of icebergs drifting southward is May, June and July.
Prices begin at $999 per person including round-trip airfare on Air
Canada from Atlanta, five nights accommodations in St. John's and a
rental car. Also included is a two-masted schooner excursion,
whale-and-bird tour and a bus tour of historic St. John's. Extra
days may be added at $59 a day. 1-800-567-6666.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Speaking of Titanic: The Manitoba Museum of the Titanic will
open April 15 at the Portage Mall in Portage la Prairie. Among the
more than 150 Titanic-related artifacts on display: a deck chair
pulled from the North Atlantic, White Star Line china and
silverware, artifacts from the rescue ship Carpathia, a table made
from Titanic wreckwood, a section of carved oak from beneath the
handrail of Titanic's first-class aft grand staircase and set
pieces and props from James Cameron's Academy Award-winning film.
The museum also offers a number of interactive displays such as
``The Dive Machine,'' which simulates looking through a
submersible's window at the Titanic debris on the bottom of the
Atlantic. There is also a reading and research area outfitted with
early 20th-century furnishings to evoke the Titanic's shipboard
reading room. 1-204-857-7447.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Go out to Alberta:
</P>
<P>
   All four of the Canadian Pacific Mountain Resorts _ Banff
Springs Hotel, Chateau Lake Louise, Jasper Park Lodge and the Lodge
at Kananaskis _ are offering ``The Canadian Rockies Experience,''
an all-inclusive, value-priced summer package. The deal includes
equipment rentals, accommodations, three meals daily, an extensive
variety of outdoor activities and the Heritage Mountaineering and
Interpretive Hiking programs. Packages are available from May 1 at
Jasper Park and Kananaskis and from June 1 at Banff Springs and
Lake Louise; all through September. Prices range about $431-$539
per room per night, double occupancy. Information: 1-800-441-1414.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An artsy summer: For the past 35 years, Sunbury Shores Arts
and Nature Center of St. Andrews, New Brunswick, has attracted
students and vacationers to study under leading Canadian artists.
This summer, Sunbury Shores is offering 17 art courses, numerous
nature programs, several ocean excursions and weekday children's
programs. The season begins in late June and runs through August.
Most courses are for five days, but weekday and weekend programs
are also offered. Information: 506-529-3386 or www
</P>
<P>
   .sunburyshores.org (The Web site lists a variety of
accommodations.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Onstage Toronto: One of the most-anticipated productions of
the summer is shaping up to be the original French language musical
``Notre Dame de Paris'' based on the Victor Hugo classic. The show
plays June 8-12 at the Prince of Wales Theatre. French-Canadian Luc
Plamondon, who has written countless ballads for Francophone
crooners (including Celine Dion), composed this modern musical
version of ``The Hunchback of Notre Dame.'' Toronto is the
third-largest theater city in the world after London and New York.
The Toronto Theatre Alliance provides up-to-date information on
what's playing on the city's stages. Call 1-800-541-0499. The Web
site (www.culturenet.ca/tta/) offers a 12-month live performance
listing that is updated monthly.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Toronto overnight: Ethnically diverse Toronto is crammed with
wonderful bed-and-breakfast. And the price is right: Prices range
generally from $33 for one person to $67 for two. For a free copy
of Bed &AMP; Breakfast Homes of Toronto, call 416-363-6362. Internet
users can see photos and access information on most of the homes at
www
</P>
<P>
   .bbcanada.com/563.html
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
