<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CANADA-TRAIN04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rail, bus journeys showcase country at its most scenic
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the best ways to experience Canada's spectacular vistas
is through the window of a train or bus. Here are four ways to
enjoy the view:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Springtime in the Rockies: Rocky Mountain Railtours celebrates
the return of warmer weather and longer days to western Canada and
the Canadian Rockies with a special Spring Savings program. For all
May departures, the Rocky Mountaineer's two-day, all-daylight
service begins at about $332, more than 16 percent off
regular-season fares.
</P>
<P>
   The rail journey covers more than 918 miles between the coastal
city of Vancouver, B.C., and the Rocky Mountain destinations of
Jasper, Banff and Calgary, Alberta. Those onboard will see snow
melting off towering peaks and glacier-fed rivers rising as well as
the return of native flora and fauna to the green valleys of
western Canada. Keen-eyed visitors may catch a glimpse of bears,
elk and eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Spring Savings also apply to more than 30 package tours to
destinations including Vancouver, Victoria, Whistler and Banff.
</P>
<P>
   Information: 1-800-665-7245 or www
</P>
<P>
   .rockymountaineer.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Journey across Canada: Uncommon Journeys is offering ``The
Great Canadian Train Ride,'' which combines a journey across Canada
aboard the fabled art deco-style Canadian between Vancouver and
Toronto with a three-day stopover in the Canadian Rockies en route.
The one-time-only trip is June 4-13. Cost is $1,995 per person,
including all first-class train travel, with sleeping car
accommodations on the vista-domed streamliner Canadian; hotel stays
in Seattle, Vancouver, Jasper and Toronto; transfers; and most
meals. 1-800-323-5893 or www.uncommonjourneys
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Amtrak options: The Amtrak/VIA North America Rail Pass allows
travelers to create a custom itinerary through the United States
and Canada for one fare. Travelers can plan a trip of up to 30
consecutive days through more than 28,000 miles of railways to more
than 900 destinations. Off-peak rate through May 31 is $450. During
peak travel season, June 1-Oct. 15, the cost is $645. Also, Amtrak
Vacations _ which includes two nights' economy lodging and passes
to top attractions _ include Montreal, Toronto and
Vancouver/Victoria. For more information about both these options,
get a free copy of the Amtrak Travel Planner by calling
1-800-872-7245. On the Web: www.amtrak.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlantic coasting via bus: For travelers looking for the
freedom and flexibility to see what Canada's Atlantic region has to
offer, Atlantic Tours Gray Line has six new independent vacation
packages. They are: Bay of Fundy Experience, a two-night package in
St. Andrews and New Brunswick; Taste of Prince Edward Island, a
two-night Charlottetown package; Discover Historic Halifax, a
two-night package; Nova Scotia Tease, a three-night package;
Newfoundland Highlights, a two-night St. Johns package; and Acadian
Memories, a two-night package in Moncton, New Brunswick. The tours
are available May 1-Oct. 15. Information: 902-423-6242 or
www.atlantictours.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
