<HEADER>
A2684 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-IFYOUGO04-COX     04-01 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-IFYOUGO04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    If you go _ Montreal
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Purchase by Wednesday to get a $310 round-trip
fare for travel through Sept. 10 on Delta (two nonstops daily) or
via connecting service on American, Northwest, USAirways, Air
Canada and Continental. Restrictions apply. United has a $150
round-trip special through May 18 for Saturday departures and
Tuesday returns only, with a seven-day advance purchase. Code:
VE7WKNB
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Family attractions: The Montreal Botanical Garden, in the
eastside Maisonneuve area, boasts a collection of 21,000 plant
species spread over 30 thematic outdoor gardens and 10 connected
exhibition greenhouses (the bonsai room is a knockout). Its
five-acre Chinese Garden features seven Ming Dynasty-style
pavilions surrounding Dream Lake. The Biodome, located nearby in
the converted '76 Olympics Velodrome, re-creates the flora and
fauna of four ecosystems _ the tropical forest, ``Polar World,''
the Laurentian Forest and the St. Lawrence Marine Ecosystem. Kids
especially like the cave with 350 bats flying overhead and the
underwater fish observatory. Nearby, it's fun to ride the cable car
up the world's tallest incline tower, rising 623 feet above Olympic
Stadium (known locally as the ``Big Owe,'' for its massive unpaid
mortgage). The observation deck provides a panoramic view of the
city. Surprisingly, exhibits at the base and deck give only
fleeting attention to the Olympic story.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Museums: Montreal's museums focus on history, art,
architecture, design, the Holocaust and even comedy. A Montreal
Museum Pass allows you to visit up to 14 museums with a one-day
pass (about $11) or three-day pass, which can be used any three
days over a three-week period (about $20). Call 1-800-363-7777. An
important stop is the Montreal Museum of Fine Arts, located in
facing buildings on Rue Sherbrooke _ a stately, marble
classical-style 1912 edifice and an airy modern 1991 expansion
(where ``Monet at Giverny'' runs through May 9). An underground
passageway connecting the two offers a mini-tour of world art,
including African, Asian and Greek galleries. Don't miss the strong
collection of Inuit carvings in the older building. The Museum of
Archaeology and History at
</P>
<P>
   Pointe-a-Calliere in Old Montreal stands on the very site where
the city was founded in 1642. The museum mixes high-tech
razzle-dazzle, including holographic conversations with early
settlers, with interesting remains (pottery, stone tools and
cast-iron cannon balls) unearthed nearby.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dining: Sophistication, selection (3,560 restaurants in the
city proper) and diversity (80 cuisines) are points of pride. With
so many neighborhood places, it's a fun city to gamble based on the
menu outside. Recommended in Old Montreal is the seafood at
Restaurant du Vieux Port, 39 Rue St. Paul East, 514-866-3175; and
the mussels at the Belgian bistro Le Petit Moulinsart, 139 Rue St.
Paul West, 514-843-7432. Specializing in the freshest Quebecois
cuisine, Toque! seems to be the trendy spot of the moment: 3842 Rue
St. Denis, 514-499-2084. Open for 44 years and going strong is Le
Paris, 1812 Rue St. Catherine West, 514-937-4898.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lodging: Myriad options, from cozy B&AMP;Bs to the classy
(Ritz-Carlton, 1228 Sherbrooke St. West, 514-842-4212), and
virtually every kind of chain in between. Modestly priced choices
include the Holiday Inn Montreal Midtown, 420 Sherbrooke St. West
(prime location near McGill University), 514-842-6111; the Queen
Elizabeth, 900 Boulevard Rene Levesque West, 514-861-351; and the
Hotel Lord Berri, 1199 Berri St. (near the St. Denis
shopping/dining zone), 1-888-363-0363. For a brochure listing
members of the Bed &AMP; Breakfast Downtown Network, call
1-800-267-5180; www
</P>
<P>
   .bbmontreal.qc.ca/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Tourisme Montreal, 514-844-5400;
www.tourism-montreal.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
