<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2685 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MONTREAL1STTAK     04-01 1249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MONTREAL1STTAKE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Montreal: Spirit of a City
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ They wore bulky sweaters and clunky boots, some
clutching strollers with babies swaddled like mini Eskimos, as they
quietly lingered in front of Monet's lush landscapes at the
Montreal Museum of Fine Arts. The Montrealers could be excused for
stealing extra moments to savor the gorgeous green water lilies and
cascading wisteria blossoms of the ``Monet at Giverny'' exhibit,
for outside on this late March afternoon it didn't look anything
like the French artist's famed garden.
</P>
<P>
   It was tres froid, and winter was getting old. Spring was
officially but a day away, yet everyone who lives for warm weather
in this city knew it still would be a few more weeks of enduring.
It meant a while longer before the black ice edging the streets and
the frozen sheets covering the beloved sidewalk cafes would start
trickling away, and before the burlap swathing the shrubs and trees
could be unfurled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty awful in winter,'' says Rufus Wainwright, the
Montreal singer-songwriter whose self-titled debut album made it
onto a lot of critics' Top 10 lists last year. ``Everyone really
worships spring when it comes. Its like May Day in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't picked the best time of year to make my first visit to
this French-Canadian city of 3.5 million people, actually an island
in the St. Lawrence River. In fact, ice floes were rolling down the
river, which gives Montreal its shape and, at least at sunnier
times, some of its abundant romance. The Montreal Canadiens were
wrapping up a so-so season at the Molson Center, but they could
just as well have been slapping pucks at the Montreal Botanical
Garden, considered one of the world's best when not frozen over.
Downtown's streets, while hardly abandoned, were missing the
partying throngs that soon will be back for the series of outdoor
festivals that add so much to the city's joie de vivre.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even appearing its worst, Montreal had plenty to
recommend it _ and to make an Atlantan more than a tad envious.
Culture and multiculturalism. A safe subway system that gets
everywhere you want to go. Beggars with shockingly good manners
(``Sir, if I may ask you seriously for some monetary assistance,''
one pitched me on the Metro). Neighborhoods that invite a healthy
walk. Historic architecture that demands a gaze. Cool restaurants,
bars and coffee joints. Open-24-hours haunts (Monsieur Falafel's
neon lights are glowing when you need that 3 a.m. Middle Eastern
fix). Endless shops and boutiques to test the favorable exchange
rate. Youthful spirit (three universities in downtown alone). New
York sophistication without the attitude. Hometown pride.
</P>
<P>
   The most tangible example of the latter is a list of ``101
Things to Love About Montreal'' that the city's daily Gazette ran
late last year. The more I rambled around during my long-weekend
visit, the more I appreciated the readers' affection:
</P>
<P>
   ``Europeans finding it's so American, Americans finding it's so
European.''_ No. 95
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I never imagined I was on the Left Bank, even when I
dined at a charming little bistro named Le Paris. The St. Catherine
Street restaurant boasts its share of French dishes and wines. But
my steak entree, Bavette Sauce a l'Echalotte, seemed more
stick-to-your-ribs French-Canadian than classic French. And my
dessert, Ile Flottante (``Floating Island''), a cruise-ship-sized
portion of meringue adrift in a sea of custard cream sauce and
almonds? That may betotally French, but my host's insistence that
it was ``light'' and that I should order it struck me as sweetly
French-Canadian, a culture that has no issues with indulgence.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Montreal is the only French-speaking metropolis in North
America, and the island is even shaped like a croissant. But even
the two-thirds majority of French speakers will take mercy on an
English-speaking visitor, especially one who offers up a feeble
bonjour. And lingering conflicts over the separatist movement only
obscure the fact that Canada's second-largest city has grown
culturally diversified in recent years. Now, 15 percent of the
population claims a language other than English or French as its
mother tongue.
</P>
<P>
   There was plenty of evidence of that at ``Simply Montreal,'' an
entertaining exhibit at the McCord Museum of Canadian History,
including a gallery of photos of residents who've married outside
their culture. ``We're part of a very cosmopolitan circle,'' reads
the text under a couple identified only as Parjo and France. ``Our
friends and acquaintances come from 121 countries.''
</P>
<P>
   I found myself agreeing with T.J. and Ken Norris, a Pennsylvania
couple who spoke of Montreal as being interestingly
``international.'' The Norrises got married here five years ago,
and returned for another week when they decided they couldn't
budget the time or money for the European vacation they'd been
considering. Nursing second cups of breakfast coffee at the
downtown B&AMP;B Les Bons Matins, they said they planned to make a
tradition of returning every five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time was beautiful because we were on our honeymoon,
and this time was just as nice,'' said Ken, 43, an editor. ``Now
we'll take some French lessons to go further in conversations on
our next visit.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Europeans perceiving Montreal as American, I could
understand how they could reach that conclusion if they stuck too
close to St. Catherine, the main tourist drag where the Gap, Hugo
Boss, Burger King and the Hard Rock Cafe lend an Anywhere USA feel
(even if I did like the ice painted on the Golden Arches logo). But
there are shopping districts where nobody says McDonald's _ a
highly recommended one being Rue Saint-Denis in the Plateau
Mont-Royal neighborhood. Here, homes of limestone with exterior
ironwork staircases have been converted into beckoning boutiques,
bookstores and cafes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The first exposed skin on jampacked St. Denis Street on a
beautiful Saturday after another endless winter.'' _ No. 40
</P>
<P>
   Montrealers, rather hotblooded for people who wear heavy winter
coats almost half the year, are not shy in a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   In June, more than 200,000 revelers per night will attend the
nine-night international musical fireworks competition over the St.
Lawrence. Forty-five thousand will participate in June's Tour de
l'Ile de Montreal, a 70K bicycle race. The Festival International
de Jazz de Montreal, which annually draws more than 1.5 million,
will present 400 concerts in July _ one of the 11 days of
</P>
<P>
   age to Louisiana's French-Canadian musical roots. Also in July,
comics and other performers from 14 countries will play more than
1,300 shows in the Just for Laughs Festival.
</P>
<P>
   While the warm weather lasts there are also festivals of dragon
boats, kites, beer tasting, gay and lesbian pride, world beat
music, French music, classical music, world film, hot-air balloons
and dance, as well as a speedboat regatta, and a new Cirque du
Soleil spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   One resident, John Archambault, said he can't wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel that you have to get out in it because it's part of
the life of the city,'' said the 41-year-old pharmaceutical
equipment technician. ``If you're at
</P>
<P>
   home, you wonder, `Why am I sitting here?' You want to be out in
the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
