<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2688 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS04-     04-01 2695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray, Bob Longino, Tom
Sabulis, Jill Vejnoska, Phil Kloer and Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This'' R (profanity, sexuality, violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Robert De Niro,
</P>
<P>
   Billy Crystal and Lisa Kudrow.
</P>
<P>
   This farce about a mobster (Robert De Niro) who takes his issues
to a psychiatrist (Billy Crystal) never becomes the laugh-riot it
could be. It's an offer you could refuse, but the stars (plus Lisa
Kudrow as Crystal's fiancee) make it worthwhile. (SM) 1 hour, 46
minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby Geniuses'' PG
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kathleen Turner,
</P>
<P>
   Peter MacNicol, Christopher Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Turner and Peter MacNicol play rival researchers _ she
the breathy villainess, he the bland do-bee _ rushing to crack the
talk code emanating from five brilliant babes. Sly _ the toddler
leader _ has got a secret twin and you've got yourself 94 minutes
chock full of stupid pint-sized tricks from the brain of Bob Clark.
At first, ``Geniuses'' is dumb, and then it just gets dumber. (Bob
Longino) 94 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Children of Heaven'' Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mohammad Amir
</P>
<P>
   Naji, Mir Farrokh Hashemian,
</P>
<P>
   Bahare Seddiqi.
</P>
<P>
   You can go see this movie intent on divining all sorts of hidden
messages in its tale of abject poverty, scary authority figures and
other aspects of Iranian life. But then you'd miss seeing a
simpler, much more delightful story about two little kids and their
quest for one pair of shoes. The ending is by turns touching,
heartbreaking and hilarious. (Jill Vejnoska) 1 hour, 27 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``The Corruptor'' R (violence, profanity, sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Chow Yun-Fat
</P>
<P>
   and Mark Wahlberg.
</P>
<P>
   Chow Yun-Fat and Mark Wahlberg play Chinatown cops forging an
uneasy truce in this violent, densely plotted action flick. Fueled
with betrayals and gunfire, it's the closest thing yet to Chow's
Hong King collaborations with John Woo. (SM) 1 hour, 51 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruel Intentions'' R (profanity, sexual situations, drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sarah Michelle Gellar,
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Phillippe and Selma Blair.
</P>
<P>
   Last decade's ``Dangerous Liaisons'' gets a makeover with Sarah
Michelle Gellar and Ryan Phillippe as a couple of desultorily rich
teens manipulating the romantic lives of everyone around them,
purely for their own amusement and without a whit of concern about
who may be hurt in the process. It's practically guaranteed to be a
runaway hit with the teen audience. (Jill Vejnoska) 1 hour, 37
minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Deep End of the Ocean'' PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Starring Michelle Pfeiffer and Treat Williams.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when your son turns up living two blocks away with
a man who has no idea his then-unbalanced, now-deceased wife
kidnapped him years ago? Well, in this movie you become Michelle
Pfeiffer and self-absorb your way to family bliss. They should post
a warning: the deep end of this ocean is filled with melodrama.
(Jill Vejnoska) 1 hour and 45 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Doug's 1st Movie'' G
</P>
<P>
   Starring the voices of Thomas
</P>
<P>
   McHugh, Fred Newman,
</P>
<P>
   Constance Shulman.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Nickelodeon series on which it's based, this movie's
appeal is centered in the carefully nurtured normalcy of its title
character, Doug Funnie, a nice kid coping with some typical preteen
passions. The gently anarchic, pro-environment plot is simply a
framework to dispense the quiet main-street morals and vivid
comic-book colors that make the wholesome Doug a superstar with
children. (Tom Sabulis)1 hour, 17 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``EDtv'' PG-13 (profanity, partial nudity, sex-related
situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew McConaughey, Jenna Elfman.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew McConaughey plays the subject of a 24-hour-a-day
documentary in Ron Howard's new comedy. Yeah, it's too much like
``Truman Show'' for its own good, but the slick packaging and
strong cast (including Jenna Elfman, Ellen DeGeneres and Martin
Landau) help it stand on its own. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 3 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight Millimeter'' R (strong perverse sexuality, violence,
profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nicolas Cage
</P>
<P>
   and Joaquin Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   A new example of Morbidity Chic from the screenwriter of
``Seven.'' Nicolas Cage plays a private investigator pursuing the
possible death of a girl in a snuff flick. It's an unpleasant crawl
through the world of porn; you can tell the filmmakers think it's a
troubling exploration of moral ambiguity, but it's an exploitation
flick tricked out as art. (SM) 2 hours, 3 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth'' R (violence and sex)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Cate Blanchett
</P>
<P>
   and Geoffrey Rush.
</P>
<P>
   This opulent period film puts a slight feminist gloss on the
early reign of 16th-century monarch Elizabeth I, showing her
transformation from a radiant, saucy innocent to a polished,
guarded ruler. Cate Blanchett gives a luminous portrayal, and
Geoffrey Rush gives her sturdy support as court politics and
intrigues swirl about. This is a really good story. (ERG) 2 hours,
4 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Everest'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary by David Breashears.
</P>
<P>
   Breathtaking. Even filmgoers accustomed to the five-story IMAX
format may gasp at the unearthly scale of ``Everest.'' David
Breashears'
</P>
<P>
   documentary was filmed at the same time as the 1996 storm that
killed eight mountain climbers, memorialized by Jon Krakauer's
best-selling book ``Into Thin Air.'' (SM) 44 minutes. A
</P>
<P>
   ``Forces of Nature'' PG-13 (profanity, sexuality, drug use)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sandra Bullock
</P>
<P>
   and Ben Affleck.
</P>
<P>
   Opposites attract as strait-laced Ben Affleck heads to his
wedding with free-spirit Sandra Bullock. Like ``My Best Friend's
Wedding,'' it's a savvy blend of romantic-comedy formula and wise
'90s updates. (SM) 1 hour, 41 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Gods and Monsters'' Not rated, but includes sexual themes and
brief nudity
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ian McKellen
</P>
<P>
   and Brendan Fraser.
</P>
<P>
   A brilliant re-imagining of the final days of gay British
director James Whale. Whale, best known for his classic horror
movies (``Bride of Frankenstein''), died mysteriously in 1957.
Played here by the marvelous Ian McKellen, he's an isolated,
forgotten recluse who becomes interested in the hunky new gardener
(Brendan Fraser). (ERG) 1 hour, 35 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The King and I'' G
</P>
<P>
   Voiced by Miranda Richardson and Martin Vidnovic.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first animated feature based on a work by Rodgers
and Hammerstein, but does this second-rate animated King of Siam
really need to high-five the paw of his pet black leopard? This
king has a hot-air balloon to fly around in and to swoop into
action when somebody's about to drown. Kids will probably be
charmed. For everybody else, it's a puzzlement. (Bob Longino) 1
hour and 26 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Is Beautiful'' PG-13 (Holocaust-related atrocities)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Roberto Benigni.
</P>
<P>
   Three Oscars, including best actor. An Italian Jew shields his
son from the horrors of a concentration camp by pretending their
predicament is part of a big, complicated game. Roberto Benigni's
low-comedy slapstick approach isn't entirely convincing and is
often chillingly wrongheaded. Subtitles. (ERG) 2 hours, 2 minutes.
B
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' R (violence and
profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nick Moran and Jason Flemyng.
</P>
<P>
   Smokin'. This whip-smart lark is an English caper comedy
glistening with confidence and a wicked sense of humor. Four
likable, conniving East End lads have a week to settle the debt
they owe a hood named Hatchet Harry. Rookie writer/director Guy
Ritchie piles on the characters, plot twists and violence, but one
thing is clear: everyone involved had a fine time making this
movie. You'll have fun watching it. (ERG) 1 hour, 45 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix'' R (sci-fi violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Keanu Reeves,
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Fishburne,
</P>
<P>
   Carrie-Anne Moss.
</P>
<P>
   A knockout sci-fi flick. Writer-directors Andy and Larry
Wachowski bring their sharp storytelling and visual showmanship to
an adventure starring Keanu Reeves that should please both comic
book fanatics and mainstream moviegoers. Balancing intelligence
with stunning special effects and action, it's a movie that earns
its explosions, high kicks and cascades of spent bullets. (SM) 2
hours, 15 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mod Squad'' R (profanity, violence, nudity, sexual
situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Claire Danes,
</P>
<P>
   Omar Epps, Giovanni Ribisi.
</P>
<P>
   It's the look that matters. Not the plot involving drugs,
murder, good guys turned bad and a car wash. This ``Mod Squad'' _
with Claire Danes, Omar Epps and an occasionally inspired Giovanni
Ribisi _ is a fashion layout for ``Details'' magazine. All image.
All blurry visuals. All reds and blacks. All jazz riffs and retro
TV music with plenty of bongo drums and brass.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Longino) 1 hour and 34 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``My Favorite Martian'' PG (violence, partial nudity and
profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jeff Daniels
</P>
<P>
   and Christopher Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
   A big-screen remake of the '60s TV series, with the annoying and
unsubtle Christopher Lloyd as the Martian who camps in Jeff
Daniels' living room. The movie is cobbled together with cheesy
special effects and easy gags. But for kids, it's an OK
baby-sitter. (SM) 1 hour, 33 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``October Sky'' PG (profanity, sensuality, alcohol use, some
thematic elements)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Jake Gyllenhaal,
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cooper and Laura Dern.
</P>
<P>
   Deeply satisfying tale of West Virginia teen Homer (Jake
Gyllenhaal) and three friends who, in the 1950s, began to build and
shoot off model rockets. Their goal: to win a science fair, which
could help them escape a future of working in the coal mine of
their small town. Based on Homer Hickam's autobiography ``Rocket
Boys,'' it makes the process of learning seem as exciting as a
special FX-driven action flick. (SM)1 hour, 48 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Out-of-Towners'' PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Starring Steve Martin,
</P>
<P>
   Goldie Hawn and John Cleese.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mess from the start. Henry (Steve Martin) and Nancy Clark
(Goldie Hawn) are a long-married couple from Ohio trying to
redefine their lives now that the children are grown. They land in
New York and high jinks ensue. The only time the film hints at the
madcap success it could be is when John Cleese appears as the
secretly cross-dressing hotel manager.
</P>
<P>
   (Drew Jubera) 1 hour, 31 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Payback'' R (violence, profanity, drug and sexual content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Mel Gibson and Gregg Henry.
</P>
<P>
   A by-the-numbers vengeance thriller starring Mel Gibson. It's as
generic as its unnamed, dull gray city. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   At metro theaters. 1 hour, 42 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rage: Carrie 2'' R (violence, gore, sexuality, profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Emily Bergl
</P>
<P>
   and Amy Irving.
</P>
<P>
   Emily Bergl plays a misunderstood, telekinetic teenager in this
cheap, dull horror flick. The sort-of sequel is so bad, you might
mistake it for self-parody. Amy Irving also stars as the first
film's survivor, but skulks through her scenes looking like she's
ready to kill her agent. (SM) 1 hour, 45 minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``The School of Flesh'' R (profanity and strong sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Isabel Huppert and
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   A smart, cool-hot drama of sexual obsession. Isabel Huppert, the
grand sphinx of French cinema, plays Dominique, a wealthy, single
Parisian whose life changes when she steps into a bar one night and
locks eyes with a hustler. It is smartly edited, trusting us to
keep up with it, never delivering a scene that feels contrived. In
French with subtitles. (SM) 1 hour and 41 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love''R (sexuality, nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joseph Fiennes, Gwyneth
</P>
<P>
   Paltrow and Geoffrey Rush.
</P>
<P>
   Seven Oscars, including best picture. Poor, overworked Will
Shakespeare (Joseph Fiennes) has to finish his play ``Romeo and
Ethel, the Pirate's Daughter'' and try to win the hand of
noblewoman Viola
</P>
<P>
   (Gwyneth Paltrow, who received an Oscar for best actress) in
this witty comedy that uses some of the Bard's more outrageous plot
devices. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   At metro theaters. 2 hours, 2 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Stepmom'' PG-13 (profanity, adult themes)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Susan Sarandon, Julia Roberts and Ed Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sarandon and Julia Roberts play competing mothers _ one
biological, the other step _ in this comedy/weepie that tackles
some complex ``blended family'' issues, then cops out by giving a
character a fatal disease. Still, the sturdy cast does much to
redeem the mush-headed script (add Ed Harris in the dishonest role
of doting dad who somehow never sees his kids). (ERG) At area
discount theaters. 2 hours. B
</P>
<P>
   ``Tango'' PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Starring Miguel Angel Sola, Mia Maestro.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Angel Sola plays Mario, a Buenos Aires
filmmaker-choreography shooting the definitive film about the
tango. As he falls for young dancer Elena (Mia Maestro), we wait
for inevitable retribution from her gangster lover. The plot is
almost secondary to the self-conscious but gorgeous theatricality
of the film's design, the steamy elegance of its dance numbers.
Subtitles. (SM) 1 hour and 55 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``10 Things I Hate About You'' PG-13 (sex-related dialogue,
alcohol/drug-related scenes)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Julia Stiles,
</P>
<P>
   Heath Ledger.
</P>
<P>
   What starts out as a terrible teen version of ``The Taming of
the Shrew'' unexpectedly starts to percolate with wit and charm,
thanks largely to its Kate-and-Petruchio stand-ins, Kat (Julia
Stiles) and Patrick (Heath Ledger). The script can't go too far
wrong with Shakespeare's plot. (It's worked for 400 years.)
References to the original verge on precious. But the film also has
a few nutty touches of its own. (SM) 1 hour, 34 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``T. rex: Back to the Cretaceous'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   Starring Liz Stauber
</P>
<P>
   and Peter Horton.
</P>
<P>
   The IMAX film has awesome special effects but, as a fictional
story, is too short. Ally Hayden (Liz Stauber) is a budding teenage
paleontologist who wants to go on a dig with her dino-hunting dad
(Peter Horton). When her dad brings what could be a dinosaur egg
into his lab, Ally accidentally cracks it and is thrust back in
time 65 million years, when the big beasts roamed the Earth. (ERG)
40 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``True Crime'' R (profanity and violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Clint Eastwood
</P>
<P>
   and Isaiah Washington, James Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Producer-director-star Clint Eastwood plays a hard-boiled
newspaper reporter trying to prove a death-row inmate's innocence.
It's so full of
</P>
<P>
   cliches, you'd think it was a self-parody. (SM) 2 hours, 7
minutes. D
</P>
<P>
   ``A Walk on the Moon'' R (sexual situations and nudity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Diane Lane,
</P>
<P>
   Liev Schreiber, Viggo Mortensen.
</P>
<P>
   The movie starts as a fondly observed look at upstate New York's
Jewish family resorts. But when housewife Pearl (Diane Lane) gets
an itch once her husband goes back to the city, her actions seem
both dumb and selfish. By the time she's making picturesque whoopee
under a waterfall with her lover, the movie has veered from
well-observed 1960s character study into silly soap opera. (SM) 1
hour, 46 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Wing Commander'' PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Starring Freddie Prinze Jr.,
</P>
<P>
   Mathew Lillard and Saffron Burrows.
</P>
<P>
   It's one loopy space lark, with pretty boy Freddie Prinze Jr.
and ``Scream's'' wonderfully woozy killer Matthew Lillard playing
fighter pilots in a galaxy at war. Earth is threatened by a
lumbering band of catlike creatures wrapped in armadillo armor. It
takes eons for ``Wing,'' based on the popular computer game, to get
to the first big dogfight. (Bob Longino)
</P>
<P>
   At metro theaters. 1 hour, 53 minutes. D+
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolves'' Not rated
</P>
<P>
   A documentary.
</P>
<P>
   Not as visually stunning as some IMAX films, this is a highly
instructive look at the once nearly vanquished gray wolf's gradual
reintroduction to Yellowstone National Park and other parts of the
American West. Covers a bit too much ground, historically and
geographically; the best parts show wolves ranging from adult pack
leaders to newborn cubs exploring and adjusting to the wild again.
(Phil Kloer) 41 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
