<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2689 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-TOWNERS04-COX     04-01 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TOWNERS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Remake uncertain of its destination
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The good news is that, at 91 minutes, this swiftly passing
remake of 1970's ``The Out-of-Towners'' is not a minute longer than
it needs to be. The bad news is that it was remade at all. It takes
the terrifically flawed original, starring Jack Lemmon and Sandy
Dennis, rubs out whatever was terrific and hatches all-new flaws.
</P>
<P>
   It's a mess from the start. The Marc Lawrence screenplay is
based on the Neil Simon original, but it feels staler the second it
starts to unreel. Henry (Steve Martin) and Nancy Clark (Goldie
Hawn) are a long-married couple from Ohio trying to redefine their
lives now that the children are grown. She wants to ``suck the
marrow out of life.'' He wants to ``catch up on my reading.'' But
their lives are jolted when Henry is fired from his advertising job
and lands an interview with an agency in New York.
</P>
<P>
   From that moment on, high jinks ensue: Plane to New York gets
routed to Boston, luggage is lost, money is stolen, hotel
reservation is forfeited. There's supposed to be weight to what's
madcap here. The calamaties are supposed to escalate and
accumulate, with New York representing all that is hard and scary
and unknown. By the end, you should feel both exhausted and
victorious. We beat this town!
</P>
<P>
   Lemmon was almost too determined to survive it all in the
original. He was the Everyman husband who was going to get where he
was going no matter what, never asking directions and always taking
down names. While it doesn't stand up so well today _ presumably
that's why we have this remake _ the 1970 version managed to
capture the oddly shifting angst of its time.
</P>
<P>
   There's no real danger or challenge in this remake's New York;
it's just a big stage for one obvious gag after another. Nothing
accumulates: We never feel exhausted. Even after jumping from a
speeding taxi, Henry's tie is still perfectly knotted.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Hawn try furiously to generate chemistry. Alas, in
vain _ though there is a certain chuckleheaded charm to their
unrelenting jokiness. Hawn doesn't know what she wants to do, but
you get the feeling that what she'd really like is to play the
whole thing with her eyes crossed.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is a bigger disappointment. He just bides his time,
hoping you don't notice. He masks his disinterest with the flailing
arms and elastic facial gestures of a silent film star. Better
there wasn't any sound at all; he recites dialogue like a line
reader feeding words to a momentarily forgetful actor.
</P>
<P>
   The only time the film hints at the madcap success it could be
is when John Cleese appears as the secretly cross-dressing hotel
manager. Evil, petty and awful, he's ridiculous the way this movie
should be ridiculous, with a kind of over-the-top believability
that requires that you mean it.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Cleese, you realize that they remade the wrong movie:
He'd be the perfect lead in the remake of ``The Cable Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Out-of-Towners''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Steve Martin, Goldie Hawn and John Cleese. Directed by
Sam Weisman. Rated PG-13. 1 hour, 31 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Out to lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
