<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2690 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MONTREAL2NDTAK     04-01 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MONTREAL2NDTAKE04-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL: the streets.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Boasting to friends elsewhere that Montreal has the world's
highest proportion of good-looking people.'' _ No. 13
</P>
<P>
   ``Montreal has very cute French boys,'' says Rufus Wainwright,
adding almost as an afterthought, ``and very pretty girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Far be it from me to question the judgment on males of the
openly gay Wainwright. But the women . . . sexy enough to cause the
first-time visitor to lose focus and wander into oncoming traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I wondered was how they could walk in platform
shoes taller than anything Elton John wore in his wild days _ and
if it's a fashion trend or a practical way to avoid the slush and
ice. Oh, never mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Having the chutzpah to call a 250-meter mountain a
mountain.'' _ No. 50
</P>
<P>
   Mont-Royal, known simply as ``The Mountain'' among natives, is
really more of a hill, but it's considered rude to bring this up.
Instead, climb the 767-foot outcropping, via the winding steps off
Rue Peel (near McGill University).
</P>
<P>
   It will deliver you to Mont-Royal Park, designed in the 1870s by
Frederick Law Olmsted as a gathering space whose popularity
endures. The park was quiet the weekday I visited, though I was
assured that tobogganing kids would be tearing up the ice and snow
that weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On most days, you can get an outstanding southeastern view of
the St. Lawrence as it rolls past Old Montreal (the cobblestoned
17th-century historic district) and the port area. There's a reason
you feel you're looking down on creation: City law prohibits any
structure from being taller than the mountain. The tallest, a
51-story downtown office tower, is a mere three feet shorter.
Another worthy stop on the mountain is the majestic St. Joseph's
Oratory, topped by the world's second-largest dome, which attracts
more than 2 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Coming back to Montreal after doing the career thing in
Toronto and realizing it wasn't worth it.'' _ No. 83
</P>
<P>
   ``Citizens who don't have a clue what's happening in other parts
of Canada because, after all, who cares?'' _ No. 84
</P>
<P>
   It's the Canadian version of the healthy loathing between San
Francisco and Los Angeles. Montrealers consider people from
Toronto, Canada's banking center, ``more interested in money,''
said Gilles O. Bengle, a Montreal tourism bureau director. ``Here,
we're more interested in the quality of life.''
</P>
<P>
   And what would Torontonians say about Montrealers?
</P>
<P>
   ``They would consider us too frivolous,'' Bengle said with a
hearty laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Lucien Gobeil, who sells his hand-tinted photographs of the city
from a Place Jacques-Cartier sidewalk in Old Montreal, needs no
persuasion about the quality of life here. He came from the Quebec
countryside to attend three years of school and has stayed for
three decades.
</P>
<P>
   As a frigid breeze blew up from the river one night around dusk,
Gobeil, 52, explained why he's the only vendor who will set up shop
in Old Montreal on winter weekends. ``This place is alive with
people, so I think its important for (a vendor) to be here if they
need directions or want to know about restaurants. I don't ask
money for that. I think that's giving back to the city.''
</P>
<P>
   His sidewalk gallery includes handsome images of Old Montreal
street lights and Plateau Mont-Royal staircases dripping with
icicles. When I complimented him for finding the beauty in the
severe weather, he explained, ``We have six months of winter, so I
have to represent that.'' Then he added, ``And when people see a
cold picture in the summer, they like it. It's refreshing!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Tourtiere, sushi, pakoras, paella, nasi goreng, pierogis,
souvlaki, ris de veau, hush puppies, pad thai, manicotti, couscous,
smoked meat, baba ghanouj, dim sum, calamari, profiteroles and Key
lime pie.'' _ No. 79
</P>
<P>
   I came, I saw, I noshed. Maybe it was those nights when the
temperature dropped into the high teens, but the appetite really
revved. If someone had offered me a midnight snack of marinaded
whale blubber, I probably would've demanded seconds.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, I devoured several meaty dishes I'd never touch back
home. At the art deco Atwater Market, I feasted at a bakery-cafe
called Premiere Moisson. Passing up the cheesecakes with their
fruit toppings arranged just so _ it was breakfast, mind you _ I
settled on a huge buttered baguette smeared with cretons (a pork
terrine cooked with onions in lard, which sounds horrible but was
yummy) and a tureen-sized serving of cafe au lait. But I had to
draw the line when offered a sample of caribou pate, one of more
than 20 available. I like 'em better on four legs, thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner at the Fromagerie, which carries more than 450
cheeses, Gilles Jourdenais tempted me with samples of the latest
flavors from rural Quebec, including the mild semi-soft Sieur
Corbeau des Laurentides. I could have stuck around all day, but the
place was so powerfully pungent I was afraid they'd be wrapping me
in pretty foil before long.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite food experience came at Schwartz's, a
hole-in-the-wall Jewish deli legendary for smoked brisket that's
much like pastrami. As I waited in line for a seat at the counter,
I had to laugh at the waiters _ crustier than any rye _ as they
bantered. ``Tell your customers good night!'' one ordered another,
as the queue stretched out into the sidewalk. Yet another answered
a customer, ``No, we don't have soup. They haven't invented smoked
meat soup yet!''
</P>
<P>
   Even my ``small plate'' of the house specialty _ as rich, smoky
and satisfying as advertised _ turned out to be massively oversize,
as did the juice-squirting monster dill.
</P>
<P>
   So you could imagine my horror when a college-aged Asian guy
sitting on the stool next to me reported to our server, Bobby, that
he thought the meat could've been spicier. I half expected Bobby to
whack the kid over the head with a steaming brisket, since there
were a dozen sitting right there.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Bobby said with almost fatherly concern, ``Yeah, it's a
little red tonight for some reason. Every night it's different.''
</P>
<P>
   And as I was paying my bill at the register a few minutes later,
I caught him out of the corner of my eye slicing off a brisket end
piece and chomping down on it.
</P>
<P>
   Quality control, I assumed.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A church on every corner and a pub on every block.'' _ No.
29
</P>
<P>
   Party-hearty reputation aside, Montreal was, after all, founded
by French missionaries intent on converting native Indians to
Christianity in 1642, and spirituality remains at the center of
many residents' lives.
</P>
<P>
   I had read that the Basilique Notre-Dame in Old Montreal was
perhaps the essential stop for visitors, but nothing quite prepared
me for the immense beauty behind the Gothic Revival facade that
dates to the 1820s. It's one of the biggest Roman Catholic churches
in North America (capacity of the main sanctuary and two balconies:
3,500), and no surface is left undecorated. Save for the
jewel-toned stained glass that depict episodes in Montreal's
history, it's made entirely of wood, either gilded or painted in
rich blues and burgundies. The frescoes rising over the baptistery
(angels at the very top) make you want to stare and stare. The
organ, with its 6,772 pipes, is an instrument of power.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the basilica's ornateness, what touched me when I
attended one of the four Sunday Masses was an intimate moment at
the end of the service. The priest, in the words of a guide who
translated for me later, instructed the congregants ``to give peace
to each other.'' Everyone smiled and shook hands with their
neighbors, and mothers hugged their little ones close.
</P>
<P>
   A few moments later, I strolled back onto the plaza, buttoning
my coat against the chill wind blowing up from the St. Lawrence.
The basilica's bell towers began pealing with joyous pandemonium,
calling even more pilgrims to pray. I listened for a while, until
there was only one bell ringing . . . and finally none. The church
doors shut and there was, for a moment, absolute silence. That's
when I noticed the sun, bathing the sidewalk with welcoming warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Pousner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
