<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Puckish pupils have cross-cultural fun
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Thirty-eight eighth-grade French students from
Northwood Middle School in Taylors, S.C., a Greenville suburb, got
a crash course in French-Canadian culture on a recent three-night
visit to Montreal and Quebec City.
</P>
<P>
   In less than 24 hours in Montreal, they managed to take in a
Canadiens hockey game (non-sports fans went to a laser-tag
attraction instead), visit the St. Joseph's Oratory, Basilique
Notre-Dame and Place Jacques-Cartier, ride to the top of the
Incline Tower over the Olympic Stadium and go shopping in the
underground mall. Oh, they also dined and slept a few winks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting for the kids to see business go on and life
conducted in a foreign language,'' said teacher Martha Rice.
</P>
<P>
   The students, many devouring Burger King hamburgers and slurping
Frappucinos at Dorval airport while waiting out a delay on their
return flight, shared their favorite Montreal things:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chris Williams, 14: ``I liked how the people talked. I said
bonjour and asked how they were doing. They replied, but the
conversation kinda ended there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lyle Parks, 13: ``The carvings at the (Notre-Dame) cathedral
were pretty neat.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Amy Harrison, 13: ``The snow, because we only get this much
(she holds two fingers a half-inch apart) in Greenville.'' Her only
complaint: ``Most of the people were nice, but I asked some of them
if they spoke English, and they'd say no even though they were
listening to American music.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lisa Durham, 14: ``At the hockey game, everyone was screaming
(for the Canadiens). My friend and I decided to yell for Nashville
_ we were going for the Americans. And the fans around us would
scream even louder for Montreal. It was so much fun, but when
Nashville scored, the scoreboard flashed `Lucky Shot!' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Howard Pousner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
