<HEADER>
A2692 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-MONTREALRUFUS0     04-01 0384
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MONTREALRUFUS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Good gig: Wainwright is singing the praises of a colorful
metropolis
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Howard Pousner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Rufus Wainwright, who has lived in Montreal for 23 of
his 26 years, released a self-titled debut album last year that is
every bit as eclectic and sophisticated as his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Montreal is a hands-on city where if you want to do something,
you do it _ not for the money or to be a part of a scene,'' says
the son of fellow singer-songwriters Loudon Wainwright III and Kate
McGarrigle. ``I used to do shows and invite people down. The only
requirement was that everything has to be very cheap, because a lot
of people are broke.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those early gigs were at Cafe Sarajevo, a club run by
and frequented by Eastern European emigres. While he's mostly on
the road these days, Wainwright enjoyed talking up some of his
other favorite Montreal haunts:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Places to see music: ``The Cabaret Music Hall. They have tons
of different shows. It's a really nice room. There's also the
Spectrum, where the big acts come through. And probably the most
famous thing is the Jazz Festival, where I've seen performers like
Henry Mancini and Nina Simone.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dance clubs: ``There's a gay club, Unity, and another club
called Sky. Montreal has an interesting gay scene _ very risque. A
lot of people come up from New York to let loose.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coffee shops: ``Tons of them. Cinema Parallele is a coffee
place with a cinema in back. (The coffee shop recently moved a
block away to the new Ex-Centris Cinema Complex.) And Bistro 4 has
some shows _ poetry and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Breakfast: ``Dusty's. It's your standard grille, your sloppy
eggs and bacon. A couple of more high-end places: Eggspectations, a
chain but actually really good, and the Crepe Breton, which, as you
might guess, specializes in crepes.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dinner: ``L'Express, which is French. And the Whitloff, which
is Belgian.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  People-watching: ``Mont-Royal Park on Sunday. (In warm
weather) they have `Tam-tam,' an event where people play drums for
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Howard Pousner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
