<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2695 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-SKUBE04-COX     04-01 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A doctor poet muses on living's debt to the dead
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Where Water Begins. By John Stone. Louisiana State University
Press. $12.95 paperback. 88 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, medical students at Emory University pay solemn
respects to those who have given their bodies to science.
Posthumous volunteers, theirs are the cadavers that anatomy
students live with _ so to speak _ in most intimate ways. Organs
can be held in the hand, parts without a purpose, and examined
minutely. The body's interior can be seen in all its intricacy,
from the wiring to the plumbing. No privilege, surely, is greater
than to open the chest cavity and to behold there the heart that
pumped blood from first breath to last, and now rests.
</P>
<P>
   The students call their commemoration a Service of Reflection
and Gratitude, and about 10 years ago they asked John Stone,
cardiologist by training, poet by nature, to write a few lines for
the occasion. ``It's hard to write a commissioned poem,'' Stone was
saying the other day. ``You can't be sure it's going to be worth a
damn.''
</P>
<P>
   The poem, collected in Stone's newest book, ``Where Water
Begins,'' is titled ``Elegy and Affirmation.'' The words, looking
both backward and forward, compress much into a short space, like
the poem itself:
</P>
<P>
   Together we are grateful, for we know
</P>
<P>
   the privilege it is to touch another,
</P>
<P>
   whether in the name of science or love.
</P>
<P>
   The touching here has been made up of both.
</P>
<P>
   By their extraordinary gifts
</P>
<P>
   these dead have taught the living how to touch.
</P>
<P>
   Through them we touch the body of the world.
</P>
<P>
   The poem is written in five-beat lines, a form used by
Shakespeare, and Stone hears ``extraordinary'' as two words. Poetry
works by the associations the ear will make, not all of them
immediate. Stone's many admirers know that one of his abiding
themes since the death of his wife, Lu, in 1991, has been the sense
of permanent loss. ``Death is one of the great preoccupations of
the poet,'' he says. But read his work closely and you will also
find a celebration of life _ of life quietly, often humorously
affirmed.
</P>
<P>
   A friend had to point out for me the full extent of this. In a
poem titled ``Big Creek'' Stone writes the simple line, ``She will
not be coming back,'' which could be read as resignation, as
unwilling acceptance, even as despair. And then, in the next
stanza, he writes, ``We are of this world / and not of that.''
</P>
<P>
   In my friend's words, ``He makes a very clear distinction
between life and death, and it is our responsibility to live'' _ to
remember, and yet to carry on. For writers, and not just poets,
certain rhythms and tonalities register on the ear. A note is
struck just so and the ear scrambles to make a connection.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Elegy and Affirmation,'' Stone writes as usual in a minor
key. Musicians know there are things that can be better said in the
minor keys, not just night thoughts but intimations of the numinous
and the sublime. Without forced sentiment, Stone expresses in
``Elegy and Affirmation'' a gravity at once personal and
collective. ``These dead have taught the living'' _ the words are
deceptively simple, but they call up other words written once to
suit an occasion. (``A few appropriate remarks,'' the invitation
suggested, the greater interest being on a keynote address that
would last three hours.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It is for us the living, rather, to be dedicated here to the
unfinished work. . . .'' We commemorate, that is, ``those who gave
the last full measure of devotion'' so that we might know our own
purposes better.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was, of course, different. But at Gettysburg the
most poetic of our presidents spoke less of the dead than of the
living, and did so in a language whose plainness is only apparent.
We owe the past not just homage but, even more, dedication anew.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, who has taught at Emory's medical school since 1968,
affirms even as he remembers. He writes of common experience _ a
trip to the mountains with a pair of friends (``two Jacks and a
Jill''), gunning a car up a gravel incline, water gurgling from a
cabin's kitchen tap, pulling on ``clean socks and last night's
jeans'' _ because it is the experience of the living. If the deeper
part of that experience is love and loss, its hard ground is that
we lived them fully.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
