<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2696 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-FLESH04-COX     04-01 0466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FLESH04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Getting an education about sex and power
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Book smarts can't help you graduate from ``The School of
Flesh.'' In this cool-hot French drama of sexual obsession, based
on a Yukio Mishima novel, Isabelle Huppert plays Dominique, a
wealthy, single Parisian whose life changes when she steps into a
bar one night and locks eyes with a hustler named Quentin (Vincent
Martinez).
</P>
<P>
   He services male and female customers, but as the frumpy
transvestite bar owner Chris (Vincent Lindon) tells Dominique,
Quentin likes women better. ``Paying can be fun,'' Chris assures
her. ``You can always swap roles.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique and Quentin do, many times, in a dance that becomes as
much about power as sex. When Dominique invites Quentin to live
with her, a friend kiddingly calls her a sugar daddy. But Dominique
loses the upper hand, developing an infatuation that reduces her to
helpless, raging tears. Quentin happily exploits her weakness, like
the spoiled kid he is.
</P>
<P>
   Quentin is an erotic vortex around which many people spin,
including an older male attorney who warns Dominique to ``count the
silver,'' and Chris, whose loyalty slowly shifts from the hustler
to the older woman. The cast also includes Marthe Keller as a
wealthy acquaintance of Dominique's, who plays a role instrumental
in Quentin's final, spectacular but somehow inevitable act of
betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Benoit Jacquot (``A Single Girl''), ``School'' is
smartly edited, trusting us to keep up with it, never delivering a
scene that feels contrived or cliched. The movie's tone is the
epitome of French sophistication, refusing to be scandalized by
sexuality but never underestimating its irrational power.
</P>
<P>
   Huppert, that grand sphinx of French cinema, has sometimes
seemed too aloof in her films _ a radiant but chilly center. Here
her poise works beautifully as she plays a woman secure enough to
venture into dangerous new territory, but whose wealth and wisdom
can't help a bit when passion infects her.
</P>
<P>
   With his off-kilter looks and rude smile, Martinez makes an
object of desire who's as engaging as he is infuriating. To the
film's credit, the character is as complex as Dominique's, capable
of ridiculous jealous fits one moment and cruel calculations the
next. ``The School of Flesh'' reminds us that, in matters of the
heart (or the groin at least), growing up can be a process that
lasts a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ``The School of Flesh''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Isabelle Huppert and Vincent Martinez. Rated R for
language and strong sexuality. In French with subtitles. 1 hour, 41
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A smart, cool-hot drama of sexual obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
