<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2701 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-GOLF04-COX     04-01 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-GOLF04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tour guides: Two reporters' views of the game of golf and its
masterly practitioners
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Other reporters are often jealous of columnist/author John
Feinstein (``A March to Madness,'' ``A Season on the Brink'') when
they see him at golf tournaments. Does he really work for a living
when he isn't counting how many chairs Bobby Knight tosses in a
season? When are we going to see him open a laptop and start typing
something?
</P>
<P>
   Well, now we know what Feinstein was doing in 1998. He spent the
year catching the main characters of golf in their most
entertaining, enlightening moments during the major championships.
Feinstein's ``The Majors'' is a wonderful follow-up to his
best-selling ``A Good Walk Spoiled.'' It's not often that you get
to feel as though you're eavesdropping on history.
</P>
<P>
   For Georgia golf fans who believe the Masters Tournament is the
center of the universe, ``The Majors'' is a great way to get ready
for Augusta's azaleas and annual Sunday agony on the back nine.
Feinstein describes last year's drama with such detail, you can
almost feel the energy rushing through winner Mark O'Meara and
leaving the disappointed David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Though Feinstein can't break his habit of tweaking his most
loathed sports agency, the International Management Group, and its
relationship with Tiger Woods every once in a while, who cares?
Nobody likes IMG, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   In ``A Good Walk Spoiled,'' Feinstein focused on lesser-known
characters such as Paul Goydos and Brian Henninger. ``The Majors''
looks at more familiar players _ specifically Duval and Fred
Couples _ and also brings us closer to tour players, including Brad
Faxon, Jim Furyk, Scott McCarron and Jay Haas.
</P>
<P>
   People who don't appreciate Duval's penchant for privacy, as he
hides behind his Oakley sunglasses, should understand the situation
a bit better after Feinstein's look at the former Georgia Tech
player, who lost a three-stroke lead on the back nine at Augusta
last year. Duval's turbulent childhood _ a brother died of a blood
disease after David was an unsuccessful bone marrow donor; his
parents fought constantly on their way to a divorce _ helped shape
his semi-loner personality. Duval sought shelter from the turmoil
on the golf course and to this day still gets great enjoyment from
playing alone.
</P>
<P>
   Some things revealed in the book that haven't been highly
publicized:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Duval was dropped by IMG agent Hughes Norton when Woods came
along. In the long run, it was a break for Duval. And Norton was
recently fired by Woods, and by Greg Norman before him.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Duval was up to 226 pounds before he started losing weight in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  In 1993, Duval missed getting his PGA Tour card by about
$2,000 because at the last minute the purse for the Nike Tour
Championship, which he won, was decreased from $250,000 to
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Justin Leonard's caddie, Bob Riefke, detailed his conversation
with Matt Kuchar's father/caddie, Peter, when paired with them
again at the U.S. Open following a distracting round at the
Masters. Not surprisingly, Peter Kuchar, after being told the
specific five or six occasions where Leonard was distracted,
basically acted as though Riefke was imagining it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  On the tour Couples is pretty much branded as an airhead _ and
sometimes does and says thing to justify the label _ but through
Feinstein's observations he comes off with a lot more substance.
Especially evident is Couples' character regarding his relationship
with his wife, Thais, during her battle with breast cancer. To read
Feinstein's account, you realize that while there certainly are
better intellectuals on the PGA Tour, there probably is no better
human being.
</P>
<P>
   David Owen's ``The Making of the Masters,'' which is subtitled
``Clifford Roberts, Augusta National and Golf's Most Prestigious
Golf Tournament,'' seems more concerned with offering
counterattacks on other Masters books than with establishing its
own identity. Despite that mind-set, Owen, a staff writer for The
New Yorker and a contributing editor to Golf Digest, uncovers some
interesting anecdotes and some new information.
</P>
<P>
   He reports that Augusta National's par three course, the
experimental area for the bent grass transformation that eventually
occurred on the big course greens in 1980, has a new strain of
Bermuda grass on some greens that might be implemented eventually
for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Owen contradicts author Curt Sampson's claim in his book, ``The
Masters,'' that Augusta National changed its rules, no longer
inviting the Canadian Open champion after black golfer Charlie
Sifford, an American, won it in 1962. Owen contended that Augusta
National at the time merely ``had a policy of inviting Canadian
winners of the Canadian Open'' and reminded that it wasn't until
1972 that the eligibility requirements were changed to invite all
winners of PGA Tour-sanctioned events.
</P>
<P>
   A humorous incident is presented that emphasizes how the late
Clifford Roberts, as Augusta National chairman, didn't let the
rules slide for anyone. He noticed Charlie Yates, a longtime
member, walking through the clubhouse one day in shorts and asked
him what he had planned for the day. When Yates said he was playing
golf, Roberts asked, ``Where?''
</P>
<P>
   When Yates returned from the locker room, he was wearing long
pants.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   The Majors. By John Feinstein. Little, Brown. $24.50. 472 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A captivating look at some of the masters of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Making of the Masters. By David Owen. Simon &AMP; Schuster. $25.
289 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Some interesting tidbits.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley is a sports writer for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
