<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ARTS AREN'T JUST FOR THE RICH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The thing that really got me was when Alma
Robinson said, ``I was thinking about this. It's time for the arts
to give something back. What do we do for poor people?''
</P>
<P>
   Usually we think of arts organizations as beggars holding out
tin cups for funding. Robinson, executive director of California
Lawyers for the Arts (CLA), a group that provides legal services
for artists, has a different view of the arts in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``One out of 11 jobs in San Francisco is in the arts, whether
it's corporate or nonprofit, advertising or fashion design,
multimedia or graphic design,'' she says. ``The arts are a
multimillion-dollar industry.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does a socially responsible industry do? One thing it
can do is provide apprenticeships, jobs, education and support to
people coming off welfare, and that's just what the CLA's Arts
Industry Employment Initiative will do.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, people will have a chance to get off welfare and work
behind the scenes in theater, opera, music and museums _ in costume
departments, front offices, computer work, whatever there is.
Welfare recipients aren't so different from you and me. They want
interesting jobs, too.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when I first met Robinson and her associates, the
thing that intrigued me was they were designing a welfare-to-work
program that treated the poor with respect _ as people with talents
for more than pushing a broom and interests in arts beyond the art
of survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, people pooh-poohed this and said `They
wouldn't be interested in the arts.' That isn't the case,'' said
Robinson, who has 18 years experience at CLA, a Stanford University
law degree and a background writing for the defunct Washington Star
in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Her reporter instincts show. She didn't assume anything about
welfare recipients. She surveyed dozens of them about their
talents, experiences and interests in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've found a man with 18 years experience as a professional
musician. We're looking for these people.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't need that much experience. You just have to be over
21, live in San Francisco and receive Temporary Aid to Needy
Families, commonly called welfare. Recipients of General Assistance
or SSI are ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   The program developer is Nanette Hogan, a career counselor with
a master's degree in education from Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I find talking to clients is that they have a lot of
talents in the arts, but they're pushed into jobs they're just not
interested in,'' Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, Hogan and the CLA have lined up an impressive array of
nonprofit arts groups to take their apprentices. You realize how
huge and diverse the arts industry is in San Francisco when you
look at the list: Intersection for the Arts, Galleria de la Raza,
the Exploratorium, the San Francisco Opera, the Bayview Opera, the
San Francisco Jazz Festival, the Wajumbe Cultural Institute, the
SOMA Art Festival, Yerba Buena Center for the Arts, the Mission
Cultural Center, the San Francisco Girls Chorus, the Precita Eyes
Mural Arts Center and the San Francisco Mime Troupe.
</P>
<P>
   CLA needs more corporations and private companies with
arts-related jobs to take apprentices. The city is loaded with
fashion operations, Web designers and graphic designers. So far CLA
has signed up only the architectural firm of Simon Martin-Vegue
Winkelstein Moris.
</P>
<P>
   CLA will pay 87 percent of an apprentice's salary and the
company will get an $8,000 tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   CLA has a six-year track record of training and placing
disadvantaged high school kids in arts apprenticeships and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Groups like CLA are not rich, and giving back to the community
costs money. Still, the cost of a three-month apprenticeship works
out to $4,750, which is cheap by job-training standards, especially
since it includes college credit courses.
</P>
<P>
   The project is supported by the Private Industry Council and the
Department of Public Services. Planning grants were provided by the
Mayor's Office of Community Development, the San Francisco
Foundation and the Institute for a Civil Society.
</P>
<P>
   The latter is a Boston foundation that seeks out worthy
community development organizations to fund _ much as the MacArthur
Foundation seeks out individuals for its so-called genius grants.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes genius lies in simplicity and common sense. The best
way to get people off welfare is to help them find work they're
interested in. Then support them in it.
</P>
<P>
   Then connect the work directly to classes, so they can learn the
things they need to know. Most important, perhaps, is to give poor
people a long-term view of a job, and the kind of networks you need
to _ well _ network.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's life with a future people haven't thought about,'' as
Hogan put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can find kindred spirits, people who are creative and
hours that are a little more flexible,'' Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
   That's what many San Franciscans want. So why can't the poorest
have a shot at it?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
