<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2730 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOKIES-FORTUNE-FILM-     04-01 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKIES-FORTUNE-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN OH, SO FAMILIAR FRONT PORCH VIEW OF THE DEEP SOUTH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A proper Southern lady knows what to do when she finds a
relative upstairs in bed with a bullet through her brain and the
pistol still dangling from her right hand. When this happens to
Camille Dixon (Glenn Close, dressed like a blend of Blanche DuBois,
Isadora Duncan and a Talbot's catalog cover) in Robert Altman's new
film, ``Cookie's Fortune,'' she simply rearranges things to make it
look like murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aunt Jewel did not commit suicide,'' she says to her painfully
passive sister, Cora (Julianne Moore). ``Nobody in this family
commits suicide. Suicide is a disgrace. Only crazy people commit
suicide.'' And just to be safe, Camille actually eats the suicide
note. It's another quiet Easter weekend in Holly Springs, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of things about Holly Springs seem familiar. But then I
grew up in Vincent, Ala., population 1,700 or so, where ``y'all's''
is an accepted plural possessive, supper is served during the
network news and summer starts in April. Altman, whose hometown is
the very metropolitan Kansas City, Mo., got a lot of things about
small Southern towns right, but then his screenwriter, Anne Rapp,
once lived in Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   That's clear from the beginning of the film, in which the
nighttime streets of Holly Springs are silent, except for the
ceaseless chirping of crickets, and dark, except for the lights in
the windows of the red brick First Presbyterian Church, where
Camille is earnestly rehearsing the cast of the Easter play.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same way at Calvary Baptist in Vincent, and at the
town's other churches, where prayer meeting, choir practice and the
like could eat up as many nights a week as theater, work-related
events and restaurant dinners do in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The events in ``Cookie's Fortune,'' in fact, depend on an
authentic small-Southern-town tradition: traveling serving dishes.
The only reason Camille drops by the house of Jewel Mae Orcutt
(Patricia Neal), better known as Cookie, is to get ``Mother's fruit
salad bowl'' for Easter dinner.
</P>
<P>
   When I was growing up, every pie plate and casserole dish in
town had a piece of masking tape on the bottom with the owner's
name scribbled on it. This wasn't always a matter of borrowing and
lending; people were forever taking their deviled eggs or string
beans or banana cream pie with vanilla wafers to church socials,
school functions and after-funeral meals. Only a fool would send a
good dish off without ID. And returning the dish was a good excuse
for paying an unannounced visit to the owner.
</P>
<P>
   One thing in the movie rang untrue: fanning. And the friendships
between black and white residents seemed suspiciously idealized. I
can't speak for the state of race relations back home, because I've
been away (in New York, that paragon of racial tranquillity) for
decades, but I (italics)can(end italics) speak for the state of
air-conditioning. You just don't see Southern women fanning
themselves anymore, the way Ms. Close's character does, because
contemporary Southerners live in a bubble of air-conditioned
houses, cars, stores and churches.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be different in Holly Springs, a real town of about
7,000, which sometimes seems considerably more genteel than my
hometown. Installing central air in one of the town's historic
houses (Camille and her sister live in the Yellow Fever House)
might be considered a sign of real disrespect.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Close is not the only star of ``Cookie's Fortune,'' of
course, but this time Altman's use of an all-star ensemble doesn't
feel like a strained series of cameos. In a town like Holly
Springs, of course, the local catfish supplier would look like Lyle
Lovett. Of course the handsome, tough-talking police investigator
from out of town would be Courtney B. Vance. Of course the dim,
young sheriff's deputy would be Chris O'Donnell; he was probably
the guy who escorted the Homecoming Queen onto the field in high
school, too.
</P>
<P>
   Small-town Southerners take pride in being colorful. Otherwise,
they wouldn't use metaphors like ``knee-high to a grasshopper.''
</P>
<P>
   Being a character is very different from being crazy, however,
and ``Cookie's Fortune'' hits the nail on the head with Camille's
horror at the prospect of anyone's thinking there is insanity in
her family. My mother still refers to a great-aunt's long-ago
mental illness as the time ``when Aunt Madeline wasn't herself.''
</P>
<P>
   When I was a child, the worst insult you could deliver was to
joke that someone should be ``sent to Tuscaloosa.'' The city of
Tuscaloosa was and is the home of the main campus of the University
of Alabama, but the reference was to its neighbor Bryce Hospital,
the state psychiatric facility. New Yorkers may say that sort of
thing about Bellevue, but not with the same fervor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The only suicide I ever heard of in my hometown took place after
I'd gone away to college. It was one of the two local doctors, a
woman, which made it easy for everyone to distance themselves from
it. That's what happens to women who go to college and concentrate
on careers rather than on their families.
</P>
<P>
   Just as important, that's what happens to people who get too big
for their britches. In big cities, sending the children to
psychiatrists can be seen as just one more way of helping them to
turn out perfect. Going into psychotherapy yourself is a
self-improvement project _ like joining a gym, learning Italian,
using a personal shopper.
</P>
<P>
   That attitude would never do in the Holly Springses of this
world. There, admitting to neurosis is admitting to
dissatisfaction, and being dissatisfied means you aspire to
something you don't have, and aspiration is considered bad taste.
</P>
<P>
   The best I can figure, this goes back about 130 years, to
Reconstruction, when only Yankees and scalawags like Rhett Butler
had money. Not having anything nice, and being proud of it, became
the norm. But I'm basing this entirely on Melanie Hamilton's
character in ``Gone With the Wind,'' so, as we say back home, don't
mind me.
</P>
<P>
   Because of anti-aspiration sentiment, being both down-to-earth
and self-deprecating is crucial in small Southern towns. That's why
in ``Cookie's Fortune'' you will see Liv Tyler as Emma Duvall, the
most beautiful girl in town, driving a pick-up truck and fishing
with the boys with a bottle of Wild Turkey in the back pocket of
her cut-offs.
</P>
<P>
   That's why a plaque beside the liquor-store cash register says
``On this site in 1897 nothing happened.'' That's why Jack Palmer
(Donald Moffat), the only lawyer in Holly Springs, is pushing his
luck when during a Scrabble game he begins explaining the
Indo-European origins of the word ``awe.''
</P>
<P>
   And it may be why Cookie can get away with living in a house
with a spiral staircase and stained-glass windows. In her old age,
she runs around the house in a sloppy Mississippi State sweatshirt
and considers Willis Richland (Charles S. Dutton), a black man who
lives in her guest house, her best friend.
</P>
<P>
   People in towns like Holly Springs and Vincent make mistakes
like everybody else, of course; it's just that nobody talks about
it. Which brings us back to deception, the only way that occurs to
Camille to deal with Cookie's embarrassing demise. Camille even
thinks she can get away with lying to God. After Willis is
mistakenly arrested for Cookie's murder, she kneels beside her bed
and prays for him: ``May God rest his soul if he committed this
terrible crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the lies in Holly Springs unravel near the end of the
film. A secret about one character's parentage is uncovered when
the sheriff's office is checking blood types. Another character,
who had supposedly died while doing missionary work in Africa, is
revealed to have met his end in a button-factory accident in
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still dying to know what Reverend Keller's transgression was
when he was removed from the First Baptist Church back when I was
12. But we don't talk about that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
