<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ADMINISTRATION ANNOUNCES SCHOOL GRANT PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Grants totaling more than $300 million will be
awarded to 50 towns and cities this summer to help them provide
safer schools and better learning environments for students, the
Clinton administration announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, communities seeking funds must submit a plan
that includes the involvement of local school administrators, law
enforcement officials, community organizations, mental health and
medical counselors, families and students.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said the problems of school violence
and underperforming students must be addressed with a
community-wide approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Law enforcement alone can't do the job,'' she said at her
weekly news conference. ``But when communities work together, we
can prevent violence in all its forms before it occurs and give our
young people a safer, healthier environment in which to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the program's administrators _ who are from the
Departments of Justice, Education, and Health and Human Services _
began accepting applications Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   She said awards will range up to $3 million a year for urban
school districts, up to $2 million a year for suburban schools and
up to $1 million a year for rural and tribal schools.
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard Riley said activities likely to be
funded include after-school programs, teen courts, the hiring of
security personnel, mentoring programs, anti-drug classes, home
nurse visits and alternative education, which consists of programs
tailored to problem students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Building safe schools depends on building strong
communities,'' Riley said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said the program, known as the Safe Schools/Healthy
Students Initiative, was conceived last October after fatal
shootings at schools in Paducah, Ky.; Jonesboro, Ark., and
Springfield, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must do all we can to prevent another tragedy from taking
the life for one of young people,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
