<SLUG> BC-FILM-RELAX-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOT MUCH NEW IN `RELAX . . . IT'S JUST SEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The independent film world seems intent on producing only two
types of stories: violent scam movies and the kind of romantic sex
comedies in which there is a perfect balance of gay, straight and
ethnic characters who hang out together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relax ... .It's Just Sex,'' which was shown at last year's
Seattle International Film Festival, falls into the second
category. It's a gay '90s ``Big Chill'' clone that settles into the
same category as ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' and several
other recent light-hearted gay-themed friendship films.
</P>
<P>
   Director P.J. Castellaneta, who made his film debut with
``Together Alone,'' has crafted another movie in which Los Angeles
is an equally important main character. In this smoggy realm live a
diverse group of 20-somethings who are trying to find their niche
in the big world.
</P>
<P>
   Vincey Sauris (Mitchell Anderson) is a gay playwright looking
for Mr. Right. Tara (Jennifer Tilly) is a kind of surrogate mother
to the gang and she wants to have a baby with her boyfriend, Gus
(Timothy Paul Perez). Gus is commitment-shy and he's already
reeling from the shock that his brother Javi is HIV-positive. Buzz
(T.C. Carson), a black artist who has just begun to date Vincey is
new to the group.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's longtime lesbian couple, Megan (Serena Scott
Thomas, sister of Kristin) and Sarina (Cynda Williams), who have
just broken up because Megan's attracted to a guy named Jared
(Billy Wirth). Sarina rebounds with the needy Robin Moon (Lori
Petty), and soon everything is in chaos because the viewer can
barely keep all these characters and relationships, well, straight.
</P>
<P>
   Though the film opens with a clever ``newsreel'' introduction
that playfully tweaks gay stereotypes, it also enforces them as
well. After awhile, the movie feels as desperate as the friends as
they climb in and out of bed with new potential partners and
desperately cling to the boyfriend or girlfriend they've already
managed to snag. They're afraid of love and getting close but they
can't think of anything else either.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that truly elevates ``Relax ... It's Just Sex''
out of the ordinary is a startlingly scary scene in which Vincey is
the victim of a hate crime. His rage and ultimate revenge upon one
of the thugs is a unique moment in gay cinema. It also shifts the
tone of the film and, from that point on, even extended family
doesn't feel very comforting or soothing.
</P>
<P>
   Castellaneta tries to introduce some new twists, but the film's
philosophy is finally the same old thing: we all need friends to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Relax ... It's Just Sex. Directed and written by P.J.
Castelleneta. Cast: Jennifer Tilly, Mitchell Anderson, Lori Petty,
T.C. Carson, Serena Scott Thomas. Jour de Fete Films. 106 minutes.
Unrated with sexual content, language, violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1631EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
