<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-UNMADE-BEDS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`UNMADE BEDS' IS SAD, BLEAK COMEDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This fascinating sad ``revisionist'' documentary is a
contradiction in terms. On one hand, it's a portrait of four lonely
people looking for love and, on the other, a rather cruel expose on
how they go about finding it.
</P>
<P>
   British filmmaker Nicholas Barker has made a ``documentary'' in
that the four people he uses are telling their real-life stories.
But he's helped them rewrite their stories to accommodate both the
screen and themselves. In short, he's directing them in screen
versions of their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   It's an iffy concept that sometimes strikes a nerve and, on
other occasions, feels stilted and exposes the ``actors'' as true
amateurs. Back in 1995, Barker hired a crew to scout the New York
City personals ads for potential candidates. The search took
several months to find four people who fit the requirements Barker
wanted for his film. He then wrote scripts based on incidents that
were concurrently happening in their lives.
</P>
<P>
   The four people are very different and also quite alike. Brenda
is a divorced mother of a 16-year-old daughter. She's tough and
jaded and certain about what she wants in a man _ money. Michael is
40 and has been looking for a wife for 15 years through the
personals. He's disillusioned because women won't look at him
twice. Why? Because he's short. Aimee is attractive and has a great
job. She moved from Kansas to Manhattan with her best friend. Her
goal is to marry by the time she's 30 but she weighs 225 pounds.
Finally, Mikey is 54 and has lived the life of a carefree swinging
single for years. He's bitter and angry toward women in general and
lives in the past.
</P>
<P>
   These characters prowl the city looking for love and yet
rebuffing most of the people they meet. Ultimately, they emerge as
funny and sometimes abrasive and self-loathing, but most of all
they're vain and deluded about their own attributes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unmade Beds,'' as a result, is a very black and bleak comedy
and it pushes and strains at the boundaries of voyeuristic bad
taste. But Barker swears he has never been a director who prides
himself on good taste.
</P>
<P>
   Barker's camera peeps into the windows of Manhattan residents,
creating a ``Rear Window'' scenario by prying into people's
privacy. It's an unsettling tool that both embarrasses us and
heightens the impact of the plight of his four single souls. As we
watch couples and other singles happily readying for bed, a night
out or even nakedly making love, we empathize more readily with
this often quite unlikable quartet whose desperate existences
become raw reminders of the unavoidable human truths _ aging and
loneliness.
</P>
<P>
   Unmade Beds. Directed and written by Nicholas Barker. Cast:
Brenda Monte, Michael De Stephano, Aimee Copp, Mikey Russo. Chelsea
Pictures. 92 minutes. Unrated with nudity, language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
