<HEADER>
A2746 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT     04-01 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE IN REVIVAL CITY  
 STAR SEARCH  
 YANKEE SCRIBES  
 FLAVOR DU JOUR  
 INNOVATIVE TROUPE DISBANDS  
 ETC. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JESSE MCKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wanted: a man. Knowledge of trouble, trombones (76)
and River City required. Broadway experience optional.
</P>
<P>
   The call is out for the perfect Harold Hill, the sweetly slick
protagonist of ``The Music Man.'' The musical is scheduled for a
Broadway revival this fall, but the push to find the right man for
the part is on now.
</P>
<P>
   Actors who have been mentioned for the role include Patrick
Swayze and Steve Martin. Michael David, one of the show's
producers, said that although producers had made tentative
inquiries to about a dozen people, only two formal offers have been
made. (He would not say to whom.) Production members involved in
negotiations said that Alec Baldwin, an early favorite, declined
because of scheduling conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   And while producers say there is no need for panic _ rehearsals
are not scheduled to begin until mid-August _ there is a need for
speed.
</P>
<P>
   By this time every spring, the three Broadway landlords _ the
Shuberts, the Nederlanders and the Jujamcyn Organization _ are
already booking for fall. The Gershwin Theater, owned by the
Nederlanders, is considered a likely home for ``The Music Man.''
But David said that the project, in the works for two years, would
be postponed unless a star was found soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The eye of the needle in this case is very small,'' David
said. ``If the elements are not in place, we'd be foolish to
proceed right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The production window is also limited because the director,
Susan Stroman, is scheduled to begin work on another Broadway-bound
show, a musical, ``The Night They Raided Minsky's,'' in early
December.
</P>
<P>
   Trailer Park Vacancies
</P>
<P>
   Darren Lee Cole, the producer of ``Killer Joe,'' Tracy Letts'
blood-soaked thriller, said this week that he was hunting for a
star to complete the new cast he is forming to keep the
five-month-old production alive.
</P>
<P>
   Barring his finding one, the show will close on April 18. ``If
we can get the right cast together, we'll make a run of it,'' he
said. The show's box office receipts at the SoHo Playhouse are
running at break-even, said Cole, who is also considering runs in
Chicago, San Francisco and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   An American Accent
</P>
<P>
   After a season with considerable hand-wringing over the dearth
of American plays, the schedules for the summer festivals are
packed with Yankee scribes.
</P>
<P>
   New York Stage and Film, for example, in Poughkeepsie, N.Y.,
will present the premiere of ``Chesapeake,'' by Lee Blessing (``A
Walk in the Woods'').
</P>
<P>
   Max Mayer will direct and Mark Linn-Baker will star.
</P>
<P>
   The festival will also include a workshop production of
``Current Events,'' the second play by David Marshall Grant
(``Snakebit'').
</P>
<P>
   This comes after word that John Guare, Warren Leight and Kenneth
Lonergan will each present new plays at the Williamstown Theater
Festival this summer, though they will probably have to fight for
attention with the likes of Gwyneth Paltrow and Ethan Hawke, who
will be appearing in ``As You Like It'' and ``Camino Real,''
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Soap Opera to Stage
</P>
<P>
   For the last several years Anna Friel has been a common sight in
the London tabloids, evidence of a fascination dating from her role
on the steamy nighttime television drama ``Brookside.'' But she has
remained little known stateside.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has a clue who I am,'' Ms. Friel said. ``It's really
lovely.''
</P>
<P>
   That is about to change. With several films nearing release, Ms.
Friel, 22, is the flavor du jour in Hollywood circles, a status
confirmed by her inclusion on a Vanity Fair cover.
</P>
<P>
   But currently she is playing Alice, a mysterious ingenue, in
``Closer,'' at the Music Box Theater in Manhattan. The role is her
professional stage debut and, she said, an enormous learning
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I got the job over classically trained actresses,''
Ms. Friel said with a smile. ``I was terrified.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she's an amateur. A former pre-law student raised near
Manchester, England, Ms. Friel's first major break came at 16, when
she was cast as a confused teen-ager named Beth Jordache on
``Brookside.'' That led to more film and television work, but no
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Now that she has made the leap, Ms. Friel said she would like to
try the stage again. ``I'm loving it,'' she said. ``But I told the
cast if I do anything wrong, tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   En Garde to Disband
</P>
<P>
   The announcement last week that Anne Hamburger would be the new
artistic director of La Jolla Playhouse in San Diego signaled the
death of one of New York's more innovative theater troupes, En
Garde Arts, which Ms. Hamburger founded in 1986. She says that the
company's board has decided to disband this summer after her
departure.
</P>
<P>
   En Garde was one of the first theater companies to devote itself
to site-specific theater, performing in spaces like the
then-dilapidated Victory Theater (``Crowbar'' in 1990) or a Hudson
River pier (``Stonewall'' in 1994). But in recent years, Ms.
Hamburger said, such sites have become harder to find. ``The real
estate boom, while great for the city, is not great for
site-specific work because not so many spaces are around anymore,''
Ms. Hamburger said, adding that production costs had soared.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was unsure whether she would undertake
site-specific works when she moves to the more conservative
environs of San Diego and to a large institutional theater.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ Irene Worth, in ``Ring Round the Moon'' at the Belasco
Theater, suffered a ``very mild stroke'' on Tuesday afternoon, said
Philip Rinaldi, a spokesman for the production. Her illness has
postponed the first preview from Thursday night to Friday night.
Marian Seldes will replace Ms. Worth in the interim.
</P>
<P>
   _ An adaptation of ``Molloy,'' Samuel Beckett's novel, will open
at the Irish Arts Center on May 6.
</P>
<P>
   _ After two years and a $5.5 million overhaul, Second Stage's
new theater opens Friday night in a former bank at Eighth Avenue
and 43rd Street with the first preview performance of ``That
Championship Season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
