   &UR; MUTFUND Quarterly &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-VALUE (Undated) _ Value managers have long shunned what
they view as overvalued growth stocks. Instead, they favor stocks
with lower price-to-earnings or other valuation ratios. But that
has lately brought grief for their shareholders, as stocks
relatively cheap by traditional measures continue to be clobbered
by the big growth companies. By Richard A. Oppel Jr. WITH GRAPHICS.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-PERFORMANCE (Undated) _ Although it's fun to see who's
hot and who's not among mutual fund managers each quarter, the real
value in the performance figures lies in the stock market
intelligence they can provide. Looking behind the numbers can help
reveal the overall market's strength or weakness. And a closer look
can help gauge the current mood and vulnerabilities of investors.
By Gretchen Morgenson. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-BOGUS-REPORT (Undated) _ The number of fund offerings
has exploded in recent years, and the excuses that fund companies
give for starting them grow flimsier each day. More and more
portfolios are tied to idiosyncratic stock indexes, obscure
industry subsectors and ever more esoteric investing styles. The
logical end? Following are excerpts from an imaginary annual
report. By Daniel Akst.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-PICKS (Undated) _ When it comes to picking among the
thousands of mutual funds out there, investors want a rating system
that separates the wheat from the chaff. Unfortunately, the most
popular rating services get only half of the equation. They do a
good job of pinpointing the chaff of the investing arena, but are
not much help in identifying the wheat. By Mark Hulbert. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-INTERNET (Undated) _ The mutual fund industry joined the
rush to the Internet over the last two years, and the move appears
to be benefiting both the fund companies and many of their
customers. By Abby Schultz. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-CLOSED-END (Undated) _ Investors looking to ride the
resurgent, although risky, emerging markets may want to consider
closed-end funds. Emerging-markets closed-end funds are up 6.4
percent, on average, so far this year. By Virginia Munger Kahn.
WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-INSURANCE (Undated) _ A few big insurers have got a deal
for you. Well, maybe. First, you pick one of their funds _ from
high-risk to mild-mannered, your choice. Then, for as little as 0.1
percent of the investment annually or possibly as much as 0.5
percent, these companies will guarantee that the money you put up
plus an annual gain of 4 or 5 percent, will always be there, no
matter how far the market plunges. On a $50,000 investment, then,
that guarantee would cost $50 to $250 a year. Sounds good, but
there is a catch: You have to die in order to collect on the
guarantee. What the companies are selling is life insurance tied to
your mutual funds. By Joseph B. Treaster. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-RETIRE (Undated) _ Despite some sharp ups and downs, the
bull market in large-capitalization stocks plowed forward through
the first quarter, confounding some money managers and rewarding
others. The story was no different for the five managers who have
built hypothetical retirement portfolios for The New York Times:
None of their portfolios lost money in the quarter, but only three
beat the average for diversified domestic equity funds, as tracked
by Lipper Inc. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-4MANAGERS (Undated) _ The managers of four of the
highest-ranked funds talked about what drove their performance and
looked ahead to the rest of the year. By Carole Gould.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL (Undated) _ Among portfolio managers who
specialize in buying shares of foreign companies, the most
successful in the first quarter were those who had researched and
cherry-picked their way through lesser-known equities, especially
the stocks hurt by the persistence of the Asian economic crisis and
Japan's deep recession. While international funds as a group rose
less than 1 percent in the quarter, many small-cap international
funds had double-digit gains. By Rick Gladstone.
</P>
<P>
   MUTFUND-TAX (Undated) _ Tax-managed mutual funds _ those that
seek to maximize after-tax gains rather than gross returns _ are
among the latest trends in the fund industry. More than half the 50
such funds were introduced after 1996, and combined assets in them
have grown from $3.19 billion to $15.36 billion over that period.
By Abby Schultz. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
