<HEADER>
A2749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOWNERS-FILM-REVIEW-N     04-01 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWNERS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE OUT-OF-TOWNERS': FEEBLE AND UNFOCUSED 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(lh) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goldie Hawn and Steve Martin are appealing performers, but none
of the energy, professionalism and gameness they display while
portraying a married couple facing problems galore in the remake of
``The Out-of-Towners'' can surmount the mess that surrounds them in
this misguided comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The 1970 Neil Simon screenplay that provided the so-called
inspiration for this excursion into relentlessly silly mediocrity
won no hosannas from the critics, but at least it had its sensate
creative fingers firmly on the pulse of an anarchic era when
municipal strikes frequently crippled New York City, muggers and
squirrels vied to top the census of wildlife in Central Park and
hijackers regularly turned flying into a literal diversion.
</P>
<P>
   But as rewritten by Marc Lawrence and directed by Sam Weisman,
who rewarded moviegoers with the disarming and funny ``George of
the Jungle,'' the new ``Out-of-Towners'' is so feeble and unfocused
as to make the Farrelly brothers of ``There's Something About
Mary'' appear to have suckled at the bosom of Aristophanes.
</P>
<P>
   Following in the footsteps of Jack Lemmon and Sandy Dennis in
the original ``Out-of-Towners,'' which was directed by Arthur
Hiller, Martin and Ms. Hawn play Henry and Nancy Clark. After 27
years of marriage, they are saying goodbye to their college-age
son, who is off to study abroad.
</P>
<P>
   A daughter is already living in New York City. Henry is about to
leave for New York for a job interview, and Nancy, who is feeling
alone and neglected in their expansive house in Ohio, decides to
come along, unaware that the distracted, defeated Henry has lost
his longtime job in advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Where ``The Out-of-Towners'' goes rapidly awry is in failing to
choose a comic focus and maintain it. The film never decides
whether it wants to be a story of the comic misadventures of a
couple on a trip to New York, a commentary on the perils of life in
the big city or a bittersweet romance about a long-married couple
facing an empty nest and rediscovering passionate love. As a
result, it flounders around all three.
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Hawn and Martin have to contend with a schizoid approach
to their portrayals as they are bedeviled by a plot that diverts
their flight to Boston and sends them without their luggage on a
tortuous trail to New York, where they are speedily robbed, denied
a hotel room, pursued by dogs and mounted police, blunder into a
sex therapy meeting in a church and a taxi involved in a bank
robbery, and are exposed while coupling on the grass outside Tavern
on the Green.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, they are sometimes characters, sometimes cartoons
and never credible comic creations. The same Nancy who clearly
yearns for some excitement in her marriage is the moron who
brandishes and loudly discusses Henry's shoe inserts and rash cream
when they occupy different aisles and seats on the plane that takes
them to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Nancy and Henry who can sensibly discuss their future
haven't got the brains to board the right train in Boston or to
handle a rented car without driving it through $2,200 worth of
crated seafood in the Fulton Fish Market. (They blithely walk away
from the damage and the car).
</P>
<P>
   The list of inconsistencies could be expanded, but the point is
that Henry and Nancy are two characters desperately in search of a
laugh track, and since ``The Out-of-Towners'' is supposed to be a
movie and not a sitcom Ms. Hawn and Martin are figuratively up the
Hudson without a paddle.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a saving grace to this film, it is John Cleese,
delivering another of his comic gems as Mersault, the snobbish
hotel manager who is as adept at publicly disdaining the
unfortunate and groveling before the privileged as he is at
privately cross-dressing in mink, earrings and spike heels and
dancing riotously to ``Bad Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   The small but noticeable role of the speechifying mayor is
credited to Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who carries it off as if to the
Gracie Mansion born.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE OUT-OF-TOWNERS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sam Weisman; written by Marc Lawrence, based on the
screenplay by Neil Simon; director of photography, John Bailey;
edited by Kent Beyda; music by Marc Shaiman; production designer,
Ken Adam; produced by Robert Cort, David Madden, Robert Evans and
Teri Schwartz; released by Paramount Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With: Steve Martin (Henry Clark), Goldie Hawn (Nancy Clark),
John Cleese (Mr. Mersault) and Mayor Rudolph Giuliani (himself). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 91 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Out-of-Towners'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes sexual situations, criminal acts, bodily
functions and a few impolite words.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1642EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2753 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-URGES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     04-01 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-URGES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`URGES:' FREE SPIRITS COPE WITH THE DEMANDS OF FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In our post-Monica, ``Something About Mary'' world, there are
fewer and fewer taboos, fewer and fewer rules about acceptable
behavior, and with a no-fault society, novelists have increasingly
focused on characters afflicted with rootlessness and a surfeit of
choices. The characters in this accomplished debut collection of
stories by Nathan Englander are an exception. Most of them are
Orthodox or Hasidic Jews, living within a ritual-bound world; they
struggle not with the fallout of too much freedom, but with the
strictures of their faith, with finding a balance between tradition
and independence, obedience and desire.
</P>
<P>
   In reading these stories, it's easy enough to see the influences
that have helped shape the work of the 29-year-old Englander. His
stories not only share the powerful mixture of allegory and
quotidian detail that Bernard Malamud pioneered, but they also owe
a decided debt to Isaac Bashevis Singer's magical narratives about
art and eros and the uncanny.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, however, Englander's voice is distinctively
his own _ daring, funny and exuberant, keenly attuned to both the
absurdities of life and its undertow of sadness and disappointment.
He's able to shift gears easily, moving from a dark, Russian fable
about writers condemned to death by Stalin (``The 27th Man'') to a
Marx Brothers-like farce about a woman willing to do anything to
get her husband to give her a divorce (``The Last One Way'').
</P>
<P>
   In many of the stories, the humor and sadness are welded
together into a seamless, Kafkaesque whole. In ``The 27th Man,'' a
young, aspiring writer finds himself sentenced to death along with
some of the most prominent Jewish authors in the Soviet Union; his
fate, the result perhaps of a clerical mistake, becomes the
occasion for a small literary masterpiece and some last-minute
collegial recognition. In ``The Tumblers,'' a group of Orthodox
Jews escape the transports to the Nazi death camps by posing as a
group of circus acrobats; their plight, the hero realizes, is ``no
more unbelievable than the reality from which they'd escaped, no
more unfathomable than the magic of disappearing Jews.''
</P>
<P>
   For Charles Morton Luger, the hero of ``The Gilgul of Park
Avenue,'' faith arrives as unexpectedly as one of Kafka's magical
transformations. Charles is sitting in a cab on Park Avenue when he
realizes that he has undergone a most strange and wonderful
metamorphosis; this WASPy financial analyst realizes, in a blinding
flash, that he is Jewish. He searches out a spiritual adviser from
Bolinas, Calif. _ a self-proclaimed rabbi, who tells Charles he
possesses an ancient Jewish soul and urges him to read ``The
Chosen'' by Chaim Potok and ``QB VII'' by Leon Uris. Charles'
snooty, bigoted wife thinks he is having a nervous breakdown _ or a
midlife crisis. ``Why couldn't you have turned into a vegan?'' she
wonders. ``Or a liberal Democrat?''
</P>
<P>
   Similar marital problems afflict many of Englander's heroes,
pointing up one of the few limitations of this collection _ a
tendency to portray women, uniformly, in story after story, as
selfish, demanding and narcissistic creatures, insensitive to their
husbands' spiritual and emotional needs. In ``Reunion,'' a woman
named Robin, fed up with her husband's embarrassing bouts of manic
depression, shrieks at him: ``Disappear or I'll have to kill you
for what you do to this family. I'll stab you to death right here
in front of the children, and that will really ruin their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Last One Way,'' a disaffected wife tells the matchmaker
who set her up with her husband that she'll end the marriage, even
if it means committing murder. In the title story, a woman refuses
to sleep with her husband until he persuades his rabbi to grant him
a special dispensation to have sex with a prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the strictures of Orthodox belief, the pragmatic
solutions of contemporary life _ like divorce, separation,
extramarital affairs or psychiatric counseling _ rarely occur to
these characters. They are forced to try to come to terms with
their problems within the framework of tradition, or make a rash
and radical break with all they have grown up believing.
</P>
<P>
   The hero of ``Reb Kringle'' _ a portly Orthodox Jew with a long
white beard _ finds himself in the unhappy situation of having to
play Santa Claus at a local department store in order to make ends
meet, or face the wrath of his practical wife. As he sees it, he
can betray his faith or his wife's wishes, choose faith or domestic
peace. As for Ruchama in ``The Wig,'' she finds herself torn
between the rule that married women must cut their hair, out of
modesty, and don a wig, and her own vain desire ``to arrive at shul
looking trim and with the long, beautiful hair of her youth.'' Her
solution is to bully a young delivery man into selling his flowing
locks, which she plans to fashion into a luxuriant (and highly
immodest) wig.
</P>
<P>
   When Englander turns from such parables to more
documentary-style narratives _ like the book's final story (``In
This Way We Are Wise''), which concerns an American visitor's
reaction to a bombing in Jerusalem _ the results are more mannered
and self-conscious. The lucid, almost transparent prose found in
the book's earlier pages turns turgid in this story (``My body
exorcises its charger of burning buildings, its icy-waters diver'')
just as the moral impetus, artfully submerged in Englander's other
tales, is bluntly set in boldface. All in all, a disappointing
conclusion to a volume that otherwise showcases this young writer's
bountiful and finely honed talents.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `FOR THE RELIEF OF UNBEARABLE URGES'
</P>
<P>
   By Nathan Englander
</P>
<P>
   205 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $22.
</P>
</TEXT>
