<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2755 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-PSYCHO-FILM-     04-01 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-PSYCHO-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGGING OUT THE HUMOR IN A SERIAL KILLER'S TALE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BRUCE WEBER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ During the 1980s, the unisex bathrooms at downtown
Manhattan clubs would get pretty crowded at the height of an
evening, but it was never this bad. Here on the set of ``American
Psycho,'' in the restroom of the nightclub that serves as a
stand-in for the Tunnel, what with the camera crew, the boom
operator and the lights, there was barely space for the elaborately
costumed extras _ girls in kitsch cocktail dresses and guys in
designer suits _ to slip into a stall for a good snort of cocaine.
(Actually, vitamin B powder.)
</P>
<P>
   The scene being filmed was a sharply satiric one. In it, two
appalling yuppies, played by Justin Theroux and Christian Bale,
wait outside a stall for their turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's this theory out now,'' says Theroux's character, an
already hyperventilating fellow on the verge of a breakdown, ``that
if you can catch AIDS virus through having sex with someone who is
infected, then you can also catch anything _ Alzheimer's, muscular
dystrophy, hemophilia, leukemia, diabetes. Dyslexia, for Christ's
sake.''
</P>
<P>
   To which Bale's character, Patrick Bateman, the serial killer
who is the film's protagonist, replies coolly, ``I'm not sure, guy,
but I don't think dyslexia is a virus.''
</P>
<P>
   The humor being aimed for _ a swipe at the blind narcissism of
the youthful privileged class during the Reagan 80s _ is crucial to
the success of the movie, which may have more prerelease bias to
overcome than any film in recent memory. The 1991 novel by the same
name, on which it is based, depicts scenes of sadistic violence
narrated by Bateman in a seemingly indifferent manner that by some
literal readings was perceived as amoral.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that many people who failed to recognize (or
consider) the satiric intent of the author, Bret Easton Ellis,
thought the disturbing work should not have even been published,
much less made into a movie. Should the film not succeed as the
black comedy and social commentary that its director, Mary Harron,
intends, it is likely to sink into the same swamp of outrage that
the novel did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name `American Psycho' conjures up horrific experience,''
said Edward R. Pressman, the film's producer. ``But the script has
made me confident that we can make a terrific film that a
mainstream audience can enjoy and tolerate, that will not be overly
violent or pornographic and that will sustain the wit of the book.
What came across in readings is how funny the film will be, and we
think that will surprise people.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's humor may be crucial as well for the career of Bale,
who is, at 25, a promising actor with a serious resume. Since
appearing, at age 14, in Steven Spielberg's ``Empire of the Sun,''
he has worked with directors like Kenneth Branagh in ``Henry V'',
Gillian Armstrong in ``Little Women,'' Jane Campion in ``Portrait
of a Lady'' and Todd Haynes in ``Velvet Goldmine.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, with the opening on Friday of ``Metroland,'' an
independent film shot two years ago by Philip Saville and based on
an early Julian Barnes novel, Bale has his first lead role as an
adult, playing a man in his early 30s in the throes of questioning
the life choices that have turned him from the rakish artist he was
as a youth into a domesticated suburban husband and father. (Emily
Watson plays his wife.)
</P>
<P>
   In May, he will appear as Demetrius in Michael Hoffman's starry
production of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   But none of these roles is likely to draw scrutiny like his
portrayal of Patrick Bateman, a rich, vacuous 26-year-old obsessed
with designer clothing, hip restaurants and exercise who has a
nasty compulsion to maim and disembowel his workplace rivals, his
ex-girlfriends and the occasional child, homosexual, homeless man,
prostitute and pet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something nice about all the red flags this project
sends up,'' Bale said, dropping, for the sake of an interview, the
American accent he has maintained throughout the filming, both on
and off camera. ``I got all kinds of messages on my answering
machine, people saying `This is career suicide, Christian.'''
</P>
<P>
   There is, he admitted, a desire on his part to flout
expectations and succeed. ``But it's not at all that I want to do
something that's shocking,'' he said. ``This is not an in-depth
psychological analysis of what drives someone to become a serial
killer. When Mary first sent me the script, I hadn't read the book,
and that's what I thought it was, so I didn't want to do it. But I
found the script really funny, and I called her and told her so.
She said, `Thank God, you find it funny.'''
</P>
<P>
   With an aquiline nose and chiseled jaw, Bale is handsome in a GQ
kind of way, especially in the custom-made suits by Cerruti he
wears for the film. (Many other designers whose names dot the novel
donated period clothes for other characters to wear, but none
wanted to be associated with a character like Bateman.)
</P>
<P>
   Bale, born in Wales, was a child actor encouraged by a
grandfather who was a stand-up comedian and ventriloquist, and
parents who, as he describes them, were both resourceful and
footloose. His mother was once a dancer and a circus clown; his
father was a pilot for a time; later, he managed his son's
burgeoning career.
</P>
<P>
   His first job was in the theater, in London, in a comedy, ``The
Nerd,'' starring Rowan Atkinson (aka Bean); he was 10. His first
film, made in Sweden and Russia and featuring Timothy Bottoms and
Susannah York, was called ``Land of the Faraway.'' ``I've only seen
it in Swedish,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, he was cast by Steven Spielberg as the
leading character in the 1987 film ``Empire of the Sun,'' which
follows the internment of a privileged British boy in a prisoner of
war camp under the Japanese during World War II. It was a
career-launching performance, but it was the last time he was
called on to carry a film. Since then, he has been cast largely as
a sweet-tempered lad.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the tortured London suburbanite in ``Metroland'' is
nearly as much of a departure for him as Pat Bateman. He is playing
Bateman as an empty shell, he said, someone who has no center, no
soul. ``If you go back and look at the magazines of the 80s, the
advertising, the stories about what a real man is, what a winner
is, where power comes from,'' Bale said, ``Bateman has this image
of himself stolen from those magazines.
</P>
<P>
   While he's emotionally vacant, the whole persona is an act for
himself, so I'm really playing somebody who's acting the whole
time, but he's acting without having anybody in his life who, when
he shuts the door he can go, `Whew, done that, this is me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bale committed to ``American Psycho'' almost two years ago, and
he, like Ms. Harron, the director, has clung to the prospect of
making the film as if to a life raft. For a while last summer,
Leonardo DiCaprio expressed interest in playing the part of
Bateman, and Ms. Harron, who understood that the presence of such a
megastar would change the nature of the film, resisted, was fired
from the project, then rehired when DiCaprio wouldn't commit to the
part. Bale, meanwhile, turned down several roles in the hope that
things would turn out exactly as they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more involved in this project than anything I've ever
done,'' he said. ``I was on board before there was any money for
it. After that much time this wasn't just another job for me, so I
never accepted that I wouldn't get to play the character. I did
have an awful lot of people saying, `Christian this is ridiculous,
you're becoming obsessed. Do something else!'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harron, a Canadian whose previous film was the well-received
``I Shot Andy Warhol,'' starring Lili Taylor as the obsessed
stalker of the famous Pop artist, wrote the ``American Psycho''
screenplay with Guinevere Turner. They deleted much, though by no
means all, of the novel's brutality (there are four scripted
killings) and the two writers have come under criticism for
adapting a work that contains so much violence against women.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harron said, however, that they were attracted to the book
because ``it had a skewed and critical look at male behavior, macho
behavior, that we'd never seen before, and that it should fit into
a feminist line.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Oxford,'' she continued. ``It was my one experience
meeting upper classes, and upper class men in gangs, and when I
read `American Psycho,' I recognized these wealthy, privileged,
handsome young men, who travel in gangs, who have such a sense of
entitlement and who are so obsessed with each other and competitive
with each other that they're only interested in sleeping with a
woman if one of the other guys wants her.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel has been controversial since three months before its
scheduled publication, when Simon &AMP; Schuster, which had a contract
with the author and had accepted the finished manuscript, reversed
itself and refused to publish it, citing matters of taste. When it
was subsequently picked up by Vintage and published as a trade
paperback, Ellis received numerous death threats, and a boycott of
Vintage and its parent, Alfred A. Knopf, was organized by the Los
Angeles chapter of the National Organization for Women _ an action
that did not, however, keep the novel from making the best-seller
list.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, here in Toronto, antiviolence and victims'-rights
groups tried _ in vain _ to keep the city from issuing a permit to
allow Lions Gate Films to make the movie here. The city is just
five years removed from the gruesome murders committed by a serial
killer named Paul Bernardo, who reportedly kept a copy of
``American Psycho'' at his bedside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very sympathetic to the protesters in Toronto,'' Ms.
Harron said. ``I didn't know there was this big connection, and I
felt terrible for the victims' families. You do feel responsible
and wonder if you're doing the right thing. It sounds like I just
want to put horrible mayhem on the screen, but I don't. I'm plagued
by these issues, actually. But how much do you restrict your work,
if it's serious work? I feel like there's something to do here that
hasn't really been done, a portrait of the late 80s that's worth
putting on the screen.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that leaves the question of what the film may do for or
to Bale. Psychotic killers tend to be memorable. Anthony Perkins,
after all, never climbed out from under the weight of Norman Bates.
On the other hand, Anthony Hopkins rode Hannibal Lecter to a career
revival.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just really need to do a romantic comedy or something very
quickly, before this comes out,'' Bale said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
