<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2768 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LE-CID-THEATER-2TAKES     04-01 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LE-CID-THEATER-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENGLISHING A FRENCH CLASSIC (WITH THEIR APPROVAL)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ French theater buffs still speak with reverence of Jean
Vilar's production of ``Le Cid'' at the 1951 Avignon Festival as
the definitive modern version of Corneille's 17th-century
masterpiece in verse.
</P>
<P>
   True, few people actually saw the two acclaimed performances
with Gerard Philipe in the lead role, but no matter. When the
Anglo-Irish director Declan Donnellan innocently suggested
presenting ``Le Cid'' in French at Avignon in 1998, the festival's
current head, Bernard Faivre D'Acier, looked decidedly alarmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `You know, there was this very important performance
at Avignon and it's very difficult to follow it,''' Donnellan
recalled. ``I was very sad and I asked him when that was. He said
it was in 1951. I thought, my God, France really is a very exotic
country. I wasn't even born then. I was taken to see Gerard
Philipe's costumes for `Le Cid' and I asked, `Where is his
third-act costume?' `Oh,' they said, `he's buried in it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if Donnellan was still not intimidated by this reminder of
the place of ``Le Cid'' _ and indeed of Philipe and Vilar, the
festival's founder _ in France's cultural pantheon, it is because
in 1986 he directed what he believes is the first-ever
English-language production of the play in England. With Cheek by
Jowl, the theater company that he co-founded in 1981, he has also
directed Racine's ``Andromache'' in English. And he happens to be
fluent in French. So he persuaded Faivre D'Acier to go with ``Le
Cid'' _ and the gamble paid off.
</P>
<P>
   The production was the high point of last year's Avignon
Festival, almost unanimously praised by French critics as an
intelligent and disturbing fresh look at a dusty classic. Since
then, it has been seen in many French provincial cities as well as
in London in February and most recently at the Theatre des Bouffes
du Nord, the Paris home of Peter Brook's experimental theater
company.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is ending its touring life at the Brooklyn Academy of
Music, with seven performances _ accompanied by English-language
surtitles _ at the Majestic Theater from Tuesday through next
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In writing ``Le Cid'' in 1636, Corneille was inspired by two
1618 plays by the Spanish poet Guillen de Castro. They were based
on the legend of an 11th-century Castillian knight, Rodrigo de
Vivar, who was banished by King Alfonso and joined one Moorish king
in battle against another. For his bravery, he was given the rank
of lord: ``Sidi'' for the Moors, ``El Cid'' for the Christians.
</P>
<P>
   But as the legend evolved, he was transformed into a Castillian
hero who married the daughter of a knight whom he had slain. Castro
added that the young woman was in love with Rodrigo before she was
orphaned. Corneille then went further.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Le Cid,'' Chimene and Rodrigue win their fathers' approval
to marry. But when Rodrigue's father, Don Diegue, is appointed
tutor to King Fernand's heir, Chimene's father, Don Gomes, is
outraged and insults his rival. Don Diegue demands that his son
avenge his honor, which leads Rodrigue to kill Don Gomes. Chimene
is now herself required to seek revenge, even though she still
loves Rodrigue.
</P>
<P>
   The young knight is sent into battle against the Moors and, in
defeating them, earns the title of Le Cid. When he returns, Chimene
designates Don Sanche to challenge Rodrigue _ and pledges to marry
the winner. To her relief, Don Sanche is defeated.
</P>
<P>
   The play's plot and its Alexandrine verses are conventionally
classical, yet in its day, ``Le Cid'' was considered brazenly
subversive. It challenged the unity of place, time and action
required by early 17th-century French theater. Corneille also
called it a tragicomedy at a time when tragedy and comedy were
never mixed.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the ensuing furor, including charges of plagiarism,
that Cardinal Richelieu summoned the Academie Francaise to sit in
judgment (it issued a 192-page critical verdict). Corneille, still
only 30, was so shaken that he was never as daring again. He went
on to write five more tragedies _ ``Horace,'' ``Cinna,''
``Polyeucte,'' ``Rodogune''` and ``Nicomede'' _ but they were far
more traditional in structure. By the time Racine shook Paris with
the emotional punch of ``Phedre'' in 1677, the aging Corneille was
considered a has-been.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in the centuries that followed, ``Le Cid'' has
become a central pillar of the French canon, its most famous
speeches learned by heart by generations of high school students, a
task facilitated by both the predictable rhythm and limited
vocabulary of its verse. Many French adults can also remember
seeing one or another production of the play as children.
</P>
<P>
   And if, as likely, it was at the Comedie Francaise, they would
have seen it interpreted as an epic tragedy. In tackling ``Le
Cid,'' then, Donnellan was also taking on French memories.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Since the production is in French, the director obviously could
not use Cheek by Jowl (which in any event was disbanded as a
permanent troupe last spring). And since he was not familiar with
French actors, auditions took several months. His first surprise
was to cast a young black French actor, William Nadylam, as
Rodrigue. (Donnellan has frequently opted for multicultural
casting, but black actors in France are still largely limited to
black roles.)
</P>
<P>
   He then stripped the play of much of its pomp and ceremony by
using simple early 20th-century costumes and uniforms. He also
designed the production so that the action segues from scene to
scene, with many actors onstage for much of the play.
</P>
<P>
   Some French theatergoers were surprised by the humor amid the
mayhem, but the 45-year-old Irish-born director said he wanted to
probe the play's dualities: tragedy against comedy, honor against
shame, passion against reason, the individual against the state,
parent against child.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the play is about the absolute crucial importance of
disobedience,'' Donnellan explained. ``What is very sad at the
heart of the play is that Rodrigue does not disobey his father. But
Corneille makes it clear that you have to embrace all these
dualities. These people are obsessed with honor because they are
also obsessed with shame. People ask, `Does Chimene want Rodrigue
dead or alive?' The answer is both. She wants him completely dead
and completely alive. She completely loves him and completely hates
him. We find it difficult to live with conflicts, but here the
conflict is absolutely played out.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most unorthodox is the transformation of Rodrigue into a
tormented and reluctant hero. And this is done by interpreting the
knight's speeches, not as oratory a la ``Henry V,'' but as
self-doubting monologues _ even when he is not alone _ a la
``Hamlet.'' After his great military victory, for example,
Rodrigue's report to the king is traditionally delivered
triumphantly. Here, it becomes a lament over the horrors of war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if someone shows off about the people he's killed _
it's really fear and doubt speaking,'' Donnellan said over coffee
at the Theatre des Bouffes du Nord. ``The louder the abuse, the
bigger the lie; the louder we shout about our certainties, the less
people believe. I think even if this scene were done with flags and
baroque splendor, the whole baroque thing is really about doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Having presented Rodrigue as something of an anti-hero,
Donnellan has understandably been relieved by the warm reception
his version has received from both the French public and theater
critics. ``Our national hit has been rejuvenated and dusted off,''
said Le Nouvel Observateur. ``Heresy?'' asked the financial daily
Les Echos. ``Not at all. This production, which is both
iconoclastic and true to Corneille, is a success. It's for those
who do not fear insolence.'' Le Figaro's headline over its review
was just one word, in English: ``Wonderful!''
</P>
<P>
   Donnellan, who directed an acclaimed production of Tony
Kushner's ``Angels in America'' at the National Theater in London
in 1992, has received praise in New York for three of his Cheek by
Jowl productions _ ``The Duchess of Malfi,'' ``As You Like It'' and
``Much Ado About Nothing'' _ which traveled from England to the
academy in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The director said he had been heartened by his first experience
of working with French actors and before French audiences. ``The
actors came with such openness and warmth that there was no
demolition to do,'' he said. ``A lot of work was done on movement
because the French tradition is very Cartesian, very intellectual.
The French are famous for their arrogance, but they could not have
been more open about my meddling with their tradition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
