<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2772 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-LOVE-LETTERS-2TAKE     04-01 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-LOVE-LETTERS-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUL MATES AGING, ONE MISSIVE AT A TIME  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn.)   (af)  
 By CHARLES STRUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Love Letters,'' A.R. Gurney's spare, epistolary duet for the
stage, is _ as the author himself has pointed out _ a quasi-play.
</P>
<P>
   The script for the original production, which opened in New York
10 years ago with a revolving cast that began with John Rubinstein
and Kathleen Turner, contains an explanatory note from the author:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a play, or rather a sort of a play, which needs no
theater, no lengthy rehearsal, no special set, no memorization of
lines and no commitment from its two actors beyond the night of
performance. It is designed simply to be read aloud by an actor and
an actress of roughly the same age, sitting side by side at a
table.'' It works best, he wrote, ``if the actors don't look at
each other until the end.'' Yet they (italics)``listen(end italics)
eagerly and actively to each other along the way, much as we might
listen to an urgent voice on a one-way radio, coming from far, far
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a leap of artistic faith, ``Love Letters'' has become a
full-length television film (ABC, next Monday at 9 p.m.), with
sets, costumes and the occasional supporting player. The stars are
Laura Linney (most recently Jim Carrey's wife in ``The Truman
Show'') and Steven Weber (who starred in the sitcom ``Wings'').
</P>
<P>
   They join the scores of famous ``Love Letters'' couples who,
until now, sat side by side reading the intimate lifelong
correspondence between Melissa Gardner and Andrew Makepeace Ladd
III _ two WASPy soul mates (this is not really an oxymoron) whose
bond begins in childhood and ends with her death in middle age.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Robards and Colleen Dewhurst took a turn. So did Steve
Allen and Jayne Meadows and Timothy Dalton and Whoopi Goldberg. Not
to mention Sandy Duncan and Peter Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   But taking an intimate two-character encounter from the stage to
the screen means taking some dramatic risks: mainly, making it
bigger. It is a risk that Gurney has been willing to take since the
day in 1990 when the producer Martin Starger bought the screen
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the money he paid me, I had a tennis court put in,''
Gurney said with a laugh in a telephone interview from his country
house in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Gurney's recreation aside, the producers meant business and
never gave up, even when some major studios dropped out. Besides
having Gurney retool the script _ yet again, for television _ they
hired Stanley Donen, the venerable Oscar-winning Hollywood
director, who had been involved with Gurney and the producers in
some of the early feature-length plans.
</P>
<P>
   Best known, perhaps, for his lavish, big-screen films _
``Singin' in the Rain,'' ``Seven Brides for Seven Brothers'' and
``Funny Face,'' to name a few _ Donen has also directed more
intimate films, like ``Two for the Road'' (Audrey Hepburn and
Albert Finney) and ``Indiscreet'' (Ingrid Bergman and Cary Grant).
</P>
<P>
   But a television movie is a first for Donen, a job he said he
was eager to undertake because ``I had a sort of image'' of how to
do it. Taking something small and making it bigger, but not too
big, is, he said, ``the fun, or the challenge or the adventure'' of
the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're involved in the pragmatic problems of a person sitting
at home watching something that they could just as easily turn
off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mean to sound grand, but I think of Diaghilev when
Nijinksy said, `What do you want me to do?' And Diaghilev said,
`Astonish me!' The challenge is how you astonish the viewer.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurney said, ``I never thought it would be a movie.'' And after
almost a decade of off-and-on negotiations, he could be excused for
wondering.
</P>
<P>
   Some might consider his work _ his plays include ``The Cocktail
Hour'' and ``The Middle Ages'' _ intellectual or elitist, but
Gurney has worked for television before. His Off Broadway play
``The Dining Room'' was broadcast on PBS in 1984, with a cast that
included W.H. Macy, John Shea and Frances Sternhagen. And in the
1970s Gurney adapted John Cheever's story ``O Youth and Beauty!''
for the PBS series ``Great Performances.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the ABC deal started to come together only after Gurney had
done rewrites for two film studios, Columbia and Universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original screenplay was quite different,'' Gurney said of
his initial, feature-film treatment. ``There were all sorts of
major changes of place. We went to Naples and Japan and the
carrier,'' the one that Andy Ladd was assigned to as a young Navy
lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   But once ABC decided to make it, the expanded story ``had to be
put back into the bottle,'' Gurney said. Rehearsal and filming, in
Toronto, took barely three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest shifts from theater to film was in having the
characters interract.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The heart of the play is that you have two people side by
side, never looking at each other,'' Gurney said. ``Since the play
is all about missed connections, you don't see them connect till
the very end, when it's too late. When she finally looks at him and
sees him for what he really is. You could argue that they're
connecting, but they're not connecting. She's an emanation of his
imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   On stage, the action is strictly chronological. Andy has the
first line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andrew Makepeace Ladd III accepts with pleasure the kind
invitation of Mr. and Mrs. Gilbert Channing Gardner for a birthday
party in honor of their daughter Melissa on the occasion of her
seventh birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa: ``Dear Andy: Thank you for the birthday present. I have
lots of Oz books, but not `The Lost Princess of Oz.' What made you
give me that one? Sincerely, Melissa.''
</P>
<P>
   Their exchanges proceed through their separate, single-sex camp
and boarding school experiences, to teen-age sexual
experimentation, college and beyond, when their lives and points of
view sometimes contrive to keep them apart.
</P>
<P>
   Andy, the upright, uptight WASP so often present in Gurney's
plays about the culture he knows so well, becomes a United States
senator with the charisma of Al Gore. He has a wife, three sons and
a dog and sends out numbingly detailed, mimeographed Christmas
letters.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa, a very rich girl from a home of multiple divorces, is
rebellious, loving, artistic and self-destructive. Over the years,
Melissa yearns for the stability his love would bring her; Andy
yearns for the freedom her open and artistic nature would bestow on
him.
</P>
<P>
   Because television movies work on slimmer budgets and tighter
shooting schedules than feature films, Donen chose to rely on a
script that resembled the stage version in many respects. But to
set it up for the viewer, he chose to abandon strict chronology by
starting with a flashback and using the letters as opportunities
for more.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens not with an exchange about a long-ago birthday
party but with Ladd's return to his suburban Washington home after
attending Melissa's funeral. He carries with him the boxes of his
letters to Melissa that she had saved. He goes to his study, opens
a safe and removes a strongbox, in which he has kept Melissa's
letters to him, carefully indexed.
</P>
<P>
   At his desk, he begins to read and Melissa _ her ghost, that is
_ materializes in a blue dress. At times during the movie, Andy and
Melissa speak to each other, hold hands, embrace. At other times
they speak only to the camera. But always, Gurney, says, the
audience is aware that ``this is a man in his study talking to a
ghost.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Linney, the troubled Melissa, says she believes that after
years of alcoholism and depression, Melissa took her own life. But
she also thinks Melissa is finally at peace.
</P>
<P>
   Andy's last letter, to Melissa's elderly mother, ends with these
words:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've every loved anyone the way I loved her, and
I know I never will again. She was at the heart of my life, and
already I miss her desperately. I just wanted to say this to you
and to her. Sincerely, Andy Ladd.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Linney said, ``He's finally admitted something. It's finally
sitting with him. It's resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also the first time, in the stage production, that one
character, Melissa, turns to look at the other. ``Thank you,
Andy,'' says Melissa.
</P>
<P>
   On film, the lovely woman in the blue dress dematerializes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
