<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-CHEVY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEVY OFF TO A SHAKY START  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 THE LEDGER   (Lakeland, Fla.)   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chevy is off to a shaky start in this year's Winston Cup
competition.
</P>
<P>
   It may be bad luck, being in the wrong place at the wrong time
or it may be the law of averages finally catching up with Jeff
Gordon and, to a lesser extent, Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, last Sunday, Gordon slammed into a wall at the
Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth and wound up 43rd, the worst
finish of his career although he has been last in races before. In
1996, he was 42nd in the Daytona 500. In 1997, he was 42nd and last
in the spring race in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But with a 39th the week before in Rockingham, S.C., after his
engine let go and now the 43rd in Texas, it can be argued that this
is Gordon's worst start since 1993, his first year of competition.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's weak eighth-place finish in Texas was only his
second time in the top 20 in the first six races this year.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that Chevy can't still save its season. While
there have been disappointments, there have also been surprises.
</P>
<P>
   Since Terry Labonte, who won in Texas, was taken out in a wreck
at Daytona, he has run with the kind of consistency expected from
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Skinner, Earnhardt's teammate, has been surprisingly
strong, although some of Gordon's bad luck seems to have rubbed off
on him.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in Texas, after Gordon hit the wall and wrecked, so did
Skinner, who finished 42nd.
</P>
<P>
   From Chevy's standpoint, all this is complicated by the
possibility of having to switch to a new car late in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Even before this year's first race, the Daytona 500, the
powerful Hendrick team which builds cars for Gordon, Labonte and
Wally Dallenbach, lobbied to postpone the car's debut until 2000
because NASCAR and Chevy could not reach agreement on its final
design.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a cutoff date, a date when we get the rules, a date
when we can test,'' John Hendrick said back then.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't get a date when we feel we have enough time to
properly test the car and know what we've got, I don't know of a
single owner who would be in favor of making the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   In a tight points race, moving to a new car with all its
unknowns could cost Chevy a championship. Now it appears that, led
by Hendrick's opposition, Chevy will hold off racing its new car
until next year.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the top Chevy teams have their work cut out for
them. Gordon probably has the best chance of breaking out.
</P>
<P>
   But for others, like Earnhardt, this is beginning to look like a
long season.
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of The New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
