<HEADLINE>
REPORT CRITICIZES UTILITY FOR POWER OUTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE COSTANTINOU and ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A state investigation into the power outage that
crippled San Francisco in December harshly criticized the Pacific
Gas and Electric Co., saying that more than 140 human errors
occurred from the moment the power failure began to when power was
restored some seven hours later.
</P>
<P>
   In the 105-page report released Wednesday, independent
consultants for the California Public Utilities Commission also
accuse the utility of stymieing its investigation into the Dec. 8
incident.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants said they were not able to talk to the PG&AMP;E
workers most directly involved in the power failure, relying
instead on interview notes provided by PG&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they said that a key document, the switching log in
the control room of the San Mateo substation where the failure
began, was doctored to cover up a misstep that ended up tripping
the system and causing the blackout.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E assailed the report as ``flawed'' and ``reckless,'' utility
spokesman Len Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to PUC President Richard Bilas, PG&AMP;E chief executive
Gordon Smith urged the commission to reject the report's most
damning conclusions, adding that the consultants had gone outside
of their jurisdiction by focusing on transmission issues.
</P>
<P>
   That turf belongs to the quasi-public California Independent
System Operator in Folsom, Smith said. According to PG&AMP;E, the
California Independent System Operator also issued a report
Wednesday that concluded the utility complied with industry
standards and had reacted appropriately to the blackout.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1 million people in the San Francisco area were
affected by the power failure, which started at 8:15 a.m. and ended
at 3:54 p.m. Hospitals, transit trains, traffic lights, elevators,
homes and businesses were affected.
</P>
<P>
   The utility has acknowledged that there were mistakes made by a
crew working at the San Mateo station and has disciplined some
employees.
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E found fault with many of the PUC assertions. It disagreed
with the dollar figure of the estimated damages. The PUC report
placed the damages between $200 million and $400 million. So far,
claims have been in the $15 million range, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   The utility disagreed with the PUC claim that full power could
have been restored within three hours, instead of the seven hours,
39 minutes it took. The procedures recommended by the consultants
would have caused serious damage to the electrical equipment of the
utility and of the customers, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the PUC places the blame for the blackout on human
errors, those errors point to systemic problems within the utility
company, according to the report, including inadequate field
supervision and double-checks of equipment and procedures.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the report says, PG&AMP;E suffers from an ``error-prone
work culture that is not self-critical ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of the December 8 outage, significant human errors
were made by the majority of the PG&AMP;E organizations involved in the
event,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Blunders were made every step of the way. ``Grounding errors,
engineering errors, operator switching errors, review errors,
testing errors, maintenance errors, etc.,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report does not carry fines or penalties, but warns that
unless its recommendations are taken, another major blackout could
occur.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
