u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASCAR-PONTIAC-NYTR &LR;      04-01 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR-PONTIAC-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONTIAC TURNS HEADS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK ZIER   
 THE LEDGER   (Lakeland, Fla.)   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Pontiac, NASCAR's stepchild in the battle between Ford and
Chevy for stock car racing supremacy, the struggle to get to the
top has not been so much a case of one step back, two steps forward
as it has one step back, one-and-a-quarter steps forward. But gains
have been made.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at the Texas Motor Speedway in Fort Worth two Pontiacs _
the team cars owned by Joe Gibbs and driven by Bobby Labonte and
rookie Tony Stewart _ finished third and sixth, respectively.
Another Pontiac driven by Ward Burton had a lead for 56 laps.
</P>
<P>
   In the first six races this season, Pontiac has two poles, two
runner-up finishes, five top fives and 14 top 10s.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Pontiac had two poles, one win, two top fives and
four top 10s after six races.
</P>
<P>
   Through the race in Texas, Labonte was second in the point
standings and Burton eighth, giving Pontiac two drivers in the top
10 compared with none a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Pontiac's resurgence began when Gibbs, unhappy over what he
thought was second-class status with Chevy, switched to Pontiac in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   With Richard Petty's team floundering, Pontiac had no lead car,
a role filled for Chevy by Jeff Gordon and for Ford by Mark Martin,
and Gibbs' operation quickly moved to fill the void.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Gibbs' two cars have accounted for both Pontiac poles,
one of the two runner-up finishes, four of the five top fives and
seven of the 14 top 10s.
</P>
<P>
   Another Pontiac problem is lack of numbers.
</P>
<P>
   This year, nine drivers are in Pontiacs compared with seven in
1998, but they pale in comparison to the Ford and Chevy
contingents.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remember the numbers are against Pontiac,'' said
John Andretti, who drives Petty's car. ``The longevity of some of
those teams with the other manufacturers also means a lot. Pontiac
has been with Petty Enterprises a long time, but they really
haven't been that long with Joe Gibbs and some of the other
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty began his association with Pontiac in 1982. The next most
senior team member is Chuck Rider, who started with Pontiac in
1989. Derrike Cope is his current driver.
</P>
<P>
   With only nine teams and many of them fairly new to Pontiac,
Andretti points out that Pontiac goes into races riding a tighter
line than either Ford or Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reality, you're not comparing apples to apples,'' Andretti
explained. ``If it was a third of the field, a third of the field
and a third of the field and everybody was dealing with the same
level of teams, then I think the results would look different.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one guy has a problem, there goes a huge percentage of the
Pontiacs out of the field and, of course, not everybody hits the
setup every weekend, so already, you're missing two or three of
them,'' Petty said.
</P>
<P>
   With Ford or Chevy, if a couple cars miss the setup it's not a
big deal, because they'll have between 15 and 20 entries in a given
race. Pontiac, though, needs everybody running well. But if they're
all not running well, at least some of them are running better.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte continues to set the pace, pulling teammate Stewart
along with him. Burton has improved dramatically over a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the parity is better this year than it was at the
start of last year between Ford, Chevy and Pontiac,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time, we've had this body for quite a while now,''
he said. ``That probably helped because we just had more of a
database to draw from because we stayed with what we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the question is, can Pontiac teams keep it up?
</P>
<P>
   ``We would love to have more wins, more top fives and more top
10s and finish higher in the points,'' Labonte said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that goal is out of reach.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger in Lakeland, Fla., is part of The New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
