<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHENTIC HORNBLOWER, WHERE GRIM MEETS GHASTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Broadcast notes are at end of review. Time and station are
for New York area; check local listings.) 
(mk) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The squeamish are advised to pop a couple of Dramamine before
sailing with Horatio Hornblower. You're in for some rough seas.
</P>
<P>
   Starting on Sunday night, A&AMP;E is presenting four new films
featuring Hornblower, the young 18th-century British naval officer
created by the novelist C.S. Forester. Judging from the first of
these, ``The Duel,'' the filmmakers have gone to great pains to
reproduce the unrelentingly grim life aboard His Majesty's ships.
They have succeeded perhaps too well. The drama's two hours feel
longer than Grandma's last Caribbean cruise.
</P>
<P>
   Horatio, who matures from a frightened boy to a leader of men,
is on screen virtually every moment, so the casting was crucial.
The producers have given the role to an actor with nautical
experience; he played a crew member on the big-screen Titanic. The
series' Horatio is a square-jawed 24-year-old Welshman named Ioan
Gruffudd (pronounced yo-IN GRIFF-iths). He is given to long periods
of stoic brooding between bursts of overacting (pronounced EAU-vuh
ACT-ing). If you can imagine a young Al Gore in a Napoleon hat,
you've got the picture.
</P>
<P>
   When first glimpsed, Midshipman Hornblower, already seasick, is
clambering from a rowboat onto the Justinian off Spithead on the
English coast. It's 1793, and war with the new Republican
government in France is imminent. Meanwhile the ship's men have
little to do but get on one another's nerves (not to mention
yours). This gives Hornblower ample time to suffer the assaults,
verbal and otherwise, of the sadistic Jack Simpson (Dorian Healy),
who looks like Rod Stewart on a bad hair day.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody likes Simpson. As he enters the cramped quarters below
decks, one of his fellow midshipmen snarls, ``Stand off, Jack, or
by God I'll trim the wall with your brains.'' (Imagine two hours of
men talking like that.) But at least Healy's psychotic bully offers
some hint of a living person.
</P>
<P>
   Hornblower must face Simpson (the duel of the title) and his
other nightmares, all in the crucible of the war that eventually
begins. During the course of this first installment he is
transferred to the frigate Indefatigable, commanded by the
tough-but-wise Capt. Pellew (Robert Lindsay), who will become
Hornblower's mentor. Lindsay is an actor with a flair for comedy
and charm, but this role (this whole production) hasn't a hint of
either quality.
</P>
<P>
   The three remaining films _ based, like the first, on sections
of one 1950 Forester novel, ``Mr. Midshipman Hornblower'' _ will
appear on succeeding Sunday nights. The hero will actually meet a
woman or two and will earn the rank of lieutenant (pronounced
left-TEN-ahnt).
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers have made a great deal of prideful noise about
the production's nautical authenticity. They say that their
125-foot-long Indefatigable is a replica of a 24-gun frigate, the
first such ship to be hand-built from wood in 150 years. But the
viewer who doesn't know a mainsail from a clearance sale will
quickly grow weary of all the smoke, fog, blood, screaming,
splashing, scowling and scurrying rats. That viewer will yearn for
another kind of authenticity. While the eye may be impressed by the
shipbuilders' craft, the mind and heart will wonder where the drama
is.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HORATIO HORNBLOWER`
</P>
<P>
   Sunday at 8 p.m. on A&AMP;E
</P>
<P>
   First of a four-part film series written by Russell Lewis, Mike
Cullen and Patrick Harbinson and based on the novels by C.S.
Forester; directed by Andrew Grieve; produced by Andrew Benson;
Neve Cunningham and Alec Curtis, directors of photography. An
A&AMP;E/UNBE co-production. Delia Fine, executive producer for A&AMP;E;
Vernon Lawrence, UNBE executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ioan Gruffudd (Hornblower), Robert Lindsay (Capt. Pellew),
Paul Copley (Matthews), Sean Gilder (Styles), Simon Sherlock
(Oldroyd), Jonathan Coy (Lt. Bracegirdle), Jamie Bamber (Kennedy),
Colin MacLachlan (Master Bowles), Chris Barnes (Finch), Frank Boyce
(Cleveland) and Dorian Healy (Jack Simpson).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
