<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLKE-ART-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-01 1786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLKE-ART-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: A GIDDY BACCHANALIA OF IMAGERY AND EXPLOSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is new if temporary treasure to be found at the
Museum of Modern Art right now, and it lies at the center of the
engrossing, challenging exhibition of early drawings by German
painter Sigmar Polke. The third gallery in this show, which has
been organized by Margit Rowell, chief curator of drawings, and is
devoted to works from 1963 to 1974, presents only four drawings,
all dated 1969-71.
</P>
<P>
   But each is the size of a large wall, and two even curl
seductively on the floor like magic carpets. All are dense with
overlapping images, exploding forms, delicate notations, mad
scribbles, florid stains, seeping colors, even footprints. Fitted
together from smaller pieces of paper, their mixes of media suggest
a startling degree of physical experimentation and include paint,
oil, felt-tip pen, ball-point pen, crayon, pencil, stencil and
collage.
</P>
<P>
   The ensemble effect is one of the most astounding artistic
sights currently available in New York, and the first encounter can
take your breath away. (This is only the third time the four have
been shown together, and their first U.S. appearance.) The drawings
easily live up to their apocalyptic title: ``The Ride on the Eight
of Infinity.'' I love the unexpected innocence of the ``eight'': it
is like a child's on-first-sight name for the infinity symbol's
double loop.
</P>
<P>
   In the first of these drawings a beatific, albeit rabbity, face
emerges in four stages from deep pale-green space; around it is a
rose window of clambering human silhouettes, outlines of a real
person lying on the paper. In the next, a blocky robotlike head is
sprayed in the face with a hose, manned by a vivid blue hand that
seems related to a face emerging from a cloud as a genie would. In
the third, a giant motorcyclist seen dramatically from above surges
diagonally across the paper, trailing a huge shell-like coil that
includes a highway, a star-spangled-banner sky and a woman's
profile. And in the final one, drawing takes over as swirling
cyclones and spirals of scribbles move in and out of expanses of
red paint.
</P>
<P>
   An obvious comparison is with the three big classic ``drip''
paintings that formed the heart of the Modern's recent Jackson
Pollock retrospective. But in place of the Pollocks' irreducible
unity and enveloping oneness, the Polkes substitute a virtual
babble of competing intellectual, visual and cultural forces. These
works did not result from an extended meditative dance around the
canvas. They came in fits and starts over time, in gestures and
images large and small, in amendments, accidents, obliterations and
accretions, in fermentation.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to think of them as the product of one person, or
even a single culture. Abstract Expressionism as filtered through
Pop Art, '60s psychedelia, even American painting of the '80s,
they're all here, but so are Egypt, Byzantium and Pompeii.
</P>
<P>
   From certain angles, the gallery suggests some opulent inner
sanctum, a hidden chamber brilliant with glowing tapestries,
frescoes or ancient cave paintings. For once, the faintly
oppressive subterranean atmosphere of the Modern's euphemistically
titled ``mezzanine'' (read basement) galleries feels just right.
</P>
<P>
   It is best to see these drawings first. They supply a kind of
fire not unlike winter morning porridge; this can power you through
the rest of the show, which sometimes feels a bit arctic.
</P>
<P>
   One problem is that the remaining galleries don't seem quite
full, as if the show needed either less space or more art. Given
the roving exuberance of Polke's art, the installation should have
been , well, more effervescent. It is also too bad that the show
stops so early in Polke's career, although it reaches the point
when his drawings had successfully established the basic tenets of
his art.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the years after 1974 are partly accounted for in two
exhibitions in galleries on the Upper East Side, which, together,
have a richness nearly equal to the Modern's show. Michael Werner,
who first showed Polke's work in his gallery in Cologne in 1970,
has mounted a mesmerizing display of drawings from the artist's
sketchbooks of the '80s. Knoedler, which sometime collaborates with
Werner, has a show of beautiful new works on paper, some of them
quite large and most of them echoing ideas first introduced in the
Modern's show. (The exceptions are the beautifully intricate
networks of bright runny color made by wild and rapid tilts of the
paper surface with results that variously suggest crackled glazes,
chaotic lace or sotto voce Pollock.)
</P>
<P>
   Polke is arguably the greatest and most influential of the East
and West German painters who came of age in the late 1960s and
early '70s, but whose work was not seen in New York until the early
'80s. His main competition is Gerhard Richter, whose intellectual
rigidity is the inverse of Polke's heady, almost (sometimes
actually) intoxicated sense of license. Not for nothing is one of
the show's final drawings, depicting an open vial of yellow
crystals, titled ``Polke as a Drug.''
</P>
<P>
   In a generation that includes Georg Baselitz, A.R. Penck, Markus
Lupertz and Anselm Kiefer, Polke has always been the mercurial
maverick, gleefully shifting styles, media and material at will. He
has, for example, produced an enormous body of photographs as
aggressively manipulated as his paintings. (They were seen in a
large show at the Los Angeles Museum of Contemporary Art in 1995.)
His art has been consistently resistant to assimilation and easy
viewing; after 40 years, its physical eccentricity and roughness
can still startle.
</P>
<P>
   The current show is no exception. Just as Polke was capable of
pushing drawing to monumental, mural-size extremes, he was also
capable of going for broke in the opposite direction, making
drawings from the slightest, most abject bits of materials and
ideas, whose first impression is of inconsequentiality.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening galleries of this exhibition you may sometimes
think you are looking at children's drawings. You are not. Rather,
you are seeing a young artist with a wide subversive streak
wreaking havoc with the tradition of the medium. On sheet after
sheet, he brashly questions accepted notions of skill, beauty,
refinement and technique, while also dealing with some of the
pressing questions of the day and the latest ideas in contemporary
art.
</P>
<P>
   In 1963, the start of the exhibition, Polke was in his third
year of a course of art study at the Duesseldorf Art Academy that
would continue until 1967. Fellow students included Richter; Joseph
Beuys was a teacher. American Pop art, with its emphasis on
consumer culture, was just making its presence felt. Its attitude
dovetailed with the growing German recovery, fueled as it was by
impeccably designed products, especially cars, desired the world
over.
</P>
<P>
   In the early part of the exhibition, Polke covers a lot of
ground, working fast and loose. His subjects fall into general
categories: modern art, modern romance, tourism, consumerism, all
of which he approaches with the double edge of satire and
sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   As his drawing styles waver, wither and expand during this
period, it is important to bear one idea in mind: Polke always
keeps his hand in, keeps it personal. He may be the most
peripatetic of postmodernists, but his drawings almost always
incorporate an element of automatism, providing readings of the
artist's nervous system as clearly as anything by Cy Twombly.
</P>
<P>
   With buoyant grids, curves and liver shapes, Polke makes
abstractions that suggest cocktail napkin designs. With cursory,
scrappy marks, he introduces phallic worms that angle and dangle,
leering at women, crowing (``Inhibitions?'') at little men, all in
a cartoon style so light as to almost wash off the page. Words and
sarcastic captions are frequent; his use of the non sequitur echoes
through the work of succeeding generations, from William Wegman to
Raymond Pettibon's laconic, loquacious verbal art, now in full view
at the Drawing Center in Soho.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, Polke plays American art off German life while
refusing to partake of the material confidence of either. The best
drawings in the show's first section are numerous smiling Roy
Lichtensteinian blondes rendered small and crabbed in scratchy blue
ballpoint, a medium more common, impoverished and intimate than the
anonymous elegance of newspaper advertising or comic-book
illustration favored by the Americans. Still, the singularly
beautiful ``Spider Man'' demonstrates that he could be suavely
illustrational when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In other instances, Polke's hand turns jovial and relaxed, as in
a series of loose, cartoonish gouaches of potato-head couples and
tourist-poster abstractions that incorporate plumes of fluorescent
spray paint and seem to satirize the flourishes of Lyrical
Abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   It is symptomatic of Polke's ability to see the expressive
potential of common implements that he may be the first artist to
take the felt-tipped pen seriously, as evidenced by sketchbook
drawings from 1971-72 in the show's final gallery. Here the artist,
who started making images that resemble children's drawings, closes
out with a few dozen that suggest the work of a juiced-up teen-age
boy. But these sometimes stark, hallucinatory images of sci-fi
faces and pretzelized creatures are much more psychologically
subtle than you initially think, and also full of unexpected
perceptual tricks and delicate positive-negative reversals that
animate the entire page. The artist's conclusion seems to be that
the late-century soul is twisted, but thriving.
</P>
<P>
   This gallery also includes some of the show's most touching
moments. One is a 1965 drawing-love letter that begins ``!Lieber
Toni,'' and over lines of neat little images seems to tell the
story of a happy relationship, full of travel and art. Also here is
a charming sketchbook, open to one page with the others reproduced
in an accordion photograph, that is devoted exclusively to images
of self-satisfied little easy chairs living happy bourgeois lives.
</P>
<P>
   After its central knockout gallery, the remainder of this
exhibition becomes richer and fuller as you spend more time with
it. It doesn't take too long to realize that the flaming
imagination and restless experimentation that courses so raucously
through ``The Ride on the Eight of Infinity'' swirls more quietly
through everything else, a rich, ceaseless underground current.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sigmar Polke: Works on Paper 1963-1974'' is at the Museum of
Modern Art, 11 W. 53rd St., Manhattan, (212) 708-9400, through June
16.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
