<SLUG> BC-US-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON APPEALS FOR PUBLIC SUPPORT AS ALLIES WEIGH WIDER MISSION  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL And ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, summoning the ``determination
and resolve'' of the American people for an escalating offensive in
the Balkans, declared Thursday that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic will be held responsible for the fate of three captured
American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The president, joined by Defense Secretary William Cohen and
Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, led a
nationally-broadcast patriotic pep rally in Norfolk, Va., as allied
leaders weighed whether to widen the eight-day-old operation to
create a safe haven inside Kosovo for tens of thousands of ethnic
Albanian Muslim refugees fleeing murderous evictions by Yugoslav
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the allied commander at NATO headquarters,
said in Brussels that NATO leaders are discussing whether to send
troops from a 12,000-troop allied force stationed in Macedonia into
neighboring Kosovo to establish a sanctuary to protect refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Clark declined to discuss the allies' capabilities or timing for
such a mission.
</P>
<P>
   A similar idea is being advanced by retired Army Gen. George
Joulwan, who preceded Clark as NATO commander in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   Joulwan said he is urging the 19-nation military alliance to
create a ``safe corridor'' for refugees inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Joulwan added in an interview with Hearst Newspapers that merely
preparing to insert allied ground forces into Kosovo could help by
``taking the initiative from Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   The former NATO commander said the rapid reaction force in
Macedonia, including 400 U.S. soldiers and about 5,000 British
troops, could move quickly into southern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke in Norfolk, Va., to hundreds of applauding
military personnel and their relatives shortly after Yugoslav
officials announced in Belgrade that they would court martial the
three U.S. soldiers captured Wednesday by Yugoslav forces while on
patrol along the border between Macedonia and the Yugoslav province
of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was absolutely no basis for them to be taken; there is
no basis for them to be held; there is certainly no basis for them
to be tried,'' Clinton declared in remarks in an aircraft hanger as
he stood before a warplane.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``President Milosevic should make no mistake: The
United States takes care of its own. And President Milosevic should
make no mistake: We will hold him and his government responsible
for their safety and for their well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's efforts to underscore U.S.
interests in the Balkans appeared to be paying off. An ABC
News-Washington Post survey completed Tuesday showed that the
percentage of respondents who believe that vital U.S. interests are
at stake in the turbulent region has grown from 27 percent two
weeks ago to 47 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made an impassioned appeal for public support at home,
emphasizing that U.S.-led intervention in the Balkans is needed to
``prevent a wider war.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the allied air campaign, Clinton said: ``We've been doing
this for seven days now _ just seven days. We must be determined
and patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton added: ``I ask you also to resolve that we will continue
to carry out our mission with determination and resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared to be addressing slackening public support for
the NATO air campaign that has failed to stem the Yugoslav armed
forces' scorched earth campaign against the Kosovars. The air
attacks also have been blamed for Yugoslavia's accelerated
offensive that has uprooted more than 600,000 Muslim residents of
Kosovo and sent more than 120,000 fleeing into neighboring Albania,
Montenegro and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The ABC News-Washington Post survey showed Americans' support
for the air strikes has eased somewhat from 60 percent supporting
the effort six days ago to 55 percent favoring the continued air
campaign as of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   As Joulwan put it: ``If the political objective was to prevent
Serb troops from ethnically cleansing and that's not being achieved
with bombing, then you have to come up with Plan B, C or D.''
</P>
<P>
   The retired Army general, who masterminded allied efforts in
Bosnia in 1995 that helped drive Bosnian Serbs to the bargaining
table, added: ``I would hope that some major somewhere has been
trying to figure out what options are available, particularly
ground options.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, a former Republican senator from Maine who joined the
Clinton administration to head the Pentagon, cited the resolve of
President Theodore Roosevelt and World War II British Prime
Minister Winston Churchill in his appeal for the American people to
``stay the course.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen added: ``We knew it was not going to be easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
