<HEADER>
A2808 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RESCUE-TRAININ     04-01 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RESCUE-TRAINING-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRUELING TRAINING PREPARES PARAJUMPERS FOR PILOT RESCUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, April 4)   (EDs: Previously moved for Friday use is embargoed for Sunday;
photos available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The Air Force special operations troops that stand
by to rescue pilots in Yugoslavia and other hot spots are a small
but elite team, enduring grueling training to prepare themselves
for risky work.
</P>
<P>
   When Air Force personnel rescued a downed F-117A stealth fighter
pilot Saturday, Airman 1st Class Fernando Riordan understood why
his training at Lackland Air Force Base is so hard.
</P>
<P>
   It takes a tough person to become a parajumper, or ``PJ.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the individual we're looking for, people who won't
quit,'' said Staff Sgt. Kevin Kirby, an instructor at the Air Force
special operations school in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   PJs, known also as pararescuers, begin their training at
Lackland. They handle risky assignments such as extracting downed
pilots and stranded mountain climbers, and they are trained to
rescue crews of the space shuttles.
</P>
<P>
   There are 470 pararescuers are among 359,222 active-duty Air
Force personnel. In all, 90 serve in the Air National Guard and 100
are in the Air Force Reserve, said Lt. Denise Kerr, a base
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   All Air Force pararescuers are men. Women are excluded because
the duty requires proficiency in hand-to-hand combat.
</P>
<P>
   The rigors and glories of PJ duty draw recruits like Riordan and
Senior Airman Kirby Cole to Lackland. But the school's
superintendent, Master Sgt. Rod Alne, advised that only a few will
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, around 80 students start 10 weeks of training. On
average, 65 students will wash out, one-third of them after the
first week.
</P>
<P>
   From Lackland, students must undergo 52 more weeks of grueling
training that includes airborne school at Fort Benning, Ga., and
survival training at Fairchild Air Force Base near Spokane, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Just making it through the first day at Lackland will strain
many recruits, who must swim 75 feet under water, run 1.5 miles in
10:30 minutes and do 50 situps and 50 pushups in 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they graduate, the recruits must run 6 miles in 45
minutes, swim 2.5 miles in 80 minutes and swim six, 75-foot laps
under water.
</P>
<P>
   Now in their second week, Airman Salem Simon and Riordan, 19, of
Concord, Calif., know they won't make it if they fail any test. But
both like their intense training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty much the baddest guys walking,'' Simon, 19, of
Buffalo, N.Y., said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary motto is, `That others may live,' and the other
motto that we live by, and the motto that most special operations
forces live by, is `the silent professional,''' Alne said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have to beat our chests or boast about what we've
done as long as inside we know what we are and what we can do,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has declined to discuss details of the downed
F-117A and the rescue of the American pilot in Yugoslavia, saying
that to do so could reveal sensitive information about the
radar-evading warplane.
</P>
<P>
   But at the Lackland school, the rescue is seen as a success of
the rigorous training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really excited,'' said Kirby, 29, who made an aborted
pilot rescue mission during the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they've been through this training, I know all the
training they've been through, I know the stress level they were
probably thinking, I know the adrenaline rush that's probably going
through them, and sometimes I even wish I was there with them,'' he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
