<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2813 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-NASCAR-CROSSROADS     04-01 1588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-NASCAR-CROSSROADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NASCAR's rapid growth fuels uncertain future
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Its meteoric rise from the backwoods to the big time has been
staggering for NASCAR, now in its 51st stock-car racing season.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR's growth has been unprecedented in sports, but for every
plus there's a minus, and the sport faces major issues and
decisions that will shape its future.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6 million people attended NASCAR's 33 Winston Cup
races last year, a staggering average of 190,940 fans per event,
including qualifying and races. But those fans paid an average
ticket price of around $50 and are finding that their access to the
drivers, the foundation of the sport, is deteriorating because of
corporate demands.
</P>
<P>
   The sport has taken its showcase event _ Winston Cup _ to every
corner of the nation. New tracks are being built and planned in
major markets, including Chicago, Kansas City and New York, and the
competition for race dates is intense. But drivers are concerned
about year-round racing, and the sport's established Southern race
facilities are worried about losing race dates to national
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Technology has refined the sport and created fan-pleasing
speeds, but the cost of that technology is astronomical and has
driven the single-car teams out of the sport. As a result, the
Winston Cup circuit has been dominated by two race teams, and fans
are clamoring that the playing field is not level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting scary to think about where (NASCAR's) going to be
in three or four years,'' said Richard Childress, owner of Dale
Earnhardt's No. 3 Chevrolet team.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the challenge. To say that NASCAR has reached a
crossroads is an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we've got a pretty good thing going right now,'' said
Bill France Jr., whose father founded the sport in 1949. ``We try
to protect it, and we try to preserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   But France knows it's a delicate balance.
</P>
<P>
   During the lean years, the sport was nurtured by a Southern
grass-roots following and endured because of its ability to adapt.
But times aren't lean for NASCAR in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate money is flowing, and the issues are real.
</P>
<P>
   Less access a threat
</P>
<P>
   to grass-roots loyalty
</P>
<P>
   A big reason for NASCAR's popularity has been the personality of
its drivers and their accessibility to the fans and media. NASCAR
officials say they take pride in being the only sport to offer fans
an open locker room _ the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that's gotten us where we are is our open locker
room policy,'' said Brian France, senior vice president of NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   But the influx of major corporate sponsors has put more demands
on drivers, who already are spending more time on the road and less
at their shops. The garage area has become a corporate gathering
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest problem for drivers today is the demands
on their time,'' said Ricky Rudd, owner and driver of the No. 10
Ford. ``In the late 1970s and early '80s, we'd sit on the pit wall
and sign autographs for two hours. It wasn't just Richard Petty
doing it; everybody did it. But back then, you didn't have to be
somewhere Monday or Tuesday. Now, everyone is trying to catch a
flight, because they've got somewhere to be on Monday. ... There
are more sponsors on the car now, and there are responsibilities
that come with sponsors.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Helton, NASCAR's chief operating officer, says the group
nearly instituted an autograph policy before this season. Drivers
would have been available for autographs after the race, but the
garage area, where most autographs are requested, would have been a
signature-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drivers tell us their concern is, `We don't want to be known
as guys who don't want to give an autograph,''' Helton said. ``We
were ready to take the hit and say if you do give an autograph,
we're going to penalize you.''
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon says the days spent away from
the track are what burn out most drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big sport now,'' said Gordon. ``There's a lot of
money involved, a lot of sponsors with commitments for the drivers
and the crew chiefs that keep you busy. You've got to learn how to
say no. You've got to ... make sure you're fulfilling your
commitments, but most of all you've got to fulfill your commitment
to the race team and to what really is making this all go around.''
</P>
<P>
   Access to the garage area, once a haven for fans, is now tightly
monitored. ``NASCAR has gotten so strict about who comes in the
garage area that you can't even get your own kids in anymore,''
Kyle Petty said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Petty, who owns two Winston Cup teams, says drivers are
still signing autographs, but there's not enough time to sign them
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was accessible, I was accessible to 20,000 people,'' he
said. ``These guys have to be accessible to 120,000 people. (It)
makes it a little bit different. Also, they can't get to the people
because the press is in the way. There's almost as much press now
as there used to be fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``These drivers are really operating and talking and signing
more autographs than I did, but there are so many more people that
they're missing so many. They're handling just as many people as we
ever handled. There's just so many more people that you get
complaints now that you didn't get back then.''
</P>
<P>
   Some radical ideas
</P>
<P>
   for a bigger schedule
</P>
<P>
   This year's Winston Cup schedule runs through late November and
consists of 34 points races and two non-points events. While some
owners are asking for a second race at existing speedways, several
new tracks are being planned. How big can the Winston Cup season
get?
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Bud Shootout and The Winston (non-points events),
we've got 36 weekends in '99,'' said Helton. ``The issue is, can we
make it 37 or 38 or 39? We think there is still room. We just don't
know how much room.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR obviously believes there's still plenty. International
Speedway Corp., the sister company of NASCAR, owns six tracks and
half of the facility in Martinsville, Va., and is in the early
stages of building tracks in Kansas City and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Penske Motorsports, which operates several racing facilities
with Cup races, is planning a track outside Denver. Other groups
are building or planning tracks in Baltimore, Kentucky and
Nashville. Real estate mogul Donald Trump and International
Speedway Corp., owner of Daytona, Talladega and three other tracks,
have announced plans to build a superspeedway in the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   ``NASCAR has reached such an unbelievable degree of popularity
that you have to sell it into every potential major market,'' owner
Michael Kranefuss said. ``I think we are pretty much covering the
whole of the United States, with respect to the coastal areas. But
I think the center _ Kansas City, Denver and Chicago _ is extremely
important.''
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers are apprehensive about expanding the schedule,
which already covers 40 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough deal,'' driver John Andretti said. ``You want to
grow quickly, because it's exciting to grow fast. But you want to
grow with some control, because it's easy for any business to
outgrow itself. ... As a driver, I want to race every day. If it
was strictly a driving thing, I'd say let's run four or five times
a week. Of course, that's not very realistic. The crews wouldn't be
able to keep up. You'd never have enough cars. The costs would be
astronomical.''
</P>
<P>
   France Jr. says he has no plans of taking away dates from
current track owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go to a track owner and say you need to repave your
track, he's going to say, `I'm not even sure if I'm going to have a
race next year.' It's very volatile.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruton Smith, who owns six tracks, thinks he has the answer:
splitting the sport, like baseball, into an American and National
League.
</P>
<P>
   France frowns at the idea, instead offering a proposal of
teammates sharing driving time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a cure,'' Smith said. ``You'd have to have two
leagues, then you could run 60 events, instead of the 30 or 40
you're running now. One day, if everybody in the sport wants to
grow together, they'd want to go to two leagues. It's been
discussed for three or four years now.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith says his plan, which would put one league on the East
Coast and the other on the West Coast on a given weekend, would
offer drivers more chances at seat time and victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a potential sponsor, you're interested in your car
winning,'' he said. ``Your car might win eight times in the
American League, but in the Winston Cup we're running today, you
might not finish in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the promoters and NASCAR would have to work very hard
to develop those `name drivers.' We don't know how many Jeff
Gordons or Mark Martins are out there. There are probably a lot of
great drivers out there, but they don't have the seat time.''
</P>
<P>
   France says track owners and promoters would never warm to the
idea of Gordon and Earnhardt driving on opposite sides of the
country and adds that sponsors are another important consideration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a race in Texas and Bobby Labonte isn't racing
there, the first thing that's going to happen is Joe Gibbs is going
to come to me and say he's got to be there because Excide
Batteries' corporate headquarters is there,'' France said. ``You
could never tell someone which league they're going to be in.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
