<HEADER>
A2814 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-WINSTONCUP-NOTES-     04-01 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-WINSTONCUP-NOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Several Winston Cup drivers to race this weekend
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most Winston Cup drivers are enjoying a rare weekend off for
Easter, but racing fans still can watch action in NASCAR's other
two series.
</P>
<P>
   A few Cup drivers will be competing in this weekend's BellSouth
Mobility 320 at Nashville Speedway. Among the drivers attempting to
qualify for the Busch Grand National race are Cup regulars Geoffrey
Bodine, Buckshot Jones, Kevin Lepage, Sterling Marlin, Joe
Nemecheck and Elliott Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a Winston Cup rookie from Tucker, will replace Larry
Pearson in the No. 00 Pontiac. Pearson injured his lower back in
last week's Busch race at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The Craftsman Truck series will be celebrating the 100th race in
its five-year history, in Saturday's NAPA Card 200 at Evergreen
Speedway in Monroe, Wash., 4:30 p.m., ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Five drivers _ Rick Carelli, Ron Hornaday, Butch Miller, Joe
Ruttman and Jack Sprague _ can collect a $100,000 bonus by winning
the race. They're the only drivers who have competed in every event
since the series' inception in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've raced for $100,'' Ruttman said. ``If we won, we paid our
expenses and were able to race the next week. It wasn't a lot, but
we did it for fun. That's why we still do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Drivers resting
</P>
<P>
   following injuries
</P>
<P>
   Several Winston Cup drivers can use the open date. Mike Skinner,
who fell from first to ninth in the standings points the last two
races, cracked his right shoulder blade in a hard crash last week
at Texas. It's the same shoulder Skinner injured at Texas a year
ago. He's undergoing physical therapy this week, and owner Richard
Childress will have a relief driver standing by at Bristol on April
11.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon has sore ribs and a badly bruised shoulder coming
off the worst finish of his career. Jimmy Spencer complained of
soreness after the Primestar 500 and skipped a testing session at
Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner's team
</P>
<P>
   penalized again
</P>
<P>
   It was a rough week for Skinner. His Busch team was fined by
NASCAR officials for the second time in four races, although this
fine wasn't quite as expensive. Skinner lost the winner's purse at
Atlanta last month after post-race inspection turned up illegal
cylinder heads. On Tuesday, C.R. Miller, his crew chief, was fined
$1,000 for illegal parts.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner was caught cheating after he wrecked during last
Thursday's practice. NASCAR officials found holes drilled in the
car's frame. It's one of the oldest tricks in racing and is
designed to make the metal lighter. The holes also were found in
his backup car. Skinner withdrew from this week's Nashville race.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR legend
</P>
<P>
   back to the track
</P>
<P>
   Junior Johnson, who won 50 races in 14 seasons, 1953-66, returns
to racing as a consultant for Sasser Motorsports, which makes its
debut at Nashville this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who sold his Winston Cup team to Brett Bodine in 1995,
doesn't have a financial investment in the venture and won't be
involved in the day-to-day operations. But Johnson says he'll help
the team in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some great offers to get back into racing,'' Johnson
said. ``Just six months ago, I had an offer to come back and head
up a big-time, competitive Winston Cup team. I just thanked them
for remembering me and said, `No, thanks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cook will drive the No. 65 Chevy of Sasser Motorsports,
which plans on racing in five events this year and adding a second
car next season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
