<P>
   CELLPHONES-SURVEY _ The Cellular Telecommunications Industry
Association releases its annual survey. These numbers will offer a
snapshot of astonishing growth and demonstrate the largest growth
in wireless phone subscribers in a single year since service
started in 1983. (Note, this is far from the largest increase as
far as percentages, just the largest in raw numbers. In several
years there has been a larger actual growth, based on percentage of
growth). (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DELTA-PRICELINE _ Delta Air Lines may have hit the gold mine
with Priceline.com, the latest redhot Internet stock. When Delta
agreed last year to be listed on the travel site and got options to
buy 11 million shares at $1.16 a share. The stock went public this
week at $12 and zoomed to $82. Not clear how or when Delta can
exercise the options, but right now it has a paper profit of about
$880 million. (Thurston, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ISS-STOCKS _ ISS Group, parent of Internet Security Systems,
announces two-for-one split. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATGAS-DEREG _ Natural gas deregulation has reached a new phase.
Now that 42 percent of AGL customers have chosen marketing
companies, marketers face obstacles in getting the rest. Warm
weather and low bills will remove the urgency for many consumers.
(Quinn, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   YAHOO _ Yahoo and Broadcast.com join forces to prepare for high
speed world of broadband. Conference call with press at noon.
Analysts call at 8:30 says Broadcast will remain a separate company
and deal will close Q3 1999. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ATM-SURCHARGES _ More banks are charging their
non-accountholders surcharges for using their ATMs, U.S. Public
Interest Research Group says. The number of banks imposing such
surcharges has increased dramatically in the past year to 93
percent. Overall, surcharges have increased 31 percent. (Joyner,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
