<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2821 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0402-CO     04-01 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BOSNIA-0402-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AID EFFORTS IN BOSNIA NEAR STANDSTILL
 &HT;    Moving in (i) international and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By SUSANNAH NESMITH
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia _ The NATO bombing of Yugoslavia has had the
unintended effect of paralyzing international aid efforts in the
Serb-controlled half of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our personnel that have been withdrawn from the (Serb
Republic) are very, very anxious to get back,'' said Nicole Szulc
(CQ), spokeswoman for the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe. ``They are very concerned that their work could suffer
as a result of inactivity.''
</P>
<P>
   The organization runs elections in Bosnia and conducts democracy
training for political candidates. The training has been suspended
because of the evacuation. That means the 47 staffers who have been
pulled out are unable to prepare for elections later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government has evacuated staffers working in diplomatic
and development missions in the Serb Republic, as have several
other embassies and most non-governmental organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all international projects to rebuild housing,
infrastructure and businesses and to clear mine fields have been
put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   The few agencies that are still working in the area are relying
on Bosnian Serb staffers. But even those workers are taking
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've moved our cars to safe places and we've taken down the
(sign) on our office,'' said, Milica Kakotovic (CQ BOTH), the
country director for the Oxfam relief agency.
</P>
<P>
   Since the NATO bombing began, several incidents have persuaded
international officials who didn't move initially to leave. A
library run by the Organization for Security and Cooperation in
Europe in Visegrad, a hard-line Serb town on the border with
Yugoslavia, was slightly damaged by a rifle-launched grenade
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, British and Austrian embassy field offices in
Banja Luka, the capital of the Serb Republic, were lightly damaged
Friday night by rock-throwing mobs.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations World Food Program office in Banja Luka also
was attacked recently and several U.N. vehicles have been destroyed
by grenades since the bombing began. So far, there have been no
serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that there have been a succession of events
that have increased the tension in the Serb republic,'' said Simon
Haselock, spokesman for the Office of the High Representative, the
agency in charge of implementing the Dayton Peace Accords in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compare it with other parts of the world, it is
relatively insignificant,'' he added, noting the violence has been
on a par with that of a soccer riot in England.
</P>
<P>
   The peace accords agency has left a skeleton staff in Banja
Luka, while closing five other offices.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   The evacuation comes at a particularly sensitive time in the
Serbian part of Bosnia. It has been tense since March 3, when
Carlos Westendorp (CQ), the international supervisor for Bosnia,
fired the president of the Serb Republic for actions Westendorp
said undermined the peace accords.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, international officials announced the north
Bosnia town of Brcko would be an independent district, removing it
from Serb control and effectively splitting the Serb Republic in
two.
</P>
<P>
   The two decisions prompted demonstrations throughout the Serb
Republic and protests from Serb politicians both in the Serb state
and in the national government. The most significant came from
Zivko Radisic (CQ BOTH), the chairman of the national presidency.
Radisic suspended his cooperation with the national government.
Without him the three-member presidency cannot act.
</P>
<P>
   The state government is also in crisis because the fired
president has not been replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Susannah A. Nesmith is a free-lance writer who lives in
Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
