<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 17:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2822 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAIKIKI-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      04-01 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAIKIKI-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY BOOMERS DISCOVER ONCE-SHUNNED WAIKIKI 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With WAIKIKI-IF-GO)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN FLINN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAIKIKI, Oahu _ Sunset is falling on Diamond Head, outrigger
canoes are surfing in on the day's last wave and up and down
Waikiki Beach, tiki torches are flickering to life.
</P>
<P>
   At the Halekulani Hotel's House Without a Key bar, a genteel,
older crowd is sipping orchid-laced mai tais and watching former
Miss Hawaii Kanoe Miller dance a sensuous hula as Sonny Kamahele
and the Islanders play ``Little Grass Shack.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the beach, at Duke's Canoe Club, the dance floor is a
roiling sea of taut, bronzed flesh _ buff young surfers sporting
Maori tattoos on their bare backs and women with pieced navels in
thong bikinis.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously missing from this scene is one group: baby
boomers. My generation has generally made a point of skipping
Waikiki, shuddering at the highrise hotels and crowded beaches as
we hurry to board our connecting flights to Maui or Kauai.
</P>
<P>
   Curious to see what we've been missing all these years, I
recently visited Waikiki, armed with my friend Lynn Ferrin's
advice: ``If you think of it as an idyllic beach spoiled by
development, you'll probably hate it. But if you think of it as a
vibrant Pacific city with the best beach of any city in the world,
you'll have a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   I went looking for the Hawaii of my parents' generation, a
Hawaii that the twentysomething cocktail-culture crowd is
rediscovering: The Waikiki of the old Matson Liners, of
floral-print aloha shirts and grass skirt hulas, of tiki bars and
umbrella drinks and Don Ho.
</P>
<P>
   City officials have recently begun to play up this theme,
instituting a sunset torch-lighting ceremony along Kalakaua Avenue,
Waikiki's main drag, and reviving the old Boat Days celebrations,
in which arriving and departing cruise ships are greeted by hula
dancers, leis tossed into the water, choruses of ``Aloha 'oe,'' and
_ if the logistics can be worked out _ coin divers.
</P>
<P>
   My first stop was a ramshackle old store in a semi-residential
neighborhood, five blocks from the beach. For lovers of classic
aloha shirts, Bailey's Antiques is Lourdes, Mecca and
Bloomingdale's all rolled into one: a dizzying, floor-to-ceiling
sartorial celebration of palm trees, hula dancers, pineapples,
orchid leis, long-board surfers, tiki heads, Pan Am Clippers,
ukuleles and erupting volcanoes.
</P>
<P>
   Racks sag under the weight of more than 5,000 aloha shirts, from
original 1940s beauties that sell for $2,500 and more, to
floral-print cotton and rayon designs, to shimmering new silk
reproductions of the old classics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1940s were the golden age of aloha shirts,'' explained
owner David Bailey as he led me past display cases of dashboard
hula dolls and used Hilo Hattie records. ``In the '70s, the Tom
Selleck orchid look took over and things went into the doldrums.
Now they've started to reproduce the old ones, and the aloha shirt
is having a renaissance.''
</P>
<P>
   After agonized deliberation _ I was tempted by a dazzling copy
of the Frank MacIntosh design that Matson Line waiters wore in the
1940s _ I chose a tasteful ginger blossom design on a tangerine
background, an early '50s pattern reproduced on luscious silk.
</P>
<P>
   I was wearing it as I strode into the open-air lobby of the
Halekulani Hotel. To my parents' and grandparents' generations,
there were just three Waikiki hotels worth considering: the pink,
Moorish Royal Hawaiian; the colonial, banyon tree-shaded Moana
Surfrider (now a Sheraton) and the five-diamond Halekulani, which
was modernized and expanded with a substantial makeover in the
early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   To enter these classic hotels is to step through a portal into
another place and time. One leaves the frazzle and dazzle of
Kalakaua Avenue behind and joins a more refined, trade wind-cooled
world that hasn't changed much in style since the days when waiters
and clerks paddled outrigger canoes out to ocean liners to present
arriving guests with leis.
</P>
<P>
   The Halekulani is famed for its service. Guests register not at
the front counter, but in their rooms. Chocolates, fruit bowls and
miniature conch shell souvenirs are delivered to all guests _ VIPs
and civilians alike. From our balcony, Jeri and I could look down
Waikiki Beach to Diamond Head, watch surfers riding the waves and
listen to the ukulele-backed harmonies of Sonny Kamahele and the
Islanders bubbling up from the terrace below. I was already
beginning to suspect I hadn't given Waikiki a fair chance all these
years.
</P>
<P>
   If there's one person who has come to embody this corner of
Hawaii, it's Don Ho, the ``Dean Martin of Waikiki,'' who's been
performing nightly here for more than 35 years. In the evening we
crossed Kalakaua Avenue to the Waikiki Beachcomber Hotel, where we
found a table in the Hoku Hale Showroom and ordered a round of mai
tais.
</P>
<P>
   It was a full house, and the crowd was a microcosm of Waikiki:
Lots of white-haired septuagenarians in matching shirts and
muumuus, plus a smattering of young Rat Pack wannabes who revere Ho
the way they do Tony Bennett and swing music. In recent years,
members of such alternative bands as Green Day, Porno for Pyros and
Foo Fighters have dropped by to catch Ho's show.
</P>
<P>
   After posing for pictures out in the lobby, Ho sauntered out
onto the stage, took a seat behind a console in a big
Morticia-style wicker chair and launched straight into his biggest
hit:
</P>
<P>
   Tiny bubbawwws
</P>
<P>
   In da wine
</P>
<P>
   Make me happy
</P>
<P>
   Make me feel fine
</P>
<P>
   ``I sing `Tiny Bubbles' twice each night,'' he told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once, at the beginning, in case some of you don't make it all
the way through the show. And again at the end, for people my age
who can't remember if we've done it already.''
</P>
<P>
   The evening was a surprisingly endearing mix of old Hawaii
standards _ ``Pearly Shells,'' ``Shack Down By the Sea'' _ corny
jokes and audience participation. ``Sing a song, tell a joke or buy
the round a house,'' Ho announced. Free champagne was sent to the
tables of couples married 50 years or more _ there were at least
half a dozen of them on this night _ veterans, current members of
the military, newlyweds, anyone celebrating a birthday and, it
seemed, just about everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   The following day Ho agreed to show me around his Waikiki. We
walked down Kalakaua Avenue to the International Marketplace, where
Ho made his reputation playing at the original site of Duke's in
the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were lined up all the way out to the street, and we'd
play until 3:30 in the morning,'' he said. ``This was the center of
the universe in the '60s. Any celebrity passing through town would
come by to sit in with us _ one night we'd have Marlon Brando
beating on the congas; the next night it would be Bill Cosby. Frank
Sintra, Sammy Davis, Jr., Bob Hope _ they'd all end up on stage
with us.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Ho why he thought the baby-boom generation abandoned
Waikiki.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're to blame,'' Ho said of himself and his contemporaries.
``In the '60s and '70s we told them to get out of here and go to
the outer islands _ and they never came back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the next generation seems like they're bored with the
outer islands. They're coming back here because this is where the
nightlife is, where the action is. I've been around long enough to
know these things go in cycles. Nowadays, with the younger people,
the honeymooners still go to Maui _ but the singles all come to
Waikiki.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ho, who still keeps an eye on the local club scene, likes the
new Duke's, Rumors, Scruples and Esprit for nightlife. And, of
course, the Waikiki Beachcomber. ``Almost every night we get
someone in their 20s who says, `My grandmother told me I had to
come see you,''' Ho said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   heading toward Diamond Head, we reached the beach-side statue of
Duke Kahanamoku, ``the father of international surfing,'' with his
hands outstretched papally and draped with flower leis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where we'd hang out surfing all day,'' Ho recalled.
``In the evening we'd sit around and get out the ukuleles and make
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho remembers Kalakaua Avenue in the 1950s and '60s as a rowdy
place, where you'd often find sailors fighting in the street
outside the bars. Today it's lined with ABC stores (the ubiquitous
suntan lotion-and-beach towel shops; if you're not standing
directly in front of one, move 10 steps in either direction and you
will be) and shimmering, rarefied boutiques with the buffed-brass
nameplates of Cartier, Gucci, Prada, Chanel, Ferragamo and Tiffany.
The price tags are all in Japanese, but the stores are virtually
empty these days. As one clerk lamented to me: ``The Japanese are
still coming, but they're not spending like they used to. They're
not shopping here; they're heading to the outlets.''
</P>
<P>
   The following day Jeri and I strolled down Waikiki Beach on
powdery white sand that for years has been barged in from the
island of Molokai, because hotel sea walls have altered the natural
process of sand accretion. We wove our way in and out of sunbathing
families of Japanese tourists (the clerk was right about that
part); basted, pinkening Midwesterners; knots of local surfers and
young hipsters who appeared to be sleeping off hangovers. This is
hardly the beach for solitude, but for people-watching it's tough
to beat.
</P>
<P>
   At a little thatch-roofed beach shack next to the Royal
Hawaiian, we stopped to take advantage of one of the greatest
tourist bargains in Hawaii _ or anywhere else, for that matter: an
outrigger canoe ride.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Waikiki tradition even older than Don Ho. I've seen
paintings of tourists riding outriggers in the 1920s and '30s, and
except for the addition of some highrise hotels it hasn't changed a
bit. Nor, it seems, has the price: You still get to ride three
waves for $5.
</P>
<P>
   While we waited for a few others to sign up, we chatted with
Dickie C-Kee, who's worked at the shack for more than 30 years and
once, he said, taught Frank Sinatra to surf.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come and go, but Waikiki is pretty much the same
place,'' he said. ``Same beach, same surf.''
</P>
<P>
   When three other tourists showed up, a muscled, tattooed beach
boy named Eddie had us drag the long, narrow canoe into the
bathtub-warm water, slide in and start paddling out toward the
surf: 14 strokes on the left, 14 on the right _ just like in the
Don Ho song.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining speed, we smacked into the face of an incoming wave and
were briefly airborne before landing with a splash that soaked
everyone. Out beyond the break, where the surfers sat on their
boards and waited, we turned around and let several swells pass
beneath us before Eddie gave the order to start paddling.
</P>
<P>
   The next swell suddenly lifted the tail of the canoe, and there
was an giddying surge of acceleration as we caught the wave and
hurtled toward shore. A rainbow arched over Diamond Head, the pink
towers of the Royal Hawaiian glowed in the late-afternoon sun _ and
if there was more fun to be had anywhere for $5, I would like to
know about it.
</P>
<P>
   At sunset I ambled back down the beach to the Duke Kahanamoku
statue. As night began to fall, three bare-chested Hawaiian men in
red wrap-around skirts and ceremonial yellow shoulder-coverings
blew on conch shells and began lighting the tiki torches along
Kalakaua Avenue. At a nearby stage, young girls wearing leis and
flowers in their hair danced a hula to ``Little Grass Shack'' _
there's no escaping the song in Waikiki _ before a crowd of
delighted tourists armed with lawn chairs and camcorders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
