<HEADER>
A2826 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CAPTIVES02-COX     04-01 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CAPTIVES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOLDIERS' CAPTURE LIKELY TO SWAY PUBLIC OPINION _ BUT HOW?
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The capture of three U.S. soldiers by Yugoslav
forces will bring the war home to Americans, but their plight could
shift public opinion either for or against President Clinton's
policy, experts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Americans awoke Friday to televised images of the bruised and
battered faces of Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles;
Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., and
Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 24, of Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Images have a great impact,'' said Lou Klarevas, a George
Washington University foreign policy professor who studied how
public opinion affected the ill-fated 1993 peacekeeping mission to
Somalia. ``It puts an American human face on the conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   After Americans saw scenes of an American soldier's corpse being
dragged through the dust of Mogadishu and the beaten face of U.S.
helicopter pilot Michael Durant, support for the Somalia mission
plummeted.
</P>
<P>
   But there was disagreement whether this week's captures have the
potential to erode public backing for the NATO strikes in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing the captured soldiers ``makes people uncomfortable. It
makes them mad,'' said Steve Kull, pollster for the Program for
International Policy Attitudes at the University of Maryland's
Center for International Security Studies. ``It dampens their
enthusiasm for the mission, but doesn't necessarily lead them to
want to withdraw.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently, public interest in the Kosovo mission is high and
support has been growing, Kull said. ``The public is more likely to
feel angry'' over the soldiers' capture, he predicted, leading to
more interest and more support.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Sands, an analyst for the Center for Strategic and
International Studies, said the opposite effect was possible.
</P>
<P>
   If the public feels ``we are winning'' in Yugoslavia, it will be
willing to accept some casualties, Sands said _ as was true in the
Persian Gulf conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But people will react differently ``if the intangible sense is
that we are losing,'' Sands said, adding, ``I think the intangible
sense is that this isn't going very well. That makes people want
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodding Carter, the State Department spokesman during the Carter
administration, said the eventual policy effect of the captured
Americans ``depends almost entirely on how the administration plays
it'' and how the news media reacts.
</P>
<P>
   Carter administration officials spoke often about American
hostages in Iran and the news media focused on the issue, he said.
The Reagan administration, by contrast, ``decided never to talk''
about American hostages being held in Beirut and ``the media could
not sustain coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that three American soldiers being held by the
enemy in a multi-nation mission to stop the killing of thousands of
ethnic Albanians, Carter said. ``In what context do you place this?
If the administration stands steady, they will overcome it with
policy _ if they have a policy to overcome it with.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
