 UPDATE &HT;    UPDATE
 &HT;    Eds; Adds: MEXICO-MURDERS, KOSOVO-CAPTIVES, KOSOVO-JOURNAL,
KOSOVO-BOSNIA, WINNING, ESCORTS, CAPTURED-GONZALES ;
 &HT;    Updates: KOSOVO-STRIKES, KOSOVO-CLINTON
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Friday, April 2, 1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA, KOSOVO CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ Yugoslavia threatens to place
three captured American soldiers on trial friday; other military
and refugee developments in the NATO strikes against Yugoslavia.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/KOSOVO-CLINTON _ NORFOLK, Va. _ President Clinton warned
Yugoslavia on Thursday to treat three captured soldiers with care
and to ``make no mistake: the United States takes care of its
own.'' Clinton's speech to military families here was largely
devoted to defending NATO's conduct of the war. (Shepard, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   CAPTURED-GONZALES _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Trying to find out what we
can about Steven Gonzales, the soldier from Huntsville who is
missing in Macedonia. Gonzales was a well-liked, academically
gifted high school student who left Texas A&AMP;M after his freshman
year because he wanted to join the elite Army Ranger corps.
(Kelley, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CAPTIVES _ WASHINGTON _ Until now, the American bombing
campaign in Yugoslavia has been a distant news event for most
Americans. But the capture of three U.S. soldiers in Yugoslavia,
and their appearance on Serb television, suddenly has brought the
conflict home. Will the images of captured Army soldiers stir
public sentiment as it did when U.S. soldiers were captured in the
Gulf War? And how might that translate into pressure on the Clinton
administration? (Dart, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JOURNAL _ KUKES, Albania _ The human suffering of the
thousands of Kosovar Albanian refugees pouring across the border
into Albania is an emotional sight for even hardened reporters. Cox
Newspapers correspondent Bert Roughton Jr. offers a personal view
of the event he is covering. (Roughton, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOSNIA _ SARAJEVO, Bosnia _ The NATO bombing of
Yugoslavia has had the unintented effect of partially paralyzing
international efforts in neighboring Bosnia. Most international
officials and aid workers have pulled out of the Serb-controlled
half of Bosnia, suspending operations there and closing their
offices. (Nesmith, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CNN _ ATLANTA _ Behind the scenes at CNN for coverage of
Kosovo. We concentrate on the International Desk, sort of the air
traffic controllers of CNN coverage, a multi-national, multilingual
bunch who work in the trenches. (Kloer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-MURDERS _ MEXICO CITY _ A man linked to a rash of
unsolved murders of women in Juarez confessed in court Thursday to
violently assaulting a 14-year-old girl who escaped from him. The
suspect, Jesus Manuel Guardado Marquez, was a bus driver who
ferried women to the city's maquiladora factories. He has
implicated eight other drivers in murders there. Meanwhile, U.S.
authorities are investigating whether a man arrested for sexual
torture crimes in New Mexico _ not far from Juarez _ could have
also committed some of the murders in Juarez. (Ferris, Cox News
Service) Moving in international and general news categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   VIDALIA-ILLEGALWORKERS _ The spring harvest of south Georgia's
famed sweet Vidalia onions _ scheduled to begin in about two weeks
_ may dodge the bitter conflicts that erupted in the fields last
year when government agents swooped down to round up workers they
suspected of being illegal aliens. Hundreds, perhaps thousands, of
workers fled and part of the $90 million crop died in the dirt.
Now, growers are taking steps to hire only legal workers this year,
experts say. (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   GALOTTO-RECORD _ Tonight's giant jackpot, the largest ever in
Georgia, will join the growing trove of state lottery lore. Among
the fascinating tales: the woman who sent a copy of her winning
ticket to her ex-hubby; the man who waited six months to collect
because he had spent his money too quickly the first time he won;
the woman who won $8.5 million, but still bought her wardrobe at
Dollar General because ``I just don't see spending any more money
than you have to''; and the worst odds in the history of the Big
Game _ tonight's. (Steiden, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   w/WINNING _ What to do ``when'' you win the $150 mill. Tongue in
cheek, obviously, but with real advice on such things as whether to
take lump sum or anual payments; what to tell people asking for a
handout; what to do about your security; whether to quit your job;
who NOT to tell. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ESCORTS _ CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ As hundreds of cars queued for the
short drive to bury Kenneth Swayney, his widow, Theresa, looked
back from the family car and smiled ruefully. So many cared, she
thought, feeling comforted. That memory compelled the usually
reserved Swayney into a City Council committee meeting here
recently to fight for a dying Southern tradition: police escorts
that enable mourners to form a procession from funeral home or
church to the cemetery. (Riddle, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
