</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FANS DEMAND JUSTICE FOR `VENGEANCE UNLIMITED'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The letters arrive in bunches, tersely worded and tightly
written, double- and single-spaced, long and short, computer-formal
and ballpoint-pen-scribbled. All expound on the dramatically
pleasing virtues of a television series that few tube voyeurs have
bothered to sample.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vengeance Unlimited,'' the low-rated drama starring Michael
Madsen as a mysterious vigilante who exacts terrifying revenge to
aid the wronged, is dying a torturous death at the hands of a
less-than-patient ABC. Those feeling the potential loss are making
a last-ditch effort to snatch the drama from the jaws of
cancellation, to reverse a decision that has probably already been
made.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's programming gurus continue to say publicly how much they
``like'' and ``believe in'' the series; that the last thing they
want to do is take an ax to its knees and watch it fall.
</P>
<P>
   Having heard this rhetoric before (only the name of the show
changes) the show's producers and viewers have banded together in
an intriguing tag team, reaching out to network chiefs Jamie Tarses
and Stu Bloomberg by asking TV critics, writers and other media
observers to take another look and make another evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   A sort of critical do-over, if you will. They hope this campaign
will remind ABC that critically acclaimed productions should be
held to different rules.
</P>
<P>
   This campaign started innocently enough: The acerbic critic of
Entertainment Weekly backpedaled on his earlier thrashing of the
drama, which he called an ``admirably lunatic attempt'' by a
hit-hungry network wanting to counterprogram against NBC's
``Friends.'' That comedy proceeded to rip ``Vengeance'' to ratings
shreds. (ABC's spin is that the series did well in targeted demos.)
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just EW's Ken Tucker who thought Madsen's portrayal of
a guy referred to only as ``Mr. Chapel'' was something from the
dark side of a bar stool. Just as fair was the media's questioning
of whether audiences would accept a shady character who seemed to
be teetering on the fringes of sheer madness.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker's reversal came via EW's online service; a printed
version of his piece is tucked into the envelope of each letter
I've received.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign asserts that reviewers had watched one, maybe two
of the 16 episodes, made their critical call and went back to
watching and touting ``ER'' and HBO's ``The Sopranos,'' cinematic
pleasures that quickened the pulse from the start.
</P>
<P>
   This irks ``Vengeance'' co-creator John McNamara and other
producers whose pilots are panned early and left to die, giving
networks reasons to put promotional dollars elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a show is good and it gets better,'' says McNamara, whose
previous credits are ``Profit'' and the delicious ``Spy Game.''
``People will find it because it's so much crap out there. But
they've got to be ``told'' that it's there from the network and
from critics. Otherwise you're taking away what's so glorious about
series television: the ability to improve on the design.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike films, television shows are living mechanisms, evolving,
having good nights and bad, deepening, softening, becoming more
character-driven, more demographically astute, etc.
</P>
<P>
   A theory on ``Vengeance'' is that viewers and critics were
thrown by a series featuring a hero who basically tortures people
and asks us to be amused by it. McNamara insisted on infusing the
series with black comedy, which is fine, but viewers need to stay
with the show to actually ``get'' it.
</P>
<P>
   The sad fact for producers is that we as viewers and critics
rarely return to a series that fails to get our attention in the
first few minutes, let alone the first few episodes. It's a result
of the dizzying wealth of programming offered to us and how a
remote control has become a network executive's worst nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vengeance'' is now in a precarious position. The last of the
show's allotted 16 episodes aired Feb. 25, so there's nothing for
viewers to go on. Judging from some stories I've seen in the past
week, the Save-This-Show campaign has indeed fired up critics, who
are now hyping the show they helped de-hype just a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, it's not as though Tarses and Bloomberg can look
at Nielsen numbers and see how the show has improved. And don't
count on the ``critically acclaimed'' equation helping out. It
didn't help ``Nothing Sacred'' or ``Cracker'' or ``Maximum Bob'' or
``Cupid'' or ... you get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
