<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW WHAT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: INSERTS the word Serbian before Internet in the 11th graf.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Kosovo war could be the unmaking of Vice
President Al Gore, who is stuck with defending the administration's
policy, and the making of GOP presidential candidate John McCain,
who is free to be a tough-minded hawk without bearing
responsibility for any mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Such a scenario, of course, is vastly premature, although the
armchair generals are already on television second-guessing the
bombing and finding it militarily inadequate, politically unwise
and a tragic repetition of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's critics have not had the courage to call for
NATO to retreat and completely abandon the Kosovar Alabanians being
forced from their homes and their country by Yugoslavia's
bloodthirsty President Slobodan Milosevic. Instead they have been
picking away at the president's already damaged credibility,
questioning his judgment, NATO's timing, the apparent lack of an
exit strategy and public confusion about just why we are there.
</P>
<P>
   The administration may have a window of two weeks in which to
sell the U.S.-led intervention in the Balkans to the voters and
demonstrate that an expanded bombing strategy may yet work without
resorting to ground troops. After that, Congress returns from its
traditional spring recess, and the doubting voices now on vacation
may be raised in unison against the commander-in-chief's
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, both the president and vice president, fully aware
that public opposition to the Vietnam War was partially due to
President Lyndon Johnson's failure to explain its strategic
importance, are making a concerted effort to articulate the reasons
behind the bombing campaign. And despite the professed puzzlement
of doves and Clinton-bashers, there are indeed powerful reasons _
humanitarian, economic and strategic.
</P>
<P>
   Accusations that the bombing campaign precipitated and
accelerated Milosovic's cruelty are reckless and uninformed. In
fact, the opposite is true. NATO started too late and probably with
too little.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction of House Majority Leader Richard Armey, R-Tex, was
typical of the armchair generals. He whined that Clinton ``had not
made the effective case about how American interests are vitally
affected.''
</P>
<P>
   What would Armey have us do if he feels no American interests
are involved? Pull a cowardly retreat, give up our claim to being
the world's greatest superpower, reaffirm Milosevic's dictatorship,
encourage Balkan instability and leave the Kosovars to their fate
as stateless, homeless people? Stick our heads in the sand?
</P>
<P>
   There is convincing evidence that Milosevic had been plotting
the massive obliteration of the ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo
since at least October. But President Clinton and Congress were
preoccupied with the 1998 election and the impeachment charade. By
the time they got around to confronting the Balkan reality, 40,000
Serbian troops were massed for a rampage in Kosovo, peace
negotiations had collapsed and there was no alternative to military
action.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the bombing campaign to immediately bring
Milosevic to his knees is disappointing but not proof that we are
permanently militarily impotent. Clinton justifiably complained in
an interview March 31 with CBS' Dan Rather that ``everybody wants
things to operate like a 30-second ad. This air campaign is not a
30-second ad.''
</P>
<P>
   But in an era when e-mail allows Kosovars to reach the outside
world and Serbian Internet hackers can cripple NATO's Web site for
several days, air campaigns cannot go on forever without definitive
results.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to the 2000 presidential campaign, which does
come close to being a 30-second ad, at least in the sense that at
this early stage quick favorable impressions can make a difference.
And the candidate most worth listening to is McCain, the former
Vietnam POW who has a reputation for courageous domestic views and
military common sense.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's reactions have been remarkably sound and persuasive. No
beating around the bush here, waiting for public opinion to jell.
He says we have a strategic interest in the Balkans and that it is
pointless to look backward toward what might have happened had we
acted differently earlier.
</P>
<P>
   In USA Today, McCain says, ``We must all keep our nerve. We are
the superior power, and any sign of hesitation or doubt on our part
will only worsen the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not afraid to suggest the deployment of ground troops, a
dangerous escalation that the administration still publicly
opposes. (Although Clinton and his advisers have conspicuously
never said ``never.'')
</P>
<P>
   In his article, McCain calls for an immediate ``manifold
increase in the violence'' against Serbia proper and the Serb
forces in Kosovo. He warns that there will be ``significant ''
civilian casualties in Belgrade and American deaths as well, but he
believes the sacrifice is necessary for the cause. ``We must use
all the force necessary to hasten this war's end,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Gore echoes the administration policy of barring the use of
American ground troops. Campaigning in New Hampshire this week, he
said we would not ``put troops into a combat situation over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the current bombing strategy continues to have little
effect, political pressure will grow on the administration and NATO
to send in troops on the ground to counter the Serbian bullies and
allow the ethnic Albanians to return.
</P>
<P>
   Troops in large numbers would be a difficult decision in any
case. No president likes to put young men and women in harm's way.
But it is emotionally wrenching and politically troublesome for a
president who ducked a regional war (Vietnam) when he was expected
to fight it now having to justify a different war when he asks
others to fight it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet we elect presidents to make tough decisions. If they were
easy, we could make them ourselves. Clinton must do what is
necessary, as McCain urges.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
