</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Jekyll Island, GA. _ The 22nd Annual Great Golden Easter Egg
Hunt on Saturday features a traditional Easter egg hunt, a visit by
the Easter bunny, live entertainment and a variety of family
activities at the Pier Road Shops off Stable Road in the Historic
District. The Georgia Egg Commission supplies 10,000 eggs that will
be dyed in Easter colors and distributed free at the end of the
event. 1-877-453-5955 or www.jekyllisland.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lakeland, Fla. _ The final performances of the Black Hills
Passion Play are Thursday through Sunday at Carpenter's Home
Church. Tickets $15 in advance or $17 at the door; $8 for children
11 and under. 1-888-859-8877, Ext. 113, 117.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jacksonville _ The World Beat Music Fest '99 at ALLTEL Stadium
Friday through Sunday includes soca, Latin, calypso, reggae,
Caribbean and African music, along with a World Market Place
offering international foods and an exhibition of arts, crafts and
gift items from around the world. 904-617-1532.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cullman, Ala. _ The Semi-Annual Bluegrass Superjam celebrates
its 35th anniversary Friday and Saturday with concerts by the
Osborne Brothers, the Legendary Country Gentlemen, Mac Wiseman and
Ralph Stanley and his Clinch Mountain Boys. At the Cullman
Agricultural Trade Center. 256-734-0454 (Cullman Area Chamber of
Commerce); 256-739-4959 (Trade Center).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Theodore, Ala. _ More than 250,000 azaleas are on display
through April 15 at Bellingrath Garden's Spring Spectacular. Guests
can view the dazzling flora from the azalea pathway and from river
cruises. 334-973-2217.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Winnsboro, S.C. _ Hop aboard the ``Easter Bunny Eggspress''
Saturday and ride the rails with the Easter bunny on
``eggcursions'' from the South Carolina Railroad Museum. Also,
guided tours of antique rolling stock and an indoor exhibit about
the state's railroad stations. 1-800-968-5909.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston, S.C. _ The 52nd Annual Festival of Houses and
Gardens, through April 17, offers visitors a glimpse of elegant
homes and gardens in Charleston's historic district. Festivalgoers
also can partake in three Lowcountry plantation oyster roasts.
1-843-722-3405.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbia _ Works of the Charleston Renaissance, created in
Charleston between 1915 through the 1940s, are the subject of a
major exhibition at the Columbia Museum of Art, Saturday through
June 6. 803-799-2810.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vicksburg, Miss. _ The 25th Annual Vicksburg Spring Pilgrimage
showcases the town's antebellum homes through Saturday.
1-800-221-3536.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Natchez, Miss. _ The Natchez Spring Pilgrimage, a tour of 31
pre-Civil War mansions, continues through April 10. Daily tours
include the Confederate Pageant, which features performers in
period costumes. 1-800-647-6742.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbus, Miss. _ The 1999 Spring Pilgrimage, Thursday through
April 11, features 12 houses, including the Williams-Gass Home,
built in the early 1840s by two ``free men of color,'' along with
the typical antebellum homes of the Southern aristocracy.
1-800-327-2686 or www.historic-columbus.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eufaula, Ala. _ The 34th annual Eufaula Pilgrimage and Antique
Show is April 9-11. In addition to tours of historic homes and
churches, there will be a candlelight tasting, ``Tales From the
Tomb'' (storytelling at Fairview Cemetery), a needlework display,
an outdoor art show and concerts. 1-888-383-2852.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The Biltmore Estate presents its annual
Festival of Flowers, Friday through May 2, ushering in spring with
more than 10 acres of formal gardens in bloom. 1-800-543-2961.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ The Southern Highland Craft Guild presents
works by Laura Sims (marbling) and Jim Charneski (metal jewelry) in
the Folk Art Center's Focus Gallery through May 5. 828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Durham, N.C. _ The DoubleTake Documentary Film Festival, April
8-11, a program of the Center for Documentary Studies at Duke
University, features curated programs including ``Documentary as
Witness: The Great Films of the 20th Century'' and ``A World
Without Limits,'' a series of films shown in collaboration with the
Special Olympics, focusing on the issues and achievements of the
disabled. 919-660-3699; 1-800-334-1085 (for travel information).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Knoxville _ The Dogwood Arts Festival April 9-25 includes
visual arts, dance, music and 60 miles of dogwood trails.
423-637-4561 or www.knoxvilletennessee.com/DogwoodArtsFestival/.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
