<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2851 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-FALLTRENDS04-CO     04-01 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-FALLTRENDS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fall fundamentals
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, April 4.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Something ``old,'' something ``new,'' something ``borrowed,''
something . . . ``whew!''
</P>
<P>
   When the time comes for trend-conscious women to reassemble
their cold-weather wardrobes, many may find the task as daunting as
planning a wedding.
</P>
<P>
   The top designers of New York and Europe, who recently completed
a monthlong series of fall/winter runway previews for the 1999-2000
season, seemed to agree on the fundamental trends. But the trends
they agreed on were so plentiful that filtering through them still
won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   The surest way to greet the next fall/winter season in style is
to first decide which essentials you need to complement your
lifestyle, body type and existing wardrobe. The numbers, after all,
are in your favor: There are so many trendy colors, cuts and
materials coming that there has to be at least one that'll suit you
just fine.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A cautionary note: Orange was the most alarmingly popular
color shown on the runways. And that's indicative of what fashion
is about. Designers exist to enact new ``laws'' from season to
season. So, while the color orange's ``fresh squeezed'' appeal is
certain to refresh your wardrobe for a season, don't overdo it.
``Grape'' could soon replace ``orange'' as the shade with the most
juice. The other standout colors included camel, cream, red, green,
brown and blue. Patterns with the most punch included paisley,
geometric or floral embroidery, and buffalo plaid.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Border patrol: Here's an arresting thought: You could escape
the fashion police's scrutiny all season _ no matter the cut, color
or material of your clothes _ as long as they're trimmed
attractively at the cuffs, seams, waistbands or hems. Most
designers showed something trimmed in lace, scalloped, beaded,
embroidered, whip-stitched or fringed, in hopes of shaking the
minimalism-minded into buying something new.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stretched-arm strong: One way to fortify your wardrobe is to
buy a top or jacket with sleeves that extend over the hands. You'll
hear much from now on about the ``utility'' features that designers
want to supply the millennial woman with, and these hyper-extended
sleeves are one example. They help ward off the cold, just in case
you forget your gloves.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Paper or plastic? Designers placed such emphasis on body
pouches, shoulder purses and handbags that a new one, in any shape
or material, looks like a must.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Waist not? Want not: Don't even try to wear the trendiest look
in pants _ ``Charlie's Angels'' tight and low in the seat, snug in
the thigh and flared from the knee down _ unless you fall somewhere
below the nation's average pant size for women. That pretty much
excludes everyone from size 14 up. But so what? Read on.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Loose-tongued: Fortunately for the majority of women,
designers seemed well-versed in the look known in the industry as
``stealth wealth.'' That means loungey pants in luxe fabrics such
as cashmere. They're for women who look as if they wield enough
power to define propriety of dress for boardrooms or dinner parties
on their own terms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Skirting the issue: There's no getting around the fact that
designers emphasized skirts over pants. And who can blame them?
Skirts can be cut thigh-high or floor-length, slit every
which-a-way and tailored tight or loose. In skirts, women have the
ultimate ``all-inclusive'' trend.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hemming and hawing: But honestly, most buyers and editors
attending the shows either laughed or stared dumbfounded at how
high some designers hemmed skirts for the fall/winter season. If
cold-weather considerations didn't enter their minds, codes of
decency should have.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Shirts leave: Watch the most stylish women you know and notice
how they've downsized the number of blouses they wear. That trend
continues, with sweaters, tanks and tunics, in delicious fabrics.
And sweaters can be woven so snugly and sheerly these days that the
phrase ``nothing at all'' applies quite often.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hide nor hare: No fur or skin escaped designers' notice.
Shearling coats were shown so often that they got to be boring. Fur
trim was everywhere, as was leather, which was treated as a
wardrobe staple akin to wool. And chances are that next March, when
the Academy Awards roll around, you'll see some starlet wearing
something that could be aptly described as ``that Oscar-winning
wabbit!''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Blanket statements: Like Linus, designers seemed infatuated
with blankets. They quilted down-filled coats, suits and separates
and threw ruggy wraps around waists and shoulders. If anything
shows how interwined designers' home and apparel collections have
become, it's these looks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Neck and neck: The throat area was featured prominently.
Designers played a ``now you see it, now you don't'' game in which
necklines plunged nearly to the navel or the turtlenecks of
sweaters were cut amply enough to serve as face guards in a
snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Given the boot: Accept what designers are doing in the way of
footwear graciously, ladies. They show their realization that you
like high heels _ for the mere idea of them _ but most are showing
shoes with flattened heels and all-purpose soles. It's that
``utility'' factor again. But it's an ``all-inclusive'' look as
well. Buy a pair of knee-high boots if you buy nothing else at all.
Worn with a skirt that's knee length or higher, they look swell on
most women.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
