<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2852 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-GETAWAY04-COX     04-01 1472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-GETAWAY04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    History is big draw in New Bern
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BERN, N.C. _ According to an old witticism, North Carolina
is a vale of humility between two mountains of conceit. The
mountains _ Virginia and South Carolina _ are renowned for a pride
in heritage that can border on ancestor worship. Everyone knows
about their original capitals, Williamsburg and Charleston: one a
sort of colonial stage set, the other perhaps the most
history-obsessed city in the South.
</P>
<P>
   But can you name the first capital of North Carolina? Unless
you're a native Tar Heel, the name of New Bern probably doesn't
roll off your tongue. Compared to its better-known peers, this
serene city of 15,000 is as easy to miss as a whisper in a roomful
of blowhards.
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad, because it would be a shame to miss New Bern. It
may be the most charming spot on the Southern seaboard that you've
never heard of.
</P>
<P>
   The clock towers and church steeples of New Bern rise from the
picturesque triangle of land where the Neuse and Trent rivers meet,
30 miles inland from the Outer Banks. Park the car. Dock the boat.
The 20-block historic district was made for strolling, with its
shady sidewalks and pocket parks and cozy shop windows and
gingerbread-trimmed homes garnished with azalea and crape myrtle.
(Fourteen of the most impressive residences _ dating from 1748 to
1922 _ will be open to the public during the annual spring tour
April 9-10.)
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't the homes that drew my eye when I first strolled
New Bern last fall. It was the bears. They're everywhere: in public
statues, on gift shop shelves, on the doors of police cars. There's
even a snarling bear bust jutting out of a wall at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The bears are a historical pun, I soon found out _ a reference
to the city's founding in 1710 by Swiss and German immigrants who
named it for Bern, Switzerland. ``Bern'' comes from the German word
for bear. A few years ago, New Bern's downtown redevelopment agency
(Swiss Bear Inc.!) decided it would be fun to fill the town with
bears, scary and whimsical. It didn't stop there.
</P>
<P>
   Swiss Bear has been at the forefront of a revitalization
movement that has seen dozens of buildings rehabilitated, sidewalks
and underground utilities constructed, and acres of derelict
riverfront reclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place used to be a disaster,'' says the agency's
director, Susan Moffat.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a new park and convention center are under way on a
waterfront that teems with sails and masts. The transformation is
so striking that Time magazine recently featured New Bern as one of
the most attractive new retirement spots in America.
</P>
<P>
   The chief attraction for tourists remains history. New Bern
(locals pronounce as if it were one word _ NEW-bun) has 36 National
Register properties, 15 antiques shops, the original state capital,
half a dozen museum homes, a Civil War museum, a fire museum, a
history museum _ all that, and a special place in the nation's
sweet tooth.
</P>
<P>
   This is Pepsi-Cola's home town. A mustachioed pharmacist, Caleb
Bradham, created the drink in 1898 at his downtown drug store. That
building is gone, but another one _ almost as old _ houses the
Birthplace of Pepsi store, a combination soda fountain, memorabilia
exhibit and souvenir stand where you can buy a bumper sticker that
says, ``Friends Don't Let Friends Drink Coke.'' When I walked in, a
TV was playing vintage Pepsi commercials starring everyone from
Harpo Marx to James Dean. Someone must have a sense of humor around
here, because I also watched a mildly subversive clip from
``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry: ``I'm getting a Pepsi. You want one?''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine: ``You can't drink Pepsi.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry: ``Why?''
</P>
<P>
   Elaine: ``We're adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, anyone with an adult interest in North Carolina
history ends up at Tryon Palace, the redbrick Georgian mansion that
served as the colonial governor's residence and first state
capital. Finished in 1770, it was regarded as one of the grandest
edifices in the colonies. George Washington once attended a party
there (although he actually slept down the street at another house
that's also part of the tour).
</P>
<P>
   Tryon Palace has a fitful history that says a lot about the
populist streak in North Carolina's character. Many colonists
opposed its construction as a British boondoggle. William Tryon,
the royal governor, returned the sentiment; he despised North
Carolina and stayed in the palace for only 13 months before leaving
for reassignment in New York. Colonists promptly ran off his
successor on the eve of the Revolution. The state's General
Assembly met in the building for a few years, then moved to the new
capital in Raleigh. The palace burned in 1798 and wasn't rebuilt
until the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the lively exchange I witnessed during my tour, the
anti-colonial feelings haven't been completely extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   We had just been ushered into the drawing room when a young man
in a powdered wig and fancy knee breeches appeared and welcomed us
to his home. In a hammy British accent, he introduced himself as
his majesty's governor and asked where we came from. A man from
Asheville caught his ear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, the frontier,'' the governor said, stroking his chin
thoughtfully. ``How is the Indian trouble going?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Trouble?'' the man shot back. ``There's no trouble. You took
care of that when you gave the Cherokees blankets full of
smallpox.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor was dumbstruck; this wasn't on the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite sure I don't know what you're talking about, sir,''
he finally replied. And with that, he bid us a brisk good day,
vanishing just as the first Gov. Tryon did more than two centuries
ago.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: New Bern is almost 500 miles from Atlanta. Take
I-20 east to Florence, S.C., I-95 north to Smithfield, N.C., U.S.
70 east toward the coast. It's about a nine-hour drive. The closest
major airport is Raleigh-Durham, two hours away. Fourteen-day
advance fares from $94 on AirTran, Delta and Midway.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Festivals: The home and garden tour, April 9-10, includes 14
homes, four gardens and 11 churches. $13.50 in advance. The
summer's big event is the Pepsi Heritage Festival, June 11-13; the
fall's is the Mumfest, Oct. 8-10. For information and tickets, call
the tourist bureau. 1-800-437-5767.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Big attraction: Tours of Tryon Palace, the first state
capital, include the building, several other homes and acres of
formal gardens bursting with tulips during the spring. 610 Pollock
St. 1-800-767-1560.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Offbeat attraction: The New Bern Fireman's Museum has a
stunning collection of antique fire engines, some of which were
pressed into service when a third of the town burned in 1922. Don't
miss the stuffed head of Fire Horse Fred, who pulled engines for 17
years; he died in the harness on his way to a false alarm. 408
Hancock St. 252-636-4087.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thirsty? Pepsi was created in New Bern just before the turn of
the century and was based there until the 1920s. The best place to
get a taste of the early years is the Birthplace of Pepsi store and
soda fountain, on the site of the pharmacy where the cola was first
concocted. 256 Middle St. 252-636-5898.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sightseeing: New Bern Tours offers guided excursions through
the historic district on open-air bus trolleys. There's a Pepsi
cooler on board, if you're still thirsty. 1-800-849-7316.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lodging: In addition to half a dozen chain motels, New Bern
has eight bed-and-breakfasts within the historic district, most
with porches and rockers that look quite seductive after a stroll.
The Harmony House has the quirky history you love in a B&AMP;B: The
1809 Greek Revival was sawed in half around the turn of the
century, and one side moved nine feet to make room for a grand
Victorian stairway. 215 Pollock St. 1-800-636-3113. The Sheraton
Grand, on the Trent River, is a favorite of boaters; they can dock
out back and see their masts from their rooms. 100 Middle St.
1-800-326-3745.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dining: The best dinner in town can be found at the Harvey
Mansion, an elegant 1790s house that doubles as an art gallery.
Continental cuisine _ try the superb veal in mushroom sauce. 221 S.
Front St. 252-638-3205. For lunch, it's hard to beat the crab cakes
at Sonny's Raw Bar and Grill. 235 Craven St. 252-637-9000. For
drinks, try the Chelsea Restaurant and Publick House, located in a
1912 pharmacy that once belonged to Pepsi's founder (hence the huge
Pepsi mural). 335 Middle St. 252-637-5469. For a treat, don't miss
the Cow Cafe, a nifty little ice cream parlor decorated in
black-and-white Holstein spots. 305 Avenue C. 919-638-1131.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Craven County Convention and Visitors Bureau.
1-800-437-5767.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
