<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2856 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUSANNAH-OPERA-REVIEW     04-01 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSANNAH-OPERA-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUSANNAH': BIG HOUSE, LITTLE OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Susannah, Susannah!'' one felt like calling out.
``What's a nice girl like you doing in a place like this?'' Such a
big opera house, such a little opera.
</P>
<P>
   Amiable, direct, wholly without guile, Carlisle Floyd's American
heroine and the work that bears her name arrived in the halls of
grand opera on Wednesday night, looking like some lonely tourist
lost in the vastness of Grand Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Opera has not done well by American composers
in recent years; the principal exception was John Corigliano's
``Ghosts of Versailles,'' a piece calculated to the grandiose
dimensions and capabilities of the house. Putting on ``Susannah''in
a 3,800-seat house seems an impulsive act. One hears that Renee
Fleming wanted particularly to sing the title role, and her lovely
sound and simple musicality made her perfect for it.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Ramey as the adulterous preacher, Olin Blitch, is as
ideally suited as she. Credit their splendid performances for the
several moments when Floyd's 44-year-old opera matched the scale of
its surroundings. Two of these episodes came in arias by Ms.
Fleming: one a long accumulation of lyrical energy (``Ain't it a
pretty night''), the other a charming copy of American folk
balladry (``The trees on the mountains''). Ramey is at the center
of Act 2's church meeting, preaching vehemently as a choir hymn
grows behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susannah'' may be getting more from the Met than it deserves.
The piece is perfect in size and difficulty for the regional opera
house or the amateur production, but lesser singing, I suspect,
reveals its thinness even more. Floyd has a nice way with hoedowns,
countrified modal melody and drumroll crescendos, but there is
amazingly little going on at the musical end of this opera. Put it
this way: Kurt Weill's music is not as simple as it seems;
``Susannah'' is.
</P>
<P>
   The subject, a Tennessee mountain version of the Bible's
``Susannah and the Elders,'' is certainly operatic. Just as Greek
tragedy finds a natural home in O'Neill's ``Mourning Becomes
Electra,'' so the simple austerity and Manichaean morality of
fundamentalist America provides just the elements on which opera
thrives. ``Susannah'' is a bleakly eloquent drama crying out for a
score to match it. Friendly as it is, Floyd's music tells its story
and nothing more. There are no layers, no resonances, no
implications beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   There are no significant demands on singers, either, although
the secondary cast does seem intent on making its music bigger than
it is. The orchestra part is so basic that relatively speaking the
splendid Met orchestra conducted by James Conlon was having an
evening off. Even the wariest ear in the audience could find
nothing capable of offense; everything went down as smooth and
digestible as can be. Serious listeners, indeed, could put up their
feet and enjoy a free night as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Met production by Robert Falls is appropriately basic.
Michael Yeargan's clapboard cottage and church (inside and out) and
his bending stand of trees in silhouette slide on and off the
stage. Mountain vistas glow with rising and setting suns. The
opening square-dance scene was a little confused, but a lot of that
has to do with the opera, not the production. Jerry Hadley (Sam
Polk) drawled effectively. John McVeigh played Little Bat in the
spastic manner of Jerry Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Again, there is a lot nice about ``Susannah'' and nothing wrong
with it. Yet one couldn't resist an impression of something small
and innocent that had wandered into the wrong place. Its 90 minutes
could be put inside the first act of ``Parsifal'' and leave so much
extra room that it would have to be tied down to keep from rattling
around. Simplicity is an admirable concept, but there is just not
enough musical ambition here to meet the theatrical potency of the
subject matter. In fairness, Floyd finds a momentum in Act 2 that
almost wholly escapes him in Act 1.
</P>
<P>
   But monosyllabic as ``Susannah'' is, maybe we should just let it
sing its sweet song well and accept small virtues gratefully. In
one way, the opera speaks well for the country we live in. Given
all our arrogance, here is at least one proof that Americans can be
modest too.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SUSANNAH'
</P>
<P>
   Opera in two acts by Carlisle Floyd, libretto by the composer;
James Conlon, conductor; production by Robert Falls; sets and
costumes by Michael Yeargan; lighting by Duane Schuler;
co-production of Lyric Opera of Chicago and the Houston Grand Opera
Association. At the Metropolitan Opera.
</P>
<P>
   With: Renee Fleming (Susannah Polk), Jerry Hadley (Sam), John
McVeigh (Little Bat McLean), Samuel Ramey (Olin Blitch), Jennifer
Welch (Mrs. Hayes), Jane Dutton (Mrs. Gleaton), Joyce Castle (Mrs.
McLean), Jane Shaulis (Mrs. Ott), Jonathan Welch (Elder Hayes),
Jerold Siena (Elder Gleaton), James Courtney (Elder McLean), LeRoy
Lehr (Elder Ott), Ross Crolius (First Man), Kenneth Young (Second
Man), Howard Richman (Square Dance Caller).
</P>
</TEXT>
