<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, April 2, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A winter storm warning was in effect Thursday night for the
mountains of Arizona as a potent Pacific disturbance approached
from the southwest. On Friday, the disturbance will move over the
central Plains, where the risk of powerful thunderstorms will rise.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of showers and thunderstorms will develop across parts
of Nebraska and Kansas as the arriving disturbance lifts
increasingly moist air streaming north from the Gulf of Mexico. A
few of these storms could approach severe levels, with hail and
high winds possible. Storms will then move eastward into parts of
Iowa and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, isolated, powerful thunderstorms will erupt
across the high plains of western Oklahoma and western Texas as a
dry line, which will mark the boundary between very humid air from
the Gulf of Mexico and dry air from the Rockies, arrives Friday
afternoon. Farther east, a second ribbon of moisture-laden air from
the Gulf of Mexico will fuel showers and thunderstorms from eastern
Texas and Louisiana to the middle Mississippi and lower Ohio
Valleys.
</P>
<P>
   Snow will intensify across parts of the northern Plains Friday
night as the disturbance arrives from the central Plains.
Moderately heavy snow is possible in parts of the western Dakotas,
southeast Montana and northeast Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean winds blowing over cold Atlantic waters will chill parts
of southeast New England. Meanwhile, in the wake of a front
stalling across the northern Middle Atlantic states, stubborn low
clouds and patchy drizzle will dampen parts of Pennsylvania and New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Sandstorm
</P>
<P>
   Fierce winds gusted as high as 100 mph across parts of northeast
Arizona on Wednesday, kicking up dust and sand while dramatically
and dangerously lowering visibility. Related auto accidents claimed
two lives. The raging sandstorm developed as a sharp cold front
swept across the Southwest states. Behind the front, momentum from
strong winds several thousand feet aloft mixed toward the ground.
These sandstorms are sometimes called haboobs, deriving from the
Arabic word habb, which means wind. Haboobs sometimes have a wall
of swirling dust and sand that is 3,000 feet high.
</P>
</TEXT>
