<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOKIES-FILM-REVIEW-N     04-01 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKIES-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COOKIE'S FORTUNE': A SALOME STORY WITH SOUTHERN SUGAR AND SPITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Productions notes appear at end of review.) 
 (DW)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The sweet assurance and guerrilla wit of Robert Altman's vintage
ensemble films makes a serenely captivating return with ``Cookie's
Fortune.'' In this seamlessly copacetic treat, Altman once again
dreams up a well-rounded community of symbiotic oddballs, then
effortlessly lures the viewer into their world. With a fine cast
working on a single, nicely eccentric wavelength, he and the
screenwriter Anne Rapp turn picturesque Holly Springs, Miss., into
a hotbed of grudges, power struggles, family secrets and historical
footnotes, all presented with the same rueful overview. ``On this
site in 1897,'' reads a sardonic sign in the local liquor store,
``nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune'' enjoys every bit of mischief that Holly
Springs has to offer. It especially notices the racial contrasts.
The film opens in a blues club where a sultry black singer (Ruby
Wilson) makes the atmosphere instantly inviting; then it checks out
what the white folks do for entertainment. At the local church,
rehearsals are in full swing for a play about Salome and John the
Baptist (``Excuse me, head coming through!'' says the prop man)
under the aegis of Camille Dixon, played by Glenn Close as a
ladylike monster who insists on sharing a writing credit for
``Salome'' with Oscar Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   The film has its own Salome story waiting in the wings. But
first it must introduce the beautiful friendship between
good-hearted Willis Richland (Charles S. Dutton, appealing and rock
solid in this central role) and crusty Jewel Mae (Cookie) Orcutt
(played touchingly by Patricia Neal in a rare screen appearance).
</P>
<P>
   The film teases its audience with the possibility that a black
man may be breaking into a wealthy old white woman's house in the
middle of the night, but in fact it's only Willis stopping by on a
friendly basis. These two have a cozy rapport of long standing.
Willis is closer to Cookie than any of her white relatives happen
to be.
</P>
<P>
   Camille, played diabolically well by Ms. Close, barges
resentfully through the story, annoyed by the wealth of her Aunt
Cookie, the pliant dizziness of her sister Cora (Julianne Moore)
and the general existence of Cora's tomboyish daughter Emma (Liv
Tyler), who prefers working with catfish to any daintier
profession.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tyler, who fits right into the Altman ensemble style, makes
it easy to understand why Emma is admired by a police rookie (Chris
O'Donnell) and a Peeping Tom (Lyle Lovett) with equal ardor.
</P>
<P>
   Though the film is loaded with local color, it doesn't drift
into the vagueness that has weakened Altman's secondary work. Nor
does it strain for humor or purpose the way, for instance,
``Pret-a-Porter'' did. Unlike his evocative John Grisham film,
``The Gingerbread Man,'' this one does not unfold on unfamiliar
terrain, preferring instead to rekindle the attitudes of his wonder
years in the 1970's. If ``Cookie's Fortune'' is lighter and less
haunting than Altman films of that era, it is also more tightly
plotted and direct. The director astutely shepherds this story
through assorted outrages and revelations until it arrives at a
lovely finale, one that gives each character exactly what he or she
deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune'' poignantly understands why Cookie herself
won't be around for much of the story. Lonely and infirm, she has
come to dwell on memories of her late husband, and in hopes of
release and reunion she decides to join him. Most unfortunately,
Willis has been leaving fingerprints on Cookie's guns around the
same time (he's been cleaning them), and Camille is the one who
discovers her aunt's body. Cursing her aunt (``How dare you do this
to me, you crazy old lady!'') while casually looting Cookie's
bedroom, Camille eats the suicide note and thus turns Willis into a
murder suspect. She is abetted in this by Cora, played by Ms. Moore
with the mix of apparent wide-eyed naivete and secret willfulness
that Shelley Duvall brought to Altman films of the past.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of ``Cookie's Fortune'' is a test of everyone's mettle,
and it unfolds with a simple decency that is one of the film's most
pleasing aspects. Far from being the story of a racist frame-up,
``Cookie's Fortune'' shows why the town sheriff (Ned Beatty)
believes in Willis: ``Because I fished with him.'' It shows how the
best of Holly Springs is brought out by this crisis, though Altman
will never be mistaken for Frank Capra when it comes to fighting
injustice and righting old wrongs. This story has a welcome
malicious edge as it brings out its characters' true colors in
unexpected ways. When Cora finally asks, in this story's most
delicately bittersweet moment, ``I did good, didn't I?'' the answer
is absolutely: for her, and for the whole film too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Cookie's Fortune'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly
cautioned). It includes mild profanity, implied sexual situations
and a few double-entendres.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `COOKIE'S FORTUNE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Robert Altman; written by Anne Rapp; director of
photography, Toyomichi Kurita; edited by Abraham Lim; music by
David A. Stewart; production designer, Stephen Altman; produced by
Robert Altman and Etchie Stroh; released by October Films. Running
time: 118 minutes. This film is rated PG-13.
</P>
<P>
   With: Glenn Close (Camille Dixon), Julianne Moore (Cora Duvall),
Liv Tyler (Emma Duvall), Chris O'Donnell (Jason Brown), Charles S.
Dutton (Willis Richland), Patricia Neal (Jewel Mae ``Cookie''
Orcutt), Ned Beatty (Lester Boyle), Courtney B. Vance (Otis
Tucker), Donald Moffat (Jack Palmer), Lyle Lovett (Manny Hood) and
Ruby Wilson (Josie Martin).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1812EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2860 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON02-COX     04-01 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON WARNS YUGOSLAVS ON SOLDIERS, DEFENDS KOSOVO POLICY
 &HT;    470&AMP;adds. With KOSOVO-STRIKES.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. _ President Clinton, at a campaign-style rally with
military families to bolster support for the NATO bombing of
Yugoslavia, delivered a blunt warning Thursday to President
Slobodan Milosevic about harming three U.S. servicemen held by his
forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic should make no mistake _ the United States
takes care of its own,'' Clinton said from a stage set up in front
of two menacing jet fighters with skulls painted on their tails.
``President Milosevic should make no mistake _ we will hold him and
his government responsible for their safety and for their
well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke to about 1,600 military personnel and their
families in a hangar at the Naval Air Station, part of a vast
military complex along the Virginia coast that includes the only
NATO headquarters in the continental United States.
</P>
<P>
   It is also the home of the U.S.S. Theodore Roosevelt, an
aircraft carrier that sailed last week for the Persian Gulf. But
U.S. Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander in Europe, has requested
that the Roosevelt be diverted to the Adriatic Sea to provide more
firepower over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The president, whose private meeting with a small group of
military dependents had been planned for several days, was forced
to address the capture of the three American servicemen in an event
that was to have been simply a gesture of appreciation for the
sacrifices of military families.
</P>
<P>
   The president said there was ``absolutely no basis'' for the
three American servicemen to have been captured by the Serbs. He
added, ``There is no basis for them to be held. There is certainly
no basis for them to be tried. All Americans are concerned about
their welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   (Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   A platoon of Marines dressed in camouflage stood stiffly in
formation during the president's speech, but many of the sailors,
soldiers, pilots and their families milled about the cavernous
hangar as the president defended his decision to rally a NATO
bombing campaign against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the military personnel departed immediately after
Clinton's remarks, many trying to avoid reporters seeking their
reaction to the president.
</P>
<P>
   But hundreds of civilians remained, crushing forward to shake
the president's hand or snap photographs of him working the crowd.
And typically, they were supportive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds so much like World War II, and we need to help them
(ethnic Kosovars) out,'' said Erica Honaker, 16, whose father, Navy
Lt. Commander Herb Honaker, is assigned to the base.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made me feel that what our country is doing is
worthwhile,'' said Becky Meyers, 24, whose husband, Army Lt. Luke
Meyer, is stationed at nearby Fort Story.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the selling of the president that is under way, but
rather the selling of his Kosovo policy, which is under greater
scrutiny after more than a week of bombing that has failed to stop
the Serbian forces' brutal expulsion of ethnic Albanians from the
province.
</P>
<P>
   (End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   While warning of the dangers to come as NATO steps up its
bombing, Clinton vowed that NATO would ``continue to carry out or
mission with determination and resolve'' and that Milosevic's
actions ``will carry a very high price indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Americans should be patient, that the NATO bombing
campaign would ultimately achieve the goal of weakening Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to decide whether we are going to take a stand with
our NATO allies and whether we are prepared to pay the price of
time to make him pay the price of aggression and murder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the horrendous images of World War II, Clinton said
taking a stand against the ``ethnic cleansing'' of ethnic Albanians
is necessary to prevent ``widespread war'' in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot do everything in the world, but we must do what we
can,'' he said. ``We can never forget the Holocaust, the genocide,
the carnage of the 20th century. We don't want the new century to
bring us the same nightmares in a different guise.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was not alone in defending the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen, who accompanied the president
to Norfolk, bristled at news reports suggest the administration did
not give adequate attention to military assessments that a bombing
campaign would not prevent Serbian forces from stepping up their
attacks on ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have read with some interest reports in today's papers, and
I have found for the most part they are completely fictitious,''
Cohen told reporters. ``The consequences of this action were indeed
considered. We had to consider whether or not we could sit on the
sidelines and watch indifferently while 40,000 (Serbian) troops
went on a rampage through Kosovo, while NATO took no action
whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
