<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENNIO-COMEDY-ART-2TAK     04-01 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENNIO-COMEDY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: NO MATTER HOW FAR OUT, COMICS STILL CROSS
PATHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Imagine, if you will, an evening with Roberto Benigni
doing impressions of Stevie Wonder, Edith Piaf, Fidel Castro,
Marilyn Monroe, Barbra Streisand and the Pope. Now imagine him
impersonating them all in a lip-synching show, with paper
headdresses, costumes and props affixed to his scalp and torso.
</P>
<P>
   No, this wouldn't necessarily be the scariest post-Academy
Awards show hallucination. It would, in fact, be an approximation
of ``Ennio,'' an honest-to-goodness off-Broadway show that, ahem,
unfolds like no other production in town. The effect may be weird,
but the strangest thing about ``Ennio'' is that it's an absolute
hoot. Its star, Ennio Marchetto, an Italian actor who takes his
inspiration from commedia dell'arte and Walt Disney, might consider
having ``the Irrepressible'' legally attached to his name.
</P>
<P>
   Riffling through a wad of whimsical costumes _ some with moving
parts _ Marchetto accomplishes for grown-up-size paper-doll
accessories what Rich Little did for the larynx.
</P>
<P>
   In skits set to pop, rock and opera music, and each over and
done with in a flash, he transforms himself into a living Potato
Head, tugging and pulling at paper noses, sleeves and handbags to
become Whitney Houston or Marge Simpson at will. The split-second
transformations are themselves the show's wittiest conceits.
Marchetto peels away a likeness of Freddy Mercury of the rock group
Queen to reveal the visage of Queen Elizabeth II; a surgically
re-engineered Cher is supplanted by that marvel of movie
engineering, R2D2.
</P>
<P>
   The moral of ``Ennio,'' a 75-minute show that runs through April
11 at the McGinn-Cazale Theater on the Upper West Side, is one that
bears sober contemplation: in New York City, you never know where
your next laugh is coming from. When someone declares, ``There's a
hyperactive guy on Broadway and 76th Street dressed as a cardboard
Celine Dion who mouths the words to the theme song from
`Titanic,''' the instinctive response is probably not, ``I'm
there!'' Which makes the success of ``Ennio'' all the more
enticing. This is, after all, also the city that taught America the
perfect shrugging comeback to any startling revelation:
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knew?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ennio'' shares the off-Broadway stage these days with any
number of vehicles for truly out-there comedy. At the Westbeth
Theater Center in the West Village, a pair of comic actors from
Australia who call themselves the Umbilical Brothers are appearing
nightly in ``Thwak,'' an exuberant and effortlessly funny showcase
for their arsenal of Saturday morning cartoons come to life.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kaufman Theater on West 42nd Street, another young comic
partnership, Premium Bob, takes absurdist swipes at depictions of
the American male in the stylized madness of ``Manhunt.''
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of outrageously joyful stand-up, there is the
shrieking, wind-up toy sensibility of Mario Cantone, a comedian of
extravagant tantrums and extravagant gifts, who just finished one
of his intermittent gigs at Caroline's on Broadway (and deserves an
off-Broadway showcase of his own, if his put-upon voicebox can
withstand it).
</P>
<P>
   And soon to arrive at the Flea Theater downtown is Elevator
Repair Service, an oddball downtown troupe that in a blending of
banal everyday behavior like sotto voce conversations, and the
tight choreography of jerky movement seeks to find laughs where no
troupe has found them before.
</P>
<P>
   These acts _ for that's what they are, each with a shtick as
identifiable as that of any comedy team that played the vaudeville
circuit _ may be stylistically diverse, but they also have a lot in
common.
</P>
<P>
   They are all products of a mediacentric age; their shows are
obsessed with popular culture and riddled with references to
celebrities. Cantone makes fun of them; Marchetto becomes them, and
Elevator Repair Service is inspired by them. Its latest offering,
``Language Instruction: Love Family vs. Andy Kaufman,'' which
begins Thursday, is the return of a 1994 production.
</P>
<P>
   And the material intersects at odd angles: Marchetto and
Cantone, for instance, both eerily impersonate Peggy Lee; Premium
Bob and Cantone are both scathing on the subject of professional
ice skaters; the Umbilical Brothers and Premium Bob both make the
lampooning of action-adventure movies a central theme.
</P>
<P>
   But there the similarities end. Cantone is a practitioner from
the medieval school of stand there with a microphone and make 'em
laugh; what distinguishes his art is that it does make 'em laugh.
(I dare you to listen to him while dealing with a mouthful of your
favorite beverage.) An actor as well as stand-up performer _ he
replaced Nathan Lane in the final months of the Broadway run of
``Love! Valour! Compassion!'' _ Cantone is a proponent of the
comedy of outrage. Everyone from Julia Child to Nancy Kerrigan gets
his dander up (if you ever meet him, plead with him to do his
impression of Carol Channing meeting the rapper Heavy D), but his
very best jokes are on his Italian-American family, ``all 900 of
them,'' gathered for the holidays at his mother's and seated on her
couch ``like a Scorsese casting call.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, David Latham and Paul Boocock, who make up
Premium Bob, take a cerebral, vaguely nonlinear approach to parody,
the kind that can find amusement in the portentous enunciation of a
single word, like ``Fact!'' as it is used in those commercials
highlighting the healing properties of antacids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manhunt'' is the latest generation of a show that Premium Bob
has been working on for about a year. It's a collection of visual
and linguistic tics that from my observations divides audiences in
about half.
</P>
<P>
   This became clear to me during a recent performance when I sat
behind a mountain of a man who shook with laughter at the precision
of Latham's and Boocock's antics. His body quaking, he turned
frequently to check the response of the man sitting next to him,
who looked so bored that he might have been mistaken for a
spectator at an eight-hour reading of the alphabet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Together they seemed like characters in a blatant editorial
cartoon: one wearing the label ``Funny,'' the other ``Not Funny.''
</P>
<P>
   With Premium Bob, both sides have a point.
</P>
<P>
   The repetitious tableaux, spoofing the opening sequences of old
television detective shows, the clipped intonation in the narration
of a meaningless story about the search for a missing no-account
named Dobie McDobie, is all meant to poke fun at pomposity, and
it's only sporadically effective. When comedy is so purposefully
unspontaneous _ the self-consciousness of the visual style
occasionally brings to mind the work of the experimental director
Anne Bogart _ the remoteness of it all becomes a bit tiresome. You
admire from a distance and never fall in love.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thwak,'' the Westbeth show featuring David Collins and Shane
Dundas, is destined for cult hit status; these ingenious Australian
cutups, with their 70-minute exhibition of astonishing sound
effects and visual gags, are smart without ever resorting to
smarminess. ``Ennio,'' too, is likely to develop a loyal following,
the kind that demands, say, a Web site devoted to Marchetto's
adorable fantasias.
</P>
<P>
   As with Cantone and the Umbilical Brothers, Marchetto's
ebullient hour on the stage reveals that it may not matter all that
much if there are no second acts in American life, as long as your
first one is funny.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled Launching Times and Pads
</P>
<P>
   Here is information about the shows and clubs in Manhattan
mentioned in the Critic's Notebook article on comedy.
</P>
<P>
   CAROLINE'S COMEDY CLUB, 1626 Broadway, near 49th Street, (212)
757-4100. Mark Curry, Friday night and Saturday at 8 and 10:30 p.m.
and 12:30 a.m.; Sunday at 9:30 p.m. Kevin Nealon, Saturday and
Sunday at 7:30 p.m. Tickets: $12.50 to $24.50, with a two-drink
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   ``ENNIO.'' McGinn-Cazale Theater, 2162 Broadway, at 76th Street,
(212) 239-6200. Through Sunday. Friday night at 8; Saturday at 7
and 9:30 p.m.; Sunday at 3 p.m. Tickets: $35.
</P>
<P>
   ``LANGUAGE INSTRUCTION: LOVE FAMILY VS. ANDY KAUFMAN,'' by
Elevator Repair Service. The Flea Theater, 41 White St., lower
Manhattan, (212) 226-0051. Thursday through May 2. Thursdays
through Sundays at 8 p.m. Tickets: $15; students and the elderly,
$12.
</P>
<P>
   ``MANHUNT,'' starring Premium Bob. Kaufman Theater, 534 W. 42nd
St., Clinton, (212) 216-9596. Thursdays at 8 p.m.; Fridays and
Saturdays at 7:30 and 10 p.m. Tickets: $12.
</P>
<P>
   ``THWAK'' Westbeth Theater Center, 151 Bank St., West Village,
(212) 307-4100. Tuesdays through Saturdays at 8 p.m. Tickets: $25
to $35.
</P>
