<SLUG> BC-MICHIGAN-SOLDIER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHIGAN TOWN RALLIES FOR AMERICAN HELD IN YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Huron Daily Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPAC, Mich. _ Yellow ribbons and U.S. flags went up Thursday in
the tiny Michigan community where Army Staff Sgt. Christopher J.
Stone, one of three U.S. soldiers captured by Yugoslav forces, grew
up.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, 25, and the other two Americans were paraded before
television cameras Thursday. His face was battered and bruised, and
state-controlled Yugoslav media said the soldiers would face a
military trial.
</P>
<P>
   People in Capac (pronounced KAY-pack) said Stone was popular, an
average student, who ran on the Capac Junior-Senior High School
cross-country team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris is a tough kid,'' said Ken Marzka, a teacher at the
school who once coached Stone. ``When push came to shove, he got
tougher and tougher.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone also was a member of Students Against Drunk Driving. He
joined the Army shortly after he graduated from Capac High in 1991.
He now is married and has a 5-year-old son. His family is staying
with relatives in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Marzka said he was told that Stone recently came home on leave
and told a friend that joining the Army was ``the best thing he
ever did for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Capac senior Tiffany Ellis said many of the students at the
500-student school hadn't paid a lot of attention to NATO air
attacks in Yugoslavia until the capture of one of their own. Ellis
said Stone's capture brought it home to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are yellow ribbons on every tree on Main Street,'' said
banker Gordon Bade. He said customers at the CSB Bank in Capac,
where he is executive vice president, talked about little else
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   School counselor Kathy Kish said Stone was something of a
prankster, who was well liked by students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't surprise us a bit that he's serving our country on
a peace mission,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, along with Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles, and Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas,
reportedly were patrolling a rugged area near the border between
Macedonia and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO forces had been stationed in Macedonia, a former republic
of Yugoslavia, as part of a peacekeeping mission that predated the
current hostilities. All three Americans are members of the 1st
Infantry Division assigned to the peace force.
</P>
<P>
   Capac is a town of about 1,600 people west of Port Huron, in the
Thumb of Michigan. It is located along Interstate 69, where
hundreds of heavy trucks rumble by each day on their way to and
from the Canadian border crossing at the Blue Water Bridges between
Port Huron and Sarnia, Ontario. Fast freight trains on the Grand
Trunk Western's main line between Toronto and Chicago pass through
town several times a day.
</P>
<P>
   Farming has been the driving force for the area for generations,
with large farms growing corn, wheat, beans and sugar beets. But
the area is changing. Located about 50 miles north of Detroit, the
area around Capac has been growing rapidly in the last few years.
Among the orchards and fields are many new developments of
condominiums and large, expensive homes. The rural lifestyle has
attracted many new residents, who commute to jobs in the suburbs of
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   But Bade said Capac hadn't lost its rural sense of community.
Bade said Capac and the surrounding towns are pulling together,
remembering and praying for Stone and the other captured soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a typical small town,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
