<HEADER>
A2870 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT &LR;      04-01 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER 101, IN HIGH SCHOOL  
 NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teen-agers misbehave in droves on screen these days, but for
extreme juvenile delinquency the ground was broken a decade ago in
``Heathers,'' Michael Lehmann's controversial film about a pair of
originals who righteously liquidate those who displease them.
</P>
<P>
   Back on a new DVD released this week by Anchor Bay, Veronica
(Winona Ryder) and J.D. (Christian Slater) remain in top form,
which is to say they get away with murder. For Veronica at least,
the experience proves to be gloriously liberating.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989 that kind of thing didn't happen. ``People were making
teen movies, but it was at the end of the John Hughes cycle _ `The
Breakfast Club,' `Ferris Bueller's Day Off,''' Lehmann said.
Teen-agers were exhibiting plenty of worldliness, but they stopped
at totally dissociating themselves from the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heathers'' removed that reticence. Conceived and written by
Daniel Waters, the film is a satire about two high school students,
one a disenchanted member of the school's viciously abusive ruling
clique and the other a rolling-stone misfit, who team up to do away
with several richly deserving classmates and make it look like
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my experience, evil starts at around age 12,'' Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   Veronica is hardly evil, however. As a member of the favored
group, she is fed up with her friends' behavior. When J.D. suggests
they feed the nastiest member of the clique _ one of three girls
named Heather _ a lethal cocktail, it seems like a cool notion.
Heather pitches over, shattering a glass coffee table. Veronica
concocts a suicide note.
</P>
<P>
   The same modus operandi works perfectly with two boorish
football players and date rapists, only this time Veronica shoots
the pair and the suicide theme is angled to make them appear to be
gay lovers.
</P>
<P>
   She is appalled by what she's done but also more than a little
thrilled. ``This isn't a geeky girl getting revenge on the popular
kids,'' Waters said. ``Here's the Albert Speer insider. She's part
of this Third Reich, so she has to work from the inside.''
</P>
<P>
   A newcomer in town, J.D. has no such connection. ``Teen movies
in the 50s had the cool loner kid riding in James Dean-like,''
Waters said. ``I wanted to have fun with that. He started out that
way, but then he pushed it to the psychopathic level.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually J.D. tries to blow up the school with everybody in
it. Slater gives the role his best Jack Nicholson impression, which
is startlingly good. J.D. isn't necessarily evil either, just
monumentally twisted. Together he and Veronica make a mess.
Infatuated with him at first, she eventually tries to disengage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about at this point that the film loses its nerve,''
Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Waters said there was truth in that. In his original script,
Veronica blew herself up. In real life teen-age suicide had reached
alarming dimensions in the late 80s, and the studios wouldn't touch
the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Finally it was made by New World. And Veronica walks away an
enlightened young woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a choice of making something that was slightly
compromised or having nothing to make,'' Waters said.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS
</P>
<P>
   BELOVED  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Touchstone. $107.37. 172 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Taking on a daunting job of literary adaptation, Jonathan
Demme's film gives Toni Morrison's novel a pulse on screen. Through
manifestations of terrible events real and demonic, the former
slave Sethe (Oprah Winfrey, left with Danny Glover) tries to
reconcile the horrors of her experience with the possibility of
renewal. From the corporeal world comes Paul D. ( Glover), an old
friend bearing a slave's name. Floating from the depths of a river
comes the beautiful Beloved (Thandie Newton) to bring Sethe face to
face with an unspeakable past. Though it begins slowly, ``
`Beloved,''' Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times,
``accelerates into a gripping, wildly imaginative film that's not
quite like any other.''
</P>
<P>
   American History X  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. New Line. $105.77. 118 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
Release date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Playing on the savage scowl and swastika tattoo of a skinhead
named Derek (Edward Norton), Tony Kaye's controversial film creates
visual enticement as it builds rhetorical fever from the ersatz
poetic idiom of videos and commercials. Derek has committed vicious
acts, re-created in almost loving detail, and done a little time in
prison. Later he repudiates the violence, in an ``inflated yet
gut-slugging film that dares to address America's neo-Nazi culture
with brutal candor'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meet Joe Black
</P>
<P>
   1998. Universal. $107.37. 160 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a latter-day version of the 1934 film ``Death Takes a
Holiday,'' the Grim Reaper becomes a piece of blond eye candy named
Joe Black (Brad Pitt) and pops in on the gilded world of the happy
tycoon William Parrish (Anthony Hopkins). Parrish has everything,
including a heart problem that is about to kill him. In return for
showing Death around his opulent domain, the mogul can have some
extra time to get squared away for ``the next place.'' Joe learns
about peanut butter and falls for Parrish's daughter (Claire
Forlani), but it all takes ``so long that every character
regrettably wears out his or her welcome'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I Still Know What You Did Last Summer  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37. 101 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A group of pals from a small North Carolina town are still
paying for a youthful indiscretion: accidentally running over a man
and then inadvisably tossing his body in the harbor. Fully
recovered, the victim has taken up a cargo hook and is dispatching
the young people like tuna on a conveyor belt. Now it's down to one
survivor (Jennifer Love Hewitt), who is trapped in the Bahamas in
this sequel with ``a higher body count, cruder shock effects,
louder screams, vanishing credibility and loss of narrative
coherence'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
