<HEADLINE>
MAKING GOOD ON A PROMISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y.)  (mk) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the last 11 years, the Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary
Art has been little more than a name and a promise. But on May 30,
it will finally open to the public, and North Adams, Mass., will be
the site of the largest center for contemporary visual and
performing arts in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987 Thomas Krens, who was then the director of the Williams
College Museum of Art in Williamstown, Mass., began lobbying to
transform the former site of an electric company in North Adams.
Krens, now director of the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum in New
York, was joined in his campaign by Joseph Thompson, then an
exhibition designer also working at the Williams College Museum.
</P>
<P>
   By 1988 Thompson had become the director of the museum, which
was still in the planning stages. Five years later, he changed the
institution's mission, deciding to encompass the performing as well
as the visual arts.
</P>
<P>
   The museum, on a 13-acre campus of renovated 19th-century
factory buildings in the northwestern corner of the state, will
open with a wide range of programs: several art exhibitions,
site-specific commissions, sound-art installations, multimedia
performances, dance and music concerts and digital, animation and
film presentations.
</P>
<P>
   A three-hour drive from Manhattan, the museum is hoping to
attract a broad audience. ``Berkshire County is already a strong
and healthy destination,'' Thompson said. ``Over 2 million people a
year come here, and 70 percent of them are from the New York
metropolitan area.''
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the museum's plans, he added: ``This campus is a
platform for all kinds of cultural activities. We do our own
exhibitions, but we also team up with productions.''
</P>
<P>
   The center will offer artists the chance to show their work in
extraordinary physical spaces. Bruner/Cott &AMP; Associates, a
Cambridge-based architectural firm, is responsible for the final
design of the buildings, but its architects collaborated on the
institution's feasibility studies with Frank Gehry, the Los Angeles
architect who designed the Guggenheim in Bilbao, Spain; Venturi
Architects from Philadelphia, and Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The finished campus has more than 220,000 square feet of
galleries, theaters and art fabrication spaces. (The museum will
also be a laboratory of sorts, giving visitors the chance to see
works in progress.) There are 19 light-filled galleries, one as
long as a football field and another that has a ceiling 40 feet
high. It also has a 10,500-square-foot black box theater, a smaller
theater, rehearsal studios and outdoor courtyards for music, film
and performance art.
</P>
<P>
   Among the projects that are to be ready for the opening are a
large-scale installation by Natalie Jeremijenko, an installation
artist from Australia; a group exhibition of works by artists
including Joseph Beuys, Mario Merz, Robert Rauschenberg and John
Chamberlain; a new work by the video artist Tony Oursler that was
commissioned by the museum, and a work that uses digital technology
to multiply the body of the dancer Bill T. Jones into an
interactive ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   Other opening programs include an extensive animation series
featuring a project by Walt Disney Pictures; the world premiere of
``Jet Lag,'' a multimedia collaboration between the Builders
Association and the architects Diller &AMP; Scofidio, and a show that
pairs drawings by the choreographer and dancer Trisha Brown and the
painter Terry Winters.
</P>
<P>
   The museum's reach will extend beyond its campus. Timed to its
opening will be billboard art _ commissioned from artists like Gary
Simmons, Leon Golub and Sue Coe _ along the highways of western
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The state has given the museum a $22 million construction grant
and board members and volunteers have raised more than $15 million.
Operating costs will come from an $8 admission fee and private
fund-raising.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thinking Big
</P>
<P>
   The Museum of Modern Art in New York will no doubt make gallery
space for monumental sculptures a priority in its expansion. It
announced this week that Leon Black, a trustee who is president of
Apollo Advisers, a New York investment concern, and his wife,
Debra, had given Richard Serra's 1988 sculpture ``Torqued Ellipse
IV'' to the Modern.
</P>
<P>
   The 46-ton sculpture is a twisted ribbon in the shape of an
ellipse standing on its edge. It is part of a series inspired by
the dynamic spaces created by the early Italian architect
Borromini. The Blacks bought the work from the artist. It is in an
exhibition at the Guggenheim Museum Bilbao through Oct. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, Ronald Lauder, the Modern's chairman, gave the
museum Serra's ``Intersection II'' (1992), a 60-ton sculpture made
of four 2-inch-thick gentle curves of hot-rolled steel. It also
owns several smaller works by the artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Serra is someone whose work we are seriously committed
to,'' said Glenn Lowry, director of the Modern. ``These are
astonishing works.''
</P>
<P>
   Degas Pastels
</P>
<P>
   The Impressionist and modern art department at Sotheby's in
London is bucking the current trend of auctioning masterpieces in
New York. For the third year in a row, Sotheby's in London will
offer important works that haven't been on the market in ages.
</P>
<P>
   In June it will auction ``Dancer in Repose,'' an 1879 Degas
pastel of a dancer sitting on a bench massaging her foot. It has
not been for sale for 104 years and has never been exhibited
outside France. The work, expected to sell for $8 million, was
acquired in 1885 by Jules-Emile Boivin, a French businessman, from
Durand-Ruel Gallery in Paris, one of the first great Impressionist
dealers. It has remained in the family since.
</P>
<P>
   At the same sale, the Boivin family is selling another Degas
pastel, ``Woman Sitting in Front of a Piano'' (1882-1885). It is
expected to sell for $4 million to $5.6 million. The two are among
six works by Degas that Boivin acquired in the 1880s. Among them
was a Degas painting, ``Woman With Vase of Chrysanthemums'' (1865),
which Louisine Havemeyer bought in 1921 and bequeathed to the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in 1929. Another pastel, ``Dancers''
(1882-1885), was acquired by the French government in lieu of taxes
and is in the Musee d'Orsay in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sending these pastels to New York wasn't even a discussion,''
said Melanie Clore, deputy chairman of Sotheby's in Europe, who
also heads its Impressionist and modern art department in London.
``Our track record shows that we can make record prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year in London, Sotheby's sold a 1900 painting by Monet for
a staggering $33 million; the year before it sold a van Gogh
drawing for $14.7 million, a record for a work on paper by the
artist.
</P>
</TEXT>
