<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO nations are quietly
planning a new role for ground forces in which the alliance's
troops would escort Albanian civilian back to Kosovo even without a
peace agreement, a senior NATO official said. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The three captured U.S.
soldiers will face a Serbian military court as early as Friday.
President Slobodan Milosevic meets the ethnic-Albanian leader
Ibrahim Rugova. Other developments. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Norfolk, Va.) _ President Clinton, General Shelton
and Secretary Cohen call for the United States to stay the course.
By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ The bombing is stepped up as the
weather clears. By Steven Lee Myers and Elizabeth Becker
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REGUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ In a chilling display of
force, Serb gunmen are systematically emptying Kosovo's capital
city, Pristina, marching its ethnic Albanians out through gantlets
of masked, heavily armed Serbs, refugees crossing the border today
said. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   IMMIG-WORKERS (Yakima, Wash.) _ When federal immigration agents
came to central Washington recently, there were no sudden raids, no
emergency deportation hearings, no buses waiting to take the
hundreds of illegal immigrants found working back to the Mexican
border. When the investigators left, though, more than 560 people
were fired, under orders from the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, because they possessed forged or otherwise improper work
documents. By Sam Howe Verhovek.
</P>
<P>
   NY-COYOTE-PARK (New York) _ Not an April Fool's joke: There was
a coyote captured in Central Park in Manhattan on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   MO-CONCEALED-WEAPONS (St. Louis) _ In what both sides of the gun
debate are calling a momentous showdown, Missouri will be the first
state to let voters decide in a statewide referendum next week
whether to allow people to carry concealed weapons in public. By
Dirk Johnson.
</P>
