<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-JOURNAL-COX-04     04-01 1356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-JOURNAL-COX-0402 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOREIGN JOURNAL: REFUGEE TEARS FLOW INTO A RIVER OF SADNESS
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania It is early morning. The sun is still hidden by
the vast craggy mountains that ring this sad old village. There are
brilliant blue breaks in the clouds, and people here study these
windows for NATO planes. Among the Albanians _ both those from
Kosovo and those from Albania _ the planes are seen as nothing less
than sweet angels of vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   We are rambling in a 25-year-old Volvo piloted by my guide and
new best friend Murat, who dreams of driving a taxi in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   I am accompanied by a photographer named Seamus Conlan, an Irish
guy who rolls his own cigarettes and tells horrific stories of the
war and famine he has seen in Europe and Africa.
</P>
<P>
   We bounce down a narrow road that is more dust and rock than
asphalt. It winds between the border with Kosovo and Kukes, a place
so poor that I can think of no point of reference in America to
help me describe it to you.
</P>
<P>
   It is ugly, full of bulky Soviet-era buildings that house dim
apartments, shops and offices. Garbage lines the street, inviting
what must be hundreds of stray dogs to rummage. Rusting engine
blocks and transmissions lay here and there. Flattened clear blue
plastic bottles are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The streets smell of urine and rotting food. This morning a
little boy played with a hoop made from some rusting car part,
guiding it with a bent wire hanger down the filthy street. I have
not seen one place of tranquility or beauty.
</P>
<P>
   We are looking for refugees. We have heard that more than
100,000 ethnic Albanians are being emptied from the towns and
villages of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   We round a bend to find the chaos for which we had hoped. As far
as I can see, there are tractors towing carts filled with women,
old men and children.
</P>
<P>
   Seamus and I get out of the car to fill ourselves with the
story. We start wandering the seemingly endless line of tractors
pulling carts jammed with ethnic Albanians from Kosovo. They look
so worn out, so dazed. One pretty little girl I'd guess to be 5 or
6 a little younger than my son rests her head on her hands. Her
tiny little nails still bear traces of bright red nail polish. I
want to touch her, but I keep moving, keep studying.
</P>
<P>
   The only distinct sounds are the tractor motors and crying
babies. Many spent the frigid night at their mother's breast. God,
these are stout people. What would Americans do in such adversity?
</P>
<P>
   One woman sits against a waist-high stone wall with a baby
nestled under her dirty Chicago Bulls T-shirt. Her eyes seem empty.
</P>
<P>
   I move on. They come on this exodus with a little food, some
blankets and water in large plastic containers like the one I use
for lawn mower gasoline at my home in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Many eat dense slices of bread handed out by the Red Cross; the
small children clutch pieces in their fists.
</P>
<P>
   Later I learn than 9,000 refugees have spent the night in this
field, which is mostly mud and garbage.
</P>
<P>
   I ask them for their stories. Many of these people haven't seen
a sympathetic face in a long time. They want to talk to me, to
unburden themselves. I feel a duty to listen and try to hear it
all. The stories are confused and jumbled. One woman looks at my
plastic ID, which has the shield-shaped U.S. symbol that American
athletes used to wear at the Olympic Games. She smiles and points
to the sky. ``NATO,'' she says, ``NATO.''
</P>
<P>
   The stories are so consistent: Serb soldiers or paramilitaries
wearing masks swept through villages and ordered people out of
their homes. The people say they are robbed and commanded to go to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that all of Kosovo is being emptied.
</P>
<P>
   Pristina, the provincial capital, must be a ghost town. Enver
Doda, (CQ BOTH) a technician with a Pristina radio station, says
the Serbs round up 20,000 people each night and take them to the
sports stadium in the city center. They spend the night on the
playing field, uncertain of their fates.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they will be shot,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But in the morning, they are loaded into buses and driven toward
the boarders with Albania and Macedonia. More than 100,000 of them
have arrived in Albania, the poorest country in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't any people left in Pristina,'' Doda says. ``There
were 400,000 people there. Now there is no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Doda has been changed by this exodus. He seems a nice,
articulate young guy who speaks great English. He says he used to
be able to separate his feelings for Serb authorities from his
feelings about Serb police and soldiers. ``But now, I think they
are barbaric people,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to think that about any people, but I understand
his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Ilir Shaqiri, (CQ BOTH) a famous singer of patriotic Kosovar
songs, waits in line at the border crossing for the Albanian police
to register his car, which has no license plates.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs are said to be stripping people and their cars of all
identity documents an act intended to strip them of their
identities. Shaqiri says his house was fired upon and his family
has fled. He intends to join the guerrilla fighters with the Kosovo
Liberation Army to go back to fight the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   I continue to the border _ and cross the red line painted across
the bridge between the countries. I am in Kosovo for a few minutes,
still unable to see the end of the parade of refugees. The border
police say the line of cars, tractors, horse-drawn carts and people
on foot stretches back 10 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually every man and woman breaks into tears as they cross
the border.
</P>
<P>
   What must it mean to them to finally reach safety? I try to ask
a couple of them how they feel, but decide to skip pursuing such a
stupid and possibly insulting question. They don't have the words
to express their feelings, and I don't have the talent to express
it for them.
</P>
<P>
   I lean on the side of the bridge and watch Serb border guards
and wonder what they would say if I could ask them about all of
this.
</P>
<P>
   An older Kosovar taps me and asks through my translator if he
can tell me something. Of course.
</P>
<P>
   Tears fill his eyes. He says the Serbs shot his brother and
14-year-old nephew. ``They each have one bullet hole in the head,''
he says, pointing to the middle of his forehead with the tip of his
index finger. ``They killed every man on my street.'' He is from
the town of Jakova. He says that last Friday, masked Serb
paramilitaries went door-to-door down his street and forced the
residents from their houses. The men and women were separated.
``They tell the women, 'Go to Kosovo.'''
</P>
<P>
   He says that after the women were sent down the road, the men
were executed. Desperate for any details that can help me judge
whether there is any truth to this story, I ask him for the names
of the men.
</P>
<P>
   He names his brother, Skender Ibrahim, 43, and Skender's son,
Rigmond Ibrahim. He doesn't want to give his name, saying he fears
for his life.
</P>
<P>
   These stories are impossible to verify, a frustrating problem
for a journalist. I don't know what to make of it all.
</P>
<P>
   I look out again towards Kosovo, frustrated that Yugoslavian
authorities won't let me in so I can see for myself. This is an
important time to get at the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Again, a tap on my shoulder. The man who says he lost his
brother and nephew hands me a paper. On it are the names and ages
of four men under the words, ``killed persons.'' The names are
Naser Thafi, 30; Qazim Godeni, 65; Bexim Godeni, 26; and Xhevdet
Sadiki, 56. (ALL CQ)
</P>
<P>
   He entrusts the names to my care. I lean again on the railing
and look at the list, and try to imagine the people the names
represent.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, a few of my tears join the vast river.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr. is the London-based European correspondent
for Cox Newspapers. He has been covering the refugee situation in
Macedonia and Albania for the past week. His e-mail is:
Bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
