<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2900 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-HNS &LR;      04-01 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENDS NATO ACTION IN KOSOVO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-GONZALES and KOSOVO-LEGAL.
Stories will move shortly.) 
 
By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORFOLK, Va. _ Urging patience and determination, President
Clinton on Thursday passionately defended NATO's military campaign
in Kosovo before a military crowd that may be most affected by how
the operation unfolds.
</P>
<P>
   In his first out-of-town speech since he ordered airstrikes last
week in Yugoslavia, the president once again laid out the case for
the military action before more than 2,000 military personnel and
their families at the Norfolk Naval Station.
</P>
<P>
   With the Serb capture of three U.S. soldiers and the inability
of the airstrikes to halt the Serb campaign against the Kosovars,
Clinton has faced mounting criticism for his decision to get
involved in the troubled region.
</P>
<P>
   But saying ``this is not an easy challenge with a simple
answer,'' the president tried to respond to his critics who say
that airstrikes are not working.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing this for seven days now _ just seven days''
he said. ``Our pilots have performed bravely and well, in the face
of dangerous conditions and often abysmal weather. But we must be
determined and patient. Remember, the Serbs had 40,000 troops in
and around Kosovo, and nearly 300 tanks, when they began this,
before the first NATO plane got in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the Serb offensive against the ethnic Albanians would
have been carried out regardless of whether the NATO forces had
struck and that at least the United States and its allies had
signaled to Serb leader Slobodan Milosevic that such atrocities
would not go unpunished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we, in the last year of the 20th century, going to look
the other way as entire peoples in Europe are forced to abandon
their homelands or die? Are we going to impose a price on that kind
of conduct and seek to end it?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also tried to blunt criticism that the United States has
been selective in its response to ethnic cleansing, ignoring
similar activity elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't respond to every tragedy in every corner of the
world,'' he said. ``But just because we can't do everything for
everyone doesn't mean that for the sake of consistency we should do
nothing for no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo is strategically significant because the region has
spawned bloody conflicts in this century, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say, what has this got to do with America? Remember we
fought two world wars in Europe,'' he said. ``This is something we
are doing to try and avoid in the 21st century the kind of
widespread war, large American casualties and heartbreak that we
saw too much of in the century we are about to leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The president also warned Milosevic of severe consequences for
Serb capture of three U.S. military peacekeepers in Macedonia,
vowing, ``America takes care of its own.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president never mentioned another thorny issue _ his
refusal so far to send ground troops into Kosovo. A number of
military experts and lawmakers have argued that the only way to
stop the Serbs is through a ground campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen reiterated the administration's
stand in a briefing to reporters before the president's speech,
saying ``there are no plans and no intent to use ground troops.
We're carrying forward with our air campaign, and that's something
that NATO is solidly behind, and we're solidly behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his speech Clinton met privately for an hour with about
20 families of soldiers deployed to the Balkans. He also called
Aviano Air Base in Italy, where many of the NATO military aircraft
flying over Yugoslavia are based.
</P>
<P>
   For the address, the White House chose a setting that they hoped
would bolster Clinton's military image.
</P>
<P>
   Behind Clinton in the cavernous airplane hangar were two fighter
jets and a bleacher filled with military personnel and their
families. The president was joined by U.S. Sen. Charles S. Robb,
D-Va., a decorated Vietnam veteran. Virginia's other senator,
Republican John Warner, a former Navy secretary and chairman of the
Armed Services Committee, declined an invitation to attend, an
administration spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed after Clinton's address expressed considerably
more support for the operation than those questioned before the
president spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should be robbed of their history, who they are and
their identity,'' said Brenda Gentry, whose husband is in the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   John Alsop, who is in the Navy, said he had become increasingly
convinced of the necessity of the mission after seeing photographs
of ethnic Albanians fleeing their homes under threat of massacre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got the makings of turning into another Holocaust,'' he
said, but added he does not believe airstrikes alone would
accomplish the mission. He said he wanted Clinton to authorize the
ground operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was waiting for him to say exactly when the troops are going
in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Etter said the president made a ``good case'' for
military action. ``A lot of wars have started in that area. Let's
just nip it in the bud.''
</P>
<P>
   But others were not as convinced that the United States should
be involved in the European dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Maclin, a 36-year old Navy aviation mechanic, said he
believed the United States had rushed into military action and
should have spent more time negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should have held out a little longer than we did,''
he said. ``Now it doesn't look too good to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
