<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2911 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-CELLUCCI-ANGIOPLAS     04-01 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CELLUCCI-ANGIOPLASTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS GOVERNOR FACES POSSIBLE HEART PROCEDURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Saying that he is not facing a medical emergency but
rather a quality-of-life issue, Governor Paul Cellucci will enter a
Worcester hospital Friday to undergo a routine medical procedure
that will likely correct a blocked coronary artery.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure on the 50-year old governor, which experts say is
a common medical operation, will begin with a catheterization to
confirm his doctor's diagnosis of why Cellucci feels shortness of
breath when he exercises. With that confirmation, the physicians
will carry out an angioplasty to expand the restricted heart
artery.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, who will be awake during the procedure, is expected to
spend the night at St. Vincent Hospital and be released on
Saturday. He said Thursday he plans to be back at his desk at the
State House on Monday for a full day of work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is really no medical emergency to do anything now,''
Cellucci told reporters Thursday as he and his doctor, George
Saperia, downplayed the risk or implications of the procedure.
``It's kind of a quality-of-life issue. I would like to exercise
without getting this discomfort.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said he has been told there is a only a ``remote''
chance that the catheterization will find some other problem than
the one diagnosed by Saperia.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he began feeling a shortness of breath just
over a year ago when he took his routine morning 4-mile walks. At
the time, the doctor perscribed drugs for high blood pressure and
high cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci also said he changed his diet several years to lower
his cholesteral count, which he said is now about 190. He said his
blood pressure reading is now about 120 over 80. Both readings are
considered normal.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he and his doctor decided in January to
schedule the procedure because they felt the medication was not
correcting it. They chose to do it Friday because it accommodated
both their schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This had no effect on my job performance, has no effect, will
not have any effect,'' the governor said. He said Lieutenant
Governor Jane Swift can make any decision when he is incapicatated.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci said did not feel any obligation to reveal the
condition during last year's campaign because it has no impact on
his ability to carry out his duties as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love my job... I don't consider this a stressful job,''
Cellucci said. He added that Dr. Saperia indicated it is ``more a
genetic thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
