<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN CALLS ON GROUP OF EIGHT NATIONS TO MEET ON KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin fired off another peace
offensive Thursday, even as a Russian military reconnaissance ship
was heading into the Mediterranean in an open demonstration of
Moscow's anti-NATO stance in the conflict in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing Thursday on national television, Yeltsin called for an
emergency meeting of the foreign ministers of the world's seven
leading industrial powers, plus Russia, to seek a political
settlement in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Since six members of the group are now involved in the NATO
bombing campaign, Yeltsin's latest proposal seemed as unlikely to
be successful as the diplomatic mission earlier this week to
Belgrade and then to Germany led by Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov.
</P>
<P>
   But with its back-to-back diplomatic initiatives, Moscow is
clearly trying to maintain a visible role in the crisis, and take
the lead in calling for a political settlement to a conflict that
has already caused damage to its relations with the West, and to
its own political equilibrium.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO bombing campaign has unleashed a powerful tide of
anti-Western sentiment in Russia, which has been a significant
factor in Moscow's handling of the crisis. Politicians of all
stripes here are united in a condemnation of NATO's actions. The
debate now is over how best to counter them, by military or by
diplomatic means.
</P>
<P>
   As the chorus for a military response picks up steam, top
generals have said they are considering more ``appropriate
measures'' as a response to the conflict. This week, the Russian
Defense Ministry notified Turkey of its plans to send seven vessels
from its Black Sea Fleet through the Bosporus, starting with the
electronic intelligence-gathering ship Liman, which is due to leave
the port of Sevastopol on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A final decision to send the other six ships, including the
flagship cruiser Admiral Golovkov; two anti-submarine ships, the
Kerch and the Sderzhanny, and two patrol ships, the Pytlivy and the
Ladny, has yet to be made.
</P>
<P>
   By ostentatiously sending ships into the Mediterranean, where
Russia already has one intelligence-gathering vessel, the
government has mixed its signals, earning an irked rebuke from
Washington. Some Russian newspapers on Thursday interpreted the
Defense Ministry's move as a step toward more direct involvement
with its historic ally Serbia, even though Yeltsin and others have
pledged to keep Russia out of the military conflict. Others have
suggested that sending out the spy ship is more a political gesture
than a military one.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military has put on other displays of force this
week. The Northern Fleet has dispatched 20 vessels on military
exercises in the Barents Sea, which Thursday was the staging area
for a successful ballistic missile launch.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin said his proposal for a meeting of the eight foreign
ministers was a sequel to the Primakov mission, which, according to
Moscow, failed because of NATO intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kosovo problem can and must be settled at the negotiating
table,'' Yeltsin said in his special television address. ``This was
clear from Yevgeny Primakov's talks with Slobodan Milosevic,'' the
president of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   According to some Russian analysts, Moscow will keep introducing
ideas _ and even taunts _ in order to keep its hand in the
diplomatic game over Kosovo, waiting until the moment when the West
has to turn to Russia to act as broker in a political settlement
with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats here have also noticed that for all the harsh
Cold War oratory heard from top officials here recently, Moscow's
actions have been relatively mild, and several key elements of its
relations with the United States have remained untouched.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1900EST &QL; 
