<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2920 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENIUM-ORVIETO     04-01 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENIUM-ORVIETO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outside Rome, the elders worship amid empty pews
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, APRIL 4. DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN.)
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORVIETO, Italy _ You can see your breath in the sanctuary of St.
Andrew and St. Bartholomew Church on a drizzly Saturday night
during Lent.
</P>
<P>
   Half a dozen space heaters feebly try to battle the chill of a
temperature barely breaking the 30s as older women, in wool or fur
coats, gather on the hard, worn wooden pews to pray the rosary.
Their voices hum below the urgent appeal of the bells in the tower,
which seem to beg others to come. As the women continue their
prayers, the tone of the bells becomes deeper and the rhythm more
frantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ave Maria, piena di grazia,'' the women repeat in Italian_
``Hail Mary, full of grace''_the cadence of the words obvious even
to those who do not know the language.
</P>
<P>
   In front of them, incongruous with the tall gray stone walls and
the dark wood of the church, a representation of Mary is haloed in
small white electric lights.
</P>
<P>
   St. Andrew and St. Bartholomew is a combined parish of about 400
families in the medieval part of this hill town of 21,000 people in
the region of Umbria about 90 minutes from Rome. The church is one
of hundreds of struggling congregations off the usual path of
tourists in Italy, the homeland of Catholicism.
</P>
<P>
   Although some 88 percent of Italians identify themselves as
Catholic, Catholicism is often more a matter of culture than of
practice.
</P>
<P>
   Great Christian works of art draw millions of visitors to
museums, the smallest alcove in the largest city may be adorned
with an icon, and a street is likely to bear the name of a saint.
</P>
<P>
   But despite Catholic teachings against artificial birth control
and abortion, the average Italian woman bears only 1.2 children,
and one in four pregnancies end in abortion. Also contrary to
church teachings, Italy's divorce rate doubled between 1980 and
1995 _ although it remains a fraction of that in the United States.
And, only 29 percent of the country's Catholics said they attend
Mass at least once a week, according to a 1998 International Social
Survey Programme, down from 34 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Alita Gia, who will not give her age but describes herself
through an interpreter as ``an old woman,'' comes to Mass at St.
Bartholomew and St. Andrew daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older people come,'' she says. ``Even here, those who are
young, both husband and wife, have to work and young people are in
school.''
</P>
<P>
   In years gone by, she says, the church was fuller. ``People were
freer. Women were much more in church. Since people are busy, women
are much more uninvolved in church.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time St. Andrew and St. Bartholomew's pastor, the Rev.
Marcello Piterelli, steps up to give a homily on Jesus' temptation
by Satan from the book of Matthew, about 40 people are in the pews.
All but a handful are women. There is one family with children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older people are the largest group,'' Piterelli, 77,
acknowledges. In his 52nd year in the priesthood, he has served
this parish and another rural one nearby since 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many people who experience intensive spiritual
foment,'' he says. ``They've lost the yeast in their life, what
brings them joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Even those people who remain ``firmly connected'' to the church,
he says, are not necessarily tied in to its full spiritual
dimensions. ``Some of them,'' he said, ``are scrupulously attached
to the formality of the gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   As Piterelli prepares the bread and wine, believed to be Jesus'
body and blood, worshippers can hear the bells of another church in
the background.
</P>
<P>
   When they have had communion, Piterelli announces that the Mass
is concluded, and the worshippers go out into a drizzling rain.
</P>
<P>
   Store windows on the streets nearby display bright pottery and
fashionable clothes. And the cobblestone lanes are crowded with
laughing, chatting shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
