<SLUG> BC-CBS-KING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS SWAPS $3.5 BILLION IN STOCK FOR KING WORLD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)   By GERALDINE FABRIKANT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS Inc. announced Thursday that it had agreed to buy King World
Productions Inc., the syndicator of television hits like ``The
Oprah Winfrey Show,'' ``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy,'' for
$2.5 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Karmazin, the chairman of CBS, said that his company would
swap 0.81 CBS share for each of King World's 74 million outstanding
shares, which values them at $33 each based on CBS's closing price
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of King World rose 56.25 cents Thursday, to $31.125. CBS
fell 68.25 cents, to $40.125.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has been looking to extend its control over programming for
its owned-and-operated stations. From a financial view, King World
not only has $800 million in cash on its balance sheet, but it
requires little capital expenditure and carries no debt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, King World's controlling shareholders, Roger King,
54, the chairman, and his brother, Michael King, 50, the vice
chairman, who have about 20 percent of King World's stock, have
long been considering whether to sell their company or expand it.
</P>
<P>
   Though King World has come up with some of the most successful
TV shows in history, it has failed to match that success investing
the cash those hits have generated. In a conference call Thursday,
Karmazin and the King brothers described the new relationship as
one in which the Kings could focus on programming while Karmazin
focused on investing the capital that King World brings to the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel is a very good banker,'' Michael King said. ``And King
World has not been a good banker. We will do what we do best,
programming, and we will let Mel invest.''
</P>
<P>
   In selling to CBS, the King brothers will keep management roles.
Both will report to Leslie Moonves, the president of CBS
Television. Because the deal is for stock, the Kings are not forced
to pay capital gains taxes on the sale. Once the deal is completed,
which is expected later this year, the brothers will own about 1.6
percent of CBS. Oprah Winfrey, who is also a King World
shareholder, will own about five-tenths of a percent. Karmazin owns
about 1 percent of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Both CBS and King World have syndication businesses, and the
companies said Thursday that they planned to keep those businesses
separate. But Chris Dixon, an analyst at Paine Webber Inc., said
the merger would give CBS more leverage in the television
syndication business because a single company will be selling rerun
rights to a larger group of programs. Among CBS's first-run shows
are ``Martha Stewart Living'' and ``Pensacola, Wings of Gold.''
King World programs about 20 hours a week, Dixon noted, including
``Wheel of Fortune,'' the highest-rated syndicated show, and the
No. 2 ``Jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   But what particularly appealed to Wall Street about the deal was
that it will add immediately to CBS's bottom line. The merger will
add about 10 cents a share to CBS's 1999 net profits. Though CBS's
television stations make money, the network itself loses money, and
the King World deal will help offset some of those losses. Because
CBS has tax-loss carryforwards that it inherited through its merger
with Westinghouse four years ago, it can probably shelter income
from federal taxes this year and part of next year as well, CBS's
chief financial officer, Fred Reynolds, said.
</P>
<P>
   Though numerous companies had considered bidding for King World,
one key problem has been whether Oprah Winfrey would renew her
contract after it expires in 2002. But as one analyst said
Thursday, few thought either ``Wheel of Fortune'' or ``Jeopardy''
would survive as long as they have, and they have been sold to
stations through 2005.
</P>
<P>
   For its fiscal year ended Aug. 31, King World had a profit of
$136 million on revenue of $684 million. In 1998, CBS had revenue
of $6.8 billion and a net loss of $21 million.
</P>
<P>
   John Tinker, who follows the company for Nationsbanc Montgomery
Securities, said King World would have a better shot at making new
shows more successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``CBS immediately gives them a broad reach since its stations
reach 32 percent of the country,'' he said. ``That leverage is very
valuable. And there may be some advantages even for shows that are
syndicated on other stations. Take Oprah Winfrey. She is now on
ABC. But even before the contract is up, CBS could do specials.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Who knows what happens when the contract is up.''
</P>
<P>
   The investment bank Allen &AMP; Co. represented King World. CBS
represented itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
