A2929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPTURE-SCENE-BOS &LR;      04-01 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPTURE-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLDIERS ON PATROL IN UNFRIENDLY TERRITORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALGUNJA, Macedonia _ When three members of the 1st Squadron of
the 4th US Cavalry were captured by Serb forces in a valley nestled
below this border village, they were driving through an area the
troops have dubbed ``Injun country.''
</P>
<P>
   In the villages northeast of Kumanovo, most of the residents are
ethnic Serbs. They have been hostile to the US troops that have
been driving through their villages for the last five years, and
especially since the NATO bombing campaign against Yugoslavia began
March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday afternoon, Slave Markovic, the local postman, led two
reporters to the top of a hill overlooking the road, he and other
local people said, on which the US soldiers were driving when Serb
troops surrounded them and peppered their armored Humvee vehicle
with small-arms fire. Speaking on the condition on anonymity, a
NATO officer confirmed that the last radio contact with the
captured soldiers was in the area pointed out by Markovic.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian TV quoted residents of the Yugoslav village of
Slavuevac as saying that the Americans had driven about a mile into
Serbian territory before they were captured, following shouted
warnings and shots.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Globe, Markovic, 36, who said he heard
but did not see the shooting, said the soldiers had been on a road
that leads into Yugoslavia. He and other locals from Tatarinovac,
the last village in Macedonia before the border, are convinced the
Americans unwittingly crossed into Serbian territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans vehemently deny this, saying that when confronted
by hostile forces the three-man reconnaissance team radioed back
that they were three miles from the border. But radio contact was
lost, and those who took part in a desperate and ultimately futile
search-and-rescue mission said they had no idea where the soldiers
were when they were captured.
</P>
<P>
   General Wesley Clark, NATO's Supreme Allied Commander, said the
three soldiers were captured while in Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   From the hillside overlooking the unpaved road where locals say
the capture took place, the rugged terrain provides ample
opportunity for an ambush. Given the hostility of the indigenous
population, military officials here are not ruling out the
possibility that the soldiers were set up by Serb partisans, who
may have tipped off Serb forces about the movements of US troops on
border patrol.
</P>
<P>
   Markovic said that local youths were bragging that they helped
lure the Americans into a trap when the US patrol stopped and asked
them how far they were from the border. US and NATO officials in
Skopje, the Macedonian capital, scoffed at that claim, saying the
soldiers never would have sought or relied on directions from
locals they knew to be hostile to them.
</P>
<P>
   Between noon and 5 p.m. Thursday, no less than five separate
NATO patrols, ranging from two to four vehicles, were seen in the
vicinity of where the soldiers were captured. While the men who
were captured went out on patrol with two other vehicles, it is
unclear how or why they got separated.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Globe on Tuesday, the captured
soldiers' commander, Lieutenant Colonel James Shufelt, said his
troops were routinely stoned as their vehicles passed through
ethnic Serb villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at risk,'' Shufelt said. Still, interviews with Shufelt
and several of the 350 soldiers under his command suggested they
have felt relatively secure as they performed scouting missions
along the border with Kosovo and southeast Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the squadron was confident enough about security along
the border that it had allowed reporters to accompany patrols this
week.
</P>
<P>
   The task force at Camp Able Sentry had just finished a five-year
UN peacekeeping mission along the Macedonian border. Last week, the
soldiers began reconnaisance missions along the border in support
of the NATO troops waiting in Macedonia to implement a Kosovo peace
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Army refused to answer questions Thursday about the
abductions, including what kind of equipment was on board that
would have helped the soldiers avoid crossing into Yugoslav
territory by mistake. But a US military source said those who
conduct border patrols routinely carry a global positioning system,
a navigation device that allows them to follow the contours of the
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their patrol plan was nowhere near the border,'' said a US
Army officer, who acknowledged, however, that the soldiers could
have taken a wrong turn or misread the positioning system.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to the scene of the capture Thursday, and to the
captured soldiers' base on Tuesday, provided some insight as to why
the Americans were unable to flee or fight when confronted on an
isolated border road.
</P>
<P>
   First, there are no markings or checkpoints clearly showing the
border. The road is treacherous and only wide enough for one
vehicle, making the prospect of turning around difficult and time
consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers interviewed Tuesday said that while the Humvees are
bulletproof, they cannot withstand hand-held or mobile-launched
missiles, which could be easily aimed at them in an ambush.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans were under orders to carry their M-16 rifles on
patrol. But the Humvee is cramped, with heavy armored doors that
are cumbersome to open. If the Americans were surrounded as they
reported, it would have been difficult for them to leap out to
defend themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Shufelt said troops at Camp Able Sentry are on a six-month
rotation, and that most of the soldiers under his command had been
at the base for about 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking privately, one NATO officer said it was possible the
soldiers got lost and inadvertently drove into Serb territory,
while another said the border mission dated back to 1993 and that
the squadron was well aware of the border's contours.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with villagers, meanwhile, suggested that the US
soldiers, and the investigators now trying to piece together the
capture, could not count on help from local residents, who consider
themselves Serbs living in Yugoslavia, despite the fact that
Macedonia quit the Yugoslav Federation in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In the Macedonian village of St. Nagoricane, a few miles from
the site of the capture, ethnic Serb residents rejoiced as they
watched news on the television of Zika Tosic's cafe and convenience
shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell Clinton this,'' Tosic said, pulling his forefinger
across his neck to imitate a throat-cutting. ``It is too bad they
only got three.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby farming community of Nikuljane, villagers
complained that troops searching for the captured soldiers ran over
and killed a dog, wrecked vineyards, and traumatized small children
with low-flying helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The jeeps go by every day and we can't sleep. They scare the
children,'' said Blagoja Jovcic, the village elder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
