<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ADVISORY-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
  
(gm)
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times is planning a five-page package of stories,
photos and graphics on the continuing crisis in Kosovo:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ Ledeall. Western officials are quietly
discussing plans to turn Kosovo into an international protectorate
under the guard of allied troops, a senior NATO diplomat said
today. NATO officials insist they are still ruling out an invasion
force to wrest control of the Kosovo province from the Yugoslav
military.
</P>
<P>
   By Michael R. Gordon
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Norfolk, Va.) _ The Clinton administration sought
grimly today to turn the Serb capture of three American soldiers
into a rallying point for the American public and a deeply
skeptical Congress to support a NATO air operation which has failed
in its most basic objective to stop brutalities in Kosovar. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Kumanovo, Macedonia) _ A look at what we know
of how and why the three soldiers were captured. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SOLIDERS (Undated) _ Talking to family and friends about
the three captured soldiers. By Brett Pulley.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ The bombing is stepped up as the
weather clears. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The three captured U.S. soldiers
will face a Serbian military court as early as Friday. President
Slobodan Milosevic meets the ethnic-Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova.
Other developments. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REGUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ In a chilling display of
force, Serb gunmen are systematically emptying Kosovo's capital
city, Pristina, marching its ethnic Albanians out through gantlets
of masked, heavily armed Serbs, refugees crossing the border today
said. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE (Berlin) _ A look at the huge refugee crisis
facing Europe and the strains it is causing among the allies. By
Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RIGHTS (Geneva) _ A human rights report on Yugoslavia
says that both the Albanians and Serbs are guilty of abuses. By
Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ President Yeltsin calls for G-8 meeting
on Kosovo; other Russian developments. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Tirana, Albania) _ A KLA spokesman in Tirana says
his rebel group is helping NATO spot targets. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ A situationer on what the Kosovo
crisis means for Albania. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELIGION (Undated) _ As celebrations of Easter,
Christianity's holiest day, draw near for the faithful worldwide, a
growing number of leaders of Roman Catholic, Orthodox and
Protestant churches are calling for an end to the hostilities
between the member nations of NATO and Yugoslavia. By Gustav
Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BOSNIA (Undated) _ At first, the parallels seem clear. In
August 1995, a NATO bombing campaign seemed to force Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to back down and end the ruinous war
in Bosnia. Now, three and a half years later, Washington has
unleashed another NATO bombing campaign expecting that Milosevic
would react the same way. But military analysts say that events in
Kosovo province are proving to be vastly different from Bosnia in
1995. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   We also commend to your attention these stories from our partner
papers, the Houston Chronicle, part of the Hearst newspaper group,
and the Fort Worth Star-Telegram:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GONZALES-HNS _ (Huntsville, Texas) U.S. Army Spec. Steven
M. Gonzales was a popular straight-A student at Palestine High
School, where he graduated in 1995, with an interest in science.
Gonzales' father is a prison worker in Huntsville, site of Texas'
death row. By Allan Turner and Kathy Walt. (Photo TK from afternoon
press conference)
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-SOLDIERS-TEX (Huntsville, Texas) _ The East Texas town
of Huntsville is best known for its prison and a succession of
executions. But today the town is festooned with yellow ribbons
because one of the U.S. Army soldiers captured on the border of
Macedonia and Kosovo, Spec. Steven M. Gonzales, calls Huntsville
home. Gonzalez's family lives in Huntsville, where his father is a
prison employee, and he graduated from high school in another East
Texas town, Palestine. By John Moritz and Michelle Melendez.
</P>
