u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PROPAGANDA-WAR-BOS     04-01 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PROPAGANDA-WAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMAGES OF CAPTURED SOLDIERS COULD CHANGE SUPPORT FOR WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until now, the warfare in Serbia has produced a confusing
collage of television images -- refugees streaming across borders,
allied planes lifting off for bombing runs, assorted demolished
buildings and talking heads pontificating from the safety of the
studio.
</P>
<P>
   The media phase of the conflict came into much sharper focus
Thursday, however, when the battered faces of three captured US
soldiers _ Andrew Ramirez, Christopher J. Stone and Steven M.
Gonzales _ became the dominant television image, dramatically
driving home the concept of real risks to real Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives (the war) a face, doesn't it?'' said Brookings
Institution senior fellow Stephen Hess. ``The media needed it; . .
. you need it to frame a story.''
</P>
<P>
   While the sight of the captured servicemen could increase public
interest in Kosovo, it also conjures up memories of Michael Durant,
the US Army helicopter pilot who was captured and dragged through
the streets of Mogadishu, Somalia in 1993. Television images of the
injured American captive were widely credited with souring public
opinion on the Somalia mission and US forces pulled out within
months. (Time magazine published a cover story headlined: ``What in
the World Are We Doing?'' next to a picture of a wounded Durant.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, the question is whether pictures of three US prisoners in
Serbia could start prompting the nation to question the wisdom of a
war about which it is already ambivalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sort of the calculus of how much sacrifice is too much
for something that is important but not vital,'' to US interests,
said Pew Research Center director Andrew Kohut, whose polling
reveals tepid support for the US role in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the story of the captured airmen _ who may stand trial
in Yugoslavia as early as Friday _ quickly moved into the media
spotlight. Their photographs led all three major network newscasts
Thursday evening. CNN's ``Crossfire'' program tackled the topic
with former Vietnam prisoner of war Senator John McCain, from
Arizona. The parents of Steven Gonzales discussed his capture at a
press conference while news reports showed yellow ribbons being
strung around trees in honor of the captives.
</P>
<P>
   With US soldiers suddenly in enemy hands, Thursday's coverage
featured other telling reminders of American foreign policy
debacles. A Fox News Channel report noted that some citizens were
``starting to talk about Vietnam,'' while a participant in CNN's
``Talkback'' program characterized the servicemen as ``hostages,''
a grim throwback to the Iranian takeover of the US embassy in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the American media have been treating NATO's war in
the Balkans as a major story. According to network news analyst
Andrew Tyndall, 64 percent of the ABC, NBC and CBS nightly
newscasts last week were devoted to Yugoslavia. That is ``more than
the peak week of Monica,'' he said. ``This is the peak foreign
policy story of the Clinton presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet public opinion does not seem to have crystallized in favor
of or against US involvement in the ethnic strife. By a narrow
margin _ 47 percent to 42 percent _ the respondents to an
ABC/Washington Post poll believed vital US interests are at stake.
A plurality of those polled by the Pew Research Center disapproved
of sending US troops to Kosovo as peacekeepers. When asked if the
United States has a responsibility to do something about ethnic
fighting in Kosovo, the Pew respondents were split right down the
middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's really important,'' said Kohut, ``is we don't have a
majority...saying what happens in Kosovo is vital to the US.''
People are responding to the war on a humanitarian basis, he added,
but have yet to be convinced it is in the best interests of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Tyndall believes that television coverage of the war to date has
not benefited American policymakers, since ``we see the refugees''
pouring out of Kosovo and it appears that ``the bombing created the
refugee crisis.'' The prisoners make the situation even more dicey,
he added, since ``Clinton's been really leery of anybody in uniform
getting killed ever since Somalia.''
</P>
<P>
   Janet Kolodzy, a former CNN producer who teaches a course in
international media at Emerson College in Boston, offered the
dissenting view that images of the captives could spark a more
hawkish public response. ``I think it's really going get people
angry,'' she said. ``People feel (the conflict in) Iraq was dragged
out, and I think it could backfire on the Serbs.'' She did
acknowledge, however, that the Serbs may have been emboldened by
what happened in Somalia to use the prisoners for public relations
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Kohut does point out that the lessons of Somalia have been
misinterpreted. ``It was misinterpreted as Americans aren't willing
to accept casualties,'' he explained. ``What's clear is that
Americans won't accept casualties when they don't think our vital
interests are at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kohut's own data, the Clinton administration has
yet to convince Americans that our national interest is on the line
in Yugoslavia. Unless he does, painful images of three bruised
American captives could prove to be the loudest shot fired in the
Balkan war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
