<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-EDTV-PRODUCTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO MANY PRODUCTS, SO FEW BUCKS FOR THEM IN `EDTV' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Holy product placement!
</P>
<P>
   Moviegoers who caught ``EDtv'' during its opening weekend
couldn't help but notice the number of name-brand products featured
in the film.
</P>
<P>
   For those not familiar with the concept of ``EDtv,'' it's the
tale of Ed, a regular guy who agrees to let a cable TV channel
broadcast his life, 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Ed eats Pop Tarts for breakfast and drinks lots of Pepsi. His
girlfriend, Shari, delivers packages for UPS, wearing the company's
trademark brown uniform, of course. When Ed and Shari eventually
break up, there's a USA Today poll _ declaring Shari an unfit
girlfriend _ to thank.
</P>
<P>
   These are just a few of the name brands featured in Ed's
everyday life. Factor in the dozens of companies _ including
Calgon, Saturn, Maytag and Trojan _ who buy commercial time on the
live TV show, and who could blame moviegoers for assuming serious
cash was made from product placement?
</P>
<P>
   Director Ron Howard wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were going to get a lot of money out of this
product placement. I really did,'' Howard said during a recent
visit to Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the case. Advertisers granted permission to use
their logos but wouldn't pay any placement fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't because of the satirical nature of the movie,''
Howard explained. ``Its irreverent edginess made them fear somehow
that their product would be in a movie that was a little too
controversial, that it may be used in a situation that might not do
the product credit. Or, they thought we might make fun of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lack of cash didn't keep Howard from using the products, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed real products. I wanted it to be as realistic as it
could be, so I wanted recognizable names. I don't want to make up a
name for a condom. I want Trojan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be a smart element in the movie, and I also
thought, we're going to offset our budget with this. I bet we can
raise a couple million bucks with this advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wound up being zippo. Well, it wasn't zippo because they
did give us the right to use their logos and that is giving
something. And I think we might have gotten a little money for the
Reebok plants, but not a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been hearing about this all my life and have never been
able to cash in on it. Maybe someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmm, Howard's next film is ``How the Grinch Stole Christmas.''
For his trip to Whoville, maybe the evil green one could drive a
Ford Explorer instead of a sleigh.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
