<HEADER>
A2948 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-NY     04-01 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ALBANIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELEAGUERED ALBANIA IS TAKING IN REFUGEES _ AND PROUD OF IT
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-SOLIDERS, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REGUGEES,
KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-RIGHTS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-REBELS,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-RELIGION, KOSOVO-BOSNIA) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(wg) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ In a muddy outdoor recreation center in this
capital city, the Albanian army has set up 200 tents around an
empty swimming pool to house 2,000 of the Kosovo refugees who have
poured across the border and been bused here for relocation.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Albanian soldiers and local volunteers ladled out rice
from huge cauldrons onto plastic plates for families, crouched on
blankets and flattened cardboard boxes under canvas roofs.
</P>
<P>
   The refugee camp, chaotic and squalid but teeming with good
intentions, has become a kind of shining tent city on the hill for
beleaguered Albania _ a source of anxiety, but also of pride.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden influx of more than 100,000 Kosovo refugees is
already straining the resources of this country, the poorest in
Europe. But the fact that Albania, long the basket case of the
Balkans, is suddenly thrust into the role of benefactor has, for
now, lent its government and its citizens a novel sense of honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it is a sign to other countries,'' said Mufta, a
50-year-old mechanic. He showed up at Tirana's indoor basketball
court and sports arena, which has been transformed into the
capital's first clearing point for refugees, to seek a Kosovo
family he could take into his home. ``Italy helped our people when
they fled to their shores,'' he said, ``and now we Albanians have
to help the Albanians of Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years, Albania was the most isolated Communist
dictatorship in Eastern Europe. The overthrow of communism in 1991
was accompanied by riots and destruction that led to starvation in
some regions and tens of thousands of refugees. A shaky transition
to capitalism was stopped in its tracks two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Albanian was overwhelmed by nationwide riots that
followed the collapse of a series of pyramid schemes that cost tens
of thousands of Albanians their life savings. About 2,000 people
died in that uprising, a new wave of refugees fled, and investment
dried up.
</P>
<P>
   The country remains mired in corruption and crime, highway
robbery, blood feuds and organized gangs, much of it sustained by
more than 600,000 weapons looted from army and police armories
during the rioting.
</P>
<P>
   A sprawling Coca-Cola bottling plant, built by an Italian
subsidiary in 1993, was proudly re-opened four weeks ago, after it
burned down last year after an electrical fire. It is heralded
locally as a sign of Albania's free-market future, but next to the
red rooftop Coca-Cola logo are two piles of sandbags put up hastily
in 1997 to shield snipers, a reminder of the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   Albania's new prime minister, Pandeli Majko, 31, chosen last
September by the Socialist Party to replace Fatos Nano, who was
forced to resign, was supposed to be represent a new generation of
leadership. While he is not viewed as personally corrupt, few in
Albania are ready to praise his tangible accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Since the refugee crisis exploded on its borders, Majkos'
government has pleaded for international aid, but it has not waited
for outside assistance to help refugees. The Albanian Red Cross,
private businesses, state and city employees, high-school students
and elderly volunteers are on the front-line of assistance to the
Kosovo refugees in the capital, from pitching tents to distributing
food and clothing, and providing medical assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need Pampers for the babies, but otherwise we are doing all
right,'' said an Albanian nurse who was directing a makeshift
medical center in the Hotel Arberia, which the government
commandeered Monday as an emergency refugee center. On Thursday,
230 Kosovo refugees were packed into its corridors and rooms,
looked after by hotel employees and a team of nurses dispatched by
a local municipal clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Western governments and international aid organizations have
sent food and have pledged nearly $100 million in assistance for
the refugees. Foreign aid workers helping on the ground provide
efficient know-how and flashes of exasperation.
</P>
<P>
   Many have complained about the lack of coordination and
occasional flashbacks to Soviet-style bureaucracy, most noticeably
a decision by Albanian authorities at the border in Kukes on
Wednesday to institute a new and complicated system of registering
refugees. That led to long lines of refugees, many of whom had gone
without food for days, stretching back across the border into
Serbia. That decision was reversed Thursday and the processing
system eased a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that Albania has done a remarkable job despite the
difficulties, and the difficulties are enormous,'' a senior Western
diplomat said. Other European officials have emphasized the dangers
that the refugee emergency poses to Albania's already shaky
stability. The country was just about to get back on its feet from
the past implosion, the riots in 1997, when the Kosovo situation
happened, Daan Everts, director of the mission in Albania for the
Organization for Security and Cooperation, told reporters on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is wonderful how welcoming the Albanians have been of the
refugees, but you cannot expect that to last very long,'' he said.
``Longer-term settlement is going to be a difficult problem that
can become dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, however, Albanians seem to be mostly basking in a
sense of pride and unity with the West that has long eluded them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have stopped all our investments, all our budget is being
redirected for the refugees,'' Tirana's Mayor, Albert Brojka said
cheerfully as he stepped through the muddy paths of the tent city.
``I am hoping that we will persuade the West that Albania is part
of it, that we are European, and no longer under the Eastern
dictatorial system that we had here for 50 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
