<HEADER>
A2954 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-STYLE-HATS02     04-01 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-STYLE-HATS02 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hats a perfect topper for a look brimming with style
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ For some women, it's love at first sight.
</P>
<P>
   Browsing in the second-floor millinery salon at Elder-Beerman
Northwest last week, Caroline Watkins spotted a cream-colored
straw-and-mesh hat trimmed in delicate silk flowers and immediately
lost her heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm going to have to buy an outfit and shoes to match
it,'' says Watkins, a minister's wife from Dayton who has come in
search of an off-white hat she can wear to church for first
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman is completely dressed when she has her hat on,'' she
insists.
</P>
<P>
   Salon manager Julia Refour, who's been in the hat business for
13 years, couldn't agree more.
</P>
<P>
   Her boutique is filled with chapeaus of every style, shape and
color: delicate straw rollers in pretty pastels trimmed in dainty
florals and ribbon, boater styles with wide grosgrain ribbons and
bows, crisp white picture hats with upturned brims, colorful
reversible berets, gold and silver metallics, luxurious furs with
matching hats, and flings and gloves.
</P>
<P>
   Refour's hats range from $59 for a simple straw cloche to $499
for elaborate designer styles bearing names such as Jack McConnell,
George Zamau'l and Frank Olive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my first hat at age 18,'' Refour recalls. ``We wore hats
to church ... it was a straw floral profile for Easter. I thought I
was lookin' good.''
</P>
<P>
   Local hat lovers have followed Refour from store to store: First
to Donenfeld's, then Lazarus and _ since March 1998 _ Elder-Beerman
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   She sends hats to customers all over the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw celebrities wearing designer hats at the Academy
Awards,'' she says. ``After people saw them on television, they
called to see if we carried them. The same thing happened after a
wedding on `The Young and the Restless.'''
</P>
<P>
   Many local women, she says, buy hats for the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``One woman bought five hats recently and said that instead of
having to go back to her hotel to change outfits, she planned to go
to her car and change hats.''
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Lehman, owner of Gretchen &AMP; Co., says hats serve more
than a fashion function these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also a health issue because of our awareness of sun
damage,'' she says. ``I have a lot of customers who have already
had a problem with skin cancer and come to buy hats when they are
going to Florida or on a cruise.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman carries Amy Hamilton's charming handmade hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Amy's hats are very romantic, they have rosebuds and tulle in
beautiful pinks and lavenders,'' she says. Hamilton hats start at
$89.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen &AMP; Co. also carries Anabel Ingall's Australian hats
fashioned from paper straw ($110 and up), a full line of cotton
crocheted hats that start at $28, and panamas in a range of brights
and pastels.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Bush, director of the Headwear Information Bureau in New
York City, has represented the hat industry for years and wears
hats everywhere _ to the mailbox, walking her dog, to the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you wear a hat, you'll have men following you down the
street and it will get you a better seat at a restaurant,'' she
insists. ``The maitre d' is not about to sit you behind a pole when
you look so attractive.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush says spring is the hat season, with Easter and Mother's Day
being major hat holidays.
</P>
<P>
   She says color is making news this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going along with what's happening in ready-to-wear _ iced
blue, mint, pinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Now in her late 50s, Bush began wearing hats when she moved to
New York from Youngstown at the age of 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to stand out from the crowd,'' she says. ``A hat does
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's women, she says, feel the same, which is why hat sales
have been increasing by 10 percent to 15 percent a year since the
mid-'80s.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy Robbins of Dayton agrees.
</P>
<P>
   The 48-year-old woman has been wearing hats for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either have a plain outfit and the hat makes the outfit or
you buy an outfit and accent it with a hat,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a total look from the top of your head to the bottom of
your toes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to tell you that when you wear them a lot of people
notice you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
