A2955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CNN02-COX     04-01 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CNN02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For CNN, war is almost familiar
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the day of her fifth anniversary working at CNN,
Mina Ivanovic was rockin'. Standing up at her desk (without even
low walls to qualify it as a cubicle) in the CNN newsroom, she
stood, phone receiver in her left ear, phone receiver in her right
ear, rocking her weight from foot to foot as she juggled two
producersin the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Belgrade, Yugoslavia, Ivanovic is part of CNN's
multinational team that coordinates all of its international
coverage, and has been working 14 hours a day, including weekends,
since NATO started bombing Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's your hometown, you can't disengage completely,'' she said
during a brief period without a phone in her ear. ``But you've got
to do your job, you've got to get the news.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivanovic was approached by CNN seven years ago in Belgrade to be
a translator when the Yugoslav conflicts were heating up. Fluent in
English (four years in the United States as a child, plus her
college major) and Serbo-Croatian, she was supposed to go to London
for a PR job at a bank, but didn't want to leave her family, and
wound up working for CNN for two years in Yugoslavia. She moved to
Atlanta five years ago, and now works on the international desk
with native Russians, Chinese, Iranians, Germans, Turks and
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The adrenaline level isn't nearly as high inside CNN as it was
one week into the Gulf War; for one thing, the international desk
is more seasoned now, with an average of 10 years on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The 27 staffers make arrangements and call the shots for the
60-plus CNN employees in the Balkans region and surrounding
countries covering the war.
</P>
<P>
   Those correspondents, producers and crews have been in more
danger recently than most journalists were during the Gulf War.
Christiane Amanpour, who won her second Peabody Award on Wednesday
for her reporting from Yugoslavia, is posted in Albania
interviewing refugees because being inside Kosovo or Yugoslavia is
considered too dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has been singled out by name by certain people,'' said
Eason Jordan, president of CNN International. ``Her life would be
in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Serbs are considered hostile to most U.S.-based
media, CNN has been given special attention; Serbian TV has called
the network ``a factory of lies'' and accused it of war crimes. CNN
staffers have been repeatedly arrested and threatened, and their
equipment confiscated at roadblocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pulled up to an army checkpoint in a Jeep Cherokee. Next
thing you know, we're walking,'' said Steve Cassidy, international
deputy managing editor in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   CNN estimates it has lost $400,000 to $800,000 worth of
equipment to members of the Serb army or paramilitary groups,
including bulletproof vests, cell phones, cameras and even an
entire armored car.
</P>
<P>
   ``They took a Wegner Digital Video Encoder,'' said Cassidy.
``What are they going to do with that, unless they're going to
start an all-news network?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult conditions,'' said Will King, also a
deputy managing editor. ``There's no international Hyatts for them
to stay in.'' Some CNN staffers are in sleeping bags, one satellite
operator lived in his truck for 36 hours, and meals can be boiled
eggs, cheese and bottled water.
</P>
<P>
   Also getting lots of air time, in addition to Amanpour, are
Brent Sadler, who's back in Belgrade after being thrown out, and
Chris Burns, CNN's Berlin bureau chief, whose stand-up on the
Albanian border Thursday referred to an ``ethnic Albanian Trail of
Tears.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficult working conditions, CNN's ratings are up
since the NATO bombing began. Ratings for the past week were about
80 percent higher than March 1998, when Monica Lewinsky was the
focus of much of CNN and other news coverage. During the actual
bombing strikes, CNN's ratings have been up about 120 percent, to
nearly 1 million U.S. homes.
</P>
<P>
   The technology in covering a war in the '90s can be amazing:
multiple satellite feeds, digital images, live shots of refugees in
Albania, broadcasts taken directly from Serbian TV. (Of the three
TV sets on Ivanovic's desk, one is tuned to Serbian TV constantly.
On Thursday, despite the war, it was showing highlights of a
volleyball match.)
</P>
<P>
   Or it can be rather low-tech. Scotch-taped to a wall just
outside the CNN anchor booth is a large map of the Balkans, the
kind you'd buy at a good bookstore, with the $9.99 price tag still
on it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
