<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2957 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RELIGION-NYT &LR;      04-01 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RELIGION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS LEADERS CALL FOR END TO HOSTILITIES DURING HOLY DAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif.)  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-SOLIDERS, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REGUGEES,
KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-RIGHTS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-REBELS,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-BOSNIA) 
(ac) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As celebrations of Easter, Christianity's holiest day, draw near
for the faithful worldwide, a growing number of Roman Catholic,
Orthodox and Protestant leaders are calling for an end to the
hostilities between NATO nations and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome Thursday, Pope John Paul II urged a weeklong cease-fire
as a step toward a political settlement of the Kosovo crisis. The
pontiff's plea came at the close of a day-long visit to Belgrade by
the Vatican's top diplomat, Archbishop Jean-Louis Tauran, who met
Patriarch Pavle, the Serbian Orthodox Church's leader who also
called for a cease-fire. The archbishop also presented the pope's
plea to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, all eight Catholic cardinals in the United States
took a highly unusual joint action, calling for an immediate end to
the conflict and a resumption of negotiations, in public letters
sent to President Clinton and Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The cardinals also urged Milosevic to end attacks on Kosovar
Albanians, tens of thousands of whom have been driven from their
homes, and asked Clinton to halt NATO's airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Cardinal Law, archbishop of Boston, said in a telephone
interview that ``it has to be a cease-fire on both sides.''
Speaking of the Yugoslav Army's attacks on Kosovo civilians, he
said: ``The atrocities that are going on in Kosovo as they are
reported are simply unacceptable by any standards and must cease.''
Were those attacks to continue, he said, negotiations between NATO
and Yugoslavia would not be possible.
</P>
<P>
   Another signer, Roger Cardinal Mahony, archbishop of Los
Angeles, said the cardinals believed that five developments must
occur closely together to bring peace: an end to Yugoslav violence
in Kosovo; a halt to the NATO bombing; a return of the refugees; an
international effort in Kosovo to aid civilians and monitor peace;
and a regional peace conference. ``It doesn't work without all
five,'' Mahony said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bishop Joseph A. Fiorenza, president of the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, issued a statement
Wednesday calling on the Yugoslav government to halt its
``intolerable aggression'' against Kosovar Albanians and for NATO
to stop bombing as an ``appropriate response'' to such a
development.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic initiatives have come amidst similar, sometimes
emotional pleas from Orthodox Christian leaders. Ecumenical
Patriarch Bartholomew I of Constantinople, senior figure among the
heads of self-governing Orthodox churches, issued a statement this
week appealing ``on bended knees'' and ``from the tormented depths
of my heart'' for an immediate cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   His message was quoted in its entirety in an Easter appeal for
an end to all fighting _ in Yugoslavia and elsewhere _ by
representatives of the World Council of Churches, which comprises
nearly 340 Protestant and Orthodox denominations, and global
federations of Anglican, Baptist, Lutheran, Methodist and Reformed
Protestant churches.
</P>
<P>
   Lending urgency to many of the appeals is the conjunction of
holy days among the world's major monotheistic faiths, occurring
over a 15-day span that began last Saturday when Muslims celebrated
the feast of Id al-Adha, which marks the culmination of Mecca
pilgrimage. On Wednesday evening, Jews began celebrating Passover.
Western Christian churches celebrate Easter on Sunday, which is
Palm Sunday in the calendar of the Orthodox churches.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, Tauran said the pope ``and many Christian leaders
like Patriarch Pavle, whom I have just met, consider that it would
be a gesture of great humanity if all military actions would be
suspended by all during the week that separates the Western and
Eastern commemorations of this feast.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar idea was recently offered by Archbishop Spyridon, head
of the Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of the United States, who wrote
to Clinton last week, asking that the NATO bombing be halted from
April 1 to April 12, a period preceding Good Friday in the Western
Christian calendar and extending until the day after Orthodox
Easter.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek Orthodox Archdiocese is a member of the National
Council of Churches, whose general secretary, the Rev. Joan B.
Campbell, said on Wednesday that she was intrigued by another idea
discussed within the council's Protestant and Orthodox member
churches, a cease-fire over the Orthodox Easter weekend. ``It seems
to me we have to break the cycle of violence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But more important than public statements, she said, was that
many churches were contributing aid to Kosovar Albanian refugees.
``The place where the church always stands strong is in those
places where people are hurting,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
