<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, April 2 and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8158.
</P>
<P>
   USCANADA-SALMON (Seattle) _ Buoyed by ad hoc accords that have
more salmon spawning in both Puget Sound and British Columbia
rivers, Gov. Gary Locke and Canada's fisheries minister David
Anderson say this is the year to resolve the U.S.-Canada fisheries
dispute up and down the Pacific Coast.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-BOMBS (Seattle) _ The Pentagon wants Boeing to speed up
production of a guidance system that turns dumb bombs into smart
ones just in case the air force runs short in a protracted bombing
campaign of Yugoslovia.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BOEING-C17 (Seattle) _ Boeing has offered to build 60 more of
its giant C-17 transport planes for the Air Force for nearly $50
million below the usual $200 million price. This would keep
production of the plane going in Long Beach until 2007. Production
now would end in 2003 after the last of 120 planes have been
delivered to the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   By James Wallace. (Story will move in the ``f'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-SONICS (Denver) _ Seattle SuperSonics visit the Denver
Nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   By Ronald Tillery. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-THIEL-COLUMN (Seattle) _ On Mike Holmgren and the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-DUEL (Undated) _ Review of ``The Duel,'' the first of four
``Horatio Hornblower'' films produced by A&AMP;E Television Networks
and England's United Broadcasting &AMP; Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TOWNERS (Undated) _ The last time Steve Martin and Goldie
Hawn teamed up it was for the smart, genuinely witty and highly
original 1992 screwball comedy, ``Housesitter.'' This time, in the
remake of ``The Out-of-Towners,'' they've given us a farce that's
the polar opposite of that first outing. This follow-up teaming is
broad, crass and so colossally stupid it's often numbing.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-WALK-MOON (Undated) _ The thing that makes first-time
director Tony Goldwyn's ``A Walk On the Moon'' unique is that it's
the first high-profile movie in ages that dares to view the great
consciousness revolution of the '60s in a somewhat positive light.
It's far from totally successful, and it fails in its effort to be
an absorbing family-relationship drama. But it's well-acted by its
three stars, and its whole '60s subtext is believable and
seductive.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-RELAX (Undated) _ The independent film world seems intent
on producing only two types of stories: violent scam movies and the
kind of romantic sex comedies in which there is a perfect balance
of gay, straight and ethnic characters who hang out together.
``Relax ... It's Just Sex'' falls into the second category. It's a
gay '90s ``Big Chill'' clone that settles into the same category as
``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss'' and several other recent
light-hearted gay-themed friendship films.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-UNMADE-BEDS (Undated) _ British filmmaker Nicholas Barker
has made a fascinating, sad ``revisionist'' documentary in which
four people tell their real-life stories. But he's helped them
rewrite their stories to accommodate both the screen and
themselves. In short, he's directing them in screen versions of
their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
