<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2974 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-EDITORIAL02-CO     04-01 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-EDITORIAL02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The next step in Kosovo
 &HT;    (EDs: The following editorial is from Friday's Atlanta
Constitution.)
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ White House and NATO officials profess to be shocked
that Serb forces have reacted to the bombing campaign by increasing
the ferocity of ethnic cleansing in Kosovo. Every day now, Serb
troops are driving out tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians and
committing genocidal horrors that we won't fully appreciate until
the gun smoke clears and the mass graves are uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   That expression of surprise by the White House _ whether feigned
or real _ is frightening and ultimately discouraging. It betrays a
fundamental lack of leadership and foresight on the part of
President Clinton and his staff and bodes poorly for U.S. efforts
to resolve this tragedy quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration certainly had reason to hope that an
intense bombing campaign would force the Serbians to back down and
negotiate. But hope is one thing; certainty is another. Given Serb
brutality in Bosnia and Croatia and the symbolic importance of
Kosovo to Serbians' sense of nationhood, the current response by
the Serbs had to be considered at least a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   But there's the rub. As a policy-maker, once you accept the
possibility that the Serbs might greatly intensify their
ethnic-cleansing campaign, you have to plan a potential response.
And the only sure way to intervene in such a nightmare would be to
have ground troops ready to roll, a step that Clinton had ruled out
from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   So, having ruled out the only solution, it's almost as if
Clinton and his staff chose to rule out the problem as well. They
took a gamble by bombing, knowing that if it failed, the price
would be paid by Albanian peasants.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials defend the president by pointing out that
he faced an extremely difficult and complex situation. Had he done
nothing, he would have been heavily criticized for standing by and
allowing the ethnic cleansing to continue. He chose to bomb instead
and is now being criticized for that move. His third option _ the
use of U.S. troops _ would have been even more controversial.
</P>
<P>
   Although that's all true, sympathy for the White House goes only
so far. Bill Clinton wanted to be president _ in fact, he put the
nation through hell in his effort to keep the job. He wanted to
make tough decisions; now he has one. Mobilizing thousands of U.S.
troops for potential insertion into Kosovo would certainly have
cost him politically, and it would have required him to actually
lead. He would have had to change the minds of the American people
on something important. But that's why we have presidents.
</P>
<P>
   As part of that effort, Clinton could have promised that troops
would not be used unless they were absolutely necessary, in
response to just the sort of humanitarian emergency we now face. In
fact, the mobilization of hundreds of thousands of NATO troops for
potential use in Kosovo might have greatly altered the calculations
of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic as he contemplated his
course of action. Instead, guaranteed that his troops would face no
ground-based opposition, he chose to fight.
</P>
<P>
   So now what? The immediate goal is to end the slaughter of
Albanian civilians, and we don't have troops as an immediate option
or even threat to force that outcome. However, Clinton should
announce as soon as possible that U.S. troops are being mobilized
for use if necessary, and he should make that case to the American
people.
</P>
<P>
   Until those troops are ready, we are stuck trying to cobble
together a solution with bombing and diplomacy as our only tools.
The long-term goal of that effort must be creation of a structure
that sustains itself over time, that restores some sense of
stability to an inherently unstable region.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, trying to resettle ethnic Albanians within a
Serb-controlled Kosovo would certainly fail that test. Humpty
Dumpty cannot be put back together with air power alone. The only
solution attainable without troops that also meets the test of
sustainability would be a partition of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The sites most dear to Serbian hearts _ the ancient monasteries
and battlefields _ lie in northern Kosovo, the area closest to
Serbia itself. Ceding that half of the region to Serbia, while
reserving the southern section to ethnic Albanians, either as a
U.N. protectorate or a part of Albania proper, might be the best
approach.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic accepts such a compromise, U.S. and NATO troops
would still be required to keep the peace, at least initially. If
he does not _ if he is intent on continuing this mad campaign of
genocide against the helpless Albanians _ the option that Clinton
unwisely ruled impossible could instead become absolutely
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 1957EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
