<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     04-01 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOW NIXON THE COMEDY 
LIFE IN FAST FORWARD 
THINKING SMALL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Few episodes of American postwar history have been
treated with more solemnity than Watergate, particularly in
Hollywood. Americans have pondered, shuddered, railed at and
perhaps even wept over the break-in that brought down a presidency
and influenced a generation.
</P>
<P>
   So now, in the era of Monicagate, maybe it is time to laugh.
</P>
<P>
   That, anyway, is the intention behind ``Dick,'' a comedy that
might be dubbed Watergate Lite. Imagine a movie with Oliver Stone's
paranoid vision and the sensibility of ``Clueless,'' and you have
``Dick,'' which is scheduled for release on July 9.
</P>
<P>
   The movie follows the antics of two teen-agers, Betsy Jobs
(Kirsten Dunst) and Arlene Lorenzo (Michelle Williams), who visit
the White House of Richard (Dick) Nixon (played by Dan Hedaya, who
was in ``Clueless''). The two wander into a room filled with
presidential secrets, which prompts a frightened Nixon to hire them
as dog walkers so he can keep an eye on them.
</P>
<P>
   The two fumble their way through the Watergate mess as unwitting
but crucial players while the audience learns what really happened
to those 18 minutes of erased tape, the identity of Deep Throat and
what supposedly made Nixon so paranoid. The baby-boom generation
was torn by those questions; Generation X is now going to have a
good chuckle over them.
</P>
<P>
   The movie was produced by Gale Ann Hurd , who has produced 22
movies and is well known not for frothy comedies but for
high-adrenaline pictures like ``Armageddon,'' ``The Terminator,''
``Aliens'' and ``The Abyss.'' Ms. Hurd, 43, said she was proud of
her ability to raft white-water rivers and take on the toughest
mountains on her bike.
</P>
<P>
   She acknowledged that ``Dick'' was something of a switch and
said it grew less out of her political interests (``When I got to
college I decided I was going to be a Marxist,'' she said. ``My
first B was in Marxist economics, so I decided to become a
righteous capitalist.'') than a sense that it might just be time to
laugh at Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing really dark and twisted happens in this film,'' Ms.
Hurd said. ``I think, given where we are, it's the best possible
time to laugh at this. It's cathartic.''
</P>
<P>
   She added, ``After doing a lot of special-effects-driven movies,
it's really nice to think about character for a change.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurd said that ``Dick'' was aimed partly at a teen-age
audience, given that the engines of Nixon's misfortune are two
teen-agers, although teen-agers looked at Watergate almost as
ancient history.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't necessarily get the more obscure Watergate
references, like Gordon Liddy, but they loved the movie in our test
screenings,'' she said. ``It was nice to do this without that
cynical 90s patina.''
</P>
<P>
   Life in Fast Forward
</P>
<P>
   Making movies that connect with teen-agers has always required a
somewhat irreverent approach. Such films often drip with sarcasm,
and their characters tend to joust with authority.
</P>
<P>
   But for the current generation, the introduction of new
entertainment technologies like computer games has in some
instances even changed how stories are told.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Go,'' for example, a new comedy by Doug Liman scheduled to
be released on April 9, the plot repeatedly stops and rewinds, each
time with a new character in the lead, suggesting the branching
structure of an adventure computer game.
</P>
<P>
   There won't be any computer mice by the theater seats. But icons
will be on-screen in the form of the stop-motion faces of the
actors, on which the director clicks before unspooling their
delirious and often amusing tales.
</P>
<P>
   ``The structural part of it fits the mind of young people
today,'' said Liman (above), 32, whose first movie, ``Swingers,''
introduced audiences to a retro-hip milieu. ``This audience doesn't
like receiving information in the traditional ways.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie follows the nocturnal antics of a group of
20-somethings as they party, botch drug deals, duel with the police
and, in one memorable sequence, go wild in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   It takes place in the span of a night and a day, and ends with
the frayed threads coming together in a spirit of manic energy and
a near-total lack of restraint. The ensemble cast includes Sarah
Polley, Katie Holmes, Desmond Askew, Timothy Olyphant, Jay Mohr and
Scott Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   ``These characters do unlikable things, but you love them for
it,'' Liman said.
</P>
<P>
   The director said he had resisted the unusual narrative
structure when he started to read the script, which was written by
John August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like gimmicky things,'' Liman said. ``I was like, `Oh,
I was really liking this script until he started jumping around
with the narrative. Oh, well.' But I read more, and he got me over
the bump. By the third story line, he had earned my confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I don't read a magazine from front to back. I read
three books at once and might be watching TV and changing the
channels. That's the way we experience things.''
</P>
<P>
   Key to the characters' misadventures is that in the end, they
survive despite their self-destructive tendencies. Liman, who
recently earned his pilot's license, compared that to a new
four-seat airplane he had just bought, part of a new aircraft
generation that has a parachute built into the fuselage as an extra
safety feature.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 18 it's like you've got that parachute,'' Liman
said. ``You've got that `get out of jail free' card. That's what
the characters in the movie have. The name `Go' refers to that.
They react rather than think.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thinking Small
</P>
<P>
   This year's Oscar derby was more contentious than usual, full of
more blatant publicity gimmicks but less interesting to the public,
with the show's Nielsen ratings down sharply.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a lesson, it was that smaller production houses,
the so-called independents, are getting better at developing the
more engaging and successful movies, at least in terms of peer
recognition if not the box office.
</P>
<P>
   Though Miramax stole the show by winning the prizes for best
movie, best foreign-language film and much more, the ``other''
independent, Lions Gate, also did well. This relatively small
operation drew five nominations and prizes for two films that it
distributed last year, ``Affliction'' and ``Gods and Monsters.''
</P>
<P>
   This year Lions Gate is aiming for more of the same. While the
major studios are cranking out their big-budget special-effects
thrill rides for the summer, most notably the latest ``Star Wars''
movie, Lions Gate and other independents are counter-programming,
looking for fare that is more intimate, unusual and, though few
want to admit it, appealing to the people who vote on the prizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I never hear the word Oscar again, it will be too soon,''
said Mark Urman , the co-president of Lions Gate Releasing, the
distribution arm of the company. ``Everything we've ever released
is a sort of antidote to Hollywood. That's what we try to think
about. We're doing that again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Lions Gate is releasing ``Metroland,'' a bittersweet romantic
adventure in which two old friends from London (played by Lee Ross
and Christian Bale) escape their homes during the 1960s, only to
return years later and confront their middle-class origins and
dashed hopes. Emily Watson of ``Hilary and Jackie'' plays a
prominent part.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a sex farce, ``Friends and Lovers,'' and what
Urman described as a classic French romantic farce, ``The Dinner
Game,'' a throwback to the freewheeling French comedies of the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The company's biggest hope for the year is ``The Red Violin,'' a
costume drama with a relatively big budget, if $15 million can be
considered big when Hollywood studios spend on average nearly $50
million a movie.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has an international ensemble cast, including Samuel
L. Jackson, Carlo Cecchi, Greta Scacchi and Sylvia Chang. It is
directed by Francois Girard and has a score by John Corigliano.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Violin'' follows a famous violin over 300 years and
the events that unfold around it. From Lions Gate's perspective, it
presents a counterpoint to the big studio movies, which tend to be
heavy on action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Urman said, ``the more different you are, the
better off you are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
