<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2981 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MO-CONCEALED-WEAPONS-     04-01 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MO-CONCEALED-WEAPONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI TO HOLD REFERENDUM ON LETTING PEOPLE CARRY CONCEALED
WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DIRK JOHNSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ In what both sides of the gun debate are calling a
momentous showdown, Missouri will be the first state to let voters
decide in a statewide referendum next week whether to allow people
to carry concealed weapons in public.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the measure have outspent opponents by a ratio of
three-to-one, with the National Rifle Association spending almost
all of the money on the efforts to pass the measure, $2.1 million,
with a blizzard of television ads, including one featuring a victim
of the notorious ``South Side Rapist.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle has drawn high-profile advocates, including Charlton
Heston, the actor and president of the National Rifle Association,
and James Brady, the former press secretary who was wounded in the
assassination attempt against President Ronald Reagan. And it has
pitted law enforcement officials against each other, with some U.S.
attorneys opposing the measure and some local police departments
supporting it.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 states allow some people to carry concealed
weapons, but in many, permits are rarely issued, and only if
applicants demonstrate a need, such as carrying large amounts of
cash in their work.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri measure, which becomes law if passed by a majority
of the voters, falls somewhere in the middle. It would grant
permits to anyone over 21 who has not been convicted of felony and
who takes 12 hours of gun training. But it gives the sheriff in
each county the right to deny any application.
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, rural voters are expected to back the measure
strongly, while urban residents, especially blacks, are more
skeptical about it.
</P>
<P>
   In an edgy St. Louis neighborhood pierced by sirens and
pockmarked with boarded storefronts, Korey Davis, a 22-year-old
resident of the North Side neighborhood grimaced at the ballot
measure. To Ms. Davis, who is black and once was held up by ``an
itsy-bitsy boy with a great big gun,'' putting more guns on the
street would turn some urban neighborhoods ``back to the Wild Wild
West.''
</P>
<P>
   But across the state in rural Hickory County, Sherry Jones, a
43-year-old coffee shop waitress, welcomes the measure, which she
believes would simply let law-abiding people protect themselves.
Allowing law-abiding people to arm themselves in public would
simply level the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad guys already have guns, concealed or not,'' she said.
``Why should it be a crime for the rest of us to defend
ourselves?''
</P>
<P>
   With the vote scheduled at a time when little else is on the
ballot in Missouri, the outcome will hinge largely on turnout.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri Legislature has passed measures allowing concealed
weapons, but the bills have been vetoed by Gov. Mel Carnahan, a
Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Putting the issue to the people for a vote gives the Missouri
campaign an extra weight in the national debate over guns, both
sides agree.
</P>
<P>
   James J. Baker, the chief lobbyist for the NRA, said a victory
at the ballot box would show broad popular support for gun rights,
and could not be dismissed as ``somehow buying off a state
legislature,'' by a powerful lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   Officials for Handgun Control Inc., the group headed by Brady's
wife, Sarah, said meanwhile that the NRA is desperate to show
strength after a series of losses.
</P>
<P>
   They point to the the election of Charles Schumer, a Democrat
and an advocate of strict gun control, to the U.S. Senate from New
York, and the filing of lawsuits by New Orleans and several other
cities against gun makers. They also note that the NRA lost a
battle over requiring participants in gun shows in Florida to
undergo background checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA is putting a lot of eggs in this basket,'' said Joe
Sudbay, a spokesman for Handgun Control Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents of the concealed weapons measure have attacked the
bill as poorly written and full of loopholes. They note that the
bill would allow people to carry weapons into places where liquor
is sold, and to sports stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   Largely for that reason, Missouri's major professional sports
teams _ the St. Louis Cardinals and Rams and the Kansas City Chiefs
and Royals _ have issued statements against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   But Brett Feinstein, a spokesman for Missourians Against Crime,
a citizens group that is organizing the campaign for the concealed
weapons measure, framed the debate as ``a fundamental right to
self-protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have called in researchers to buttress their claims.
For the concealed weapons proponents, a University of Chicago
professor, John Lott, said that states that issue concealed weapons
permits have seen a bigger drop in crime in recent years than
states that do not. Lott, the author of ``More Guns, Less Crime''
(University of Chicago Press, 1998) said criminals prey on people
they think are defenseless.
</P>
<P>
   Giving people the right to carry arms, he says, changes the
thinking among some criminals. ``Some criminals are going to think
twice,'' Lott said, if they have to wonder whether a potential
victim is carrying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Glick, a researcher for the Violence Policy Center in
Washington, a research group that focuses on gun laws found that
many people issued such permits in Texas, a state with
comparatively loose gun laws, in recent years have run afoul of the
law.
</P>
<P>
   Some 15 people in Texas who were issued permits to carry
concealed weapons since 1996 have been charged with murder or
attempted murder, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some 31 states provide concealed weapons permits to persons who
meet certain objective standards, like age and background checks.
Another dozen states allow public officials to issue permits to
people who show a need for them, such as workers who carry large
amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   About half of the states that allow people to carry concealed
weapons require no gun training. The Missouri measure would forbid
guns to be taken to government buildings, schools, polling places
and churches. It does not forbid guns in taverns but gives bar
owners the right to prohibit them. Carrying a firearm while
intoxicated would remain a felony in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri bill would allow the issuance of permits to people
over 21 who have no felonies in their background and have taken a
minimum of 12 hours of gun safety courses from the state's
Department of Safety. Applicants would also have to submit
fingerprints for background checks by the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only law-abiding people are going to be willing to do this,''
said Feinstein. ``Who else would submit themselves to this?''
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of the measure say that the bill would not screen
out potentially violent people, since many offenses are pleaded
down to lesser charges.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen Fitzgerald, a spokeswoman for Safer Schools and Workplaces,
a citizens group that opposes the proposition, said putting more
guns on the streets ``increases the likelihood of temper tantrums
to become gun fights.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls conducted by Missouri newspapers have shown the measure
leading by a wide margin among likely voters, but many are
undecided. But opponents of the bill say they can win with a strong
turnout in urban areas, especially among black voters.
</P>
<P>
   They are counting on the votes of people like Troy Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, a 37-year-old mortgage banker who considers himself a
political conservative on most issues, says he will vote against
the concealed weapons proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a black man who is 6 foot 7, weighs 270 pounds and wears a
beard,'' Harris said. ``In a dark alley, I'm a suburban white
woman's worst nightmare _ at least I look that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris recounted an episode last year in which he chased a
mugger, finally lunging at the man and tackling him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, what if somebody with a gun had just turned the corner
and seen this big black guy chasing somebody down the street?'' he
said. ``I worry that they would have pulled the trigger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
