<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2982 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSINGSOLDIERS-TEX     04-01 0865
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSINGSOLDIERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURED TEXAN DESCRIBED IN HOME TOWN AS BRIGHT AND RESOURCEFUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN MORITZ 
and MICHELLE MELENDEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ The mother of a young Texan who dropped out
of college to join the Army said Thursday that he and two other
U.S. soldiers were just doing their duty when they were captured
along the Yugoslavia and Macedonia border.
</P>
<P>
   ``These soldiers _ Steven and the other two _ are not
criminals,'' Rosie Gonzales told a cluster of reporters huddled
into a pavilion near the Walls prison unit. ``They should not be
dealt with as criminals. They are innocent young men over there
doing their duty for their country.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Spec. Steven Gonzales in Huntsville and Palestine,
where he graduated from high school, hung yellow ribbons on doors,
fences and trees on Thursday to show their support for Gonzales;
Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; and Staff Sgt.
Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's state news agency reported that the three
servicemen will go on military trial today, a move President
Clinton condemned as a violation of international treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales' parents said their son will draw strength from his
Christian faith and his professionalism as a soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is very strong, very devoted to the Bible and to God,''
said his father, Gilbert Gonzales, a classification officer for the
Texas Department of Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned about the situation over there. We are
concerned about our son. It means a lot to us that he be returned
to us safely.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gonzales and his wife, Rosie, who also works for TDCJ,
described their son as a bright, strong-willed 21-year-old who
joined the Army over their objections for the adventure and
experience it promised. They shuddered at the thought that Steven,
who gave up an academic scholarship to Texas A&AMP;M, might be put on
trial in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The Gonzales couple, who have two other sons, Joshua, 8, and
Andrew, 13, were notified shortly before 8 p.m. Wednesday that
Steven was one of three U.S. peacekeepers in Macedonia being held
captive. They asked Americans to join them in Easter prayers for
the safe return of all three.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad, obviously,'' Rosie Gonzales said. ``But we know
that he is strong, stronger than us in a lot of ways. And that will
help him get through this.''
</P>
<P>
   From news photographs of the captured soldiers, Gilbert Gonzales
said it appeared that his son had been ``roughed up a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hibbard, Rosie Gonzales' supervisor in TDCJ's substance
abuse treatment division, described the couple as a ``bright ray of
sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are holding up much better than anyone could expect,''
Hibbard said. ``We are all ready to give them any support that they
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales' former teachers at Palestine High School, 90 miles
north of Huntsville, recalled him as a bright and dedicated student
who ranked 10th among 217 seniors in the 1995 graduating class.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was more mature than the rest of the class,'' said Tammy
Armstrong, Gonzales' freshman English teacher. ``With Steven, you
trusted him to make the right decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Starkey, who was Gonzales' senior advanced placement
English teacher, said, ``He was very clever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hope he would pull on that and some of his academic
skills now,'' Starkey said. ``I don't remember him being physically
powerful, but there are a lot of physically powerful guys I
wouldn't want to be in a fox hole with. Steven was wily enough to
use his brains and I hope he's doing that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Physics teacher Andy Jones recalled that Gonzales was diligent
about his high school work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of those kids where you look at your rolls, and if
he wasn't in your class, you go out and recruit him,'' Jones said.
``He was never a problem; not too quiet, not too loud _ a very
well-rounded kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's also the kind of kid the military needs,'' Jones added.
</P>
<P>
   Though many of Gonzales' classmates have left Palestine since
graduation, the current students and faculty observed a moment of
silence Thursday for the captive soldiers, and yellow ribbons
adorned the school's front doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hits you. It's home town _ somebody you really liked. And
now they are in dire straits,'' said chemistry teacher Kathleen
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales attended Texas A&AMP;M for a year, then quit to join the
Army.
</P>
<P>
   His parents said Thursday that he plans to return to A&AMP;M after
his military enlistment ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been so proud of Steven,'' said Rosie Gonzales,
who appeared to sob at times but spoke in a clear and steady voice.
``He always excelled at everything he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Gonzales said that his son was upbeat when they last
spoke about a month ago, just before the soldier's unit left for
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The parents avoided questions concerning the military operation
in Kosovo and its political implications, saying only that ``people
need to get back to the basics of loving each another.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
