<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2984 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-BOS &LR;      04-01 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEE FLOW OUT OF KOSOVO CONTINUES UNABATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORINA PASS, on the Albania-Yugoslavia border _ By day, armed
thugs and Serb police menaced the city of Pristina. By night, NATO
bombed the area around them. And by Thursday, the bedraggled
residents of the capital of Kosovo had been driven out completely,
forced by machine gun-toting soldiers to make the tortuous trek to
neighboring Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Carrying their crying babies, ethnic Albanian refugees from the
city walked in a 6-mile-long line over the mountainous border to
Albania Thursday, robbed of their belongings, and fearful that the
homes they left behind may already have been burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   As of midday, the refugee count in Albania neared 120,000, with
the flow unabated Thursday night. The forced marches add up to the
biggest ``ethnic cleansing'' episode in a decade of brutal Balkan
wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pristina is in a catastrophic condition,'' said Dukagjin
Humolli, clutching the tiny hand of his 5-year-old daughter. ``We
are so exhausted. My children have not eaten.''
</P>
<P>
   Serb police and army have been methodically clearing the ethnic
Albanian population out of Kosovo, a pattern seen repeatedly since
the 1992-95 Bosnia war when Serbs coined the term ``ethnic
cleansing.'' But the fall of Pristina marks a critical point in the
fight over the disputed province.
</P>
<P>
   The scene at the border Thursday was one of misery,
bewilderment, and shock. Women shivered in the cold mountain air as
they tried to breast-feed their infants. One family huddled over a
small fire. When an aid truck arrived to hand out bottles of water,
children and adults alike crushed up against the vehicle, desperate
to get a drink.
</P>
<P>
   Albania, Europe's poorest nation, has been overwhelmed by the
number of refugees and the speed of their arrival. The government
has been sending buses and trucks to the border to take Kosovar
Albanians over poorly-paved, barely navigable roads to refugee
centers or to the private homes of Albanian families.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of needy is unmanageable, aid workers say, and
the fact that the Pristina refugees arrived mainly on foot makes
the task even more difficult. The few trucks operated by the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees and private organizations
were lost in the massive crowd of hungry, homeless people. The
trucks were crammed, and on the ground mothers thrust their
screaming children upward, hoping to get them on the vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Some families appeared ready to bunk down in the mountain grass
for the night, waiting for a ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really difficult to handle. It's too much and it's not
very well organized,'' said Mathias Schreiber, a German missionary
and aid worker. ``We need blankets, we need mattresses, we need
diapers.''
</P>
<P>
   A year of fighting in Kosovo had barely touched the capital
until last month. But in the past few days, a number of refugees
said in interviews, Pristina has been a city under siege. On
Wednesday, the siege was broken by masked soldiers who robbed the
Kosovars, threatened to kill them, and bused them out of the city.
Because international observers have withdrawn and most journalists
expelled from the province, it is difficult to get independent
verification of the refugees' accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Several families said they were sitting in their apartments when
men in black masks and carrying machine guns kicked open or knocked
on their doors. The men told them to leave immediately. A few were
allowed to take their own cars, but only if they paid large sums of
money to the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Everybody out! Kosovo is not yours!' '' said Idriz
Abdullah, a 45-year-old economist.
</P>
<P>
   Residents were forced onto the street and made to kneel with
their hands up, said Nuje Ahmeti, 38. When Ahmeti asked why he had
to leave, Serb soldiers kicked him and beat him with the butt of a
gun, Ahmeti said, showing a wound on his face.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands people were herded together near the soccer
stadium in downtown Pristina, refugees said. Soldiers demanded
money, ripped gold necklaces from the throats of women, and hustled
people onto buses.
</P>
<P>
   Three women gave birth during the ordeal, Ahmeti said. ``I saw
it myself. Some people gave them first aid, but the Serbs didn't do
anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Pristina was burning when the refugees left, they said.
Most of the fires were coming from the area of Dragodan, one of the
wealthier neighborhoods and the area where international
organizations had been located.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of ``Arkan's Tigers'' _ the feared paramilitary
group accused of committing some of the worst atrocities of the
Croatian and Bosnian wars _ increased the fear, refugees said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Terror and ethnic cleansing is taking place in Pristina now,''
said Ahmeti. ``Pristina is almost empty of Albanians now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
