<HEADLINE>
HAPPY BIRTHDAY, ONCE AGAIN, TO HERB CAEN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday is the late columnist  &UR; Herb Caen &LR; 's birthday, an
occasion Personals will mark with a namephreak submitted months ago
by  &UR; Robin Sutherland &LR;  and saved for the occasion:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Canaan Banana &LR; , who was president of Zimbabwe in the '80s, has
been sentenced to 10 years in prison, nine of them suspended, after
dozens of men _ students, aides, soccer players and soldiers _
complained of having been sexually harassed by him. Banana was
found guilty of assault and sodomy.
</P>
<P>
   In more specific homage, reader  &UR; Donna Green &LR;  wrote: ``Have you
taken a look recently at Herb's memorial down by the waterfront?
... It seems to need a bit more than a bath in Vitamin V.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right. The photo of Herb etched on a plaque _ dated June
1996 and posted on the semicircle of concrete columns south of the
Ferry Building _ is badly faded, and the name ``Angela White,'' a
Social Security number and several other words are crudely
scratched into its surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``The San Franciscan is hopelessly sentimental,'' says the
Caenism on the plaque, ``and I am hopelessly San Franciscan.'' So
let's do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE MESSAGE IS THE MEDIUM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Hillaryno.com, a new Web site posted by the Friends of
 &UR; Rudolph Giuliani &LR;  fund-raising committee, describes the first lady
unflatteringly, mentioning her ``failed health care experiment''
and background: ``Born in Illinois and carried to power in
Arkansas, with no connection of any kind to New York, Hillary has
set her sights on the New York Senate seat and maybe ... probably
... set her sights even higher.''
</P>
<P>
   New York state Democratic chairwoman  &UR; Judith Hope &LR;  said the tone
of the site matched the direction of Giuliani's approval ratings:
``negative, negative, negative.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In Sonoma last week,  &UR; Harry Wyeth &LR;  saw a man in a vest marked
Good Vibrations on the front, and on the back: ``If You Want
Something Done Right, Do It Yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Noting those movie ads on the sides of buses, right next to
the Muni logo, that say, ``10 Things I Hate About You,'' &UR; Marc &LR; 
 &UR; Huestis  &LR; says he's sure other commuters could come up with many
more, among them &UR; Eric Umansky &LR; , who set up for business at Powell
Street and quickly sold out of T-shirts with a Muni logo that say,
``Better Never Than Late.'' More information on those shirts is at
ihatemuni &LR; yahoo.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MILLENNIUM RACE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 competitors have signed up to participate in a
``tough guy'' endurance test planned in England for the millennium,
reports the Times of London in a report gleaned by
 &UR; Paul Collins &LR; . Racers will carry wooden crosses to commemorate the
crucifixion of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Because ``we respect all our competitors,'' organizer  &UR; Billy &LR; 
 &UR; Wilson &LR;  told the newspaper that Jewish and Muslim competitors will
be allowed to carry trees instead of crosses.
</P>
<P>
   The race, to be held in Wolverhampton, is ``in the worst
possible taste,'' said the Rev.  &UR; Robert Ellis &LR;  of the nearby
Lichfield Diocese.
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Alice Kahn &LR;  sends word of a shopper who bought a box of
bran matzo emblazoned with the slogan, ``Let My People Go.''
Season's greetings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RUNNING DRY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   An electronic message whizzing through the Internet urges angry
drivers to refrain from buying gasoline on April 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time we did something about the price of gasoline in
America!'' says the message, which concludes with a plea to send
the message ``to everyone you know. Ask them to do the same. ... We
CAN make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLOTHES THAT GLOW WHERE YOU DO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Norma Kamali  &LR; is out with a new line of Mood Clothing that uses
the mood ring concept on fabric. The fabric used in the line's
first items _ jackets, blouses, pants, very tight skirts and
dresses _ looks shiny and black when cool.
</P>
<P>
   Body heat changes the colors over the surface of the garment,
especially in the areas touching thighs, bellies and crotches. The
press release calls it ``exciting''; subtle it is not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You could eat a whole box of (marshmallow) Peeps, and you
would still crave chocolate. You would be better off having a small
amount of chocolate. Bite the ear off that chocolate bunny, or have
one chocolate egg.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Advice for Easter from Marianne Carter of the University of
Delaware Wellness Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
