<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   US-KOSOVO (Washington) _ President Clinton, summoning the
``determination and resolve'' of the American people for an
escalating offensive in the Balkans, declares that Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic will be held responsible for the fate
of three captured American soldiers. By STEWART M. POWELL And ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Washington) _ Yugoslav television shows three
bruised U.S. Army soldiers who were snatched along the
Yugoslavia-Macedonia border. The soldiers are from California,
Michigan and Texas. NATO says their capture will not stem air raids
that are moving closer to political power center in Belgrade. By
CRAGG HINES.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-LEGAL (Washington) _ We look at the legal status of the
captured American soldiers and what the military and international
law experts expect. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SAFETY-GRANTS (Washington) _ The Clinton administration
announces that grants totaling more than $300 million will be
awarded to 50 towns and cities to help them provide safer schools
and better learning environments for students. By MARK HELM.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-GONZALES (Huntsville, Texas) _ U.S. Army Spec. Steven M.
Gonzales was a popular straight-A student with an interest in
science at Palestine High School, from which he graduated in 1995.
He is now one of three Americans being held captive by Yugoslav
forces. By ALLAN TURNER and KATHY WALT. (Photo will be available on
NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN-SOLDIER (Capac, Mich.) _ Yellow ribbons and U.S. flags
go in the tiny Michigan community where Army Staff Sgt. Christopher
J. Stone, one of three U.S. soldiers captured by Yugoslav forces,
grew up. Stone, 25, appeared on television in Yugoslavia, his face
battered and bruised. By the Huron Daily Tribune. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Norfolk, Va.) _ Urging patience and
determination in the Yugoslav conflict, President Clinton
passionately defends NATO's military campaign before a crowd at the
Norfolk Naval Base. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-SIESTA (Undated) _ A centuries-old tradition disappears
as the Mexican government bans two-hour lunch breaks for federal
employees. Some say it will be good for the economy, cutting
electricity bills and increasing the number of hours that people in
the United States and Mexico can do business. By JENA MORENO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The Kosovo war may be the undoing of
Vice President Al Gore, who is stuck with the administration's
policy, and the making of potential GOP presidential candidate John
McCain, who is free to be a tough-minded hawk without being held
responsible for mistakes along the way. By MARIANNE MEANS.
(1stld-writethru filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Salt Lake City) _ The Houston Rockets put their
nine-game winning streak on the line tonight as they play the Utah
Jazz for the first time this season. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   With: BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN and BKN-ROCKSIDE
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ As the Houston Astros prepare to
break spring training and return to Texas, we take a look back at
the highs and lows, ups and downs of this ``Camp Dis-Astro.'' By
CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID-CUTOFF (Washington) _ Despite a painful, crippling
disease, Eva Amey of Elmira, N.Y. got herself off welfare more than
a year ago and is working as a teacher's aide. But she earns only
$5,756 a year and, because she is now employed, has lost her
Medicaid benefits. With medical bills averaging more than $500 a
month, she often finds she can't afford to see the doctor or buy
medicine. Health care advocates say there are tens of thousands
cases like Amey's. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
