<HEADLINE>
FENWAY TICKET AMONG THE COSTLIEST, MAGAZINE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Baseball lovers say Fenway Park is one of the best
places to watch a Major League game. But love can be expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox tickets are the most expensive of the 30 franchises in
Major League Baseball this year, and watching a game at Fenway is
second only to Yankee Stadium in expenses for a family of four,
according to a study released Thursday by a nationally recognized
trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   The average Sox ticket costs $24.05, 72 cents more expensive
than the average Yankees ticket, according to the Chicago-bsed Team
Marketing Report. That is a 16.6 percent increase over last year
for the Red Sox, compared to an average increase of 9.7 percent
among all of the teams.
</P>
<P>
   A family of four purchasing tickets, parking, four small soft
drinks, two small beers, four hot dogs, two game programs, and two
adult-sized caps will spend $160.21 at Fenway Park _ $6.63 less
than at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Boston, a lot of it is really the park itself,'' said Sean
Brenner, editor of Team Marketing Report. ``Winning baseball today
is an expensive proposition, and for the Sox to compete _ as they
usually do _ with such a small park, gets pretty expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The revenue streams produced by these stadiums are used mostly
to pay for the most expensive aspect of playing major league
baseball _ the players' salaries,'' Brenner said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey reveals two other important factors in the current
economics of baseball: A new ballpark does not necessarily make
attending games comparatively cheaper, and watching a winning team
is usually a more expensive proposition than watching a loser.
</P>
<P>
   Of the top 10 most expensive stadiums for a family of four, five
are recently new: Atlanta, Baltimore, Cleveland, Colorado, and
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And six of the winningest teams in baseball over the past five
years play in stadiums that are among the 10 most expensive:
Atlanta, Baltimore, Boston, Cleveland, the Yankees, and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fits right into the Red Sox argument for a new ballpark,''
said Larry Moulter, president of Woolf Associates. ``If you want a
winner, you've got to be able to pay for the good players.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it also shows that the fans never win out,'' Moulter said.
``As you build the new facilities, you have new opportunities for
revenue streams. But you're setting prices to increase your
prospective performance, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox management had some complaints about the survey,
saying that it does not take into account that they do not charge a
handling fee for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   While Brenner generally agreed with that, he said that because
there is no way of knowing what percentage of tickets at any
stadium is sold with a handling charge, the survey is conducted on
the basis of ticket prices at the box offices.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, adding $2.75 cents to all of the other prices would
still hold the Red Sox as the second most expensive ticket in the
game, right behind the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we present a very attractive product,'' said Larry
Cancro, the Red Sox' vice president of sales and marketing. ``Since
1976 and the advent of free agency _ and that's the single greatest
factor, far-and-away, in terms of driving up these prices _ we have
the second best record in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moreover, if you take those numbers in the study and look at
them in the proper way, what you see is a very good argument for a
new stadium,'' Cancro said. ``If you take the highest-priced
tickets and realize that a team like the Yankees has many more
tickets to sell at that price level, and if you consider that the
other teams have many more seats of all kinds to sell, what you
realize is that this stadium has given us all that it can. And if
we're going to continue to present a good product, and we will, we
need a new way to draw new revenues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
