<HEADLINE>
BOSTON LOSES OUT IN BID FOR WOMEN'S FINAL FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Boston's bid to host the 2004 NCAA Women's Final Four
in basketball has been rejected by the National Collegiate Athletic
Association, in part for geographical reasons, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Final Four will be played in Philadelphia next year
and the NCAA tries to move its championships through different
regions around the country, eliminating Boston, officials
responsible for the bid said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really nothing personal,'' said Jack Grinold, the sports
information director at Northeastern University, one of four local
institutions and groups involved in the unsuccessful bid. ``I know
you, and I, and most people do not consider Philadelphia to be the
Northeast, but the NCAA does. And it's their decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA announced Thursday that Atlanta, Detroit, New Orleans,
Charlotte and Memphis are the finalists for both the 2003 and 2004
Women's Final Four. The women's tournament is an increasingly
popular event in college athletics, both in terms of attendance and
television ratings, with players like Chamique Holdsclaw of
Tennessee garnering a share of the national sports spotlight along
with the men's players, every March.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's site-selection committee will visit the final cities
during April and May, and invite a narrowed list of them to make
another presentation, before the bids are awarded.
</P>
<P>
   NCAA officials said that an additional factor weighing against
Boston in their consideration was the high price of hotel rooms,
and the fact that the bids from other cities contained more
financial information.
</P>
<P>
   ``High prices is one thing, but $350 a night is something
else,'' said Tricia Burke, vice-president of championships for the
NCAA. ``We probably could have negotiated that, all other things
being equal, but we also were looking for some better financial
background on the actual host committee in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just a matter of being more familiar with the
NCAA process,'' Burke said. ``Some of the other cities were able to
provide that information, and I think it helped them.''
</P>
<P>
   Northeastern, Harvard University, the Fleet Center and the
Boston Visitors &AMP; Convention Bureau organized Boston's bid.
Officials had expressed confidence that the city would receive it,
especially given what was considered a strong effort in hosting two
early rounds of the NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship
last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only other sports bid recently that was not successful was
for the US Figure Skating Championships in 1998,'' said Pat
Moscaritolo, president of the convention bureau. ``So, 8-for-10,
those are Hall of Fame numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned right around and resubmitted that bid, and we got
the US Figure Skating Championships in 2001,'' Moscaritolo said.
``I think you are going to see us turn right around and do
something similar, here. We're interested to see if those same open
dates, now, at the Fleet Center line up for the Frozen Four _ the
men's hockey finals.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
