A2999 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ESCORTS02-COX-COX     04-01 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCORTS02-COX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dying tradition? Charlotte may end funeral escorts
 &HT;    By Lyn Riddle
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ As hundreds of cars lined up for the short
drive to bury Kenneth Swayney, his widow, Theresa, looked back from
the family car and smiled ruefully. So many cared, she thought,
feeling comforted.
</P>
<P>
   That memory compelled the usually reserved Swayney into a City
Council committee meeting here last week to fight for a dying
Southern tradition: police escorts that enable mourners to form a
procession from a funeral home or church to the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte-Mecklenburg Police want to stop the generations-old
courtesy of providing funeral escorts, saying the liability in the
event of an accident is too great. City after city has done the
same _ Atlanta, Jacksonville and Orlando, Fla., and Columbia, S.C.,
among them.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, off-duty officers provide the service for a fee of
more than $100. Birmingham and Nashville, Tenn., provide escorts
only for funerals of police officers and public officials. While
providing official escorts for pretty much any family that asks,
the city began charging a token $20 fee in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic congestion has spurred the larger Southern cities to get
out of the funeral escort business. But in Charlotte, which has
seen more development than many Southern cities, council members
say they want to find a way to hold fast to tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It speaks volumes about a people for them to stop and pay
tribute to someone's passing,'' said City Councilman Don Reid, who
chairs the committee studying the situation. ``If we can't stop for
three minutes, then we've reached a point where we need to look at
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   A bill pending in the North Carolina Legislature would require
motorists to stop for funeral processions but does not remove
liability from cities or police departments. Reid said Charlotte
needs to work with legislators to get that included.
</P>
<P>
   In many Southern towns, it has long been a simple matter of
courtesy for police to escort funeral processions, stopping traffic
at lights so the cortege could pass while other motorists pull to
the side, paying respects to a family in mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Said Swayney, 39: ``I will never ever have anything worse happen
to me than my husband's funeral, and anything that can give a
family comfort should be done. They deserve that respect. It is a
small price to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Swayney's husband was 36 when he died after a car ran into his
motorcycle on a downtown Charlotte street about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as newcomers unaccustomed to local traditions come in
and traffic mushrooms, it is not unusual to see motorists cutting
off funeral processions or even becoming so angry they raise a
finger in vulgar salute.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster their argument, Charlotte police say that despite
years of practice, they lack the legal authority to allow hearses
and other funeral cars to run red lights. Only emergency vehicles
have that right under North Carolina law.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they say, courts in North Carolina and other states
have found cities, and even individual police officers, financially
liable in accidents.
</P>
<P>
   They say traffic here has more than doubled in the past 10 years
and all funeral processions occur during the day, the peak travel
time. And using officers as escorts takes them away from other
duties.
</P>
<P>
   Police records show they work 2,100 funerals a year, and each
one takes about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel compelled to make sure the public understands that
it's not a matter of if, but when, that enormous lawsuit comes
down,'' Deputy Police Chief Bob Shur told the committee.
</P>
<P>
   But police could not provide any documentation of how many
accidents have occurred in Charlotte as a result of funeral
processions. One officer told The Charlotte Observer he had
witnessed 10 to 15 in a 28-year career.
</P>
<P>
   Police want funeral homes to provide maps to mourners and allow
them to get to the cemetery on their own, as best they can.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Police Department just doesn't want to provide
escorts anymore,'' said Swayney, who speculated that more accidents
would occur as mourners hurry to a cemetery that they may not know
how to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're distraught that's not the time to be trying to
read a map,'' she said. ``It shouldn't be stressful.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid said he thinks the city will find a way to continue the
practice. Some cities have used off-duty officers for processions,
which stop for red lights. Others, like Louisville, Ky., use
three-wheeled vehicles operated by civilians as escorts. Houston
lets off-duty officers use their own motorcycles for processions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not as easy to solve as I thought it would be,'' said
Reid. ``Most people who responded to our survey want to keep this,
but it's a safety issue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
