<SLUG> BC-VIDALIA-ILLEGALWORKERS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vidalia growers vow to shun illegal workers
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Vidalia onion growers, looking forward to an
above-average crop, are going to be as sweet as their famed onions
this spring to avoid the immigration problems that soured last
year's harvest, says the manager of the Vidalia Onion Business
Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growers want to do what's right,'' said Bob Stafford, a
retired agriculture inspector who manages the newly formed council.
``They know they need to cooperate because they definitely don't
want to go through what they went through last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vidalia harvest begins in mid-April and continues for six to
eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, part of the $90 million Vidalia crop died in the dirt
after agents of the Immigration and Naturalization Service swooped
into South Georgia onion fields during the peak of the harvest to
round up workers suspected of being in this country illegally.
Hundreds, perhaps thousands, of workers fled.
</P>
<P>
   When the growers agreed to obey laws, the INS allowed the
harvest to proceed. But some of the crop was lost.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Alexander, INS deputy director in Atlanta, said the agency,
in cooperation with county extension offices and the U.S.
Department of Labor, has staged workshops in onion country during
the past few months to educate growers on immigration laws.
</P>
<P>
   Some larger growers also are participating in a much-reviled
federal program called H-2A, designed to make temporary foreign
labor available in the United States when domestic labor is
inadequate, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vidalia growers have long complained they cannot find the 4,000
to 5,000 workers necessary to harvest the 15,000-acre onion crop.
But they say the H-2A program, which requires growers to provide
decent housing and worker compensation benefits, is too expensive
and cumbersome.
</P>
<P>
   Stafford said many council members will do their own hiring this
year to avoid using labor contractors who have provided them with
illegal help. They also will open their books to the INS so agents
can cross-check workers' immigration documents, he said. The
council was organized by growers who hope to stabilize onion prices
and provide a top-quality product, Stafford said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the INS announced plans this week to deploy
additional agents in quick response teams to Georgia and 10 other
states with growing illegal immigration problems. The Georgia
teams, to be based in Atlanta, Dalton, Albany and Savannah by Sept.
30, will include INS special agents, detention officers and
deportation officers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
