<HEADLINE>
N.H. FAILS ONCE AGAIN TO LEGISLATE A REVENUE BILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ New Hampshire's Senate, desperate to solve the
state's school funding crisis, has passed an $825 million revenue
bill that includes legalizing video slot machine gambling at the
state's race tracks and grand hotels.
</P>
<P>
   Forewarned that passage was imminent, the 400-member House
adjourned briefly for dinner Thursday and then returned to
summarily kill the bill by, 300-14, thus keeping its anti-gambling
track record intact.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire now enters the Easter weekend in violation of a
state Supreme Court order, with no legal source of funding schools
past June, with bond rating agencies breathing down its neck and
with no proposal having anything close to majority support in
either body.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's an end game, no one knows what it is,'' said one
lobbyist who has worked for year to find a solution to the
connundrum facing residents of the only state never to have enacted
a broad base sales or income tax.
</P>
<P>
   After a day in which one fragile accord after another formed
only to swiftly burst, the Senate reluctantly embraced gambling as
a component in an amended version of a plan first offered by Gov.
Jeanne Shaheen.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to $200 million in new gambling money, that plan
called for increased business taxes and the imposition of the
state's first entertainment tax, an 8 percent surcharge on tickets
to ski areas, movies, concerts and other amusements. In speeches
before the vote, the bill's Senate supporters acknowledged their
offered compromise was doomed in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection of video gambling marked the third option to be
foreclosed on during New Hampshire's 15-month struggle to find a
replacement for a school funding system that relies on
wildly-varying, and thus unconstitutional, local property tax rates
to pay for public education. Still alive, although without much
enthusiastic support, are proposals for statewide property tax, a
sales tax and a consumption tax that would hit both services and
the sale of goods.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier vote Thursday, the House killed a
conservative-backed bill that would have preserved the existing tax
system by declaring the state Supreme Court's rulings in the
so-called Claremont lawsuits to be ``an unconstitutional violation
of the separation of powers.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month the Republican-controlled House passed the
first income tax in the frugal state's history. An amended version
subsequently won approval in the Senate, but with Gov. Shaheen
adamant in her threat to veto any income tax bill, it died upon
return to the House this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
