<SLUG> BC-GALOTTO-RECORD02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big Game tickets flying out of stores
 &HT;    By Bill Steiden
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A giant jackpot means giant sales.
</P>
<P>
   Today's 11 p.m. drawing will be the largest in the history of
the Big Game, with a six-state jackpot of $160 million for a single
winner, up from the $103 million at stake in the last drawing on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets were selling at a clip of 5,594 a minute between 3 p.m.
and 4 p.m. Thursday, more than four times the 1,327-a-minute pace
for the same period last week, said Parquita Nassau, a Georgia
Lottery spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The previous Big Game record was $77 million in 1997. If the
jackpot rolls over again _ as it has since Feb. 2, leading up to
tonight's drawing _ the jackpot will almost certainly approach $200
million.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the quest for the record prize will become a
part of the growing trove of Georgia lottery lore. Some highlights
of the Georgia Lottery's nearly six years include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Biggest single payout: $21.9 million in a lump sum to Big Game
winner Jim Sheets, 42, of Harrison, Tenn., in February. Sheets,
whose winning sequence included a Big Ball number of 13, promptly
handed over his suburban Chattanooga bait shop business to his son
and began working on his golf game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most controversial winner: Kenny Dukes of Darien, who waited 2
1/2 months to claim his September 1998 record Lotto prize of $31
million. It turned out that Dukes had served multiple prison terms
and had faced charges over the years that included assault, robbery
and fraud. He remains on probation through 2001 for burglarizing
his mother's trailer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most satisfied winner: It's hard to judge this category, but a
top contender would certainly be Pamela Reynolds of Norcross, who
won $11.6 million in early 1997. She promptly sent a photocopy of
her winning ticket to the man from whom she had been divorced a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   _ Luckiest winner: It's also hard to say which Georgia Lottery
winner was most fortunate, but Randell Johnson of Norcross (notice
a pattern here?) has a strong claim on the title. Asked why he had
waited until May 1995 to collect on his $87,000 Fantasy 5 win, he
said it was because he wanted to cool down and avoid a wild
spending spree like the one he went on when he won $131,000 in the
Illinois Lottery in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most modest winner: Mary Marshall of Cleveland, Tenn., who won
$8.5 million in 1995. Though she quit her minimum-wage factory job
and built a cozy three-bedroom house for herself and her husband,
she continued to shop at Dollar General and dine at buffet-style
restaurants. ``I just don't see spending any more money than you
have to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Most surprising lottery fact: A 1998 Atlanta
Journal-Constitution/Georgia State University poll found that more
than half of Georgians said they never play the games. At least,
that's what they told us.
</P>
<P>
   _ Worst chance of winning: Any ticket for tonight's drawing.
Along with the record jackpot go astronomical odds: 76 million to
1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
