<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINNING02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hit the jackpot? Don't tell anyone but your shrink
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just shut up. Don't tell a soul, even family members.
Don't cuss out the boss, quit your job, buy that Jaguar convertible
you've long been coveting or hold a news conference to crow and try
not to even smile if you win that $160 million Big Game jackpot
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   But do _ please do _ call a shrink.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a checklist of things to do if the big prize comes in:
</P>
<P>
   _ Take your winnings upfront, even though that'll lessen the
prize to a measly $90 million or so, advise Bill Merritt and Lex
Watson, Atlanta estate planners. Taking the prize in a lump sum
gives you more leeway in investing it and setting up untouchable
trusts for family members and charities. Then you can tell people
it's out of your hands, and you won't be lying.
</P>
<P>
   _ But don't collect right away. If you don't already have a safe
deposit box, get one, then slip the winning ticket inside. You've
got 180 days to claim your prize, and that'll give you plenty of
time to protect yourself from predators by retaining reputable
financial professionals, says Ann Salo, an Atlanta estate planner
who's had two lottery winners as clients.
</P>
<P>
   _ Unless you're in a stable relationship, Salo advises, don't
even tell your spouse for a while, because some secrets are almost
impossible to keep.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get an unlisted phone number, and move to another house,
Merritt says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't tell your boss to shove it, Salo says. Or go on a
spending spree. Or do anything unusual. You don't want to offer any
clues that you've hit it big.
</P>
<P>
   _ Quietly retain a financial planner who charges by the hour,
not one who'll charge commissions, Salo says. The planner will help
you assemble a team of experts to help you minimize the tax bite,
and keep relatives and friends off your back.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't put your money into a bank account, which is insured
only up to $100,000, she says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Get psychological advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, whoever wins will feel isolated and alone,'' says Dr.
Rick Winer, a suburban Atlanta psychiatrist. ``For people with an
outgoing personality, you might tend to withdraw into a shell
because you're afraid of what everybody else wants from you.''
</P>
<P>
   And you'll be right, Salo says. ``You'll have cousins saying, `I
need $5,000 to get out of a jam,' and they'll resent it, or you
think they will, if you don't put forth.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Patricia Wheeler, a local clinical psychologist, says such a
windfall won't just suck in freeloaders, bloodthirsty relatives,
friends, stockbrokers and bankers, ``but it'll create a vacuum in
your life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll have to look at all the things you've said you'd do if
only you had the resources,'' she says. ``Now your excuses are
gone. This causes instant anxiety and stress, and stress can
kill.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Once your head's on straight, learn to say ``no,'' Salo says.
``All of a sudden, you're going to be the most popular person in
the world. Remember, relatives aren't going to like you anyway
because you've hit it big, and it's better to be disliked than
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
