<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPTIVES-IMPACT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURE OF SOLDIERS BRINGS HOME TO AMERICANS DANGER OF WAR IN
DISTANT LAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The capture of three U.S. soldiers in the Balkans
suddenly brought home to many Americans on Thursday the cost and
dangers of war in a distant land.
</P>
<P>
   With the public ambivalent and Congress uneasy about NATO
airstrikes against Yugoslavia, President Clinton sought Thursday to
reassure Americans about the nation's commitment to the three
soldiers, including Spec. Steven Gonzalez of Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Farer, dean of the graduate school of international studies
at the University of Denver, said TV images of the battered Army
enlisted men ``demonizes'' the conflict for Americans who are
trying to form opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does having three of our men seized undermine public
opinion?'' Farer asked rhetorically. ``I think it will harden it.
But it's hard to predict.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Turner, D-Crockett, whose 2nd Congressional District
includes Gonzalez' hometown of Huntsville, said he has been working
with the Pentagon to get information to the serviceman's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it really strengthens our resolve,'' Turner said of
the soldiers' capture, speaking in a telephone interview. ``It's
important for us to exhibit our resolve and wait for the airstrikes
to take their toll. I think Americans rally around the troops.''
</P>
<P>
   But another Texas lawmaker took an opposing view. Rep. Ron Paul,
R-Surfside, an outspoken critic of the war effort, said Thursday:
``I would hope this would wake up the American people not just in
terms of money but in terms of lives. I would think public opinion
would be against this policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The offices of both Texas senators, Republicans Phil Gramm and
Kay Bailey Hutchison, reported that calls and e-mails are
overwhelmingly against further U.S. involvement in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from Gramm reiterated his opposition to the U.S.
presence, but added: ``The three soldiers who were captured had no
role in the operation against Yugoslavia. They should be released
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   A previous case of Americans held captive overseas _ 52
Americans seized by Iranian militants at the U.S. Embassy in Tehran
in 1979 _ affected all aspects of U.S. policy and ultimately the
1980 presidential election. Republican nominee Ronald Reagan
depicted President Carter as weak and ineffectual, and Reagan won
the election.
</P>
<P>
   L. Bruce Laingen, the highest-ranking foreign service officer
held in Iran, said Thursday of the captive soldiers: ``They'll be
all right physically. It'll be uncomfortable psychologically.''
</P>
<P>
   As for broader impact, Laingen said that the episode is ``a
small incident'' that is very different from the hostage crisis in
Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Laingen, president of the American Academy of Diplomacy, said
his heart goes out to the young servicemen, but ``I do not think it
should affect policy in any way except to deepen anger'' at
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
