<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0300 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAPTURED-GONZALES-COX     04-01 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPTURED-GONZALES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friends of POW pray for the best
 &HT;    By Mike Kelley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ When Terri Sumrall saw the television image Thursday of
the boy she dated in high school, it looked like a totally
different person. Steven Gonzales is so much taller now. And he
looked so serious. She'd never seen him look serious before.
</P>
<P>
   He'd never been in such a serious situation. U.S. Spc. Gonzales,
just days from his 22nd birthday, was one of three U.S. Army
soldiers taken prisoner by Yugoslav forces as they patrolled along
the border between Macedonia and Kosovo. They are to face criminal
proceedings today in a Yugoslav military court.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, friends universally described the former Texas A&AMP;M
University student as highly intelligent, devout in his Christian
faith, and having an exuberant sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales was graduated from high school in 1995 in the East
Texas town of Palestine. It was there that Sumrall, now a senior at
the University of Texas at Austin, knew him. ``He's just a real
sweet guy,'' she said. ``I had all my honors classes with him. He
liked to joke around and be silly. He's a jokester. He's real
smart, and such a good Christian. He was always asking people to go
to church with him. He never has done anything mean to anyone. I
can honestly say that he has no enemies. I keep imagining what he's
going through and how terrified he must be. He was always there for
me. The worst thing about it is that I can't do anything about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Gonzales was in the top 10 percent of his high school
graduating class. He won letters in both soccer and track. He won a
scholarship from A&AMP;M to attend school there. But he quit school
after a year to join the Army. His high school biology teacher, Kay
Stroud, said she believed that the scholarship wasn't enough to pay
all the young man's expenses and that he enlisted to earn money to
go back to school.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Glen Castlebury, a spokesman for the Texas
Department of Criminal Justice, where both of Gonzales' parents
work, Steven's father Gilberto Gonzales said his son planned to
return to A&AMP;M under a military program in which he would get a
bachelor's degree and a commission and go back on active duty as an
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Stroud said her former student ``is very level-headed. As
far as the situation he is in, I believe he is going to be able to
take care of himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter Tracy Stroud, a high school classmate of Gonzales'
who works for a property management firm in Austin, agreed. ``He's
the kind of person that no matter what comes up, he'll be able to
handle it. He's very smart, a very rational person. And just
watching the tapes they're showing, he seems calm to me. That's
just how he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Williams, another classmate who's now a student at Texas
A&AMP;M-Galveston, said ``The picture I'm thinking of is how he used to
wiggle his ears. He had big ears and we'd all tease him about them
and he'd wiggle them and make us laugh. That's how I knew it was
him when I saw the pictures on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating because I can't do anything. We have a
prayer network going. We're all saying our prayers and wishing he
could be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven's parents met reporters Thursday afternoon in Huntsville.
They talked with their son before he enlisted about the dangers a
soldier might face, his father said. ``He made the decision himself
to join. He thought it would be beneficial for him . . . He's very
strong . . . very devoted to God,'' Gilberto Gonzales said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven and the other two soldiers don't deserve this,'' said
his mother Rosie Gonzales. ``They're young men with their whole
lives ahead of them. They were put in a bad situation and we just
pray . . . for their safe return, all three of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the criminal proceedings, she said, ``These soldiers
are not criminals and they should not be dealt with as such.
They're innocent young men who were over there as part of their
duty to their country. ``
</P>
<P>
   Steven Gonzales is based in Germany and had volunteered to be
part of the peace-keeping mission in Macedonia. He had been there
for about a month. Castlebury, the TDCJ spokesman, said that
Gilberto Gonzales said his son was to end that temporary duty and
return to Germany ``yesterday, today, any day now.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, the family of another captured soldier spoke with
reporters. Tricia Stone and 4-year-old Ryan Stone, the wife and
child of Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek,
Mich., are living in San Antonio with her relatives. At a news
conference with her mother, Lisa McKinney, Tricia Stone answered no
questions. Her mother read a statement expressing gratitude to
those who have offered support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very proud of Chris and all the soldiers serving our
nation,'' the statement read. ``As a family, we are doing all
right. We are doing our very best to help Tricia and Ryan through
their ordeal until Christopher is returned safely to us . . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
