<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NM-TORTURE-ART-$ADV04     04-01 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NM-TORTURE-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEW DETAILS IN BIZARRE TORTURE TRAILER CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Ariz., Texas)   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELEPHANT BUTTE, N.M. _ In the 10 days since a young woman ran
terrified and naked down a gravel street here and told a harrowing
tale of rape, torture and escape, the authorities have repeatedly
hinted at even worse horrors inside the double-wide trailer home at
513 Bass Road. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the 45 federal agents and 30 state police officers who
spent much of Wednesday and Thursday searching the property with
shovels and metal detectors have found no bodies, the specter of
serial murder continues to hang over the trailer like one of the
red dust clouds kicked up by the strong winds of springtime in New
Mexico. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators said they were ``looking into anything and
everything,'' including the possibility of homicides. They are
tracking down leads in Arizona, Texas and Mexico. And New Mexico
Public Safety Director Darren White said what he had seen inside
513 had ``literally made my stomach turn.'' He added, ``This is
very disturbing stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   But so far the authorities have provided few details to explain
the stomach turning and the digging, an information vacuum that has
been quickly filled by mystery and myth. ``We're doing a lot of
rumor control,'' admitted FBI Special Agent Doug Beldon, who is
overseeing much of the inquiry. ``But we simply can't do anything
to screw up future cases.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday, Beldon said the search at the
trailer home, which has included a cadaver-sniffing dog, would
probably be finished by Friday. He said he was optimistic that
investigators were closer to knowing ``whether we have a
homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of details in the case has frustrated some here in
Elephant Butte and in the nearby city of Truth or Consequences,
known in the area as T or C. ``Why aren't they telling us
everything?'' asked Brenda McCormick, a 39-year-old medical
technician who was having breakfast Thursday in a cafe in T or C.
``That's the scary part.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Landon, 70, a retired medical secretary who lives in
Elephant Butte, said she did not need to know all the details.
``We'll probably learn a lot more than we want to know,'' she
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What is known about the bizarre case is that on March 22, a
59-year-old state parks employee, David Parker Ray, and his live-in
girlfriend, Cynthia Lea Hendy, 39, were arrested and charged with,
among other crimes, kidnapping a young woman in Albuquerque and
driving her 150 miles south to Elephant Butte, a tiny town on the
edge of the sparkling Elephant Butte Lake, a popular recreation
area. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the criminal complaint filed against them in Sierra
County District Court, the couple then raped and tortured the woman
at gunpoint for three days until she escaped, a chain and padlock
still dangling from her neck as she ran down the street for help. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few days after that escape, a second woman came forward and
said she too had been taken captive the month before when she went
to the trailer to borrow some cake mix. ``Inside the trailer, on
the walls,'' court papers said, ``were numerous restraint devices
and medical tools.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The court papers said police had verified that the second woman
had reported in February that she had been attacked, soon after it
was said to have occurred. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Why the authorities did not act then and possibly prevent the
second attack is unclear. New Mexico State Police Lt. Randy Bertram
said, ``We are investigating what happened, but I can't say
anything else.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Ray and Ms. Hendy said their clients would enter not
guilty pleas. The couple are being held on $1 million bond each.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Ms. Hendy told an Albuquerque television station
that during a night of drinking Ms. Hendy said that Ray had killed
four to six women and had either buried their bodies in the desert
or dumped them into the middle of Elephant Butte Lake, which is 18
miles long and 300 feet deep in some areas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are two boats on Ray's one-acre property, which overlooks
the water. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beldon of the FBI said that the man had also told the
authorities the same story and that it was being investigated, but
so far there are no immediate plans to drag the lake. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hendy, according to court documents, has an admitted problem
with the truth. In 1998, after charging a boyfriend with domestic
violence, Ms. Hendy wrote the judge in the case and asked him to
``please disregard these charges that I have made.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very sorry that I lied,'' she wrote. ``I have been in
counseling for manic depression.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She also said she had lied before and was going to stop with her
counselor's help. ``I drink too much,'' she concluded, ``and that's
why I'm on medication.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As for Ray, Jo McClean, the manager of Earl's Shamrock, a gas
station and convenience store here, said he ``was just like any
other person who came here.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McClean said Ray stopped at the store every weekday with 6
or 8 co-workers at the Elephant Butte State Park for doughnuts and
lunch supplies and she would give them free coffee. She described
him as ``very intelligent, clean-cut.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But on television, as he was being led off in handcuffs, she
said, ``he looks like a madman.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McClean said that when she first met Ray in 1984 he was
married and that he told her that he had left a used car lot that
he owned in Arizona. Arizona and Texas are two of the other states
where federal agents are seeking clues to Ray's activities. She
said Ray left Elephant Butte in about 1987 and then returned in
1990 without a wife. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ray told her that he and his wife had divorced.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elephant Butte seems an unlikely place for the arrival of what
is now an army of police officers. It is the kind of place where
people come to retire or to escape from the stress of other places.
</P>
<P>
   Elephant Butte just became a city last year and is about halfway
between El Paso and Albuquerque, but the closest town with any
significant population is Truth or Consequences, with 6,200
residents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jack Grimm is one of four members of the Elephant Butte City
Council and he said that one reason the residents supported
cityhood was to control growth and to figure out how big the place
was. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't even know the population,'' he said Thursday. ``We
think it's around 2,000.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the summer, the population of Elephant Butte explodes with
boaters and on Memorial Day, Labor Day and the Fourth of July there
are as many as 80,000 people in town. ``I can't wait for this
investigation to be over,'' Grimm said. ``The place is full of
rumors and this is not a good way to get our city on the map.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 2034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
