<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3042 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUMSHOE-SFCHRON &LR;      04-01 1352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUMSHOE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Gumshoes Stake Out the Workplace
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Move over, Sherlock Holmes, Hercule Poirot and Sam Spade.
</P>
<P>
   A new breed of investigator has arrived in American workplaces _
outside professionals who are hired by companies to sleuth out the
truth of employee complaints about sexual harassment,
discrimination or embezzlement.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these sleuths are employment lawyers or private
investigators. Others are human resource consultants _ although a
little-known California law says that only those with private
investigator licenses should be doing this kind of work.
</P>
<P>
   There are no numbers available on how big this mini-industry is
becoming. But demand for outside investigators is clearly growing _
spurred by several state and U.S. Supreme Court rulings that stress
the importance of doing a thorough, unbiased investigation of
employee complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The routine bread-and-butter investigations are still being
done by in-house HR professionals, but we're now seeing a cottage
industry of outside experts who do more intense investigations,''
said Brian Ashe, an employment lawyer with Seyfarth, Shaw,
Fairweather &AMP; Geraldson in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole market area of outside investigations is growing,''
agreed David Durham, managing partner of the San Francisco office
of Littler Mendelson, an employment law firm. ``It's got to be one
of the bigger growth markets out there, either in the legal or
nonlegal field.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside investigators are typically hired to look into employee
complaints that could lead to major lawsuits or that are too
politically sensitive for an internal person to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Janie Jensen, a Santa Clara HR consultant who does
investigations, estimates that 70 percent of &LR;   &LR; her cases involve
sexual harassment charges.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Scholick, a former partner at Littler Mendelson who opened
his own investigation firm last year, has looked into a variety of
cases:
</P>
<P>
   _A software saleswoman claimed that her manager raped her in her
hotel room at a trade show.
</P>
<P>
   _A low-level female employee at a startup firm complained about
constant sexual teasing by several managers and said they
retaliated against her when she wouldn't play along.
</P>
<P>
   _Several employees at a security service firm claimed that a
high-level executive in charge of computer purchases was taking
some of the equipment for her own personal use or resale.
</P>
<P>
   Ten or 15 years ago, such complaints would probably have been
handled entirely by in-house HR people or the company's lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   But the rising number of employment-related lawsuits over the
past decade led many companies to reassess their policies.
</P>
<P>
   In the landmark Cotran vs. Rollings Huding Hall decision in
January 1998, the California Supreme Court ruled that even if a
company came to the wrong conclusion in responding to harassment
charges, it could defend itself by showing the conclusion came out
of a reasonable and good-faith investigation. Several 1998 U.S.
Supreme Court decisions on sexual harassment cases made similar
points.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies figured that juries would be more likely to view
their investigations as reasonable and fair if they were done by
someone not on the firm's permanent payroll.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many law firms began shying away from doing
investigations for their clients: They feared a conflict of
interest if cases went to trial and they had to both argue the case
and testify as a witness about the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The result? Companies started hiring outside investigators, at
costs ranging from $100 to $300 per hour. The total bill for an
investigation can range from $3,000 to $30,000, depending on its
complexity _ and the cost often isn't covered by the company's
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   What's involved in a typical investigation?
</P>
<P>
   Investigators usually start by interviewing both the complainant
and the target of the complaint. Then they follow up by
interviewing potential witnesses and examining relevant documents.
</P>
<P>
   They end by giving the company a written report that states, as
best they can determine it, what really happened.
</P>
<P>
   Most investigators stick to determining the facts. They rarely
tell the company how to respond, although sometimes they will
present a range of possible actions for the company to consider.
</P>
<P>
   The stories and evidence presented to investigators are often
confusing or contradictory. But they still feel obliged to come up
with some kind of a conclusion for their clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not uncommon for a sexual harassment claim to end up with
little more than `he-said, she-said,''' said Howard Simon, a lawyer
with Landels Ripley &AMP; Diamond who frequently does investigations.
``But you can learn things from people's body language, their eye
contact or their recall of specific details that have a bearing on
who you're going to believe. You really do have to make a
credibility determination.''
</P>
<P>
   Like more traditional detectives, employment-claim investigators
must contend with wily perpetrators who try to throw them off the
track.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Pratt, an Alameda HR consultant who has been doing
investigations since 1986, recalls one sexual harassment case where
the accused employee made casual but calculated references to his
cousin, a famous sports figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was subtle, nothing overt, but it was an attempt to put
himself and me on the same male side dealing with these `whiny
females,''' Pratt said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside investigators also must navigate the sometimes-fuzzy
boundary line between specific allegations of wrongdoing and
broader patterns of corporate mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've run into trouble sometimes when there are different ideas
about the scope of the investigation,'' said Amy Oppenheimer, a
Berkeley attorney who does some sexual harassment investigations.
``Issues come up that the company doesn't want examined but I
really feel need to be looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   To deal with all this, good investigators need excellent
interpersonal skills and an understanding of human relations in the
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   They must also have a finely honed understanding of employment
law so they don't phrase their reports in a way that could
undermine a client's case in court.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the legal knowledge needed, some investigators feel
that no one but lawyers should really be doing this work.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone is an HR person, quite frankly, there are a lot of
legal nuances they just miss,'' said Scholick.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some people feel that the need for
interpersonal skills makes the job appropriate for anyone &LR;  but &LR; 
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very little of what we investigate has to do with something
unlawful,'' said Pratt. ``More often, it's subtleties of
interpersonal relationships. And practicing law often doesn't give
people any experience in being in a functioning work unit, which
they need in order to understand these situations.''
</P>
<P>
   The state of California actually has a law determining who can
do these kinds of outside investigations _ although few
practitioners are aware of it.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Consumer Affairs says that independent
investigators like Pratt are required to have private investigator
licenses unless they're lawyers. (HR professionals who are
employees of a firm don't need a license to do investigations
within their company.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are doing it on a contract basis, they absolutely need
to have a license,'' said Jay Van Rein, spokesman for the
department's Bureau of Security and Investigative Services. &UR;  &LR; Van
Rein said unlicensed investigators can face fines of several
thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But HR professionals who have been doing investigations for
years say they've never heard of this law _ or known they might be
in violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are attorneys out there who have been hiring us for
years and years, and they're probably not aware of that
requirement,'' said Jensen. ``I wasn't aware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time I've ever heard of it,'' agreed Pratt,
``and I've been hired a half-dozen times by state agencies to do
these investigations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 2036EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
