<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0310 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3044 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT &LR;      04-01 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA HESITATES, THEN CONFIRMS PREMIER'S VISIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Angered by the NATO bombing in Yugoslavia and renewed
attacks on China's human rights policies, senior Chinese officials
were seriously debating on Thursday whether Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji should postpone his visit to the United States, scheduled to
begin next week, said a Chinese person with knowledge of the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   But around midnight Thursday, the officials decided that Zhu
should proceed as planned, arriving in Los Angeles on Tuesday
before traveling on to Washington and other cities, the person
said.
</P>
<P>
   Both China and the Clinton administration have expressed hopes
that the visit by Zhu could help repair relations between the
countries. A postponement could add to the deep strains caused by
disputes over trade, American proposals for East Asian missile
defenses, and charges of nuclear espionage, as well as the NATO
bombing and human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about Zhu's visit was set off on Thursday at a
regularly scheduled foreign ministry press briefing when a
spokesman, Sun Yuxi, surprisingly refused to confirm the dates of
the supposedly imminent trip.
</P>
<P>
   Although the American government had already announced that Zhu
was visiting several cities from April 6 to 14, the Chinese
government had officially announced only that the trip would be in
April. Pressed by reporters, Sun would say only that he had
``nothing to add'' to earlier statements.
</P>
<P>
   Alarmed by the reticence at the news conference and other signs,
American Embassy officials here sent a cable to Washington
reporting that the Chinese appeared to be having second thoughts
about a visit next week, a senior American official said.
</P>
<P>
   Several issues had converged that would cause the Chinese to
reconsider the trip.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials had hoped to see a breakthrough by now over
China's entry into the World Trade Organization. But it became
clear this week, after a period of intense negotiations, that China
had not yet satisfied American demands for the opening of its
markets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Clinton administration, under pressure from
Congress, recently announced that it would sponsor a resolution
this month to condemn China's human rights record at a U.N. meeting
in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   China has reacted with special fury to the bombing in
Yugoslavia, which it portrays as an illegal act of intervention
inside a sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did NATO countries bypass the U.N. Security Council,
where China holds a veto, but in the Chinese view the action also
sets a dangerous precedent. Officials here fear that it could be
used to justify foreign interventions in their own regions of
potential strife like Tibet and the predominantly Muslim province
of Xinjiang, or in Taiwan, which they consider a renegade province
of China.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese argued that it would be humiliating for Zhu to
visit the United States while the bombing continues, especially in
the absence of a trade deal that could cap the meetings in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The state-controlled news media have painted an extremely
one-sided picture of the conflict in Kosovo, virtually ignoring
evidence of Yugoslav attacks on ethnic Albanians while broadcasting
on television scenes that cast the Serbs in a heroic light.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
