<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3043 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACK-CHILD'S-EASTER:     04-01 1263
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACK-CHILD'S-EASTER:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTER MEANT FUN, SWEET INNOCENCE _ AND NEW CLOTHES
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By BILL MAXWELL 
 &HT;    (Bill Maxwell, African American, is an editorial writer and
columnist for the St. Petersburg Times in St. Petersburg, Fla. He
can be reached on the Internet at maxwell(at) sptimes.com) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Only now, as a 53-year-old columnist, do
I appreciate the Easter celebration of my childhood.
 &HT;    Only now do I realize that, although it is the solemn day
commemorating Jesus' triumph over death and His gift to humankind
of eternal life, Easter for most black children in the South was a
time of camaraderie, fun and sweet innocence.
 &HT;    In fact, Easter was a day for children.
 &HT;    And, much like Christmas, half of the fun of Easter was the
activities during the days leading up to it, when our parents
bought, cooked and colored eggs, when lilies were collected. For us
children these were days of excitement and, most importantly, of
going with our parents to shop for new outfits.
 &HT;    We did not see the symbolism _ spring, starting anew _ in buying
new clothes. The boys knew that Easter meant a new black and often
ill-fitting suit, complete with a new white shirt, a new black hat,
and a new skinny black tie. Why black? I think it had something to
do with looking grownup, like replicas of the men in our lives
whose Sunday suits were black. Whatever the reason, we looked like
waiters. More accurately, I know now that we looked like the Blues
Brothers.
 &HT;    And I recall that a group of us would stand around outside the
church, quietly talking trash and lying about our female conquests,
our hands stuffed deeply in our pants pockets, our hats cocked to
one side. And we flirted with the girls _ if they passed without
their parents. It was the ``cool pose'' long before the term was
coined. If the morning was hot, we sweated inside our black suits.
But we did not care. We were having a good time.
 &HT;    The fun would end, though, when an adult, usually a man smiling
knowingly, told us to come inside for service, an event that, to
us, went on interminally.
 &HT;    And the girls? How beautiful they were in their new outfits,
their crinoline-flared, bright-colored dresses. I remember the new
hairdos that made them look so fresh and radiant, their smart
pocketbooks or handkerchiefs in which their money was tied in a
knot.
 &HT;    Like the Resurrection itself, girls were a transcendent mystery.
 &HT;    I asked Jounice L. Nealy, a colleague at the St. Petersburg
Times, what Easter meant to the girls at the time.
 &HT;    She remembers well. ``The excitement of my new school clothes
had long worn off, and even the Christmas gifts were getting a
little old. Oh, but then came Easter. And the hunt was on ....
 &HT;    ``My Easter shoes were always shiny and white, usually with a
strap across the foot. This was usually the time when my Mom
talked, complained, about how much my foot was growing. And, of
course, after we got home, she had to keep me out of those shoes so
I wouldn't scuff them before Sunday.
 &HT;    ``Then there was the dress, which had to be pretty to me. One
year my mom was so excited about a bonnet she bought for me. She
was equally disappointed when I refused to wear it.
 &HT;    ``Mrs. Bell Rogers would wash and press my hair with a
straightening comb, then twirl candy curls on Easter eve. Again,
Mom fussed Saturday night if I played too hard with my big brother.
She did not want me to mess up my curls. When I got in fifth grade,
I got a perm, and Easter became less tense,'' she recollects.
 &HT;    In Crescent City, Fla., where I spent much of my childhood,
Easter afternoon was an oratorical festival, when select children _
I was never among them _ marched to the front of the church and
delivered narratives or poems, some quite inspiring, written for
the ocassion. If a boy made a mistake or forgot some of his lines,
his buddies would fight for dear life to hold back their mirth.
Some of us would give in to the hilarity, of course, causing most
of the congregation to join in the laughter. The victim, always
good-natured, would start over.
 &HT;    For some reason, we never laughed at a girl who stumbled.
 &HT;    My colleague Jounice said that she and her childhood friends
also suffered the pain of the Easter speech. But Jounice and
company did not write their own speeches. ``Easter afternoons
always brought a sigh of relief. Weeks before, either Mrs. Durham
or Mrs. Smith had given us our Easter speeches. Somehow the
speeches my brother and I got always seemed to be the longest. And
we had to memorize our lines and rehearse at the church on
Saturdays.
 &HT;    ``On Easter morning, it was a matter of remembering all the
details: entering the stage from one side, walking to the piece of
tape on the floor, speaking right into the microphone and
remembering all of your lines. And, if I forgot to curtsy, Mrs.
Durham would yell from the audience and remind me,'' she recalls.
 &HT;    When our church service finally ended in the late afternoon, the
real fun began: We would dash home, trade our new duds for regular
clothes and return to the church for the communitywide Easter egg
hunt. We, the boys, would romp and tussle and, when the adults were
not watching, throw eggs at one another. If we mistakenly hit a
girl with one of these missiles, all hell broke loose, as it were,
and the perpetrator was spirited away for a whipping.
 &HT;    After that, order would be restored among the boys, who quietly
snickered and whispered about the poor sucker who got punished.
 &HT;    Later, the entire congregation would enjoy dinner on the
grounds, where tables would be ladened with the best soul food
imaginable. In the evening, we would dress and return to church,
where music would shake the rafters, where the minister would
invoke the spirit of ``He who died on the cross for our sins, who
resurrected and went to heaven to be with his Father.''
 &HT;    All the while, we boys sat _ sullen and anxious _ perspiring and
itching inside our new black suits. Occasionally, someone would
snore. An adult would march over to the miscreant, shake him awake
and point a warning finger in his face. The rest of us would again
struggle to hold back the laughter.
 &HT;    The alert among us sensed exactly when the preacher came to the
part about holy sepulcher and the ascension. At this point, about
9:00 p.m., we knew that soon we'd be going home for the night.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Bill Maxwell 
<TEXT>
