<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTER-MEMORIES:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTER MEMORIES: MOM'S BIG HAT, RAIN AND THE BEST HAM ON EARTH
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By RAOUL LOWERY CONTRERAS 
 &HT;    (Raoul Lowery Contreras, Mexican American, is a columnist and
editorial board member of La Prensa San Diego. He hosts his own
radio talk show on KOGO-AM.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    When I was a boy of 8, Easter Sunday meant three things to me:
My mother bought a big white hat to wear to church; it always
seemed to rain that day; and, every year we had a delicious ham
baked under a blanket of pineapple rings. I don't know why we had
ham on Easter Sunday and I don't know why pineapple rings. It
didn't matter; it was a terrific dinner.
 &HT;    The rain always bugged me, for it rains hardly at all in San
Diego. So, why the rain on Easter Sunday? The reason was simple. On
the greatest day of the Christian calendar, the day all life is
renewed, the rain came because the buses hardly ran and my mother
and I had to walk four miles in the downpour to and from Our Lady
of Sacred Heart. Of course it would rain on my mother's new hat!
 &HT;    Easter of 1950 brought a stepfather from central Texas who knew
ham, but pineapple was out of his universe. Not being a Roman
Catholic didn't help him understand why it was so important for us
to be at church on Easter Sunday, but then again, I didn't know
either. Not speaking Latin didn't help. But the Irish priest
managed to explain it to us, despite his brogue being so strong
half of the congregation _ the English-speaking half _ could barely
understand him.
 &HT;    At least, we wouldn't have to walk to and from church anymore _
I thought. Wrong! Rookie cops have to work on Sundays, especially
Easter Sundays, and my stepdad was a cop. It rained that Easter. My
mother's big white hat, almost as big as her umbrella, got wet.
During Mass, I prayed my mother would learn to drive before next
Easter. She didn't.
 &HT;    Easter of 1951 arrived on schedule with low-hanging rain-filled
clouds and the driver of the house having to work. My mother still
didn't know how to drive. This time I had to push a stroller with
my new brother all the way to church and back. Have you ever tried
to push a stroller in a light rain and hold an umbrella at the same
time?
 &HT;    Finally, in 1952, I was able to ride in a car to Easter service.
It didn't rain that day. I still couldn't understand the priest.
But after mass he pulled me aside and asked if I wanted to be an
altar boy. Of course! Of course, I wanted to be an altar boy. I
figured I would be able to understand him because he would have to
speak to me in Latin and that was easier than my learning Irish. I
had to be confirmed first, for a Catholic boy wasn't really
Catholic until he was confirmed.
 &HT;    Confirmation classes were after school, so my days got longer
and longer. I had to study my confirmation lesson book in school
and on the bus on the way to class. There, I learned about Easter.
The priest told me, ``on the Third day He arose from the dead'' and
ascended to heaven. Really? I was 11. Wow, I thought, that Jesus
was really something; he had to be the Son of God, without a doubt.
 &HT;    No wonder Easter is the most important day of the year. The
proof had to be the ham we had on that day, the only time we ever
had ham. Ham cost a lot of money then, a lot of money to us before
my stepdad joined the family with his $300-a-month police officer's
salary. It was very special. The day we had it, had to be a very
special day.
 &HT;    By 1954, I had three younger brothers. When we went to church,
Mother dressed them all exactly alike, complete with bow ties. I
didn't have to wear a bow tie, even on Easter. It was that 1954
Easter that we invited the whole family for Easter dinner. We had
three hams that time. There must not have been a pineapple left in
Hawaii. Everyone had such a good time; the family decided Easter
would be celebrated at our house the next year and the year after
that.
 &HT;    And so it went every year. A beautiful ham, pineapples, mashed
potatoes, sweet potatoes, green beans, corn, refried beans and
Spanish rice made our Easter dinner. What? Refried beans and
Spanish rice? Well, except for my stepdad, we are Mexican, you
know.
 &HT;    The Easter after I came home from the U.S. Marines, perhaps, is
the most memorable of my life. I had re-enrolled in college and was
working at a new Safeway grocery store in the city's first major
shopping mall. The day before Easter, I went to work and was told
by the smiling store manager to report to the mall office for the
day's work. OK, I said.
 &HT;    At the mall office, the pretty receptionist giggled when she saw
me and called her boss. He laughed as he shook my hand and led me
into his office. There sat a large white bunny rabbit suit;
complete with ears almost two feet high. I stared at it. It was my
size.
 &HT;    It was a great and happy Easter that year. The family dinner was
a riot of laughter. After all, how many families could celebrate
life's renewal and the Ascension with a real live 6-foot-tall
Easter Bunny in their midst?
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Raoul Lowery Contreras 
<TEXT>
