<HEADER>
A3050 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EASTER-POLITICS:MONIF     04-01 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTER-POLITICS:MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTER THEN AND NOW
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By AKILAH MONIFA 
 &HT;    (Akilah Monifa, African American, is a freelance writer living
in Oakland, Calif., and a contributor to the forthcoming book
``Seductions of Justice: Lesbian Legal Theories and Practices.''
(1999) Routledge Press.)
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    For most people Easter conjures up two images: the religious and
the commercial.
 &HT;    For Catholics and Protestants Easter is the highest of high holy
days. OK, Christmas is also big with Christians, but it doesn't
always fall on Sunday and after all it is a birthday party.
 &HT;    And commercially, Easter has chocolate rabbits, colored and
decorated eggs which are either placed in baskets or hidden in
lawns for children to find. There is the Easter Bunny who, although
pales in comparison to Santa Claus at Christmas, still reigns over
the holiday.
 &HT;    Easter, however, is normally not thought of as a particularly
political scenario. However, two events one current and one
occurring more than 35 years ago, illustrate how political Easter
can be.
 &HT;    The first occurred in Huntsville, Alabama circa 1962. Much of
the country, Huntsville included, were in the grips of various
forms of racial segregation.
 &HT;    My family, like most other black families, celebrated Easter
both religiously and commercially. The religious side consisted
mainly, no, exclusively, of going to church. Folks went to church
who would normally not attend on any other Sunday. The commercial
side of Easter included the baskets, cards, egg-hiding parties and
Easter egg hunts.
 &HT;    But the big commercial impact of the holiday was the purchasing
and donning of Easter outfits for church. It was spring, and we
always got new clothes in which to parade around on Easter Sunday.
There was a great deal of excitement and discussion about your
clothes on Easter. It was almost as if the Easter outfit was
reserved for that sole occasion.
 &HT;    But now a new perspective _ a political one _ dramatically
affected Easter 1962: no one bought new clothes. We all wore blue
jeans to church as part of an organized economic boycott of the
segregated stores in town. The protest was organized by Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr. It was both a visible and economic display of
disgust at segregation on not only the holiest of holidays among
Christians, but also the holiday on which African Americans spent
the most money.
 &HT;    Now the year is 1999 and I have moved to the city by the bay,
Oakland, right across the bridge from San Francisco. Now there is
another political action taking place on Easter. Easter 1999 is the
20th anniversary of a gay lesbian bisexual and transgender group of
people who call themselves the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence. The
Sisters, though small in number _ around 15 _ wanted to celebrate
their anniversary as they have in the past, with a rally on the
streets of the predominately gay neighborhood in San Francisco
known as the Castro.
 &HT;    The Sisters, mainly cross-dressing gay men, dress in nuns'
habits and appear in ``white face.'' They have names like Sister
Reyna Terror and Sister Ann R. Key. In the past they have held
``hunky Jesus contests'' and other such mocking activities. In
addition to their annual Easter parade and rally they also raise
money for charities. But this year because of the power of
newsletters and e-mail in this the information age, many
Christians, particularly Catholics, protested against the Sisters
getting a permit for their Easter parade and rally.
 &HT;    The Sisters prevailed in a 9-2 vote of the San Francisco Board
of Supervisors and have been granted their permit. Catholic
organizations and activists opposing the event state that they are
neither intolerant nor homophobic. These celebrations would be
fine, they say, if they were held on any other Sunday. But they see
Easter Sunday as holy and sacred and certainly beyond ridicule.
Protesters are threatening to boycott the city and county of San
Francisco by not holding conventions there.
 &HT;    Even though the two events are different and almost 40 years
apart, I'm sure most think Easter is not an appropriate time for
protest or rallies of any sort. I was proud to participate in that
`blue jeans' Easter Sunday when I was a child.
 &HT;    I'm not a member of the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence and I do
understand why some Catholic groups are upset. However, we do live
in a nation where for the most part freedom of religion and speech
are upheld. Regardless of whether one agrees with the message or
the messengers.
 &HT;    Easter is Easter, and my childhood political Easter looms large
in my memories. Politics and religion can and do mix.
 &HT;    Happy Easter!
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Akilah Monifa 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) &QL;
</P>
