Oakland, right across the bridge from San Francisco. Now there is
another political action taking place on Easter. Easter 1999 is the
20th anniversary of a gay lesbian bisexual and transgender group of
people who call themselves the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence. The
Sisters, though small in number _ around 15 _ wanted to celebrate
their anniversary as they have in the past, with a rally on the
streets of the predominately gay neighborhood in San Francisco
known as the Castro.
 &HT;    The Sisters, mainly cross-dressing gay men, dress in nuns'
habits and appear in ``white face.'' They have names like Sister
Reyna Terror and Sister Ann R. Key. In the past they have held
``hunky Jesus contests'' and other such mocking activities. In
addition to their annual Easter parade and rally they also raise
money for charities. But this year because of the power of
newsletters and e-mail in this the information age, many
Christians, particularly Catholics, protested against the Sisters
getting a permit for their Easter parade and rally.
 &HT;    The Sisters prevailed in a 9-2 vote of the San Francisco Board
of Supervisors and have been granted their permit. Catholic
organizations and activists opposing the event state that they are
neither intolerant nor homophobic. These celebrations would be
fine, they say, if they were held on any other Sunday. But they see
Easter Sunday as holy and sacred and certainly beyond ridicule.
Protesters are threatening to boycott the city and county of San
Francisco by not holding conventions there.
 &HT;    Even though the two events are different and almost 40 years
apart, I'm sure most think Easter is not an appropriate time for
protest or rallies of any sort. I was proud to participate in that
`blue jeans' Easter Sunday when I was a child.
 &HT;    I'm not a member of the Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence and I do
understand why some Catholic groups are upset. However, we do live
in a nation where for the most part freedom of religion and speech
are upheld. Regardless of whether one agrees with the message or
the messengers.
 &HT;    Easter is Easter, and my childhood political Easter looms large
in my memories. Politics and religion can and do mix.
 &HT;    Happy Easter!
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Akilah Monifa 
<TEXT>
