<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORYBOOK-DOLLS:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE DID SHE GO _ THE PERSON WHO RAN OFF WITH TIME?
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By KIRSTEN CHAPMAN 
 &HT;    (Kirsten Chapman writes a weekly column for the Columbus
Dispatch in Columbus, Ohio, and is the author of three books,
including recently published ``The Way Home.'') 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Fifty-five isn't nearly as sobering as 56: the numeral ``6''
underscoring that the leap to 60 is that much closer.
 &HT;    Only yesterday I was in my late 40s, still fooling myself that
life was infinite. Then, the future was mine to plan; now, the
future is making plans for me. And now that my seventh decade looms
nearer, I realize that tomorrow may never come.
 &HT;    What happened? Where did she go _ the person who ran off with
time? Who is the new acquaintance inhabiting my old skin?
 &HT;    Perhaps each of us is merely a series of strangers.
 &HT;    Why does each new me disappear just as I start to know her?
 &HT;    Half a century ago, I knew exactly what I wanted for my
birthday. I never thought to wish for a long and healthy life or
parents who live forever or lasting world peace. Instead, when I
was 6, I pined for a Storybook Doll.
 &HT;    Actually, I wanted every single one in the Nancy Ann Storybook
Doll display at Barden's Department Store: Little Betty Blue, Polly
Put the Kettle On, Daffy Down Dilly and One, Two Button my Shoe _
all of them and more.
 &HT;    My nose to the case in the girls' section on the second floor, I
prayed that Mother would get lost in the nearby notions department.
I could never tire of gazing at the 5 1/2 inch beauties, I told
myself. If my parents really loved me, why wouldn't they want to
give me all those polka dot boxes, each one filled with a
diminutive doll in a dainty outfit?
 &HT;    Ginny Vincent seemed to have half the collection lined up on her
bedroom shelves. If I owned that many dolls, I thought, I'd never
want for anything else. I promised myself when I grew up, I'd go
back to Barden's and buy every one _ even the display case, lights
and all.
 &HT;    In the era before Barbie, cars had fewer flat tires and the milk
was delivered by a horse-drawn wagon. Ladies wore hats, as did
well-dressed gentlemen, while girls covered their heads with
babushkas on a cold March day.
 &HT;    Our school desks still bore the holes for long-forgotten ink
bottles, while our classrooms bore the holes of missing students.
 &HT;    Though young, we knew about polio and tuberculosis and an iron
lung machine. Our homes sometimes displayed ``QUARANTINE'' signs in
the windows and received visiting nurses.
 &HT;    When we dreamed about Storybook Dolls, though, we escaped that
world of terror. When we received one of the dolls, we were
transported.
 &HT;    Yet, after the ribbon and wrapping paper were off and the lid
was removed, after we and our birthday guests had oohed and aahed,
we faced a conflict: whether to leave the cellophane seal intact.
 &HT;    I could forever preserve my porcelain doll like a sleeping Snow
White. Still, in the end, after listening to the urgings of my
friends and my inner self, I'd rip off the transparent covering and
seize my new toy.
 &HT;    My hands couldn't resist touching her bisque face, moving her
jointed arms, playing with her lovely hair _ and putting her in a
pocket.
 &HT;    My travels left her scruffy and worse for wear _ flowers fallen
from her hair, a wrinkled dress _ but oh, the adventures we had.
 &HT;    Now some 50 years later, the memory of a Storybook Doll still
hovers: it reminds me that having the experiences, even the
mistakes, is better than remaining intact, never taking risks.
 &HT;    Did I ever receive all the dolls? No, only a few.
 &HT;    Today, even if I wanted to keep my childhood promise and collect
them in one fell swoop, I couldn't find them to buy. Other dolls
are sold, of course, but not those dolls _ all new and lined up in
a case at Barden's. In fact, the store no longer exists.
 &HT;    Nor does the girl who used to dream there.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Kirsten Chapman 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
