<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0321 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3072 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OFFICER-SHOT-FOLO02-C     04-01 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OFFICER-SHOT-FOLO02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Facts of officer's fatal shooting elude police
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Police were still trying to figure out on Thursday why
a traffic stop, where an Atlanta cop tried to help a stranded
motorist, ended in the death of one of his fellow officers.
</P>
<P>
   Russell ``Rusty'' Stalnaker, a well-liked officer in the Zone
Five mini-precinct downtown, was shot to death doing what he did
best _ trying to help another cop.
</P>
<P>
   Stalnaker, 24, was prounounced dead at 8:01 p.m. on Wednesday at
Grady Memorial Hospital. He received four gunshout wounds from a
9mm handgun, police said. The fatal bullet hit the three-year
veteran in the head; three others lodged in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   A shroud of sadness and disbelief fell over the Atlanta Police
Department on Thursday as dozens of officers _ from Police Chief
Beverly Harvard to the greenest recruit _ asked themselves what
could have made the shooter, identified as Kimani Atu Archie, also
24, get violent with police. Archie is being held in jail, charged
with killing Stalnaker.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, an emotional Harvard, whose eyes brimmed with tears,
recounted the events that began at about 7 p.m. at the intersection
of Pine and Linden streets.
</P>
<P>
   Officer J. Daigle encountered Archie pushing a pickup truck.
Daigle asked Archie if he needed help, even offering to call a tow
truck for him, said Harvard and Lt. Debbie Reese, Stalnaker's
direct supervisor. When Archie firmly refused, Daigle drove away
only to come across Archie a few minutes later at the corner of
Spring and Pine streets.
</P>
<P>
   This time Archie became belligerent, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officer told him he could cause an accident and then
called a wrecker,'' Harvard said. ``When the officer saw that
Archie was getting into his truck and would not come out, the
officer then called for back up.''
</P>
<P>
   Stalnaker and officers J. Price and M. Wiskermann responded,
Reese said. When the officers arrived and confronted Archie, he
began struggling and scuffling with the officers, Harvard and Reese
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Archie pulled out a handgun and fired at the officers first,''
Harvard said.
</P>
<P>
   As officers returned fire, Archie jumped into a patrol car
parked nearby and sped away toward Peachtree Street, police said.
He abandoned the car and ran to the parking lot of St. Luke's
Episcopal Church at the corner of Peachtree and Pine streets. There
he attempted to steal a woman's car. Rebecca Parker, a St. Luke's
parishioner, said she was that woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started screaming,'' said Parker, 44, director of continuing
education at Columbia Theological Seminary. ``Then he pulled me out
of the car and threw me onto the concrete.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the man then jumped into her car and grabbed her purse.
Realizing she was under the car and fearing she was about to get
run over, Parker scrambled to her feet and ran. As she looked up,
she saw the church security guard and began yelling.
</P>
<P>
   When she turned, Parker said she saw the man run into the
church.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Spenser Simrill, rector of St. Luke's, said he was
sitting in the back of the church with regular worshipers when the
suspect barrelled through the door. It was dark, because the church
was lighted with only candles for the service, but Simrill said the
man did not appear to be wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was running pretty good,'' Simrill said.
</P>
<P>
   Simrill got up and joined the security guard in pursuing Archie
down the brick-paved center aisle of the church. There was a table
full of candles about 15 paces in front of the altar. Archie veered
to the right around the table, spotted a doorway, and ran through
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He stepped out of the door and said 'I want sanctuary,' ``
Simrill recalled Thursday. ``I held him,'' Simrill said,
demonstrating a simple embrace rather than any kind of restraining
hold, ``trying to calm him down. I didn't want to escalate this
thing. But I wasn't about to let him go, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Simrill said the suspect also asked for water, which he was
given by parishioners who came back to see what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   When police arrived, Simrill said, ``They kept asking, 'Where's
the gun? Where's the gun?''' The guy told them, `It's in the
car.'''
</P>
<P>
   Archie, originally from Pennsylvania, appeared briefly in
Municipal Court, dressed in a bright red Atlanta corrections
uniform, shackled from head to toe. His face was partially covered
with a mask resembling that worn by a beekeeper. The suspect's
arraingment was rescheduled for April 28 at 4:30 p.m. so that he
would have the opportunity to hire an attorney, police said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 Atlanta officers huddled together in the wooden
pews in Courtroom 3 at the Municipal courthouse in a show of
solidarity for the slain officer. They stared intently at Archie
when he shuffled out of the holding area escorted by two guards.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Thursday whether Archie was intoxicated with
drugs or alcohol when the incident occurred Wednesday night.
Harvard said that was still under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Georgia Department of Corrections, who keep a
hefty file on Archie for a handful of misdemeanor violations going
back as far as 1994 in Fulton, Cobb and DeKalb counties, were
surprised he acted so violently. However, records from Metro-Dade
Police in South Florida showed Archie was charged with battering a
police officer in 1993 when another traffic stop in Miami went
awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a shock because there was never anything in his
probation file that would have indicated any violence towards
anyone,'' said Larry Anderson, director of the probation unit at
Corrections. ``A person who has been convicted of misdemeanor
offenses is not the one you would expect would do this kind of
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Predictible or not, Lt. G.W. Pierce, a 40-year Atlanta police
veteran and the officer with the most years of service in the city,
said some things are still hard to accept. ``I've been here a long
time and you never get used to seeing one of your own killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Atlanta police Maj. John Woodard, commander of
the Zone 5 precinct, was busy establishing a fund for Stalnaker's
widow, Dana, a schoolteacher in Henry County. The account will be
opened at NationsBank; anyone interested in donating should call
404-658-7054, Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This girl is devastated,'' Woodard said Thursday night. ``We
want to try to help her as much as we can. She's been left on her
own.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
