A3055 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANN-LEE:WU-NEWAMERIC     04-01 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANN-LEE:WU-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSISTANT ATTORNEY GENERAL FOR CIVIL RIGHTS: WHY BILL LANN LEE?
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales Executive DEBORAH
WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By FRANK WU 
 &HT;    (Frank Wu, Chinese American, is a columnist for Asian Week and
associate professor of law and supervising attorney at Howard
University.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Bill Lann Lee deserves to be the assistant attorney general for
civil rights. The former NAACP Legal Defense Fund lawyer has been
holding the top civil rights post in an ``acting'' capacity ever
since late 1997, but President Clinton recently re-submitted his
name to a hostile Senate in another effort at confirmation of his
choice.
 &HT;    Everybody agrees Lee is better than qualified. He spent 20 years
at the Legal Defense Fund. This branch of the NAACP is the
non-profit group which, under the guidance of the late Supreme
Court Justice Thurgood Marshall, brought about the end of
segregation.
 &HT;    Nobody suggests that Lee has the type of personal problems which
have affected other nominees. He is so well-regarded that even his
adversaries in lawsuits, such as Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan,
have endorsed him.
 &HT;    Instead, the attacks on Lee are about a single issue:
affirmative action. Washington lawyer Clint Bolick, an advocate
against those racial remedies as well as all anti-discrimination
legislation, is pursuing Lee with the same zealous inaccuracy that
he used in defeating Lani Guinier for the same job a few years ago.
With help from former Attorney General Edwin Meese, Bolick asserts
that Lee is ``defying the rule of law.''
 &HT;    Bolick is wrong about the law. Furthermore, he is asking
senators to abuse the confirmation process.
 &HT;    To be sure, the Supreme Court is highly skeptical of affirmative
action. It has directed the lower courts to apply stringent
standards in reviewing the programs.
 &HT;    Nonetheless, like Congress and a majority of the public, the
courts have recognized that in exceptional circumstances addressing
racism may require taking into account race. The former presidents
of Princeton and Harvard Universities recently published a
book-length study, entitled ``The Shape of the River,'' offering
copious evidence that affirmative action has been effective in
college admissions. Their work makes it all the more important to
seek compromise on this contentious matter.
 &HT;    As would be expected, Lee agrees with the long-standing White
House policy of ``mend it, don't end it.''
 &HT;    Of course, Bolick and his colleagues have their own arguments.
They ought to make their case in the courts and in Congress or
through ballot initiatives. Perhaps they will prevail through
democratic debate.
 &HT;    However, it doesn't help society resolve persistent problems of
bias and prejudice if one side insists that their opposition lacks
principles. It is absurd, as a few have done, to compare Lee with
someone who believes in Jim Crow.
 &HT;    The anti-Lee campaign continues an unfortunate trend of making
the Senate ``advise and consent'' privilege a partisan contest. The
Senate plays an important role on high-level executive branch
appointments. It isn't supposed to block presidential decisions and
hold up good candidates to show its power though.
 &HT;    During the initial controversy over Lee, former assistant
attorney generals under Presidents Eisenhower, Kennedy, Johnson,
Nixon, Ford, Carter, and Bush wrote an open letter observing, ``if
the test for confirmation is whether a nominee shares the views of
the Senate,'' then the Civil Rights division ``could well have gone
without a confirmed leader during the administrations in which we
served.''
 &HT;    Ironically, Lee symbolizes the success of affirmative action. He
is the son of Chinese immigrants who operated a Harlem hand
laundry. He benefited from a scholarship program for racial
minorities, opening the doors to Yale, from which he graduated
magna cum laude.
 &HT;    As the first individual who is neither black nor white to be
selected for this position, Lee signals that everyone has a stake
in the civil rights movement. As an Asian American representing the
Legal Defense Fund, he gave meaning to the metaphor of ``building
bridges.''
 &HT;    Both before joining the Justice Department and now as one of its
officials, his clients have included people of all identities. The
hallmark of his approach has been resolving difficult disputes
through settlements helping all parties. He demonstrates how
diversity can work.
 &HT;    If the Senate says yes to Lee, it will not only benefit the
people whose civil rights he would protect, but also restore public
faith in the political system.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Frank Wu 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
