<HEADER>
A3057 &Cx1f; tab-z
r v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EASTER-BUDGET-NEWAMER     04-01 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EASTER-BUDGET-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (These ``separate buy'' articles from this week's New America News
Service moved today.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish a NEWAM article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate Sales
Executive DEBORAH WEYDERT at 1-732-390-4480.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EASTER MEANT FUN, SWEET INNOCENCE _ AND NEW CLOTHES. Although
Easter Sunday is the solemn day commemorating Jesus' triumph over
death and His gift to humankind of eternal life, notes columnist
Bill Maxwell, for most black children in the South it was a time of
fun and sweet innocence. ``Boys knew that Easter meant a new black
and often ill-fitting suit, complete with white shirt, black hat,
and skinny black tie,'' he writes. ``We looked like waiters. More
accurately, I know now, we looked like the Blues Brothers!'' But,
however uncomfortable they were in their new outfits, it was a time
of showing off, flirting with the girls in their pretty new
dresses, and consuming the best soul food imaginable, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Moved BC-BLACK-CHILD'S-EASTER:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF as in
``k'' commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   EASTER MEMORIES: MOM'S BIG HAT, RAIN AND THE BEST HAM ON EARTH.
When he was a boy of 8, Easter Sunday meant three things: His
mother's new big white hat for church; rain; and, a delicious ham
baked under a blanket of pineapple rings for dinner, recalls
columnist Raoul Lowery Contreras. ``The rain always bugged me, for
it rains hardly at all in San Diego.'' So, why the rain on Easter
Sunday? ``On the greatest day of the Christian calendar, the day
all life is renewed, the reason for the rain was simple,'' he
writes. ``It was because the buses hardly ran and my mother and I
had to walk four miles in the downpour to and from Our Lady of
Sacred Heart. Of course it would rain on my mother's new hat!''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-EASTER-MEMORIES:CONTRERAS-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   EASTER THEN AND NOW. For most people Easter conjures up two
images: the religious, and the commercial, observes columnist
Akilah Monifa. ``But Easter is not normally associated with
politics,'' she adds. However, two events _ one current and one
more than 35 years ago _ illustrate how political Easter can be,
she writes. Read how disgust with segregation, and a boycott
organized by Martin Luther King Jr., made the Easter of 1962 highly
political and one to cherish, and how a gay San Francisco parade,
however controversial, is making the Easter of '99 an affirmation
of freedom of religion and speech.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-EASTER-POLITICS:MONIFA-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE DID SHE GO _ THE PERSON WHO RAN OFF WITH TIME? Only
yesterday I was in my late 40s, still fooling myself that life was
infinite, muses columnist Kirsten Chapman. Then ... What happened?
Where did she go _ the person who ran off with time? ``Who is the
new acquaintance inhabiting my old skin?'' she wonders. Perhaps
each of us is merely a series of strangers. ``Why does each new me
disappear just as I start to know her?'' she asks. Half a century
ago, she knew exactly what she wanted for her birthday. She pined
for a Storybook Doll. ``But now ... the dolls, and the store where
I used to gaze at them, no longer exist. Nor does the girl who used
to dream there,'' she realizes wistfully.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-STORYBOOK-DOLLS:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   ASSISTANT ATTORNEY GENERAL FOR CIVIL RIGHTS: WHY BILL LANN LEE?
The former NAACP Legal Defense Fund lawyer, Bill Lann Lee, has been
holding the top civil rights post in an `acting' capacity ever
since late 1997, but President Clinton recently re-submitted his
name to a hostile Senate in another effort at confirmation, notes
columnist Frank Wu. ``Lee is better than qualified,'' he writes. He
spent 20 years at the Legal Defense Fund where, as an Asian
American, he gave meaning to the words `building bridges.' ``Both
before joining the Justice Department and now as one of its
officials, his clients have included people of all identities,'' Wu
declares. ``He demonstrates how diversity can work,''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-LANN-LEE:WU-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k'' commentary and
``a'' general news files.
</P>
