<SLUG> BC-GUMSIDE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Sam Spade Takes on the Workplace
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Employment investigators see the seamy side of work life:
harassment, discrimination, office politics and paranoia.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, though, they get to clear up misunderstandings and
help improve working conditions. Here are summaries of three recent
investigations handled by attorney Gary Scholick of Independent
Employment Counsel in San Rafael.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Trade-show rape claim.  &LR; A saleswoman at a software firm went
to a trade show where, she claimed, one of her firm's managers
accompanied her back to her hotel room after an evening of drinking
and raped her. The saleswoman called the police the following
morning, and they arrested the executive.
</P>
<P>
   Scholick was hired within a week to find out the facts for the
company, which wanted its own independent assessment of the
charges. His conclusion? ``It was an unwelcome sexual event. ... I
made a finding of what happened, and then said the company should
discuss the situation with its lawyers.'' He doesn't know if
criminal charges have been filed against the manager, but he's
expecting that his papers on the case will eventually be subpoenaed
as evidence in a civil suit or criminal trial.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Sexual harassment and retaliation claim.  &LR; A low-level employee
at a startup said she was subjected to unwelcome sexual teasing
from several managers. She also claimed they retaliated against her
by giving her bad assignments. Scholick found that the woman's
claims about the teasing were accurate. ``It took me back to the
'60s or early '70s: The guys almost treated this woman as a
plaything,'' he said. But he didn't find any basis to her
retaliation claim. What happened, Scholick found, was that there
were genuine problems with the woman's work performance that no one
had mentioned to her. When she was denied good assignments, she
assumed it was retaliation _ but it was really performance-related.
``After the investigation, she came around and saw that it wasn't
retaliatory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _Equipment theft claim.  &LR; Several employees of a security
service firm wrote anonymous notes saying that a top executive in
charge of computer acquisitions was buying more equipment than was
needed and taking some of it for her own use. Scholick found that
the executive was indeed ordering some equipment that appeared to
be excessive, such as electronic games. And some equipment was
indeed delivered to the executive's home. ``She couldn't answer
questions about why it was delivered to her house, and just said,
`I don't remember,''' Scholick said. Scholick's personal conclusion
was that something was amiss _ but the company disagreed. ``There
was a disagreement between what I believed was happening and what
the company believed was happening,'' he said. Ultimately, the
executive submitted a voluntary resignation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 2038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
