<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3071 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      04-01 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: When a Good Worker Has a Bad Attitude
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Ilana DeBare &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I have a small business and one of my employees does his
job better than anyone I've ever seen. He's fast and efficient.
However, he has a bad attitude toward other employees and sometimes
customers. He has also made comments to another employee that he
may leave the company and take some clients with him. I would like
this person to stay with the company, but not with his current
attitude. Any suggestions?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Have you voiced any of your criticisms directly to
this employee? If not, it's high time to sit down and have a
serious talk. Let him know how much you appreciate his strengths.
Then explain the problems you see _ and focus on specific comments
or actions rather than making general complaints about his
``attitude.'' Lay out some specific steps he can take to improve,
and set a timetable for follow-up reviews.
</P>
<P>
   You should make very clear to him that teamwork and customer
service are an essential part of his job. But that leads to a
second question.
</P>
<P>
   Have you made crystal clear to all your employees that you
really  &LR; do  &LR; value teamwork and customer service? And do those
values show up in your actions as well as your words _ in parceling
out raises or bonuses, for instance?
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask yourself if you've really articulated your values,
demonstrated them yourself ... and set up a system where people are
publicly acknowledged for meeting those standards,'' said Jim
Kouzes, a Palo Alto management expert and author of ``The
Leadership Challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   But let's return to your immediate problem. If you're worried
that this guy may jump ship and pull your clients with him, take
some preventive action. ``This owner may personally need to go
spend some time with clients, to make sure they're identifying with
the company, not the individual employee,'' Kouzes said.
</P>
<P>
   If this fellow won't shape up, you may have to fire him. Don't
feel intimidated: Your firm will survive without his skills. In
fact, it may even do better without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd just as soon deal with a lesser-skilled individual with a
good attitude than a higher-skilled one with a bad attitude,'' said
Donna Shepherd, human resources director at the San Francisco
Marriott. ``The damage to teamwork that comes from a bad attitude
can outweigh all the positive attributes that someone brings to the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   Language Rights
</P>
<P>
   Q: Two of my co-workers have been told by our employer not to
speak to each other in Spanish. What are the rights of the employer
and employee around this issue?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: Employers are generally not allowed to have broad
English-only rules that ban all use of other languages at work,
according to Marielena Hincapi &LR; e &LR; , a project attorney with the
Employment Law Center in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the courts have ruled that blanket English-only
rules amount to illegal discrimination on the basis of national
origin.
</P>
<P>
   But companies  &LR; can  &LR; have narrower English-only rules that govern
certain work situations, if there's a genuine business reason.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, retail stores can require salespeople to talk to
English-speaking customers in English. And firms can require
meetings to be held in English, if there are English-speaking
employees who otherwise wouldn't understand what was being said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say there's a workplace like an oil refinery where there
are safety concerns, with people shouting orders back and forth
that everyone needs to understand,'' Hincapi &LR; e &LR;  said. ``That's a
situation where an English-only rule might be considered a business
necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employers impose broad English-only rules for reasons of
workforce morale: They fear that English-speaking employees will
feel left out and resentful if their colleagues chat in Spanish,
Mandarin or Arabic.
</P>
<P>
   But such employers should think twice. The courts have said that
fears about morale aren't enough to justify an English-only policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an English-only rule is simply to please customers or
co-workers, it's not considered a business necessity,'' Hincapi &LR; e &LR; 
said. ``So it probably wouldn't be legal.''
</P>
<P>
   More questions about English-only rules? The Employment Law
Center has a free language-rights hotline: Call (800) 864-1664.
</P>
<P>
   Clerical Error
</P>
<P>
   Q: A month ,ago my company gave me a letter of promotion that
said I'd be getting a raise of $200 a week. Last week, I received
my paycheck with only a $14.92 addition to my original salary
amount, so I questioned it. Now the boss is saying that I received
the wrong letter because of a clerical mistake. He says that
although I got the promotion, I am only getting a $14 raise. Was
that letter a binding contract?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: I hope you didn't go out and buy a new car counting on
that extra $200: You're pretty much stuck with the $14 raise.
</P>
<P>
   Even in binding contracts, the law allows the parties to correct
mistakes _ and it sounds like this was an honest mistake.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the letter promising you the raise most likely
wouldn't have been considered a legal contract, according to Alan
Exelrod, who represents employees with Rudy Exelrod Zieff &AMP; True in
San Francisco. ``It was a unilateral statement, not a binding
contract,'' Exelrod said.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal wage laws do require employers to pay
employees all the money they've been promised for time they've
actually worked. For example, companies can't hire people at $8 an
hour, make them work for 40 hours, and then tell them, ``Sorry,
we're only paying you $6 an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   So you might have a valid claim to that extra $200 for the
couple of weeks you worked before being told that the correct
amount of your raise was $14.
</P>
<P>
   But that would be only for the time you've already worked. The
boss has no obligation to continue paying you that extra $200 in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
