<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CAPTURED-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTIVE SOLDIERS A NIGHTMARE FOR CLINTON ADMINISTRATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-GONZALES and KOSOVO-LEGAL) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The bruised, bewildered faces of three young U.S.
infantry scouts staring from the repeatedly run video clip sent a
shudder through official Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In their camouflage uniforms _ and in the hands of the enemy _
the captive soldiers represented one of the Clinton
administration's worst nightmares about what NATO forces face in
the Balkan fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The White House had conditioned itself to the likelihood of
troop losses in the fight with Yugoslavia but was worried about how
many casualties a risk-averse United States would accept.
</P>
<P>
   The engagement's first brush with disaster, last weekend's loss
of an F-117A stealth jet, ended with a sigh of relief. The pilot
was rescued in six hours and returned to his air base in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic had been denied a public
relations coup early in the fight.
</P>
<P>
   But from the initial report Wednesday night that three 1st
Infantry Division soldiers were missing, the incident had a more
harrowing feel, and the dread was not misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday came the pictures from Serb television: stiff,
grim soldiers, their U.S. insignia, name patches and swollen faces
flashed around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The administration reacted with practiced concern and toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``All Americans are concerned about their welfare,'' President
Clinton told a military audience in Norfolk, Va. ``President
Milosevic should make no mistake, the United States takes care of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``And President Milosevic should make no mistake, we will hold
him and his government responsible for their safety and for their
well being.''
</P>
<P>
   The military echoed the warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all seen their pictures. We don't like it,'' said U.S.
Army Gen. Wesley Clark, who as supreme allied commander is NATO's
top soldier. ``We don't like the way they're treated, and we have a
long memory about these kinds of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will be held accountable,'' Clark told a briefing at NATO
headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not clear what, if any, specific action either
Clinton or Clark had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington and Brussels, officials also wondered what
Milosevic has in mind.
</P>
<P>
   State Department James P. Rubin was asked if the Yugoslav leader
is interested in using the captured soldiers as a bargaining chip
in halting the NATO bombardment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I wouldn't rule out any tactic on the part of someone
who's conducted the terrible policies that he's conducted in
Kosovo,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO air commander David Wilby said it was not clear if
Yugoslavs were deliberately looking for Americans to use as
hostages.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fully investigating the matter just to try and
determine exactly what did happen, to try and make sure that we get
our soldiers back as soon as possible, and also to preclude any
such event happening again in the future,'' Wilby said.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the three soldiers looked roughed up in some way _
scratches, cuts, bruises. Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles appeared to have a gauze bandage on the back of his head.
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Draskovic, Yugoslav deputy prime minister, said at least one
of the soldiers was ``trying to fight physically before being
arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic, in an ABC-TV interview, said the U.S. soldiers will
be treated in the ``most, best humane way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon identified the other soldiers as Spc. Steven M.
Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville; Texas, and Staff Sgt. Christopher J.
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sending regards to the families of captured soldiers, and
they must know for Serbs, captured enemy is not enemy,'' Draskovic
said. ``And they have no reason to be worried about them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Serb television report was apparently aired from Pristina,
the main city of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Wilby said the allies have ``a reasonable idea'' where the
soldiers are being held, ``but I couldn't put my hand on my heart
and say exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   Like soldiers throughout the ranks, Clark was irked by seeing
the men as part of what could be viewed as a propaganda exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Clark noted that after the soldiers' last radio transmission
while on patrol, ``the next we saw, they were badly beaten up there
and shown on television in Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   David Leavy, spokesman for the National Security Council, said
``the signs they have been mistreated are very disturbing.'' He
said a ``strong note'' had been sent to the Milosevic government
through the Swedish delegation in Belgrade, which is handling
diplomatic contacts between the United States and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   But, Leavy conceded, the picture from the television screen also
could have been worse: ``We're thankful the servicemen are alive.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
