<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3076 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MURDOCH-MALONE-650&AMP;AD     04-01 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDOCH-MALONE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDOCK TO BUY OUT MALONE'S STAKE IN REGIONAL SPORTS NETWORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rupert Murdoch is taking a strong step toward increasing his
hold over sports programming, agreeing to buy out the 50 percent
stake owned by John Malone's Liberty Media in a venture that
controls a dozen regional sports networks, according to people
familiar with the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, they said, News Corp. will also double its
stake in the New York Knicks, the New York Rangers, Madison Square
Garden and Radio City Music to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Liberty Media is getting $1.4 billion of News Corp.
stock, giving it 5 percent of the company and making it the largest
single outside investor. The Murdoch family owns roughly 31
percent.
</P>
<P>
   One industry expert who requested anonymity said Thursday that
the deal might pave the way to Liberty Media acquiring up to 10
percent of News Corp., whose stock has been relatively depressed
compared to other media stocks. An investment by Malone certainly
underscores his belief in its inherent value.
</P>
<P>
   A News Corp. spokesman said: ``There is no deal now,'' adding
that he did not comment on rumors. A Liberty spokesperson declined
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   The deal fits the style and interests of both men. Murdoch has
long believed that sports is one of the four key elements in
programming, along with movies, news and children's shows, and has
been willing to spend heavily to add to his arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   He already owns the Los Angeles Dodgers, the Manchester United
soccer team in England, and has options to invest in the Los
Angeles Lakers basketball team and Los Angeles Kings hockey team.
But, he has always preferred to control his own operations and
avoid answering to partners who might hold him back from making
investments he desires.
</P>
<P>
   As for Malone, he has generally preferred to hold stakes in
programming companies that were managed by others. And when
possible, he has preferred to build a portfolio of assets in public
companies that gave Liberty both liquidity and a public valuation
for its investments.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Media, which was originally spun off from
Tele-Communications, the giant cable company, has acquired stakes
in a wide variety of media companies. It already owns 10 percent of
Time Warner as well as positions in USA Networks, Discovery
Communications, United Video Satellite and others.
</P>
<P>
   One veteran media expert quipped that Malone sees himself as the
Warren Buffett of the media industry, alluding to Buffett's
strategy of taking large passive positions in other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, when Malone agreed to sell Tele-Communications Inc.
to AT&AMP;T and took control of Liberty, it was clear that he planned
to expand it, and indeed he has been building a hefty war chest.
</P>
<P>
   That company already has $5.5 billion in cash, about $5 billion
in Sprint-PCS stock and the right to borrow up to 25 percent of its
market capitalization _ $36 billion Thursday _ without getting
permission from AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a tremendous war chest,'' said John Tinker, who follows
the company for Nationsbanc Montgomery Securities. That enormous
clout is one reason why Malone may be eyeing a larger stake in News
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership between Malone and Murdoch, called Fox Liberty
Networks, has reflected the increasing complexity of sports
programming as cable television has grown. The two companies share
ownership of 12 regional sports television networks.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, each has a 20 percent stake in Rainbow Programming,
a venture controlled by Cablevision Systems Corp. The venture owns
eight regional sports networks, the Knicks, Rangers, Madison Square
Garden, Radio City Music Hall and the Staples Center arean, which
is now being built in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   After the deal, though News Corp. will own 40 percent of the
Cablevision venture, Cablevision will still retain control.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Regional sports networks acquire rights to carry games of local
teams and integrates those games with national programming. For now
Fox Liberty Networks continues to lose money. It lost $62.1 million
last year. However it had operating income of $57.6 million and a
News Corp. spokesman noted that the bulk of the loss was
attributable to interest costs from borrowings to fund the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Murdoch's buyout of Malone was reported Thursday in The Los
Angeles Times. While Wall Street clearly expects Malone to become
more aggressive on the deal front, Murdoch may as well. Murdoch has
the right to exercise an option to purchase 40 percent of the Kings
and 9.8 percent of the Lakers. It was not clear whether the
exercise of that option would trigger ownership issues with the
league.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the 20 regional networks that are part of the deal, the
two companies also have stakes in five other networks. In these,
there are outside investors, and it was not clear Thursday whether
they were part of this transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The news Thursday pushed News Corp. stock up $1.0625 to close at
$30.56, though it has only risen 12.4 percent in the past 52 weeks
during a bull market. Liberty Media closed at 54.75, up $2.15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
