<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3082 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDENERS02-COX     04-01 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENERS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rooting in the dirt does wonders for respondents, who readily
tout benefits of their earthy passion
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ What is it with these people who can't keep their
nails clean _ who would rather plunge their bare hands into
40-pound bags of cow manure than plug in the Dirt Devil or do a
load of wash?
</P>
<P>
   People who don headlamps at 3 in the morning in search of slimy
slugs that in minutes will turn a perfect hosta leaf into a block
of Swiss cheese.
</P>
<P>
   People like Margie Archer, who swears every March she won't work
with such vengeance to cultivate a glorious garden, and already
she's going at it gangbusters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere on Earth do I feel more comfortable _ with no makeup
on, hair matted to my head, dirty old torn clothes, beat-up shoes _
than in a garden,'' said the Duluth resident, 52. ``No one ever
told me that the sweat, aches and tears of battling mosquitoes,
worms, bugs, snakes and even spiders could be so much fun!''
</P>
<P>
   Yet for Archer and most of the other 2,629 readers who responded
to The Atlanta Journal-Constitution's February survey of gardening
habits, the hobby is about far more than just growing the brightest
jonquil or juiciest tomato. It's about a passion, an addiction _
even a lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds wrote of the therapeutic benefits reaped from being
outdoors. Their gardens are gyms for those who dislike exercise,
brightly lit bars for drowning their workday stress, psychologists'
lounge chairs for coming to grips with a spouse's death.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Lee's garden in Cedartown proved a salvation after her
40-year-old son's death from brain cancer four years ago. She had
to do something. As a memorial, she placed a large birdbath with an
angel on top in the center of her yard. ``From that, many wonderful
things began to happen,'' the 74-year-old said.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and relatives brought plants and seeds. Grandchildren
donated bird feeders and wind chimes _ all in tribute to Steve Lee,
an Alpharetta (Ga.) veterinarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The garden has helped me deal with it all _ and still does,''
Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   For Wanda Jackson, gardening is a link to her mother, who gave
her dozens of plants when she moved into a new home in Kennesaw
(Ga.) two years ago. The plants now represent hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother disappeared Oct. 23, 1998. I pray for her safe
return, and I want to show her all the new things I've added to my
garden,'' wrote Jackson, 41. ``If she has gone on to heaven, I want
her to be with me in my garden and share the beauty that I learned
from her.'' Her mother's car was found abandoned, and Tennessee
authorities are investigating, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long five months,'' said Jackson, whose father
recently drove from Chattanooga to help her plant ivy _ an excuse
perhaps to get close to the missing wife and mother. ``It's amazing
what gardening can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it's the simplest rewards. ``I'm a celibate,
perimenopausal 50-year-old divorced mom of a teenage boy. I don't
drink. I don't smoke,'' wrote Janan Henry of Morningside (Ga.). ``I
dig. I push. I pull. I water. I plant, I sweat. I ache. And then
some little green frond pokes up through the dirt, and my son says,
`Mom, that's so pretty.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gardening is an icebreaker in meeting new friends, finding a
date or getting to know neighbors. In John Hampton's North Augusta,
S.C. neighborhood, exchanging vegetables, cuttings and advice has
brought families, black and white, to the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The garden talk has really helped us to become friends way
beyond the racial lines,'' said Hampton, who is black.
</P>
<P>
   That's because gardening knows no barriers among color, economic
means or age. Since the '80s, baby boomers have become the largest
group to hone in on horticulture, and as the millennium approaches,
nostalgia plays a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have been born some time during the era of James
Madison, when growing vegetables was a requirement for sustaining
life,'' wrote Rodney Petty, a Marietta middle school teacher. ``I
garden for some of the same reasons I drive a four-wheel-drive
Jeep, cut and split my own firewood, keep honeybees and sculpt
dough bowls from oak and poplar. It is important for me to know I
have this sense of independence.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, gardening is a matter of community pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my yard looking like Billy Joe Six-Pack lives
there,'' wrote George Kaulbach of Stone Mountain (Ga.). ``Second, I
hate it when my neighbors complain. Third, I have a wife. Need I
say more?''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Henderson didn't know beans about gardening until she
bought her first house in Grant Park and decided to spruce up the
yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a mattock one day and just starting digging out all this
terrible clay,'' the 34-year-old said.
</P>
<P>
   After losing her share of plants, she began to buy gardening
books and learned about amending the soil.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, Henderson, a lawyer, began to see signs of hope.
``I got so excited I couldn't figure out how I hadn't gotten into
this before,'' she said. ``Then I really got caught up in hunting
for certain colors and kinds of plants.''
</P>
<P>
   What's been most rewarding, she said, is her sudden awareness of
nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never looked at plants before, and now _ I can't help it _
I'm constantly seeing them, identifying them on walks, while
driving,'' she said. ``Once I dug up that one little corner in my
yard, I was sold.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharing is as much a part of gardening as digging, as Christine
Vogt learned over the years from ``a little old Italian lady named
Mary.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogt said the 74-year-old Lawrenceville (Ga.) resident ``runs
around wearing a dress tucked in long pants, an unbuttoned
long-sleeve shirt (none of which match), topped off with Army boots
(size 7) and a hair net that often finds its way onto a low branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary shares her garden with neighbors, sometimes dropping off
a basket for those in need, who are ill or just because. She
delivers thank you's to friends, doctors and nurses and her vet,
signed in produce, just to let them know that she appreciates their
efforts and kindness.''
</P>
<P>
   Vogt signed her tribute, ``With love to Mary, from her daughter
Christine.''
</P>
<P>
   For true gardeners, though, sharing isn't just a basket of
home-grown corn or freshly cut flowers.
</P>
<P>
   For Debbie Missroon, the sharing brought someone to fill the
void in her life after her 81-year-old grandmother died 2 1/2 years
ago. ``I suffered from depression after her death,'' said the
35-year-old Roswell resident. ``One day I was driving past a yard
that always seemed to be in bloom when I noticed the most beautiful
tree I had ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, she noticed an elderly woman pruning plants who
``really reminded me of my grandmother,'' Missroon recalled. The
woman, 93-year-old Mattie Smith, told her the plant she had admired
was an angel trumpet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I knew it, she was showing me around her yard, giving
me seeds from marigolds,'' Missroon said. ``I felt as if an angel
had sent her to me to ease the pain of losing my grandmother.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Missroon's depression began to lift. The two became
friends and now share gardening information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see her every week or spend hours with her on the
phone, but I know she's there,'' said Missroon, who is moving to
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   She's giving her surrogate grandmother some of her own plants.
``I just wanted to give something back,'' she said. ``I'm so
grateful to my `angel gardener.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
