<HEADER>
A3083 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOODFRIDAY-GARDENS02-     04-01 0607
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODFRIDAY-GARDENS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `It's become a way of life' and a $76 billion industry
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Antoinette Suarez has a dirty, expensive habit. She
has no idea how much she's invested, just that it's gotten out of
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am continually buying plants, books on plants, fertilizer
for plants, plants to go with other plants, plants for shade,
plants for sun, plants for partial shade, plants that bloom in
spring, plants that bloom in fall, plants that bloom in summer,
and, oh, yes, plants that bloom in winter,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Suarez of Atlanta is among the 70 percent of Americans who have
latched on to gardening with a grip stronger than kudzu on guy
wires, one that reaches a diverse $76 billion industry.
</P>
<P>
   She's also among the 2,630 readers who responded to The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution's February survey of gardening habits. Nearly
50 percent were between the ages of 45 and 64, and 76 percent were
female, hailing from Dalton to Valdosta.
</P>
<P>
   Some 76 percent consider themselves ``die-hard diggers,'' a
majority of whom spend from $150 to $1,000 on plants and materials
every spring.
</P>
<P>
   One-third said they devote six to 10 hours per week in the
garden, while another 33 percent spend 20 hours per week. ``That's
some heavy-duty gardening,'' said Walter Reeves, the Georgia
Extension Service's horticulture educator.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are reflective of nationwide trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is growing not just because of the flood of
households but because they're spending more and more on this
hobby,'' said Kip Creel of P K Data Systems, an Atlanta marketing
research firm that tracks national garden industry trends.
</P>
<P>
   Americans average seven to 10 hours per week gardening, Creel
said, and about 50 percent of all households hire a professional
lawn care service or landscape contractor. Wholesale nursery
revenues alone totaled $10.9 billion in 1997, up 42 percent from
1992.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest industry impact has been from baby boomers, who in
the '80s traded happy hour for happy homemaking, and the desire to
improve their surroundings outweighed a night on the town. Having
the disposable income didn't hurt either.
</P>
<P>
   For most survey participants, their big investment is a mix of
trees, shrubs, annuals and perennials, designed so there's
something in bloom every season. ``They want color longer and are
more conscious of how they can get that with trees and
perennials,'' said Pete Pike, founder of Pike Family Nurseries,
which has 25 stores in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, on another level, about 25 percent said their motivation to
garden is far greater than the desire to create something beautiful
or edible. The rewards are exercise, emotional therapy and the
opportunities for getting close to nature and improving the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This confirms gardening is a lifestyle,'' said Sherry
Loudermilk of the Georgia Green Industries Association, which
includes 850 wholesale nurseries, landscape contractors and retail
garden centers. ``It's become a way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution's gardening survey found:
</P>
<P>
   51%
</P>
<P>
   spend from $150 to $1,000 on seeds and plants each spring, and
39 percent spend a comparable amount on compost, fertilizer and
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   47%
</P>
<P>
   spend from 10 to 30 hours a week gardening each spring and
summer.
</P>
<P>
   21%
</P>
<P>
   would prefer a pile of composted cow manure to a department
store gift certificate or a night out on the town.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
