<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3087 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-01 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BOMB AND CALL IN GEORGE MITCHELL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you ever played one of those video arcade games where you
try to shoot as many targets as you can in a set period of time?
When you start such a game a little sign flashes up and asks: ``One
Player or Two?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Clinton team's approach to the Kosovo crisis reminds
me of such a game. The U.S. put a quarter in, pressed ``One
Player,'' and took aim against the Serbian armed forces.
Unfortunately, it forgot that war is an interactive game and that
somebody else was playing _ someone able to run up the score on us.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO air power has no doubt inflicted enormous damage on
the Serb army, and while the NATO allies were well-intentioned,
they clearly did not anticipate Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic's mendacity and ability to drive out thousands of ethnic
Albanians from Kosovo. In doing so, Milosevic has run up the score
on NATO and built up a huge counterpressure on the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb leader has in effect said to NATO: ``You may think you
have all the time in the world to shoot at my forces like fish in a
barrel. But time is not just on your side _ because I am saddling
you with Kosovo refugees (and now POW's) faster than you are
degrading my army. As long as you rely on air power alone, you are
a hostage to the weather and the time that air power takes to
destroy an entrenched army in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But I have no such problems. My forces rely on low-tech terror
that can force Albanians out of Kosovo, no matter what the weather,
and much faster than you can cripple me. You wanted to help the
Kosovars, well now you can _ you've got all 1.8 million of them in
your lap. I've got Kosovo and you've got the Kosovars. As they say
in the video arcade: Game Over.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO has a serious problem. All these refugees have
fundamentally changed the equation. We are losing now, folks, and
that means America needs to look at its four options in a much more
clear-eyed way.
</P>
<P>
   Option one is to bomb Serbia into the Stone Age until it accepts
the Rambouillet peace plan _ which gave the Kosovo Albanians
autonomy in Kosovo, under NATO protection, for three years and then
hope for independence. The only problem is that by bombing Serbia
into accepting Rambouillet, the U.S. is undermining any prospect
the plan could work.
</P>
<P>
   It is going to be very difficult now for Kosovo Albanians _ who
have just been expelled and savaged by the Serbs _ to return to
Kosovo and live as an autonomous community under Serb sovereignty,
even with NATO protection. It is going to be even harder now for
any Serb leader to swallow NATO troops on their soil. At best, NATO
troops would be serving as ``peacekeepers,'' not between two
contented factions, but between two factions thirsting for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Option two is to invade Kosovo with NATO ground troops, drive
out the Serbs and create an independent Kosovo-Albanian state that
would be a NATO protectorate. The human, military and diplomatic
cost of this would be enormous, and it would fracture NATO. In
victory would lie defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Option three is to declare victory and leave, while letting the
Red Cross tend to the Kosovo refugees. This would be an unthinkable
moral sellout, and it would leave floating around the Balkans an
angry, highly destabilizing refugee population.
</P>
<P>
   Option four is to intensify the bombing of the Serbs, while also
dangling before them a peace plan that Milosevic might be tempted
to accept. It would have to be a modified version of Rambouillet _
an end to the air war in return for the Serbs allowing a return of
all refugees, some form of permanent autonomy for the Kosovo
Albanians and a non-NATO observer and protection force.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovar nationalists may not like this tactic, but if it can
get the refugees back home and enable the Serbs to accept some
foreign peacekeepers in Kosovo, it would be the least bad option
and could still achieve our basic goals. We should be doing this
now: Bomb and call in George Mitchell to negotiate a solution with
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But those are our options: Beat the Serbs until they learn to
love the Kosovars. Invade Kosovo and own it forever. Cut and run
and bear the stain forever. Or bomb and talk and hope to build a
messy diplomatic solution from the ashes of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there's a fifth option: Put your hands together and pray
that the Clinton team knows something that you don't.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
