<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3092 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSONO-NATO-HNS &LR;      04-01 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSONO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURED U.S. SOLDIERS MAY FACE MILITARY TRIBUNAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-CAPTURED, KOSOVO-LEGAL and
KOSOVO-GONZALES, which will move shortly.) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Three captured U.S. Army soldiers, including one
from Texas, were displayed on Serb television Thursday, and the
official Yugoslav news service said they will face a military
tribunal, perhaps as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The servicemen were captured, apparently by Serb forces, on the
Macedonia-Yugoslavia border Wednesday during what the Defense
Department said was a routine reconnaissance mission as part of a
NATO force.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was absolutely no basis for them to be taken,''
President Clinton said in a speech to military personnel and their
families in Norfolk, Va. ``There is no basis for them to be held.
There is certainly no basis for them to be tried.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon identified the captured soldiers as Spc. Steven M.
Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville; Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of
Los Angeles; and Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths
Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO leaders said detention of the servicemen, however
unreasonable, will not deter a continued allied air assault to curb
violence by forces of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic against
ethnic Albanians in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mission I have asked our armed forces to carry out with
our NATO allies is a dangerous one,'' Clinton said. ``We will
continue to carry out our mission with determination and resolve.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana said the alliance ``remains
united and remains determined.''
</P>
<P>
   ``After one week of air operations, I am confident that we are
having a major impact on Belgrade's criminal war machine,'' Solana
said. ``The ring is closing around the Yugoslav forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen said the three captured soldiers
were being ``illegally detained'' and pledged: ``We will do
everything in our power to secure their safe return.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon described the detainees
as ``prisoners of war.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a court martial-like proceeding heightened
American outrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Such a trial is obviously ridiculous,'' said State Department
spokesman James P. Rubin. A trial, he said, ``would be in violation
of international law.''
</P>
<P>
   The report by state-run Tanjug news service quoted a judicial
officer in Pristina, the Kosovo capital, who suggested that the
initial proceeding could be like a grand jury hearing to determine
if charges should be brought against the U.S. soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   A dispute erupted over where the servicemen were picked up.
</P>
<P>
   Vuk Draskovic, Yugoslav deputy prime minister, contended the
soldiers were ``captured deeply in Serbian territory,'' but NATO
air chief David Wilby said the soldiers ``certainly were in
Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Defense Department, which had initially contended that
the three soldiers were in Macedonia, said the issue was under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Hugh Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
that after the men's Humvee was surrounded and had been fired on,
it was unclear ``whether or not they later had escaped from that
and had driven in the wrong direction or whether they were fleeing
on foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia officials said the border in the rough, hilly region
where the incident occurred was not clearly marked.
</P>
<P>
   In the NATO air assault Thursday, allied missiles knocked out a
major Danube River bridge in Novi Sad near a military warehouse.
Shipping sources told Reuters news service that shipping was halted
in both directions on the key waterway between central Europe and
the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Another Danube bridge, near Beska on the road from Belgrade to
the Hungarian border, sustained minor damage, Serb television
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the bridge attacks were intended to ``make force
mobility more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The scope and tempo of our operations are increasing all the
time,'' Solana said in Brussels. ``We are degrading (the Yugoslav
force's) ability to carry out the current acts of violence in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``The impact of our campaign will be increasingly cumulative,''
Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Cohen had ordered 13 additional U.S. F-117A stealth
fighters to the campaign against Yugoslavia. One of the planes is
to replace the plane downed over Yugoslavia on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Solana insisted the NATO goals were unchanged: halting Yugoslav
aggression and demanding a cease-fire to be policed by an alliance
force.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic said Yugoslavia was engaged in ``a just battle,
defending its citizens ... and will never give up its land and
freedom.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended against reports that the White House, in
seeking the NATO attack, had ignored reports from military planners
and intelligence sources that the assault was likely to increase
Milosevic's campaign of ethnic cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we not acted, the Serbian offensive would have been
carried out with impunity,'' Clinton said in Norfolk. ``We are
determined that it will carry a very high price indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, three trains with thousands of refugees pulled up to
the Macedonian border, reported Judith Kumin, a spokeswoman for the
U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees. Two more trains were reported
en route.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen defended the military operation from criticism, such as
the claim of Sen. Richard Lugar of Indiana, a leading Republican
spokesman on foreign policy that, ``We are losing the war.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said allied ``forces are doing a magnificent job in the
face of expected strong resistance. The president and all of his
advisers knew that achieving our military goals would be difficult,
it would take time, and it would pose a risk to NATO forces.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House also faced new calls, including one from two of
the most liberal members of Congress, to use ground forces against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Jerrold Nadler and Eliot Engel, both New York Democrats,
said in a joint statement: ``It is now clear ... that the use of
air power alone cannot and will not prevent these atrocities. Only
troops on the ground can stop the murders and crimes against
humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic met in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, with Kosovar
Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova and, according to Serb television,
agreed ``problems can be resolved successfully and long term only
through political means.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Rubin questioned whether Rugova
attended of his own free will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we have an opportunity to discuss directly with him and
make sure that he has freedom of movement and his family has
freedom of movement ... I just have no way of assessing that
situation,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied sources pointed out that the comments attributed to
Rugova contrasted with views he expressed in an interview in the
current issue of the German magazine Der Spiegel, including a call
for immediate use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO needs to give its all and if necessary threaten a
complete destruction of Serbia,'' Rugova said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and the White House rejected a call by Pope John Paul II to
halt the aerial attack in Easter week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
