<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3093 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS &LR;      04-01 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURIER, MARTIN TO CARRY US FLAG AT DAVIS CUP MATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, England _ Todd Martin told his captain, Tom
Gullikson: ``Get over it!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It'' was the hope that somehow the extremely self-centered No.
1 Pete Sampras would put himself out for a weekend and indulge in
Davis Cup for the United States against Great Britain. The
best-of-five first-round series between the original Cup
antagonists of Boston 1900 commences Friday at the National Indoor
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Since neither Sampras nor another figment of Gullikson's once
hopeful imagination, Andre Agassi, has been seen walking beside the
barge canals that snake through central Birmingham, the American
singles starters are the shopworn but historically reliable Jim
Courier and Martin, currently planetary Nos. 54 and 8. Countering
are the higher regarded Tim Henman and Greg Rusedski, Nos. 7 and
11.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the more quixotic, capricious corners of sport for a
century has been the Davis Cup, where the branding of guys with
their nationality either sears them into the trembles or heats them
into sky-high performers. Greats have fainted. Remember Sampras in
the losing 1991 final to France? Nonentities can become
kings-for-a-day like No. 285 Hugo Chapacu, beating the US for
Paraguay in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson has gotten over it, thanks to Martin and Courier. ``We
put the full-court press on Pete and Andre. Both Judy Levering (US
Tennis Association president) and I visiting them, going over the
positive aspects of playing for their country,'' he said. ``That's
never happened before, the president going to see guys, making a
personal appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The answer was no.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras said at The Lipton last week, ``Tom understands. I have
other goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson doesn't understand. He and his late twin, Tim
(Sampras's coach), would have killed to play Davis Cup themselves.
A good sport publicly about ``Pete's indifference to the Cup,''
Gullikson is hurt. He told a friend, ``How can Pete look at me and
not see my brother, who would have been really upset about his not
playing?''
</P>
<P>
   It's a free country. Sampras isn't unpatriotic. But he is
un-Pete-riotic for a guy who says he reveres tradition, idolizes
Rod Laver, and wants to be considered the all-time champ. Laver,
acknowledging Sampras's brilliance, merely rolls his eyes when the
subject of Pete and Davis Cup arises.
</P>
<P>
   Time to move on. Martin shook friend Gullikson out of his
revery, expressing some tough love: ``Those guys don't want to
play. Courier and I do. We're committed. We're gonna win for you''
_ possibly saving Gullikson's job in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is better to have guys who do want it, instead of twisting
arms,'' Gullikson concedes. ``Todd and Jim are cool under pressure,
and this is the highest form of tennis pressure. They've been here,
been on winning teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, Courier, who leads off against Henman, and helped win
the Cups of 1992 over Switzerland and 1995 over Russia, has never
played in a losing series. The US has been 12-0 with him in the
lineup. Martin, at 6 feet 6 inches the tallest American Davis Cup
participant ever, has a tall order in 6-4 fireballer Rusedski, but
has always played better on the road, a cog in the Moscow victory.
His maybe problem: abdominal muscles strained at the Australian
about which he's ``cautiously optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you not want to play for your country?'' is as far as
Martin will go in badmouthing Sampras. ``We're playing for
ourselves, our team, and our country. I don't know of a better
combination. For me, Davis Cup _ losses as well as wins _ has meant
more than any other big victories I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Courier seconds the motion, and grows chilly when anybody calls
this the B team or the jayvees. ``We are the team, America's team,
and we came to win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though no longer the player who stood No. 1 in 1992, winner of
four majors, Courier said, ``I'm better than I have been in a long
time.'' True. ``Todd and I are capable of beating these guys. We
have beaten them.'' My hunch is they will again, 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   But if they are capable _ despite local bookies' naysaying,
7-to-4 for the home side _ it will spoil a grand party to be played
out before 9,400 in the long sold-out building, and the rest of
Britain hanging on the telly.
</P>
<P>
   While this is hardly a breath-holder back in the Colonies, it's
one of the bigger British sporting occasions in 20 years. Not since
rookie John McEnroe beat the Brits in the 1978 final at Mission
Hills, Calif., has Davis Cup meant so much in this land where the
game was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we've been laughingstocks in tennis, and that's been
an incentive for me,'' said the slim, stylish 24-year-old Henman.
``We were rock-bottom when Greg and I joined the team in 1995 so
this has been a mission for us. The Americans may have been around
in Davis Cup, but we haven't. There's an edge on it for us. Sure
we're nervous, but we've got a lot of people behind us. Of course
this is a very difficult first round.''
</P>
<P>
   Choke or charge? That's the question.
</P>
<P>
   After years in the boonies, the Brits have worked their way back
from the third division sub-basement to the 16 country World Group
from which they were booted in 1992. Their captain, David Lloyd,
said justifiably, ``We should have been seeded as the Americans
are, and not be facing them at the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he said with a smile, ``it may be kismet. How nice in
this 100th year of Davis Cup to have the two teams that started it
going head to head. It might not have happened if we'd been seeded.
We're happy to play the Yanks. We haven't beaten them since 1935.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, a British team showed up at Boston's Longwood Cricket
Club to challenge for the sterling crock donated by a Harvard kid,
Dwight Davis. Davis, the playing captain (well, it was his Cup),
and chums bageled the visitors. Few beyond The Bean and London
noticed. But presently the entire world (129 countries this year)
was in on it.
</P>
<P>
   The US returns to Longwood (July 16-18) either very much in the
quarterfinal chase for the Cup _ or in a last-gasp battle to avoid
the pits of relegation that Britain has just escaped. B team or the
team? Birmingham, site of James Watt's inventing the steam engine
in 1769, is where the US will pick up steam or run out of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
