<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATM fees in Georgia on par with nation's
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bank customers in Georgia pay an average of $2.53 in
automated teller machine fees, mirroring national figures in a
study released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Public Interest Research Group study was released on
the third anniversary of the decision by the two largest automated
teller networks _ owned by Visa and MasterCard _ to allow banks and
other ATM operators to impose surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   Customers who use another bank's ATM often end up paying two
surcharges: one to the bank operating the ATM, plus a fee to their
own banks.
</P>
<P>
   The study said the national average for surcharges is $2.57.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia banks' ATM fees ``reflect a disturbing trend that
virtually all consumers in Georgia are being charged twice to use
ATMs once,'' said Bob Pregulman, PIRG's Southern field director.
</P>
<P>
   In general, larger multistate banks charge higher fees.
</P>
<P>
   Credit unions and smaller, local banks tend to have lower ATM
fees, Pregulman said.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank and SunTrust banks charge noncustomers $1.50 to use
their ATMs, spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   The study found more than 90 percent of banks charge people to
use their ATM machines if they aren't customers of the bank, up
from 71 percent a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's bankers say the surcharges are outweighed by the
24-hour convenience and are needed to make the machines profitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, consumers have more choices than ever to get cash when
and where they want it,'' Donald Ogilvie, executive vice president
of the American Bankers Association, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said the surcharges ``have led to an explosion of new ATMs in
places that previously couldn't support them due to low usage, such
as theaters, hospitals and neighborhood markets.''
</P>
<P>
   The survey by PIRG covered 336 banks and 31 credit unions in 23
states and the District of Columbia, out of some 9,000 institutions
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
