<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Latino group stresses need for participation in census
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Stand up and be counted in census 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative _ remaining undercounted _ could result in the
loss of some of the economic gains Latinos have made in recent
years, said Antonia Hernandez, president and general counsel of the
Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund. ``We cannot
afford to be undercounted,'' Hernandez said Thursday at the second
annual regional Latino Summit.
</P>
<P>
   The one-day summit, organized by the Latin American Association
in Atlanta, was designed to help companies, government officials
and educators reach and understand the growing numbers of Latino
consumers. More than 250 people attended.
</P>
<P>
   Census figures help companies determine marketing strategies,
hiring, what services are needed and where. In particular, the
numbers help corporations ``realize the economic power of the
Latino community,'' Hernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   But she acknowledged some Latinos' wariness of the Immigration
and Naturalization Service hinders the effort to count them for the
census. The result is companies don't get an accurate estimate of
the size of the Latino market.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez estimates Latinos were underrepresented by 5 percent
in the 1990 census because of such fears. The summit covered such
topics as marketing to the Latino community, how to recruit and
retain Latino employees, the impact on the community health care
system and how to improve communication between the metro area's
ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Jose de la Cruz, a human resource executive with Pfizer Inc.,
said most companies are still woefully behind in managing
diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, companies are just talking,'' de la Cruz
said. ``Even those who have made great strides have a long way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, progressive companies are hiring Latino
recruiters and offering bonuses for employee referrals. De la Cruz
suggested going to churches, flea markets, community-based and
Latino professional organizations, and using radio advertising in
Latino media to reach potential employees.
</P>
<P>
   Getting tips like those are among the reasons Matt Reyer,
associate director of human resources for Kraft Food Inc., attended
the summit at the Swissotel. Learning ways to recruit Latino
workers was also a high priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly part of our overall business strategy,'' Reyer
said. ``We value diversity, and we understand that we need a
diverse work force to accomplish our goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers say they have had such an overwhelming response to
the summits that they plan to have a two-day program in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
