<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELLPHONES-SURVEY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cell phone customer base up 25% in year
 &HT;    By Bill Husted and Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The cellular phone _ a status symbol restricted to a
handful of executives and salespeople just a decade ago _ has
become standard equipment these days, especially in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association
released Thursday says the largest one-year cellular subscriber
growth ever was recorded in 1998. There are now 69,209,321 cellular
customers, a gain of 13,897,028 over 1997 and a 25 percent
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The association does not break out cellular statistics by city
or region, but almost all experts agree Atlanta is one of the
nation's top five cities when it comes to cellular telephone
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Every third person within the reach of metro Atlanta is a
subscriber to wireless service, according to Lee Bailey, a
consultant with the Strategis Group, a Washington, D.C.-based
consulting and research company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic growth and cell phone penetration generally go
together,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the top five _ a group he said was too close to
rank _ are Orlando, Fla., Charlotte, N.C., Hartford, Conn., and El
Paso, Texas, Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to sheer numbers _ and not just market penetration
_ Atlanta remains in the top 10, according to Tracy Ford, editor of
RCR magazine, a trade publication covering the wireless industry.
Roughly 1.4 million people in metro Atlanta have wireless phones,
according to projections based on RCR's 1998 studies.
</P>
<P>
   Some previous projections of Atlanta put the penetration of
wireless use at better than 40 percent. However, estimates of
wireless use _ especially for a particular city or region _ tend to
vary, depending on who is doing the estimating. Nationally, the
penetration of wireless is about 25 percent, according to the
association.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wheeler of the association said there was ``a tremendous
surge in subscribership during the last half of 1998. During the
last six months of the year, more than 45,500 individuals signed up
for service each day.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, there were just about 2 million cellular customers
in the entire nation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
