<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELTA-PRICELINE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Delta hits Internet jackpot
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The latest red-hot Internet stock, Priceline.com, is
making a fortune for Delta Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   Delta this winter became the biggest airline yet to offer seats
through the online booking site, whose pitchman is former ``Star
Trek'' star William Shatner.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Atlanta-based Delta got warrants to buy 18.6 million
Priceline.com Inc. shares at 93 cents each.
</P>
<P>
   The stock went public this week in one of the hottest initial
offerings ever. It hit the market at $16 and zoomed as high as $92
before settling back. It closed Thursday at $80.50, down $2.37 1/2.
</P>
<P>
   That makes Delta's warrants, which work like stock options,
worth $1.48 billion on paper.
</P>
<P>
   The warrants are exercisable only when Delta meets certain
booking volume targets or in seven years, whichever comes first,
Priceline.com financial filings show. So Delta's actual gain
depends on its participation and Priceline.com's future success.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Internet companies, the Stamford, Conn.-based firm has
yet to make money, posting a $114 million loss last year.
</P>
<P>
   The site invites air travelers to name their price for flights.
It then tries to match the bids with seats made available at a
discount by participating airlines. To generate initial business,
the firm has sold many bookings below what it pays the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But volume is rising. The site handled 103,000 bookings in
January and February vs. 135,000 in the previous nine months. It
also sells hotel rooms, new cars and mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   Investors seem to believe the company's early market position
will pay off as e-commerce matures.
</P>
<P>
   The airline service works best for fliers with flexible
schedules who missed advance-purchase deadlines and want to avoid
high walk-up fares. The airlines get revenue for seats they don't
expect to sell otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   To discourage heavy use by business travelers, which would
dilute the airlines' most lucrative passenger base, bookings are
nonrefundable and don't earn frequent flier points.
</P>
<P>
   Other carriers involved are Northwest, TWA, America West and
Midway, along with numerous foreign airlines. Delta is the only one
with such a potentially lucrative stock stake.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com founder Jay Walker _ himself sitting on a $5
billion stake after the IPO _ said the deal was worth it to entice
a carrier as big as Delta.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys took a brilliant risk in joining with an unknown
Internet company,'' said Walker. ``They said if they were going to
do it they also wanted to participate on the equity side.''
</P>
<P>
   A Delta spokeswoman declined to comment on the financial
arrangement but said the carrier is ``very satisfied'' with its
participation in Priceline.com thus far.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
