A3104 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISS-STOCKS02-COX     04-01 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISS-STOCKS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISS Group splitting its stock 2-for-1
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ISS Group, a network security software company,
announced a 2-for-1 split of its common stock Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The split, approved by the ISS board this week, takes effect
when the stock market closes May 19. ISS shareholders of record as
of May 5 will receive one additional share for each share owned.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Macchia, ISS chief financial officer, said the company had
been looking at a stock split for a while. ISS was one of the stock
market's stronger performers last year.
</P>
<P>
   The split, Macchia said, indicates the board believes in the
company's strategic direction and its prospects for future strong
performance.
</P>
<P>
   After a second public offering early last month at $59, ISS
shares have climbed to close Thursday at $79.50.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lower share price makes it more accessible to potential
investors who often like to buy smaller blocks,'' he said. ``It
makes it more affordable to those investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Macchia said last month's secondary offering of 2.4 million
shares of ISS stock was an effort to increase the number of large
institutions investing in ISS by making a larger number of shares
available, he said.
</P>
<P>
   About 19 million ISS Group shares are on the market. About 9
million of those are held by venture capital partners or ISS
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 10 million shares held by the public, 70 percent to 80
percent are held by institutions, which are considered more stable
than individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   ISS founder and Chief Technology Officer Christopher Klaus is
the largest single ISS shareholder, with 3.1 million shares,
representing about 17 percent of the shares outstanding. The
25-year-old Klaus' stake was worth about $246.5 million, based on
Thursday's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   ISS makes and markets a group of adaptive network security
software products. The products detect, respond to and monitor
intrusions to a computer network. ISS is the market leader, but the
market is a nascent one.
</P>
<P>
   ISS has yet to make a profit. In the calendar year that ended in
December, ISS lost $4 million, or 28 cents a share, on revenue of
$35.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   The quarter before, ISS lost $791,000, or 5 cents a share.
Without a one-time charge of $802,000 tied to the purchases of
March Information Systems and DbSecure, ISS would have turned its
first profit, $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ISS earnings for the quarter ending March 31 are due to be
released April 21.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
