<HEADER>
A3108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YAHOO02-COX     04-01 0648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAHOO02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yahoo! purchase prepares it for high-speed users
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Yahoo!, the No. 1 search engine and portal site on the
Web, took a giant step toward preparing for the broadband future
Thursday with the formal announcement of an all-stock deal _
estimated to be worth about $5.7 billion _ to buy multimedia audio
and video company Broadcast.com.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to close at the end of Yahoo!'s third
quarter ending Sept. 30 and is subject to the usual regulatory
approvals and the approval of Broadcast.com shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Mallett, Yahoo! chief operating officer, said in a
conference call that the company had owned an equity stake in
Broacast.com since 1997. Dallas-based Broadcast.com will remain a
stand-alone company called Yahoo! Broadcast Services.
</P>
<P>
   The Broadcast Services unit will continue to produce live audio
and video events for consumers and commercial clients. The
Broadcast.com management team will remain in place with Chief
Executive Officer Todd Wagner reporting to Mallett.
</P>
<P>
   For Yahoo!, already a popular destination for those with
high-speed access through the At Home and Road Runner network,
Broadcast.com's multimedia will make the site compelling in the
high-speed world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rapid shift up and to the right for multimedia
content,'' Mallett said. ``It puts us in the position to define the
future. The demand for broadcast services are clearly on the
rise.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallett also said Yahoo! will continue to remain an independent
aggregator of Web products and won't stake a claim to any
particular high-speed platform such as DSL access over phone lines
or cable television modems. ``Distribution continues to be
important for us _ but we know nothing is locked up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mallett said the decision to acquire Broadcast.com is based on
Yahoo!'s strategy of acquiring ``best of breed'' companies in any
given area. He said Broadcast.com had positioned itself as a leader
in multimedia. ``This will become even more important as broadband
access grows,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! plans to include multimedia in its news, sports, shopping
and financial areas as well as offer multimedia advertising
opportunities to its advertisers. Both Mallett and Wagner said they
were excited about the possibilities of bringing multimedia to
consumers as well as advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing Yahoo!'s potential broadband strategy, Mallett said
the Broadcast.com deal uniquely positions Yahoo! for today's
broadband customer. Broadcast.com was developed for the
slower-speed connections of dial-up customers, and its technology
will only improve as more and more consumers eventually make the
move to the higher speeds offered by broadband.
</P>
<P>
   However, Mallett stressed that multimedia content will be just
one component of the Yahoo! service. ``Consumers are going to
expect integrated components,'' he said, ``and we can deliver them
in multiple facets. Sometimes you want a quick check-in of scores
or stocks, and sometimes you want video of a local news event. It's
about today and setting ourselves up to be in a good position for
tomorrow. Broadcast.com understands the world of rich media
content.''
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo! ``wants to be the only place you need to go for anything
and everything you need on the Web,'' said Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
analyst Henry Blodget.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com, with its combination of video streaming for
business and its consumer events such as live concerts and the
infamous Victoria's Secret fashion show, is already available to
workplace users accessing the Web through high-speed T1 lines.
``Our ability to reach more people during the day than traditional
media is now even stronger,'' Wagner said. ``We can scale our
business immediately to reach new users.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
