<SLUG> BC-BOX-OFFICE-MIDWEEK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISUAL THRILLS, MARKETING SAVVY PROPEL `MATRIX' TO RECORD OPENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ First-day grosses of ``The Matrix'' smashed a
6-year-old record with $4.8 million at 2,704 theaters on Wednesday
as the science-fiction thriller dominated the nation's box office.
</P>
<P>
   The Warner Bros. release, featuring never-before-seen special
effects and starring Keanu Reeves as the leader of a rebellion
against computers, opened Wednesday to take advantage of spring
break for many teen and young adult moviegoers. Distribution chief
Dan Fellman said Thursday that exit polls showed strong positive
response from audiences, who were mostly male.
</P>
<P>
   ``Young people say the movie is mind-blowing and the special
effects are a cross between `Terminator' and `Blade Runner,' ''
Fellman said. ``We're extremely excited about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix,'' which has received mixed reviews, easily broke
the $2.9 million mark for an Easter week Wednesday opening, set in
1993 by Paramount's ``Indecent Proposal.'' About 145 theaters will
be added today.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bucksbaum, president of the Reel Source forecasting
service, credited the studio for a strong trailer, smart scheduling
and offering a unique look at virtual reality. ``There has not been
a hard action film aimed at young men since `Enemy of the State,'
so there's not a lot of competition and the effects are very
unique,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing a distant second on Wednesday was Disney's opening of
teen-comedy ``10 Things I Hate About You,'' loosely based on
Shakespeare's ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' with $1.2 million at
2,271 theaters. Paramount will open ``The Out-of-Towners,'' a Steve
Martin-Goldie Hawn comedy, today at 2,102 theaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Matrix'' may energize overall box office before May 19's
opening of ``Star Wars Episode 1: Phantom Menace.'' Year-to-date
domestic grosses have hit $1.3 billion, down 8 percent from the
``Titanic''-driven equivalent period of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
