<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPTURED-SOLDIERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURED US SOLDIERS FACE MILITARY COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Struggling on the ninth day of NATO airstrikes to
define an increasingly blighted military campaign, President
Clinton issued another impassioned appeal for support of the Kosovo
effort Thursday, at the same time strongly denouncing Serb forces
for the capture of three US soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials were investigating whether the Army unit had
accidentally crossed into Yugoslav territory on Wednesday during
training exercises in Macedonia before coming under attack.
Yugoslav officials, branding the men ``invaders,'' said they would
be hauled before a military court Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But despite unsettling video shots of the bruised American
soldiers on Serbian TV _ alongside images of thousands of ethnic
Albanian refugees continuing to flood from the Kosovo capital,
Pristina, into neighboring regions _ both US and NATO officials
denied accusations the mission was veering off an already
ill-defined course. Clinton, speaking at the Norfolk Naval Station
in Virgina, justified the campaign in dramatic, domino-effect
terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something we are doing to try to avoid in the 21st
century the kind of widespread war, large American casualties and
heartbreak that we saw too much of in the century we are about to
leave,'' Clinton said. ``So this is not just about a small piece of
the Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   The public entreaty came as the Pentagon announced plans to
launch a new round of fighter planes to Kosovo. Thirteen F-117A
stealth fighters, including a replacement for the F-117 downed last
week, will join the more than 200 US planes already in service in
Yugoslavia, defense officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier USS Theodore Roosevelt was also on its way toward
the Adriatic Sea, equipped with some 70 planes that are likely to
join the battle over Yugoslavia in the coming days. Three other
ships from the Roosevelt battle group _ a Navy cruiser, destroyer
and attack submarine, each capable of firing Tomahawk missiles _
have been authorized to take part as well, an official told the
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, NATO airstrikes continued through the day and
into the night, with defense officials reporting a new batch of
destroyed ground targets, including a fuel storage center and a
Yugoslav army unit in central Kosovo. A key bridge over the Danube
River in the town of Novi Sad was also blown apart, and its debris
created a traffic jam in the important commercial route to the
Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Such dual-use targets important for both commercial and military
use are expected to play an increasing role in NATO strategy,
Senator John W. Warner, chairman of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, said after meeting with military officials Thursday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can expect in the next 24 to 72 hours a broadening
of targets,'' Warner said, ``namely, targets used for both the
military and possibly some civilian use, like bridges and the
like.''
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO airstrikes began nine days ago, about 180,000 ethnic
Albanians have fled the country _ at least 100,000 to Albania,
31,000 to Macedonia and 30,000 to Montenegro, said UN spokesman
Fred Eckhard.
</P>
<P>
   Trains packed with 10,000 refugees arrived on the Macedonia
border, where UN officials described scenes of panic.
</P>
<P>
   The captured Army unit, based in Skopje, Macedonia, had been on
a training mission with two other Humvees near the border of
Yugoslavia at approximately 3 p.m. local time Wednesday. The three
men _ Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.,
Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles, and Spc. Steven
M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas _ detoured from the group on
a civilian road, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, they were surrounded by small-arms fire. After
frantically radioing, ``They're all around us... We can't get
out,'' according to a Pentagon transcript, the patrol fell silent.
By the time NATO and local police forces launched a massive hunt,
the three had disappeared into the rugged terrain, presumably taken
at gunpoint by a Serb or Yugoslav force.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav Deputy Prime Minister Yuk Draskovic said the troops
tried to fend off their captors, saying they ``tried to fight
physically before being captured.'' Black bruises and facial cuts
on all three were the result of that tussle, not later abuse by
Serb troops, Draskovic said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was notified Wednesday afternoon of a possible capture,
just before taping a TV interview. He he did not mention the
missing soldiers in the CBS interview, but he did voice opposition
to sending in ground troops, saying he was worried about ``the
prospect of never being able to get them out.'' Pentagon officials
released news of the missing men several hours later, when it was
clear the search mission had all but failed.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, after images of the battered soldiers had been beamed
across Serbian TV, Clinton voiced outrage at their capture: ``There
was absolutely no basis for them to be taken. There is no basis for
them to be held. There is certainly no basis for them to be
tried.''
</P>
<P>
   After initially saying the men had been ``illegally detained,''
Pentagon officials upgraded their status, placing them in the
category of prisoners of war, which means their treatment will be
governed by the Geneva convention of 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Under the treaty, POWs must be treatedly humanely by their
captors, who can be tried as war criminals if they do not comply.
POWs are also required only to hand over their name, rank, serial
number and date of birth, and can be held captive until the
conflict ends.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said POWs are not required
to stand trial under any circumstances, and in responding to
Yugoslav comments that the prisoners will appear in court, he said
defense officials are ``outraged by that.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said: ``President Milosevic should make no mistake:
We will hold him and his government responsible for their safety
and their well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of the capture, Serbian TV showed footage of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic meeting with Ibrahim Rugova,
a leader of the ethnic Albanian majority. It was unclear whether
Rugova appeared with Milosevic voluntarily, and there were no
reports the two had reached an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, leaders from several corners of the world stepped up
their pleas for the bombings to end. Russian leaders, who are in
the process of dispatching a warship to the Mediterranean, demanded
an emergency meeting of the Group of Eight industrialized nations,
with the unlikely hope of pushing a diplomatic exit strategy. Other
G-8 nations did not agree to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, Pope John Paul II repeated his plea for a weeklong
cease-fire starting Easter Sunday. In Boston, Cardinal Bernard Law
said he and the seven other US Roman Catholic cardinals were urging
Clinton and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to agree to a
ceasefire and return to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rhetoric and actions of war will not bring all the parties
to a negotiating table without further, incalculable loss,'' Law
said.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO and the Clinton administration remained steadfast in
its refusal to consider a break in the airstrikes, pointing to a
broken string of promises by Milosevic during his decade-long
diplomatic history. Instead, Clinton dispatched Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott to the neighboring countries to check on their
stability and continued his own efforts in selling the mission back
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we can't respond to every tragedy in every corner of the
world. But just because we can't do everything for everyone doesn't
mean that, for the sake of consistency, we should do nothing for no
one,'' Clinton said to the military families in Norfolk. ``We've
been doing this for seven days now, just seven days. Our pilots
have performed bravely and well in the face of dangerous conditions
and often abysmal weather. But we must be determined and patient.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 2103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
