<HEADER>
A3119 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GONZALES-ART-H     04-01 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GONZALES-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS OF CAPTURED TEXAS SOLDIER WARN YUGOSLAVIA NOT TO HARM SON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Photo available on NYT database) 
 
(Eds.: Also see: KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-CAPTURED, KOSOVO-LEGAL and
KOSOVO-NATO.) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
and KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ &UR;  &LR;  The parents of U.S. Spc. Steven M.
Gonzales, one of three American soldiers captured by Serb forces,
faced cameras _ and the world _ Thursday to warn Yugoslavia not to
harm their son.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to consider the consequences very, very carefully,''
Rosie Gonzales said in addressing the ominous pledge to try the
captive soldiers in military court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven and these other two soldiers are not criminals and
should not be dealt with as criminals,'' she said, fighting back
tears. ``They are innocent young men over there as a duty to their
country, and it's just not right.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. servicemen, part of a United Nations peacekeeping
force, were captured Wednesday after they were surrounded by
Serbian forces as they patrolled the Macedonia-Yugoslavia border.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has condemned the planned military trial, set
to begin Friday, as a violation of international treaties.
</P>
<P>
   In a 40-minute news conference at Texas Department of Criminal
Justice headquarters, Rosie and Gilbert Gonzales, both prison
system employees, described the relief they felt when they saw a
televised video of their son and the other captives, Staff Sgt.
Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles and Staff Sgt. Christopher J.
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were thrilled,'' the soldier's mother said. ``We had been
informed that he was missing, but we didn't know anything at all.
It was a great relief.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bittersweet relief,'' added his father, alluding to
the apparent beating the captives suffered at the hands of the
Serbs. ``He looked roughed up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huntsville soldier's parents said he had been aware of the
danger in his military assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it in-depth,'' said Gilbert Gonzales, who
works in TDCJ's classification division.
</P>
<P>
   But though the young man discussed his desire for a military
career before dropping out of Texas A&AMP;M University in 1996, his
father admitted he still was perplexed by the decision. Although
the elder Gonzales' uncle was awarded a Purple Heart for service
during World War II, he said his family has no military tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went back and forth about it,'' Rosie Gonzales said. ``We
were opposed to it. But he said the big thing was the
opportunities, the travel, the acquired experiences he would not
have otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales enlisted in September 1996 and re-enlisted for two more
years in 1998. He was deployed to Germany in February 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie Gonzales said she last spoke with her son Feb. 21, three
days before he shipped out for Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very, very sad,'' Rosie Gonzales said. ``But he's a
true Christian and a strong person _ stronger even than we are. I
think he will deal with it very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales is the eldest of the couple's three sons. Andrew, 13,
is a middle-school student; Josh, 8, is in elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   As Gonzales' parents spoke with the media, TDCJ workers tied
oversized yellow ribbons to the iron railing in front of The Walls
Unit.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood around the Gonzales' mobile home also was
adorned with yellow ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to show support, for them to know that our
thoughts and prayers are with them,'' said neighbor Doug
Williamson. ``These are simple reminders that they're not the only
ones pulling for him to come home.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Gonzales' friends and former classmates were shocked to
learn what had happened to the popular young man universally
described as bright, athletic and funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of those kids you went out and recruited to be in
your class,'' said Palestine High School science teacher Andy
Jones, who taught Gonzales chemistry and physics. ``You wanted a
whole class of students like him.''
</P>
<P>
   A soccer player and member of the school's cross-country team,
Gonzales was vice president of the National Honor Society, and was
on the school science team that won first place in the district in
1995, according to his former teachers.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating 10th in a class of 220, he attended Texas A&AMP;M
University in College Station, where he planned to major in
engineering, former classmates added. He dropped out of college
after his freshman year to earn money to pay the remainder of his
college bills. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Kelly Williams, a former high school classmate and now a senior
in marine biology at A&AMP;M's Galveston campus, was one of the first
to alert family and friends about Gonzales' capture when she saw
the televised reports. Although authorities had not yet released
the identity of the soldiers, Williams had no doubt about Gonzales.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to wiggle his ears for us and make us laugh,'' she
said. ``I recognized him immediately, because his ears were
wiggling as he talked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the scariest feeling I think I ever had,'' she added.
``We're thousands of miles away and there's nothing we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond his family, perhaps the most concerned about Gonzales is
the soldier's boyhood friend, Tommy Russell. Friends since the
fourth grade and just six days apart in age, they joined the Army
in September 1996 under the buddy system.
</P>
<P>
   Russell talked Gonzales into joining the Army when both faced
financially tight times trying to pay for college, said Russell's
mother, Debbie McKinney of Palestine.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty upset, more in shock,'' said McKinney, who
talked with her son _ who is stationed in Germany _ by phone
Thursday morning. ``He feels responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her son's unit is on alert in Germany, ready to be sent
to Kosovo on a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's ready to go over there now and fight,'' McKinney said.
``He wants to go get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
