<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS HAVE VAUGHN, BUT HE'LL NEED HELP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Angels have experienced enough highs and lows to last a
season _ and opening day isn't until Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life with the Angels, who opened camp with optimism only
to be forced to realize that it's never easy in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   The signing of free-agent first baseman Mo Vaughn to a six-year,
$80 million contract on Nov. 25 started the excitement. Then they
signed free-agent pitcher Tim Belcher to a two-year, $10.2 million
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Those two additions to a team that had a healthy Tim Salmon, Jim
Edmonds, Gary DiSarcina, Darin Erstad, Garret Anderson, Chuck
Finley, Todd Greene and Troy Percival had the Angels thinking about
October and playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Then reality hit. On Feb. 21 _ days before position players were
required to report to spring training _ shortstop DiSarcina was
struck by coach George Hendrick's fungo bat, breaking a bone in
DiSarcina's left forearm.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, DiSarcina was expected to miss four to six weeks and
be ready sometime in April. A week before opening day, an
examination showed the bone had not healed to expectations and
surgery was recommended. DiSarcina, the club's most valuable player
in 1998, will miss three to four months.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Sheets, acquired in a trade with the Padres, will be the
Angels' opening-day shortstop. He's no DiSarcina, but the Angels
still have reason to think they can improve upon consecutive
second-place finishes.
</P>
<P>
   A lineup of Erstad, Edmonds, Vaughn, Salmon, Anderson and Greene
taking up the first six spots in the batting order is imposing. And
it is Vaughn in the heart of the order _ and clubhouse _ that is
expected to make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these years we've been undermanned, but we were still
right there at the end,'' said Percival, who had 42 saves last
season. ``We've been one player away. If we make a deal, it might
put us over the top. Well, we've made that deal. Now I guess the
pressure's on us.''
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Vaughn gives the Angels a definitive leader. He
was the American League MVP in 1995. He's hit 40 or more homers in
a season twice in his career, while no Angel _ present or past _
has ever hit 40.
</P>
<P>
   But Vaughn can't _ and won't _ do it alone. He's not the savior,
manager Terry Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say this is something we had to have,'' said Collins,
about to begin his third season as the club's manager. ``But it's
part of the total package. He knows what it takes to win and
demands it from everybody around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Those around Vaughn are plenty solid.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a trade, the Angels will go forward with their outfield
rotation, alternating one of the four as the designated hitter.
Anderson is the wild card because of his ability to play all three
outfield positions. He'll get the most starts at DH.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon (right field) and Edmonds (center) won't be moved around.
Erstad primarily will play in left.
</P>
<P>
   On the infield, Vaughn will man first. Randy Velarde, although
36, is in great shape and will handle second base. This week's
trade of Dave Hollins means the time is now for 22-year-old Troy
Glaus at third base. Glaus has hit well this spring and is good
with the glove.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Walbeck, Charlie O'Brien and Greene will share the catching
duties, providing a mix of offense and defense.
</P>
<P>
   As it is most years with the Angels, it's not offense that
causes Collins to run for the antacid. The team's success _ and
hopes of surpassing the Texas Rangers and holding off the Seattle
Mariners in the AL West _ hinges on the arms of its pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Belcher to the starting rotation gives the
Angels a solid top three when joined with Finley and Ken Hill,
who's coming off surgery. The Angels need No.4 starter Steve Sparks
and No.5 starter Omar Olivares to produce like they did last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have three very good No.2-type guys,'' Collins
said of Finley, Belcher and Hill. ``You're talking about
durability, guys that give you innings. That means a lot. All three
guys can keep us from having losing streaks.''
</P>
<P>
   With the scarcity of pitching these days _ Texas failed to land
a No.1 starter in the offseason and Seattle lost its ace, Randy
Johnson, last year and has remade its nuclear bullpen _ that may be
enough to advance to the playoffs for the first time since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   A strength of the pitching staff is the bullpen, which is
anchored by Percival. Shigetoshi Hasegawa has become Percival's top
set-up man. Former Royal Mike Magnante joins Mike Holtz as the
lefties. Ex-Cardinal Mark Petkovsek _ who can also start, if needed
_ is another newcomer to the staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the guys stay healthy, we're going to win, we're going
to the playoffs,'' Salmon said before DiSarcina's latest setback.
``I don't think this team will finish second. We're that kind of
team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
