<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3122 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-LEGAL-HNS &LR;      04-01 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LEGAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OF LEGALISMS RAGES OVER CAPTURED U.S. SOLDIERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Also see: KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-CAPTURED, KOSOVO-GONZALES
and KOSOVO-NATO.) 
 
By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The capture of three U.S. soldiers Wednesday by
Serbian forces has ignited a debate over legal semantics between
the United States and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon on Thursday called Spc. Steven M. Gonzales and
Staff Sgts. Andrew A. Ramirez and Christopher J. Stone ``prisoners
of war.'' But Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has refused to
call them war prisoners, saying Yugoslavia has not declared war on
the United States or its allies.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has threatened to put the three men on trial as early
as Friday, but has not said what the charges would be.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging in the balance in this battle of legalisms is the
responsibility that Milosevic has under international law for the
captives' safety.
</P>
<P>
   By calling the three Americans prisoners of war, the United
States has insisted that Yugoslavia comply with the Geneva
Convention, a 1949 international agreement that applies rules to
the conduct of war. The accord prohibits captors from mistreating,
even insulting, prisoners of war, and requires that injured and
sick captives receive medical care.
</P>
<P>
   The convention also requires that prisoners placed on trial have
an opportunity to present a defense and be represented by a
``qualified advocate or counsel.'' Prisoners are obliged to provide
only their first and last names, ranks, dates of birth and serial
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But by classifying the servicemen as war prisoners, the United
States has also given Yugoslavia legal authority to hold the
soldiers until the armed conflict ends, said international law
expert Scott Silliman, a Duke University law professor.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's classification of the three soldiers as prisoners
of war followed Defense Secretary William Cohen's description of
them earlier Thursday as ``illegal detainees.``
</P>
<P>
   As illegal detainees, Yugoslavia would have been obligated to
release them immediately. In addition, Milosevic would have had no
legal authority to investigate the soldiers' activities or to put
them on trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider them to be prisoners of war and covered by the
Geneva Convention,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said several
hours after Cohen's comments about detainee status.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's updated classification removed a seeming
contradiction in the way the United States wanted the servicemen to
be treated. Even as Cohen declined to call the three men prisoners
of war, he and State Department spokesman James Rubin insisted that
Yugoslavia extend Geneva Convention protections to the captives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're prisoners, clearly,'' Rubin said. ``We're not in a
state of war, but nevertheless, the international lawyers advise me
that the requirements that they be treated humanely, that they get
the necessary medical attention, that they're protected from any
form of coercion, that they get the adequate food and clothing,
that they get access by ... the International Committee of the Red
Cross still pertain.``
</P>
<P>
   Silliman agreed with the State Department that Milosevic has a
duty to safeguard the Americans. He said the captives are ``at the
very least'' protected by the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The convention protects the three men, even though the United
States has not declared war, because it applies to members of armed
forces not only in war but in the wider category of armed conflict,
added Silliman, executive director of Duke's Center on Law, Ethics
and National Security.
</P>
<P>
   The professor also said that the Pentagon and State Department
had a very strong argument that the captives were illegal
detainees, not prisoners of war. The soldiers, arguably, were not
combatants but part of a U.N. peacekeeping force to protect
Macedonia from the spread of the Yugoslav conflict, Silliman said.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. peacekeepers operating under orders not to fire except in
self-defense are not considered combatants under international law,
he added.
</P>
<P>
   That peace effort officially expired Feb. 28, after China vetoed
a U.N. Security Council proposal to extend the mission, but the UN
flag under which the soldiers were operating reportedly had not
been taken down by the time of their capture.
</P>
<P>
   The legal question that arises is whether the mission ended Feb.
28 or if the troops continued to enjoy U.N. protection because the
organization's flag was still flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time they were captured, who owned them and what was
their legal status?'' Silliman said, noting the unresolved issue of
whether the soldiers were still on the U.N. assignment when they
were taken. ``It's a very, very unusual fact situation that we're
trying to sort out.``
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon, despite calling the servicemen prisoners of war,
is investigating the circumstances of their capture _ an
examination that could lead to a change in their classification,
University of Houston law professor Jordan Paust said. The
Pentagon's investigation will focus, in part, on establishing
whether the Americans were taken in Macedonia or captured in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   If they were taken in Macedonia, a neutral country and the site
of the U.N. operation, their capture was clearly illegal and they
must be returned immediately, Paust said. But if they were captured
in Yugoslavia, a nation embroiled in an armed conflict with the
United States, they might well be regarded as prisoners of war,
added the professor, an expert in international law.
</P>
<P>
   An incursion by Yugoslav troops into Macedonia would be a
violation of that country's ``territorial integrity,'' and
Macedonian leaders would be justified in pressing Yugoslavia to
release the Americans, Paust said. President Clinton should enlist
the help of the Macedonian government in seeking the soldiers'
freedom, the professor added.
</P>
<P>
   But if the U.S. troops were in Yugoslavia on a reconnaissance
mission, Yugoslav forces would be justified in capturing the
Americans and holding them as prisoners of war. However, if the
soldiers mistakenly wandered into Yugoslavia, they should be
immediately released because their presence there would have been
related to the U.N. peacekeeping mission, Paust said.
</P>
<P>
   In such a circumstance, Clinton could urge UN Secretary-General
Kofi Annan to press Yugoslavia to release the captives, the
professor added.
</P>
<P>
   Paust also took issue with Yugoslavia's decision to televise the
three Americans shortly after their capture, saying such a public
display might qualify as the type of ``insult'' of war prisoners
that the Geneva Convention expressly prohibits. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
