u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ART-8     04-01 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ART-885(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES EXPAND TARGETS, HIT TROOPS AND DANUBE BRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-SOLIDERS, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REGUGEES,
KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-RIGHTS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-REBELS,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-RELIGION, KOSOVO-BOSNIA) 
(ART ADV: Graphics _ targets hit by NATO over the last 8 days and
NATO airbases _ are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS and ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO expanded the scope of its raids on Yugoslavia
Thursday, attacking a military unit whose armored personnel
carriers were involved in the killing of ethnic Albanians in
central Kosovo, Pentagon officials said.
</P>
<P>
   American warplanes also destroyed a bridge over the Danube, the
first target, the officials said, that could disrupt the lives of
ordinary Serbs, not just the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The shock of having three American soldiers captured and shown
on Yugoslavia's official television did not affect the pace or
intensity of Thursday's raids, officials here and in Europe said.
The weather, however, did, once again.
</P>
<P>
   Since the air and missile strikes began nine days ago, American
and allied fighters and bombers have had only one day largely
uninterrupted by rain and fog, that makes striking targets on the
ground infinitely more difficult, even for pilots flying the most
advanced airplanes and firing the most sophisticated missiles.
</P>
<P>
   American officials provided scant details about Thursday's
bombing. They declined to say which targets were hit in central
Kosovo or whether the attacks were carried out by cruise missiles
or warplanes. They also did not explain why NATO left intact one of
the two bridges that cross the Danube River in the Yugoslav city of
Novi Sad.
</P>
<P>
   The United States reacted angrily Thursday to reports from
Yugoslavia that the soldiers might be put on trial, saying this
would be a violation of international law. The Pentagon asserted
Thursday night that the captured three Americans, who were seized
near the border between Macedonia and Yugoslavia, should be
considered prisoners of war and treated according to the rules of
the Geneva Convention.
</P>
<P>
   More than a day after the soldiers disappeared, there was still
considerable confusion about the circumstances of their capture,
with conflicting reports on their location and mission along a
rough, hostile border with little firepower backing them up.
American and NATO forces in Macedonia did not call off the search
for the three until they were seen, looking battered and bruised,
on Serbian television.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance officials acknowledged that the Serbs were pressing
ahead with their attacks in Kosovo, and one said that Belgrade had
already achieved many of its military objectives. But the officials
said that in recent days, the air attacks had begun to diminish the
Serbs' ability to wage war.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, said at the alliance
headquarters that the the strikes had already caused ``substantial
damage'' to the armed forces involved in the crackdown against
ethnic Albanians, who make up most of Kosovo's population. NATO's
secretary general, Javier Solana, said that while NATO's raids have
been hampered, they were having a cumulative impact on the forces
of President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ring is closing around the Yugoslav armed forces,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A senior NATO diplomat said that after nine days of bombardments
there were indications that the Yugoslavs were having problems
receiving ammunition and fuel, though refugees continued to leave
their villages and head for Kosovo's borders with Macedonia and
Albania. American and NATO forces have struck several depots used
to stockpile supplies, including another fuel depot in Kosovo
Thursday, the Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a briefing on Capitol Hill, the chairman of the
Senate Armed Services Committee, John Warner, said that in the last
48 hours there had been ``positive signs that this air campaign is
causing problems for Milosevic's deployed troops conducting ethnic
cleansing in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The tanks and other military vehicles are running short on
fuel,'' the Virginia Republican said. ``Food and ammunition is
running short. And we're having, I think, a considerable success
rate in destroying their supply depots.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark, the NATO commander, said the air war now included ``a
slightly larger array of targets,'' including some of Yugoslavia's
civilian structures, which have nominal military uses. He dismissed
Serbian charges that NATO was targeting civilians, but said NATO's
forces would pound any target thought to aid Yugoslavia's military.
</P>
<P>
   ``Insofar as it's drawing reinforcements and supplies and extra
materiel and so forth from throughout Yugoslavia,'' he said, ``the
routes throughout Yugoslavia are legitimate targets. And when we
deem it appropriate, then they will be struck.''
</P>
<P>
   The bridge over the Danube, Europe's longest waterway, was
struck before dawn in the city of Novi Sad, northwest of Yugoslav's
capital and far from the crackdown in Kosovo. The steel suspension
span was one of two that cross the river near Novi Sad's center. A
squadron of American F-15 strike jets left it a crumpled mass in
the river.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear Thursday night why NATO forces did not attack
Novi Sad's other bridge or major transit points in other parts of
Yugoslavia, though officials said much of the decisions on striking
targets swung with the fickleness of Balkan weather. They did not
rule out that the other, older bridge in Novi Sad could be struck.
</P>
<P>
   Senior NATO and American officials said the expansion of targets
would accelerate as the weather cleared, which forecasts predict it
will by the weekend.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NATO's political leadership approved the expansion of targets at
a meeting in Brussels, Belgium, on Tuesday, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Although NATO officials have repeatedly said they have the
forces they need to wage the air war against Yugoslavia, the United
States and other NATO powers, including Britain and France, have
bolstered the number of aircraft in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week the United States dispatched five B-1 bombers.
Thursday, Secretary of Defense William Cohen ordered 13 more F-117
``stealth'' fighters to Italy. They will join 11 others that have
been taking part in the raids. A 12th F-117 was shot down over
Serbia on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Two more Navy warships _ the Ross, a destroyer, and the Vella
Gulf, a cruiser _ entered the Mediterranean Thursday loaded with
cruise missiles and are expected to join the assault soon. The
aircraft carrier, Theodore Roosevelt, is expected to arrive by the
weekend, bringing with it some 75 aircraft, 50 of them combat jets.
</P>
<P>
   The question remained: would they arrive soon enough? A senior
Pentagon official said that Milosevic's forces, although pummeled,
appeared to be wrapping up a campaign to carve out a Serb-enclave
in Kosovo, having cornered the last remnants of ethnic Albanian
rebels known as the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's basically got every objective he wanted,'' the official
said, citing intelligence reports from Kosovo. ``He's destroyed the
KLA and chased everyone else out.''
</P>
<P>
   American warplanes have flown 60 to 70 percent of the strikes,
largely because the United States has more aircraft suited to foul
weather and able to evade radar, a Pentagon official said. But the
allied contribution has been significant, making up at least half
the total missions flown.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has repeatedly refused to quantify how many missions have
been flown in the air war or break them down by country or
distinguish between bombing runs and support activities such as
refueling.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's raids were overshadowed by the seizure of the
Americans, something that the White House and the Pentagon,
recalling the capture of American troops in Somalia in 1993, had
deeply feared.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, in Norfolk, Va., initially described the three soldiers
as ``illegal detainees'' rather than prisoners of war, but by the
end of the day, the Pentagon described them as POWs and demanded
that they not be brought before a military trial in Kosovo, as the
Yugoslav authorities threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, the Pentagon spokesman, said Thursday evening that
depending on the circumstances of their capture _ namely whether
they were inside Macedonia or had strayed into Serbia _ the three
``may be'' entitled to immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   He said that, pending an investigation and, ideally, the direct
questioning of the three, ``our belief'' is that they did not
violate the Yugoslav border. ``The soldiers should be released
immediately,'' he said at another point, contending that ``at a
minimum'' they were entitled to the protections of the Geneva
Convention, which calls for the humane treatment of the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   Given the border tensions of the situation, some critics
questioned whether the three soldiers observed regulations and
should have been better protected by operating within some larger
formation better able to defend itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm astounded,'' said a retired senior Army officer familiar
with the Balkans. ``In Bosnia, we figured one of our
vulnerabilities was a hostage snatch or an ambush.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner said their capture raised questions. He said the United
States had been on ``full notice'' that the Serbs ``would like to
seize'' a NATO serviceman. ``And that's precisely what happened,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon declined to say whether lax procedures might have been a
factor, but said an investigation was underway. ``I don't think
I'll second-guess what's going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
said a possibility was that the Americans inadvertently crossed the
border while fleeing an ambush by Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said that among the many unknown factors was
whether they were captured by Yugoslav troops or border police or
by some of the many local Macedonian Serb villagers who are armed
and openly sympathize with the Yugoslav Serbs. Scores of troops and
several helicopters, Bacon said, were dispatched in a ``massive''
search for the three in poor weather, without result. The Americans
armored vehicle _ a Humvee _ remains missing.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said that three Humvees had been on patrol, then split up
``to do some individual training exercises'' that he did not
otherwise describe. They had been working near a border observation
post inside Macedonia, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he would hold the Yugoslav authorities responsible
for their well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all seen their pictures,'' he said. ``We don't like it.
We don't like the way they're treated. And we have a long memory
about these kinds of things.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
