u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COYOTE-PARK-ART-NY     04-01 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COYOTE-PARK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COYOTE IS CORNERED IN CENTRAL PARK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A coyote was first spotted Tuesday night in Central
Park by an alert police officer. The next night, he was spotted
again, and dozens of officers were called in to join the search. As
a police helicopter buzzed overhead, he emerged from the brambles,
running furiously. Then, he was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Far from an April Fool's joke, it almost seemed that some
character out of the Old West had stormed into town and a posse had
mobilized to bring him to bay. In fact, the coyote was a terrified
fugitive, and after the police were able to corner him, he was
tranquilized, captured and left to await his fate: a short stay at
the Bronx Zoo and a trip to the wilds upstate.
</P>
<P>
   Parks officials say that coyotes have become an increasing
presence in New York City, particularly in the Bronx, but how one
got onto the island of Manhattan _ and more specifically, into
Central Park in the shadows of some of New York's grandest
apartment buildings _ remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   At first, parks and animal care officials were not sure the
animal was a coyote, and not some scruffy mutt. But he matched the
basic descriptions: a burnished silver coat with black detailing,
legs and snout the color of a bad sunburn. His tail, which he held
low as he ran, was classic coyote.
</P>
<P>
   After his capture, animal care officials verified his identity,
and said that he would get a full physical examination Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, coyotes lived only in Western states, but they have
spread to every state except Hawaii. Despite determined efforts by
ranchers and others to eradicate them, there are believed to be
about twice as many as there were in 1850, according to the
May-June issue of Audubon magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coyotes are spreading not just in ranching country but in
metropolises nationwide, from the suburbs of Los Angeles to the
streets of New York City,'' the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Stern, the city's park commissioner, said that in recent
years, coyotes have been regularly sighted in the Bronx, in Van
Cortlandt Park and Woodlawn Cemetery. A coyote that was found dead
on the Major Deegan Expressway is now on display _ in a stuffed
state _ in the Arsenal, the Park's Department's headquarters in
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Parks officials think it most likely Thursday's coyote came from
the Bronx, probably crossing the Henry Hudson Bridge. Adding
credence to this theory was a report from a Parks Department office
worker that she saw an animal that could have been a coyote on
Saturday, at 149th Street and Riverside Drive, a possible route
down from the Bronx. How it then may have navigated through the
West Side remains a mystery.
</P>
<P>
   By 11 a.m. Thursday, a small army of reporters had shown up at a
news conference, drawn by the story of the coyote.
</P>
<P>
   Stern emphasized the coyote was probably not dangerous, though
he suggested people might not want to unleash their dogs, alluding
to his current crackdown on dogs who are allowed to run loose. The
news conference came to an abrupt end when word arrived that police
and park workers had the coyote cornered in the Hallett Nature
Sanctuary, a four-acre preserve that is fenced and closed to the
public except for occasional guided tours.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who had gathered at the Bethesda Fountain, just north
of 72nd Street, raced to the southeastern corner of the park,
joining police cars, park enforcement vehicles and ambulances. The
coyote charged in and out of view, as the police repeatedly fired
tranquilizer darts that fell well behind the speedy animal.
</P>
<P>
   Around noon, the animal dived into a nearby pond. He swam
furiously, finally pulling himself onto a rock. He was hit by a
tranquilizer dart, then another. He tore off, finally slowing seven
blocks away near a World War I monument. He staggered, then
collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   For all the excitement, most Central Park visitors seemed
oblivious. Joggers jogged, ice skaters skated and people lined up
for hot dogs. A man with a golden cocker spaniel asked what all the
commotion was about, then nodded and walked silently on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
