u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SOLDIERS-NYT &LR;      04-01 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SOLDIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THREE HOMETOWNS, YELLOW RIBBONS HANG IN SUPPORT OF CAPTURED
SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mich., Texas)  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-SOLDIERS, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-RIGHTS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-REBELS,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-RELIGION, KOSOVO-BOSNIA) 
(js) 
 By BRETT PULLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dreaded symbol of war began to mark the landscape in three
communities Thursday, as friends and family of the American
soldiers captured along the border of Macedonia and Kosovo hung
yellow ribbons on their clothing, in their yards and along the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers, who are members of the U.S. First Infantry
Division that has patrolled the border for several years, were
taken prisoner on Wednesday by Serbian forces. The sight of the
soldiers appearing bruised and scarred on Serbian television came
as bittersweet comfort for their families, who had earlier received
word that they were missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's alive,'' a half-relieved Gilbert Gonzales said of his
son, Specialist Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas.
``He's blinking his eyes. But we don't know what's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's president, Slobodan Milosevic, whose forces have
been the target of NATO bombing since last week, has announced that
a military inquiry will determine whether to try the three men. The
other two soldiers being held are Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24,
of Los Angeles, and Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths
Creek, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   In the prisoners' hometowns, friends and relatives recalled the
days when the three soldiers were growing from boys to men. Mario
Rios, who lives two doors down from the modest, well-kept East Los
Angeles home where Ramirez grew up, described him as a child who
stayed out of trouble and was determined to follow in the footsteps
of his older brother, Steven Ramirez, who served in the Army and is
now a member of the Los Angeles Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Steve liked, Andy liked,'' Ms. Rios said. ``He wanted to
be just like his brother, and everything that the brother wanted to
do, he wanted to do.'' After graduating from Schurr High School in
nearby Montebello in 1992, Ramirez enlisted in the Army that year.
</P>
<P>
   Neither his brother nor parents were available for comment on
Thursday. Relatives said that Ramirez's parents were separated, but
that his father still lived in the house where he grew up. No one
appeared to be home there Thursday, but friends and relatives
gathered at the house throughout the day, praying and placing
bouquets of flowers at the doorstep, and hanging yellow ribbons and
American flags throughout the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the home, Robert Carcano, a cousin of Ramirez and an
officer with the Montebello police department, said the news of the
capture sickened him. ``It's family _ it really hit home,'' he
said, adding that he still supports the NATO involvement in Kosovo.
``I'm behind what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   In Huntsville, Texas, where both parents of Gonzales work for
the Texas Department of Corrections, yellow ribbons were hanging
outside the entrance to the prison's infamous Wall Unit, the
execution site for death row inmates. Inside one of the prison
buildings, the parents, surrounded by colleagues with yellow
ribbons pinned to their clothing, held a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   His mother, Rosie Gonzales, decried the Yugoslav government's
suggestion that the three men may be put on trial. ``These soldiers
are not criminals, and they should not be dealt with as
criminals,'' she said. ``They are innocent young men who are over
there as part of their duty.''
</P>
<P>
   His father commented on the apparent condition of the soldiers
after seeing them on television. ``They looked in pretty good
spirits,'' Gilbert Gonzales said. ``They were standing tall with
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, who was an honor student and athlete at Palestine High
School in Palestine, Texas, attended Texas A &AMP; M University for one
year before deciding to join the Army in 1996. He had just
re-enlisted, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a good student,'' recalled Andy Jones, a physics
teacher at the high school, which is 60 miles north of Huntsville.
The family moved to Huntsville after Gonzales graduated in 1995.
``I'm sure whatever the military has taught him, he knows very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Another teacher at the school, Richard Sylvester, agreed. ``This
kid has all the discipline he needs to get through about any
situation in life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, some of Stone's relatives gathered at a
candlelight prayer vigil near the Michigan town of Capac, the
rural, tight-knit community where he grew up. ``At first we thought
he was dead,'' said Dianna Stone, Stone's 29-year-old sister. ``We
had some mixed emotions when we saw him on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone's wife, Tricia, and 4-year-old son, Ryan, are living in
the San Antonio, Texas, area, and could not be reached. Stone's
mother died when he was young and his father lives near Capac,
which is located 80 miles north of Detroit. Another sister, Dawn
Reliford, 31, also attended the prayer vigil, along with her
husband, Mike Reliford, who described his brother-in-law as ``a
smooth talker'' who ``could talk his way in and out of any
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Family members had just received a letter from Stone last week,
which he wrote prior to the start of the NATO bombing. In the
letter, he was in good spirits and said that he expected to come
home soon. ``I know he'll tough it out, no matter what they do to
him,'' said Reliford. ``He'll be strong and he'll be a good
American soldier.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Marzka, Stone's cross-country coach and history teacher at
Capac High School, said that although he was an average student and
an average athlete, he had one superior quality. ``He never quit,''
Marzka said. ``He'd be behind by 15 or 20 yards and finish as
strong as he could without ever giving up.'' Stone graduated from
the school in 1991 and enlisted in the Army the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Tiffany Ellis, 18, a senior at Capac High School, said that
students there Thursday were stunned by the news of Stone's
capture. ``We thought it was an April Fool's joke,'' she said. She
and other students spent the afternoon on Main Street in Capac,
hanging yellow ribbons on lamp posts, trees, and storefronts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
