<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAPTIVES-IMPACT-1STLEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTURE OF SOLDIERS BRINGS HOME TO AMERICANS DANGER OF WAR IN
DISTANT LAND
</HEADLINE>
 (EDS: Corrects spelling of Gonzales; adds Texas to Huntsville
location) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARIA RECIO 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The capture of three U.S. soldiers in the Balkans
suddenly brought home to many Americans on Thursday the cost and
dangers of war in a distant land.
</P>
<P>
   With the public ambivalent and Congress uneasy about NATO
airstrikes against Yugoslavia, President Clinton sought Thursday to
reassure Americans about the nation's commitment to the three
soldiers, including Spec. Steven Gonzales of Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Farer, dean of the graduate school of international studies
at the University of Denver, said TV images of the battered Army
enlisted men ``demonizes'' the conflict for Americans who are
trying to form opinions.
</P>
