<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBANIAN FIGHTERS SAY THEY HELP NATO SPOT SERB TARGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-SOLIDERS, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REGUGEES,
KOSOVO-EUROPE, KOSOVO-RIGHTS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-REBELS,
KOSOVO-ALBANIA, KOSOVO-RELIGION, KOSOVO-BOSNIA) 
(ac) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _ A spokesman for the Kosovo Liberation Army
said Thursday that guerrillas in Kosovo are aiding NATO forces in
their bombing campaign of Serbian targets in the province.
</P>
<P>
   The separatist insurgents are cooperating with NATO air-raid
operations in targeting, Jakub Krasniqi, a spokesman for the
rebels, said at a news conference here. Krasniqi gave no specifics
on how the guerrillas are helping NATO forces to pinpoint targets
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He said the ethnic Albanian rebels on the ground, severely
outnumbered and underarmed, have not tried any offensives against
Serbian forces since the bombing campaign began. He asked that NATO
ground troops intervene in Kosovo. If not, he said, the West should
arm the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Krasniqi's remarks were aimed at buoying the morale of his
movement, which is badly shaken by Serbian attacks and the
widespread reports of Serbian looting and burning of villages and
the forced flight of tens of thousands of civilians. The rebel
movement was also dealt a blow Thursday by a joint appearance in
Belgrade of the Yugoslav President, Slobodan Milosevic, and one of
the best-known leaders of Kosovo ethnic Albanians, Ibrahim Rugova,
who called for a halt in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that he was coerced, and that the statement was
extracted by force, or because he was afraid, Krasniqi said. But if
he made the declaration voluntarily, he said, then he has committed
high treason.
</P>
<P>
   Krasniqi, who was accompanied by Xhavit Halitaj , a member of
the political directorate of the rebels' general staff, arrived in
Albania last night from the Kosovo capital, Pristina, traveling
over hard mountain paths. He appealed emotionally for arms and
assistance for the beleagured rebels, saying, ``We demand the
intervention of ground forces in Kosovo.'' He added: ``If NATO
troops will not go in, then they must immediately arm the KLA. If
they do not arm us, then NATO must go in.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebel spokesman said the peace agreement that the Kosovo
negotiators signed at Rambouillet has lost its sense. He said the
United States, the international community and the European Union
should recognize the independence of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And to that end, he also said the rebels had ordered ``a general
mobilization among Kosovar men, to defend the dignity and survival
of our nation.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night the rebel army issued a statement that was
broadcast on Albanian television, ordering all Kosovo Albanian men
between the ages of 18 and 50 to join its ranks within one month.
The statement said the rebels are setting up training camps in
Kosovo for new recruits.
</P>
<P>
   If the men refuse to join the rebel army, the general staff
warned that its military police ``will act even outside Kosovo,''
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how much coercion had been used to persuade men
and boys to leave their families and report to makeshift camps,
which the rebels maintain in the Albanian hills a few miles west of
the border. Kraniji declined to discuss the recruitment campaign,
saying only that those who are ordering the mobilization are also
giving thought to training.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported that some travelers said they had
seen rebel soldiers taking men off buses that have been ferrying
refugees from nearby Kukes to other towns and cities in Albania for
resettlement.
</P>
<P>
   In Tirana, in the tent city where 2,000 Kosovo refugees have
been sheltered under Albanian Army tents, supporters of the rebels,
like Albanian and Italian evangelical Christians who are handing
out bibles and Christian pamphlets to Muslim refugees, are free to
mingle with the refugees and recruit.
</P>
<P>
   Agron Ramai, a 22-year-old refugee from a village near Pritzen,
said he was well aware of the call to arms, and said he would
comply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to get my family safe and settled,'' he said,
``and then I will go back. Kosovo has to be liberated and nobody
else can do it but us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
