<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Individual Shareholders Have the Power With New Web Site
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
You may not know Mark Coker, but he's in your corner.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old public relations executive from Los Gatos has
launched a Web site that is intended to bolster the rights of
individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   The site,  &LR; www.BestCalls.com &LR; , is a free directory listing
thousands of company teleconference calls, and it could become a
revolutionary tool in the small investor's battle against selective
disclosure of material information.
</P>
<P>
   The site lists the schedules and access information for analyst
telephone conference calls, which often are closed to mom-and-pop
investors. By registering at the site, investors can have e-mails
sent to them telling when companies whose stock they own have
scheduled such conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't created a Web site, we've created a cause,'' Coker
says.
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneurial Coker bootstrapped the site's startup, using
his own cash and employees from his small public relations firm.
While he doesn't charge companies or users of the site, he hopes to
sell advertising to fund the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the site is already running high. It's no secret
that the playing field isn't always level between Wall Street's big
guns and the little guy. And one of the advantages that major
shareholders often enjoy is access to telephone conference calls
that companies conduct shortly after reporting their quarterly
financial results, usually after the market has closed.
</P>
<P>
   Corporations often invite a select audience to listen to their
chief executives and chief financial officers explain their most
recent performance. The clubby group often includes sell-side
financial analysts from brokerages, buy-side analysts and portfolio
managers from institutional investors such as mutual funds,
individuals with big stakes in the company and sometimes members of
the press.
</P>
<P>
   An immense amount of information is sometimes exchanged during
these briefings, which usually are toll-free with the companies
picking up the tabs. Analysts are encouraged to ask questions while
individual investors, when allowed to participate, are not. The
press is sometimes allowed to listen but usually banned from asking
questions (which is appealing to some, I suppose).
</P>
<P>
   Interesting tidbits that aren't included in press releases often
are revealed during these sessions. And Coker wants all
shareholders to be able to hear the information at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, it's a mixed bag. Some companies, such as Yahoo and
Inktomi, open their conference calls to all shareholders and the
press. Others, meantime, allow only Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, some companies provide free taped-delay versions
via telephone or the Internet at scattered times after the
briefing. Proponents of this approach argue that every investor
doesn't need to hear the briefing live because the markets are
closed, and all shareholders have plenty of time to digest the
information before the next day's opening bell.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, some companies allow investors but ban the
press. Or, conversely, others prohibit small investors from
listening to the calls but allow news organizations instead.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions vary, and the Securities and Exchange Commission is
vague on the issue, which leaves companies scratching their heads.
Some advisers, such as securities lawyer Boris Feldman of Wilson
Sonsini Goodrich &AMP; Rosati in Palo Alto, advocate letting the press
act as a proxy for the rest of the market. As long as most of the
sell-side financial analysts and major wire services are on the
call, the marketplace is getting the information in a fair and
efficient manner.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman says companies aren't obligated to include investors in
conference calls, suggesting that it's better policy to exclude
them because mass audiences can sometimes cause conferences to
``become too bland.``
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have to let the Guy from Boca on the call? Absolutely
not,'' Feldman recently told a group of investor relations
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you have to be ready to get flamed'' by the unhappy
individual investors, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Feldman contends that too many investors on a call actually
inhibit management from being very forthcoming and encourage
executives to dribble out juicier information later in private
one-on-one situations with influential analysts and shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   That sometimes spurs a deeper degree of selective disclosure,
which is precisely what companies should try to avoid, Feldman
argues. (For those interested in learning more about disclosure
issues and conference calls you can read several of Feldman's
articles on the subject posted on his firm's Web site at
 &LR; www.wsgr.com &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   But Coker, who has been investing since he was a teenager, sees
it differently. If he has his way, someday all public companies
will open their investor teleconferences to everyone. Period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to blow the door wide open,'' Coker says.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OOPS: &LR;  Looksmart, an Internet directory of Web sites, said that
its recent private placement was one of the largest rounds of
funding by a private Internet media company. In Wednesday's column,
Street Smarts wrongly reported that it was the largest round raised
by such a company.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 2138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
