<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3145 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PUC-SFCHRON &LR;      04-01 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUC-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Regulators Tussle Over PG&AMP;E
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Rebecca Smith &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Two investigations of the December 8 blackout that paralyzed San
Francisco and parts of the Peninsula have exposed cracks in the
state regulatory process.
</P>
<P>
   The state Public Utilities Commission and a new rival
quasi-public agency acknowledged this week that they have been
having a dustup over who has authority to investigate Pacific Gas
and Electric Co. over the power failure.
</P>
<P>
   The grid-operating Independent System Operator said it has
jurisdiction because the incident began with transmission line
failures. The PUC said the matter is in its domain because it
involved the distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   They still haven't sorted it out. Both organizations issued
reports Wednesday analyzing the event and suggesting improvements
PG&AMP;E should make.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco officials want the agencies _ or the state
Legislature _ to sort out the jurisdictional question quickly and
make sure whoever is in charge has proper police powers.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Klein, general manager of Hetch Hetchy Water and Power,
said he's gone to both the PUC and ISO to find out who's in charge
and who's going to do something to improve San Francisco's power
supply and reliability. Since it appears everyone is in charge,
he's concluded no one is in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, if the mayor is concerned about reliability, whose
desk does he pound on?'' Klein says he asked the organizations.
``The more I heard, the more I concluded the only desk he has to
pound on is mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, it was clear who was in charge. The PUC was the
big cop, wielding a baton that gave it the unquestioned authority
to inspect utility books and equipment, issue citations and levy
fines.
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation of the electric industry stripped the PUC of its
authority over the high-voltage transmission system and vested it
in a new grid operator. But the Legislature didn't give the ISO
rights equal to the PUC because it's a nonprofit corporation, not a
state agency.
</P>
<P>
   It wears a cop's uniform, in effect, but doesn't have a badge or
gun.
</P>
<P>
   That's looking more and more like a problem. The issue of
regulatory gap seems certain to come up, across the country, as
states deregulate their electric industries and strip their
utilities commissions of century-old powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're now seeing is a structural weakness in the new
deregulated system,'' says Theresa Mueller, a deputy city attorney
for San Francisco who's concerned about the agencies'
investigations of the blackout. ``We now have a system where the
utilities aren't as accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   The ISO can ask utilities to open their books and records but
can't order it. It can't put utility executives under oath. And it
can't issue citations or fines unless it gets special permission
from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Winter, the ISO's chief executive, says his team got
complete cooperation from PG&AMP;E in pursuing its investigation of the
December power failure. He thinks he got all the information he
needed, speedily and truthfully. But he admits the ISO isn't in a
particularly powerful position going forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I got into a case where people didn't cooperate, what
authority would I have?'' asks Winter. ``I'd have to say very
little.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the PUC investigative team said its efforts to get
information on the December power failure from PG&AMP;E were hampered,
at times, by the ISO and its overseer, the California Oversight
Board.
</P>
<P>
   Chong Chiu, head of the PUC investigative team, says he got the
information his 14-person team needed during the first two weeks of
his investigation. But that information dried up for a month when
the ISO instructed the utility that it didn't need to cooperate
fully with PUC investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Winter said yesterday he thought some of the PUC questioning was
inappropriate. They were asking questions he'd already gotten
answered and he was willing to share with the PUC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that I was telling them what they could or couldn't
ask,'' Winter said. ``It was more like PG&AMP;E had already answered
the questions so don't bug them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Schulte, director of the Consumer Services Division that
commissioned Chiu to prepare the independent report, said he didn't
want jurisdictional issues to stand in the way of a thorough
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured we could sort that stuff out later,'' he said. ``I
felt it was crucial to have an independent investigation and I
wanted it to go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer advocates say they find the regulatory vacuum
appalling, especially since power supply is as much a matter of
public safety as public convenience. Legislators need to take a
hard look at what they've created, some say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not regulation anymore,'' says Nettie Hoge, executive
director of the consumer group The Utility Reform Network in San
Francisco. ``It's peer pressure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
