<HEADLINE>
A MEXICAN GOVERNOR DROPS FROM SIGHT IN DRUG INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Federal authorities have intensified a drug
investigation that is focusing on the governor of the state of
Quintana Roo, calling him for new rounds of questioning and warning
that protests by his allies will not halt the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   But Gov. Mario Villanueva Madrid has dropped from public view.
He failed to show up for questioning on Saturday. The attorney
general's office said in a statement issued late Wednesday that
prosecutors did ``not know Villanueva's whereabouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Villanueva has not been charged with a crime, his
failure to respond to a citation for questioning was, at worst, a
minor infraction. But Attorney General Jorge Madrazo informed the
governor last month that he was a target of an investigation and on
Wednesday noted that Villanueva had enjoyed constitutional
protection against arrest as a sitting governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as this situation continues, it is not possible to
move ahead with criminal prosecution,'' Madrazo said in his
statement. Left unsaid was that Villanueva will lose that immunity
when his term ends on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Joaquin Hendricks Diaz, who is also from President Ernesto
Zedillo's governing Institutional Revolutionary Party and was
elected in February to succeed Villanueva, will take office on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Villanueva has repeatedly denied involvement in drug or other
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Because official statements here are usually shrouded in cryptic
diplomatic niceties, the attorney general's blunt words led
immediately to widespread speculation that Madrazo was preparing to
ask a federal judge for Villanueva's arrest after he had left
office.
</P>
<P>
   One of several criminal lawyers retained by Villanueva, Rafael
Heredia, said Thursday that the governor had not been in touch with
him in recent days. Most official business in Mexico has halted
because it is the week before Easter, schoolchildren are on
holidays, and thousands of bureaucrats are vacationing.
</P>
<P>
   The federal inquiry, which has lasted more than a year, has
shaped up as a personal showdown between Madrazo, a bespectacled
former human rights lawyer, and Villanueva, a back-slapping
old-style politician who has enjoyed considerable popularity in
Quintana Roo despite the often authoritarian tactics that he has
brought to bear on opponents.
</P>
<P>
   In Villanueva's administration, Quintana Roo has become a major
transport hub for loads of Colombian cocaine headed toward the U.S.
border, and some of the state's hundreds of luxury hotels have been
used to launder drug profits. Several major Cancun hotels were
seized by the narcotics police last fall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When Villanueva learned in late 1997 that several traffickers
had accused him of using the Quintana Roo police to protect and
even coordinate drug shipments, he met the attorney general to
proclaim his innocence. Madrazo responded by urging the governor to
submit to questioning by prosecutors, and Villanueva was infuriated
to find that the federal inquiry only seemed to accelerate despite
his offers to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   After he was notified last month that Madrazo was aiming at him
in the inquiry, Villanueva's allies began organizing displays of
support for him in Quintana Roo, and Villanueva accused Madrazo of
pursuing baseless charges against him as part of a political
vendetta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The organization of protests, marches, public demonstrations,
strikes or threats,'' Madrazo said in his statement on Wednesday,
will not stop federal prosecutors in carrying out their legal
responsibilities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
