<HEADER>
A3155 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     04-01 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: PROTECTING DiMAGGIO'S DIGNITY  
 (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio once had a question for Morris Engelberg, his
lawyer who lived next door to him in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morris,'' he asked, ``what makes you tick?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking into Yankee Stadium behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg meant hearing the cheers that always welcomed the
Yankee Clipper to the Stadium, but the next time they arrived
there, DiMaggio took his lawyer's arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morris,'' he said, ``you're not behind me now.''
</P>
<P>
   And ever since Joe DiMaggio's death March 9, it's as if Morris
Engelberg were still walking arm in arm with him. After having been
his lawyer for 15 years, Engelberg is now entrusted with protecting
DiMaggio's name and likeness, which means protecting the image
DiMaggio developed for privacy and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe once told me, `I don't want my name abused,''' Engelberg
was saying from his Hollywood, Fla., office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was easy when he was alive, because people feared him. He
was the most honorable man I've ever known. If he agreed to
something, that was it. But if you double-crossed him, you were
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg wouldn't talk specifically about offers he has refused
for DiMaggio's name in this quick-money society, but he said,
``There won't be any Joe DiMaggio watches,'' nothing that might be
tacky. He's also involved in exposing any memorabilia promoters
falsely advertising DiMaggio's signature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the signatures are forgeries,'' he said. ``Joe
wouldn't sign everything. Somebody wanted him to sign a 1996 Yankee
pennant, but he said: `That's not my pennant. That's their
pennant.'''
</P>
<P>
   The 40-acre park where DiMaggio often read the newspapers near
his home in Hollywood, Fla., will be named for him, and the West
Side Highway in Manhattan will be renamed the Joe DiMaggio Highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the idea of changing the West Side Highway to the Joe
DiMaggio Highway first came up quite a while ago, Joe told me,
`That has a nice ring to it,''' Engelberg said. ``He never liked
the idea of changing the Major Deegan Expressway, because he didn't
like taking somebody else's name off it.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio's memory was honored a week ago at a candlelight
ceremony at the Joe DiMaggio Children's Hospital in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phil Rizzuto, Reggie Jackson and Gov. Jeb Bush spoke,''
Engelberg said. ``Reggie was wonderful. He should be a preacher.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio will be remembered in New York on Friday, April 23, at
a memorial Mass at St. Patrick's Cathedral. On Sunday, April 25, at
Yankee Stadium, a DiMaggio monument will be unveiled in Monument
Park beyond left-center field, joining those for Babe Ruth, Lou
Gehrig, Mickey Mantle and Miller Huggins.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Yankees talked about putting up his monument a few
years ago, Joe said, `Are they burying me already?''' Engelberg
said. ``That was the end of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg also sifts through anywhere from 50 to 75 letters a
day, some for business offers for DiMaggio's name, some from
memorabilia collectors, some from people who just want to tell
their own memories of DiMaggio. Like the letter received here the
other day from Dick Caime, who grew up as a Yankee fan in the
Ridgewood section of Brooklyn, but now lives in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was one particular series against the Red Sox in Fenway
when Joe D was coming off the bone-spur heel operation when I
prayed on hands and knees for his comeback and success,'' Caime
wrote. ``My friends, mostly Dodger fans, laughed at me.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when I went to confession that Saturday (we would go even
with nothing to confess, especially if we had nothing to confess),
I told the priest what I was praying for. He smiled that Bing
Crosby/Barry Fitzgerald Irish smile and said, `Can't you think of
something more important to pray for?' and I said, ``Like what?'
</P>
<P>
   ``His laughter shook the whole church, &QC; St. Bridget's. I was
embarrassed to go out of the confessional. He said, `Oh, we'll pray
together,' and we did, right then and there. I found out later the
priest was a Dodger fan. Joe D had a great series.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Yankees' sweep of that three-game series in 1949,
DiMaggio hit four homers, drove in nine runs and scored five.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got a chance to tell Joe D my story,'' Caime's letter
ended, ``but I continued to pray for him throughout his life. I'll
tell him someday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
