<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PRISONERS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Three American Army soldiers captured by Yugoslav forces on
Wednesday while patrolling the Macedonia-Kosovo border will face
military trial as early as Friday, Yugoslav state television
reported. President Clinton said there was no basis for their
seizure and demanded their immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMBAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth day of the NATO bombing campaign, allied warplanes
destroyed a bridge over the Danube River at Novi Sad in northern
Serbia, blocking a key shipping route to the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army said Thursday
that the ethnic Albanian guerrillas in Kosovo are aiding NATO
forces in their bombing campaign of Yugoslav targets in the
province.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was considering air drops of relief assistance
to the KLA, at the rebels' request, a State Department spokesman
said. He declined to comment on reports that the rebels had also
asked for heavy weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve more F-117 stealth fighter jets like the one downed
recently in Yugoslav territory will be deployed, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; YUGOSLAV POLITICS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   President Slobodan Milosevic was shown on state television
meeting with Ibrahim Rugova, a prominent leader of Kosovo's ethnic
Albanians. The two men signed a document calling for a peaceful end
to the Kosovo crisis through ``political means.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic removed Montenegro's army commander and seven other
top generals, in what was widely seen as an effort to tighten
Serbia's control over Montenegro, the smaller of Yugoslavia's two
republics.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REFUGEES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav troops loaded thousands of ethnic Albanians onto a
train to the country's frontier, then forced them to walk the final
miles across the border into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations was considering an airlift to help the more
than 180,000 ethnic Albanians who have fled to Macedonia, Albania
and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Japan pledged $15 million in aid for Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Germany held talks with its Western European partners and
Yugoslavia's Balkan neighbors to discuss how to cope with the
refugee crisis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIPLOMACY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin appealed for foreign ministers
of the Group of Eight industrial countries to convene an emergency
meeting on the Kosovo crisis and said he was considering sending
more warships to the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II urged the United States, Yugoslavia and NATO
to observe an Easter truce between April 4 and 7. The Vatican's
chief foreign affairs official arrived in Belgrade, Yugoslavia,
with a personal message to Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   American Roman Catholic and Serbian Orthodox religious leaders
appealed for a halt in the violence in Kosovo and for a resumption
of peace talks as their congregations began Easter observances.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONTINUOUS COVERAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Kosovo, as well as
background information with video and audio and links to Internet
resources, are available to computer users from The New York Times
on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
