<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0374 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3161 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-COX-04     04-01 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-COX-0402 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON WARNS YUGOSLAVIA AS THREE CAPTURED AMERICANS FACE TRIAL
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The Pentagon voiced outrage after Yugoslavia said
it would open a military trial Friday to prosecute three American
soldiers, and President Clinton put Belgrade on notice that it
would be held accountable for the captives' fate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called for the prisoners' immediate release, as
state-run television in Yugoslavia broadcast grim footage of the
U.S. infantrymen, at least one of whom appeared to have been
severely beaten about the face.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've all seen their pictures. We don't like it. We don't like
the way they're treated, and we have a long memory about these
kinds of things,'' said U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO
commander who is running the allied bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia's military.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know very well what the right way to treat people is,''
Clark told reporters at NATO headquarters in Brussels. ``They know
what the law is, and...they will be held accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   By late Thursday, there were as many questions as answers about
the circumstances surrounding Wednesday's capture of the three
soldiers near Macedonia's border with the embattled province of
Kosovo. The Pentagon, for instance, could not say precisely where
the troops were captured, where they were being held or even who
was responsible for the ambush.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and allied pilots slammed Yugoslavia with a ninth day of
air raids on Thursday, as the Pentagon dispatched 13 additional
B-117 stealth bombers to the region, bringing to roughly 220 the
number of U.S. warplanes there.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks Wednesday night hit Serb army forces in central Kosovo,
blew up an ammunition depot in the province and destroyed a major
bridge across the Danube River at Novi Sad, a city of a half
million people northwest of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The routes throughout Yugoslavia are legitimate targets,''
said Clark, ``and when we deem it appropriate, then they will be
struck.''
</P>
<P>
   Matching raids with rhetoric, Clark called on Yugoslavia's
military commanders to unseat Milosevic, as NATO forces struck at
the military and security underpinnings of his authoritarian
regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should stop the inhumane treatment of their own
citizens,'' Clark said, referring to what he said is an ongoing
Serb campaign of shelling civilians, torching homes and otherwise
terrorizing the ethnic Albanian community across Kosovo. ``They
should look at the source of illegal orders and take the
appropriate action.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade, however, remained defiant, announcing that ``criminal
proceedings'' would begin Friday against the captured soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're outraged by that,'' said Pentagon spokesman Kenneth
Bacon. ``They're covered by the Geneva Convention. The Geneva
Convention says that prisoners of war should not be tried.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department said Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
lodged a protest through the Swedish mission in Belgrade, but
offered no further details.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon identified the captives as Staff Sgt. Andrew A.
Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25,
of Smiths Creek, Mich.; and Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of
Huntsville, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   They were on what the Pentagon described as a routine
reconnaissance patrol when they were ambushed, fired on, surrounded
and captured.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was absolutely no basis for them to be taken. There is
no basis for them to be held,'' said Clinton. ``There is certainly
no basis for them to be tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing before a pair of attack jets at the Norfolk Naval
Station in Virginia, Clinton told a crowd of military families that
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic must ensure the prisoners'
rights and protections as set forth in the Geneva Conventions, the
basis for international law concerning captured troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic should make no mistake: The United States
takes care of its own,'' Clinton said. ``We will hold him and his
government responsible for their safety and for their well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   The Geneva Conventions a set of four agreements developed
between 1864 and 1949 form the basis for international law
regarding the protection of civilians, the humane treatment of
prisoners and the care of the wounded during times of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   No formal declaration of war is necessary for the conventions to
apply.
</P>
<P>
   If the captives are treated as prisoners of war, however, the
conventions permit them to be held in custody until the cessation
of hostilities.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the United States recognizes their status as prisoners
of war would revolve in part around the circumstances of their
abduction. As of Thursday, there were more questions than answers.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't clear, for instance, exactly where the men were when
their Humvee army vehicle was surrounded by gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   The men were last seen on patrol inside Macedonia, about three
miles from the border of neighboring Kosovo, the embattled southern
province of the Yugoslav state of Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Belgrade alleged that the Americans had crossed over into
Kosovo. Bacon said U.S. officials simply did not know whether the
Humvee had wandered across the border in the mountainous terrain or
whether it had been ambushed on Macedonian soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were patrolling an area in which they had partolled for
some time,'' said Bacon. ``They were familiar with the area.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon also couldn't say whether the Americans, who were
armed with M-16 infantry rifles, returned fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that they were trying to take escape (cq) and
evasive action,'' said Bacon, ``but obviously that failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor could the Pentagon say with certainty who captured the
troops whether it was Serb military or police units operating in
the area, for example, or paramilitary troops who later turned them
over to Serb regular forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an investigation going on, and that will answer all
these questions,'' said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   When they were ambushed, the troops radioed to two other Humvees
patrolling nearby. Troops in the two other Humvees set off
searching for their fellow soldiers, but couldn't find them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They reported being under fire and being surrounded,'' said
Bacon. ``At that point the radio broadcast broke off. That's all
the information we have.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and NATO forces conducted what Bacon called a ``massive''
search and rescue effort involving more than 80 American troops on
the ground and in a Blackhawk combat helicopter. They were joined
by more than 60 French troops, two British helicopters, French and
Italian helicopters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also at one time had an aircraft up with some infrared
capability to try to find the Humvee,'' said Bacon. ``But the
weather was very bad last night and the search was difficult. And,
of course, in the end it was unsuccessful.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, Gonzales and Stone were part of a small contingent of
American troops in Macedonia providing support to a NATO force of
between 10,000 and 12,000 soldiers, Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO force has been patrolling Macedonia's border with
Kosovo in part to prevent violence in that province from spilling
over into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO force would be the vanguard of a larger peacekeeping
force, should a cease-fire be reached in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
