<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves home for preview
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves are back. Atlanta plays the Orioles at 7:10
p.m. today in an exhibition game at Turner Field and the Indians at
1:10 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But with the advent of interleague play, the excitement of
seeing American League teams in the ballpark isn't the same. So
what does a pair of glorified spring training games in Atlanta have
to offer?
</P>
<P>
   For the fans, it's a first glimpse of the 1999 edition of the
Braves. It'll give them a look at Ryan Klesko at first base, Bret
Boone at second, Brian Jordan in right field and Otis Nixon, in his
return to Atlanta, in left. Mark Wohlers is scheduled to pitch
tonight, giving Atlanta fans a chance to witness his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz will pitch against Scott Erickson of the Orioles and
Kevin Millwood faces hard-throwing Bartolo Colon of the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   For Braves players, it's a chance to spend several nights at
home after spending seven weeks in Florida, get in some final work
before the season starts and reacquaint themselves with Turner
Field. For Jordan and other new players, it's a chance to get a
feel for their new home park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets you in front of the home crowd, gets the adrenaline
and emotions started,'' Jordan said. ``That's a tone-setter.''
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones said, ``It's knowing the regular season is right
around the corner, it's your own fans that watch you religiously,
and it's good we go in and kind of get your feet wet before that
first pitch against (Philadelphia's Curt) Schilling on Monday.
We're looking forward to it. We've got two good teams coming in and
they'll be two good games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have won three of four this spring from the Indians.
The Atlanta pitchers have faced one of baseball's best lineups, one
that makes Cleveland a heavy favorite to win its fifth AL Central
title in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles slumped last year trying to defend the East and fell
to fourth, in part because of injuries in the starting rotation and
a disappointing year by the bullpen. Gone are Roberto Alomar and
Rafael Palmeiro, but the Orioles added Albert Belle and catcher
Charles Johnson. With Mike Mussina back to health, the Orioles
expect to contend.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the Braves are glad to be home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can go home and get guys on the home field for
two games, it's good,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``We'll get three
extra nights there. We've got a long road trip right out of the
chute (April 12-26), so at least we get to go home for a little
bit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
