<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Busch, truck series on tap
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Most Winston Cup drivers are enjoying a rare weekend
off for Easter, but racing fans still can watch action in NASCAR's
other two series.
</P>
<P>
   A few Cup drivers will be competing in Saturday's BellSouth
Mobility 320 at Nashville Speedway, 2 p.m. CBS. Among the drivers
attempting to qualify for the Busch Grand National race are Cup
regulars Geoffrey Bodine, Buckshot Jones, Kevin Lepage, Sterling
Marlin, Joe Nemechek and Elliott Sadler.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a Winston Cup rookie from Tucker, will replace Larry
Pearson in the No. 00 Pontiac. Pearson injured his lower back in
last week's Busch race at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   The Craftsman Truck series will be celebrating the 100th race in
its five-year history in Saturday's NAPA Card 200 at Evergreen
Speedway in Monroe, Wash., 4:30 p.m. on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Five drivers _ Rick Carelli, Ron Hornaday, Butch Miller, Joe
Ruttman and Jack Sprague _ can collect a $100,000 bonus by winning
the race. They're the only drivers who have competed in every event
since the series' inception in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've raced for $100,'' Ruttman said. ``If we won, we paid our
expenses and were able to race the next week. It wasn't a lot, but
we did it for fun. That's why we still do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior's back
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR legend Junior Johnson, who won 50 races in 14 seasons,
1953-66, returns to racing as a consultant for Sasser Motorsports,
which makes its debut at Nashville this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who sold his Winston Cup team to Brett Bodine in 1995,
doesn't have a financial investment in the venture and won't be
involved in the day-to-day operations. But Johnson says he'll help
the team in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had some great offers to get back into racing,'' Johnson
said. `` ... I just thanked them for remembering me and said, `No,
thanks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cook will drive the No. 65 Chevy of Sasser Motorsports,
which plans on racing in five events this year and adding a second
car next season.
</P>
<P>
   Injury list
</P>
<P>
   Several Winston Cup drivers can use the open date. Mike Skinner,
who fell from first to ninth in the points standings the last two
races, cracked his right shoulder blade in a hard crash last week
at Texas. It's the same shoulder Skinner injured at Texas a year
ago. He's undergoing physical therapy this week, and owner Richard
Childress will have a relief driver standing by at Bristol on April
11.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon has sore ribs and a badly bruised shoulder coming
off the worst finish of his career. Jimmy Spencer complained of
soreness after the Primestar 500 and skipped a testing session at
Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
