</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monday mania: Falcons in prime spots
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Falcons lost the Super Bowl, but won the hearts of
TV executives.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL released its schedule Wednesday, and Atlanta will play
three games on ABC's ``Monday Night Football'' and an ESPN prime
time Sunday game, and two other games will be part of Fox national
doubleheaders.
</P>
<P>
   Also, it was announced that the start time for ``Monday Night
Football'' will return to 9 p.m. after a year at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta is just 5-15 on Mondays and has lost seven in a row
since a 31-30 home win over Minnesota in 1981. The Falcons' season
opener will be a Sunday, Sept. 12, rematch of the NFC Championship
Game, in which the Falcons beat the Vikings 30-27 in overtime. The
second game will be Monday, Sept. 20, at Dallas, and the season
finale will be Monday, Jan. 3, against NFC West rival San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Atlanta has a Monday night road game at Pittsburgh
(Oct. 25) and four road games in five weeks in the second half of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest part of the schedule will be right after the bye
week (Nov. 14),'' coach Dan Reeves said. ``Again, to get the
Falcons organization back on `Monday Night Football' is great.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning the NFC West earned Atlanta a schedule that includes
three division champs _ Minnesota, Dallas, Jacksonville _ and six
playoff teams.
</P>
<P>
   FALCONS SCHEDULE
</P>
