</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Potential draftees begin visits soon
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With the NFL draft set for April 17, some 20 college
players tentatively are scheduled to visit Suwanee in the next 10
days or so for interviews with Falcon officals.
</P>
<P>
   They include cornerbacks Antoine Winfield (5 feet 8 5/8, 176
pounds, Ohio State), Fernando Bryant (5-10, 183, Alabama), Fred
Vinson (5-10 5/8, 177, Vanderbilt) and safety/corner Antwan Edwards
(6-0 1/4, 210, Clemson); defensive ends Patrick Kerney (6-5 5/8,
266, Virginia) and Lamar King (6-3, 299, Saginaw Valley State); and
defensive tackles Anthony McFarland (6-0 1/2, 299, LSU), Reggie
McGrew (6-1 7/8, 307, Florida).
</P>
<P>
   Offensive tackles slated to visit are Georgia's Matt Stinchcomb
(6-6, 306) and Chris Terry (6-4 7/8, 291), Kris Farris (6-7 7/8,
313, UCLA), Soloman Page (6-4 3/8, 306, West Virginia), Jon Jansen
(6-6 3/8, 305, Michigan) and Lonnie Shelton (6-5 1/2, 341, Eastern
Michigan). Others slated are wide receivers Peerless Price (5-10
7/8, 180, Tennessee), Kevin Johnson (5-11 1/8, 194, Syracuse), Troy
Edwards (5-9 1/2, 191, La. Tech) and fullback Rob Konrad (6-3, 251,
Syracuse).
</P>
<P>
   Schedule notes
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta will play 10 regular-season games in domes next season.
Last season, the Falcons were 13-0 in domes, including the
playoffs. . . . Next fall will be the third time the Falcons have
played three Monday night games. They were 1-2 in 1979 and in 1981.
. . . Atlanta's opponents for next season were a combined 126-130
last season. Last season's opponents were 106-150. Last season's
nondivision opponents were 54-74. Next season's nondivisional
opponents were 74-54.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have about $1.5 million left under the salary cap. .
. . Rather than waive free safety Eugene Robinson, which would
create $1.55 million more in cap space, the team could ask him to
take a cut in his $1.8 million base salary. . . . Several weeks
ago, the Falcons and free-agent cornerback Ashley Ambrose were $1
million per year apart. But Ambrose, who was seeking $4 million per
year, knows the market is drying up and is talking about playing
out a one-year contract. Atlanta remains interested. . . . Atlanta
has 60 players on the roster before re-signing deep snapper Adam
Schreiber. The Falcons can take 81 to training camp. . . . Former
San Francisco and Miami wide receiver Iheanyi Uwaezuoke, a free
agent, worked out in Suwanee this week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
