<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAISMITH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Driesell again top state coach
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Georgia State coach Lefty Driesell, who last fall
joined Dean Smith, Adolph Rupp and Bobby Knight among those with
700 career wins, will be one of many figures from high school and
college basketball to be honored Saturday in the annual Atlanta
Tipoff Club Naismith Awards banquet at the Cobb Galleria Centre.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tribute to our players and our coaching staff,'' said
Driesell, selected state Division I coach of the year for the
second consecutive year. ``Hopefully, it says that we're serious
about basketball and about trying to develop a strong and
respectable program.''
</P>
<P>
   In Driesell's second season at Georgia State, the Panthers' 17
wins set a school season record. Georgia State has gone 16-12 and
17-13 under Driesell.
</P>
<P>
   The Naismith national college players of the year are sophomore
forward Elton Brand of Duke and Tennessee senior Chamique
Holdsclaw, while the coaches are Mike Krzyzewski of Duke and
Carolyn Peck of Purdue. Peck led Purdue to a 34-1 record and the
NCAA women's championship, and Krzyzewski led the Blue Devils to
the national title game before losing to Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's Andy Landers, whose Lady Bulldogs (27-7) made the
Final Four before losing to Duke, is Georgia Division I women's
coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Others to receive state honors include Georgia Tech's Niesha
Butler (women's Division I) and Jumaine Jones of Georgia (men's
Division I); Kennesaw State's women's coach Colby Tilley and Owls
senior Dion Thornton (Division II); Augusta State coach Gary Tull
and senior guard Kavossy Franklin (Division II); Georgia
Southwestern coach Randolph Barksdale and Hurricanes senior Ernest
Scott (NAIA), and North Georgia women's coach Buffie Burson-Watson
and Lady Saints junior Morey LeFeve (NAIA).
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Perimeter College men's coach Alfred Barney and shooting
guard Derrick Lyons, along with Middle Georgia women's coach Greg
Wilson and Lady Warriors standout Latasha Jackson, will be awarded
junior college honors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
