<HEADER>
A3168 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-     04-01 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVENTS LEADING TO CAPTURE OF U.S. SOLDIERS STILL UNCLEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: subs lede to correct last message from GIs) (ATTN: Calif.,
Mich., Texas)  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-SOLIDERS,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REGUGEES, KOSOVO-EUROPE,
KOSOVO-RIGHTS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-RELIGION, KOSOVO-BOSNIA) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUMANOVO, Macedonia _ It was around 4 p.m. Wednesday when the
three-man American reconnaissance unit radioed in to base to say
they had come under fire. The reply came back asking if the message
was a joke. But the unit was not joking. ``We're taking direct
fire, they said. ``We're trapped ... They're all around us ... We
can't get out ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not have time to say where they were,'' said Lt. Col.
Eric Kersabiec, ``so we took it seriously.'' Kersabiec, commander
of the main NATO base here, said he then ordered out search parties
and sent up a helicopter with night vision to scour the border
region through the night.
</P>
<P>
   They found nothing. Thursday morning the American soldiers
turned up on Yugoslav television looking bruised and exhausted,
captives of the Belgrade authorities.
</P>
<P>
   The men, all cavalry scouts, were Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez,
24, of Los Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths
Creek, Mich., and Specialist Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The three, from the 1st Squadron, Fourth Cavalry of the First
Infantry Division, were among only 350 American soldiers in
Macedonia. Until recently they were part of the U.N. mission in
Macedonia, but in the last two weeks they have been used for
reconnaissance work along the border with Yugoslavia, watching for
incursions or any hostilities aimed at the NATO forces based not
far from the border.
</P>
<P>
   The men were on a routine patrol close to the Yugoslav border,
some 10 miles northeast of Kumanovo in an area of Macedonia
predominantly populated by ethnic Serbs. Their patrol would have
brought them up to the one-kilometer buffer zone before the border.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt among fellow soldiers on the ground that
they were seized by armed Serbian villagers who were cooperating
with Yugoslav forces across the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a strong Serb minority that feels very close to
Serbia,'' Kersabiec said.
</P>
<P>
   Another officer, who spoke on the condition of anonymity, said,
``Of course the Yugoslav Army obtained information from locals.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the locals took them,'' said a European officer
leading a reconnaissance unit. He said he suspected that the Serbs
would have been watching the soldiers and when they spotted three
men on their own, had moved in to seize them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every man in this area has a Kalashnikov in his house,'' he
said. ``We are in hostile territory here. We know that the threat
is not from the north, but it is all around us.''
</P>
<P>
   The officer was leading a reconnaissance unit of four armored
vehicles topped with heavy machine guns. His men were all armed
with automatic rifles, and wore heavy duty bulletproof vests,
although only some bothered with helmets.
</P>
<P>
   NATO soldiers in the area all said they had encountered
hostility from villagers who hurled stones and bricks at their
armored vehicles. One French unit was parked near a bridge where
``NATO Go Home'' was daubed in red paint.
</P>
<P>
   How the capture actually happened remained unclear Thursday. The
three men were patrolling in a Humvee, an armored vehicle that is
fast and versatile on rough terrain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is fully armored and weighs about seven tons,'' said a
spokesman at the unit's base at the main airport just outside
Skopje, the Macedonian capital. The men must have been outside the
vehicle when they were apprehended, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want that to happen to anyone, but especially when
they are your friends,'' he added. The three men had arrived only
on Feb. 16 from their squadron's base near Wurzburg, Germany, for a
six-month tour of duty.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The officers here made no reference to reports that the men had
been separated from a larger patrol.
</P>
<P>
   The region where they disappeared is full of curving valleys
between craggy cliffs and ridges. Small farming villages with
red-tiled houses nestle in the valleys. At the village of Pelince,
just a mile short of the border with Yugoslavia, half a dozen armed
policemen were standing outside a white-washed building.
</P>
<P>
   Several others, dressed in camouflage fatigues, disappeared
quickly inside. The men outside were Macedonian policemen, but one
man on the edge of the group had a Yugoslav flag on the sleeve of
his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Most were ethnic Serbs and clearly sympathized with their
neighbors across the border, who less than a decade ago had been
their countrymen in the old Yugoslavia. They spoke out angrily
against the NATO bombing in Serbia. ``We hear the planes and hear
the explosions as they bomb,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   They said that they knew nothing of the missing American
servicemen but that they had seen them come through regularly on
patrol.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, working so close to the border, that the men
simply got lost, a NATO officer said. ``If you are right on the
border, you just have to turn a corner and you are in Serbia,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that could have led to their capture is their
transformation overnight from being a U.N. peacekeeping task force,
to becoming, or being perceived as, the main actor in the war next
door. Their original role as a U.N. force may have made the U.S.
unit vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   American troops have been in Macedonia for three years as part
of the U.N. mission, sent in to secure the Macedonian border and
watch for any potential spillover from the wars in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Since the U.N. mission ended on Feb. 28, after China refused to
agree to further extend the mandate in Macedonia, the task force is
being dismantled. The American troops who took part in the mission
have continued their reconnaissance duties under American command,
continuing the U. N.'s job of patrolling a half-mile zone between
the border and the French and British NATO forces, based in
Kumanovo.
</P>
<P>
   The American troops are, however, not part of the NATO
peacekeeping force assembled to keep order in Kosovo in the event a
political settlement. ``These guys are not used to having
trouble,'' a NATO officer said. ``They are not used to being
threatened. We, on the other hand, arrived ready as a fighting
force.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
