<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-C17-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING OFFERS DISCOUNT IF AIR FORCE BUYS MORE C-17 TRANSPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In a bold move that would extend production of its
C-17 military transport plane out to at least 2007, The Boeing Co.
has offered to cut the price of the $195 million plane by 15
percent if the Air Force buys 60 more.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is under contract to build 120 of the planes for the Air
Force, and delivered the 49th last week. Without new orders, the
production line in Long Beach, Calif, would shut down in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing President Harry Stonecipher personally delivered Boeing's
proposal to the Air Force Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force is conducting a study to determine its long-range
air lift needs. It will be later this the year before the Air Force
completes that study and it will then make a decision on Boeing's
offer, said Air Force spokeswoman Gloria Cales.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday in Washington, D.C., to announce
details of the company's unsolicited bid, Stu Thomson, Boeing's
vice president for business development, told reporters Boeing
wanted to have its best price for the C-17 ``on the table'' while
the Air Force study is under way.
</P>
<P>
   He said Boeing will spent $275 million of its own money on
cost-savings initiatives to make the C-17 more affordable for the
Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing C-17 spokesman Rick Fuller said the Boeing initiative
would yield about $3 in cost savings for every $1 expended.
</P>
<P>
   The C-17 is Boeing's most profitable airplane, with
significantly better margins than the company's flagship 747,
according to aerospace analysts.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Air Force is the only customer for the C-17. In
addition to the 120 planes on order, the Air Force is seeking about
$3 billion from Congress to buy 15 more of the transports for
special operations.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting the price of the C-17 could also help Boeing win foreign
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has so far failed to win a single foreign order for the
C-17, in part due to its high cost. Boeing recently submitted a
C-17 proposal to the United Kingdom's defense ministry, which wants
to lease four military cargo jets with the capability of the C-17
for delivery beginning in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   With the current order backlog, production in Long Beach will
peak at 15 planes a year beginning in 2002. McChord Air Force Base
near Tacoma will get the first of 48 C-17s in July. They will
eventually replace the aging fleet of C-141s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
