<SLUG> BC-TV-DUEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST OF A&AMP;E'S `HORNBLOWER' SERIES SETS THE STANDARD HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evidently, the people who made ``The Duel'' aren't practiced in
the wily ways of Hollywood. There isn't a female with a speaking
role in the entire cast. No Elizabeth Hurley lookalike to romance
our hero, Horatio Hornblower. No secondary love story to keep
things afloat between the trimming of mainsails and swashing of
buckles.
</P>
<P>
   What were they thinking? Do they not remember the first day of
Action/Adventure Filmmaking 101, when everyone learns that war is
hell and war without women is hell on reels? See what it got
``Private Ryan?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the first of four ``Horatio Hornblower'' films produced by
A&AMP;E Television Networks and England's United Broadcasting &AMP;
Entertainment _ the same team that did the dreamily romantic ``Jane
Austen's Emma'' _ bravely persists in its guy-centricity.
</P>
<P>
   And surprise! It works splendidly because of a fine cast, a
brisk pace and a commanding performance by Ioan Gruffudd (yo-IN
GRIF-iths), who may be remembered by some keen-eyed moviegoers as
Fifth Officer Lowe in James Cameron's ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't despair, all you lovers of Jane Austen. Hornblower will
eventually rub elbows with the opposite sex (in films three and
four). But Sunday's first installment in this quartet of
stand-alone dramas is notable for staying true to the goal of
establishing Hornblower as a peach-fuzzy boy struggling to stay
afloat in a gene-typing pool brimming with machismo.
</P>
<P>
   Welshman Gruffudd, still a newcomer to cinema, brings to the
character of Hornblower the uncertainty, exuberance and courageous
impetuousness of youth. It is the late 18th century, the Napoleonic
Wars are thrusting England into war with France. As the 17-year-old
son of a physician who seems completely at sea about being at sea,
Hornblower is at once eager and frightened, appreciative and
appalled to be a midshipman in the king's navy. His thoughts even
turn to suicide _ briefly _ and Gruffudd is equal to the test,
expressing every emotion appropriately: sometimes subtly, sometimes
not, but always with the upper lip stiff.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Duel,'' Hornblower's nemesis isn't so much the French
as it is another English midshipman. This oafish fellow, Jack
Simpson by name, is everything Hornblower is not: boastful, mean,
manipulative, dishonest, insensitive. He's the schoolyard bully,
the big-talk guy at the staff meetings who never, ever delivers but
always manages to skate by.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he's a coward in warrior's clothing, too, and Dorian
Healy is so thoroughly slimy in the role you might have to wipe an
oil slick from the screen as the credits roll. But Simpson is also
the catalyst for Hornblower's hasty metamorphosis from callow sea
scout to crafty seafarer, a sea change that might be implausible in
another context but hits convincingly as cannons thunder and
yardarms splinter.
</P>
<P>
   When Hornblower first boards the frigate Indefatigable, his
commanding officer, Captain Pellew, dismisses anything he might
have heard about the untested Hornblower, saying, ``I judge a man
by what I see him do.''
</P>
<P>
   Hornblower himself is a manchild of principle. Thanks in large
part to deft cinematic touches by director Andrew Grieve (and
director of photography Neve Cunningham), Hornblower's deeds speak
louder and land harder as he gains the confidence and trust of
those serving with him. Near the end of the film, Pellew says, ``I
see something in you, Mr. Hornblower. ... A great future awaits
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Credit Gruffudd and Healy, with an assist to Robert Lindsay as
the unflappable Captain Pellew.
</P>
<P>
   For lovers of C.S. Forester's ``Hornblower'' books, all four
films in this A&AMP;E series are based on ``Mr. Midshipman
Hornblower,'' published in 1950. With generous embellishment, ``The
Duel'' encompasses the first five chapters. Subsequent films,
airing on successive Sundays, are ``The Fire Ships,'' covering
chapters seven through nine; ``The Duchess &AMP; The Devil,'' chapter
10, and ``The Wrong War,'' chapter six.
</P>
<P>
   If they're as good as ``The Duel,'' viewers are in for a
delightful month of Sundays on A&AMP;E. A word of warning, though:
``The Duel'' is occasionally violent and bloody, and it includes a
scene involving rats that will turn more stomachs than a
storm-tossed ride on HMS Indefatigable.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if parents are looking for a sumptuously produced,
smartly told story about a young person's acquisition of leadership
and character under trying circumstances, they won't be
disappointed by the outcome of ``The Duel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Duel. First of four ``Horatio Hornblower'' films based on
the character created by C.S. Forester and airing on consecutive
Sundays in April. ``The Duel,'' starring Ioan Gruffudd, Dorian
Healy, Robert Lindsay, Paul Copley and Sean Gilder, premieres
Sunday on A&AMP;E. Parental guideline rating: TV-PG.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
