<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-HOFFARTH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARV TO LAKERS? YE ... NO!
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So I'm having this recurring fantasy about Marv
Albert. (Nah, it's not what you think.)
</P>
<P>
   It starts with Chick Hearn who, God bless him, decides to
retire. The Lakers throw him a big teary-eyed party. Then they
close the refrigerator door. The search begins for a new
play-by-play man _ one for TV, one for radio, as it should be.
</P>
<P>
   And here comes Marv. End of daydream?
</P>
<P>
   Seems so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love coming to the West Coast, and one of the nice things
about games in L.A. is the climate, but . . .'' Albert said.
</P>
<P>
   The best Albert can do is show up for TNT tonight at 5 p.m. to
call the Lakers-Suns game in Phoenix. It'll be his first national
exposure _ and (begin ital)there's(end ital) a word we're not sure
is wise to use _ since NBC fired him in the fall of '97, when
assault charges were brought up as revelations about a kinky
personal lifestyle were reported.
</P>
<P>
   There were times in the last year-and-a-half when Albert, long
considered not just the voice of the New York Knicks but of the
NBA, didn't know if he'd ever get a chance to do one of these
coast-to-coast broadcasts again.
</P>
<P>
   He admits in the months when he was putting his life back
together he never thought about uprooting New York and making a
complete change of scenery in forgiving Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so ingrained in New York and my family and so many
friends are here,'' Albert said. ``I'm so comfortable here in New
York, and I love the city. And the Madison Square Garden network
has been so terrific to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect what Chick has accomplished over the years . . .
(coming to L.A.) is not something I even think about. It doesn't
enter my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But with TNT's coverage going head-to-head with KCAL's, viewers
might not automatically click onto Chick tonight; many could listen
instead to Albert with analyst Reggie Theus and sideline reporter
Cheryl Miller.
</P>
<P>
   This will be is the only game involving the Lakers that Albert
has on his six-game TNT assignment sheet. He's been doing selected
radio play-by-play on Knicks games (although he didn't make the
team's Western trip that included a stop at the Forum last Sunday)
as well as hosting the week-night studio show for the Madison
Square Garden cable channel.
</P>
<P>
   Since he's eased back into TV work and continues to field media
questions about his progress with counseling and a new marriage,
Albert realizes it's all ``part of the process and in many ways a
good thing for me to express feelings I have. Being part of the
media, I understand what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   He says fans in New York and elsewhere have ``been terrific''
toward him. TNT executive producer Mike Pearl says there's been no
negative mail, e-mail or phone calls about the hiring. And when
Albert attended a network advertising photo shoot in New York about
two weeks ago and had time to talk basketball with Theus, Hubie
Brown, Dick Stockton, Doc Rivers and others, Albert said he felt
welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was going into this game without having done games with
the Knicks already this season, I'd have a lot more anxiety,'' said
Albert, who actually made his TNT debut as a studio analyst last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Theus, the Lakers' pregame show regular on Fox Sports West, says
he's been listening to tapes of games that Albert has done recently
to get in tune with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing Marv said was important for us was to just have
fun,'' said Theus. ``I'm excited. This man is synonomous with the
NBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert on Rodman: One of the sidelights to tonight's game is
what kind of opinions Albert might have about the antics of Lakers
forward Dennis Rodman. Albert was asked about that on a conference
call with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to make a judgment on someone's lifestyle,'' Albert
said rather ironically. ``I don't know if what we see publicly
takes place privately. . . These days, there seem to be other
standards for guys who can contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Albert, who has had the media spotlight turned on him,
raise those issues on the air?
</P>
<P>
   ``I already have (on MSG) and I would on a telecast,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The ESPN World Tour: After pulling off a telecast from Cuba last
weekend, ESPN's Sunday Night baseball opener from Monterrey,
Mexico, between Colorado and San Diego this week seems simple for
coordinating producer Tim Scanlan.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Cuba game was the most difficult remote I've ever been
part of, not just on the technical limitations but from all the
interested parties involved in the game taking place,'' said
Scanlan of the contest between the Baltimore Orioles and the Cuban
national team.
</P>
<P>
   All of ESPN's expenses in Cuba had to be cleared through the
State Department in advance, Scanlan said. ESPN brought in four
cameras plus its own production truck to add to an eight-camera
set-up already in place by Cuba's national broadcast network. The
transmission of the pictures also went through the Cuban state-run
ministry; ESPN floated over a transmitter from ABC News in Miami as
a backup in case things didn't go as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the technology advances, it's shared worldwide
immediately,'' said Scanlan. `So with all the cultural and language
differences, it came off a lot better than it could have.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 5 p.m. game in Monterrey, ESPN has a most costly
production, having to bring through customs two mobile units and
four huge lighting vehicles to brighten up the stadium. The
downside?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not able to broadcast in stereo,'' said Scanlan.
``That's a luxury we often take for granted.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Staff Writer Tom Hoffarth's media column appears Fridays in the
Daily News. He can be reached at (818) 713-3661 or sptmediaaol.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
_Considering that former Dodgers pitching great Sandy Koufax says
this was only his second extended interview with TV since he
retired in 1966, ESPN's Charley Steiner pulled off quite a feat
convincing him to do the sitdown for tonight's ``SportsCentury''
telecast (7:30 p.m.). Koufax came up No. 42 on the list of the
greatest athletes by the ``SportsCentury'' project voters, of which
Steiner is one. Koufax is also the only pitcher in the top 50,
ranked better than Walter Johnson (60), Satchel Paige (63), Bob
Gibson (67) and Cy Young himself (77). ``(Koufax) is a person who
wants his privacy because he wants to live a normal life, and he
can't do it if his face is on TV all the time,'' said Steiner,
allowed into Koufax's circle after an extended dinner with him last
spring in Florida set up by former broadcast partner Kevin Kennedy.
After explaining to Koufax that his inclusion was an honor, Steiner
said he didn't have to beg too much further for the interview.
``But he did want to take a day in case he changed his mind if he
wanted,'' said Steiner. Thankfully, Koufax didn't. &QL; 
_ESPN's ``SportsCentury'' free interactive mall tour, by the way,
continues through Saturday at the Glendale Galleria. One of the
neat things to do is to make the call of a classic sporting event
and take home a free video of it. &QL; 
_Dodgers broadcaster Ross ``Dress for Less'' Porter gave a lovely
thank you on the air to all the people at Vero Beach, Fla., during
the ninth inning of what could be the team's final game Wednesday _
and then launched into a Ralph Nader-like review about how the
Touch of Class dry cleaners (``Touch of Class . . . that's a
misnomer,'' said Porter) lost $500 worth of his clothes and
wouldn't replace them. Next time we're in Vero, we'll know not to
go there. And we're telling everyone else, too. &QL; 
WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
_If she wanted to, Fox reporter and former ESPN employee Bonnie
Bernstein could probably raise a pretty big stink about the last
episode of ABC's ``Sports Night,'' which hit awfully close to what
viewers could interpret as her home. The newest character on the
dramedy was an anchor named ``Bobbie Bernstein'' (Lisa Edelstein)
who was upset that she had to work with Dan (Josh Charles) because
he didn't remember her from a one-night stand years ago. Hmmmm.
Does that mean next week, someone named ``Lucy Kolber'' will be
caught making out with Dan in the janitorial supply room? &QL; 
_Within minutes of Duke's Final Four win over Michigan State last
Saturday, KCBS-Channel 2's ``Sports Central'' had its Vegas guy,
Caesars Palace bookie Vinny Magliulo, on the air with Jim Hill to
announce that Duke would be a nine-point favorite against UConn in
Monday's final. Now, that's quick service. But is it appropriate,
even to bring Magliulo back on Monday's pre-game show to rehash the
line again? At a time when CBS decided that its own Web site, CBS
SportsLine, had to disconnect a link to an on-line betting service
because it didn't want to appear to be promoting gambling of an
event it was covering, CBS's L.A. affiliate doesn't seem too
bothered by bringing on a guy named Vinny to discuss how bettors
were reacting to this spread. Hill justifies putting on Magliulo
because, in Hill's words, ``everyone's asking right now, what's the
spread?'' after the semifinals. For the record, this newspaper runs
daily point-spread information on the scoreboard page. But when a
network has a serious financial partnership with an event _ where
the underdog eventually wins _ that doesn't look like such a wise
bet.
</P>
</TEXT>
