<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/01/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) HUNTSVILLE, Texas -- April 1, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-3, 4-01 -- Gilbert Gonzales holds up a 1996
photograph of his son, Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, at a press
conference Thursday afternoon in Huntsville. Gonzales, 21, is one
of 3 U.S. soldiers captured near the Macedonian-Yugoslav border.
Also captured were Staff Sgts. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles, and Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
(Karren Warren/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- April 1, 1999 -- NY-COYOTE-PARK, 4-01 --
Tranquilized, a coyote who made his way onto Manhattan Island is
strapped to a stretcher for removal from Central Park on Thursday.
Parks officials say that coyotes have become an increasing presence
in New York City, particularly in the Bronx, but how one got onto
the island of Manhattan - and more specifically, into Central Park
- remains a mystery. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BRECKENRIDGE, Colo. -- April 1, 1999 -- RECKLESS-SKIING,
4-01 -- Andy Lapkass, a ski patrolman at the Breckenridge Ski
Resort in Colorado, talks with two skiers he stopped after they
appeared to be speeding through one of the newly established
slow-skiing zones. Despite dwindling lift ticket sales, Colorado
resorts have recorded 12 skiers and snowboarders killed in
collisions - double the season average and the highest number since
record keeping began 15 years ago. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) ST. LOUIS -- April 1, 1999 -- MO-CONCEALED-WEAPONS, 4-01
-- Korey Davis, 22, of St. Louis, has doubts about a state measure
that would allow Missouri residents to carry a concealed weapon. To
Ms. Davis, who is black and once was held up by ``an itsy-bitsy boy
with a great big gun,'' putting more guns on the street would turn
some urban neighborhoods ``back to the Wild Wild West.'' (Bill
Stover/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) TERRACE HEIGHTS, Wash. -- April 1, 1999 --
IMMIG-WORKERS, 4-01 -- ``This is a nightmare for so many of us,''
says Mireya Chavez, one of more than 560 illegal immigrants fired
in Washington State under orders of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service. She has worked for nine years in Yakima
Valley and has two sons who are American citizens. (Jackie
Johnston/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) ORVIETO, Italy -- April 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL
4 -- MILLENIUM-ORVIETO-COX, 4-01 -- Parishioners worship during
Saturday evening Mass at St. Andrew and St. Bartholomew Church in
Orvieto. It was so cold in the small parish church that worshippers
kept their coats on and small space heathers were placed in the
aisles. (Jean Shifrin/Atlanta Journal Constitution Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) VATICAN CITY -- April 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 4
-- MILLENIUM-VATICAN-COX, 4-01 -- Shafts of light pierce the
interior of St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. Pilgrims and tourists
from around the globe come to see the largest basilica in the
world, home to some of the most important and impressive religious
art anywhere. (Jean Shifrin/Atlanta Journal Constitution Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) VATICAN CITY -- April 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 4
-- MILLENIUM-CHRISTIANITY-COX, 4-01 -- A group of nuns poses for a
photo in front of St. Peter's Basilica, which is obscured by
scaffolding while renovations are being done in preparation for
Rome's celebration of the new millenium. The setting is
appropriate. The history of the faith can be traced by a walk down
these narrow streets. (Jean Shifrin/Atlanta Journal Constitution
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MORINI BORDER CROSSING, Albania -- April 1, 1999 --
KOSOVO-ALBANIA-2, 4-01 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo's
capital city, Pristina, receiving food from Catholic Relief
Services volunteers shortly after crossing the border into Albania
in Morini. The refugees say Serb gunmen have been systematically
emptying Pristina and marching its ethnic Albanians out through
gantlets of masked, heavily armed Serbs. (Edward Keating/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) PETROVEC, Macedonia -- April 1, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-2, 4-01 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo
camped in a field next to the Macedonian border Thursday. Three
American soldiers were captured by Serbs on Thursday while on a
routine patrol close to the Yugoslav border, some 10 miles
northeast of Kumanovo in an area of Macedonia predominantly
populated by ethnic Serbs. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) PETROVEC, Macedonia -- April 1, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-1, 4-01 -- An American soldier in front of M-16
rifles from the Fourth Cavalry, the unit from which three American
soldiers were captured by Serbs on Thursday. The Americans had been
part of the U.N. peacekeeping force which has been in Macedonia
since 1993. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) AOMORI, Japan -- April 1, 1999 -- JAPAN-ORIGINS, 4-01 --
The archeologist Yasuhiro Okada at Aomori, with a reconstructed
tower and houses of the early Jomon people in the background. The
origins of the Japanese people remain a much-debated puzzle, but
part of it is being pieced together here on the vast archeological
site some 375 miles north of Tokyo. (Nicholas D. Kristoff/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MORINI BORDER CROSSING, Albania -- April 1, 1999 --
KOSOVO-ALBANIA-1, 4-01 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo's
capital city, Pristina, waiting for transport shortly after
crossing the border into Albania in Morini on Thursday. The
refugees say Serb gunmen have been systematically emptying Pristina
and marching its ethnic Albanians out through gantlets of masked,
heavily armed Serbs. (Edward Keating/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- April 1, 1999 -- WEIR-THEATER-REVIEW, 4-01 --
The cast of Conor McPherson's play ``The Weir,'' which opened
Thursday night at the Walter Kerr, includes, from left, Kieran
Ahern, Dermot Crowley, Brendan Coyle, Jim Norton and Michelle
Fairley. Under the seamless, gentle direction of Ian Rickson, the
show's five actors make an unforgettable case for the impossibility
of distinguishing the teller from the tale. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- April 1, 1999 -- ENNIO-COMEDY, 4-01 -- Shane
Dundas, left, and David Collins are the Umbilical Brothers in
``Thwak'' at the Westbeth Theater. The production is an exuberant
and effortlessly funny showcase for their arsenal of Saturday
morning cartoons come to life. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- April 1, 1999 -- SUSANNAH-OPERA-REVIEW, 4-01
-- Renee Fleming and Jerry Hadley in ``Susannah'' at the
Metropolitan. Amiable, direct and wholly without guile, Carlisle
Floyd's American heroine and the work that bears her name arrived
in the halls of grand opera on Wednesday night, looking like some
lonely tourist lost in the vastness of Grand Central Terminal.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- April 1, 1999 -- THEATER-NOTES, 4-01 -- The
British soap star Anna Friel is in ``Closer'' at the Music Box.
Despite her popularity overseas, she remains little known
stateside. ``No one has a clue who I am,'' says Ms. Friel. ``It's
really lovely.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- April 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 4 --
READING-ROOM-ANTIQUES-B&AMP;W, 4-01 -- An original and its copy in the
refurbished main reading room at the New York Public Library: a
restored saddle-seat chair, right, and its reproduction. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- April 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 4 --
SPACEY-ICEMAN-THEATER, 4-01 -- Kevin Spacey as the salesman Hickey
in Eugene O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh.'' ``There are a thousand
little reasons why this matters so much,'' he says. ``But
basically, to be part of a production where this play gets heard
and people respond to it is something maybe you do once in a
lifetime.'' (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- April 1, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 4 --
GYPSY-DANCE, 4-01 -- Sayeri Sapera, a dancer with Musafir, a group
from Rajasthan, India, is part of the Gypsy Caravan tour, which
will be at City Center on Friday and Saturday. The story of Gypsy
music is one of flexibility backed by hidden tenacity. (Stephanie
Berger/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
