<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3182 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-BOMBS-SPI &LR;      04-01 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-BOMBS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE WANTS MORE BOEING KITS TO MAKE DUMB BOMBS SMART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Air Force wants Boeing to speed up production of a
guidance kit that turns dumb 2,000-pound bombs into smart ones in
case the service runs short during what could become a long bombing
campaign over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   These bomb kits, known as Joint Direct Attack Munition, or JDAM,
are built in St. Charles, Mo., and have been used for the first
time in combat during Operation Allied Force.
</P>
<P>
   They have so far been fitted to 2,000-pound bombs dropped by the
stealth B-2 bomber.
</P>
<P>
   The B-1 bomber, which has been sent to the region, will also
drop the Boeing bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The smart bombs are dropped up to 15 miles from targets and
signals from the global positioning satellite system help keep them
on track.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force not only wants to accelerate production of the
JDAM kits under an existing contract with Boeing, but wants to buy
about 1,100 more, Air Force spokesman Gloria Cales told the
Post-Intelligencer Thursday. She did not know how much additional
money that might mean for Boeing. The kits cost about $18,000 each.
Including production and support the Air Force is paying about
$23,000 for each.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman Tom Downey in St. Louis, headquarters of the
company's fighter and missile programs, confirmed Boeing is talking
with the Air Force, but he declined further comment and referred
questions to the Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   Cales said the Air Force wants Boeing to increase production of
the JDAM kits from 110 a month now to 200 per month.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is supposed to provide the Air Force information before
the end of the week on how rapidly and at what cost it could ramp
up production, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with Defense Daily, Joseph Diamond, Air Force
program executive officer for missiles, said he believes Boeing
could reach the higher production rate within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're looking at now is a ramp that is consistent with
production plans already in place, just accelerated,'' he told the
publication. ``They (Boeing) are going to increase their capacity
sooner or later anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Bombs fitted with JDAM kits can be used in all kinds of weather,
which makes them more effective than traditional laser-guided smart
bombs in Yugoslavia, where many NATO bombing missions have been
hampered by poor weather.
</P>
<P>
   JDAM is still in low-rate production. Of the first lot of 937
kits, Boeing has delivered all but 108 to the Air Force, Cales
said. The second lot is for 2,202 kits, followed by a third lot of
2,500 kits.
</P>
<P>
   Given NATO's plans to increase bombing missions over Yugoslavia,
the small number of JDAM-equipped bombs so far produced by Boeing
for the Air Force could soon be gone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
