   (NYT20) HUNTSVILLE, Texas -- April 1, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-3, 4-01 -- Gilbert Gonzales holds up a 1996
photograph of his son, Spc. Steven M. Gonzales, at a press
conference Thursday afternoon in Huntsville. Gonzales, 21, is one
of 3 U.S. soldiers captured near the Macedonian-Yugoslav border.
Also captured were Staff Sgts. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles, and Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.
(Karren Warren/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- April 1, 1999 -- NY-COYOTE-PARK, 4-01 --
Tranquilized, a coyote who made his way onto Manhattan Island is
strapped to a stretcher for removal from Central Park on Thursday.
Parks officials say that coyotes have become an increasing presence
in New York City, particularly in the Bronx, but how one got onto
the island of Manhattan - and more specifically, into Central Park
- remains a mystery. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BRECKENRIDGE, Colo. -- April 1, 1999 -- RECKLESS-SKIING,
4-01 -- Andy Lapkass, a ski patrolman at the Breckenridge Ski
Resort in Colorado, talks with two skiers he stopped after they
appeared to be speeding through one of the newly established
slow-skiing zones. Despite dwindling lift ticket sales, Colorado
resorts have recorded 12 skiers and snowboarders killed in
collisions - double the season average and the highest number since
record keeping began 15 years ago. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) ST. LOUIS -- April 1, 1999 -- MO-CONCEALED-WEAPONS, 4-01
-- Korey Davis, 22, of St. Louis, has doubts about a state measure
that would allow Missouri residents to carry a concealed weapon. To
Ms. Davis, who is black and once was held up by ``an itsy-bitsy boy
with a great big gun,'' putting more guns on the street would turn
some urban neighborhoods ``back to the Wild Wild West.'' (Bill
Stover/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) TERRACE HEIGHTS, Wash. -- April 1, 1999 --
IMMIG-WORKERS, 4-01 -- ``This is a nightmare for so many of us,''
says Mireya Chavez, one of more than 560 illegal immigrants fired
in Washington State under orders of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service. She has worked for nine years in Yakima
Valley and has two sons who are American citizens. (Jackie
Johnston/New York Times Photo)
</P>
