<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECKLESS-SKIING-ART-6     04-01 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECKLESS-SKIING-ART-680&AMP;ADD-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESORTS TARGETING RECKLESS SKIERS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRECKENRIDGE, Colo. _ Whizzing down Crescendo and cutting across
Swinger, hot-shot skiers and snowboarders on these intermediate
slopes now run into a speed trap on snow. Yellow banners suddenly
caution: ``Speed control in progress'' and ``No Warnings.''
</P>
<P>
   At the top of this new ``slow skiing zone,'' Caroline Elliott, a
Breckenridge Ski Resort employee, recently called out to two
speeding young men, ``Please make some turns.''
</P>
<P>
   Farther down the slope, linked by radio, members of the ski
patrol stood waiting, armed with wire clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone wants to be confrontational, and let the
four-letter words fly, I just take their pass,'' said William A.
Jensen, the resort's chief operating officer, who also skis patrol
duty. ``Very few policemen will allow you to go 100 and not give
you a ticket. We don't give you a ticket. We pull your ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   This hard line on reckless skiing comes after a hard winter in
Colorado. Even though the number of lift tickets sold is down this
season, Colorado resorts have recorded 12 skiers and snowboarders
killed in collisions _ double the season average and the highest
number since record keeping began 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Breckenridge has been the hardest hit, recording five of the
fatalities during one month in midwinter. Now, Breckenridge is the
most visible in an industrywide effort to improve skiing safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been far and away the worst year for the recreational
skier in Colorado,'' said Jim Chalat, a lawyer who represents the
family of a 13-year-old Texas boy who died March 21 after skiing
into a boundary rope at Beaver Creek. ``For hitting trees,
collisions, at the major ski areas it has been just awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's spike in skiing and snowboarding deaths does not seem
to indicate that these sports have become any more dangerous than
before, and ski experts largely consider Colorado's bad winter as a
fluke.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, 33 people have been killed this year, the same
number as the annual average for the last seven seasons. This
fatality rate makes skiing and snowboarding more dangerous than
bicycling and slightly safer than swimming. Statistics indicate
that driving to a ski resort is riskier than skiing there.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 25 years, the rate of skiing injuries requiring
medical attention has dropped in half, to about 1 injury for every
400 lift tickets sold, said Jasper E. Shealy, who has been studying
ski injuries for almost 30 years, most recently for the Rochester
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond a search for safety, the speeding crackdown here and
elsewhere _ highly popular among women and older skiers _ also
reflects the realization by resort operators that their bread is
increasingly being buttered by the older generation.
</P>
<P>
   Today's resorts do not make their money selling lift tickets.
Indeed, because of poor snow and a weak Canadian dollar, the
Colorado ski industry expects a 5 percent drop in ticket sales this
season. Instead, the big money is now in real estate.
</P>
<P>
   In early March, Breckenridge unveiled plans to build 853 ski-in
ski-out condominiums. A few peaks to the east, Keystone Resort
plans to build almost 1,700 single-family homes and condominiums
over the next five years. Building lots will start at $300,000, and
condominiums will be priced as high as $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Ten miles to the west of here, Copper Mountain Resort in
February sold $53 million worth of second home real estate in seven
hours. Even at Winter Park, long a bargain area for day trippers
from Denver, ski condominiums have pole vaulted in price to $425 a
square foot.
</P>
<P>
   With 51 years the average age for an American to buy a second
home, ski resorts do not want testosterone-crazed young skiers to
rule the slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the destination resorts, their principal clientele is from
the baby boom generation, the `gold coasters,''' Michael Berry,
president of the National Ski Areas Association, said, referring to
affluent skiers who fly here from New York and Los Angeles. ``That
clientele wants a more managed environment.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
