<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RECKLESS-SKIING-ART-6     04-01 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECKLESS-SKIING-ART-680&AMP;ADD-(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BRECKENRIDGE: managed environment.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In Colorado, the nation's most popular state for skiing, skiers
and snowboarders are increasingly older and wealthier than before,
according to a recent survey for Colorado Ski Country USA, an
industry group.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of five winters, the median household income of
Colorado ski area patrons jumped by 57 percent, hitting $87,200 in
the 1998-1999 winter. The segment earning $200,000 almost tripled,
hitting 18.3 percent last winter. Skiers aged 45 to 54 years, the
prime age group for buying a second home, increased slightly, to
almost 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Colorado Rockies, resorts that cater to wealthy
out-of-state skiers and snow boarders are cracking down on reckless
speeding. Aspen Skiing Company, which prides itself on charging the
highest lift ticket price in the nation _ $63 _ recently adopted
the Tuck Buster Program.
</P>
<P>
   Ski patrols there target skiers, usually young men, speeding
down the mountain in a racing crouch, giving out warnings or in
some cases taking away lift tickets.
</P>
<P>
   By this spring, many of Colorado's rowdier young athletes had
learned the new rules of the game. Snowboarders increasingly
congregate around obstacle courses known as terrain parks.
Daredevils disappear into the black diamond expert slopes or into
the back mountain expanses known as ``bowls.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, males have accounted for all this winter's fatalities in
Colorado ski resorts. A study of Colorado's ski area fatalities
from 1990 to 1996 found that 80 percent were men, 68 percent were
Coloradans, and 62 percent were under 35. Most were killed speeding
on intermediate, or blue, slopes. On these smoothly groomed slopes,
radar studies indicate that skiers average 25 to 40 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   At Breckenridge, the program is popular on the three heavily
trafficked blue slopes where slow skiing is in effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to see them trying to control the other skiers who are
whizzing by me,'' said Betty Shea, a 62-year-old beginner who was
trying her first intermediate run in a slow skiing zone. She added
cryptically, ``I wish there was a place for the snowboarders.''
</P>
<P>
   Much as highway patrolmen try to keep vehicles moving at roughly
the same speed, ski patrollers do the same with skiers and
snowboarders of all abilities. A mix of speeds leads to passing
and, on congested slopes, collisions, ski patrollers say.
</P>
<P>
   Others attributed accidents to high-speed chairlifts that
deprive skiers of needed rest and on helmets and the new-shaped,
parabolic skis, which can give a skier a false sense of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great idea,'' Lisa Cowan, a 39-year-old from
Orlando, Fla., taking a break on a slow zone here, said of the
crackdown. ``It is the first time I have skied when I didn't think
people were zooming by me.''
</P>
<P>
   At the bottom of the mountain, Jensen reflected on the new
safety program, clicking his wire clippers for effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The compliments and thank you's are running 10 to 1 to the
complaints from the people who are going too fast,'' he said. ``I
get letters from 50-year-olds who want us to do it on all 163
runs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
