<HEADER>
A3194 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIG-HOUSE02-COX     04-01 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-HOUSE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Land deal sets South Florida record
 &HT;    By Ava Van de Water
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANALAPAN, Fla. _ In one week, builder Frank McKinney leaped
from a record house proposal to a record land sale. And McKinney
still will build a mansion on the Manalapan property _ a custom
home for the buyer, instead of the $39 million ``spec'' house he
planned.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, McKinney and partner Thomas Melone sold the
8.66-acre oceanfront property for $26.45 million. Half of the land
was slated for a 61,318-square-foot house that would've been built
before a buyer was found.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the partners' land deal set a record for a residential
property in South Florida. McKinney and Melone received almost $10
million more than they paid for the land in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Title to the property went to James Rutledge as trustee. Malcolm
Healey, owner of Mill's Pride kitchen cabinets, is believed to be
the buyer. Through Rutledge, Healey has contracted with McKinney to
build a house on the land. McKinney says he doesn't know whom
Rutledge represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are building a house similar to the $39 million spec house
approved by the town of Manalapan on the site,'' McKinney said
Thursday. ``I do know the intent of all parties is to carry forward
what has already been approved. We've already gone through a
one-year permitting process.''
</P>
<P>
   But just how big the house will be and whether it will be the
only structure on the property is uncertain. McKinney and others
involved in the deal are bound by a confidentiality agreement.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney, through his Manalapan Development Co., and investor
Melone, as trustee, paid $17 million for the property, just south
of Manalapan Town Hall at 700 and 750 S. Ocean Blvd. On the north
half of the property, McKinney had planned to build the spec house
with glass-domed rotunda big enough to seat 150 people for dinner,
a 5,000-square-foot master bedroom suite, movie theater with
popcorn stand, and a game room the size of most people's houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't necessarily mean that what we have will not be
built on another lot, although it is much more difficult now to
find the inventory on which to build,'' McKinney said.
</P>
<P>
   There are no documents to show who the mysterious buyer is, but
it is believed to be Healey, whose Mill's Pride kitchen cabinets
are sold at Home Depot stores. Healey owns a beautiful
9,100-square-foot oceanfront house and 4,600-square-foot guest
house on 2 acres in Palm Beach, but he's been looking at property
in the Manalapan area.
</P>
<P>
   Healey appears to like a lot of land. Last year, after netting
nearly $373 million by selling one of England's largest kitchen
companies, he paid about $67.8 million for an 11,000-acre historic
estate in England. The estate, once owned by the Marquis of
Normanby, includes 63 houses and cottages, a school, store and post
office, according to the Daily Mail in England. Healey is traveling
and could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   This latest record-setting sale is a further sign that
Manalapan, once a quiet vacation retreat for wealthy Europeans, is
evolving into a mega-mansion mecca. Just down the road from
McKinney's property is the former Howard Vanderbilt estate, which
owner and mall magnate Mel Simon expanded to 40,000 square feet.
Then there's Lois Pope's expanded 30,000-square-foot manse on the
market for $18 million, and billionaire William Ziff's
47,000-square-foot mansion, now under construction.
</P>
<P>
   The sale also proves Frank McKinney _ whose last spec house sold
for $9.5 million, including furnishings _ is on target with his
multimillion-dollar ideas, said real estate broker Clark French,
who marketed the property for McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again, everybody said, 'You're crazy,' and he says, `No,
I'm not,''' French said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
