<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-GAS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gas prices take leap
 &HT;    By Trebor Banstetter
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The good ol' days at the gas pump are
over.
</P>
<P>
   When adjusted for inflation, gas prices this year had fallen to
their lowest level in history. But during the past two weeks,
prices in Florida jumped an average of almost 11 cents per gallon,
according to a special survey by the Tampa-based AAA Auto Club
South.
</P>
<P>
   The average price for a gallon of regular unleaded gas in
Florida was $1.10 Wednesday, according to the survey. Prices
haven't been that high since mid-1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've definitely noticed it going up,'' said Linda O'Hare of
Boca Raton as she filled the tank of her black Ford sedan at a
Shell gas station in Delray Beach. She paid $1.18 a gallon for
regular unleaded. ``The only thing you can do is try to find the
best deal when you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami, where a gallon cost an average of $1.13, had the
second-highest prices in the state after Jacksonville, where it
cost $1.14, according to the survey. Miami prices are usually on
par with the rest of South Florida, said Yoli Buss, who monitors
gas prices for AAA.
</P>
<P>
   The cheapest gas, at $1.07 a gallon, can be found in the Tampa
area, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   The surge in gas prices is largely due to a recent decision by
the 11 oil-producing nations in the Organization of the Petroleum
Exporting Countries to slash production and reduce the world's oil
glut.
</P>
<P>
   It was that glut that had kept prices so low.
</P>
<P>
   ``OPEC was responding to those low gas prices we've enjoyed all
year,'' Buss said. The auto club, which usually releases its price
reports in mid-month, conducted the special survey after OPEC's
decision. ``They couldn't afford to keep them that low.''
</P>
<P>
   Pete Foley, a retired Lake Worth resident, believes the oil
industry's actions are just another attempt to unfairly squeeze
money from consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as OPEC announced the cut in production, prices went
up instantly, before the cuts even took effect,'' Foley said as he
filled the tank of his Honda motorcycle with $1.19-per-gallon fuel
at a Texaco gas station in Boynton Beach. ``It's another rip-off of
the American public.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices also are rising in anticipation of spring and summer
travel and weather, Buss said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see people using their air conditioners more, and then
we'll hit the heavy summer travel months,'' she said. ``That is all
having an impact on gas prices.''
</P>
<P>
   The upswing in gas prices is not a surprise to energy experts,
who have been predicting an end to the heyday of fuel prices since
the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has been waiting for OPEC's move,'' Buss said. ``It
was just a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time gas prices jumped as quickly was in 1990, at the
onset of the Persian Gulf War. The price of a gallon leapt more
than 20 cents then, sparked by concerns over the oil supply in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Will prices continue to rise? It's all up to OPEC, Buss says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they continue to cut production, we'll continue to see
steep hikes,'' she said. ``If not, we'll see some increase but
nothing too dramatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida residents can take some pleasure in knowing that gas
prices are even higher in some other states.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, which has some of the highest gas prices in
the nation, motorists are shelling out $1.61 per gallon, according
to AAA of California.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
