<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO DISCUSSES PLAN TO SET UP AND PROTECT ALBANIAN ENCLAVE IN
KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  (See also: KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, KOSOVO-SOLIDERS,
KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-BELGRADE, KOSOVO-REGUGEES, KOSOVO-EUROPE,
KOSOVO-RIGHTS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-RELIGION, KOSOVO-BOSNIA) 
(ART ADV: Graphics showing targets hit by NATO over the last 8 days
and showing NATO airbases are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Brussels _ Western officials are discussing a plan
under which NATO troops would escort ethnic Albanians back into
Kosovo after Serbian forces there have been routed by bombing, and
would set up a self-governing enclave under allied protection, a
senior NATO diplomat said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have repeatedly ruled out an invasion force to
halt the brutal campaign by President Slobodan Milosevic's Serbian
forces, which has driven almost 190,000 ethnic Albanians from the
province.
</P>
<P>
   But Western officials say that NATO ground troops may be called
in if airstrikes eventually succeed in driving back the Serb
military to bring back the refugees and to set up what the official
called a ``protectorate.'' They say this might be possible even if
a formal peace agreement with Belgrade has not been reached, as
long as it was clear that the Serbs could not mount serious
resistance.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations on the plan are still in the early stages and
still under discussion in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   A senior American official in Washington said in a telephone
interview that much would depend on whether the ground force will
be able to enter Kosovo without facing serious military resistance
from remaining Serbian troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The line that has not been crossed in Washington is whether we
would deploy such a force in anything but a permissive
environment,'' the official said. ``That is, an environment in
which hostile forces have been removed.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, NATO has continued to back the plan presented to the
Serbs and ethnic Albanians at the Rambouillet Castle in France,
under which Kosovo would remain a Serbian province, but with
extensive autonomy for its Albanian majority. But officials have
privately acknowledged that the proposal, which was rejected by the
Serbs, is no longer applicable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo within Yugoslavia is becoming more and more difficult
to conceive of, even with the maximum degree of autonomy involving
the Rambouillet package,'' the diplomat said. ``It may still not be
too late to go back to that, but it is becoming more and more
remote. So a protectorate, independence with international
guarantees, these are at least coming into the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   The discussions over a protectorate _ an independent entity
whose security would be guaranteed by the international community
but whose status would be less than a state _ reflects a major
change in the long debate over how to bring peace to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Rambouillet approach, NATO was to send 28,000
peacekeeping troops only after both the Serbs and the ethnic
Albanians had accepted the autonomy plan.
</P>
<P>
   But with the plan rejected by the Serbs, and with their forces
on the march in Kosovo, there is a growing sense among diplomats
that the coexistence between the Serbs and Albanians is no longer
viable.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, some diplomats say, the Albanians would find it
difficult to live again under Serb authority, even with the
autonomy projected by the Rambouillet agreement. Additionally,
President Clinton has warned Milosevic that his campaign against
the ethnic Albanians was jeopardizing his right to govern Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Even NATO Secretary General Javier Solana suggested in an
interview earlier this week that the Rambouillet accord would
probably need to be modified but did not say how.
</P>
<P>
   The plan under discussion by diplomats here, to turn Kosovo into
a NATO protectorate, also reflects a resistance to make Kosovo an
independent state _ no NATO nation has formally called for it _ or
to make Kosovo part of a greater Albania, for fear that such steps
could destablize the region.
</P>
<P>
   Many critical details of how a protectorate might work remain to
be worked out. The basic thinking is that weeks of bombing would
cripple the Yugoslav military and force Serbian soldiers and police
units to retreat from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Then, ethnic Albanians refugees would begin to return under the
protection of NATO troops. The refugees would be allowed to return
to all of Kosovo. The province would not be partitioned.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO force would function more like a protection force than
a peacekeeping presence. It might be sent even if Belgrade did not
agree to the presence of NATO forces in Kosovo, though probably not
in the face of determined Serb resistance. Diplomats could try to
work out a peace accord afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sequence used to be full political agreement, followed by
an international peacekeeping force,'' the senior NATO diplomat
said. ``The question that will have to be answered now is whether
the international presence is so indispensible to the return of the
refugees that one has to look at a different sequence.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear how large such a NATO force might be. While air
strikes would have reduced Serb threats, the force would have to be
substantial enough to protect not only the ethnic Albanians, but
the international officials and workers that would likely be
involved in the reconstruction of the province.
</P>
<P>
   ``The security risks to the force might be less but the task
would be very different,'' the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the senior allied commander, hinted Thursday
in a press conference that contingency planning was being carried
out for using ground forces in new ways. But he refused to provide
any details.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials reiterated, however, that there was no
consideration of using ground forces to invade Kosovo. NATO
officials also pointed to the difficulties in dispatching ground
troops as part of a effort to create ``safe areas'' in Kosovo for
Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   During the war in Bosnia, the U.N. force there established
``safe areas'' for Muslim populations under attack by Bosnian Serb
forces in places like Srebrenica.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces under Gen. Ratko Mladic later attacked Srebrenica
and killed thousands of civilians, with U.N. forces unable to stop
them even with NATO bombing behind them.
</P>
<P>
   That is why, a NATO military officer said, ``We must not
establish anything like safe areas in Kosovo unless we can
absolutely guarantee the safety of the people who are within
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-01-99 2209EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990401.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-AUDITS-MAYOR-325&AMP;A     04-01 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AUDITS-MAYOR-325&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT PERMITS STATE AUDITS THAT GIULIANI TRIED TO BAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani exceeded his authority when he
blocked state auditors from reviewing how effectively the city's
government is managed, the state's highest court ruled Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision by the state Court of Appeals was the
second this week that took the mayor to task for overstepping his
powers. The court ruled Tuesday that Giuliani could not lease a
city hospital to a private company without first obtaining changes
in state law.
</P>
<P>
   In its ruling Thursday, the court upheld a lawsuit by state
Comptroller Carl McCall that sought to compel city agencies to
cooperate with McCall's auditors, who were trying to examine how
effectively the city delivered services. The court said that the
state constitution and state laws clearly give the comptroller the
authority to conduct such reviews, known as performance audits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We conclude that the comptroller has authority to perform such
audits,'' wrote Chief Judge Judith Kaye in the decision, which
affirmed two lower court rulings. Afterward, McCall said he would
pursue the audits and Giuliani said he would make available most,
if not all, of the information sought by the Comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   The decision settled a bitter dispute that began two years ago
when McCall set out to review the performance of a half-dozen city
agencies and to verify how accurately they had been reporting
significant improvements in cleaning the streets, reducing crime
and moving people from welfare to work.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, a Republican who was facing re-election when the
audits were initiated early in 1997, had accused McCall, a
Democrat, of being politically motivated and seeking to embarrass
him in an election year. Giuliani ordered city agencies to stop
sharing most information with the state comptroller's auditors and
he ordered the auditors evicted from the offices of two city
agencies, the Health Department and the Human Resources
Administration.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The mayor had previously indicated that he thought McCall was
partisan, and he occasionally cited that as a reason why he had
declined to meet with McCall for more than four years. The two men
finally met last Saturday for breakfast at Gracie Mansion as part
of an effort by Giuliani to reach out to black elected officials
after two months of turmoil over the fatal shooting by four white
police officers of an unarmed West African immigrant, Amadou
Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   After efforts to mediate the dispute over performance audits
failed, McCall issued 17 subpoenas in April 1997 to obtain records
and other information from six city agencies, including the Police
Department, the Taxi and Limousine Commission, the Administration
for Children's Services and the Department of Finance. The city
ignored the subpoenas, and McCall went to court to have them
enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides agreed that the state comptroller had the right to
conduct traditional financial audits of the city. But Giuliani
argued that McCall lacked the statutory and constitutional power to
perform broader reviews of the efficiency and management of city
government, as well as its compliance with the law.
</P>
<P>
   In their court filings and in oral arguments before the Court of
Appeals in February, city lawyers contended that the language of a
1925 amendment to the state constitution should be interpreted
narrowly when it said that the state comptroller was responsible
for supervising ``the accounts'' of political subdivisions in the
state. That meant that the comptroller had the authority to review
only a municipality's finances, the city's lawyers argued.
</P>
<P>
   But the Court of Appeals rejected that interpretation. ``We find
the city's argument unpersuasive, concluding both that the
constitution permits delegation to the comptroller of the authority
to conduct performance audits of political subdivisions, and that
in exercise of that authority, the Legislature has empowered the
comptroller to conduct such audits of city agencies,'' Judge Kaye
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   McCall said in a prepared statement that he was pleased by the
decision and was hopeful that, after meeting with Giuliani last
weekend, he and the mayor would work more cooperatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to working with the mayor so that my auditors
can resume auditing New York City agencies in a cooperative and
productive manner,'' McCall said. ``The legal battles have cost us
two years of providing New Yorkers with vital information about how
their tax dollars are being spent. There is much time to be made up
and much work to be done. Let's get to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he disagreed with the court's interpretation, but
would abide by the ruling. The mayor noted several times at a news
conference yesterday, though, that in the last paragraph of the
decision, the court said it had ruled only on the broad principle
of performance audits and not on any objections that the city might
make about specific aspects of the proposed audits.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he had expected the court to rule as it did.
``And we are ready to comply with it, although it does say _ and we
are thankful for that _ that we can raise other objections beyond
the objection of performance audit,'' he said. ``So there may be,
in some cases, other grounds in which there are objections, so we
have to reserve that right. But they will get most of the
information, if not all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
