<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-01 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3200 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-ISSUES02-COX     04-01 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ISSUES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush becomes object of political egg hunt
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A day after announcing he has collected more
than $6 million for his probable presidential campaign, Gov. George
W. Bush on Thursday found himself in the cross hairs of the
Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has not said he is definitely running, is running
scared, according to Joe Andrew, the DNC's national chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is Bush afraid of? That reporters have only seen the
sunny side up until now?'' Andrew said as part of an effort to
portray Bush as a side-stepping know-nothing.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Bush, insisting the current Texas Legislature
is his top priority, has declined to take specific positions on
some national issues. Critics say he is ducking questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hiding more than Easter eggs?'' the Democrats asked in a
Thursday release.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say he is working on answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he gave us some clear pictures and answered some
pretty direct questions,'' said Pennsylvania GOP Chairman Alan
Novak, who met with Bush here Wednesday. ``I think he convinced us
he has good instincts, that he knows what he still needs to learn
and he is committed to learn it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has raised more than $6 million for his campaign, said
his image as a candidate who is not fully known by the voters has
reached the joking level with his family.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was surprised at the support he amassed though some
people know little about him other than his lineage, he said, ``Are
you referring to the time my mother called me after (a poll showing
him running atop the pack) and said, `Son, I love your strategy:
Don't let them get to know you.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush said he believes supporters do know him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people would write a check like that unless they
knew where my heart is, what my intentions are. I believe I've
shown the people that I know how to lead. I'm the governor of the
second-largest state in the United States,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That, according to the Democratic National Committee, leaves him
far short of qualified for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you compare him with Democratic candidates who are
running, he is not even close,'' said DNC spokesman Rick Hess. ``He
lacks experience at the national level.''
</P>
<P>
   The top two Democratic presidential contenders _ Vice President
Al Gore and former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley _ have that
experience. The most recent two Democratic presidents _ Bill
Clinton and Jimmy Carter _ did not. Clinton was governor of
Arkansas. Carter was governor of Georgia. Neither held federal
office before getting the top job.
</P>
<P>
   But Hess said Clinton ``had a lot of experience running a state
for four terms,'' and dabbled in foreign relations when riots broke
out among Cuban refugees held in Fort Chafee, Ark. In 1980,
Clinton, then governor, called out the National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is a couple of months into his second term as
governor,'' Hess said of Bush, grudgingly giving Bush some points
for picking up some foreign policy expertise as a border state
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Politically, Bush is untested, according to Hess.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a candidate who has never been in a Republican primary
before. He was elected in 1994, which was a watershed year for
Republicans, and re-elected in 1998. He has never run in a
presidential year,'' said Hess.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Bush's landslide win last year over Democrat Garry
Mauro, Hess said, ``I don't think it was a good test.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes accused the Democrats of ``trying
to reinvent history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, Ann Richards (the Democratic incumbent Bush ousted
in 1994) is an easy candidate to beat and Garry Mauro, who was a
16-year incumbent (state land commissioner), was not a very good
candidate,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In an excruciating exchange of Easter-related one-liners, the
Democrats and Hughes shelled each other Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. George W. Bush is again taking eggs-traordinary steps to
avoid discussing his political positions with members of the
media,'' the DNC said in a release rapping him for ``barring''
reporters from last week's Easter egg hunt at the Governor's
Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual, the Democrats have their facts all scrambled,'' said
Hughes, noting that Bush has had two press conferences in the past
10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The egg hunt was off-limits to reporters at the request of the
legislative spouses who sponsored it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not want the Easter egg hunt, intended for little
children, to be turned into a news conference on the presidential
campaign,'' Hughes said. ``And the governor agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
