<HEADER>
A3202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYCLING-DRUGS-NYT &LR;      04-01 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYCLING-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE YEAR LATER, DOPING SCANDAL RESURFACES IN BELGIUM AND FRANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Belgium, Italy)  By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The drug scandal in professional bicycle racing erupted
on two fronts Thursday, with Belgian police yanking the top-ranked
professional team out of a race and an announcement in France that
a top cycling official is under criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The unprecedented police intervention in the Three Days of La
Panne race came after a Belgian newspaper reported that the
authorities were investigating a case involving amphetamines seized
at the Brussels, Belgium, airport. Five flasks of the drug had been
traced to the hotel where Mapei, the Italy-based racing team, was
staying.
</P>
<P>
   Deciding that they could not wait until Thursday's competition
ended, the police stopped Thursday morning's road stage after two
kilometers and took the Mapei riders and officials to Kortrijk for
questioning. In a show of support, the other racers refused to
continue the day's first of two races.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities later exonerated the Mapei team members, but it
was too late for Tom Steels, a Belgian who had been leading the
event. While Mapei's riders were in custody, the final stage, a
14-kilometer (8.68-mile) time trial, was run as scheduled. Frank
Vandenbroucke of Belgium won the stage for the Cofidis team, and
Peter Van Petergem, another Belgian who rides for TVM, won the
overall title.
</P>
<P>
   In Lille, France, Daniel Baal, head of the French Cycling
Federation, was accused of complicity to facilitate and incite
doping, his lawyer, Paul Mauriac, said. In French law, being placed
under formal investigation is a step short of being indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Baal insisted that he has tried to prevent doping, which marred
last year's Tour de France by overshadowing the racing. He said he
was shocked by what he called an unjust decision to investigate
him.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made after he was questioned Thursday by
Magistrate Patrick Keil, who is leading the investigation that
began last July and nearly caused the cancellation of the Tour de
France, the sport's most prestigious race. The Festina team, then
No. 1 in racing, was expelled from the Tour after its officials
admitted the systematic use of illegal performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Marie Leblanc, the director of the Tour, was also
questioned by Keil and announced afterward that he had not been
placed under investigation, Agence France-Presse reported.
</P>
<P>
   Keil ``declared himself satisfied with the replies I had
given,'' Leblanc said. ``As a consequence, I have not been put
under formal investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Keil is moving up the sports hierarchy in his investigation.
This week, Roger Legeay, president of the French league of
professional cycling and Baal's deputy at the federation, and
Richard Virenque, the former leader of the Festina team, were both
placed under formal investigation. A dozen others, including
officials, riders and doctors, have also been placed under formal
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In the case in Belgium, The Associated Press reported that
Belgian news media said that the flasks had been discovered in a
videocassette box. The package was bound for Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The Mapei riders in the La Panne race _ considered a tuneup for
this weekend's Tour of Flanders _ included Michele Bartoli, ranked
No. 1 among world professionals; Johan Museeuw, a former world
road-racing champion, and Steels, the Belgian champion.
</P>
<P>
   The team's hotel was searched and sealed off, and a Belgian
television network said the riders had been taken to the courthouse
in Kortrijk for further questioning after initial questioning near
the race site. The team's director, Patrick Lefevere, a Belgian,
and two other team officials were already in Kortrijk for
questioning, the network said.
</P>
<P>
   Louis Denecker, a prosecutor, said the authorities had intended
to intervene after the race but changed their minds and stopped the
race after news of the inquiry appeared in the Het Laatste Nieuws
newspaper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
