A3208 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-STARS-PLAYOFFS-TE     04-01 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PLAYOFFS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS READY TO GET DOWN TO NITTY-GRITTY BEFORE PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Stars' training room is filled with injured
bodies, including leading scorer Mike Modano. The power play is in
its worst slump in two seasons. And the Stars' detail game has
been, in a word, sloppy, forthe past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   So with eight games remaining in the regular season, how much
work do the Stars have to do to get ready for the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``We have a lot of
work to do to get ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the good news: The Stars have the time and the schedule
to be perfectly prepared. In fact, Hitchcock said the schedule
couldn't have set up better for the Stars in their stretch run to
the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have solid competition that should keep us focused and we
have plenty of time to rest and practice,'' Hitchcock said
yesterday after taking the Stars through their most intense
practice in more than two months. ``We had to suffer through a lot
in the past month or so, but now we're reaping the benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, benefits might be too strong a word to grasp, what with
Modano out seven to 14 days with a groin strain and Richard
Matvichuk (knee), Shawn Chambers (hip) and Brian Skrudland (chest)
not expected to return until next week. But the potential for
benefit is there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things that we can straighten out in our
game right now,'' winger Pat Verbeek said. ``We have to be serious
about the details, all the little things that can help us be a
better team. You can't just flip a switch and expect it to be there
for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Those details are a little shaky, but with good reason. The
Stars played 16 games in March, including 10 on the road. At one
point, the Stars played nine games in 15 days, with seven of the
nine on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the two home games felt like road games,'' Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Stars had a 4-3-2 record in that stretch, it was
clear the details of their game had eroded. They weren't passing
the puck well, they had miscommunications like offside calls and
bench minors for illegal substitutions, they allowed opposing
players to get open in front of their net, and they couldn't
stretch leads once they got them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not one to complain, but by the Anaheim game \Ra 5-1 loss
March 26\S, I could feel it,'' defenseman Craig Ludwig said.
</P>
<P>
   With Matvichuk and Chambers out, the Stars were forced to pile
more minutes on Ludwig and fellow defensemen Derian Hatcher, Sergei
Zubov and Darryl Sydor.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think we really saw it affect their game,'' Hitchcock
said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hitchcock is hoping for the return of his injured
defensemen and also is looking to provide more rest for his healthy
players. What's more, the extra practice time will be crucial in
finding the timing and the puck handling that have been missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a game of skill, and you have to practice if you're
going to have skill,'' Hitchcock said. ``I know the players aren't
always happy with practice, they want to just get right to the
playoffs, but I think they also know they need the practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the season, the Stars had the most detailed game in
the NHL. Players tracked hard on specific forechecking assignments
to force opposing team's defensemen to cough up the puck. When the
Stars went to the offensive net and missed on a scoring chance,
forwards backchecked hard to prevent an outmanned rush going the
opposite way. If a Stars' defenseman decided to push hard into the
offensive zone to help create a scoring opportunity, a forward
always would rotate back into the defenseman's spot and cover
appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's anyone's guess as to whether a player will be there.
</P>
<P>
   The inconsistency with the power play also has been a problem.
As recently as Feb. 1, the Stars had the dominant power play in the
NHL. They had hit for 51 goals with the man advantage and had a
20.7 success rate. Since then, however, the power play has scored
15 goals on a 12.5 percent success rate. The Stars now rank sixth
in success and trail the Mighty Ducks of Anaheim (76 goals) by 10
goals in overall power-play production.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we have to fix,'' Modano said. ``When it's
scoring, it's like we get an extra goal a game. Right now, we're
fighting for every goal we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   The good side to that struggle is the Stars have won a lot of
close games. They are 23-6 in one-goal games and are 12-2-5 when
tied after two periods. Although there have been some third-period
struggles, the Stars are showing they don't mind playing in
high-pressure situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's playoff hockey,'' Ludwig said. ``That's what we're used
to. We're not afraid to have a one-goal lead and we're not afraid
to win a game 1-0. Those are things that should help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Stars wouldn't mind giving themselves a little
breathing room. That's one reason Hitchcock is going to err on the
side of caution when it comes to returning his injured players.
(Modano likely will be out the longest, Hitchcock said.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be hurt right now, but we should have everyone healthy,
knock on wood, with at least three games left in the season,''
Hitchcock said. ``And three games should be enough to get anyone
ready for the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the case, just think what the Stars can do with eight
games. regular season, where postseason preparation is the target.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
