<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-TEEN-SMOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMOKING BY MIDDLE-SCHOOL STUDENTS DROPS SHARPLY IN FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ One year after Florida started a statewide educational
campaign against tobacco, directed at teen-agers, smoking among
middle-school students has declined by the largest margin observed
in the United States in almost 20 years, the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a study that will appear in Friday's issue of the Morbidity
and Mortality Weekly Report, the centers cite a survey conducted by
the Florida Department of Health showing that the number of
children in grades six through eight who reported using cigarettes
this year fell to 15 percent from 18.5 percent, a decline of 19
percent from a year ago, when students were last surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also charts more modest declines in cigarette and
cigar smoking among high school students. The decrease was steeper
among non-Hispanic white students than among Hispanic and black
students, the survey showed, but non-Hispanic whites still had the
highest rate of cigarette use as a group.
</P>
<P>
   The results, which were gathered from a sample of almost 23,000
students in 225 schools around Florida, were hailed by national
health experts after years of reports showing little or no decrease
in cigarette smoking by teen-agers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely is a pleasant surprise,'' said Dr. Michael
Eriksen, the director for the Office on Smoking and Health at the
Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, based in Atlanta.
``There is no question that the reduction in Florida is real.''
</P>
<P>
   Although further study is needed to determine the cause for such
a steep decline, Eriksen added, the results are most likely due to
Florida's aggressive anti-tobacco campaign, which has been hailed
as one of the most effective in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's campaign, the Tobacco Pilot Program, is financed by a
$13 billion settlement reached between the state and the tobacco
companies in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the survey's results come at a time when the survival of
Florida's anti-smoking initiative faces challenge by the state's
policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   In his appropriations request to the state Legislature, Gov. Jeb
Bush trimmed the amount of money the program spends on enforcing
laws against underage possession of tobacco, requesting $61.5
million for the fiscal year that begins on July 1. Last year, the
state spent $70 million on the program. The budget is currently
under committee review.
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, President Clinton said Thursday that the
survey results showed ``why every state should have a comprehensive
program to reduce youth smoking and why I oppose any legislation
waiving the federal government's claim to tobacco settlement funds
without making a commitment from the states to fund such efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   The cornerstone of Florida's anti-smoking initiative is a
campaign called ``Truth'' that has launched aggressive television
and radio advertisements in which angry teen-agers accuse tobacco
companies of lying.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Pilot Program doubled its enforcement efforts,
imposing fines or community service for thousands of teen-agers
caught smoking, and going after retailers who sold cigarettes to
minors. In schools around the state, teachers received special
training to conduct workshops where middle-school students engaged
in discussion and role playing to learn how to overcome peer
pressure to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The increase in the price of cigarettes nationally over the past
year may have also contributed to lower rates of smoking among
middle-school children, but it is unclear how much this may have
helped lower the Florida smoking rates, Eriksen said. Although
tobacco companies have raised the price of 20-cigarette packs to
wholesalers by about 60 cents nationwide, they have also offset
some of the ensuing lower demand through special promotions that
lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Experts said it was unlikely that results as statistically
significant as those made public Thursday would be replicated as
other states begin to release their smoking data for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida has a unique program,'' said Kathryn Kahler Vose,
director of communications for the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids
in Washington. ``They have one of the most aggressive and
comprehensive programs in the country. You don't see these kinds of
numbers in other states. Most spend very little money on tobacco
prevention.''
</P>
</TEXT>
