<HEADER>
A3212 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-HARRICK-CHANGESMI     04-01 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HARRICK-CHANGESMIND02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harrick double-dribbles job
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Had Vince Dooley been in his office rather than on
a Civil War battlefield in New Market, Va., Thursday when he got
the news Jim Harrick wanted to return to Rhode Island, the Bulldogs
would have named their second basketball coach in 24 hours on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Harrick had his second change of heart in a
day and reaffirmed his decision to become the Bulldogs' 19th head
basketball coach. That it happened on April Fools Day was a cruel
coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   In a case of waffling that would make Bobby Cremins blush,
Harrick left Georgia, returned to Rhode Island, then returned to
the Bulldogs all in one day. The former UCLA head coach remained in
Providence, R.I., Thursday night but was to return to Athens this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley and his grandson were on a vacation retreat in Virginia,
where they were touring Civil War battlefields. Therefore, when
Dooley got the call from university President Michael Adams that
Harrick had backed out, he was unable to call his next coaching
prospect, believed to be Appalachian State's Buzz Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, I didn't have my phone numbers with me,'' Dooley
said.``Otherwise, I might have made another commitment, who
knows.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in four years that Georgia has been the
victim of a coach's indecision. The Bulldogs hired football coach
Glen Mason from Kansas on Dec. 18, 1995 to have him back out of the
job on Christmas Day. That same day, they named Jim Donnan as
football coach.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Dooley said he called Donnan to offer him the job
without ever laying down the telephone. Fortunately for Harrick,
Dooley was not in position to do the same thing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dooley said the only reason Georgia took Harrick back was
because the source of his decision was his unwillingness to leave
his family, many of whom had moved to Rhode Island just to be close
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had been for any other reason, I don't think I would
have understood it and we would have gone in another direction,''
Dooley said.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick did not return repeated phone calls to his cell phone
Thursday. Georgia officials said they hoped he would be available
for interviews sometime today.
</P>
<P>
   According to Adams, who handled the crisis in Dooley's absence,
Harrick called him at 9:30 Thursday morning to tell him he was
having second thoughts and was considering a return to Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick met with Adams and Georgia senior associate athletics
director Dick Bestwick for more than an hour. Harrick left the
meeting to return to Providence and said he would call them back
with a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:30 p.m., Harrick informed Adams he indeed planned to stay
at Rhode Island, at which time Georgia set forth its public
relations machine and prepared a release. Rhode Island also called
a 7 p.m. press conference to discuss Harrick's return.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said Harrick then called him again at 5:30 p.m. to say
he'd changed his mind yet again, but now was completely committed
to join the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I told him I could not tell him that he could
still be the coach because that had to come from the athletics
director,'' Adams said. ``I called coach Dooley and he called coach
Harrick and they worked it out.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the embarrassment Harrick's indecision caused the
university, Adams said: ``Sometimes in this business, you get into
a no-win situation and I do believe that was the case here.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley insisted the whole incident was not an embarrassment
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's the case,'' Dooley said. ``It's not good.
If it were not a case where it was because of family, it could have
been an embarrassment. But it was because of his family and that's
something we can live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Harrick actually had a job to return to at Rhode Island
is unclear. Georgia's Adams assured that he did. But Harrick
definitely will not be welcomed back in Providence if he
about-faced again.
</P>
<P>
   At what was supposed to be the press conference to announce
Harrick's return to Rhode Island, URI vice President Robert Beagle
read the following statement: ``It's clear to all of us that coach
Harrick is troubled. President (Robert) Carothers has indicated to
us we should announce that it is clear that coach Harrick is not
capable of coaching the University of Rhode Island basketball team
at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
