<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN PUTS 2000 RACE ON HOLD; SAYS GROUND TROOPS MAY BE NEEDED IN
KOSOVO 
  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID PARRISH AND JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Just after calling for complete victory in
Kosovo, even if it means using U.S. ground forces, Arizona Sen.
John McCain announced Thursday that he's temporarily suspending his
presidential campaign because of the escalating military conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not appropriate at this time to launch a political
campaign,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the 62-year-old Republican senator stressed that McCain
was not having second thoughts about his bid for the White House in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' said Howard Opinsky, McCain's press
spokesman. ``There's a war going on.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's announcement that he was postponing next week's
presidential announcement tour came just after he made some of his
harshest comments to date concerning the Clinton administration's
handling of the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly recommend that we not rule out the option of ground
troops,'' McCain said Thursday during a news conference at Sky
Harbor International Airport. ``Which is what the administration,
for all intent and purpose, has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia President Slobodan Milosevic should not be given any
assurances that ground troops wouldn't be used, McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it caused U.S. casualties _ ``and pain to American
families'' _ ground troops should be used if that what it takes to
win, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The consequences of failing to win this conflict are severe
and would then entail a much larger sacrifice of American blood,
not only there but in other parts of the world,'' McCain said.
``They pay attention in Pyongyang, North Korea, and Baghdad, Iraq,
and other places in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   American credibility is at stake, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A recent CNN poll showed that 57 percent of Americans opposed
using U.S. ground troops in Kosovo and that 54 percent approved so
far of how President Clinton is handling the situation.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said Clinton has failed to explain to the public the
importance of the conflict and why U.S. ground forces could be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make the American people aware that this is a very
difficult situation we are in now,'' McCain said. ``There are no
good options. . . . You have to go to the American people and
explain to them what is at stake here, then I believe the American
people will understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain said he did not think the military campaign has
been achieving its goals, the bombing should continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do it until it has lost any effectiveness that it might
obtain, and at the same time plan to, if necessary, send in ground
troops,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   The world's only remaining military superpower should not be
intimidated into holding it army, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a formidable adversary,'' McCain said. ``The
Croatian Army defeated the Serbian Army a few years ago. So this is
not some overwhelming force we are facing. In fact, Yugoslavia is
the size of the state of Connecticut. The United States has
superior force. We need to use it.``
</P>
<P>
   McCain acknowledged that similar statements were made by U.S.
officials during the 1960s about Vietnam, but he said there were no
real parallels between the two conflicts. He said communist powers
supplied North Vietnam during that war.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, this week there was at least one similarity for McCain, a
POW during the Vietnam War. He reacted strongly to the capture by
Serbian forces of three American servicemen assigned to
peacekeeping duties along the Yugoslavia-Macedonia border.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that is an affront to all of us,'' he said.
``We will not allow such a thing, and we will make it clear to
Mister Milosevic and his government they are in trouble now, and
they will be in a lot more trouble if they are not returned.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the servicemen were part of U.N. peacekeeping operation
along the border _ participating in the armed conflict _ and should
not be put on trial, as Serbian leaders have threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they were somehow viewed by a great stretch of the
imagination of having been captured in combat, they are subject to
the Geneva Convention, which expressly prohibits them being placed
on trial,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of us remember the Vietnamese threat during the Vietnam
War to put American pilots on trial. They were told in no uncertain
terms that if they did such a thing, they would pay a very heavy
price. Mister Milosevic has to be told the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he can understand what the servicemen are going
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a certain anguish because the most difficult period of
the prisoner of war experience is the initial period, the
adjustment to mistreatment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain warned Serbian leaders that if they harmed the three
service men, a war crime trial would be in order after the conflict
ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could speak directly to these three young men,'' McCain
said, ``I would say, `You are well-trained. You are professional.
You are the finest fighting men in world. We are proud of you, and
we are completely confident that you will behave in a manner in
which you and your country will be proud.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
