<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' NO. 2 UNIT IS FIRST-RATE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ Survey some of the Lakers' biggest scoring runs of
the last week, and at their core you'll find a familiar threesome:
the steady point guard, the hyperactive power forward and the
quick-scoring small forward.
</P>
<P>
   Harper, Rodman and Rice? Try Fisher, Horry and Fox.
</P>
<P>
   While the Lakers' starting five _ Derek Harper, Kobe Bryant,
Glen Rice, Dennis Rodman and Shaquille O'Neal _ continue to start
games at half speed, the second unit has been providing the early
scoring punch.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it shouldn't be such a surprise. The first group of subs _
Derek Fisher, Robert Horry and Rick Fox _ were all starters for the
Lakers last season. For the last three games, that trio has entered
the game simultaneously, late in the first quarter, and with either
Bryant or O'Neal still on the floor, the combination has been
effective.
</P>
<P>
   Against Sacramento last Friday, the Fisher-Horry-Fox unit (with
Bryant and J.R. Reid) keyed a 20-point burst in four minutes to
turn a deficit into a 30-20 lead by the end of the first quarter.
Against New York on Sunday, the trio combined with O'Neal and
Bryant for an early second-quarter run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a mix that was good for last year.... It's good to know
that if that's the second unit that can pull away from teams,
that's an asset,'' Fox said. ``I know it felt comfortable because I
knew those guys. It was like last year's starting lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of incorporating new players and tinkering with the
starting lineup and rotation, coach Kurt Rambis has settled on a
more consistent substitution pattern. The consistency has helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all three of us are just feeling more comfortable with
our roles,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give Kurt and his coaching staff credit to get us back
together since we played so well together last year,'' Fox said.
``I like the results and the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   It's led to an offensive resurgence for Fox, who's averaging
13.0 points in 20.0 minutes in the last three games. Rambis has
been running plays lately for Fox, a scorer most of his career, and
Fox has been able to take advantage of his part-time role as a
shooting guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm posting up two-guards, who are way too small, and in 20
minutes, I can get you 15 quick points if plays are run for me,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Rambis won't commit to a permanent rotation pattern yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not completely sold that that's my final situation,'' he
said, ``but I'm happy with what all those players are doing when
they do get substituted in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher hopes the current arrangement will stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as it's working, definitely,'' he said. ``I think all
three of us just bring a total change from the first group to the
second group. Robert and I try to bring some energy and some spark
to the defense, and then Rick, when he's shooting the ball well, he
brings some spark to the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The depth that you have and the guys coming off the bench are
just as important as those guys that start the game. So we have to
keep that in mind and understand that our roles are just as
vital.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Horry practiced Thursday for the first time since
injuring his hip in Monday's game against Vancouver. He's listed as
probable for tonight's game at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, still suffering from a cold, sat out a second
straight day but is expected to be available tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
