<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-COURTROOM-BROADCASTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: COURTROOM BROADCASTS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.Y.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, April 2:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., has teamed up with a Republican
colleague, Charles Grassley of Iowa, to address a nagging affront
to open government _ the bar against televising federal court
proceedings. Their newly proposed ``sunshine in the courtroom''
bill would give federal trial and appellate judges discretion to
allow unobtrusive cameras to cover proceedings in their courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Present law prohibits televising federal criminal proceedings,
and few federal appellate or trial courts have taken advantage of
local rules giving judges flexibility to allow cameras into civil
proceedings. Yet Americans have a strong interest in seeing the
machinery of justice at work. Moreover, the favorable experience of
states that allow cameras and the successful pilot program run in
federal courts several years ago suggest that with sensible
safeguards and firm oversight by a judge, broadcast coverage can
enhance justice and educate the public about significant legal
issues without sacrificing fairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal courts can only gain in dignity and respect if the
cloak of secrecy is lifted,'' Schumer says. That message deserves
prompt attention in Congress. It also deserves attention closer to
home. At the moment, New York is one of only three states to deny
any televised access to its courts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
