<HEADER>
A3332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COHEN-PROFILE-2TAKES-     04-01 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COHEN-PROFILE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARNOLD P. COHEN: COMPANY KILLER OR RETAIL GURU? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As 1997 began, J. Peterman, &UR;  &LR; the catalog retailer known for its
quirky merchandise, seemed poised for big things. For starters, in
an astonishing public-relations windfall, the super-sitcom
``Seinfeld'' was featuring even more episodes in which the
character Elaine worked for the company. Peterman had also just won
the rights to sell reproductions of the clothes and jewelry worn in
the movie ``Titanic,'' soon to be a monster hit.
</P>
<P>
   To bring it all together, the company hired a new president and
chief operating officer who seemed the perfect complement to the
creative but not especially business-minded co-founder, John
Peterman. When the effusive new executive, Arnold P. Cohen,
arrived, he spoke of a golden future, predicting that sales would
rise 50 percent by the following year.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen, who headed the charge to expand beyond catalogs into
stores, was not quite able to deliver. In January, J. Peterman
declared bankruptcy, and early last month its few remaining assets,
mainly its name and the lease on an enormous store in Grand Central
Terminal, were sold to Paul Harris Stores Inc. for $10 million. The
company lists $14 million in debt in its last court filing, but
that is unlikely ever to be collected.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first of Cohen's ventures to run into trouble in
recent years. In less than a decade, he has played a leading role
at three well-known clothing firms _ London Fog, Today's Man and J.
Peterman _ as each has descended into serious financial trouble or
gone bankrupt. As J. Peterman's co-founder, Don Staley, sees it,
Arnold Cohen is nothing less than ``a serial killer of companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Retailing is a tough business, and Cohen can certainly not be
blamed for all these companies' ills. In fact, from Cohen's
perspective, he is mostly guilty of signing on to run firms that
were in much worse condition than he first thought. Asked recently
to look back at his career, Cohen says simply, ``I wish in
hindsight that I hadn't selected some of the companies I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his story may offer a cautionary tale in an era enamored
of executive visionaries. Cohen is a charismatic salesman who works
at a frantic pace _ traits that have repeatedly made him attractive
to companies looking for management talent. But in each of these
cases, Cohen has persuaded his superiors, and apparently himself as
well, that daring initiatives to expand or reorganize would lead
inexorably to success. Each time he was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   After learning his trade at Gucci America and Bloomingdale's,
Cohen, 42, came to prominence in the late 1980s as president of J.
Crew Group Inc. In his five years at the company, he helped to
refine its trademark all-American style and more than doubled its
sales. These achievements quickly established Cohen as a first-rate
executive _ a rare commodity in an industry notoriously short of
talent at the top.
</P>
<P>
   And his reputation has stayed with him, even as he has moved
from disaster to disaster. As late as last year, one colleague
said, he bragged that he was one of the two greatest merchandisers
in the country. Cohen does not deny making the remark. ``It is one
of my great strengths,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But even at J. Crew, all was not idyllic under Cohen. In 1992,
he left without having another job lined up. Cohen says he left
because he had ``more than achieved my personal goals'' and it was
time to move on. Cohen says he was also looking for a business
where he could have a significant equity stake, something J. Crew
founder Arthur Cinader did not give him.
</P>
<P>
   Cinader was not available for comment, but a former associate
says that Cohen made mistakes during the catalog company's rapid
expansion into store-based retailing. For example, Cohen signed
long and expensive leases for outlets that the associate says were
too big to display merchandise effectively. To this day, the source
says, several J. Crew stores have to wall off and leave unused
large sections of floor space.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen, however, disputes that point. ``I am proud of my rollout
of the J. Crew stores, they served the brand well,'' he says. ``I
am not aware of any stores that opened during my tenure that did
not do well. There is only one store that I know of when I left
that we felt was too big.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was only when Cohen had the opportunity to run a
business unchecked by a powerful overseer like Cinader that he ran
into serious trouble. Cohen took the helm of London Fog Co. in
September 1993, at a time when the company, a venerable
Maryland-based raincoat maker, was facing a slow decline. Cohen,
hired to give the staid brand a jolt, promised a turnaround,
including a doubling of sales to $700 million from $350 million
within three years. He set about cutting costs by, among other
things, closing five American factories.
</P>
<P>
   While that move was necessary, former colleagues say, Cohen
moved too quickly, causing quality and delivery glitches. Cohen
would not comment on the record about the transformation, but even
his allies said it was not well paced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arnie has great ideas,'' said Chris Fiore, who worked under
him at London Fog. ``He needs to learn patience. Organizations just
cannot absorb all the initiatives that he wants to accomplish on
his schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Cohen began another unusual policy, a notable
instance, former colleagues say, of his assertiveness. He forbade
stores to mark down the brand's merchandise until Dec. 8 of that
year, saying his aim was to reestablish London Fog's elite image.
But the move infuriated retailers, who traditionally do their best
raincoat business during promotions around Thanksgiving. William
Crain, who was part of the team that came in to resuscitate the
company from near-death a year later, said the policy ``clearly
alienated the trade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It had the unintended and costly consequence,'' he added, ``of
shifting orders to the company's lower-priced, lower-margin brand,
Towne.''
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen disagrees. ``The campaign was strategically
appropriate, it won critical acclaim.'' He adds in his defense,
``Many of the strategies we applied to rebuilding the brand are
still in force today.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bob Grayson, a retail veteran on the board of London Fog as well
as a personal friend of Cohen's from Westport, Conn., argues that
the company was in worse shape when Cohen took over than anybody
knew. ``Critical financial information was not made available to
the new management,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Cohen took some of the blame. Eleven months later, with
London Fog hemorrhaging cash and its debt swollen to $425 million,
Cohen was out of the company. He quickly rebounded, though not to
the same heights. He was hired in the spring of 1994 by Today's Man
Inc. as executive vice president for merchandising and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   As testament to his abilities as a salesman, he not only
negotiated a mid-six-figure compensation package but persuaded
David Feld, the chairman and founder, to buy his Westport home out
of his own pocket for several million dollars so Cohen could afford
to move to the Philadelphia area to be near the company's
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   When Cohen arrived, Today's Man was booming. Less than two years
later, in February 1996, it filed for bankruptcy. Certainly, there
were forces at work well beyond Cohen's control, including a poor
retail season in 1995 and an overexpansion that was started before
Cohen's tenure. Still, executives at the company say he was a key
mover behind decisions that resulted in inflated advertising
budgets and ballooning inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Johnson, the chief financial officer at Today's Man then
and now, characterized Cohen's tenure gingerly: ``Certainly he was
a member of the management group during the period of time that the
company went through a serious financial crisis. He made decisions,
but those did not occur in a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Gross, who was president of Today's Man when Cohen was
there, is still a big fan. He said, ``Arnie has a tremendous feel
for merchandise.'' But he admits his subordinate took a lot of
careful watching. ``He can be overly aggressive, push too far to
the edge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Cohen says that he was in ``no way responsible''
for what happened at Today's Man and that the heavy advertising and
promotions he engaged in ``were the kind of actions people take
when they need to raise sales.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen was out again by spring 1996. By this time he had
apparently decided it might be wiser to be his own boss. He started
shopping around for a company and made a bid for a job at J.
Peterman. Peterman turned him down at first, but after a year of
negotiations hired him to be president and chief operating officer.
The company's sales, which had been rising steadily, were $65
million in 1997, but the poorly run firm had almost never made a
profit.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen envisioned raising sales to $90 million by the end of 1998
by expanding into as many as 70 retail outlets. To reach this
explosive goal he spent lavishly, especially for a company as small
as J. Peterman. He hired a slew of expensive executives, paying
generous six-figure salaries in addition to pricey fees to
headhunters. He himself earned $500,000 a year in salary plus $1
million in stock options (which are now worthless).
</P>
<P>
   In addition, former colleagues say, Cohen insisted on opening a
Hollywood office for J. Peterman, paid for large groups to go on
far-flung trips and started two brand new catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, when Staley, who co-founded the company and was on its
board, suggested running an ad during ``Seinfeld'' simply to inform
viewers that there was a real J. Peterman, Cohen instead suggested
in all seriousness having his lawyers contact NBC and demand that
the show flash J. Peterman's toll-free number every time the
company's name was used on the air, Staley recalls. It was
laughable, he says. (Cohen says he made that suggestion as part of
a brainstorming session and that he never tried to act on it.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, to cut costs, Cohen began using cheaper materials for
the clothing line. As soon as customers received the new items,
they began complaining about low quality. Catalog sales started to
plummet. Cohen says J. Peterman was a victim of an industry-wide
slump in sales. Still, the loses were real and the lenders began to
panic. Both Cohen and Peterman say the business was destroyed by
lack of credit at this key juncture. But even Cohen's booster, Bob
Grayson of London Fog, admits there were errors in judgment.
``Should we have seen this coming over our shoulder?'' he asked.
``Yes. Should we have been expanding so aggressively? No.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arnie,'' he added, ``is not a crisis manager.''
</P>
<P>
   By the fall of 1998, Peterman confessed to Staley that Cohen had
run through $16 million and the company was in dire straits. Soon
after, the firm declared bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen now works as a retail consultant. He says he has clients,
but declined to list any. He admits that he is ``disappointed''
with how J. Peterman turned out. ``But,'' he added, with
characteristic optimism, ``I think it was a learning opportunity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
