<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  
(DW) 

</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CBS TO BUY KING WORLD FOR $2.5 BILLION IN STOCK
</P>
<P>
   As expected, CBS announced that it had agreed to buy King World
Productions, the syndicator of television hits like ``The Oprah
Winfrey Show,'' ``Wheel of Fortune'' and ``Jeopardy,'' for $2.5
billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   CBS has long been looking to extend its control over programming
for its owned-and-operated stations. King World not only has $800
million in cash on its balance sheet, but it requires little
capital expenditure and carries no debt, so it will contribute
immediately to the bottom line of CBS.
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLERCHRYSLER POSTS STRONG SALES
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler reported sales of 16.5 percent more Chryslers,
Dodges, Plymouths and Jeeps in the United States, setting
first-quarter and March sales records, as demand for new vehicles
continued to grow. Nearly every auto maker that reported March
results also had double-digit increases. DaimlerChrysler's sales
were led by a 20 percent gain in light trucks. Car sales rose 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   MCCAIN OPPOSES ENCRYPTION POLICY
</P>
<P>
   In a surprising about-face, Sen. John McCain said that he was
abandoning his support for the Clinton administration's policy
requiring that the authorities be given keys enabling them to
unlock scrambled data.
</P>
<P>
   VIRUS HUNT INCLUDES AMERICA ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents hunting for the author of the Melissa computer
virus obtained a court order seeking background information from
America Online, one day after seizing a computer from a Florida
Internet access provider that may contain clues to the virus'
origin.
</P>
<P>
   YAHOO CONFIRMS BROADCAST DEAL
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo confirmed that it would buy Broadcast.com, the Web's No.1
audio-video provider, in a deal valued at $5.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   MANUFACTURING AND SPENDING GROW
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing strengthened in March as consumer spending on
automobiles, computers and furniture remained strong and export
orders grew for a second month. Meantime, consumer income and
spending rose in February, and construction spending is on the
rise, driven mainly by a big jump in government spending on
construction.
</P>
<P>
   FCC SEEKS INPUT FROM REGULATED
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Federal Communications Commission is
encouraging Ameritech and SBC Communications to help draw up terms
that would promote competition so the commission would approve the
companies' pending $62 billion merger.
</P>
<P>
   SEC INVESTIGATES FUND MANAGER
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission is investigating whether
a portfolio manager at Oechsle International Advisers, a Boston
money management firm, tried to manipulate the price of a security
in London.
</P>
<P>
   STOCKS CLIMB, LED BY ONLINE ISSUES
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose as the Yahoo acquisition of Broadcast.com bolstered
optimism for both on-line and telephone issues. The Dow Jones
industrial average gained 46.35 points, to 9,832.51, and the Nasdaq
composite index climbed 31.97 points, or 1.3 percent, to 2,493.37.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 7.35 points, to
1,293.72.
</P>
<P>
   Prices of Treasury securities fell as strong economic reports
heightened fears of renewed inflation later this year.
</P>
<P>
   MOST MARKETS CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   Stock and most commodity markets will be closed Friday in the
United States and many other countries in observance of Good
Friday. United States bond markets will close at noon, and some
commodity markets will have abbreviated morning sessions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
