<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZAMBIA: Shots Fired At Kaunda's Car
</P>
<P>
   Four gunmen shot at a car belonging to former President Kenneth
D. Kaunda as it pulled up to his house, his family said, but
Kaunda, who was warned last month that an attempt might be made on
his life, was not in it. No one was hurt. The incident happened the
same day Kaunda, who is running for the presidency again, appealed
a High Court decision rendering him stateless and won a court order
preventing his arrest until the appeal is heard.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: Prisoners Can Vote
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's highest court ruled that prisoners can vote in
the June 2 elections. The court said only Parliament has the power
to disenfranchise prisoners, which it has not done.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: Military Tie To Police Cut
</P>
<P>
   Command of the 187,000-member national police force was formally
removed from the military as part of a reform of Indonesia's armed
forces. ``We hope the police will change in their attitude and
behavior, based on their function and role as the protector of the
people,'' said Gen. Wiranto, the chief of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA: Toxic Waste Switch
</P>
<P>
   In a switch, an American waste disposal company, Safety-Kleen
Corp., announced it would not send 3,000 tons of toxic waste to
California from Cambodia, where it has caused panic, controversy
and at least two deaths. It acted after the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency rescinded its approval of the shipment. The waste
will be returned to Taiwan, where it originated.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: Anwar Verdict Postponed
</P>
<P>
   Judge Augustine Paul pushed back to April 14 the date when he
plans to issue a verdict in the case of former Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim, saying he needed more time to consider the
final arguments. The sex-and-corruption trial, which has continued
over 77 hearings since it began Nov. 2, has become the longest
criminal trial in Malaysian history.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH AND SOUTH KOREA: Ship Sinks
</P>
<P>
   A North Korean ship sank after colliding with a South Korean
vessel between Sri Lanka and Indonesia, and 37 North Korean crew
members are missing. It was not clear what caused the collision
between the two ships, both freighters, and there was no indication
politics was involved or that the crash was anything but an
accident.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG: Immigration Order
</P>
<P>
   Two days after a high court ruled against 17 mainland Chinese
who claimed residency in Hong Kong, a judge ordered the government
to release 100 other detained mainland residents. Immigration
authorities rounded up the immigrants after the ruling, but the
judge said they could remain in the territory until the court
decided on an appeal from the original 17.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: Berlin Airport
</P>
<P>
   In a further sign of Berlin's growing significance as Germany's
reclaimed capital, the government approved plans for a huge
expansion of the city's Schoenefeld airport. The $4 billion
project, due to be completed in 2007, will consolidate air traffic
into a single hub. Berlin's other two airports _ Tegel and the
historic Tempelhof _ will be closed.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: Election Protests
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of people blocked streets in the capital of Guerrero
State, Chilpancingo, in an attempt to stop the inauguration of a
new governor. Supporters of a leftist opposition candidate accuse
the governing party of vote-buying in Guerrero's Feb. 7 election,
but an electoral court ruled the election fair. The State
Department advised U.S. citizens to ``defer unnecessary travel'' to
Chilpancingo, saying major Guerrero beach resorts, including
Acapulco, may also see protests.
</P>
</TEXT>
