<HEADLINE>
ON THE JOB: LAUGHING ALL THE WAY TO THE OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, April 4) 
(bl) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The workplace can be pretty grim. But there is an antidote:
humor. Applied in the right doses, it can transform a job into a
joy.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a rabbi in the Philadelphia suburbs, Robert Alper
faced a problem. An emotional issue was coming up for a vote, and
the synagogue's trustees were divided. How could he calm the
passions?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was teaching a course in Judaism at a nearby Catholic
college,'' writes Alper, now a rabbi in East Dorset, Vt., where he
also practices stand-up comedy. ``The dean of our department was
friendly and curious about the workings of a synagogue, so I
invited her to see us `up close and personal' at a meeting of our
leadership. She attended on that perilous night.
</P>
<P>
   ``In full nun's habit. It was the most polite meeting in our
congregation's history.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Brostek of New York City, director of special events at
Queens College, used to work for Continental Can Co., organizing
management meetings. At one meeting, he noticed that 10 of the 300
attendees were named Robert. ``Suspending diversity guidelines, I
put them all at the same dinner table,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   The maneuver, he said, resulted in instant camaraderie that
``spread through the room and lasted for the three-day meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, not every jest is taken as intended. Charles
Kazanjian of New York City was entering data for the Census Bureau
in 1990 when a supervisor asked what was done when the information
was incomplete. Hoping for a laugh, Kazanjian said, ``We make it
up.'' End of data-entry tasks. Beginning of filing duties.
</P>
<P>
   A syllabus from Luke Barber, a professor of philosophy at
Richland College in Dallas, says, ``I am very committed to laughter
and play.'' And, he writes, so is his school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call our annual convocation of faculty, administrators and
support personnel the feast of fools. We discuss serious goals;
however, we do so by also lampooning our most sacred objectives.
One year, the college president arrived on stage by swinging in
like Tarzan on a rope.
</P>
<P>
   ``Video lampoons have included a poke at our efforts to make
registration easier for students. `Drive-Through Registration'
showed students ordering, `I'll have one English (hold the poetry),
a philosophy and two histories.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barber, co-author of ``Work Like Your Dog: 50 Ways to Work Less,
Play More and Earn More'' (Random House Villard, 1999), said: ``We
spend more of our time thinking about working, driving to and from
work and working than any other waking activity. If we can't have
fun at work, then when are we going to have fun?''
</P>
<P>
   Every year, PHH Vehicle Management Services of Hunt Valley, Md.,
holds seminars for clients _ ``your basic snooze-a-rama,'' says
Dick George, a marketer for the company. To add spice to a recent
meeting, George impersonated the television detective Columbo. It
was such a hit he decided to do an encore.
</P>
<P>
   So a month later, he found himself in a rumpled trench coat,
pacing outside a meeting room, cigar in hand. Inside, he said, a
senior vice president was ``explaining the glories of our new
product to 100 of our biggest clients and all our senior brass.''
</P>
<P>
   At the appointed moment, he barged in, muttering: ``Oh, excuse
me, just a minute, if I could. I'm sorry to interrupt. I really am.
I just feel terrible. But I was trying to get out of my parking
space, and somebody's got me blocked in.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he glanced around the room. ``Evidently my impression more
closely resembled your basic psychopathic killer,'' he said. ``Some
people appeared to be looking for the emergency exits. One client
sitting nearby _ an ex-Marine _ told me later he was thinking of
`taking me out.' I don't think he meant a date.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon the tension ebbed, and Columbo asked, ``Does anybody here
have a red Ford Taurus?'' He squinted at a paper and turned it 180
degrees. ``A blue Chevy Blazer, license number OM 1367 D?'' There
were titters. He headed for the door as the vice president
continued his talk, saying a new Internet tool called PHH
Interactive could search fleet data by vehicle identification
number, by driver or by license number.
</P>
<P>
   ``By license number?'' Columbo said, coming back into the room.
``Would you check OM 1367 D?''
</P>
<P>
   After the vice president demonstrated the product, Columbo
jumped up and summarized what he had heard. The vice president
responded, ``That's right, Lieutenant, and it can do all those
things in real time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Real time?'' Columbo asked. ``I'm confused. What other kind of
time is there?'' The audience roared.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little humor,'' George writes, ``made it a lot easier to
absorb a message that was important to our company.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
