<HEADLINE>
COMPTON PROUD OF WILLIAMS SISTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMPTON _ A cultural landmark sits near the corner of Compton
and Atlantic Boulevards. Dreams were built here, from the ground
up. And yet this is not a registered treasure like the Watts Towers
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find no sign anywhere explaining its significance. You
probably would have driven right past it had a local historian not
kindly directed you to the spot where the tennis careers of Venus
and Serena Williams were born.
</P>
<P>
   The businesses on the 15100 block of S. Atlantic Blvd. turn over
like numbers on an odometer. Amid the constant change what remains
are plenty of people who remember watching the Williams sisters
chase down tennis balls on the two city-owned courts at East Rancho
Dominguez Park in the late 1980s. That was long before they became
the most successful African-American sister act that L.A. has had a
hand in raising since basketball players Pam and Paula McGee at
USC.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Williams, the girls' father, had a vision. He was not
unlike Simon Rodia, the Italian immigrant of modest means and no
architectural training who took that which was at his fingertips _
tiles and glass and rocks and the like _ and working intuitively,
created 100-foot towers of breathtaking beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Rodia needed 33 years to build his legacy; Williams has been at
it less than 20 and already it appears his life's work is just
about complete; 18-year-old Venus, who defeated her younger sister
in the final of a tournament in Miami last weekend, has risen to
No.6 in the world. Seventeen-year-old Serena is No.11 with a
bullet.
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, bullets. They are, like the shells imbedded in Rodia's
sculpture, part of the mosaic Williams has created. He speaks often
of how the sisters once dodged gang gunfire on the courts, diving
for cover right on the very spot where you're now standing.
</P>
<P>
   The Williamses lived a few blocks from these courts for eight
years, moving to Florida in 1991. It was the memory of these mean
streets that pulled Richard Williams out of his seat Sunday in the
middle of the Lipton Championships final between his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   He left the stadium to keep from crying. As he later told
reporters, he grew teary-eyed contemplating how far Venus and
Serena had come from the cracked concrete courts and gang-infested
neighborhoods of their childhoods.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, the treacherous terrain that Richard Williams
remembers seems rather sleepy save for staccato sounds coming from
behind the courts, where an outdoor basketball court once stood
that drew both players and provocateurs.
</P>
<P>
   But it is gone, like the Williamses. Going up in its place is a
gym that is scheduled to be completed by the end of the summer, one
of many projects borne of the community's resolve to fill kids'
idle time.
</P>
<P>
   Things are definitely getting better here, says 18-year-old
Ernando Solis, who has grown up in the neighborhood. ``When I first
moved here, it was really bad,'' he says. ``But not anymore. It's
changed a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Solis lived two blocks from East Rancho Dominguez
Park. He used the tennis courts to tell time by. He'd walk past
them every weekday morning; if the Williams sisters were out there
hitting balls, he could be pretty certain it wasn't yet 8 o'clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't understand exactly why they were doing that every
day,'' Solis tells you. ``You'd see them all the time working hard.
Now I see them sometimes on TV. It kind of inspires me.''
</P>
<P>
   No one you talk to here begrudges the Williams sisters their
success. There is no Venus envy that you can see, just palpable
pride that two kids who once were part of the community are forcing
people to re-think some tired old stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   What does bother some of his old neighbors is that Richard
Williams continues to get mileage out of some of these same
stereotypes, at their expense. Where does he get off, these
longtime residents wonder, emerging from the family's gated
compound in posh Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., to talk about the
bullet-riddled streets and the gang-filled neighborhoods and the
unkempt courts of Compton as though it were just yesterday that he
fled the city?
</P>
<P>
   Cities, like tennis players, can improve dramatically in a few
years' time. If the old neighborhood's progress hasn't kept pace
with that of the Williams sisters, well, it's not for a lack of
trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people get a biscuit above starvation and they
forget,'' Anquanetta Walker says with a sigh.
</P>
<P>
   She is speaking from the senior community center across the
street from East Rancho Dominguez Park. She remembers Richard
Williams, from the tennis courts. She says a man so devoted to his
daughters isn't easily forgotten in a day and age when too many
girls grow up never knowing their daddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you hear about are gangs and fighting and shooting,''
Walker says. ``So you think of Compton, you think of the ghetto.
But overall, you've got a lot of good people here. You look at what
the Williamses have done, coming from here. It says to me there's a
lot of good in Compton, a lot of talent sitting here waiting to be
drawn out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Williams shouldn't knock the city now that he's got
his millions of dollars. He got it because he invested his time in
his daughters. Instead of telling people how bad it is here, I wish
he'd come back, talk to all the absent fathers and be a mentor to
some other man's daughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams donates equipment and a large chunk of change to the
longstanding after-school program at the Rancho La Cienega Sports
Center in South Central L.A. But you get the feeling some of his
old neighbors aren't impressed. They'd rather see him give more of
his precious time, like Juan Sayles is doing.
</P>
<P>
   Sayles is on the court next to you, hitting tennis balls with
his 14-year-old niece Keisha. He taught Keisha how to play tennis
when she was 6. Now he says people will stop him at the gas station
or in the liquor store and ask, ``Did you see the girls from
Compton on TV?'' in a way that lets him know they hope his niece is
next.
</P>
<P>
   The next ghetto Cinderella, if you believe Richard Williams. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
