<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: AGENCIES USING WIDE RANGE OF FORMULAS TO SET
PAYMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   PATRICIA WINTERS LAURO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 15 percent commission on media spending that
clients pay advertising agencies as their fee was once standard in
the advertising business. Now it is about as dead as the
three-martini lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate America is turning away from billings-based
commissions in large numbers, and many now routinely look at a wide
range of new formulas that can be custom &UR;  &LR; tailored for a client's
needs. The new methods of agency payments may include anything from
straight hourly fees for labor to performance incentive fees to
fixed retainers, or a variety of combinations .
</P>
<P>
   Driving the changes are two key factors: belt-tightening clients
who began cutting commissions more than a decade ago, and vast
changes in how ad agencies reach consumers that go way beyond
network TV advertising. The commission formula tends to encourage
costly media buys and has been criticized for overlooking important
emerging mediums such as the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Together it amounts to a sea change in how agencies are paid,
which is underscored by the fact that giants like Young &AMP; Rubicam
and DDB Needham Worldwide, a unit of Omnicom Group, now oppose the
structure that once made Madison Avenue very profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's top two advertisers, the General Motors &UR;  &LR; Corp &UR; . &LR; 
and , are both moving away from billings-based compensation plans.
GM spent $3.09 billion in advertising and promotion in 1997, and
P&AMP;G spent $2.74 billion, according to Advertising Age, the industry
trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   Procter &AMP; Gamble now pays media commissions but will soon change
that. In July, the company will institute a series of tests around
the globe that will determine how ``to link financial rewards of
our agencies to increased sales revenue'' at P&AMP;G, said Gretchen
Briscoe, a P&AMP;G spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional commission does not reward increased sales or
development of holistic marketing plans,'' Ms. Briscoe said. ``We
want a system that's media neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   GM has been using a variety of compensation programs over the
last decade, ranging from traditional commissions to straight fees
to performance incentives. The auto giant is now working toward ``a
performance-based fee compensation'' system with agencies ``where
we don't already have one,'' said Philip Guarascio, GM's vice
president for advertising and corporate marketing.
</P>
<P>
   One key advantage to performance fees is that they encourage
agencies to think about how to promote as broadly as possible,
utilizing every marketing resource available from web site design
to Internet marketing, Guarascio said. It also requires the
discipline to set and later evaluate very specific goals that keep
both the agency and the client on target.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about doing the work, it's about how well the
work is done _ that's what accountability is about,'' Guarascio
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, only 35 percent of advertisers paid their agencies
based on media commissions, down from 61 percent three years
earlier, according to a study by the Association of National
Advertisers Inc., a New York-based trade group. Meantime, the study
showed just 9 percent of respondents paid agencies 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Though that would seemingly be bad news for ad agencies,
especially the giants that routinely handle accounts that spend $50
million in media and more (translation: $7.5 million in
commissions), DDB Needham says the opposite is the case: the
changes are not happening fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Reinhard, DDB Needham's chairman and chief executive
officer, said the old system undervalues an agency by paying a flat
rate that is not based on merit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ludicrous because it doesn't talk about quality,''
Reinhard said. ``If we're going to be brand architects and
strategists, we have to figure out a way to get paid for our
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission system was developed in the last century as a way
to attract agents to place ads in newspapers, said Robert Lundin of
Jones-Lundin, the Chicago-based consultancy that conducted the
trade group study.
</P>
<P>
   The 15 percent figure was ``picked out of a hat'' and never well
loved among clients, Lundin said. But it was not until the
mid-1980s that cost-conscious clients began reducing commissions en
masse, creating something of a panic in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts ``tapped into a pent-up anger clients had about paying
15 percent, whether an agency performed or not,'' said Edward H.
Vick, Young &AMP; Rubicam's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   In classic Madison Avenue fashion, agencies have since turned
clients' lemons into lemonade, by coming up with new formulas that
can earn an agency even more than a 15 percent commission, said
Lundin. Last year, DDB Needham made some $6 million in additional
compensation beyond its base fees for reaching client objectives,
Reinhard said.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, the 15 percent commission's demise has actually
benefited some small agencies because commissions on small media
budgets often do not adequately pay agencies for their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of work you do for a client with a $4 million or $5
million budget is very often the same amount as the client with the
$10 million or $15 million budget,'' said Adam Stagliano, president
of Weiss Stagliano Inc., a New York shop with about $100 million in
billings.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes that means more than a 15 percent commission.
Ciociola &UR;  &LR; &AMP; Co., a $50 million shop also in the city, often takes a
guaranteed fee with a provision to take the greater of either fees
or media commission, Mel Ciociola, the agency's chairman, said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Flexibility is the watchword,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While labor-based compensation agreements now outpace
billings-based payments, according to the trade group study, more
than 30 percent of advertisers now also include some type of
incentive compensation agreement that ties bonus money to the
agency's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Young &AMP; Rubicam said the performance might be based on increased
sales, or on other qualitative research measures such as brand
preference or consumer awareness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incentive compensation says that we'll take less up front and
if we're successful, we have an opportunity to make a lot more
money,'' Vick said. ``We're saying we're willing to put a large
part of our profit at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, linking advertising to sales revenue can be
risky because often problems beyond the scope of advertising cause
a brand to fail, such as the wrong price point or poor
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Lundin, whose company conducted the trade group study, said that
this problem may soon be solved because a more exact formula to
measure the success of advertising has been defined in the academic
world, and he expects it will be adopted by business in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Still, until then, incentives tied to sales remain a risk _
though some agencies consider it worth it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clients take those risks every day,'' Reinhardt said, ``so
why shouldn't we?''
</P>
</TEXT>
