<HEADLINE>
TURKEY WITH JIMMY, THREE MNF DATES ON TAP FOR COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Guess who's coming to dinner on Thanksgiving
Day.
</P>
<P>
   How about former Cowboys coach Jimmy Johnson, who will bring his
up-and-coming Miami Dolphins to Texas Stadium for the annual
holiday game.
</P>
<P>
   It will be Johnson's first visit as a coach since his bitter
breakup with Cowboys owner Jerry Jones after the 1993 Super Bowl
season. Johnson visited Texas Stadium in 1995 as part of the Fox
studio team.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's much-anticipated visit will be the highlight of the
Cowboys' 1999 schedule, which was released yesterday by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game will be exciting for me personally,'' said Jones,
smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Jones already has the satisfaction of the Cowboys' 29-10 victory
in Miami during Johnson's first season as coach in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who was hired by Jones in 1989, helped orchestrate the
franchise's return to prominence with Super Bowl titles in 1992 and
1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``... I anticipate there will be ``some'' interest in our
Thanksgiving Day game,'' Johnson said yesterday. ``And for me
personally, I am looking forward to going back to Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys open the season at Washington on Sept. 12. The
schedule also includes a franchise-record six nationally televised
games, which tops the previous high of five. The Cowboys will make
three appearances on ``Monday Night Football,'' including the home
opener against the Atlanta Falcons (Sept. 20) and road trips
against the New York Giants (Oct. 18) and Minnesota Vikings (Nov.
8).
</P>
<P>
   ``The schedule speaks to the interest in our team and the
excitement we have for the upcoming season,'' Jones said of the
Cowboys' TV schedule, which also includes three nationally
television preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   The home schedule includes games against the Dolphins, Jets,
Packers and Falcons. In addition to playing on Sunday, Monday night
and Thursday, the Cowboys have a Friday, Christmas Eve matchup
against New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Within the first six weeks of the season, the Cowboys will have
faced each of their NFC East opponents. The Cowboys swept the
division last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to go through training camp and be ready to compete
at a high level because the challenge is to get ahead of it in the
division,'' Jones said. ``We know from last year that can make a
lot of things positive for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the schedule, which ranks 12th-toughest in the league
based on opponents' 1998 records, is one of the most challenging
the Cowboys have had in years. In addition to playing the AFC East,
Jones cited a stretch in October and early November when they
sandwich a home game against the Redskins (Oct. 24) between road
games against the Eagles (Oct. 10) and Giants (Oct. 18) and the
Colts (Oct. 31) and the Vikings (Nov. 8).
</P>
<P>
   The positives, Jones said, are that the Cowboys end the season
with three of their final five games at home and that they play one
potential cold-weather game, at New England on Dec. 5.
</P>
<P>
   The bye week comes early for the Cowboys, Sept. 26, after two
games. Cowboys' pursuit Jones had no update on the Cowboys' pursuit
of receiver Raghib Ismail, center Mark Stepnoski and linebacker
Quentin Coryatt. Jones said he remains confident the team will sign
all three players, but reiterated the deals are not yet finalized.
Visiting prospects Although the Cowboys have been visiting with a
number of draft prospects _ they brought in Louisiana Tech tight
end Marlon Chambers a few days ago _ they won't begin serious
business until next week. Jones said the team has scheduled visits
for some of the draft's top prospects at several positions.
Southern California inside linebacker Chris Claiborne is one of the
players scheduled to visit Valley Ranch next week.
Schedule breakdown With a first-place schedule in the NFC East, the
Cowboys might have a difficult time repeating as division
champions. Staff writer Clarence E. Hill Jr., takes a look at the
schedule: Date Opponent Comment Sept. 12 at Washington The Cowboys
are 29-9-1 on opening day Sept. 20 vs. Atlanta Chan Gailey's first
matchup against boyhood idol Dan Reeves Sept. 26 Bye Oct. 3 vs.
Arizona First chance against Cardinals since surprising playoff
loss Oct. 10 at Philadelphia Cowboys should be heavy favorites Oct.
18 at NY Giants Deion's first return to New York since Primetime
performance last season Oct. 24 vs. Washington Cowboys have won six
of past seven at home against Redskins Oct. 31 at Indianapolis
Cowboys get their first look at Peyton Manning Nov. 8 at Minnesota
Vikings receiver Randy Moss burned them for 163 yards and three
touchdowns last season Nov. 14 vs. Green Bay Cowboys have won seven
consecutive at home against the Packers Nov. 21 at Arizona Could
loom as showdown for division Nov. 25 vs. Miami Jimmy Johnson
returns as rival coach for first time since bitter departure Dec. 5
at New England Cowboys are 7-0 all-time against Patriots Dec. 12
vs. Philadelphia Cowboys have won eight of past nine at home
against Eagles Dec. 19 vs. NY Jets ``Big Tuna'' Bill Parcells
visits Texas Stadium Dec. 24 at New Orleans Cowboys look for
revenge after embarrassing loss last season Jan. 2 vs. NY Giants _
Cowboys have won seven of past eight at home against the Giants
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
