<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC MEETS WITH KOSOVAR LEADER; U.S. SOLDIERS TO FACE YUGOSLAV
COURT 
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS 10th graf (``Only after....'') to add NATO version of U.S.
soldiers' capture.) 
(ATTN: Calif., Mich., Texas)  (See also: KOSOVO-NATO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-MACEDONIA,
KOSOVO-SOLDIERS, KOSOVO-MILITARY, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-EUROPE,
KOSOVO-RIGHTS, KOSOVO-RUSSIA, KOSOVO-REBELS, KOSOVO-ALBANIA,
KOSOVO-RELIGION, KOSOVO-BOSNIA) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Three American soldiers captured along
the border with Macedonia will appear before a Yugoslav military
court that could charge and try them, the state news agency,
Tanjug, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, a judicial officer in the Kosovo
capital, Pristina, said that the court investigation of the three
could begin as early as Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government said a Yugoslav court-martial of the
Americans would violate international law.
</P>
<P>
   The men _ Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 24, of Los Angeles;
Staff Sgt. Christopher J. Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., and
Specialist Steven M. Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas, _ were
paraded on Serbian state television Thursday, but the main evening
broadcast led with another news event, an unexpected meeting
between the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, and a prominent
leader of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians, Ibrahim Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   On the broadcast, the two men, looking relaxed, signed a
document calling for a peaceful end to the Kosovo crisis through
``political means.'' Rugova was a part of the ethnic Albanian
delegation that signed a Western-drafted peace treaty rejected by
the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   With Serbian forces now driving to destroy the armed Kosovo
Liberation Army and forcing tens of thousands of civilians from the
province, Rugova's seemingly uncoerced meeting led a spokesman for
the ethnic Albanian rebels, Jakub Krasniqi, to call Rugova's action
high treason. But other than the television images, which carried
Thursday's date, there was no confirmation that the men had
actually met on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova, who has long advocated a nonviolent political solution
to the problem of Kosovo, appeared relaxed, chatting with an
evidently cheerful Milosevic. But it was only on Wednesday that
Serbian television announced that Rugova had sought the protection
of the Serbian police and showed a nervous Rugova asking NATO to
stop its bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Although the three captured soldiers, grim-faced and nervous,
were shown on television here throughout the day, the Serbian
evening news did not even mention them until deep in the broadcast,
and then in the context of a commentary. First, it showed Milosevic
meeting representatives of the Greek Orthodox Church. Then it
showed the Serbian president, Milan Milutinovic, Foreign Minister
Zivadin Jovanovic and the Serbian Orthodox Patriarch Pavle all
meeting separately with Archbishop Jean-Louis Tauran, sent here by
Pope John Paul II to call on all sides to observe a week-long
Easter truce that would extend from the Western observance of
Easter, April 4, through the Orthodox observance on April 11, a
suggestion the allies have already rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Then, a delegation of Russian parliamentarians was shown meeting
various officials.
</P>
<P>
   Only after all this footage did the announcer mention the
capture of the American soldiers ``on Yugoslav territory,'' as
another event ``casting doubt on the Western interpretation of
events.'' At first NATO said the soldiers were captured about three
miles inside Macedonia, though later top officers said it was
unclear exactly where they were caught.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one gloating touch when the announcer read: ``The
Western aggressors have over night forgotten the humanitarian
crisis'' that is their ostensible reason for intervention and
``have now directed all their attention to three of their soldiers
who were captured,'' the announcer said. ``This puts the American
Fuehrer in the most uncomfortable position because he is the one
who launched the theory that America would win without a single
casualty.''
</P>
<P>
   Western officials were debating Thursday why Rugova might have
met with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's secretary-general, Javier Solana, said in Brussels
Thursday that Rugova might have been under duress. ``I don't see
that Rugova is freely doing what he is doing,'' Solana said, adding
that he would feel ``much more relaxed'' if he had been able to
speak to Rugova.
</P>
<P>
   While the Americans originally backed Rugova, who was re-elected
as the leader of the ethnic Albanians last April, his credibility
was sharply diminished by the rise in support for the insurgents of
the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Unity among the ethnic Albanians has been fragile, and with the
Serbian military trying to destroy the KLA in the current fighting,
some Western diplomats suggested by telephone that Rugova may be
trying both to restore his position and to save what is left of
Kosovo from catastrophe.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may think that half a state is better than a killing ground
and a wasteland,'' said one Western diplomat who left Belgrade
before the bombings began. He drew a possible comparison with the
Palestinian leader, Yasir Arafat, who has sacrificed Palestinian
claims to parts of the West Bank for a Palestinian Authority likely
to become a state.
</P>
<P>
   But it is not clear whom Rugova now represents. As thousands of
ethnic Albanians are driven out of Kosovo, some will regard him as
a traitor, quisling or worse, while others will regard him as
trying to save something from the rubble.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials said they were concerned that Milosevic might
conduct his own negotiations with Rugova and come up with a plan
for Kosovo's partition or political autonomy along the lines the
West has drawn _ but without the presence of NATO peacekeeping
troops that the West is insisting upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Milosevic and Rugova announce a deal that gives political
autonomy, a sharp reduction in Serb forces in Kosovo and protection
for refugees to return, it will be awkward,'' another Western
official said by telephone. ``It will look even more like NATO is
on the side of the KLA.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, in another move to shore up his support in the
Yugoslav Army, fired an army commander and seven other generals
based in Serbia's sister republic, Montenegro. He replaced the
Second Army Corps commander, Gen. Radosav Martinovic, with a closer
ally, Gen. Milorad Obradovic.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro has a more pro-Western government and has tried to
distance itself from Serbia's conflict with NATO. Yugoslav analysts
wondered whether Martinovic might have resisted orders to crack
down on Montenegro's separatist-minded government, or if Milosevic
feared an army coup starting from Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Despite U.S. support for Montenegro, NATO warplanes have bombed
Yugoslav military facilities there, including the airport. The
strikes have undermined President Milo Djukanovic's opposition to
Belgrade's policies and raised concerns that Milosevic may move
against Djukanovic.
</P>
<P>
   In the air war early on Thursday, NATO struck targets in Kosovo
and destroyed a major bridge over the Danube River in Novi Sad,
Serbia's second city. NATO officials said that military warehouses
line one end of the bridge. Serbian officials said the city's water
supply was badly damaged. The wreckage blocked the Danube waterway,
one of the main passages for trade between Western and Central
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   For Belgrade's 2 million people, it was a frazzled day, with
rumors flying at warp speed about NATO's plans for bombing
government buildings, for the first time, in the city's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   As people lined up to buy an informal ration of two packs of
cigarettes _ one kiosk owner said he'd sold 1,000 packs by noon and
had none left on Thursday _ they exchanged worried talk about where
they lived in town and how close it might be to the defense
ministry or the interior ministry.
</P>
<P>
   A man who would only identify himself as Sasha, who owns a
basement cafe downtown, said his parents were sleeping in the cafe,
and he was considering going out to the suburbs for the night. A
man named Ilija said he would go to his sister's house; others
talked of heading down to the crowded bomb shelters for the first
time in several days.
</P>
<P>
   Milan Bozic, Belgrade's deputy mayor, said in an interview
Thursday that there was little more the city could do to prepare
for new bombings. ``We just want to insure there are enough
supplies on both sides of the river in case they destroy the
bridges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that 100 yards from the federal and Serbian ministries
for internal affairs is Belgrade's largest hospital complex, the
Clinical Center of Serbia, attached to the university. It contains
4,000 of Belgrade's 5,000 hospital beds, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bozic said, there had been ``10 or 11'' civilian deaths
from the bombing in and around Belgrade and 47 people kept at least
one night in the hospital for their wounds. Military casualties are
classified information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   One Serb said Thursday that he had read on the Internet a New
York Times report that NATO would spare the Presidential Palace
because it had a Rembrandt on the first floor. ``It's good news and
bad news,'' the Serb said he told a friend. ``The good news is
Milosevic's palace will be spared because it has a Rembrandt. The
bad news is that you, unfortunately, do not have a Rembrandt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
