<HEADLINE>
WETTELAND, PALMEIRO PASS FINAL SPRING TESTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Two performances yesterday eased the
Rangers' greatest fears this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Closer John Wetteland appeared dominant during a 1-2-3 first
inning, and first baseman Rafael Palmeiro delivered a game-winning
home run in the bottom of the eighth inning in the Rangers' 6-4
victory against Cincinnati at Charlotte County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sent positive vibes throughout the clubhouse,'' manager
Johnny Oates said after the Rangers' final Florida exhibition game.
``It was a nice way to end it.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be an understatement.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, whose progress this spring was slowed by a
soft-tissue injury to his right ankle, required only nine pitches
to complete his appearance and never allowed the ball to leave the
infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't expect this,'' said Wetteland, who threw
seven pitches for strikes. ``I really didn't. My warmup was so bad
that I wondered if I should even leave with the team, but there was
a lot of adrenaline. I'm sure that helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland displayed ``a good fastball,'' catcher Ivan Rodriguez
said, and none appeared better than the one Cincinnati shortstop
Barry Larkin saw on a 2-1 count. Larkin's swing could not catch up
to Wetteland's fastball, and the All-Star reliever recorded the
strikeout on the next pitch with a slider on the outside corner
that the shortstop only could watch.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland also retired outfielder Jeffrey Hammonds on a foul
ball that Lee Stevens caught between the plate and first base and
induced an inning-ending come-backer to the mound from Hal Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as excited as I've seen him this spring, and there's no
doubt in my mind that he's ready physically and mentally,'' Oates
said. ``I told John in the dugout before the game that I wasn't
looking for results, but I saw in his eyes, `I am.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who underwent arthroscopic surgery Feb. 10 and March 7
to remove torn cartilage from his right knee, hit his game-winning
home run on a 1-0 pitch from right-hander Danny Graves.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro also drew a fifth-inning walk in addition to his
opposite-field home run in four plate appearances, but the
left-handed power hitter never received an opportunity to test the
knee as a base runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about my hitting,'' Palmeiro said. ``I just
want to put my leg through a test. I want to see if I can score
from second on a single or from first on a double, and I've got two
more days to figure that out. I feel like I can, but it's one thing
to think you can and another to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers returned to Texas, though, having witnessed enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two of the biggest question marks we had,'' Oates said, ``were
able to perform well for us.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
