<HEADLINE>
MATEO TO OPEN AT TRIPLE-A OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Outfielder Ruben Mateo, listed by
oddsmaker Danny Sheridan as the favorite to win 1999 American
League rookie-of-the-year award, was told yesterday that he will
start the season at Triple-A Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   Sheridan, whose line is published in ``USA Today'', installed
Mateo as a 5-to-1 favorite to win the rookie award.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is he going to get playing time?'' general manager Doug
Melvin asked.
</P>
<P>
   With Mateo ticketed for Triple A, five players are left to fill
two remaining Opening Day roster spots.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers do not intend to announce their roster until after
tomorrow's game against the New York Mets at The Ballpark in
Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Today's and tomorrow's games at The Ballpark, though, will not
influence the decisions, manager Johnny Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made them in my mind before \Ryesterday's\S game,'' Oates
said. ``I know the roster right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Bournigal, Jon Shave and Scott Sheldon are the candidates
to become the utility infielder, and the fifth outfielder will be
either Scarborough Green or Milt Cuyler.
</P>
<P>
   NO INTEREST
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who could use a right-handed hitter with Mike Simms
(torn left Achilles' tendon) on the 15-day disabled list for an
undetermined length of time, have no interest in free agent Cecil
Fielder or Baltimore's Chris Hoiles, Melvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Gilhooley, who represents Fielder, placed a call to Melvin
after the Toronto Blue Jays released his client this week.
Baltimore wants to trade Hoiles and his $3.5 million salary, but
Melvin informed Orioles general manager Frank Wren that the Rangers
are not interested.
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers officially informed right-hander Mike Morgan that he
has made the ballclub. Morgan signed his contract Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Plate umpire Tim Welke ejected Reds designated hitter Greg
Vaughn in the second inning for questioning balls and strikes.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
