<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ATHLETICS-PREVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEN-A'S ARE CANDIDATES FOR PRIME TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Art Howe hears a ruckus down the hall in the Oakland
Athletics' hotel, and decides to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The team's manager, clad in A's pajamas and stocking cap,
discovers the noise is coming from Ben Grieve's room.
</P>
<P>
   Howe opens the door and finds Grieve, in pre-adolescent glee,
jumping up and down on his bed with the A's elephant mascot.
</P>
<P>
   No, Grieve isn't reverting to his childhood. He's acting.
</P>
<P>
   This scene comes from one of a series of commercials designed to
promote the team. The theme: ``Generation A's. They're young, but
they can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Other spots have former California governor Jerry Brown running
Eric Chavez' rookie-of-the-year candidacy, and Howe and pitching
coach Rick Peterson scouting videotape of a Little Leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   It's a clever campaign, and unlike other clever ad campaigns _
talking amphibians come to mind _ this one is based on truth. These
A's indeed are young, but they really can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are the real deal,'' pitcher Gil Heredia said.
</P>
<P>
   The A's have as much young talent as any team in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Grieve, the Martin High School graduate, was the American League
rookie of the year last season. The right fielder is 22.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, who hit a combined .327 with 126 runs batted in and 33
homers in 135 games from Double A to the majors in '98, is a
prohibitive favorite to be the league's top rookie this year. The
third baseman is 21.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Tejada, a talented shortstop with a potent bat, is 22.
Catcher A.J. Hinch, in his second season, is 24. Second baseman
Scott Spezio is 26. Center fielder Ryan Christenson is 25. Jimmy
Haynes, the No. 2 starter in the rotation, is 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are young,'' pitcher Kenny Rogers said. ``We'll make some
mistakes. But these guys have talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, not all the A's are young. The team is an intriguing
mix of peach fuzz and graybeards. The roster includes two
41-year-olds in pitchers Tom Candiotti and Doug Jones, and a couple
of 39-year-olds in outfielders Tony Phillips and Tim Raines. Closer
Billy Taylor is 37.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers is 34.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, but I act young,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On this team, that's a compliment. Young is good.
</P>
<P>
   Grieve, the centerpiece of the ad campaign and the youth
movement, seems to have a one-way ticket to stardom. Concerns are
cropping up about his defense, but no one doubts his ability to
hit. He batted .288 with 18 homers and 89 RBI last year, and
expects to improve this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with it,'' he said. ``I know my potential is to
be better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is replete with players who fall victim to the dreaded
``sophomore slump,'' but those who know him would be surprised if
the son of former big-league player and executive Tom Grieve is one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good enough player, and he was around baseball at an
early age,'' Rogers said. ``Those experiences help him get through
rough times. He's level-headed enough. And he's got a great swing.
That swing will get you out of a lot of slumps.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Grieve, Chavez has a smooth, powerful left-handed swing.
Like Grieve, he has been anointed rookie of the year on the
strength of an outstanding minor-league season and solid
performance in the majors after a September call-up (.311 in 45
at-bats).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Grieve, he has got a little swagger in his stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got confidence,'' Rogers said. ``Maybe a little too much,
but that's the way to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But like Grieve, Chavez knows not to believe all his press
clippings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not expecting to do anything wonderful this year,'' he
said. ``I'm just concentrating on how I handle myself when I fail.
I know there's going to be lots of ups and downs, and I've got to
be prepared for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The entire team would be wise to adopt that attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The official party line is the A's can contend in the West this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're better than we were last year, and I think we should
be, we'll surprise some people this year,'' Grieve said. ``Our goal
isn't to do anything less than win the division. You don't want to
go into the season saying we want to finish in third place instead
of last place. Every team's goal is to win the division.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it's more likely that this will be a season of growing
pains.
</P>
<P>
   Heredia has seen it happen before. He was in Montreal in '92
with young, talented players such as Moises Alou, Marquis Grissom,
John Wetteland, Delino DeShields, Cliff Floyd, Darrin Fletcher and
Wil Cordero. Within two years, the Expos had the best record in
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to have consistency, and that's the bottom line,''
Heredia said. ``They have the talent, but not the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   If the youngsters all mature at the same time, they could team
with Matt Stairs (26 homers, 106 RBI) and Jason Giambi (27 homers,
110 RBI) to give the A's a powerful offense.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the A's do hit, the pitching staff looms as a weakness.
Especially if Rogers is traded sometime between now and the end of
July, as expected.
</P>
<P>
   They're young. They can play. It should be fun to watch them
grow up. But for now, it'll be tough for the A's to avoid finishing
last for the fifth time in the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a challenge,'' Heredia said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
